<HEADLINE>
METS BEAT MARLINS, 12-8 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MIAMI _ Octavio Dotel will always remember the New York Mets'
12-8 victory over the Florida Marlins on Thursday night because it
was his first victory in the major leagues. Otherwise, it would
have been a day to forget.
</P>
<P>
   Staked to an early eight-run lead, Dotel barely hung on for five
rocky innings to record the victory in his second major-league
start. All the 23-year-old right-hander needed was two more walks
to complete a bizarre pitching line: five innings, five hits, five
runs, five earned runs, three walks, five strikeouts.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it was not quite the stuff major-league dreams
are made of. Nor was it convincing, considering that the Mets'
offense, with Mike Piazza given the night off, ran up leads of 8-0
and 10-2 for Dotel.
</P>
<P>
   After two starts, Dotel has allowed 11 hits, 10 runs and 8 walks
in nine and one-third innings. His earned run average is 10.61. But
he was happy just the same. He said he had not received the
traditional game ball yet. ``But it's not the only one coming,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Dotel is obviously not short on confidence. But his struggles
may be one reason the Mets are considering re-signing Allen Watson,
whom they traded two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   Besides Dotel's quest for victory No. 1, the main question for
the Mets at Pro Player Stadium was would they get five innings in
before the game was rained out. That was one of the reasons Dotel
said he had problems in the fifth with the 10-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody said anything to me, but I was thinking to myself that
I wanted to finish the fifth quickly so the game would be
official,'' Dotel said.
</P>
<P>
   By then, he was pitching in a downpour. A half-inning earlier,
he had been hit in the head by a pitch from Brian Edmondson, and by
the time Dotel had struck out Mark Kotsay to finish the fifth, it
was a 10-5 game.
</P>
<P>
   Dave Wallace, the Mets' pitching coach had already visited the
mound once to chastise Dotel for having shown dismay at an umpire's
ball call. There was action in the Mets' bullpen. Another visit
would have meant Dotel was gone _and along with him, his chance for
victory.
</P>
<P>
   He was nearly gone in the top of the fifth after being struck
squarely on the back of the helmet. ``It worked,'' the trainer Fred
Hina said of the helmet that protected Dotel's head. ``We teased
him and said it hit him in a good spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Dotel said he was fine after the game. Still, the momentary
trauma might have explained Dotel's troubles in the bottom of the
inning, except for the fact Dotel was already struggling before the
beaning.
</P>
<P>
   ``At times his fastball was down in the zone and he threw his
breaking ball for strikes,'' Manager Bobby Valentine said. ``And at
times his fastball was up in the zone and he was hanging some
breaking balls.''
</P>
<P>
   Luckily for Dotel, he had a big cushion to work with. Which was
one reason he gave special thanks to his catcher, Todd Pratt, who
again was the hitting star. His two-run single with the bases
loaded helped key a six-run third, in which the Mets sent 11
batters to the plate. And Pratt's run-scoring single in the fourth
gave him three hits and three runs batted in.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt was in the starting lineup for only one reason. With a
three-game series at Shea Stadium against the first-place Atlanta
Braves this weekend, Valentine gave Piazza tonight what he had
given John Olerud the night before: a rare night off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because of the schedule we have coming up,'' Valentine said.
``Mike came into the office and we talked about it. In order to
maximize his performance from here to the All-Star break, we
thought today was the best time to give him a blow.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it was up to Pratt to give the catcher's critique of
Dotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got a live arm,'' Pratt said. ``He's got some things to
learn, but he's going to be good.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mets will settle for an outing better than tonight's the
next time Dotel takes the mound.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
