<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-TIGERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES SHUT OUT TIGERS, 6-0 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ With Orlando Hernandez cheering him on _ ``Go!''
Hernandez yelled, in English, Spanish or Japanese _ Hideki Irabu
rushed out of the Yankees' dugout to pitch the fifth inning on
Thursday night, feeling great, his confidence high, probably the
best it has been since joining the Yankees two years ago. But there
was a problem.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees hadn't finished batting in the bottom of the fourth;
there were only two outs. Irabu retreated to the dugout, grinning
at his own mistake, his teammates laughing, at him and with him.
Gone are the days when Irabu walks sluggishly to the mound each
inning as if marching onto a scaffold, and for now, there is no
talk of dumping Irabu. Nobody's calling him a fat toad anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu pitched a three-hit shutout against the Detroit Tigers on
Thursday night, as the Yankees won, 6-0, in what Manager Joe Torre
called the best regular-season outing of Irabu's tenure with the
Yankees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it is my best overall game with the Yankees,'' said
Irabu, who was supported by a home run from Paul O'Neill and a
two-run double by Shane Spencer. The Yankees, who beat Dave Mlicki
(3-8), have won 10 of their last 12 games.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu (5-3) always does pitch well against the Tigers, a
free-swinging team that ranks last in the American League in
on-base percentage and walks; going into Thursday night's game,
Irabu was 4-0 with a 1.67 earned run average in seven career
appearances versus Detroit. But as one scout who watched Irabu on
Thursday night said, it didn't really matter who he faced. ``He
would've pitched well against anybody,'' the scout said.
</P>
<P>
   What Irabu did against the Tigers _ what he has been doing for
the better part of a month _ is to throw his curveball and fastball
for strikes early in the count. His curveball is unusually slow,
65-68 miles an hour, or about 25 mph slower than his fastball, and
for that reason, batters almost never swing at it; he threw 12 to
15 curves among his 105 pitches on Thursday night, and only Dean
Palmer tried hitting it, and that in the ninth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu got ahead in the count with his curveball, placing the
Tigers at an immediate disadvantage. ``If you get ahead like
that,'' Torre said, ``the hitter is pretty much at your mercy.''
</P>
<P>
   Firing fastballs to both sides of the plate, Irabu needed only
36 pitches to get through the first three innings; it was not until
the fourth inning that the Tigers generated a hit, Bobby Higginson
slapping a single through the middle. Irabu retired the first 10
batters after Higginson's single, before Tony Clark and Juan
Encarnacion had back-to-back hits in the seventh _ the only time in
the first eight innings that the Tigers had a runner in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu threw just six pitches to set down the Tigers in order in
the eighth, and for Torre and the pitching coach Mel Stottlemyre,
there was no debate about whether Irabu would pitch the ninth
inning: He had earned the right, and when Irabu emerged from the
dugout to throw the final inning, the fans clapped generously for
him.
</P>
<P>
   A month ago Torre said that all he wanted from Irabu was
consistency, and Irabu has responded, allowing four runs or less in
his last six starts. He has won his last four decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu closed out Detroit quickly, the last out coming when Clark
lifted fly to O'Neill in right, the 16th fly ball or popup hit by
the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Irabu pumped his right fist slightly, twice, a third time, and
shook hands with his catcher, Jorge Posada, and with his teammates,
chuckling and smiling as he went through the traditional line of
handshakes and high fives. Some fans who remained from the crowd of
26,311 waited behind the Yankees' dugout, stood and cheered, and
Irabu lifted off his cap. Not bad for the fifth starter in the
rotation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
