<SLUG> BC-CONGRESS-BANKING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOUSE APPROVES DEREGULATION OF FINANCIAL SERVICES INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: The following story is an added starter on The New York Times
front page.) 
(Eds. TOPS with house approval of bill; CHANGES throughout.) 
 (rk) 
 By STEPHEN LABATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The House of Representatives approved legislation
Thursday night that would deregulate the nation's financial system
by removing the last remnants of Depression-era laws that have
largely kept banks, securities firms and insurance companies from
entering one another's businesses.
</P>
<P>
   The legislation was adopted by a 343-86 vote. Despite new
opposition that developed Thursday by some Democrats, the measure
was largely endorsed by the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   It will now be forwarded to a conference committee, where the
lawmakers will try later this summer to reconcile it with a
different version that the Senate adopted two months ago. President
Clinton has threatened to veto the Senate version because, unlike
the House version, it would take away some authority of the
Treasury Department to regulate banks.
</P>
<P>
   The White House has also opposed the Senate measure because it
dilutes the current law that requires banks to lend money to
minorities, inner-city neighborhoods, rural areas and others who
have historically been denied access to credit.
</P>
<P>
   Many experts say the legislation would set off a new wave of
financial services mergers and allow banks, insurers and brokers to
expand their ranges of businesses. But there is debate over whether
it would benefit consumers. Although the lawmakers managed to get
the bill through the House by pushing aside several contentious
issues that could still doom the legislation, the vote Thursday
night was a milestone.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fundamental precept of this bill is that it will end the
artificial restraints on commerce embodied in 65 years of law,''
said Rep. James Leach, R-Iowa, who is chairman of the House Banking
Committee and was one of the main authors of the legislation. He
said it would ultimately save consumers at least $15 billion a
year.
</P>
<P>
   House approval marks the first time that both chambers of
Congress in the same legislative session have approved measures
repealing the Glass-Steagall Act of 1933. That landmark law
reflected the view that the close affiliations between banks and
securities firms had been a primary cause of the Great Depression.
</P>
<P>
   The Glass-Steagall Act restricted the securities activities of
national banks and prohibited investment banks from engaging in
commercial banking activities. Over the last 12 years, those
restrictions have eased considerably as judges and regulators have
interpreted the act more loosely.
</P>
<P>
   Their rulings have enabled the rise of some enormous financial
conglomerates. But many federal and state restrictions remain, and
they either limit the expansion of such conglomerates or make it
prohibitively expensive for affiliations between investment banks,
commercial banks and insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Both the House and Senate bills eliminate most of those
remaining restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   But Democratic supporters of the House legislation either
withdrew their support Thursday or raised criticisms of it after
many of the items they had thought were in the legislation aimed at
protecting minority borrowers and the privacy rights of all
consumers were removed by the Republican leadership.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all voted for this legislation in committee because we were
able to have strong community reinvestment provisions, because of
consumer protections and because of strong anti-redlining
provisions,'' said Rep. John J. LaFalce of New York, the ranking
Democrat on the banking committee. ``Once those items eroded, so
did our support.''
</P>
<P>
   Among the provisions of the legislation considered Thursday
night by the House:
</P>
<P>
   _ Companies that engage in any activities that are ``financial
in nature'' would be able to affiliate under a holding company.
Insurance underwriters and real estate developers would not be
permitted to be in subsidiaries of the conglomerates but would have
to operate as affiliates. By structuring such companies in this
way, both the Federal Reserve and the Treasury Department would
have important roles in regulating conglomerates.
</P>
<P>
   _ Restrictions would continue to limit industrial companies from
owning banks.
</P>
<P>
   _ The legislation authorizes the establishment of a new banking
institution, the wholesale financial institution, that has the
powers of a national bank but could only accept deposits of more
than $100,000 and would not be federally insured.
</P>
<P>
   _ A new federal crime would be created that outlaws the practice
of using trickery and pretending to be a customer to obtain
confidential bank information.
</P>
<P>
   _ Banks would be required to post surcharges on their automated
teller machines.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, the chief author of the Senate version
of the legislation, said the House action significantly increased
the odds that the House and Senate would be able to reconcile their
differences and produce a bill.
</P>
<P>
   ``With the House vote, we now have it within our grasp to pass a
good bill, and that's my objective,'' said Gramm, . ``We face some
very high hurdles, and negotiations will require a tremendous
effort. But I am ready to take the time and do the hard work with
this goal in mind: The bill must benefit consumers by making the
broadest array of financial services available at the lowest
possible price.''
</P>
<P>
   Until Thursday, the House measure had not faced any of the
partisan bickering that pervaded the Senate legislation. The House
bill was co-sponsored by leading Republicans and Democrats and it
was largely embraced by Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin after the
House rejected a proposal by Alan Greenspan, chairman of the
Federal Reserve, that would have the effect of taking regulatory
authority away from the Treasury and giving it to the Fed.
</P>
<P>
   But Thursday's debate was steeped in bitter partisan wrangling
after House Republicans stripped the measure of a provision that
would have prohibited insurance companies affiliated with banks
from discriminating against poor neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   The practice, known as redlining, is already against the law for
banks. A provision pre-empting state insurance laws and extending
the prohibition to the insurance industry was passed earlier this
year by the House Banking Committee by a single vote. It was
sponsored by Rep. Barbara Lee, D-Calif.
</P>
<P>
   After the Republican leadership decided late Wednesday evening
to remove the Lee Amendment and not allow further consideration of
it by the full House, Democrats who had supported the legislation
defected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do a good job in fostering conditions in which our
capitalist system can flourish and it's in our interest that our
capitalist system flourish,'' said Rep. Barney Frank, D-Mass..
``But can we try to do a little bit for those who are being left
behind. This is an inappropriate continuation of a pattern of
helping those who need a benefit but ignoring those who are left
behind.''
</P>
<P>
   Many Democrats also complained that the legislation did not go
far enough in protecting the privacy interests of bank customers
and medical patients. And in one of his final acts in office, Rubin
criticized an amendment to the Bank Secrecy Act proposed by Rep.
Bob Barr, R-Ga., that would eliminate the requirements that banks
report suspicious money transactions.
</P>
<P>
   Banks are now required to report all transactions of more than
$10,000 to the federal government as part of the secrecy act, which
is intended to discourage tax evasion and money laundering. The
amendment criticized by Rubin would raise that amount to $25,000.
</P>
<P>
   The House ultimately defeated the Barr amendment.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
