<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GM-PLANT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GM WEIGHS BUILDING NEW LINE OF CARS AT PLANT IN KANSAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   General Motors Corp. said Thursday it probably would build the
platform components for a still-secret next generation of compact
and midsize cars at the company's Fairfax plant in Kansas City,
Kan.
</P>
<P>
   If the deal comes about, the plant would turn out chassis, drive
train and engine components as part of a project that has a code
name of Epsilon.
</P>
<P>
   GM's Pontiac Grand Prix assembly would be moved to a Canadian
plant.
</P>
<P>
   The Oldsmobile Intrigue assembly line at Fairfax would remain
for the time being and even could overlap production for the new
Epsilon line. The Epsilon platform could carry Chevrolet, Pontiac
or other GM body styles.
</P>
<P>
   GM spokesman Kyle Johnson declined to answer questions about
project costs or employment needs for a retooled plant. Workers at
Fairfax, which employs about 3,500 people, were advised of the
possible change at noon Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There (are) a lot of things that have to happen'' before GM
will declare that the change absolutely is coming, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   Those factors include a new labor agreement with local Auto
Workers and negotiation of infrastructure and tax incentive deals
with state and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Russell, president of United Auto Workers Local 31, said he
thought GM's move would ensure the long-term viability of the
Fairfax plant.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a car GM plans to market worldwide, and we've been
chosen to build it,'' Russell said. ``I feel like it's going to
give job security to our people, particularly the younger
employees.''
</P>
<P>
   However, Russell said there was some work force anxiety about
the departure of the Grand Prix, which has been a popular Pontiac
model in recent years.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have some concern, because the Grand Prix has given us job
security since 1994,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Don Denney, spokesman for the Unified Government of Wyandotte
County and Kansas City, Kan., said news of GM's plans came
unexpectedly.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Denney said, the company had made no proposals to
Unified Government officials regarding tax breaks, development
incentives or public assistance.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're that far down the road yet,'' Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   But requests for various forms of taxpayer assistance certainly
will come later, Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   It wouldn't be the first time economic incentives have been
traded for GM jobs at Fairfax.
</P>
<P>
   In 1985, city officials agreed essentially to waive GM's
property taxes for 10 years when the auto industry giant agreed to
build a state-of-the-art, $1 billion assembly plant on the grounds
of an abandoned, city-owned airport.
</P>
<P>
   In doing so, the area's poorest municipality granted the
nation's largest corporation tax breaks worth an estimated $270
million. The vast majority of the plant's workers live outside
Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   The Fairfax plant has since returned to the tax rolls, and GM
now pays about $10.1 million a year in real estate and personal
property taxes _ making it the municipality's largest taxpayer,
Denney said. The taxes paid by the plant allowed for both a tax cut
in the community with the area's highest property taxes and a
spending increase for public services.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of a retooling at the plant appears likely to spark
a renegotiated deal between GM and local officials.
</P>
<P>
   The conversion to Epsilon production at Fairfax ``is contingent
upon a sound business case and appropriate agreements with
stakeholders, including with governmental bodies on infrastructure
and tax arrangements,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to have a competitive local labor agreement that
benefits both sides,'' he said. ``We've got to put the whole
package together.''
</P>
<P>
   GM is keeping details of its Epsilon platform top secret. It is
being developed as the undercarriage for a new generation of
compact and midsize cars that will be sold internationally, Johnson
said.
</P>
<P>
   Platform components are often interchangeable among GM
companies. Such a production scheme saves money, simplifies the
manufacturing process and smooths deliveries from suppliers. One
such platform today, for instance, is the engineering foundation
for both the Pontiac Sunfire and the Chevrolet Cavalier.
</P>
</TEXT>
