<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-PEPSI-RUDD-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TIDE OF EMOTION FUELS RUDD'S RUN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SIMON GONZALEZ 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA, Fla. _ Ricky Rudd valiantly tried to mask his
bitterness at losing the sponsor he'd had for almost 10 years, the
sponsor that wasn't as loyal to him as he was to it, the sponsor
lured away by a carpetbagger from CART.
</P>
<P>
   After saying most of the right things, Rudd finally let his true
feelings slip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a fighter,'' he said. ``It just makes me mad and I want to
come back and stick it in their face and say, `Hey, you made a
mistake.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd almost did that last night, putting his No. 10 Ford Taurus
on the outside pole for \Rtomorrow's\S Pepsi 400 during qualifying
at Daytona International Speedway last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Front Row'' Joe Nemechek won the pole position with a fast lap
at 194.860 mph in the No. 42 BellSouth Chevrolet Monte Carlo,
slightly faster than Rudd's best circuit at 194.574.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had about as perfect a lap as I could drive,'' Nemechek
said. ``That was all I could do to keep the car from going sideways
and keep it headed as straight as I could.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the first pole since 1997 for Nemechek, who has fallen on
hard times since finishing fourth in the Texas 500 at Texas Motor
Speedway two years ago. He hasn't finished in the top five since
then. He enters tomorrow night's race 37th in the points standings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had high expectations coming into 1999,'' Nemechek said.
``We've had some really good race cars. Where we are in the points
definitely doesn't show what kind of team we have. We've been
involved in about seven accidents, and had a lot of crazy things
happen. To get the pole is definitely special.''
</P>
<P>
   Not as special, though, as getting on the outside of the front
row in the No. 10 Tide Ford was for Rudd.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rudd'' and ``Tide'' go together in stock-car racing circles
like ``Mark McGwire'' and ``home run,'' ``Juan Gonzalez'' and
``RBI'' or ``Randy Johnson'' and ``strikeout.'' The driver and the
sponsor have been paired since 1991.
</P>
<P>
   This, though, is the last year for that association.
</P>
<P>
   Rudd found out Tuesday that Procter &AMP; Gamble, the parent company
for the laundry detergent, isn't renewing the contract, even though
he has won at least one race every season of the deal until this
one.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't quite understand it,'' he said. ``We haven't
been competitive this year like we need to be, but we've been able
to win a race every year since we've had the association.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd is 38th in the points standings and hasn't recorded a
top-10 finish, but there's more to it than that.
</P>
<P>
   For one, Rudd wanted more money. He is in the last year of a
three-year deal that left him underfunded because he didn't
anticipate the escalating costs of racing.
</P>
<P>
   But that, he said, isn't the biggest reason. Tide is leaving the
long-time stock-car driver and going to NASCAR-come-lately Cal
Wells, a CART owner who plans to run a Winston Cup team next year.
</P>
<P>
   To Rudd, Tide's departure continues a disturbing trend of
newcomers luring major sponsors away from established teams and
drivers that built the sport.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm probably guilty of working too many hours and worrying way
too much about this race team instead of going up to Cincinnati
with a fancy briefcase and a nice powerpoint presentation,'' said
Rudd, one of a dying breed of owner/drivers.
</P>
<P>
   That hard work paid off in a solid qualifying effort last night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really am not that low,'' Rudd said. ``This sport is full of
highs and lows. You just learn to deal with them and move on. I
know no way of dealing with it other than getting mad and running
harder.''
</P>
<P>
   Rudd also qualified well earlier this season. He was on the pole
for the second race at Rockingham, N.C.
</P>
<P>
   To truly be able to tell Tide it made a mistake, he needs to
race well, also. That would also help in finding a replacement
sponsor.
</P>
<P>
   ``A good run here \Rtomorrow\S wouldn't hurt anything,'' he
said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
