r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AQUADROME-PLAN-KAN &LR;      07-02 0863
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AQUADROME-PLAN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
N.Y. COMPANY EYES SITE NEAR PLANNED KANSAS SPEEDWAY FOR DOMED WATER
PARK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RICK ALM  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A New York company is considering building a glass-domed
water-recreation theme park near the international motor speedway
under construction in western Wyandotte County, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks, about 8,000 households within a 21/2-hour drive
of Kansas City have received a four-minute videotape about the
Aquadrome park and a marketing questionnaire from Aquatic
Development Group Inc. in suburban Cohoes, N.Y., near Albany.
</P>
<P>
   Based on the video _ filmed at comparable company-affiliated
parks in Europe _ an Aquadrome appears to be a smaller version of
Oceans of Fun, complete with wave pools, water slides, hot tubs and
other features, all under glass.
</P>
<P>
   The typical size for such indoor water parks is about 100,000
square feet, a company official said. The official said it was too
early to estimate development costs.
</P>
<P>
   The prospect of such competition doesn't daunt Rick Rau,
director of marketing at Oceans of Fun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oceans of Fun is 60 acres,'' Rau said.
</P>
<P>
   Smaller water parks ``are really community-centered
attractions,'' he said. ``They serve a purpose. We think of Oceans
of Fun as a mainstream attraction ... a tourism destination.''
</P>
<P>
   There has been no downturn in business whenever a local water
park has opened in the region, Rau said. A water-recreation park in
Olathe, Kan., a Kansas City suburb, was open in the early 1990s
before closing in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Aquatic Development representatives in recent weeks have met
with Unified Government leaders in Wyandotte County about
purchasing part of a publicly owned 400-acre tract just north of
the auto racetrack site near the Interstate 70 and Interstate 435
interchange.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're doing everything we can to make it become a reality,''
said Don Denney, a spokesman for the Unified Government of Kansas
City, Kan., and Wyandotte County.
</P>
<P>
   J. Gregory Crozier, vice president for marketing and
architectural design for Aquatic Development, said Thursday that
other sites near the track also were under consideration.
</P>
<P>
   In its marketing letter, the company pledges that the project
``will not be financed with tax revenues.''
</P>
<P>
   A Kansas City, Kan., Aquadrome is far from a done deal.
</P>
<P>
   Crozier said the company was engaged in similar talks with
several other cities, hoping to import and adapt the popular
European water attraction to American tastes.
</P>
<P>
   So far, he said, there's nothing like an Aquadrome anywhere in
this country.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (marketing survey) is just the first stage of analysis,''
Crozier said. The company hopes to decide by the end of summer
whether the project is feasible.
</P>
<P>
   The 40-year-old Aquatic Development Group successfully emerged
from a Chapter 11 bankruptcy in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, the company completed design and construction
work on Hurricane Harbor, an outdoor water theme park at Six Flags
St. Louis that opened May 29.
</P>
<P>
   Six Flags spokeswoman Elizabeth Gotway said Thursday that
Aquatic Development did a splendid job.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just gorgeous,'' she said of the 12-acre attraction.
Gotway said Aquatic Development had done other projects for the Six
Flags theme park group.
</P>
<P>
   Kansas City, Kan., officials are enthusiastic.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is indicative of the types of developers that have
contacted us about the racetrack area,'' Denney said.
</P>
<P>
   Denney would not disclose other potential developers but said
the Unified Government was fielding numerous inquiries from hotel
and motel companies, restaurants and others interested in projects
to complement the speedway, which is expected to open in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   Aquatic Development's promotional videotape is generic for any
market and touts an ``all-weather paradise ... a water playground
... near your home.''
</P>
<P>
   Crozier said spacious and inviting domed indoor water parks in
Belgium, Holland and Germany were used in the video. Those
facilities feature plenty of greenery and open spaces for
sunbathing.
</P>
<P>
   In its written material, Aquatic Development mentions its
proposed proximity to the International Speedway Corp. track. But
speedway officials said they had not been contacted by the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounds cool,'' said Gillian Zucker, director of business
development for Kansas Speedway Corp., the parent company's Kansas
subsidiary. ``But anything that they have said that includes our
name is without our permission.''
</P>
<P>
   Zucker said none of the 1,250 acres owned by her firm was
available for development by outside firms.
</P>
<P>
   Information that accompanies the video suggests that the water
park's daily admission would be $20 for adults and $15 for
children. Annual memberships also would be available.
</P>
<P>
   The Aquadrome would be only the second public swimming facility
in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   City officials Thursday announced that next week three high
school swimming pools would be opened for public use through Aug.
13 for a $1 entrance fee.
</P>
<P>
   A long-discussed plan to develop a swimming beach at Wyandotte
Lake was voted down by the Unified Government last month.
</P>
</TEXT>
