<SLUG> BC-CHERNOBYL-VICTIM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MODERN PROSTHESES MEAN FREEDOM FOR VICTIM OF CHERNOBYL DISASTER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STACY DOWNS  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a struggle for 9-year-old Tonya Khvitko to walk two years
ago when she first visited Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Now she enjoys running and riding bikes, thanks to more than
$12,000 worth of prostheses from Project Restoration, a nonprofit
group started by Laurann Schlapper of Merriam.
</P>
<P>
   Tonya, of Belarus, was born with one leg that ended at the ankle
and one that stopped above the knee, possibly the result of
radiation from the Chernobyl power plant disaster in 1986. She also
is missing fingers on each hand.
</P>
<P>
   Until two years ago, Tonya wore leather prostheses with wooden
feet. The one on her shorter leg had a heavy, metal knee. The
prosthesis often fell off, making it difficult to walk more than a
short distance.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not independent before,'' Doyle Collier, a prosthetist
for Rehab Designs of America, said Tuesday. ``She had to have help
on stairs and uneven ground. She had to be carried at the zoo
because she grew too tired. Now she wouldn't let you help her.''
</P>
<P>
   Tonya's prostheses look more human than the more primitive ones
she wore before, and they allow her knees to bend and put a spring
in her step. Collier will have to replace straps and the feet in
both prostheses because they're worn and she has grown.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, Tonya ran around the Rehab Designs examination room
in Overland Park and climbed on wooden bars. She smiled, sang songs
and tried to entertain those around her.
</P>
<P>
   Schlapper said the change was unbelievable: Tonya used to cower
in front of other people and felt bitter that she wasn't able to do
things that other children could.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm thrilled by what has happened in her life,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Schlapper created Project Restoration five years ago. For the
last three summers the project has brought children from Belarus to
the Kansas City area, where dentists and medical professionals have
donated their services. The organization also has received money
from individuals, churches and other sources.
</P>
<P>
   On a trip with a Christian organization in 1991, Schlapper
visited Belarus, a country the size of Kansas. Belarus bore the
brunt of the Chernobyl Atomic Power Station disaster in nearby
Ukraine.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say that Chernobyl's aftermath is worse than Hiroshima's
and that the widespread contamination has resulted in millions of
physical deformities and ailments. Nearly 800,000 children live in
the highest-contaminated areas of Belarus, and the continuing
low-level exposure puts children at risk for thyroid disease and
gastrointestinal, circulatory, neurological and immune system
problems, Schlapper said.
</P>
<P>
   For the next three weeks, 18 children age 5 to 17 will receive
medical attention in the Kansas City area, up from 12 children last
year and five two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Tonya still must visit the dentist and receive the new parts for
her prostheses. She's staying with Kathy Ingram of Lenexa, who has
watched Tonya swim without her prostheses or any
self-consciousness.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's pretty spunky,'' Ingram said.
</P>
<P>
   Interpreter Galina Denisova said Tonya had made a breakthrough:
She has worn shorts while she's been in America.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wears pants in (Belarus), although it's very hot,''
Denisova said. ``She said that people laugh.''
</P>
<P>
   Those around Tonya say she has turned from being a frustrated
child into a girl who is forming goals about her future.
</P>
<P>
   ``She says she wants to be a doctor and help others like her,''
Schlapper said.
</P>
</TEXT>
