<SLUG> BC-DEECEE-BEATING-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO GIRLS ARE HELD AFTER WOMAN IS BEATEN TO DEATH
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Subs for updating throughout to say victim died)   (sw) 
 By MICHAEL JANOFSKY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A 25-year-old woman died on Thursday night after a
severe beating by two teen-age girls who the police said assaulted
her when she complained that their car was blocking a street.
</P>
<P>
   The woman, Natalie Giles Davis, died after two days in a coma at
a Northern Virginia hospital.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities in Prince William County, where the incident
occurred in a generally quiet, middle-class neighborhood of
Woodbridge, said it was unusual for girls to commit so brutal a
crime, although the county police said violence by teen-age girls
and young women was on the rise throughout the area.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we've ever had anything like this with girls
involved,'' said Sgt. Kim Chinn, a spokeswoman for the Prince
William County Police Department. ``But we have noticed in the last
several years that more young girls are becoming involved in crime,
and more in violent crime.''
</P>
<P>
   Paul Ebert, the commonwealth attorney for Prince William County,
said in an interview that the girls had administered ``an unusually
brutal beating with little justification.''
</P>
<P>
   The girls, Teresa Hattie Dixon, 18, and a 16-year-old girl whose
name was not released because of her age, were arrested shortly
after the beating and are being held without bond. They were
initially charged with aggravated malicious wounding, but
authorities said they would elevate the charges to murder if the
victim died.
</P>
<P>
   The police said the incident began shortly after a car in which
Mrs. Davis was riding with her two young children and two other
young cousins left the Davis house to attend a church service.
</P>
<P>
   As Mrs. Davis's car drove around a stopped vehicle, heated words
were exchanged between her and the two girls, who were on the
sidewalk with three friends, Sergeant Chinn said. Mrs. Davis drove
on, and the five girls jumped into the stopped car and caught up
with her, pulling in front to force the car to stop.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Davis and the 16-year-old girl left their cars and got into
a fight, which Ms. Dixon joined, the police said. Mrs. Davis' head
was pounded against the sidewalk, the police said, and was also
kicked.
</P>
<P>
   Ebert said he intended to ask the court to try the younger girl
as an adult.
</P>
</TEXT>
