</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISLAM-FESTIVAL-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNITED NATION OF ISLAM CELEBRATING ITS SUCCESS WITH A FESTIVAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE NICELY  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Skepticism from northeast Kansas City, Kan., area residents
abounded three years ago when the United Nation of Islam began
refurbishing and opening businesses along Quindaro Boulevard in
Kansas City, Kan., the heart of the city's high-crime area.
</P>
<P>
   But since that inauspicious start with Your Diner, at least
eight other businesses have followed.
</P>
<P>
   They include Your Supermarket and Bakery, Your Service Station
and Your Variety Store. The newest shop, Sweets to Eat, a
whole-wheat pastry and low-fat ice cream shop, is opening next to
the diner this weekend _ in conjunction with the United Nation of
Islam's first annual Independence Day Unity Festival to celebrate
the organization's success in Kansas City, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers are expecting about 1,000 people to attend the
festival, which begins today and concludes Sunday evening with an
address by Solomon, the organization's founder and spiritual
leader. He is coming in from the organization's national
headquarters in Temple Hills, Md., outside Washington D.C.
</P>
<P>
   Members of the United Nation of Islam regard Solomon, a former
dock worker and auto mechanic, as Allah, the Supreme Being.
</P>
<P>
   Leaders of the organization say their long-term goal is to give
_ not sell _ their business operations to private operators and
replicate the Kansas City, Kan., model in other cities, including
Kansas City.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the business expansion and lofty goals, United Nation of
Islam officials acknowledge that community skepticism of the
organization's motives persists. James 2X, United Nation of Islam
national secretary, said that is evident in the lack of a strong
customer base for the diner, supermarket and other sect-operated
businesses.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Hudgins, who lives near Quindaro, characterized community
skepticism by saying: ``People are always suspicious when change is
occurring. Especially when something is going good, people think,
`Let's wait and see when the bottom drops out.' ''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Hudgins takes delight in the convenience of a
sit-down restaurant and the luxury of fresh fruit in the
neighborhood for the first time in more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   Others take a bottom-line view of the new entrepreneurial
activity along Quindaro. LaVert Murray, development director of the
Wyandotte County Unified Government, praised the group's
accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're certainly happy to see the activity they're involved
in,'' Murray said. ``We can use all of the help we can get because
the blight and disinvestment has been in place so long.''
</P>
<P>
   James 2X said the main reason for public skepticism is that many
people confuse the United Nation of Islam with Louis Farrakhan's
Chicago-based Nation of Islam or other mainstream Muslim faiths.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our purpose is not to come in espousing a religion,'' he said.
``We do not espouse the religion of Islam....There is no hidden
agenda. We do not proselytize....We are about doing.''
</P>
<P>
   But 2X, who lives in Kansas City, Kan., does not hesitate to say
the sect emphasizes ``doing right'' and embracing a healthful,
civilized way of life. For adherents, doing right means, among
other things, shunning alcohol, tobacco and illegal drugs; eating
health foods and substituting fructose for sugar, fish for red meat
and organic vegetables for processed and chemically treated foods;
smiling courteously and acting and speaking respectfully.
</P>
<P>
   Organization leaders try to inculcate those traits and habits in
young people early on.
</P>
<P>
   The organization currently operates a private school that about
100 children attend at two locations, including the group's local
headquarters at a former tire store at 12th Street and Minnesota
Avenue. Early next year, the organization plans to open a private,
year-round elementary school and training center _ the University
of Islam _ in the former Roosevelt Elementary School.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City, Kan., School District donated the building at
North 36th Street and Washington Avenue for $1.
</P>
<P>
   The events begin today with a tour of Roosevelt Elementary
School at 6 p.m. and a ``mathematical thinking'' class at the
school from 7 p.m. to 10 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The main events take place Saturday, when three blocks east of
Quindaro east of 18th Street will be blocked off. From noon to 7
p.m., the street will be filled with displays, booths, music, food,
ethnic dancing and other attractions. A talent search will take
place from 7 p.m. to 10 p.m. at Sumner Academy of Arts and Science.
</P>
<P>
   A buffet will be held from 11 a.m. to 4 p.m. Sunday at 1726
Quindaro. Solomon is scheduled to speak at 6 p.m. at the buffet
site.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
