r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUPERINTENDENT-TALKS-     07-02 1126
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUPERINTENDENT-TALKS-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TALKS BETWEEN KC SCHOOL BOARD, SUPERINTENDENT CANDIDATE BREAK OFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PHILLIP O'CONNOR, TANIKA WHITE and MATT STEARNS  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Negotiations between school superintendent finalist Jay T.
Edwards and the Kansas City Board of Education abruptly ended
Thursday night after he and board members were unable to reach
agreement on a contract.
</P>
<P>
   Board members spent about an hour behind closed doors Thursday
evening, exchanging offers via an attorney with Edwards, who was
elsewhere in the Board of Education building.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had hoped, of course, that we were making the right
selection,'' board President John Rios said. ``The general had
great skills. We just couldn't agree on the contract. It was the
consensus of the board that we need to reopen the search, and the
general understood. It was a mutual parting, and I just wish him
well. He was a good man.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards, a retired Air Force major general, immediately checked
out of his hotel and headed to Kansas City International Airport to
catch a flight back to Oklahoma City.
</P>
<P>
   ``My counter-counteroffer was not accepted, and we both
recognized by that point that we were at a stalemate,'' Edwards
said as he waited to board his flight. ``I think if we had more
time, we could have come to an agreement. It was an agreeable,
affable, friendly parting.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards and the board disagreed over the length of the contract.
But the key stumbling block was the financial package, Edwards
said. He said the incentives the board had offered him were too
vague.
</P>
<P>
   The board originally offered Edwards a salary of $125,000.
Edwards asked for $200,000. Board members countered with an offer
of $140,000 in base salary plus $34,000 if he met certain
performance incentives. With benefits, the total compensation
package offered by the district equaled close to the amount paid to
former Superintendent Henry Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards' final request was for $164,000 in base pay, plus about
$10,000 more in possible incentives.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards praised the district's teachers, students, facilities
and parents. And he would not criticize the school board or the
process that led to his withdrawal, saying, ``They did the best
they could under the circumstances.''
</P>
<P>
   But when asked whether he had any advice for the next candidate,
Edwards shook his head, laughed and said, ``No.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think there's regret on both sides,'' he concluded. ``If we
could have worked out the numbers, I could have worked with the
board and with the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards said he would continue in his post as general
administrator of the Oklahoma Corporation Commission.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier Thursday, a court-appointed monitoring committee denied
a request by the board to delay past a deadline today for
completion of negotiations with Edwards. The Desegregation
Monitoring Committee instead recommended the board turn to three
other finalists recommended for the post if the board was unable to
reach accord with Edwards. The monitoring committee set a new
deadline of July 9 for the board to name a new superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   Rios said the district contacted the other three finalists to
see whether they were still interested in the Kansas City job. He
said the board could meet through the holiday weekend to try to
identify its next choice.
</P>
<P>
   But at least one of the other three finalists, Grandview School
District Superintendent John Martin, said he no longer wanted the
Kansas City job.
</P>
<P>
   ``Under the circumstances, I'm simply not interested, not at
this point,'' Martin said. He declined to elaborate.
</P>
<P>
   A second finalist, Pascal Forgione Jr., former U.S. education
commissioner for statistics, said he still would consider the
position.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've kind of thrown me,'' Forgione said when reached at his
Washington home. ``I guess I've got to think some. I definitely
would think about it. I'm impressed with the community and the
commitment to quality education that they want, so I have to give
it thought.''
</P>
<P>
   The third finalist, Benjamin Demps Jr., former Oklahoma
Department of Human Services director, could not be reached
Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   Board members and the Desegregation Monitoring Committee want
the new superintendent to receive an incentive-based contract
because it would coincide with their efforts to hold employees
accountable.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to come to the Kansas City School District and
accept this position, you better be willing to work on commission,
at least for part of the salary,'' board member Lance Loewenstein
said.
</P>
<P>
   Board members opposed Edwards' request for a three-year
contract. They expressed concern about having to buy out a
long-term deal if their relationship with Edwards soured.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, they offered a one-year deal that could be renewed
annually.
</P>
<P>
   Rios also said some board members were concerned by the
reception Edwards received from some community groups he visited
during a daylong tour of the district on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Edwards met early Thursday with several ministers and leaders in
the African-American community. He later met with community
members, including Hispanic parents and activists, at Westport
Middle School. He finished his tour with a similar meeting in
Independence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things didn't work out as we hoped,'' Rios said. ``We hoped
there would be a bonding there, and I guess it was hit and miss in
his travels today.''
</P>
<P>
   Edwards was to appear at a 7 p.m. forum at Central High School
but was on his way out of town by that time.
</P>
<P>
   Many community members in the packed auditorium used the forum
to express their dissatisfaction with the process that led to
Edwards' selection. Several complained that the process was being
controlled by U.S. District Judge Dean Whipple and that the
community was left out. As the judge overseeing the federal
desegregation case, Whipple has wide-ranging authority over the
district, including the selection of the next superintendent.
</P>
<P>
   ``When do we get to a point where we say our kids are not going
to a school run by Whipple (or) a monitoring committee?'' asked
community activist Ron McMillan.
</P>
<P>
   Whipple has ordered school board members to keep the names and
backgrounds of candidates confidential to avoid political
interference.
</P>
<P>
   McMillan and others asked board member Terry Riley how community
members could be more empowered, and Riley advised the community to
unite and sue the court.
</P>
<P>
   Rios said ultimately it was the breakdown over the contract and
not community concerns that led the board to end discussions with
Edwards. Rios said he expected the next candidate to hold similar
meetings with community groups.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're back to square one,'' Rios said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
