<SLUG> BC-BRIDGE-PROBLEMS-KAN </SLUG>
  
 151st STREET BRIDGE IN OLATHE NEEDS EXTENSIVE REPAIRS  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ROBERT A. CRONKLETON  
 c. 1997 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A little over four years ago, politicians and business leaders
climbed aboard school buses and crossed the 151st Street bridge in
Olathe, Kan., marking the opening of an economic gateway into
southern Johnson County.
</P>
<P>
   Now highway officials say the $3.9 million bridge needs $3
million in repairs. Abutments that support the ends of the bridge
have shifted, causing extensive damage and raising concerns about
the structure's ability to withstand normal stresses.
</P>
<P>
   But they will delay repairs until next year, partly to avoid
subjecting holiday shoppers to a maze of detours and traffic
congestion.
</P>
<P>
   The interchange connects 151st Street, Interstate 35 and U.S.
169, a major economic corridor on the county's south side that is
used by many who go to the Great Mall of the Great Plains and to
the Olathe Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   State officials ``could not be sure that they would have the
repairs completed before Thanksgiving once they got it designed and
built,'' said Rick Biery, city engineer for Olathe. ``They decided
it would be better to wait until next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``While it will be somewhat of an inconvenience, people will be
able to get where they want to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim McKee, Olathe's director of economic development, said
Olathe has an economic incentive to keep the bridge open past the
holiday season.
</P>
<P>
   ``A big portion of the city's budget is created from sales
taxes,'' he said. ``The mall is a large contributing factor to that
revenue.''
</P>
<P>
   Also, the closing could affect more than 1,500 businesses within
a three-mile radius of the bridge, McKee said.
</P>
<P>
   If the repairs were started this year, the bridge work might not
get done before winter, causing a longer closing. If repair work
starts next year, it should take about four months.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation officials say the delay won't compromise public
safety. Sensors and survey crews will monitor the structure.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as we see there is a safety problem, we will shut it
down right away,'' said Ruben Noguera, field engineering
administrator for the Kansas Department of Transportation.
</P>
<P>
   The Transportation Department is trying to figure out what is
causing the bridge, which opened in November 1994, to move. An
Olathe official said preliminary indications are that erosion has
eaten away at the abutments, and it has started to settle.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge's eastern abutment had dropped 2.5 inches and moved
3.75 inches to the west, and the western abutment had moved 1.5
inches to the east.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Department officials hoped the abutments had
stopped moving, but Noguera said recent rains, including this
week's heavy downpour, had caused them to move again.
</P>
<P>
   Engineers are concerned that the bridge, which is built on
rockers to allow for expansion and contraction, might not be able
handle normal stresses if the abutments continue to move.
</P>
<P>
   Cracks have appeared on the abutments. Also, the concrete
covering of the slope leading to the western bridge abutment has
fallen apart in places, exposing the soil and parts of the bridge's
pilings that should be buried.
</P>
<P>
   Crews made temporary fixes last week by inserting wood supports
near the rockers to help bear the weight of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, crews will fix the concrete covering on the western slope
of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Department officials met Wednesday with Olathe
officials and bridge designers and decided to close the bridge next
year to rebuild the abutments.
</P>
<P>
   Transportation Department officials estimate that more than
6,000 vehicles use the bridge daily, but that number climbs during
the holiday season as shoppers flock to the mall.
</P>
<P>
   John Myers, assistant professor of civil engineering at the
University of Missouri-Rolla, said settling of a bridge is not
uncommon.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most settlement occurs very quickly after the initial
construction,'' said Myers, who has not seen the damage but agreed
to be interviewed about bridges in general. ``So it does happen.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the amount of movement the 151st Street bridge has
undergone is significant.
</P>
<P>
   The bridge's problem is a major disappointment for the
Transportation Department because a bridge's lifespan is supposed
to be 40 to 50 years.
</P>
<P>
   Noguera said the Transportation Department never had a bridge
with settlement problems of this magnitude.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has been really frustrating,'' Noguera said. ``It is a
really good-looking bridge. It really is a beautiful bridge.''
</P>
<P>
   Biery said it is uncertain who would have to pay for the
repairs. The city is negotiating with the Transportation
Department. The Transportation Department is trying to determine if
the bridge designer and contractor should be held liable for any of
the problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this stage, we just don't know,'' Noguera said.
</P>
<P>
   Local officials said emergency services should face only minor
inconveniences and delays.
</P>
<P>
   McKee said traffic will be detoured to the U.S. 169//Kansas 7
bridge under the 151st Street bridge, so an east//west connection
in that area will be available.
</P>
<P>
   Olathe Medical Center expects the repairs to have little effect
on its patients, said Lesle Knop, corporate director of marketing
and wellness for the Olathe Medical Center.
</P>
<P>
   Art Mabry, Olathe's chief of police, said emergency services
should not be hampered.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as they don't mess with any of the other roads with
any other major construction, all that I see it causing is some
minor delays,'' Mabry said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do not think it will be a show stopper.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
