<HEADLINE>
US WEST TO TALK WITH QUEST 
</HEADLINE>
  (sw) 
 By LAURA M. HOLSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The board of US West, the smallest regional Bell company, has
agreed to allow management and its advisers to enter into
preliminary merger talks with Qwest Communications International
Inc., the company said on Thursday night.
</P>
<P>
   The move was an important development for Qwest, the
fourth-largest long-distance telephone company, which is trying to
buy not only US West but the Frontier Corp. Those two companies
have already agreed to be acquired by Global Crossing Ltd.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing, the telecommunications upstart based in
Bermuda, has given US West its consent to have discussions with
Qwest. Thus, US West does not need to declare that Qwest's offer is
``superior'' as required by its existing agreement with Global
Crossing.
</P>
<P>
   US West agreed in May to merge with Global, which offered $30
billion in stock. Frontier, the fifth-largest long-distance
carrier, also agreed to be acquired by Global Crossing in a stock
swap valued at $11.1 billion. Frontier said on Wednesday that its
management and advisers would begin exploratory discussions with
Qwest.
</P>
<P>
   Qwest's first bid on June 13 _ a combination of cash and stock _
did little to inspire US West and Frontier, so Qwest revised its
bid last week.
</P>
<P>
   Global Crossing is offering Frontier shareholders $63 a share in
Global stock and US West stockholders about $60 a share in stock.
Qwest is offering Frontier shareholders $68 in stock and cash and
US West shareholders $69 in stock or cash. But there are several
issues both boards will have to consider besides price, including
regulatory risks, the deal's structure and its strategic
rationale. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
