A6877 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LA-SCHOOL-FIASCO-LADN     07-02 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-SCHOOL-FIASCO-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BOARD PRIMED TO HALT BELMONT WORK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREG GITTRICH  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Shortly after being sworn in to office, the new
reform-minded Los Angeles school board has agreed to hold an
emergency meeting Tuesday at which it is expected to order
construction on the Belmont Learning Center halted temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   A majority of board members said on Thursday they were prepared
to vote to halt construction on the $200 million school -- the
nation's costliest -- and decide whether to abandon the project
within a month because of growing evidence of the seriousness of
toxic soil contamination and the cost of mitigation.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, administrators were directed to offer the board
legal options that could include suing the lead contractor, Kajima
Urban Development, and others involved in the project.
</P>
<P>
   ``We shouldn't put another dime into Belmont until we know what
we're going to do,'' said Genethia Hayes, who was elected board
president.
</P>
<P>
   ``The future of Belmont is a top, top priority for the new
school board. We can't keep throwing money into that project. I
expect the board to make a final decision within the next 30
days.''
</P>
<P>
   A continuing Daily News investigation disclosed last week that
internal documents showed Kajima repeatedly used incomplete
environmental data to assure the Fire Department that no hazardous
levels of methane existed around the site of school buildings.
Comprehensive environmental tests later determined that the
explosive gas, seeping from an old oil field, pervades the entire
site.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes and fellow new San Fernando Valley board member Caprice
Young said they will support earlier efforts by David Tokofsky and
Julie Korenstein to stop construction on the partially-built school
until the district determines whether there is an economically
feasible way to finish the school and make it safe for children.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no reason for the construction to keep going on,''
said Young. ``If we decide it is not cost-effective or safe to put
children at that school, there will be less to tear down.''
</P>
<P>
   Board member Valerie Fields and newcomer Michael Lansing have
expressed serious reservations about going forward.
</P>
<P>
   Victoria Castro, once Belmont's most adamant supporter, told the
Daily News last week that she believes district administrators
misled her about the severity of methane problems and other
environmental contamination at the 35-acre site and said she was
considering abandoning the project.
</P>
<P>
   The three new board members and Tokofsky were all backed by a
well-funded campaign organized by Mayor Richard Riordan. They
ousted Jeff Horton, George Kiriyama and Barbara Boudreaux.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly half of the retail and school complex had been completed
before the state Department of Toxic Substances Control determined
late last year that previous environmental assessments of the site
failed to adequately characterize toxic and methane contamination.
</P>
<P>
   While construction was partially halted in February, work has
continued on portions of the complex where foundations for
buildings already were poured.
</P>
<P>
   A School Safety Team, created with staffers and outside
consultants to cope with the growing crisis, warned last week
against finishing the school unless a ``failsafe'' methane
mitigation system could be installed and maintained ``without human
error'' for the 30- to 50-year lifespan of the complex.
</P>
<P>
   The safety team has forwarded test results from 900 new soil,
vapor and groundwater tests to the state Department of Toxic
Substances Control, and plans to conduct additional tests until the
end of the year. The cost of mitigation was estimated at close to
$10 million.
</P>
<P>
   Tokofsky said allowing construction to continue while the
district's internal audit department investigates environmental
problems and alleged criminal actions surrounding Belmont is
comparable to ``trying to catch a runaway train.''
</P>
<P>
   The investigation, being conducted by LAUSD chief of special
investigations Don Mullinax and closely reviewed by the District
Attorney's Office, received support Thursday from the state Senate,
which voted 37-1 to approve a bill by Sen. Tom Hayden, D-Los
Angeles, to grant subpoena power to Mullinax.
</P>
<P>
   Civil legal issues also were raised byTokofsky, who said he has
asked Superintendent Ruben Zacarias to give the board ``a list of
legal and financial options for the future of Belmont.''
</P>
<P>
   The list will include the possibility of suing Kajima, as well
as several environmental and legal consultants who told the
district to proceed with the project, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   According to Zacarias, the board will receive a list of options,
compiled by general counsel Richard Mason, by next week.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes said if anyone expects the board to back down from a legal
fight over Belmont, they are mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   ``If legal action is necessary, we will move forward
expediently,'' Hayes said. ``If people are legally culpable for
this, they need to be held accountable and need to know they can't
do this with taxpayers' money.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
