<HEADER>
A6887 &Cx1f; tth-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI &LR;      07-02 0601
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-SONICS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SONICS GAIN TOUGHNESS, FLEXIBILITY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RONALD TILLERY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Horace Grant knew several teams were interested in
trading for him on draft day.
</P>
<P>
   There was only one thing Grant found puzzling about him being
shipped to the Sonics.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Magic never mentioned Seattle,'' Grant said. ``Not once.''
</P>
<P>
   If you were to go by the 1999 Sonics, it would seem like a
mismatch. Grant is known for his colorful goggles and tough
defense. Last season, the Sonics were only a shade of their former
selves _ particularly on defense.
</P>
<P>
   However, when the Sonics introduced Grant Thursday at their
practice facility, they revealed an intention to re-establish a
defensive prowess and reputation.
</P>
<P>
   When Gary Payton and Olden Polynice said last season no one
feared the Sonics, Grant believed them from afar.
</P>
<P>
   ``Watching the Sonics this past year, they needed that toughness
more so that aggressive defense they had in past years. That's what
made the Sonics,'' said Grant, whose built a 12-year career and
reputation on being a tenacious front-line defender.
</P>
<P>
   Grant runs the floor well, rebounds and keeps post-up players
off balance even as he approaches his 34th birthday on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   Excited about the prospect of adding Grant, Paul Westphal rushed
into a film session with team president Wally Walker one day last
month. The tape Westphal put in the VCR showed Grant hustling from
end to end on the court twice in one sequence.
</P>
<P>
   Grant snared a defensive rebound, made the outlet pass, filled
the lane on offense, then made the sprint back on defense and drew
an offensive foul.
</P>
<P>
   ``It enables us to do what I want to do defensively. If you have
players who can do it, it works a lot better,'' Westphal said. ``He
brings a defensive mindset. ... His leadership and his example will
be very good for the rest of the guys.''
</P>
<P>
   In Grant's locker at the O-rena were several Indian warrior
figures, which he says serve to remind him that every game is a
war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I take pride in that aspect of my game,'' Grant said. ``I'll
come to work every night and be ready to perform against the best
out here. I've made my name on defense.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics were regularly beaten inside for dunks and layups
last season. Defense is not a strong suit for forward Vin Baker,
whom the Sonics hope to re-sign as a free agent. Polynice was not
much of an enforcer, either. Grant is expecting to change how
opponents attack the paint.
</P>
<P>
   Westphal envisions Grant and Baker playing together. Grant is
capable of defending centers _ a chore from which he will not back
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have no problem with that whatsoever. As long as I'm here,
this team is going to be aggressive,'' said Grant, who stands
6-foot-10 and 245 pounds. ``I watched Gary and Hawk (Hersey
Hawkins) play defense and it excites me to see guys play like that.
My best assets are defense, a no-nonsense attitude and hard work.''
</P>
<P>
   Grant brings leadership in addition to defense.
</P>
<P>
   The Bulls made him the 10th overall pick in the 1987 draft. In
Chicago, Grant, Michael Jordan and Scottie Pippen were known as the
``Dobermans'' for the way they attacked on defense. The result was
Grant becoming an integral part of three NBA titles with the Bulls
from 1991 to 1993.
</P>
<P>
   The Sonics did not see much of a dropoff during Grant's five
seasons in Orlando.
</P>
<P>
   ``We like his energy,'' Walker said. ``There's no doubt we need
to get better defensively. And that's exactly what we were thinking
when we made the deal.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
