<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6889 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-DEREGULATION-IMPACT-6     07-02 0931
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEREGULATION-IMPACT-650&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCIAL SERVICES INDUSTRY AWAITS BIGGEST TRANSFORMATION SINCE
DEPRESSION
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Okla.)  (rk) 
 By LESLIE WAYNE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As sweeping deregulation measures to remake the nation's
financial system near the congressional finish line, an oft-heard
comment is that the efforts would ``level the playing field'' among
banks, securities companies and insurers, which currently have
different rules of engagement for competing with each other.
</P>
<P>
   But the legislation, one version passed the Senate in May and
another cleared the House Thursday night _ would do more than that.
Many experts say it would usher in a new financial era in which the
playing field would be greatly expanded, where many competing teams
would be merged into fewer and bigger teams and where today's
teams, which look quite different from one another, will begin to
look alike.
</P>
<P>
   If there is any prototype for the future, it is Citigroup, the
product of the $70 billion merger of Citicorp and the Travelers
Group Inc. into a financial giant empowered to sell securities,
take deposits, make loans, underwrite stocks, sell insurance and
engage in a wide variety of financial activities under one roof.
These combinations are currently either prohibited _ or made very
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it was the Citicorp-Travelers merger, announced in
April 1998, that threw out the challenge to Washington to change
Depression-era laws that had hampered such bold unions. Parts of
that deal were not permitted under current law, and
Citigroup-Travelers were faced with either getting the law changed
within five years or scuttling big parts of the deal, for instance,
jettisoning large chunks of Traveler's insurance business.
</P>
<P>
   It now appears that the law will be changed, knocking down all
legal barriers to such unions and, some believe, setting off a new
wave of financial services mergers. In addition, banks, insurers
and brokers will all begin to expand their ranges of businesses. As
examples, a consumer could go to a securities firm and buy life
insurance, or go to a life insurer and buy stocks and mutual funds,
or go to a securities firm and make a bank deposit _ or simply go
to one financial services company and do all these things.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill will open the door for a new wave of financial
services mergers,'' said Kenneth Guenther, the top lobbyist for the
Independent Community Bankers Association. ``It will put a lot more
companies _ companies like Merrill Lynch and other big bank and
insurance companies _ in play.''
</P>
<P>
   For each of the three big players _ securities firms, banks and
insurers _ the bill means something different. While the bill is
generally associated with banks, in some ways, it means the least
change for them. Banks, through court rulings and regulatory
changes, can now engage in a limited amount of insurance and
securities activities. This bill would remove those limits and let
them enter these businesses unfettered, rather than fighting for
changes.
</P>
<P>
   Securities firms would be able to buy banks _ currently, banks
can buy securities firms, but not vice versa. For them, this is a
big victory, and firms like Merrill Lynch have been at the
forefront of the lobbying effort to get the measure passed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to have any strategic option foreclosed as we
attempt to compete on a global basis and in an industry seeing
substantial consolidation,'' said James Wiggins, a Merrill
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   And insurance companies, which have seen their business fall as
fewer people buy life insurance, like the bill for the same reason:
They feel banks are poaching into their business, and they want to
poach back. Acquiring a bank would give them access to new
customers and allow them to enter new businesses. Moreover, it
would put banks and insurance companies under the same regulatory
system.
</P>
<P>
   ``This bill is a recognition that the market has just outpaced
the regulatory system,'' said Daniel Zielinski, a spokesman for the
American Insurance Association. ``The big win for us is it allows
us to move into banking territory. ''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   For the consumers, the picture is less clear. David Runkel, a
staff member of the House Banking Committee, said consumers would
benefit from increased convenience, more protections on securities
and insurance sales, and a reduction in fees from increased
competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have more people and more companies offering more
services, you should have additional choices and convenience for
consumers,'' Runkel said. ``If you have $10,000, you can go to one
place and buy stocks, get a life insurance policy and open a
banking account.''
</P>
<P>
   Guenther, opposing the measure, contends that the consumer could
lose, arguing that financial consolidation will lead to fewer
choices and higher consumer fees. ``You will have fewer and fewer
institutions controlling the credit and debit card empire, and the
world will be divided more into really big and really small
institutions,'' said Guenther, whose group opposes the measure.
</P>
<P>
   One such sign of the future came last month when Wal-Mart Stores
Inc. applied to purchase an Oklahoma savings and loan company so
that it could offer banking services alongside the fishing tackle,
car batteries and other retail goods at its superstores. This
activity would be permitted under a complicated provision of the
bill that allows a limited number of acquisitions of unitary
savings and loan companies by commercial companies, like Wal-Mart.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
