<P>
   NY-SUV (New York) _ Despite congested streets, narrow roadways,
aging bridges and tunnels and polluted air that, in some respects,
make the New York area uniquely inhospitable to light trucks, the
region has become one of the nation's hottest markets for sport
utility vehicles. Now, state regulators are on the verge of
proposing new registration rules that could further increase the
number of heavy vehicles on area roadways. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   SCI-STEM-CELLS (Undated) _ Is research on human embryonic stem
cells ethically justified? Theologians have a clear answer _ in
fact quite a few of them, depending both on their faith and their
relative position within it. The research, made possible by a
discovery last November, provokes a stark moral choice: the
primordial cells can give rise to all kinds of human tissue, making
them potentially priceless as a tool to repair aging and ailing
bodies.. But in most cases a human embryo must be destroyed to
obtain them. By Nicholas Wade.
</P>
<P>
   OBIT-NKOMO (Johannesburg, South Africa) _ Joshua Nkomo, the
once-fiery African nationalist and guerrilla leader who was father
to Zimbabwe's struggle for independence, died early Thursday in the
Zimbabwean capital, Harare. He was 82. By Donald G. McNeil Jr.
</P>
<P>
