<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-MARINERS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POWER STILL OUT ON M'S 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By TYLER KEPNER  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OAKLAND, Calif. _ It turned on a bloop and a plunk, and it could
have used a bomb.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners came that close to beating the Oakland Athletics
Thursday and heading happily to Texas for three crucial games this
weekend. Instead, they will meet the division-leading Rangers
trailing by six games, thanks to a 5-4 loss to the A's before
11,632 fans in the Coliseum.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners lost for the second game in a row to the A's, the
plucky, low-budget team Seattle can't shake in this American League
West race. After blowing out the Mariners Wednesday, Oakland won in
the ninth inning Thursday, when Tony Phillips' one-out single off
Jose Paniagua (5-7) brought home pinch runner A.J. Hinch.
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners scored just two runs in 21 innings against Oakland
starters this series, and they went homerless over the three games.
The M's still lead the majors in homers by a wide margin, but have
failed to homer in six of their past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``When one guy gets hot, another guy gets hot,'' said third
baseman Russ Davis. ``You saw it in their game (Wednesday). It was
one guy, the next guy and it took off from there. We're going to
score runs, I don't think anybody here is thinking about that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Mariners have to win games like Thursday's, Davis said, when
the pitching gives the offense a chance. Frankie Rodriguez and Paul
Abbott pitched effectively for eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez allowed an opposite-field homer to Eric Chavez in the
third, and had six strikeouts through four innings. In the fifth,
Jason Giambi led off with a single, and Rodriguez induced a pop-up
to shallow right-center from Chavez.
</P>
<P>
   Second baseman David Bell went after it, and his only option was
to turn his back to the ball and attempt an over-the-shoulder
catch. The sun, he said, prevented him from getting a better look.
Bell came close to catching the ball, but it dropped for a hit,
putting two runners on with no outs.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that was the difference in the game for us,''
Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   The next batter was rookie catcher Ramon Hernandez, who went
7-for-13 in this series, his first in the majors. Hernandez singled
to load the bases, and Giambi scored when Rodriguez got Ryan
Christenson to ground into a double play. Another run came in on a
single by Phillips, his second of three.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez departed after the fifth, having allowed three runs on
six hits but walking none in a spot start. Rookie Gil Meche will
join the rotation the next time around, replacing Abbott, who used
a good changeup to toss three strong innings. The A's scored only
once off Abbott, on a seventh-inning single by Christenson that
gave them a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Aided by two errors, the Mariners tied it in the eighth, driving
Jimmy Haynes from the game, and getting to closer Billy Taylor for
stolen bases by Brian Hunter and Ken Griffey Jr. and a run-scoring
single by David Segui. Two of Seattle's runs were unearned.
</P>
<P>
   The score was still 4-4 when Paniagua entered in the ninth. The
Mariners' set-up man had overwhelmed Oakland on Tuesday, but he
failed to repeat that Thursday. After Hernandez's one-out single,
Paniagua hit Christenson, putting pinch runner Hinch in position to
score _ which he did, when Phillips ripped one down the right-field
line one batter later.
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua's inconsistency has been frustrating for the M's,
especially in a stretch of games in which he has played such a big
role. The right-hander blew saves in losses last Monday and last
Thursday. He blew a save but won Saturday, pitched two shutout
innings and won Tuesday, then lost Thursday. He declined to talk
after the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``Early in the year, he was using too many two-seam (fastballs),
and the ball was moving so much he had trouble controlling it,''
said pitching coach Stan Williams. ``We tried a four-seamer to get
ahead, then the two-seamer. Obviously, he flew open on that pitch
today. Hitting a guy was the last thing in the world he wanted to
do there.''
</P>
<P>
   Paniagua was successful using a new grip on his slider on
Tuesday, but that pitch might have indirectly worked against him
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're working on his slider and trying to mix his pitches,''
Williams said. ``He's been doing a real good job with the slider,
but whether or not it's screwing up his delivery on the fastball,
that's something I plan to talk to him about.''
</P>
</TEXT>
