<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0030 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 01:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6895 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BKL-ROCKERS-COMETS-HN     07-02 0776
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKL-ROCKERS-COMETS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By W.H. STICKNEY JR. &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
A gypsy without a crystal ball could have predicted how the
road-weary Comets might have played against the Cleveland Rockers
on Thursday night at Compaq Center.
</P>
<P>
   Playing for the second straight night and for the third time
since Sunday, the Comets needed a big injection of energy from
somewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Tina Thompson, who has had an injured knee and has been in a
shooting slump, gave the Comets exactly what they needed. She
pumped in a career-high 26 points as the Comets overcame a slow
start to jet past the Rockers 76-64 before a crowd of 9,059.
</P>
<P>
   Never one to take off a minute from practice unnecessarily or
use an injury as an alibi, Thompson, true to form, wouldn't own up
to an offensive slump over the previous four games.
</P>
<P>
   ``What does that mean?'' she asked. ``I really don't get it.
Because I haven't been making shots that I usually make doesn't
mean that I haven't been myself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've played very well on defense and rebounded, just helping
my team in any way I could. Cynthia (Cooper) and Sheryl (Swoopes)
have been very good offensively. And we haven't needed anyone to
step up and be an offensive threat, because they've been doing so
well.''
</P>
<P>
   That was not the case Thursday. Cooper admitted she played badly
and didn't shoot well.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, her string of scoring in double figures in every
WNBA game in which she has participated over two-plus years was in
jeopardy until the final minutes, but Cooper finished with 13
points.
</P>
<P>
   Swoopes, who carried the bulk of the offensive load in a 78-68
win at Utah on Wednesday, struggled against Cleveland _ as did most
of her teammates. Swoopes hit six of 17 shots for 13 points.
</P>
<P>
   But Thompson, who in the previous three games had shot 38
percent (12-for-32), provided the safety net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that you can say her game's been off,'' said
Swoopes. ``It's still early in the season. Tina maybe has been
struggling a little bit, and she's gotten down on herself a little
bit.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I think this (Thursday night) did a lot for her confidence
and it did a lot for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Playing much of the game with her back to the basket for one of
the few times in her career, Thompson exhibited a power game that
resulted in 8-of-12 shooting from the field.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets got support from another team member who has been
mired in a rut of late, too.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve point guard Jennifer Rizzotti had her best game in the
WNBA, playing 18 minutes that yielded eight points and four steals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she gave us a spark tonight,'' coach Van Chancellor
said of Rizzotti. ``I thought we were tired tonight, and I slipped
her in.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought she played well.''
</P>
<P>
   During their impressive run to the 1998 WNBA championship, one
of the blemishes on the Comets' 27-3 regular-season record was an
overtime loss to the Rockers at Compaq Center. With a 9-1 start to
the 1999 season, the Comets are on that same record .900 pace.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland came in Thursday riding a two-game win streak after
starting the season 0-7, a league record. The Rockers (2-8) also
had the advantage of two days of rest.
</P>
<P>
   The difference in energy levels between the teams was
immediately evident, though the scoreboard might not have showed
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we were a little tired and a little sluggish,'' said
Cooper.
</P>
<P>
   With ABL refugee Chasity Melvin ranging free inside, the Rockers
played on even terms with the Comets until late in the first half.
There were seven early ties, and neither team led by more than
three points until the Comets outscored the Rockers 15-0 to go
ahead 36-23.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson scored five straight points during the surge and was a
constant terror on the backboards.
</P>
<P>
   The Comets led by as many as 13 points on three occasions in the
first half and by 15 (53-38) _ following a 3-pointer by Thompson _
in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   With 7:15 remaining, a basket by reserve Alisa Burras brought
the Rockers to 66-60.
</P>
<P>
   Cooper then scored eight points during a closing 10-4 run that
carried the Comets to their ninth win in 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll tell you, you ride on a jet plane for three hours from
Utah and you're playing back-to-back,'' said Chancellor, ``and
you're in a grueling game like we were tonight?
</P>
<P>
   ``And you're playing Cleveland, who's won two in a row. Yeah,
I'm pleased.''
</P>
<P>
   Also thrown into the mix was a 68-66 loss to Orlando at Compaq
Center on Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team's just got it. We got beat Monday night. This is a
team that just has that special something,'' Chancellor said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
