<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 01:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6896 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDINALS-     07-02 0807
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-CARDINALS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CARLTON THOMPSON  
 c. 1999, Houston Chronicle  
The good news _ if you're an Astros fan _ is that the Astros won
two of three games against the St. Louis Cardinals and showed signs
of breaking out of the funk that has defined them for two weeks.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The bad news is that Chris Holt seems to have reverted to his
early-season problem of poor pitch location.
</P>
<P>
   Holt let a three-run lead slip away and stood helpless as the
Cardinals pulled away for a 10-4 victory before a Thursday
afternoon crowd of 43,727 _ the largest at the Astrodome since
opening day.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros scored three runs in the first inning, but the game
was tied by the fifth and the Cardinals blew it open with four in
the sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got three runs in the first inning against their No. 1
starter (Kent Bottenfield), and we couldn't hold them,'' interim
manager Matt Galante said. ``When we get a 3-0 lead, I kind of
expect us to take the bull by the horn, but it didn't happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Holt (1-8) allowed runs in the second, third and fifth innings
and two more in the sixth before being replaced by Jose Cabrera.
After compiling a 2.27 ERA over a five-start stretch that included
his only win, Holt has allowed 11 earned runs in his last two
starts, covering 9 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not making good pitches,'' Holt said. ``When I get a
three-run lead, I should hold it. I didn't throw many first-pitch
strikes, and you can't do that when you get a three-run lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``All in all, it was just a bad outing. I've gotten a little out
of sync, and I need to find it again.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, he'll try to clear his head in hopes of
finishing the first half of the season on a good note. Considering
the Astros' 2-11 record in Holt's starts, he is getting plenty of
advice. And questions regarding the security of his spot in the
rotation are beginning to surface.
</P>
<P>
   On top of that, the 28-year-old righthander is wondering if the
coaching staff has confidence in him. Despite a 3-2 lead in the
third inning Thursday, Galante had Brian Williams warming up in the
third, fourth and fifth innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like that at all,'' Holt said. ``I don't know if they
don't have confidence in me or what the deal is, but it was still a
3-2 ballgame in the third inning, and I felt I could get out of
those situations. There are a lot of things being said and a lot of
things going on in my head, and I just need to block that out and
pitch like Chris Holt knows how to pitch.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to be able to do that. I'm not even worried about
(losing his spot in the rotation). I know 1-8 doesn't look good; it
looks terrible. But it doesn't completely show how I've pitched.
Whenever things aren't going well, you have people telling you to
do this and do that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just need to pitch like I'm capable of pitching. I know I'm
a better pitcher than what my record shows.''
</P>
<P>
   Galante indicated he has not lost confidence in Holt's stuff,
but he did admit to being displeased with the pitcher's location
and his approach after he was staked to a 3-0 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure he went after people the way he needed to go
after them,'' Galante said. ``I'm concerned with his location, not
his stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield (12-3) didn't have his best stuff, and the Astros
took advantage in the first when Craig Biggio hit a leadoff homer
and Carl Everett topped off the inning with a towering two-run shot
to right.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros got only three hits over the next six innings.
</P>
<P>
   Holt, who allowed the leadoff runner to reach in five of the
first six innings (three of them scored), was on the verge of
getting out of a second-inning trouble spot before throwing a wild
pitch with Ray Lankford on third base.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire singled home a run in the third, and Joe McEwing's
fifth-inning sacrifice fly tied the score at 3. Galante pulled the
plug on Holt after McGwire walked to open the sixth inning and
Lankford followed with a double.
</P>
<P>
   Cabrera gave up an RBI single to Fernando Tatis, a sacrifice fly
to Edgar Renteria and a seeing-eye, two-out double to Bottenfield
after an intentional walk. The ball dropped between Biggio and
right fielder Derek Bell.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bidge came pretty close to it,'' Galante said. ``But he
(Bottenfield) just hit the ball where no one could get to it. The
disheartening thing is that we went to a 3-0 count on him. That was
an out waiting to happen, and we didn't get it.''
</P>
<P>
   Bottenfield left after facing two batters in the sixth, and the
Astros got a run when Rick Croushore walked Jeff Bagwell with the
bases loaded.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals scored three runs in an eighth-inning rally
highlighted by J.D. Drew's liner into center field that Everett
misplayed into the first inside-the-park home run against the
Astros since 1986.
</P>
</TEXT>
