<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0032 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 01:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6897 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-     07-02 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DaleRobertson
</P>
<P>
   &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
WIMBLEDON, England _ For the third time in four days, Wimbledon's
tarps got more court time than the tennis players. And once again
Thursday, the BBC was reduced to filling hours of air time with
ancient matches involving fading legends wielding rackets made of
Stone Age materials.
</P>
<P>
   We were given the third set of Martina Navratilova's win over
Chris Evert in the 1978 final. Martina's weapon was made of steel,
Chrissie's of wood. Both rackets appeared as small as flyswatters
and seemingly capable of generating about the same amount of
sizzle.
</P>
<P>
   Compared to the live tennis _ there were sporadic yet brilliant
interludes of same throughout the afternoon and evening _ the two
greats looked almost prissy, exchanging patty-cake serves, soft
volleys and safe, looping groundstrokes that rarely threatened to
clip a line.
</P>
<P>
   Their gentle, almost dainty style seemed more closely akin to
Lottie Dod's era, the Edwardian, than to Jelena Dokic's
millennium-straddling one.
</P>
<P>
   You were left with the impression any of the current
quarterfinalists _ including Dokic and Alexandra Stevenson, the
other teen-age qualifier she'll resume playing today _ would pummel
either of the women who together created the most compelling,
longest-running rivalry their sport has known.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, put a titanium boron graphite Kevlar weapon in
Navratilova's or Evert's mitts, rewind their body clocks, and
perhaps our contemporary bashers would be grossly overmatched.
That's why it's unreasonable, even impossible, to compare players
of different eras. The game has evolved exponentially, thanks to
its more sophisticated technology and the players' advanced
training regimens.
</P>
<P>
   Venus Williams cracked a couple of 110-mph serves at Steffi Graf
in one of the three women's matches that dragged on deep into the
damp evening's gloaming. More amazingly, perhaps, Graf smacked them
back despite what had to be marginal visibility. Thirty years ago,
as he pursued his second Grand Slam, Rod Laver rarely, if ever,
belted a tennis ball with such velocity.
</P>
<P>
   Steffi's career roots predate 1985, the year her countryman,
Boris Becker, won Wimbledon as a burly 17-year-old boomer using a
racket that's of the same species as those of today. Tennis changed
radically with Boris, who said bye-bye forever to Wimbledon this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Although arguably not for the better.
</P>
<P>
   In the intervening years, the men's grass-court game clearly has
suffered from the excess of oomph, unless your idea of
entertainment and intrigue is watching terror-stricken linespeople
duck and dodge subsonic aces that could leave them with contusions,
if not concussions.
</P>
<P>
   But women's tennis is in full flower, having maintained a
tactical element while adding sufficient muscle to cement the
ladies' status as athletes of the first rank. Graf, pursuing a 23rd
Slam title, had even admitted Wednesday that Williams, 19, sort of,
well, scares her.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, Venus hits the ball that hard.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's very tough,'' Steffi said. ``You could see the last two
years the kind of potential she has.''
</P>
<P>
   But Graf, 30, still hits the ball better _ and pretty hard
herself, too, for an old gal. Her forehand never has taken a back
seat to anyone's.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, which came more than seven hours after the start
because of more maddening weather delays that have thrown the
weekend's schedule into chaos, Graf had sufficient power and too
much crucial-point poise for Williams, who remains a work in
progress.
</P>
<P>
   Thus Steffi has an eighth Wimbledon title in her cross hairs,
with only the defending U.S. Open champion, Lindsay Davenport,
seemingly presenting a serious threat to same.
</P>
<P>
   Graf's first championship here came at Navratilova's expense in
1988, after a rain delay. The same as Boris, she brought a
different game to the court, one with which Martina wasn't
familiar, or comfortable. It continues to serve Steffi well, now
that she has recovered from serious knee and wrist injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Williams was asked what Graf had going for her.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything she wants to do,'' Venus said.
</P>
<P>
   Steffi's strokes were strong enough for her to win the French
Open, and her supreme confidence on grass compensated for Williams'
salvos. Given the skewed circumstances, the caliber of play stayed
remarkably high, equal aesthetically to Evert and Navratilova at
their peak, with a much faster pace.
</P>
<P>
   Chrissie and Martina couldn't go sideline to sideline like
Venus, never mind matching the crackling pop of her serve and the
penetrating depth of her groundstrokes. Once she solidifies her
volley
</P>
<P>
   ``Venus has the game,'' Graf said, ``and the physique, which is
equally important, (to be No. 1). I think so, yes.''
</P>
<P>
   Bigger, faster, stronger. Such is sport, hurtling through time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
