<HEADER>
A6901 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAMPAIGN-LOOPHOLE-AZR     07-02 1095
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-LOOPHOLE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOP LETTER URGES PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES TO EXPLOIT `SOFT MONEY'
LOOPHOLE
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By JEFF BARKER  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Republican Party has sent a letter to GOP
presidential candidates suggesting that the party intends to
exploit the same ``soft money'' loophole in 2000 that led to widely
criticized campaign finance practices in 1996, The Arizona Republic
has learned.
</P>
<P>
   In the June 18 letter, obtained by The Republic, the Republican
National Committee told all of the Republican presidential
contenders to ``channel'' their top donors to the RNC to help fund
``an aggressive issue advertising campaign designed to counter the
efforts of union bosses and the Democratic National Committee.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We need you to let your donors know that once they have
reached their contribution limit for (the candidate), all further
support should be channeled to the RNC,'' the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   Public-interest groups said the letter raised the issue of
whether the party was attempting to circumvent federal election
contribution limits by using soft money contributions to the RNC as
a back door on behalf of the ultimate GOP nominee. During
congressional hearing, Republicans accused President Clinton of
using the Democratic National Committee for the same purpose in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Soft money is supposed to build support for parties rather than
assist specific candidates. But both parties bent the rules during
the 1996 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Campaign finance reformers say the soft money loophole made
campaign spending limits meaningless during the 1996 campaign. The
result, they say, is that the political system is awash in big
donations given for favors that aren't available to the average
voter.
</P>
<P>
   ``This (the letter) is one of those things you don't expect to
see in writing,'' said Paul Hendrie, a spokesman for the watchdog
Center for Responsive Politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It illustrates the kind of fraud that the party-purchased ads
are. They are pretending they're not campaign ads, and a letter
like this shows this is just what they are,'' Hendrie said.
</P>
<P>
   But RNC spokesman Mark Pfeifle said, ``These dollars are not
earmarked for any one particular candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the ads would run in the heat of the campaign, Pfeifle
said they would not directly benefit any presidential candidate.
For that reason, the RNC believes soft money may be used to fund
the ads, at least in part, he said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the letter, the ads would appear after the
presidential primaries and would be designed to avoid ``a
repetition of 1996,'' when a Democratic media blitz, whose funding
later became the subject of congressional hearings, helped Clinton
defeat GOP challenger Bob Dole.
</P>
<P>
   That year, Democrats, and to a lesser extent Republicans, spent
millions of dollars on advertising financed by soft money from
wealthy donors, corporations and labor groups.
</P>
<P>
   The RNC letter suggests that the line between soft money to the
national party and direct contributions to a specific candidate
again may be improperly blurred, Hendrie said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What it tells you is down the road we're going to see a
campaign in the fall, or post-primary, that is modeled after the
kinds of campaigns that occurred in 1996, and those are problematic
campaigns. This is a precursor,'' said Fred Wertheimer, president
of Democracy 21, a public-policy group specializing in campaign
finance issues.
</P>
<P>
   Pfeifle said the ads, part of a new campaign called Media 2000,
will run after the primaries as a self-defense.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a time when Republicans are most vulnerable to
Democrat attack ads aimed at misrepresentation of the GOP message.
It's designed to counter union bosses, the Democratic National
Committee, trial lawyers, the Hollywood crowd and (Vice President)
Al Gore,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The RNC letter, which was signed by Chairman Jim Nicholson,
appears to link the planned ad campaign to the presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are determined to avoid a repetition of 1996,'' the letter
said. ``The combined Clinton/Gore, DNC and union media blitz
attacking Senator Dole and Republicans proceeded uninterrupted from
March through August and built a Democratic lead that we never
closed. That must not happen next year.''
</P>
<P>
   DNC spokeswoman Jenny Backus said, ``It's no surprise that the
Republican Party wants to go back to their same old ways, just like
the days before Nixon where we had the abuses which led to the
funding caps in the first place.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hendrie said it would be difficult for the Democrats to
rightly complain, saying, ``If anybody pioneered this whole
approach, it was Bill Clinton and the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Arizona Sen. John McCain, a Republican presidential candidate,
has introduced a bill that would prevent either party from
collecting soft money for ``issue advertising,'' as the RNC is
proposing.
</P>
<P>
   McCain said in a speech earlier this week that soft money is a
loophole ``that corrupts our political ideas, whether it comes from
big business or from labor bosses and trial lawyers.''
</P>
<P>
   Efforts to reach the presidential candidates were unsuccessful.
</P>
<P>
   But David Beckwith, a spokesman for Texas Gov. George W. Bush,
said, ``This (the letter) shows one of the major problems with
campaign finance restrictions of any kind. There will be ways to
avoid them _ legal ways _ and people encouraging others to do just
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Beckwith said Bush, the front-runner by a wide margin in the
polls and in fund-raising, hadn't decided whether to cooperate with
the RNC by encouraging his donors to contribute to the party ads
once they had given him the maximum $1,000.
</P>
<P>
   Donors who contribute to a specific candidate's campaign and to
the RNC will have the satisfaction of knowing that the campaign
will be made aware of both gifts, the letter said.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been so concerned with our fund-raising that we haven't
had time to cooperate with anyone else,'' Beckwith said. ``But,
basically, you cant blame a Republican leader for attempting to
counter abuses on the other side. To do anything else would be
unilateral disarmament.''
</P>
<P>
   But Wertheimer said the letter was a harbinger of a campaign
that may be worse than 1996, in terms of bending the rules. He said
the new RNC plan, by itself, didn't illustrate abuses because the
GOP hasn't yet picked its nominee. But he said the letter was a bad
sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're likely to have more soft money in the system in 2000.
Shame doesn't seem to work in this process,'' Wertheimer said. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 0138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0035 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 01:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
