r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-LA     07-02 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERS-PADRES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DODGERS SWEPT BY PADRES AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Of all the Los Angeles Dodgers to attack for the
offensive offense, left fielder Gary Sheffield should be last. He's
hitting .300, producing and scoring runs and drawing walks.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was Sheffield who went to Dodgers starter Darren Dreifort
after the Dodgers lost 6-3 to San Diego _ the Padres' second
three-game sweep of the Dodgers in a week _ to say the offense is
failing the pitchers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to the pitchers and said, `We have to get you some runs
to give you something to work with,''' Sheffield said. ``We have to
make your job easier. When you pitch with a cushion, it takes
pressure off the pitchers, makes it so it's not a do-or-die
situation all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres have won a club-record 13 straight and at 38-38 are
.500 for the first time since the 12th game of the season. The
last-place Dodgers (34-42) have lost four straight overall and
seven straight to the Padres.
</P>
<P>
   In going 8-17 in June, the Dodgers scored in the first inning in
four games. Ditto on the first day of July, though they did give
Dreifort a 2-0 lead with runs in the second and third inning. In
fact, the Dodgers scored first in each game of the series.
</P>
<P>
   But the Padres loaded the bases in the fourth with none out and
scored on a fielder's choice, a single and a groundout to take a
3-2 lead. Quilvio Veras hit a solo shot in the fifth to make it
4-2.
</P>
<P>
   So while the Padres scratched and clawed for runs by making
contact and getting runs with outs, the Dodgers offense is feeling
the pressure.
</P>
<P>
   Devon White scored in the second by running through a stop sign,
and Dreifort failed to get a bunt down with two runners on in the
fifth. Raul Mondesi, batting leadoff for the first time in six
years, then singled in one run instead of two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we can do anything right,'' injured Dodgers
shortstop Mark Grudzielanek said. ``I've never seen anything like
it. I don't know if there's a cloud over this team right now, but
it's got to be lifted for there to be success.''
</P>
<P>
   The Padres tacked on two runs in the eighth with back-to-back
homers by Ruben Rivera and Wally Joyner. Rivera, who robbed Eric
Karros of a homer Friday with a great catch, made another
spectacular catch against the wall in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Rivera also happens to be the model of why the Padres are
playing well. He's got loads of talent, but entered each of the
three games as a defensive replacement.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's working out and everybody's happy,'' Rivera said. ``I'm
happy. I'm just waiting for my time. But I'm happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreifort (6-7) allowed four runs in six innings in the loss.
Matt Clement (5-7) pitched 52/3 innings for the win, and Trevor
Hoffman got his 20th save.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told the guys to hang with it,'' Dodgers manager Davey
Johnson said. ``There's a long way to go. You can turn things
around. Offensively, we have to do something. The look we had today
(with Mondesi leading off) wasn't bad. I'd like to do some other
things with the lineup, but right now we're having trouble scoring
runs, getting base hits.''
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers, 14th in the NL in scoring, had eight runs and 17
hits against the Padres. They also went 3 for 38 (.079) from the
seventh inning even though one game was tied and another was a
one-run contest at the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are 8{ games out of first but that's in the mediocre
NL West.
</P>
<P>
   ``Luckily, we're in this division,'' Sheffield said. ``For us to
play the way we are playing, we're still in striking range.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
