<SLUG> BC-BBN-DODGERNOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JOHNSON LOOKS TO `JUMP-START' OFFENSE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ Davey Johnson is trying everything to break Raul
Mondesi _ and the Los Angeles Dodgers _ out of their offensive funk
that has lasted 76 games.
</P>
<P>
   Two days after the Dodgers manager batted Mondesi sixth for the
first time in two years, Johnson moved Mondesi to the leadoff spot
for the first time in six years as the search for offense
continues.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to jump-start him and our offense _ be a Bobby
Bonds-type,'' Johnson said. ``We definitely have to try something
offensively to free us up some more. We're not meshing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi began July by going 1 for 5 with an RBI in Thursday's
6-3 loss at San Diego. Usual leadoff hitter Eric Young hit .346 on
the six-game road trip, but Johnson wanted to mix things up because
the offense still isn't performing even adequately.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I've got to be right-handed (in the lineup), I might as
well rub my finger in there quick,'' Johnson said. ``When I look at
what we're doing offensively, as a group, we have to try something.
I'm going to keep throwing things against the wall.''
</P>
<P>
   It's pretty much gotten to the point where Johnson is ready to
pound his head against a wall. The Dodgers are 14th in the NL in
runs scored (340) and hit .257 and drove in 96 runs in 25 games
(8-17) in June.
</P>
<P>
   Mondesi's a shining symbol. He hit .210 with one homer and six
RBI in June. His averaged dropped from .305 at the end of April to
.261.
</P>
<P>
   His insertion as the leadoff hitter, instead of the cleanup
spot, where he's batted 63 times, marks the first time he's hit
there since Sept. 29, 1993, against Chicago. It's the fourth time
Mondesi hit leadoff in his career. He was 6 for 13 with a triple,
homer, four RBI and two runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek to begin rehab: Injured shortstop Mark
Grudzielanek, who's been out since breaking his hand June 2, will
begin a rehab assignment today for Single-A San Bernardino at Lake
Elsinore.
</P>
<P>
   ``Davey will be looking to see how I do, see how I feel out
there,'' Grudzielanek said. ``... 10 to 15 at-bats and I'll be
ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, who's hitting .284, said he's hoping to be
activated either Sunday or Monday. That would cause a logjam among
middle infielders, and Johnson said he'd like to remain with five
outfielders if Todd Hollandsworth's injury isn't serious. But none
of the Dodgers infielders have options remaining, which could
expose Tripp Cromer on the waiver wire.
</P>
<P>
   June swoon, July jolt?: This is for those who are a step beyond
eternal optimists. The Dodgers' 8-17 mark in June is their worst
for one month in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But the Dodgers' public relations staff, whose job it is to find
the silver lining in even tornadic situations, came up with this
one: In the past two Julys, the Dodgers are 37-17 (.685). They went
17-10 last season and 20-7 in 1997. In the previous two Junes, the
Dodgers were 26-29.
</P>
<P>
   In closing: Right-hander Antonio Osuna (elbow surgery) threw
another bullpen session before the game. ``Osuna threw a great pen,
threw some breaking balls, about 60 pitches,'' Johnson said. Osuna
will face live hitters before Sunday's game at Dodger Stadium and
could be sent on a rehab assignment shortly thereafter....
Outfielder Todd Hollandsworth returned to Los Angeles before the
game to have his ailing left triceps examined. Johnson said the
swelling and pain are symptomatic of a bruise.... Tonight's series
opener against the Giants is sold out, as is Sunday's
fireworks-highlighted night game.
</P>
</TEXT>
