<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-ODOM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODOM FINDS HIS WAY TO L.A.
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The symbolism may not have been orchestrated, but
it was loud.
</P>
<P>
   Rows of Convention Center windows presented a view of the rising
Staples Center at point-blank range, but also managed to frame a
first-hand look at this year's touchstone of Los Angeles Clippers
construction.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't ask for anything more,'' said 19-year-old Lamar
Odom, referring to his NBA opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   It was 21 hours after the Clippers realized that dropping to
fourth position in the NBA Draft lottery wouldn't separate them
from the type of player an NBA team can build on.
</P>
<P>
   Odom, who has been something of a hoop vagabond, spent the past
two weeks sticking his foot in and out of the draft waters. At
Thursday's welcome to L.A. press conference, he discussed the
personal uncertainty that made drafting him a risk the Clippers
were happy to assume.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think maybe I was a little scared,'' Odom said of his
reluctance to leave Rhode Island after one official season for a
high-paying and high-profile life in the NBA. ``My whole life was
about to change.''
</P>
<P>
   Clippers employees believe the same can be said for theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we realized the draft had gotten down to the fourth pick
and he was still on the board,'' Clippers coach coach Chris Ford
said, ``we were thrilled. He's made some mistakes, but we will
judge Lamar Odom from this day forward.''
</P>
<P>
   Away from the cameras, the soft-spoken Odom, a versatile
6-foot-10 small forward, seemed relieved to be able to return his
focus to basketball and away from any decision deadlines.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost cried last night,'' he said of the NBA's draft show
at the MCI Center in Washington, D.C. ``I'm happy I was able to
share the moment with my family and some of the players I grew up
playing with.''
</P>
<P>
   The lineup from Odom's AAU days included first-round hot shots
Elton Brand, the draft's first pick, Wally Szczerbiak and Ron
Artest.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Odom is eager to use his creative passing skills for the
Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to get out there and start playing,'' said Odom,
whose desire to participate in the summer pro league at Long Beach
State may be tempered by being unable to sign an NBA contract until
Aug. 1. ``I just want to be a leader and get everyone involved.
They have plenty of players on this team who can put the ball in
the basket.''
</P>
<P>
   One of those is last year's small forward, Tyrone Nesby, whose
senior year at Nevada-Las Vegas didn't lead to selection in the
1998 NBA Draft. But it did steer Nesby to the Clippers as a free
agent, and his performance was rated by Sports Illustrated as
fifth-best statistically among rookies.
</P>
<P>
   Nesby is a free agent again, but Thursday, the Clippers tendered
him an offer, a relative formality that secures their position of
holding the right of first refusal. If he signs on offer sheet with
another team, the Clippers can keep Nesby by matching it.
</P>
<P>
   A Clippers source says the team intends to do that.
</P>
<P>
   But the biggest fish in the Clippers' potential free-agent pond
is Maurice Taylor. As of Thursday, the team can offer the power
forward a six-year contract extension. Taylor, who has become one
of the game's top young players in two pro seasons, is seeking the
maximum boost, which would pay him $70 million over those six
years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We started talking,'' Norm Nixon, Taylor's agent, said, ``and
we expect it to be completed soon.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the windows behind Nixon, the Staples Center
construction crew continued pounding a little irony.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
