<SLUG> BC-BBA-DEVIL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RAYS STING RED SOX AGAIN 
</HEADLINE>
 RAYS-RED SOX-BOS   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LARRY WHITESIDE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON _ Nothing like a dose of reality to remind the Red Sox
their position in the American League East is extremely fragile.
There are still 10 games before the All-Star break, so the season
is far from over.
</P>
<P>
   That point was brought home dramatically Thursday &UR;  &LR; night at
Fenway Park in a 12-3 loss to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays that came on
the heels of an 11-10 Boston loss Wednesday night. Tampa Bay backed
veteran lefthander Wilson Alvarez with 16 hits, including home runs
by Miguel Cairo and Peabody's Paul Sorrento. The Sox are 3-6 this
year against the Devil Rays, 1-5 in Fenway.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox, sitting in second place in the AL East, simply were
outgunned by the fourth-place Devil Rays (11 games worse than
Boston in the standings at 34-44). Red Sox pitching was flat-out
bad. Bad location. Bad execution. Bad results.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could say something about the effect of being in two games
like the ones we played,'' said Sox manager Jimy Williams. ``You
shoot a lot of bullets in games like the first one. We put a lot of
energy into coming back three times only to lose. But I won't do
that. We have no excuses. They beat us both nights. We just have to
forget about it and move on.''
</P>
<P>
   Entering the series, the Sox were coming off a four-game set
with the White Sox in which they won three games and their bats
were sizzling. They took a 1-0 lead in the first Thursday &UR;  &LR; night,
but after Tampa gained the lead by scoring once in the second and
three times in the fourth, the Sox attack vanished until it was too
late. Alvarez left after the seventh inning, when he gave up two
more runs. But by then it didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   Jin Ho Cho, who suffered his first loss in four starts, was
knocked out in the fourth, and the bullpen could do little to slow
the Devil Ray attack.
</P>
<P>
   ``These kind of games happen sometimes,'' said Williams.
``They're swinging the bat good. They hit good and pitched good,
especially tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox were done in by backup catcher Mike DiFelice, who drove
in a career-high five runs on three singles and a sacrifice fly.
</P>
<P>
   Nomar Garciaparra singled with two out in the first to extend
his hitting streak to a season-high 16 games. Mike Stanley then
walked, and Troy O'Leary singled to left for Boston's only lead of
the night.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa tied it in the second inning after a leadoff double by
Wade Boggs, who continued his march to 3,000 with a pair of hits.
After Sorrento walked, DiFelice singled to left for his first RBI.
There would be more.
</P>
<P>
   Tampa got to Cho for three runs in the fourth. After three
decent innings, the Korean-born righthander began making mistakes
in his mechanics. ``He was under the ball,'' said Williams. ``By
that I mean he was dropped down on his release point instead of
staying on top. The ball stays high. He can't pitch like that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We made a lot of mistakes with our location both nights,''
said pitching coach Joe Kerrigan. ``When you make mistakes to major
league hitters, they're going to smack you around. Cho had poor
location. It's as simple as that. He threw a lot of backup sliders.
Fastballs that were supposed to be away that he threw in. And vice
versa. He's had four starts so far, three of them good. Let's go
back, work on the side, and see if we can find a solution.''
</P>
<P>
   Sorrento started the Tampa fourth with a double to center and
scored on a hit by DiFelice for a 2-1 lead. Randy Winn bounced into
a force out at second, but Cairo followed with a two-run homer,
giving the Devil Rays a 4-1 lead.
</P>
<P>
   ``I came back to the locker room and saw myself on TV,'' Cho
said through an interpreter. ``I saw I wasn't on top. I'll fix it
next time.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox aren't about to panic over two losses, but they
certainly don't like it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody is worried about the break right now,'' said
Garciaparra. ``We're worried about playing hard every day. Today
was just another loss. We don't look at the size, how they did it,
and how many runs they scored. We've got to go to Chicago, play a
good team, and win.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
