<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STATER-BROS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STATER BROS. EXPANDS TO FILL GAPS BETWEEN GIANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY ENRIQUE RIVERO  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Antelope Valley and Santa Clarita residents will
soon have a company in their neighborhoods that prides itself on
being an old-fashioned, customer-friendly grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Colton-based The Stater Bros. bought 43 stores from
Albertson's, including two each in Palmdale and Lancaster and one
in Canyon Country _ areas that the chain has been eagerly eyeing
for five years, said Jack Brown, the company's chairman, president
and chief executive officer.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the opportunity we've been waiting for,'' Brown said this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Brown knows competition for the consumer's grocery dollar is
coming from all sides; from Wal-Mart and its
everything-under-one-roof strategy to specialty retailers like
Bristol Farms and Trader Joe's.
</P>
<P>
   But Stater Bros. keeps doing what it does best: Sell groceries
in a traditional grocery store format. And if the company's growth
and popularity are any indications, that strategy is working just
fine.
</P>
<P>
   Ironically, Stater Bros.' most recent opportunity to grow came
because of the latest mega-merger, this one between Albertson's and
American Stores. Albertson's received regulators' approval last
week to buy the parent company of the Lucky grocery chain and
Sav-on drugstore chain on the condition that it sell 145 stores
across the West to preserve market competition.
</P>
<P>
   Stater Bros. ate up 43 of the 117 California stores for
$147.2million, adding them to the 112 it already owns. Certified
Grocers of California Ltd. bought 32 of the divested stores on
behalf of its member grocers.
</P>
<P>
   Independent grocery chains like Stater Bros. and the members of
Certified Grocers ``are looking for niches in the marketplace that
they can exploit _ and they do it very well,'' said Tom Schaffner,
a spokesman for the association.
</P>
<P>
   The five north Los Angeles County stores represent a prime
opportunity for Stater Bros. to extend its reach further from its
San Bernardino County hub, Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Stater Bros. got ``a really good deal'' on its 43-store
purchase, said Andrew P. Wolf, senior grocery industry analyst with
Scott &AMP; Stringfellow Inc. in Richmond, Va.
</P>
<P>
   ``On a per-store basis, that is really quite inexpensive,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's also a local chain up against a host of national and
often publicly traded companies that have economies of scale,
access to cheap capital and other advantages. Thus, Stater Bros.
faces challenges _ but challenges that the independents frequently
meet by offering better service and lower prices.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be even better than the big chains because of
some of the disadvantages that you face when you're up against much
bigger players,'' Wolf said.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, Stater Bros. raked in $2billion in sales last year and
was able to pay cash for its newest stores _ and all as a privately
held company, without the benefit of stockholders' money.
</P>
<P>
   As far as Brown is concerned, stockholders would only have
gotten in the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't answer to shareholders, we can do the right things
for the right reasons,'' he said. ``If we were a public company, we
would probably have had 10 shareholders' meetings to try and do
what we did with a phone call.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I did is call Albertson's. They sent me a list, I looked
at all the stores and said, We want these stores,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   The chain had first considered expanding in the Antelope Valley
about five years ago and went so far as to complete some
feasibility studies.
</P>
<P>
   Those plans, however, stalled when the desert communities where
Stater Bros. has a strong presence saw their economies decline as
military bases closed or scaled back. Rather than expand, the chain
focused on what it had.
</P>
<P>
   But now Southern California's economy is on the upswing and when
the Albertson's stores became available, Stater Bros. opened its
wallet.
</P>
<P>
   Brown said the new stores will stock everything that both Stater
Bros. and Albertson's carried. The only changes customers can
expect to see will be the elimination of in-store pharmacies.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't operate pharmacies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Part of the reason Stater Bros. chose the stores it did was that
they were all already quite successful, and in family-oriented
areas. Buying existing stores also saved the company the time and
money it would have taken to build and staff new ones from the
ground up.
</P>
<P>
   ``So we're able to acquire a going business and hopefully, all
the employees that are there now will be there with us,'' Brown
said. ``We think that's very important.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
