<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0046 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 03:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A6927 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-SILICONVALLEY-SF     07-02 1041
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-SILICONVALLEY-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 BUSH HITS RIGHT NOTES IN SILICON VALLEY  &HT;     By CARLA MARINUCCI and ROBERT B. GUNNISON  
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ In a rousing speech to Silicon Valley
executives, George W. Bush attacked President Clinton's handling of
Y2K legislation Thursday and promised lower taxes and easier
immigration rules for the high-tech industry.
</P>
<P>
   The enthusiastic response by the 500 high-tech executives
demonstrated that Democrat front-runner Al Gore's grip on the
prosperous region is less than firm, despite years of careful
political cultivation.
</P>
<P>
   For one of the few times during his three-day trip to
California, Bush tailored his basic stump speech for an industry
that ``speaks to the spirit of America.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It not only talks about the new technologies that shape our
lives,'' he said, ``but it speaks about daring and enterprise and
the ultimate American dream.''
</P>
<P>
   The special attention seemed to thrill many in the audience, who
paid $1,000 apiece to eat quiche with Bush. The Texas governor has
collected more than $5 million during his three-day swing through
California.
</P>
<P>
   One sign of slippage for Gore was the presence of Halsey Minor,
chief executive officer of C-Net, who had hosted a ``Gore Tech''
event for the vice president at his San Francisco mansion less than
two years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Another was Meg Whitman, CEO of eBay, who only two weeks ago
appeared at Gore's side at a symposium on welfare to work.
</P>
<P>
   ``For the first time, there's a viable Republican candidate,''
Whitman said in explaining her presence. She said that she has not
yet decided whom to support and that, like many of her colleagues,
she has donated to both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Whitman said she was trying to understand Bush's positions on
the issues.
</P>
<P>
   Wade Randlett, Democratic consultant for Technology Network, an
industry lobbying group that includes donors to both parties, said
Bush's effective fund raising _ a record $36.3 million _ is worse
news for his GOP rivals than for Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's campaign spokesman, Roger Salazar, said the vice
president has strong support in the high-tech industry and was not
concerned about Bush's money-raising prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pretty much on target,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's overflowing bank account attracted the attention of
President Clinton, who said in Washington, ``Money may be
important, but ideas are even more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush may choose to forgo federal matching funds, which would
cost his campaign about $16.8 million in federal dollars but allow
him to raise and spend as much as he wants from individual donors.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said such a decision by Bush would show that the Texas
Republican is ``hostile'' to campaign finance reform. ``The
American people will have to make up their minds about whether this
is an important issue or not,'' the president said.
</P>
<P>
   During a fund-raising event Thursday in Palo Alto, Calif., that
drew high-profile Silicon Valley executives, Bush got a little
ahead of himself. He told the crowd he had been to California
before but that this is ``my first trip as president of the United
States.'' He quickly caught himself and corrected, ``the soon-to-be
president of the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   In his speech, Bush underscored his record in his state's own
burgeoning technology industry and called for charter schools, free
trade and loosening restrictions on encryption software.
</P>
<P>
   Drawing a contrast with Gore, the Texas governor labeled Y2K
lawsuits ``the ambulance chase of the millennium'' _ a statement
that drew cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's comments were timely as Congress approved Thursday
protections for companies against lawsuits stemming from year 2000
computer breakdowns _ legislation that Clinton had threatened to
veto but now will sign.
</P>
<P>
   ``With this administration, wisdom comes so rarely that we
should not complain when it comes too late,'' Bush said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush also addressed a roster of other technology issues, calling
for a permanent research and development tax credit and an increase
in the number of H1B visas, which would allow high-tech firms to
import highly skilled foreign workers.
</P>
<P>
   On technology exports, Bush said ``our current system doesn't
work.'' He said America must devise better ways to protect
sensitive military technology, without hamstringing the industry.
</P>
<P>
   The success of Bush's first official visit to Silicon Valley as
a candidate was stunning to some insiders, who noted that Gore has
visited the increasingly important region nearly every month and
met with industry leaders for more than a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``They've been out here, but in reality, Bush can walk the walk
and talk the talk,'' said Brian Halla, CEO of National
Semiconductor.
</P>
<P>
   Some high-tech leaders also said that they have been
disillusioned with the Clinton-Gore administration's response to
key valley issues _ and that Gore's exclusive meetings with
industry insiders may even have fostered some resentment.
</P>
<P>
   ``The high-tech community is very savvy, and there are issues
that Clinton-Gore have not supported, like easing the regulation on
encrypted products,'' and tort reform, said Christine Hughes, a
vice president at San Jose-based Secure Computers.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are gravitating to an inclusionary candidate,'' she
said. ``Bush is not just holding sessions with the same cast of
characters.''
</P>
<P>
   Carol Bartz, CEO of Autodesk Inc. of San Rafael _ who, as one of
the industry's star female executives, has been wooed by both sides
_ raised her eyebrows when asked about Gore's celebrated savvy in
the Valley. ``People are real excited about some change,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's camp hinted that more surprises may be in store. ``I
think you're going to see some surprising things and more big-name
defections,'' said economist Michael Boskin, one of Bush's
``kitchen cabinet'' advisers from the Stanford-based Hoover
Institution.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's biggest accomplishment this week may have been his
success in grabbing the ``new money'' that Silicon Valley's
fledgling political donors represent, said venture capitalist and
Bush supporter Floyd Kvamme.
</P>
<P>
   ``The valley is 15 percent Democrat, 10 percent Republican
and,'' said Kvamme, ``75 percent wish-it-would-all-go-away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
