r w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NEWDEMS-HIGHTECH-SFCH     07-02 0902
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEWDEMS-HIGHTECH-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`NEW DEMOCRATS' WOO HIGH-TECH INDUSTRY
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     By CAROLYN LOCHHEAD 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Making their third annual Silicon Valley pilgrimage
next week, members of the burgeoning ``New Democrat'' House
coalition declared Thursday that they seek _ without apology _ to
reposition the Democratic Party as high-tech's top ally.
</P>
<P>
   Washington politicians are practically tripping over themselves
to court the high-tech industry, with the Democrats' visit coming
on the heels of the House Republicans' unveiling last week of their
``e-Contract,'' a 10-point legislative agenda.
</P>
<P>
   The Democrats' visit will , which includes an all-day session
Friday in San Francisco where C-net co-founder Shelby Bonnie will
lead a tour of his company, comes on the heels of the House
Republicans' unveiling last week of their ``e-Contract,'' a
10-point legislative agenda aimed squarely at wooing Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, we're both going after the same girl to some extent,''
conceded Rep. Adam Smith, D-Washington. But, he added, ``There's no
such thing as a low-tech district'' in Congress anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Cal Dooley, a Democrat from Visalia, Calif., who heads the
group, insisted that the high-tech community has more in common
with Democrats, at least the new variety.
</P>
<P>
   Techies, he maintained, are generally a young and socially
liberal set that gets turned off by Republican jihads on guns and
abortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Republicans are just not in sync with them,'' Dooley said.
``Democrats can provide leadership on business and economic issues,
and (the high-tech community) is much, much more comfortable with
us on social issues.''
</P>
<P>
   But Republicans point out that if young techies are concerned
about social issues, they're even more concerned about such
fundamental GOP principles as low taxes, low regulation and
protection from lawsuits.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Billy Tauzin, a Louisiana Republican and former Democrat,
laughed when he heard about the trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are they going to take their trial lawyer friends with them?''
Tauzin asked. ``Are they going to take the FCC regulators, the
local taxing authorities, the immigration and control board and the
State Department officials who won't let them export encryption
technology?''
</P>
<P>
   The New Democrat coalition, founded in part by Bill Clinton
before he became president, has grown to 63 members, including
Ellen Tauscher, Anna Eshoo and Mike Thompson, all representatives
from the San Francisco Bay area.
</P>
<P>
   ``We make no apologies for trying to reposition the Democratic
Party,'' Dooley said. Noting that many coalition members were
elected within the last four years, Dooley said the party ``is
going through its own ideological and generational changes'' that
take into account ``a sensibility toward the new economy and new
economy workers.''
</P>
<P>
   Democrats got ahead in courting high tech with the Clinton-Gore
campaign in 1992. Gore touted the ``Information Superhighway'' long
before most politicians took notice and has been a staunch
supporter ever since, making at least 30 trips to Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin conceded that Silicon Valley ``correctly gives Gore
credit for paying them attention sooner rather than later, and
that's fine.'' But, he said, Democrats ``talk the talk,'' but
Republicans ``walk the walk'' and ``can understand their issues and
won't side against them when it comes time to deciding whether the
labor unions and the lawyers are running the process here in
Washington, D.C.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Republicans and New Democrats say their voting records
prove their superior devotion. The Information Technology Industry
Council, which represents more than two dozen large computer,
software and telecommunications companies, actually surveyed nine
congressional votes 1997 and 1998, including securities litigation
reform, ``fast track'' trade negotiating authority, H1B immigrant
visa expansion, and export controls on encryption technology.
</P>
<P>
   The tally showed House Democrats with a slight edge _ 14 with
``perfect'' pro-industry voting records, versus 12 Republicans.
California Democrats Dooley, Eshoo, Tauscher and San Jose's Zoe
Lofgren all got perfect scores, along with Southern California
Republicans Brian Bilbray, Mary Bono and David Dreier. The
breakdown was more lopsided in the Senate, where 17 Republicans got
perfect scores, versus 14 Democrats. Neither of California's two
senators, Democrats Dianne Feinstein and Barbara Boxer, made the
list.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, there are plenty of signs that more and more
politicians from both parties will be voting with high tech.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is that policymakers are leery of killing the goose
that lays the golden eggs,'' said Ed Gillespie, a former top aide
to House Majority Leader Dick Armey who now lobbies for TechNet,
the Silicon Valley lobbying powerhouse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Silicon Valley is not only creating jobs in Silicon Valley,
it's creating wealth that is being broadly dispersed in the
economy,'' he said. ``People's college funds, their 401K retirement
funds are getting stuffed fatter and fatter with the gains
generated from the high-tech sector of the economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Tauzin said Washington's sudden interest reflects ``the fact
that Congress and the high-tech community are interfacing finally.
We're finally plugging into each other's ports. It's natural for
both parties to do what the parties are doing.''
</P>
</TEXT>
