<HEADER>
A6929 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r n &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-UC-OVERBILLING-SFCHRO     07-02 0830
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-UC-OVERBILLING-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 UC ACCUSED OF OVERBILLING U.S. FOR RESEARCHERS  &HT;     By TANYA SCHEVITZ 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The University of California overcharged the federal government
by almost $24 million for research by graduate students during the
past three years, according to a new report by Congress'
investigative arm.
</P>
<P>
   The yearlong General Accounting Office investigation of payments
since 1996 concluded that the university has improperly compensated
graduate student researchers $23.7 million more than allowed under
federal guidelines from the $201 million it billed for federally
sponsored research.
</P>
<P>
   ``Based on our review of the compensation paid to GSRs for
services charged to federal research grants, we found that these
payments sometimes exceeded the allowable costs that could be
charged to such grants,'' the report says.
</P>
<P>
   The report has prompted calls in Congress for stricter rules in
disbursement of grants for research financed at universities across
the nation by federal agencies such as the National Institutes of
Health and the Department of Health and Human Services.
</P>
<P>
   But UC attorney Chris Patti disputed the report's conclusions as
flawed and said the university was audited in 1997 by the
Department of Health and Human Services without any allegations of
wrongdoing in graduate student compensation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We strongly disagree with the report,'' he said. ``The only
limit on what you are allowed to charge is this vague standard on
what is reasonable compensation.''
</P>
<P>
   However, the report _ released Thursday _ says the National
Institutes of Health has grant guidelines that the university
violated by paying graduate students working on federal projects
more than first-year researchers who have already earned their
doctoral degrees. UC thus improperly charged the government $19.3
million for the compensation, it said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, the report says the university gave $4.4 million in
``unreasonable compensation'' to graduate students by paying them
more than the $23,000 then allowed per student. The rate was raised
to $26,000 last year.
</P>
<P>
   At Berkeley in 1997, 3.4 percent of the graduate student
researchers received more than the standard from grant money,
including one who was compensated $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   But Patti said the grants allow for some flexibility in how
funds are spent on a project.
</P>
<P>
   He said the report also underestimated the salary of qualified
researchers with doctoral degrees by 10 percent because
investigators used a base salary that few are paid. In addition,
they counted the fringe benefits _ tuition or fee remission _ for
graduate students but not the medical and other benefits that post
doctoral researchers get.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are comparing apples and oranges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The report also raises questions about whether the university
has underreported the taxable compensation paid to graduate
students, who get tuition or fee waivers in addition to wages.
</P>
<P>
   It says the university treats the salary and tuition and fee
remissions as compensation to be reimbursed with grant funding, but
reports only the salaries to the Internal Revenue Service.
</P>
<P>
   The report declines to make a conclusion on the issue, but
critics say the university is trying to double-dip from federal
coffers.
</P>
<P>
   However, Patti notes the report includes statements from both
the Internal Revenue Service and the National Institutes of Health
that imply there are no inconsistencies in the way the university
has been treating tuition waivers.
</P>
<P>
   The report mentions another university practice that critics say
is unethical. Students are supposed to be compensated for work
performed, but the university gives foreign students a
proportionally larger share of fee and tuition payments because
they pay a higher nonresident tuition, raising costs for taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
   While foreign students represented 21 to 24 percent of the
graduate student researchers at the university's campuses from 1985
to 1998, the report says they received 34 to 39 percent of the
$38.6 million charged to federal research grants for tuition and
fee remission.
</P>
<P>
   Critics argue that those students take their skills back to
their home countries after they graduate.
</P>
<P>
   House Commerce Committee Chairman Thomas Bliley,cq &LR;  R-Va.,
commissioned the report in response to allegations that surfaced in
a 1996 whistle-blower lawsuit that six of the nine UC campuses
recouped tuition that had been waived for graduate students by
billing the federal government for research contracts. He is now
calling for a strictly defined set of rules on compensation of
graduate student researchers from federal grants, and has asked for
a report on progress toward that goal by September 30.
</P>
<P>
   ``This compensation scheme is a misuse of government funds,''
Bliley said in a statement. ``It is a disturbing example of how
weak guidance in federal programs can lead to waste and abuse by
the recipients of those programs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
