r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CAR-JARRETT-COX     07-02 0871
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-JARRETT-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jarrett is halfway home with biggest lead of year
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daytona Beach, Fla. _ The way NASCAR driver Dale Jarrett figures
it, he probably has lost four or five layers of skin from the heel
of the foot he rests on the hot floorboard of his No. 88 Ford.
</P>
<P>
   To prepare himself for the nearly unbearable temperatures he
endures every week during a Winston Cup race, Jarrett installed a
sauna in his home in Hickory, N.C. Twice a week, he turns the
temperature to 120 degrees and stays inside the sauna for about an
hour. And he avoids cool temperatures at all costs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm with my family, that's one thing,'' Jarrett said, ``but
otherwise, I'll never be in a car with air-conditioning. And if I
get in a restaurant that's cold, I'll leave. I'm really not doing
myself any favors by staying in cold air.''
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett, 42, won't have to worry about cooling off anytime soon.
He'll face plenty of heat during the next five months, as he tries
to maintain a 157-point lead in the Winston Cup standings.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's main challengers _ Bobby Labonte, Mark Martin, Jeff
Burton, Jeff Gordon and rookie Tony Stewart all are within 400
points _ begin their second-half assaults in Saturday night's Pepsi
400 at Daytona International Speedway.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first half of the season, you just kind of position
yourself to try and win the championship, and the second half is
where you try to capitalize from what you learned in the first
half,'' said Jarrett, who has held the points lead for six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Generally, over the last three years, the second half of the
season has been a better part of the season for us, but it's gonna
have to be pretty good to be better than our first half.''
</P>
<P>
   Through 16 of 34 races, Jarrett has two victories and 12
top-five finishes. He finished outside the top 10 only twice _ 37th
after wrecking in the season-opening Daytona 500 and 11th in the
Las Vegas 400, the third event.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's current points lead is the largest any driver has held
this season, and he seems to be getting stronger. Both of his
victories came in the last six races, and he started sixth or
better in three of the last four events.
</P>
<P>
   Jarrett's recent run _ fifth at Dover, first at Michigan, third
at Pocono and sixth at Sears Point _ offset a serious challenge by
Gordon, the two-time defending Winston Cup champion. Gordon had one
victory and three runner-up finishes in June, but gained only 40
points on Jarrett.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the scenario better when (someone else) goes home and
cusses me, instead of me going home and cussing him,'' Jarrett
said. ``We've known what it's like the last few years to really run
good and not gain any points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're on a good roll right now'' he said, ``and hopefully we
can continue that. We want to be out front, and we want to make
those guys chase us. We know there's still a long way to go,
because it's a long season where a lot of things can happen, but we
also realize that right now we're kind of controlling things. We'll
enjoy it while we can. I don't know how long it will last.''
</P>
<P>
   In the 1990s, only three drivers who led the points standings
with 18 races remaining won the Winston Cup championship _ Dale
Earnhardt in '91 and '93 and Gordon in '97. Only Earnhardt's
209-point lead on Rusty Wallace in 1993 was larger than Jarrett's
at this point in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Jarrett's) running good, and they're finishing good,'' Gordon
said. ``It's quite a lot of points that we have to close. I'm not
saying we're out of it. We're just going to keep doing what we've
been doing and see what happens.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Gordon trailed Jeremy Mayfield by 36 points with 18
races left, but Gordon won the title by 364 points over
second-place Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gordon, who is fifth in points and trails Jarrett by 314,
says it could take a complete collapse by the drivers in front of
him for him to win his third title in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mathematically, we can still win the championship,'' Gordon
said. ``There are going to have to be a lot of things that happen
first to win the championship this year. We need to keep doing what
we're doing. If we can keep that up, then the other thing that
would have to happen is that Jarrett, Burton, Labonte and Martin
would all have to have problems. ... Those things are not likely.''
</P>
<P>
   Ned Jarrett, a former driver who won 50 Winston Cup races in 14
seasons, says his son's close finishes in the past _ Dale Jarrett
finished third, second and third in points the past three seasons _
have taught him patience.
</P>
<P>
   ``He certainly feels better than he's ever felt before, because
he's never been in this position,'' Ned Jarrett said. ``But he also
realizes that there are things that can happen and that things can
get turned around even quicker.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has made mistakes over the years and the team has made
mistakes over the years that maybe cost him a shot at the
championship,'' his father said. ``They've learned from those
mistakes. I think he's confident in his abilities and confident in
his team's ability to get the job done.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
