<HEADER>
A7080 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BORDERS-COLUMN03-COX     07-02 1021
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BORDERS-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cow books and a few to take to the beach
 &HT;    By Gary Borders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NACOGDOCHES, Texas _ Two recent photography books crossed my
path the other day, courtesy of the publisher who hopes for a kind
word in this column. I'm happy to oblige.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs in both were taken by Kathleen Jo Ryan, a
Washington-state based photographer. ``Texas Cattle Barons: Their
Families, Land and Legacy'' is a handsome coffee-table book with a
foreword by Tommy Lee Jones and essays by Elmer Kelton, a fine
novelist and author of the classic, ``The Time It Never Rained.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelton's book about the 1950s drought is one of my favorites,
one of the few novels I've read more than once, along with ``All
The King's Men'' by Robert Penn Warren and ``Prince of Tides'' by
Pat Conroy. The fact that he wrote the essays for ``Cattle Barons''
was incentive enough to take a closer look.
</P>
<P>
   The book depicts through Ryan's photos and Kelton's essays the
stories of 13 modern cattle ranches, in South Texas, the Panhandle,
Big Bend Country _ with only one in our neck of the woods: Broseco
Ranch near Clarksville.
</P>
<P>
   The photographs are somewhat uneven. All in color, more than a
few are absolutely gorgeous, but there are also a few that should
have been culled because of exposure or composition problems.
</P>
<P>
   Luckily, the best of the photographs make up for the mediocre,
like a two-page horizontal shot of a cowboy getting ready to rope a
calf at 6666 Ranch in the Panhandle, or the photo of a woman
watching a thunderstorm in the distance while checking the goats at
her South Texas ranch.
</P>
<P>
   Kelton's essays, like his novels, are straightforward, sparely
written and contain a minimum of hyperbole. This is straight
journalism, enlivened by the words of these ranchers, most of whom
are third-or-fourth generation cattlemen.
</P>
<P>
   Here's Primo Walker of the Vaquillas Ranch saying, ``We're
cattle people. The stock market is not real. Everything is floating
on computer screens.''
</P>
<P>
   Lest one get too romantic, Kelton is quick to point out that
ranching is very much a business, and those who survive learn to
adapt to the times. As Mike Gibson of the 6666 Ranch points, out,
``We have to watch everything very closely. It used to be that
you'd pretty much run a ranch out of the daybook in your shirt
pocket. Not now.''
</P>
<P>
   Two of the ranches featured are owned by men who made their
money somewhere else: West Texan Clayton Williams Jr., who got rich
in oil and gas and ran unsuccessfully for governor against Ann
Richards in 1990; and Nolan Ryan, future Hall-of-Famer, who has a
spread outside Alvin, south of Houston. It certainly helps to
survive in ranching if one has another source of income to get
through the hard times, like the drought last year _ which was when
this book was compiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``Texas Cattle Barons'' (192 pages, $49.95) is published by Ten
Speed Press of Berkeley.
</P>
<P>
   Also from Ten Speed Press comes a companion book in softcover:
``Deep in the Heart of Texas: Texas Ranchers in Their Own Words''
($24.95, 158 pages.), photographed and compiled by Kathleen Jo
Ryan. Shot entirely in black-and-white and reproduced in deep
selenium tones, the photography appears stronger, though my
prejudice for black-and-white over color probably comes to play
here.
</P>
<P>
   Ryan talks extensively to the ranch owners of the same outfits
featured in ``Cattle Barons.'' The talk is more technical _ pasture
rotation, sources of outside income, the differences between
raising cattle in West Texas and East Texas _ but it's a good
companion piece to ``Cattle Barons,'' especially as a gift to that
wanna-be cattle raiser who's looking to buy a little spread and
raise some Hereford cross.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately, I got that itch out of my system some years ago.
I'll settle for looking at the pictures.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, while we're talking about books, here are a few
summertime reading suggestions if you're on vacation, roasting your
skin on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jacquelyn Mitchard had a blockbuster debut with ``Deep End of
the Ocean,'' the story of a mother searching for her young son
who's snatched away in a hotel lobby. ``The Most Wanted,'' her
second novel now out in paperback, is set in Texas outside of San
Antonio and features a 15-year-old girl who marries an older
inmate, the female attorney who helps her to do so, and what
happens when the inmate escapes from prison and comes after his new
bride and her baby. It's one of those books that you'll get a
sunburn reading on the beach, because it's nearly impossible to put
down. Mitchard, a syndicated columnist based in Milwaukee, is
obviously a newcomer to Texas, but except a few exaggerated
attempts at capturing our dialect, the book is engrossing and
entertaining.
</P>
<P>
   _ Anna Quindlen used to write a column for The New York Times
before taking up fiction writing full-time, and ``Black and Blue,''
her latest in paperback, is a heartbreaking story of a woman trying
to escape an abusive husband. She and her young son flee New York
for Florida.
</P>
<P>
   This is not a cheerful book, but it is skillfully done. Quindlen
is quickly establishing herself in a class along with a very few
female American writers _ Anne Tyler, to name one. Oprah picked it
for her book club, which is good enough for me.
</P>
<P>
   _The above novels can be found in the supermarket or any
bookstore, but you might have to order ``Sugar Land,'' the second
novel by Joni Rogers (Spinsters Ink, Duluth, Minn.) It tells the
story of two Texas sisters who used to be singing sensations as
kids, ala Leanne Rimes. Now they're approaching middle age, are
married to dootbrains and trying to figure out exactly what went
wrong.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sugar Land'' is funny and heartbreaking at times, with some
priceless one-liners that sound exactly like a big-haired Texas
girl had uttered them.
</P>
<P>
   Enjoy your summer reading and don't forget the sunblock.
</P>
<P>
   Gary Borders is editor and publisher of The Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel. His e-mail address is gborders(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
