<SLUG> BC-EMURRAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    There's more to remember
 &HT;    By Ernest Murray
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LUFKIN, Texas _ A recent column on they way things used to be
really struck a chord with readers. I've been flooded with notes,
letters and e-mails from folks around the courner and across the
country who remember the way were.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Hammer from Salida, Calif., wrote: ``I'm closing in on 55
years of scattered memories, here's a few that I recall:''
</P>
<P>
   Going into a small Texaco gas station that sold bread, milk,
butter _ the essentials and coming out with a quart of milk and a
loaf of bread for two-bits (that's where I learned what two-bits
meant).
</P>
<P>
   When TV meant one channel and 5-6 hours of broadcast time each
day.
</P>
<P>
   When the first color broadcast was, ``sing-a-long with Mitch''
and we watched it!
</P>
<P>
   When potato chips came in a cardboard box with no other
wrapping.
</P>
<P>
   When getting a ``swat'' from the coach meant you had slightly
misbehaved.
</P>
<P>
   When buying a TV that cost almost as much as the family car and
had only 12 channels on the tuner.
</P>
<P>
   I earned 25 cents a week and that 25 cents got me into the movie
(news, cartoon, feature and serial) plus a candy bar with 10 cents
left over for a comic book and more candy.
</P>
<P>
   Mary Meaux, at mmeaux(at)ruralcomm.com, wrote:
</P>
<P>
   ``I really enjoyed remembering the old days. I was born in '65
so I have a little different perspective but it all amounts to the
same idea.''
</P>
<P>
   No caller ID so when someone called a store and asked if ``they
have Prince Albert in a can,'' the call couldn't be traced.
</P>
<P>
   When the cable boxes came into style, they went up to like 60 or
so channels and we would have to stand there and switch through
each channel _ no remote.
</P>
<P>
   Being worried about my ``permanent school record.''
</P>
<P>
   Remembering when there was no PG-13 movies, just PG.
</P>
<P>
   Trick-or-treating when there were only a few teens who tried to
pass off as a little kid.
</P>
<P>
   You didn't hear about people breaking into cars to steal a
stereo system with an 8 track.
</P>
<P>
   The antics of the worst-behaved kid in the class back then would
be laughed at nowdays.
</P>
<P>
   My children aren't scared of the same shows that terrified me at
their age.
</P>
<P>
   Having the checker at the grocery store look for the price on
the product before ringing it up.
</P>
<P>
   Myrna and Al Rochelle, mimig(at)clarksville.net sent along these
remembrances:
</P>
<P>
   When you could mail 11 letters for $.33.
</P>
<P>
   When people respected police and vice versa.
</P>
<P>
   When the most popular drugs were aspirin and Black Draught.
</P>
<P>
   When farm implement power ran on corn and hay.
</P>
<P>
   When smoking was socially acceptable and homosexuality wasn't.
</P>
<P>
   When the banks paid you for your checking account business and
supplied checks.
</P>
<P>
   When welfare and bankruptcy were considered to be social
stigmas.
</P>
<P>
   When mothers actually cooked supper from scratch and didn't take
special orders.
</P>
<P>
   When pickup trucks were only bought and used for work purposes.
</P>
<P>
   When no self-respecting female would be caught dead driving a
pickup, Jeep or other SUV.
</P>
<P>
   When the USA produced more things than it consumed.
</P>
<P>
   When items for sale in a store had price tags on them.
</P>
<P>
   When an automobile didn't cost more than most houses.
</P>
<P>
   When the high school building was bigger than its parking lot.
</P>
<P>
   When teachers drove better cars than the students.
</P>
<P>
   When you wanted sweetener on your cereal, you had to put it on.
</P>
<P>
   When walking was a principal means of getting somewhere _ not an
exercise routine.
</P>
<P>
   When high school graduates could read and write _ at grade
level.
</P>
<P>
   When there was only one telephone in the house, if any.
</P>
<P>
   Send me your thoughts on the way we were and I'll print more.
</P>
<P>
   Ernest Murray is managing editor of The Lufkin Daily News.
E-mail: emurray(at)coxnews.com. Mailing address: P.O. Box 1089,
Lufkin, TX 75902.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
