A7083 &Cx1f; tad-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN03-COX     07-02 0583
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MCCARTY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Don't sleep on drive-in movies
 &HT;    By Mary McCarty
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ As the credits rolled on the new ``Tarzan''
movie, the kids in the row in front of us at the drive-in clambered
on top of the van, beat their chests and belted out a lusty Tarzan
yell.
</P>
<P>
   I nudged Jim and said with satisfaction, ``I have a feeling
we're not at Showcase any more.''
</P>
<P>
   They don't have stadium seating and 16 screens, but only at the
drive-in can you bellow the Tarzan yell. Only at the drive-in can
you pack the kids in the car in their PJs. Only at the drive-in can
you say what you like without being shushed. Only at the drive-in
can half the family fall asleep and snore with impunity.
</P>
<P>
   The cinemas can be comfortable, luxurious even, but going to the
drive-in can still be an event, an adventure.
</P>
<P>
   They seem so much a part of the landscape of another era, you
almost forget they're there. Until summer comes, the new Disney
movie arrives, and it's time for the drive-in.
</P>
<P>
   Chances are, you have to remind yourself to go. The typical
drive-in is a mom-and-pop operation, with a limited advertising
budget.
</P>
<P>
   Once you get there, you wonder why you don't go more often. It's
a chance to relive your own childhood while creating memories for
your kids.
</P>
<P>
   Jim grew up in one of those draconian households where soda pop
and candy were not distributed liberally. Bedtimes and behavioral
codes were strictly enforced. The one exception: drive-in nights.
The Coke was put on ice, the candy bars packed, the popcorn popped
over the stove (none of that namby-pamby microwave stuff) and
stashed in brown paper bags.
</P>
<P>
   ``Going to the drive-in had a Christmas feeling to it,'' Jim
said, ``a feeling of something out of the ordinary.''
</P>
<P>
   He'd get into his PJs and vow not to fall asleep, to make it
through the late-late feature. By the beginning of the second
feature, he invariably crashed in the back of the station wagon.
</P>
<P>
   There are those (SET ITAL) other (END ITAL) drive-in memories,
of course, which Jim and I, high school wallflowers that we were,
failed to take proper advantage of. ``It was an adventure to go to
the drive-in, even more so on a date,'' recalled one friend.
``Being a Catholic girl, I started much too late, but going to the
drive-in turned into a coming-of-age rite for some people.''
</P>
<P>
   The drive-in audience seems to be mostly families these days,
with a minimum of the passion-pit activity so common in my high
school years. A scientific survey of my high school-age baby
sitters confirmed my hypothesis: Kids may go together in groups,
but the drive-in is no longer a hot date ticket. Too many bugs, too
few screens.
</P>
<P>
   From time to time, there is talk of a drive-in revival, but
local and national trends indicate otherwise. Two years ago, the
Belmont Auto Drive-In breathed its last, after 50 years in
business. Today, only the Dixie Drive-In, the Melody 49 Twin
Drive-In, the Skyborn Cruise-In near Fairborn and the Park Lane
Drive-in are left.
</P>
<P>
   Some kids told me they had never been to the drive-in. Maybe the
drive-in movie _ a tradition begun 66 years ago this summer in
Camden, N.J. _ will slowly go the way of the silent movie.
</P>
<P>
   I hope not. This summer, do your part to keep this piece of
Americana alive. Make one less trip to the multiplex and visit an
old friend.
</P>
<P>
   All in favor, give a Tarzan yell.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
