<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MINTER-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    A store of Southern heritage
 &HT;    By Jim Minter
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   FAYETTE COUNTY, Ga. _ The older we get, the wiser we get, at
least in some respects. One thing we learn is to be careful about
ranking people. So I won't say that Gene Asher is my most loyal
friend, and about the finest human being I know.
</P>
<P>
   What I can say is that if I made up such a list, Gene would rank
very, very high. He would also rank high on a lot of other people's
lists. He has been collecting friends since before Tech High School
in Atlanta through the University of Georgia, the sports
departments of both The Atlanta Journal and Constitution and a
career in insurance, Korea and the Marines, where he rose to the
rank of colonel.
</P>
<P>
   In youth he was a better-than-average amateur boxer. As a child
prodigy he toured Georgia theaters giving Al Jolson impersonations,
his mother at the piano. He can still be persuaded to do a few
Jolson numbers on occasion.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost 10 years ago when he invited me to lunch, to hear
one of his ideas. He wanted to start a newspaper, something not
easy to do, as a lot of dreamers have discovered on the way to
bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   Before lunch was over he had sketched out a table of contents
and the newspaper had a name: The Jewish Georgian.
</P>
<P>
   Most new publications have a short lifespan. But they don't have
Gene Asher for a founding editor and publisher. The Jewish
Georgian, 10 years old next year, is alive and well, although Gene
has semiretired to the position of consulting editor and columnist.
</P>
<P>
   I pick up a copy whenever I can. The newspaper is exactly what
he intended it to be: a warm and upbeat celebration of Jewish life
in Georgia, present and past. I recently read his story about
Charles Harris, a South Georgia icon from Ocilla, who has been
chairman of the Board of Regents and who in World War II commanded
the Navajo Talkers, a platoon of combat radiomen who communicated
in their native language, totally baffling Japanese eavesdroppers.
</P>
<P>
   The latest issue features the Alexander family, descended from a
Revolutionary War hero and the only American-born Jew among
Atlanta's pre-Civil War pioneers. The Alexanders are now
sixth-generation Atlantans. Cecil Alexander, a Distinguished Flying
Cross Marine pilot in World War II, headed the architectural team
that built Atlanta Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The Jewish Georgian is a reminder of how much Jewish history is
a part of our Southern heritage, especially in rural areas. Every
small town had a ``Jew Store'' selling ``small dry goods,'' mostly
needles, thread, buttons, clothing: household items on the shopping
lists of those not overly affluent. Ours in Fayetteville belonged
to Mr. Rosenbloom.
</P>
<P>
   Most Jew Stores are gone, or have grown into much larger
operations, like Charles Harris' in Ocilla. Some became Rich's and
Macy's and Neiman Marcus.
</P>
<P>
   The Jew Store is a Southern icon that shouldn't be forgotten,
and now, according to the Jewish Georgian, it isn't. Stella
Suberman, whose father was a small dry goods merchant in a small
Tennessee town, has written a book: ``The Jew Store.'' When Cecile
Waronker, who reviewed it, tried to buy a copy at an Atlanta
bookstore, the clerk misunderstood. She began a computer search for
``The Juice Store.''
</P>
<P>
   St. Simons was sold out when I inquired. The store owner said
it's becoming a classic, and that first editions are going to be
very valuable. Anybody who has been sent by a grandmother to buy
buttons or bobbins, or a spool of thread for a foot-pedaled Singer
sewing machine, ought to have a copy.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did Barnesville have a Jew Store?'' I asked an elderly friend,
Capt. Alex Moye. ``Of course,'' he said. ``It only closed this
year.'' Neither Alex nor I, when we were growing up on the farm,
knew why the Jew Store was called the Jew Store. I thought it just
another shopping stop, like Custard Mize's store, or McElwaney's,
or John M. Jackson's, where we bought on credit to be paid off when
cotton was picked, ginned and sold.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Jew Store'' is a funny, poignant, revealing account of a
family living in a small town, separated from neighbors by
religion, by country of origin; trying to make a living and a life;
being accepted but not totally accepted.
</P>
<P>
   The book made me think of the Jewish family from south Fayette
County. The grandfather walked dirt roads with his backpack,
selling ``small dry goods'' to farm wives. One of his
granddaughters taught with my mother at the Woolsey school. Her
brother, after finishing business college, had to change his name
to get a job in Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Waronke, the Jewish Georgian reviewer, grew up in Clio,
S.C., (pop. 1,000), where her father owned the Jew Store. She wrote
about an Indian who came in needing long underwear for the winter,
but could afford only a pair of overalls and 25-cent socks. She
watched her father reach under the counter and discreetly roll and
wrap a pair of long johns inside the overalls, careful not to
injure his customer's pride. I don't think they do that at the big
discount stores in our nice new malls.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Minter is a former editor in chief of The Atlanta
Journal-Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
