<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NETHAWAY-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Motor vehicles another example of right vs. privilege debate
 &HT;    By Rowland Nethaway
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WACO, Texas _ Operating a motor vehicle is a privilege, not a
right.
</P>
<P>
   That's often repeated and assumed to be true.
</P>
<P>
   After all, while the Constitution gives Americans the right to
own and use guns, it doesn't say a word about the right of
Americans to own and drive cars.
</P>
<P>
   A nitpicker might point out that the founders didn't make it a
right to own and drive cars because cars wouldn't be invented for
another 100 years or so.
</P>
<P>
   By the same token, the founders also didn't give Americans the
right to fly planes or keep and bear nuclear weapons, unless an
argument can be made that the right to keep and bear arms includes
atomic bombs and planes are needed to fly these personal weapons to
selected targets.
</P>
<P>
   While the framers of the Constitution couldn't have known what a
car was, they knew good and well what a gun was.
</P>
<P>
   Guns were the most modern, sophisticated and deadly weapons
available to the human race in the last quarter of the 18th
century. The founders used them to overthrow their legitimate
government and establish a new government more to their liking.
</P>
<P>
   Every American who celebrates the July 4 holiday has to be
thankful that the founders had access to the guns that were needed
to win this nation's independence.
</P>
<P>
   But just as the founders couldn't have foreseen the invention of
the automobile, they also couldn't have foreseen the invention of
tanks, shoulder-fired Stinger missiles, flamethrowers or easily
concealed machine pistols.
</P>
<P>
   Pro- and anti-gun Americans will probably be arguing what the
founders meant for the next 100 Independence Days.
</P>
<P>
   Right now, I'm more interested in what the founders might have
said about the right of citizens to drive a car.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps some people say that driving a car is a privilege and
not a right because they believe that the only rights Americans
have are those spelled out in the Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   That's certainly a point of view. But without access to cable
TV, telephones and the Psychic Hotline, that reasoning puts a heavy
burden on men who could not foresee the future.
</P>
<P>
   For people who believe the Constitution a living document
subject to continued interpretation, perhaps the reason that
driving an automobile is considered a privilege and not a right is
because this activity applies only when people drive cars on public
roads, not on private land.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the argument would hold that if the public paid
for the road with tax dollars, then the public, through its
government, gets to decide who can use the road and under what
conditions.
</P>
<P>
   If that is the case, then what justification does the government
have to say who can fly airplanes? No tax dollars paid for the sky.
</P>
<P>
   If the sky is not publicly owned, then how can the government
require that pilots undergo rigorous training and testing before
they can fly?
</P>
<P>
   The government must have laid claim to ownership of the sky when
no one was looking.
</P>
<P>
   You can drive your new Corvette 150 mph on your own property,
but you can't pull over and fire machine guns or other
government-banned arms.
</P>
<P>
   One of this nation's greatest strengths is the ability to search
for the meaning of rights specifically granted in the Constitution,
find the limits of specifically granted rights and uncover rights
and limitations through constant interpretation.
</P>
<P>
   For my part, I think that operating a motor vehicle on a public
road is a privilege, not a right. I also believe that the
requirements to obtain a driver's license should be more like the
requirements to obtain a pilot's license. Only skilled drivers in
good physical condition should be granted the privilege to operate
a motor vehicle on a public road.
</P>
<P>
   Rowland Nethaway is senior editor of the Waco Tribune-Herald.
E-mail: rnethaway(at)wacotrib.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
