   LOOK ON THE WEB: Stories marked as a CoxNet layout are available
for purchase in paginated form: www.nytsyn.com/pageexpress.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   MISTER-FAN _ When Barbara Mason spotted a Mister Fan combination
spray bottle and small fan, she remembered seeing others use
similar products and decided to buy one. Now she's sold on what
she's dubbed her ``spritzer.'' The concept is simple: Fill the
bottle with tap water and squeeze it periodically to release a fine
mist. To add to the cooling effect, there's a battery-operated fan
with an on/off button. Similar products have names such as Mist N
Cool and Misty Mates. Consumer column. (Dayton Daily News)
</P>
<P>
   VACATION-TIPS _ If you're one of the hundreds of families
getting ready to pack up the minivan for a summer vacation, there
are a few things you'll need to know such as: turning off the main
water valve, cleaning up the yard, etc. Our safety home/garden
story offers a checklist of things to do before hitting the road.
(Flanders, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). 21. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   WARNER-ON-WOOD _ Once you understand all the principles, and
decide what you want in the way of a workbench, you can sit down
with paper and a ruler or a simple drawing program on the computer,
and make your own dimensioned plans with notes on the construction.
(Warner, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVES FRIDAY.
</P>
<P>
   BOOKS-BORDERS _ ``Texas Cattle Barons: Their Families, Land and
Legacy'' by Kathleen Jo Ryan is a handsome coffee-table book. Also,
here's a few summertime reading picks. (Borders, Nacogdoches Daily
Sentinel) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SCIENCE/MEDICINE
</P>
<P>
   LAMB-COLUMN _ DAYTON _ We do health care a little differently
here. A market of Dayton's size can't have nationally renowned
centers for treating grave illnesses, but it can find different
ways of reaching more people and keeping them healthy. That's a
particularly valuable knack in this era of cataclysmic changes in
the way health care is delivered. (Lamb, Dayton Daily News). 21.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION
</P>
<P>
   REDCROSS-BULLOCK _ Conversation with Steve Bullock, acting
national president of the American Red Cross. Bullock is the first
African-American president of the Red Cross, and the first to come
from within the organization's ranks. (Henry, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 20.
</P>
<P>
   CURSEFREE-TV _ Less is more for many Christian homes. Now
there's a gadget that will do away with offensive words on
television and let the show go on. V-chips are out. Curse Free TV
is in. (Gushee, Palm Beach Post). 18.
</P>
<P>
   SHABBAT _ DELRAY BEACH, Fla. _ ONLINE-SHABBAT _ WEST PALM BEACH,
Fla. _ Religious law bars Jews from working, driving, or even
flipping a light switch on the Sabbath. So why has an organization
dedicated to bringing Jews back into the fold released a CD-ROM to
help guide them through Sabbath rituals when a computer is required
to view it? File the answer under D, as in desperate times call for
desperate measures. (Belkin, Palm Beach Post) MOVED MONDAY.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT-ARTS
</P>
<P>
   RADIO-FUTURE _ A Century in the Arts series continues. This is a
look at the future of radio. (MLongino, Cox News Service). FOR
SUNDAY
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-MUSICALS _ The 1970s were when Broadway and pop music
finished making their break. Now that they're nostalgic, but still
punchy, the pop-rock sounds of the decade are big on the London
stage and probably will be soon on America's. Dual reviews of
ABBA's ``Mamma Mia'' (thumbs up) and the Broadway-bound ``Saturday
Night Fever'' (thumbs down) in a broader critical look at the state
of rock musicals. Length includes fact box. (Hulbert, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 32. FOR SUNDAY
</P>
