<HEADER>
A7090 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GOT-JESUS03-COX     07-02 0731
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GOT-JESUS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Marketing a Messiah
 &HT;    By Mark Beaver
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Got Jesus?''
</P>
<P>
   Well, yes, I do, as a matter of fact. Thanks for inquiring. But
I must admit I resent the way you ask the question.
</P>
<P>
   Driving down Barrett Parkway north of Atlanta recently, I was
confronted by a stark, black billboard with white letters. The
billboard, etched in the same type face as the dairy
advertisements, merely substituted ``Jesus'' for ``milk.'' Simple
as that, ``Got milk?'' becomes ``Got Jesus?'' and somebody
somewhere thinks he's spreading the Gospel.
</P>
<P>
   All the sudden, Christianity is sounding a lot like capitalism.
The shift started innocently enough, I suppose. First it was bumper
stickers: ``God is my co-pilot,'' ``My boss is a Jewish
carpenter,'' ``In case of rapture, this vehicle will be unmanned.''
</P>
<P>
   Through the genius of marketing, you could make a generalized
statement about your beliefs while steering your minivan through an
intersection.
</P>
<P>
   Next it was WWJD bracelets. Ball caps. T-shirts. Pencils. Coffee
mugs. Etc. Seemingly, any object larger than a pinhead was posing
the question ``What Would Jesus Do?'' The purpose was genuine: In
every situation, the question reminded the Christian to ask himself
what Christ would do under the same circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   As an added bonus, the letters, like the fish symbol on cars,
identified Christians to one another. Again, sounds legit, but the
question, I confess, made me uncomfortable, a bit suspicious. To
me, ``What Would Jesus Do?'' sounded dangerously close to a catch
phrase _ something with more style than substance.
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, the trend didn't last long. Lately, I'm seeing
fewer and fewer of those WWJD products. America knows a trend when
it sees one, and soon tires of it. To a public short on attention
span, the question WWJD must be replaced by a new question: WN?
What's Next?
</P>
<P>
   Sadly, I found the answer on a billboard. I don't know how many
conversion experiences the ``Got Jesus?'' advertisement has
prompted, but I wouldn't set the number too high. Maybe if we gave
Jesus one of those little milk mustaches, folks would get the
message.
</P>
<P>
   Proselytizing has its place, don't get me wrong. I'm all for
witnessing. I grew up in a Baptist church. I'm the son of a Baptist
deacon. I'm not like some of the other naysayers who probably see
the billboard and mutter under their breaths about how the ``Jesus
Freaks'' are at it again.
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, I appreciate a person's attempt to share his or
her faith, since religion and spirituality seem to be the only
subjects that are off limits in our society.
</P>
<P>
   But the question ``Got Jesus?'' strikes me as a concession to a
commercial culture, one that can sum up something as complex as
religious faith with a slogan.
</P>
<P>
   Packaging religion as a product is selling it out. It suggests,
however innocently, I can drop by Winn-Dixie after work to pick up
some Jesus.
</P>
<P>
   Someone's going to argue that this advertising approach is only
using our culture's means to achieve heavenly ends.
</P>
<P>
   Last time I checked, though, the Good Book told me to be ``in it
but not of it.'' We're in this world, all right _ not much we can
do about that. But instead of playing by its rules, it seems we
should try to change the rules. Rise above the rules. Gandhi did
it. The Rev. Martin Luther King did it. Oh yeah, a guy named Christ
did it, too.
</P>
<P>
   After all, at the door of heaven, I don't think saying ``I got
Jesus'' will guarantee admission. Not unless heaven is a
capitalistic economy. And despite those streets of gold, I don't
think it is.
</P>
<P>
   If religious beliefs were slogan material, if they were only
products in the marketplace, I wouldn't want any part of it. A milk
mustache is a temporal thing. Religious faith, however, has eternal
implications.
</P>
<P>
   Seems to me that some of these church billboards come closer.
Some offer quotes or Scripture. To me, quotes invite contemplation,
provoke thought, ask us to go deeper. Slogans, on the other hand,
clip investigation, curb thought.
</P>
<P>
   Got Jesus? If not, don't count on picking up a quart of him to
go with a loaf of bread. Even if you've got a coupon.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Beaver, a teacher, lives in Douglasville, Ga. His e-mail
address is msbeaver10(at)hotmail.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
