<HEADER>
A7091 &Cx1f; tad-z
r t &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-VACATION-TIPS03-COX     07-02 0714
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VACATION-TIPS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Vacation tips for a safe, sound home and garden
 &HT;    By Danny C. Flanders
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ There you are, on the beach of some tropical isle and
that long pre-vacation to-do list suddenly runs through your mind:
Did I leave enough lights on? Did I unplug the TV? Did I water the
geraniums?
</P>
<P>
   Most people know the drill before getting on the road, but with
so many tasks at hand, it never hurts to be reminded.
</P>
<P>
   ``Normally, when people take vacations, they take more
precautions _ the kinds of things they should be doing day to
day,'' Atlanta police Inspector Juanita Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition, you'll need to take measures to protect your garden
so that, like your belongings, it's still around when you return.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what Smith recommends for the home:
</P>
<P>
   _ Lights. Leave on exterior lights but only if they're on a
timer so that would-be burglars don't suspect you're gone. Indoor
lights also should be on timers. ``They're a must for making the
house look as lived-in as possible,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Garbage. Never leave your garbage roll cart on the street for
more than one night because it signals you're away. Ask a neighbor
to wheel it in.
</P>
<P>
   _ Deliveries. Postpone mail and newspaper deliveries or ask a
neighbor to collect them.
</P>
<P>
   _ Keys. Don't leave out keys, no matter how hidden you think
they are. ``Anybody can see someone stooping down to get a key from
under a flowerpot or doormat, or reaching above a door,'' Smith
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Answering machines. Don't advertise you're away by leaving a
recording to that effect and don't leave notes for delivery
drivers. And don't record a greeting on your phone mail at work
stating you'll be out of the office for several days.
</P>
<P>
   _ Alarms. If you own a security system, make sure you have a
backup battery in case of a power outage. Also, alert your security
company and people on your emergency call list that you'll be out
of town.
</P>
<P>
   _ Neighbors. Ask neighbors to keep an eye on things. ``That way,
when a U-Haul backs up to your house, they'll know you're not
moving,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Patrols. Ask police to patrol your street and inspect your
property while gone. For a directed patrol, call your zone office.
</P>
<P>
   _ Appliances. Unplug appliances, such as TVs and computers, to
guard against power surges.
</P>
<P>
   _ Lawns. Ask a neighbor or hire a service to mow the lawn and
trim the shrubbery if you'll be away more than a week. ``Shrubbery
should never be higher than window level because it provides a
hiding place for peeping Toms or someone to rob you at the front
door,'' Smith said.
</P>
<P>
   A garden not only can signal that homeowners are away, but it
could mean a slow death if not tended for more than a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really helps to have a friend stop by frequently and check
on things,'' said Atlanta horticulturist Erica Glasener, who
travels often as host of Home &AMP; Garden Television's ``A Gardener's
Diary.''
</P>
<P>
   Here are some of her suggestions:
</P>
<P>
   _ Houseplants. Place houseplants in the sink or bathtub in
several inches of water and close the curtains to keep them cool.
</P>
<P>
   _ New plants. Don't plant anything new and don't fertilize
before going out of town, when extra care and maintenance might be
necessary.
</P>
<P>
   _ Trade favors. Ask a friend or neighbor to check on things
about twice a week and offer to return the favor. As a gesture of
thanks, give that person a souvenir from your trip, such as a
gardening book or a plant; or share your bounty by offering friends
their pick from your garden.
</P>
<P>
   _ Timers. Place a timer on sprinklers and soaker hoses so that
all a friend or neighbor has to do is stop by and turn on the
water.
</P>
<P>
   _ Containers. Group all pots and hanging baskets in the shade,
not only to protect them but to make it convenient for others to
water. ``That way, they won't miss anything, either,'' Glasener
said.
</P>
<P>
   _ Mulch. Freshen beds and containers with several inches of
mulch to help soil retain moisture and discourage weeds.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, chill out. Now that you've taken care of things for the
home and the garden _ relax and enjoy yourself. Remember: There
will be plenty to catch up on when you get home.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
