<HEADER>
A7092 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD03-COX     07-02 0543
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WARNER-ON-WOOD03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Joinery method should suit the furniture function
 &HT;    By Jack Warner
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The topic is, basically, how furniture is made.
</P>
<P>
   We're discussing the fact that once certain basic principles of
joinery are understood, a woodworker can make any sort of
furniture, from a workbench to a chest of drawers, without
commercial plans or ``patterns.''
</P>
<P>
   The rant was inspired by a poor reader who sent me an e-mail
inquiring where he could get a pattern for a workbench.
</P>
<P>
   There are certain kinds of joints, chiefly the mortise and tenon
and its many variations, that are used to joint pieces of wood in a
cross-grain assembly. There are other kinds of joints used in
casework, which involves the joining of two pieces of wood in which
the grain is running in the same direction, such as a chest or a
drawer.
</P>
<P>
   The best, and the cheapest, place to learn this is in Tage
Frid's first book. Its rather cumbersome title is ``Tage Frid
teaches Woodworking: Joinery: Tools and Techniques.'' You may be
able to find it in a big bookstore. If not, you can certainly find
it in any woodworking store that stocks books.
</P>
<P>
   In this book, a fine man and a great teacher shows how to make
more joints than you'll ever need with both hand and power tools
and which should be used in any given situation. It should be the
first book in a woodworker's library.
</P>
<P>
   Now, a workbench is a special-purpose piece of furniture. It
would be a mistake to simply begin building one without learning
something about them, and the various styles in which they are
commonly constructed.
</P>
<P>
   There are dozens of books and many magazine articles about
workbenches. There is even a big, beautiful coffee table book about
them. Check out as many as you can _ you canfind some in your local
library.
</P>
<P>
   Certain things are true about any style. A workbench undergoes
severe stress, and it must be unwavering. One that sways or quivers
is useless. Thus it must be very heavy. It is also good to make the
lower stretchers adjustable so that any play which develops during
use may be taken out.
</P>
<P>
   The top must be absolutely flat.
</P>
<P>
   Provision must be made for at least one vise. The Scandinavian
type of bench has two vises; the standard cast iron vise at one end
of the working side, and a shop-built, integrated shoulder vise at
the other end. You can buy a hardware kit for the shoulder vise,
but making it properly is still a formidable task. This is why many
woodworkers begin with the English style bench, which has just the
cast iron vise.
</P>
<P>
   My correspondent wanted a bench with two drawers. I wouldn't
fool with drawers in a workbench, but if you really want them you
can use ordinary kitchen hardware to hang a couple under the top.
Be sure they are set an inch or two behind the top, so the pulls
don't get in your way and there's less likelihood of scraps getting
into them.
</P>
<P>
   Once you understand all the principles, and decide what you want
in the way of a workbench, you can sit down with paper and a ruler
or a simple drawing program on the computer, and make your own
dimensioned plans with notes on the construction.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
