<P>
   BUSH-BUSINESS (Palo Alto, Calif.) _ If Silicon Valley leaders
want to know how George W. Bush would handle technology issues as
president, they should look no farther than Texas. Bush's record on
technology issues as governor has been so pro-business,
particularly on the thorny issue of tort reform, that critics have
questioned whether he has consumers' best interests in mind. By
ZACHARY COILE.
</P>
<P>
   HIGH-RENTS (San Francisco) _ Meng Chen has rented space for his
engineering firm in for 22 years without feeling a need to buy the
property. But he was in for a shock when he received his new
three-year lease: His rent had doubled. He is one of many
small-business owners feeling increasingly squeezed by high-end
Internet tenants and live-work loft developments in San Francisco.
By VICTORIA COLLIVER.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   JAIL-RESTRAINTS (Albany, N.Y.) _ Unruly inmates at Albany County
jail will no longer be strapped face down in their cell bunks in
the wake of Monday's death of a 42-year-old mentally ill inmate who
died after being physically restrained by guards and injected with
a powerful tranquilizer. By RENDAN LYONS.
</P>
<P>
   HEALTH-PLAN (San Francisco) _ Alarmed by heavy losses and jobs
cuts at the University of California at San Francisco-run Stanford
Health Care, four state legislators have introduced a bill to force
the private hospital system to comply with public records and
disclosure laws. The legislators also seek a state audit and a
legislative hearing on what had gone wrong. By ULYSSES TORASSA.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT (``e'' category)
</P>
<P>
   FILM-REVIEW-SAM (Undated) _ Heat and fear rise palpably from the
screen in ``Summer of Sam.'' Spike Lee's 13th picture is an
astonishing, virtuosic film. It's also a jarringly effective time
machine nearly as lurid and evocative a creation of New York in a
specific, conflicted time as Martin Scorsese's ``Taxi Driver.'' By
STEVE BARNES.
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MORSE-COLUMN (San Francisco) _ A panhandler from Texas was in
San Francisco and in a few hours near Union Square made $1.2
million. George W. Bush didn't even hold a cardboard sign saying
``Will be whatever you want me to be for money.'' The main thing
we've learned about Bush is that he speaks fluent Spanish. But
Bush's real second language is money, the same as that other son of
privilege, Al Gore. By ROB MORSE.
</P>
<P>
   LYNCH-COLUMN (Albany, N.Y.) _ An aide to Gov. George Pataki and
New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani have taken some shots at President
Clinton's drug czar, Barry McCaffrey. Disagree with Barry McCaffrey
on drug policy? Hey, that's fine. But trash the guy? I'll never
outgrow outrage over cheap stunts like that. By DAN LYNCH.
</P>
<P>
   NEW-DEAL (Danville, Calif.) _ It was 67 years ago that Franklin
D. Roosevelt accepted the Democratic Party's presidential
nomination and made a momentous promise: ``I pledge you, I pledge
myself, to a new deal for the American people.'' The New Deal
thrust government into everyday life. Before that, most Americans _
except during war _ rarely had dealings with Washington beyond
voting. After the New Deal, such isolation was nearly impossible.
By CYNTHIA BASS.
</P>
