<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NEW-DEAL-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT 67, NEW DEAL REMAINS ROBUST 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By CYNTHIA BASS  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   DANVILLE, Calif. _ It was 67 years ago that Franklin D.
Roosevelt accepted the Democratic Party's presidential nomination
and made a momentous promise: ``I pledge you, I pledge myself, to a
new deal for the American people.''
</P>
<P>
   The New Deal thrust government into everyday life. Before that,
most Americans _ except during war _ rarely had dealings with
Washington beyond voting. Indeed, as late as 1932, the average
citizen's only contact with the federal government was paying (or
not) his federal income tax or observing (or not) Prohibition.
</P>
<P>
   After the New Deal, such isolation was nearly impossible.
</P>
<P>
   Almost all aspects of life _ social, economic, political _ were
subject to legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Beyond the actual legislation, however (and the myriad programs
that went with it), the New Deal changed forever how Americans
perceive government. Ever since Roosevelt, most citizens (and both
major parties) have come to believe government has a responsibility
to not only protect the public from general harm but to actively
promote its well-being and health.
</P>
<P>
   Through much of the '30s, such an activist government seemed
just what the country needed and wanted. America, four years into
the Depression, was in terrible shape when Roosevelt took office,
with 25 percent unemployment, mass layoffs, dust, drought and daily
foreclosures and bankruptcies.
</P>
<P>
   Some 9,000 banks had gone under after the stock market crash in
1929 _ 4,000 in the first 60 days of 1933. Starvation, despair and
talk of revolution stalked the land.
</P>
<P>
   FDR's first act as president, on March 5, 1933, was to declare a
bank holiday. For one week, the whole country ran on a cash-only
basis. It produced a camaraderie that only deepened when he held,
on March 12, the first of his ``fireside chats'' _ radio
announcements in which he reassuringly explained his goals to a
jittery public.
</P>
<P>
   During that week, Roosevelt pushed legislation through Congress
that restored the nation's faith in the banking system.
</P>
<P>
   When the banks reopened _ and stayed open _ ``depositors wept,''
said one reporter. Roosevelt had, at one stroke, demonstrated the
power of the federal government. The nation's confidence, and its
spirits, soared.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next nine years, as the Depression ebbed and flowed,
the New Deal introduced a number of programs. Some faltered; others
were found unconstitutional; many survived.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the best-known survivor is Social Security.
</P>
<P>
   Decried as ``destroying initiative and discouraging thrift'' and
feared because the numbering of all citizens reflected ``the lash
of the dictator,'' Social Security was to become the most popular
federal program in U.S. history.
</P>
<P>
   That program was a response to human misery; other New Deal
legislation was designed to prevent future misery.
</P>
<P>
   In the Depression's early years, thousands of people had lost
their savings as banks closed. To prevent a repeat, the Federal
Deposit Insurance Corporation was set up. This insurance of bank
deposits is still in place today, and still going strong.
</P>
<P>
   Because the stock market crash was widely regarded as having
caused the Depression, the securities industry was a natural New
Deal target. In June 1934, at Roosevelt's urging, the Securities
and Exchange Commission was formed, introducing federal regulation
(and such niceties as full disclosure) to the stock market. The SEC
remains today, watchdogging the Dow and the dot.coms.
</P>
<P>
   Other New Deal legislation had little to do with ending the
Depression or preventing a new one; it was more a matter of the
federal government asserting its power because it could.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly the Federal Communications Commission had nothing to
do with poverty. Nor did the creative work of such artists and
actors and authors as Jackson Pollack, Orson Welles and Richard
Wright (all hired under the Works Progress Administration) do much
to enrich the nation's pocketbook, however it may have enriched its
soul.
</P>
<P>
   How much economic enriching did the New Deal actually do? Today
most economists believe the Depression ended not with the New Deal,
but when we chose to arm Britain against Hitler.
</P>
<P>
   And yet the New Deal, simply by letting Americans know that its
powerful government cared, had a profound effect on the nation's
confidence, helping us weather the crisis of a great depression
with our major institutions intact _ no mean feat with one out of
four Americans jobless and communism and fascism seeming to offer
alternate systems.
</P>
<P>
   These days, questions arise as our technology-driven ``new
economy'' collides with its New Deal legacy _ an omnipresent
government that seems to care about almost everything.
</P>
<P>
   Do we need today the level of caring and government care we
needed during the '30s? Is the assistance the New Deal provided
during a stormy and terrible time useful _ or even desirable _ when
the sun comes out?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
