<HEADLINE>
TO INSTALL OR NOT TO INSTALL, THAT IS THE QUESTION
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By DR. EMILIO BOMBAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: Give it to me straight. Should I install the
Windows 98 CD that Microsoft sent me for free last July, or is
there something new out there that debugs the old stuff? Windows 95
suits my needs just fine, but you know the feeling you get when
there is an uninstalled disk sitting in your drawers!
</P>
<P>
   _Happy With 95
</P>
<P>
   DEAR HAPPY: Where I keep my disks is none of your business.
Sometimes I just like to warm them up before using them. There's
nothing wrong with that. I just have to remember to keep from
sitting down.
</P>
<P>
   I'm guessing that the ``free'' Win98 CD actually came by way of
your computer maker, since Microsoft isn't exactly in the habit of
giving away free upgrades, as you Office 2000 upgraders are finding
out. It's pretty common practice, though, for manufacturers to cut
a deal with the Big Evil Corporation when a new version of
something is close to being ready so their customers can have the
latest and greatest.
</P>
<P>
   Anyway, if you're happy with 95, just leave things the way they
are. Win98 is definitely an improvement _ thousands of bugs have
been fixed and several new features and utilities have been added _
but until Bill Gates figures out a way to put a gun to your head
and force you into it, you really don't have to upgrade, although I
understand that Microsoft Armbreaker 2000 is almost ready for
release.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I'm going to give you a chance to do something
for all your readers that, as far as I know, you've never done
before _ give us some actual, useful, usable information. How can I
upgrade my Windows 98 program using the Microsoft Web site?
</P>
<P>
   _Intermediate User
</P>
<P>
   DEAR INTER: Nice attitude. This is just a wild guess, but maybe
you should try following the instructions that are clearly
displayed when you click on Windows Update in the Start menu.
</P>
<P>
   Even though it feels like you're letting Big Bill rummage around
your underwear drawer, the updater is one of the nicest features
about Win98. It connects you to the Microsoft Web site, then sends
you a program that will poke around your system to see what version
of everything you have. Don't worry, you can tell it not to. Based
on what it finds, it recommends a number of updates. You pick what
you want, the download starts and you sit back with a cold one. The
downloaded stuff even installs itself.
</P>
<P>
   If you've never updated 98 at all, maybe you should consider
getting all the fixes at once by going to
www.microsoft.com/windows98/ and sending Bill 20 bucks for the
Windows 98 Second Edition upgrade. I hear he really needs the
money. He's down to his last $91 billion.
</P>
<P>
   DEAR DR. BOMBAY: I am a college student who will graduate from
Syracuse University in August. My idea is to open an online store
that allows people to purchase personal items (birth-control
devices, feminine-hygiene products, diet pills, adult diapers) from
the privacy of home. Please send me advice.
</P>
<P>
   _Entrepreneur
</P>
<P>
   DEAR ENT: Don't tell your parents where the tuition money went.
</P>
<P>
   (Noted computerologist Dr. Emilio Bombay is never too
embarrassed to pick up an economy-size pack of Depends. He uses
them to polish his car, of course, not that it's any of your
business. Dr. Bombay also offers occasionally accurate advice about
most things electronic. He can be reached on Internet at
drbombay(at)star-telegram.com; via snail-mail at Fort Worth
Star-Telegram, Box 1870, Fort Worth 76101; or fax: (817) 390-7257.
In real life, Dr. Bombay is Michael Gerst, editorial systems
manager for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com)
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
