<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LYNCH-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG CZAR IN THE FIRING LINE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DAN LYNCH  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ You're supposed to outgrow outrage.
</P>
<P>
   It's OK when you're a kid, when you still operate under the
innocent delusion that life is inherently just. But when you've
wandered around for a few more decades _ when you've seen the
extent to which human frailty and sheer, unmitigated stupidity
permeate the times in which we live _ then you're supposed to get
past outrage.
</P>
<P>
   You're supposed to adopt an attitude of cynical resignation.
Most of the time I can manage that. It's a sign of maturity, isn't
it _ the ability to live at peace with the available world?
</P>
<P>
   Every once in a while, though, I feel the outrage bubble up
again. It happens most often, I think, when I'm reminded of the
events of my youth. Vietnam, for instance. I've never lost my sense
of outrage over Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   It was a crummy, pointless war, a tragic, monumental
misjudgment. I opposed it and never fought in it. I spent my
military time in a nice, safe, stateside office putting out a base
newspaper. I figured I was lucky. And I was, too.
</P>
<P>
   Barry McCaffrey wasn't so lucky. He was a career soldier, sworn
on his personal honor to fight in bad wars as well as good ones.
When President Clinton selected him as the nation's drug czar,
McCaffrey was the country's most decorated Army general. He had two
Silver Stars, three Bronze Stars and two Distinguished Service
Crosses. That's the nation's second-highest medal for valor in
battle.
</P>
<P>
   The other day in Albany, McCaffrey complained about the Pataki
administration's drug policies. He said they were misguided. And
Gov. George Pataki's people went right at him in response.
</P>
<P>
   Katie Lapp, Pataki's criminal justice honcho, said McCaffrey was
``ignorant'' of the situation in New York. An unnamed Pataki aide _
I could find out who, but I won't bother _ basically accused
McCaffrey of being a political operative trying to savage the
Republicans in advance of Hillary Rodham Clinton's expected Senate
campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Lapp isn't a political type. She has a reputation as a capable
criminal justice technician with no partisan ax to grind. She could
have expressed her disagreement with McCaffrey in more measured
tones, I suppose, but honorable people can disagree on matters of
policy _ and do, all the time.
</P>
<P>
   The Pataki aide who painted McCaffrey as a political hack,
though, that's another matter entirely. So is New York Mayor
Rudolph Giuliani, who got worked up a few months ago when McCaffrey
took issue with his stand on methadone treatment for junkies. With
typical venom, Giuliani called the general a ``disgrace` and a
``disaster.''
</P>
<P>
   I haven't heard Pataki or Giuliani do it, but other members of
their party have taken great glee in stomping all over Bill Clinton
as a draft dodger. That's fine with me, because he was.
</P>
<P>
   There's something profoundly repelling, though, about today's
politicians pretending that moral choices for young men in the
Vietnam era were as simple and uncomplicated as the choices their
fathers faced when Hitler was around. They weren't. Also, neither
Giuliani nor Pataki ever served. While McCaffrey, who's nobody's
political operative, was taking a .50-caliber bullet in his arm in
Vietnam, these guys were studying at fancy law schools. McCaffrey
bled for his country three times _ and has the Purple Hearts to
prove it _ while these wannabe tough guys were building political
careers in cushy, carpeted offices.
</P>
<P>
   Disagree with McCaffrey on drug policy? Hey, that's fine. Even
heroes can be wrong.
</P>
<P>
   But to trash the guy the way Giuliani did? The way Pataki's
unnamed aide did?
</P>
<P>
   Sorry, but I'll never outgrow outrage over cheap stunts like
that.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Dan Lynch is a columnist for the Albany Times Union, P.O. Box
15000, Albany, NY 12212.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
