<HEADER>
A7139 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN07-COX     07-02 0567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEPEN-COLUMN07-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    COMMENTARY: The never-ending culture war
 &HT;    (Eds: This is the Teepen column that normally moves Mondays,
moving today in advance of the Monday holiday.)
 &HT;    By Tom Teepen
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   It only takes nanoseconds after any new item lands on the public
agenda these days before sides are chosen up and a new battle in
the culture war is declared. Consider, of all improbable matters,
urban sprawl.
</P>
<P>
   Sprawl is an emerging concern, especially with swamped
suburbanites themselves, and not unreasonably. Suburbia has become
boundless, oozing toward the horizons with consequent increases in
air pollution and the human aggravation (and cramped family time)
born of hours spent in traffic. Center cities are left to struggle,
at huge economic and social cost to all of us. Green space is
rolled every 10 years in amounts equal to Connecticut and Rhode
Island combined.
</P>
<P>
   A bit of thought about all that would not seem to be untoward,
but if you've ever sat around with neighbors and grumbled about the
game of developer leapfrog, it may surprise you to learn you are
toying with environmental extremism, neosocialism and federal
tyranny.
</P>
<P>
   All this because Vice President Al Gore a few weeks ago put
forward a modest Clinton administration proposal to help state and
local governments get a handle on growth. The key feature is a
low-cost bond program that could be used to preserve open spaces
and water resources and to leverage investment in planned growth
areas _ abandoned industrial sites, for instance. There's a boost
for public transportation, too.
</P>
<P>
   Nothing there is ideologically lurid. Yes, there's politics. The
political wisdom du jour says next year's presidential election
will go whichever way the suburban vote sloshes. Gore has noticed
there were 240 local controlled-growth issues on last year's
ballots and 70 percent passed.
</P>
<P>
   But if political, the matter needn't be intensely partisan. Many
of those issues passed in Republican electorates. Here,
classically, is a matter of legitimate public interest that by
rights ought to be attended to simply as a problem to be solved,
not as another bugle call to the ever-keen cultural rangers.
</P>
<P>
   But the hyper-conservatives are having none of this mutual
problem-solving bull.
</P>
<P>
   According to them, the evil Clintonites, personified by Gore,
want to confiscate your car, deny you the American-dream home in
Bucolic Acres, force you to move into town (with Them!) and make
you ride buses. Gore, one conservative commentator says, is waging
a holy war _ ``a Jihad,'' no less _ against the American people.
</P>
<P>
   Not to put too fine a point on it, but this is plain crazy.
Federal policy _ freeways, subsidized FHA and GI Bill loans _
created suburbia. The political decisions that keep U.S. gasoline
taxes a fraction of what they are in other countries literally fuel
limitless expansion. It is hardly anti-capitalist to wonder if,
now, other policies might not be in order to check the unforeseen
excesses.
</P>
<P>
   The brawlers of the cultural and political right must think we
Americans love nothing more than to fight endlessly, they have us
doing so much of it.
</P>
<P>
   Tom Teepen is national correspondent for Cox Newspapers. He is
based in Atlanta. E-mail: teepencolumn(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
