<HEADER>
A7141 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-02 0701
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MORSE-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE TEXAS GREEN MACHINE 
</HEADLINE>
   Commentary  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ROB MORSE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A panhandler from Texas came to town and in a
few hours near Union Square made $1.2 million.
</P>
<P>
   George W. Bush didn't even hold a cardboard sign saying ``Will
be whatever you want me to be for money.''
</P>
<P>
   The main thing we've learned about Bush is that he speaks fluent
Spanish. But so did Franco and so does Castro. Not that Bush is
such a bad guy, even if he's against women's right to abortion and
favors executing teen-aged criminals.
</P>
<P>
   So what if he's the governor of a state where the governor has
less power than a pickup truck dealer? He's quite personable, which
is his main selling point.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, Bush's real second language is money, the same as that
other son of privilege, Vice President Al Gore. What we have here
is Andover vs. St. Albans, Yale vs. Harvard, the son of a president
vs. the son of a senator, one fund-raiser vs. another.
</P>
<P>
   I don't want to hear either of them knocking elites.
</P>
<P>
   Bush is more elite, though, because he is a Republican _ a
Republican arriving after a dispiriting string of political duds
like Dole, Gingrich and, well, an older Bush. So before he's
stocked up on campaign sound bites, young Bush has picked up an
astounding $36 million in donations.
</P>
<P>
   He's made so much money without producing anything he should put
a ``.com'' after his name.
</P>
<P>
   If you think fund-raising irregularities are bad, consider this
scary fund-raising regularity: Since 1976, when the current
campaign finance system went into effect, the Republican and
Democratic presidential nominations have always gone to the
candidates who raised the most money in the year before the
election.
</P>
<P>
   It ain't over when it's over. It's over as soon as they're in
the clover. The election is more than a year away, and Bush already
is acting like he's president.
</P>
<P>
   Democracy has turned into dueling rubber chicken dinners. The
voter no longer counts. Power belongs to those who write big checks
to get ``access.''
</P>
<P>
   We all know this, but George W. Bush has done his first big
service to his country by making it $36 million clearer.
</P>
<P>
   What can we do? This is a nation built on a system of checks and
balances. The checks are rolling in, so it's up to voters to
provide the balances.
</P>
<P>
   Only your little votes can beat the powerful forces of boredom
and big money. I admit it. After years of cynicism, focus groups
and Clintonian triangulation, that sounds ridiculously like a Frank
Capra movie.
</P>
<P>
   But what can we do? I'm damned if I'm going to start exercising
my democratic rights by eating rubber chicken and writing big
checks.
</P>
<P>
   Personally, I'd like to see a race between Sen. John McCain,
R-Ariz., and former Sen. Bill Bradley, D-N.J. Whatever their flaws,
they're men of character, discernible beliefs, interesting
histories and unconventional ways of thinking.
</P>
<P>
   OK, so they also have elite backgrounds, as the son of an
admiral and a Princeton graduate.
</P>
<P>
   The press and their parties are already writing them off because
$36 million is more important than character or issues.
</P>
<P>
   That's enough reason to consider them.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, if George W. Bush is elected president, it
will be a nail in the coffin of machismo. Americans will have put a
cheerleader in the White House.
</P>
<P>
   Bush was a cheerleader at Andover, and recently I saw a yearbook
picture of him in his cheerleader sweater, megaphone in hand, and
he was cute. Even by Texas cheerleader standards.
</P>
<P>
   One good thing about Bush's windfall. Elizabeth Dole looks like
Southern-fried toast. That lady was getting way too scary. She
proposed a ban on federal subsidies for libraries that provide
access to obscene Web sites _ for adults, not just children.
</P>
<P>
   Isn't this the woman married to the old guy in the Viagra ads on
television? There's nothing on the Web as bad as Bob Dole uttering
the letters ``E.D.'' and the words they stand for.
</P>
<P>
   They don't stand for ``Elizabeth Dole.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Rob Morse is a columnist for the San Francisco Examiner, P.O.
Box 7260, San Francisco, CA 94120.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
