<HEADER>
A7150 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FIREWORKS03-COX     07-02 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FIREWORKS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    FIREWORKS ARE BOOMING IN THE MILLENNIAL YEAR
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington , (f) financial and (l) lifestyle
categories.
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Preparations for the new millennium have ignited a
boom in the fireworks business.
</P>
<P>
   Orders usually fizzle after the Fourth of July, but this year
they're skyrocketing, said Julie Heckman, spokeswoman for the
American Pyrotechnic Association
</P>
<P>
   Millennium celebrations will set a worldwide record for
fireworks displays, Heckman predicted. In the United States, there
will be a ``second season'' for consumer fireworks between
Christmas and New Year's. Normally, over 90 percent of the
firecrackers, Roman candles, cherry bombs and other at-home
fireworks favored by amateurs are shot off around the Fourth of
July.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're getting a large response from consumers as well as
municipalities,'' said Gerry Serpico of the International Fireworks
Manufacturing Co. in Douglasville, Pa. ``New Year's Eve will be
really bang-up, but then the celebrations will continue all through
the year.''
</P>
<P>
   ``More fireworks shows mean that more fireworks need to be
made,'' said Bret Swenson of Fireworks West Internationale in
Logan, Utah. The fireworks manufacturer has been filling orders for
the Fourth of July since April 1, he said, and on Tuesday will
start packing black powder and chemical colors into canisters meant
to celebrate the calendar change from 1999 to 2000.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. fireworks industry had revenues of just over $425
million in 1998 and is expecting about a 30 percent increase in
1999, said Heckman. ``There will be a significant boom,'' but
financial forecasts are tricky because the celebrations will bridge
two years and much of the increased profit will be reflected on the
2000 ledgers rather than in 1999, she explained.
</P>
<P>
   Large cities have budgeted for fireworks in their millennium
celebrations, but some small towns will probably wait and make
their annual community festivals ``more grandiose'' during 2000,
Heckman explained. Private organizations are also ordering
fireworks for parties all during the year, so the financial
windfall is expected to last until 2001.
</P>
<P>
   The cost of a community fireworks display ranges from $2,000 or
so for low-level shells to light the sky for a few minutes to
$100,000 for a half-hour extravaganza with a multitude of low- and
high-level effects choreographed to music.
</P>
<P>
   To augment the fireworks that her firm makes, said Serpico,
``for this season, we've imported more than ever. Our product is
gone and we have shipments on the water coming in.''
</P>
<P>
   The fireworks business has been pretty hot since the American
bicentennial, said Heckman. In 1976, a then-record 29 million
pounds of fireworks were set off in the United States. In 1997,
132.9 million pounds of fireworks were ``consumed,'' Heckman said.
``It increased fourfold.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fireworks are Americana,'' she said. Displays routinely light
up the skies at baseball games, the Super Bowl, and theme parks
such as Disney World.
</P>
<P>
   For these shows, she said, pyrotechnic artists often mix shells
made in China, Italy, England, Australia and other foreign
countries, as well as domestic ones, to make an international
mosaic of light and color.
</P>
<P>
   There will be some innovations for millennium shows, she said.
``New patterns in the sky. New colors. We're seeing more pastels _
pinks, mint green, violet _ rather than just the traditional red,
white and blue. That's what makes a fireworks display so
wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
