<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HEALTH-PLAN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAWMAKERS TAKE STEPS TO OPEN HEALTH PLAN'S BOOKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ULYSSES TORASSA  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Alarmed by heavy losses and jobs cuts at the
UCSF Stanford Health Care, four California legislators have
introduced a bill to force the private hospital system to comply
with public records and disclosure laws.
</P>
<P>
   The legislators also called Thursday for a state audit and a
legislative hearing on what had gone wrong at the nonprofit
corporation that is owned jointly by Stanford University and the
University of California.
</P>
<P>
   ``We intend to find out the causes for this fiscal hemorrhage so
we can find ways to stop it,'' Sen. John Burton, D-San Francisco,
said in a statement. Burton was joined in the legislation by
Assembly members Carole Migden and Kevin Shelley, both Democrats
from San Francisco, and Sen. Jackie Speier, D-Daly City.
</P>
<P>
   UCSF Stanford expects to lose $60 million this year and says it
will cut 2,000 jobs and may shut down parts of Mount Zion Medical
Center to stay afloat.
</P>
<P>
   UCSF Stanford spokesman Mike Lassiter had no comment on the
legislation. However, when the merger that created the hospital
system was being debated, proponents said it wouldn't work if the
hospitals had to operate under public disclosure rules.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to opening the hospital system to greater public
scrutiny, the bill would require its 16 board members to disclose
their personal holdings and potential conflicts of interest.
</P>
<P>
   UCSF Stanford was formed in 1997 by combining the UC-San
Francisco's hospitals with the Stanford University and Lucile
Salter Packard Children's hospitals in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   At the time, the state auditor issued a report saying the merger
would provide significant benefits to UC-San Francisco. Now, the
legislators say they want the auditor to focus on why the hospital
system has sunk so quickly into the red.
</P>
<P>
   Officials say the losses, which are primarily from Mount Zion's
operations, result from inadequate reimbursements from Medicare and
Medi-Cal that are affecting academic medical centers nationwide. To
stanch the losses, administrators have proposed several options
including eliminating Mount Zion's emergency room and all or most
of its hospital beds.
</P>
<P>
   Unions and other critics say they believe poor management and
the merger have made things much worse, but contend neither their
assertions nor those of administrators can be verified without
access to the nonprofit corporation's records.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many of us doubt the actual debt that they're reporting, and
this is the only way we're going to be able to see what is
happening at the hospital,'' said Karen MacLeod, president of the
UC-San Francisco chapter of the University Professional and
Technical Employees.
</P>
<P>
   Among other things, critics have singled out the hiring of about
1,000 new employees, payments to a consulting group hired to find
ways to cut costs, and what they say are high salaries paid to
administrators, which are not publicly available.
</P>
<P>
   Migden said she hoped opening the system's books could help
avoid drastic cuts like cutting Mount Zion's hospital beds and
closing its emergency room. A hearing before the state Senate's
Select Committee on Government Oversight is scheduled for July 16
in San Francisco, a week before the UCSF Stanford board plans to
take up whether to cut programs at Mount Zion.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1233EDT &QL; 
