<HEADLINE>
KANSAS CITY STAR BUDGET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Kansas City Star plans to move the following stories for use
by clients of the NYTimes News Service for AMs and PMs of Saturday,
July 3. If you have any questions, please call The Star's News Desk
at (816) 234-4720.
</P>
<P>
   NEWS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   GOP _ How ugly is the split between the moderate and
conservative wing of the Republican Party in Kansas? In a move that
echos the sensitivity of Serbs departing Kosovo, the losing
conservatives leaving state party headquarters in Topeka trashed
records and computer files, left 29 cents in the bank and sold a
donor list to a competing group. Steve Kraske. 30.
</P>
<P>
   DUCKS: The latest sports sensation in Missouri is the Ozark
Mountain Ducks, Springfield's first minor-league baseball team in
49 years. They inaugurated their new stadium this month. A look at
how baseball remains a slice of Americana. And, as major league
baseball struggles to get fans back after the 1994 strike, the
Ozark club is doing it the old-fashioned way. The team is
reminiscent of the humble early days of baseball and is bringing
together a small town coping with newcomers and unprecedented
growth. Oscar Avila. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   SUPER: After failing to reach an agreement with Jay Edwards, the
school board goes back to looking for a new superintendent. The
board is expected to meet today. Three other candidates are under
consideration. It's not known when the board will begin
interviewing them. It could happen as early as this weekend.
Phillip O'Connor and Tanika White. 25. Photos
</P>
<P>
   SHIPPE: We meet the ghost of Jay Shippe, archaeologist, who
discovered three pre-Colombian sites in Western Missouri and
created a collection of artifacts unparalleled in this area. His
daughters now have given his collection to the St. Joseph, Mo.,
Museum. 30. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   RACES: Speeding cars hurtle down the straightaway, but pile into
each other on the turns. Some spin out of control. Some overturn.
It's a sight that would cause gasps of anguish at Indianapolis or
Daytona. But heck, this is Pleasant Hill, and these are
radio-controlled cars. The fanatics are out there every Friday
night. Robert Carroll. 15. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   FISH: In the beginning, there was the water, and the fish. But
people began erecting roller coasters and music halls and shopping
malls. And in the hubbub that became Branson, Mo., the country
music show capital of the world, many forgot about the fish. But
they were still there. And those who have always believed in this
town because of the fish say that in 100 years, after the glitter
fades on the strip, there still will be fish. Matt Schofield. 25.
Photos.
</P>
<P>
   UKRAINE: Two city officials from Ukraine come to the Kansas City
area as guests of MARC to study local government, American-style,
in Kansas City, Lenexa and Lee's Summit. They also try to line up
some dealers for Ukranian handcrafts. Yang Jianxiang. Photos.
</P>
<P>
   COX (Tent.) _ Chipper Cox, a convicted burglar accused of
killing his ex-girlfriend after she helped him escape prison, is in
court today. He may plead. Tony Rizzo. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   TEACH. On Thursday, the feds started sending money to the states
to hire more teachers, part of an effort to reduce class sizes in
kindergarten through third grade, with goal of student-teacher
ratio no higher than 18-to-1; even affluent district like Shawnee
Mission, Kan., where the ratio already is down to 17-to-1 will get
a slice of the pie. Jim Sullinger, Lee Hill Kavanaugh.
</P>
<P>
   CODE. Jamiah Khaliq just wanted to dance. When she and a group
of friends showed up at Adolfo's, an upscale Kansas City nightclub,
the 30-year-old dental student was wearing a two-piece navy suit.
She thought she measured up to the club's strict dress code, which
bans jeans and tennis shoes. But she was turned away, she says she
was told, because of her dreadlocks. This follows a similar
situation at Roadhouse Ruby's South in Olathe. Dawn Bormann. 25.
Photo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   Y2K3 _ Column by David Hayes-Finn Bullar
</P>
<P>
   VICA _ Winners and a little color from VICA convention and final
round competition. Also elects national officers. All results
available Friday afternoon. By Rick Alm. Photo
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS BUDGET OFFERS
</P>
<P>
   SUMMER. Jenni Carlson. 25-30. It's summer time in Kansas City,
and if you're a parent with kids who aspire to be athletes, that
means it's time to break out the checkbook. Going to the local high
school summer basketball camp just isn't good enough anymore. Kids
today want to attend the $350-a-pop Roy Williams and Marion
Washington camps. Even if you don't have kids, you'll probably see
them on the street washing cars or in pictures posted at the
grocery store, all seeking sponsorship money to play sports.
</P>
<P>
   ROYALS. Dick Kaegel. 16-18. Kansas City at Cleveland, 6:05 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   WWC. Mechelle Voepel. 20. Feature on U.S. soccer midfielder
Julie Foudy, team comedian, who will be back in her old territory
for the semifinal game Sunday in Palo Alto, Calif. Foudy played for
Stanford.
</P>
<P>
   KERSEE. Pedley. 17. Jackie Joyner-Kersee and husband Bob plan to
field a NASCAR team next year. If they do manage to put together a
Winston Cup team, they will become the first black owners since
Wendall Scott did it in the 1950s.
</P>
