<HEADLINE>
ALBERT WELCOMED HOME 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By HOWARD MANLY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The circle of life is complete now that Marv Albert is back at
NBC.
</P>
<P>
   No sense beating up on the guy anymore. He was sick and needed
help and now that therepy has worked its cure over the last two
years, why shouldn't the recovering be allowed to work in their
field of expertise?
</P>
<P>
   It's about redemption and forgiveness, and if Albert is willing
to subject himself to public ridicule, then so be it. NBC gets the
credit for taking care of one of its own. The network did the right
thing by firing him when he lied about his affair. And NBC Sports
Chairman Dick Ebersol is doing the right thing by giving, by all
accounts, the best NBA play-by-play announcer another chance at the
network level.
</P>
<P>
   Sports is the one field in which talent matters most. It also
helps to be friends with the boss.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a very happy day for NBC Sports,'' Ebersol told
reporters on Tuesday. ``Marv has been a great friend to all of us
here for a long time, above all to me in particular. He is my
friend. He is a great talent.''
</P>
<P>
   And so it goes. Reaction has been one of inevitability. Everyone
knew Albert would be back. Just not this quickly. The process
started just 10 months after his plea-bargain deal in Virginia,
where he pleaded guilty to the misdeamnor offense of assault and
battery. Madison Square Garden Network rehired him to call the
Knicks game on its radio station and a 30-minute sports news show
called ``SportsDesk.'' Seven months later, Turner Sports hired him
to call NBA games.
</P>
<P>
   The new NBC deal calls for Albert to call as many as 15 NBA
games as well as hockey and boxing events during the upcoming
Summer Olympics. Fox Sports had made overtures to Albert to call
football games. Once Ebersol learned of the talks, he quickly moved
to secure his old pal.
</P>
<P>
   Like him or not, Albert is a good announcer. But more pressing
to NBC, and for that matter, the NBA, is how to increase ratings
for NBA games. The recent playoff series between the New York
Knicks and San Antonio Spurs was the lowest rated since 1991. With
NBC vowing to show more regional games, attaining higher national
numbers will be even more difficult.
</P>
<P>
   But ratings weren't the issue with Albert.
</P>
<P>
   Character was, and if Latrell Sprewell can find a home in
Manhattan, then certainly Albert can.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe when the NFL rights are available again, NBC can outbid
other network competitors and put O.J. back on the sidelines.
</P>
<P>
   By that time, the Juice will be something of a senior football
statesman, and his words will be worth a ratings point or two.
</P>
<P>
   Time healed Richard Nixon. It healed Albert.
</P>
<P>
   It can heal Simpson, too.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Cup draw
</P>
<P>
   The Women's World Cup game on Sunday between USA and Korea
scored a 3.3 rating and 7 share on ESPN2 last Sunday. Those cable
ratings numbers are great when compared with those of other
programming that day. ESPN earned a 1 rating and 3 share for its
coverage of the Lysol 200 Nascar race and a 2.5 rating for its
coverage of the SaveMart/Kragen 350K Nascar race. The women's match
easily outperformed its head-to-head competition that night. The
New York Mets game against the Atlanta Braves on TBS pulled a .6
rating. ESPN managed only a 1.4 for its airing of the
Dodgers-Giants game.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In full view
</P>
<P>
   Suyzn Waldman and Christine Brennan make their television debuts
on Lifetime Friday night during the Sacramento-Washington WNBA
game. Waldman is the first women to call play-by-play for a major
league baseball team (Yankees) and works as a host for WFAN radio,
the New York-based sports talk show. Brennan is a sports columnist
for USA Today. ABC airs six telecasts of the Tour de France,
starting 3 p.m. Saturday and ending with an hour's worth of
coverage on Sunday, July 25 at 5 p.m. Robin Roberts anchors the
telecasts with commentators Phil Liggett and Paul Sherwin . . .
ESPN Classic has seven hours worth of great ABA moments Sunday
starting at noon with the 1976 slam dunk contest with Dr. J, David
Thompson, George Gervin and Artis Gilmore . . . ESPN
``SportsCentury'' unveils its 29th best athlete _ Arnold Palmer.
``He was golf,'' Sports Illustrated's William Nack tells ESPN
Friday night at 7:30. ``He literally picked it up on his shoulders
and carried it to the people. It had been a game of the
martini-swilling, country-club set and he gave it to the beer
folks.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Howard Manly is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
