<SLUG> BC-FINANCE-HOOKER-$ADV05-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIGGER HOUSE WON'T SHELTER OWNER FROM UNCLE SAM 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, July 5, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KENNETH HOOKER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. I am single, 41, and contribute the maximum allowed to a
401(k) plan. I also have a regular IRA as well, of which I've
already made my $2,000 maximum contribution for 1999. My taxable
investments are all with Vanguard, including two tax-exempt money
market funds for reserves and emergencies, the Index 500 and Index
Growth, and a small amount in the Health Care fund. In addition to
my $52,000 annual salary, I am going to receive approximately
$96,000 in net stock option distributions over the next two years
from a recent buyout of our division. This is money that I do not
have a need for right now, or in the foreseeable future. In your
opinion, what is the best solution to shelter myself from Uncle
Sam? Should I open a Roth IRA, buy a bigger house, or put it all in
Vanguard Index 500?
</P>
<P>
   G.S., San Diego, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   A. The wild card here is the idea of buying a bigger house.
Usually when that's thrown in as an option, it's because the
questioner wants to buy a bigger house, and you'll have to decide
for yourself if that's really where you want to go. All I will
suggest is this -- buying a new house isn't going to shelter you
from taxes; in the short run, if you buy $96,000 more house, you're
going to pay taxes and insurance and maintenance costs on that
$96,000 more house, and when you eventually sell, Uncle Sam is
likely to be there to take notice.
</P>
<P>
   You don't mention how much is in your current IRA, but I think
an attractive option would be to take a portion of the windfall and
use it to pay the taxes on a transfer of your current IRA savings
to Roth accounts. This would create a nice balance in retirement,
with the Roth money being tax-free and providing you flexibility in
managing your withdrawals from the more sizable amount that you'll
probably have in the tax-deferred 401(k) account.
</P>
<P>
   As for the rest, Vanguard Index 500 is certainly a very solid
long-term investment. But if you're certain that you won't have a
use for this money before age 59 1/2, consider investing in a
variable annuity account which Vanguard offers, with the investment
tracking the same index as the taxable fund. The advantage of the
variable annuity is that the growth within the account is
tax-deferred, much as in an IRA or 401(k) account.
</P>
<P>
   When you make withdrawals after age 59 1/2, you pay taxes on the
proportion of the money which can be attributed to internal growth;
the amount of the withdrawal which can be attributed to the initial
contribution is not taxable. But you will pay both taxes and a
penalty if the funds are withdrawn before age 59 1/2, except in a
few exceptional (and generally unpleasant) circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Another disadvantage is that in order to gain the tax deferral
that attracts most people to variable annuities, there is an
element of insurance provided in the product. This smidgen of
insurance does its job, but it also costs money, so you can expect
the returns from a variable annuity to run about one half of one
percentage point behind the returns of a comparable taxable mutual
fund.
</P>
<P>
   Before you made such a move, try to estimate where your various
investments are likely to be once you retire. While moving your IRA
to a Roth account will give you added flexibility, buying a
variable annuity will serve to increase the amount of money on
which taxes will be levied upon withdrawal. You might eventually
decide on a three-pronged strategy -- paying the taxes to transfer
to Roth IRAs, putting some of the money into a Standard and Poor's
500 variable annuity, and putting the balance in Vanguard Index
500. But remember if you take the final step that while Index 500
in quite tax efficient, it is still almost certain to provide you
with regular, and growing, tax liabilities.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. When I read your column it seems most of these people have a
pretty good handle on what they're doing. Well, I make $110,000 a
year and don't have a lot to show for it in terms of investing for
myself and my family. I'm 46 years old and my wife is 40. We have
children nine and six years old. My retirement light has finally
come on. As of this date, we have a wide variety of investments,
mostly in a 401(k) and IRA accounts. Aside for money for the
children, the accounts now amount to $48,306. Reading the
</P>
<P>
   questions people write to you, it seems to me that the people
who write to you are light years ahead of me. How much should I be
saving based on what I'm making? What should I be doing so I don't
get killed by inflation?
</P>
<P>
   G.R., Boston
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, let's work backwards to see how deep a hole youre in
when it comes to retirement. A common approach is to calculate that
people will need about 60 percent of their pre-retirement income to
finance a fairly comfortable retirement. In your case that would
work out to $66,000 a year. But if inflation runs at a 3.5 percent
annual average for the next 19 years, you'd need $126,885 to buy
what $66,000 buys today.
</P>
<P>
   So what are you likely to have to meet those costs? Let's
estimate that you're putting $10,000 a year into the 401(k) plan,
and are fully funding both your IRA and your wife's. At that rate,
if you achieve 10 percent average investment returns you would have
$1,044,330 after 19 years -- a tidy sum, but not sufficient to meet
those projected retirement costs for very long.
</P>
<P>
   So how much should you be saving? If my assumptions about the
401(k) and IRA contributions are correct, you are currently saving
about 12.7 percent of your income. Many people set 15 percent of
income as a savings target. But it's also clear from the levels in
the various accounts either that you haven't been saving regularly
or haven't been saving for long. So my suggestion would be not only
to go to that 15 percent level, but to stretch beyond it if
possible to make up for lost time. If you were able to boost your
savings to 15 percent of income, the 19-year growth projection
would be to $1,178,067, using the same assumptions as above.
</P>
<P>
   If you could make the mammoth leap to 20 percent, the projection
would go out to $1,472,064. (But remember that it's better to set a
savings level you can live with and stick to the plan, rather than
to set your sights too high and find yourself regularly slipping
behind plan.)
</P>
<P>
   The picture isn't quite as bleak as I paint it. Whatever savings
level you decide on, maintain it as a percentage of income rather
than a flat dollar level -- thus every time you win a raise the
picture will grow brighter. Moreover, my guess is that there will
be some sort of Social Security program remaining in place when you
retire, and that could make the picture brighter still.
</P>
<P>
   But the main thing to do it save more, and keep doing it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. The conservative reputation of New Englanders is not well
served by your advice against saving for a child's education in
their own name. Gifts under the Uniform Gifts to Minors Act, with a
good trustee, protect the child's assets against adverse outcomes
in divorce court, probate court, and bankruptcy court.
</P>
<P>
   R.M., Bolton, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. My frequent advice that parents save for college expenses in
their own names is based on the staggering escalation that is
expected for college expenses. The latest edition of ``Paying for
College Without Going Broke'' by Kalman A. Chany projects the
average annual expense of a four-year college to be $41,942 in
2013, with a figure of $16,310 for a public university in the same
year. For most people, facing expenses like that without applying
for some sort of financial aid would simply be impossible, and
accordingly it is wise to do everything you can do to maximize the
student's eligibility for financial aid -- and putting funds in a
student's name has precisely the opposite effect, reducing the
student's eligibility for assistance.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Send letters, including your name, address and telephone number,
to: Kenneth Hooker, The Boston Globe, Boston, Mass. 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1330EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0083 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 13:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7203 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-02 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JACKSON-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGGINBOTHAM'S WORDS OF WISDOM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DERRICK Z. JACKSON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Few people understood the duality of the Declaration of
Independence as did A. Leon Higginbotham Jr., the late federal
judge, legal scholar, Harvard professor and Presidential Medal of
Freedom honoree. It was Higginbotham who, in the midst of the
bicentennial of the American Revolution, dared to interrupt the
fireworks to ask:
</P>
<P>
   ``Did the Declaration of Independence announce a self-evident
truth or a self-evident lie?''
</P>
<P>
   On this Fourth of July, it is important to remember
Higginbotham, who died last December. He combined a biting sense of
the nation's beginnings with an underlying irony for what the white
forefathers had set in motion. ``If the authors of the Declaration
of Independence had said `all white men are created equal' or even
`all white men who own property' they would have more honestly
conveyed the general consensus,'' Higginbotham wrote in his 1978
book ``In the Matter of Color, Race and the American Legal Process:
The Colonial Period.''
</P>
<P>
   ``But when they declared, as they did, that `all men are created
equal' without introducing any qualifications, they created a
document that put moral demands on all Americans who would ever
quote it.''
</P>
<P>
   Higginbotham was not the kind to rail for a cancellation of the
fireworks or the Pops. But he insisted on people being honest with
what they were celebrating. You cannot understand America today
without being clear that the Declaration of Independence was
written in a cesspool of hypocrisy. The white colonists, with no
mention of slavery in the Colonies, vigorously depicted themselves
as slaves to the British.
</P>
<P>
   Josiah Quincy of Boston said: ``I speak it with grief. I speak
it with anguish. Britons are our oppressors. I speak it with shame.
I speak it with indignation _ we are slaves.'' John Adams said the
colonists were ``the most abject sort of slaves, to the worst sort
of masters!''
</P>
<P>
   When Rhode Island Governor Stephen Hopkins opposed the Sugar Act
of 1764, he said, ``Liberty is the greatest blessing that men enjoy
and slavery the heaviest curse that human nature is capable of.''
Higginbotham wrote, ``Of course, Governor Hopkins was not speaking
of the enslavement of blacks. Ironically, he argued that white
colonists were being enslaved by England because the Sugar Act of
1764 decreased the profits from Rhode Island's involvement in the
international slave trade.''
</P>
<P>
   Slavery, so fundamental to the economy of the United States that
it would go on for nearly nine decades after the Declaration, and
racial discrimination, so fundamental to the superior economic,
educational, and social position of white people that it was
legally encoded for nearly 190 years, received their silent
blessings in the Declaration. The Continental Congress struck out
Thomas Jefferson's only reference to the international slave trade,
the reference that criticized England for waging ``cruel war
against human nature itself, violating its most sacred rights of
life and liberty in the persons of a distant people who never
offended him.''
</P>
<P>
   Even if the reference had survived, Higginbotham found it
hypocritical because it referred only to England and not to slavery
in the Americas. At the time of the Declaration, Jefferson had
posted a reward for the capture and return of one of his runaway
slaves. ``If, in Jefferson's phrase, the international slave trade
was initiated by `cruel war against human nature itself, why was it
not just as depraved for him to keep in lifetime servitude in the
Colonies those who had been so cruelly captured abroad or their
children?'' Higginbotham wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the declaration took on another life. Abolitionists used it
to urge the end of slavery. Martin Luther King Jr. implored America
to ``live out the true meaning of its creed _ we hold these truths
to be self evident, that all men are created equal.'' Higginbotham
found the declaration to be alive in the civil rights acts passed
in the 1960s, acts which guaranteed basic rights for ``all
persons'' or any ``individual'' on the basis of ``race, color,
religion, sex, or national origin.''
</P>
<P>
   The Declaration of Independence was so alive that Higginbotham
knew he was answering his own question. The declaration was a
self-evident lie that, despite the nation's murderous history of
supremacy and patronization, has been moved significantly closer to
that self-evident truth. It is still not reasonably close enough in
a land that remains infested with racism, sexism, homophobia, and
widening economic disparity.
</P>
<P>
   But it is close enough so that the proponents of equality now
have a taste of what the framers wrote. ``Once the drafters of and
signers of our Declaration made the decision not to weaken their
moral argument for nationhood by attempting to rationalize the lie
many of them were living,'' Higginbotham wrote, ``they made
inevitable the irony that the truth they espoused, and not their
example, would eventually guide their progeny to a society more
just than their own.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Derrick Z. Jackson is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
