<HEADLINE>
OUTSIDERS ENHANCE CHEMICAL BROTHERS' EFFECT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM SULLIVAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE CHEMICAL BROTHERS 
Surrender 
Astralwerks 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We start out in Kraftwerk-ville with altered man-machine vocals
intoning, ``Music triggers some kind of response,'' over and over
against techno-squiggles, guitar riffs, space-age synth dive-bombs,
and bracing break beats. It's called ``Music: Response'' and it is
clear we are in good hands, cared for by the happy, sly minds of
``brothers'' Tom Rowlands and Ed Simons, the duo who gave us those
big block-rockin' beats of 1997 with ``Dig Your Own Hole.''
``Surrender,'' the Chemical Brothers' third album, gives us some of
the same but a lot more. With the third song, they give us New
Order-style dance-floor angst and slippery sexuality _ replete with
New Order/Electronic singer Bernard Sumner on guest vocals _ with
its mix of hooks and trance-rock, its sinuousness and disruption.
Shortly, it's the Beatle-esque entry (circa ``Rain'') with Oasis's
Noel (I am the Walrus) Gallager doing his bit, ``Let Forever Be,''
as he did on the last disc. The overall cheeriness is countered by
Gallagher's musings about spending ``a little lifetime sitting in
the gutter.'' (Primal Scream singer Bobby Gillespie also joins.)
Mazzy Star's Hope Sandoval takes over for Beth Orton in the
sad-song chanteuse category and contributes a shimmering, watery
``Asleep From Day.''
</P>
<P>
   Is it all a pastiche? Is it all a stylistic rip from another era
done up with late '90s electronic gizmos? Is it too dependent on
outside collaborators? No, not really, or so what, who cares? are
possible answers. You can cite the reference points, if you wish,
but none of them get in the way of this delicious sonic assault.
``Surrender'' is somewhat less busy _ less acid-jazzy _ than its
predecessor. It is less exhausting an experience, but just as
rewarding. There are a multitude of levels to this CD; the moods
vary, the beats go nuts and then shut up, the idea of music as
adventure reigns supreme.
</P>
<P>
   Just as, say, the Cure survived post-punk and new wave, the
Chemical Brothers look to be surviving electronica. It is any
band's challenge to emerge from an era or sound, or, more
specifically, hyped-up expectations of that era or sound. One thing
the best electronica groups have done _ and the Chems are certainly
among them _ is bring dance audiences to rock, and vice versa.
Rowlands and Simons are not too hung up on what it all means. A lot
of this is instrumental music _ no lyrics to bother you _ and it's
a near perfect mix of music that functions on physical and cerebral
planes simultaneously . Wave after wave of smile-induing
psychedelia comes at you; you'd have to be made of stone to not
surrender.
</P>
<P>
   I have a lot of respect for albums that are well paced _ peaks,
valleys, and all that. This one is aces in that regard. ``Asleep
From Day'' is the calm in the eye of the hurricane, and then the
Chems and company gently crank up the space-dance rock on ``Got
Glint?'' There's an Indian strain in the gliding title tune, and
the final wind-down track is the celestial ``Dream On'' (no, not
that one) with guest guitarist-singer Jonathan Donahue from Mercury
Rev. ``Sleep and dream on . . . '' urges Sandoval, as Donahue and
pals paint gentle circles around and above her. It's a graceful
denouement, a soft rest after an exhilarating ride, reminiscent of
``Sad Song'' at the end of Lou Reed's masterpiece ``Berlin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
