<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MCCAIN'S ACE IN THE HOLE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PORTSMOUTH, N.H. _ There's an Army out there somewhere for John
McCain. And a Navy and an Air Force, too, McCain enthusiasts
devoutly hope.
</P>
<P>
   If the veterans of America's military want a straight-shooting,
high-flying, damn-the-torpedoes military hero, McCain's their man,
and the vets are part of his plan. His strategy is simple: Survive
the early skirmishes in Iowa and New Hampshire, which is much more
important to him than Iowa, and then, like 10 other also-ran
Republicans, pray that George W. Bush implodes. The Granite State's
twin reputations for rock-ribbed patriotism and humbling
front-runners are McCain's pair of hole cards here.
</P>
<P>
   Every one of the dozen Republicans is running as an
anti-Clinton. Much talk of homespun virtues punctuates their stump
speechifying. But just as he was the only Republican to declare US
ground troops as the sensible way to defeat Milosevic, and just as
he is the only Republican four-square against soft money and the
existing campaign finance loopholes, and just as he is the only
heavyweight Republican to take on Big Tobacco and the telecom
lobbyists, he enjoys one other distinction:
</P>
<P>
   He's the only conservative arguing against ``the pervasive
public cynicism that is debilitating our democracy . . . cynicism
bordering on alienation.'' And he bravely admits it's not just
Clinton at fault. ``We who are currently privileged to hold public
office have ourselves to blame for this sickness in American public
life. It is we who have squandered the public trust. We, who have
time and again, in full public view, placed our personal or
partisan interests before the national interest, earning the
public's contempt with our poll-driven policies, our phony
posturing, the lies we call spin, and the damage control we
substitute for progress.''
</P>
<P>
   Wow!
</P>
<P>
   If you read no other political speech this year, go to
www.mccain2000.com and dig up his May 27 commencement speech at
Johns Hopkins. It'll make even liberal Democrats think about
sending a check to the most truth-telling candidate in either
party. I guess once you've been a POW for a sixth of your adult
life, you might as well tell it like it is. The Beltway scandal
culture may raise the premium on McCain's years in a Hanoi prison
after his jet was shot down. ``The most dramatic contrast we have
to the Clinton era is John McCain,'' South Carolina legislator
Terry Haskins told The Los Angeles Times. ``He's a national hero
known as a leader who tells the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   McCain hopes to use South Carolina's early primary in a
pro-military state (two weeks after New Hampshire) to jack him into
contention in California. If Bush wins both Iowa and New Hampshire,
the Texan will be nigh unstoppable. McCain seems to be lowballing
Iowa, where his stand against ethanol (corn-into-fuel) subsidies
irks corn-growing, subsidy-fed farmers. So New Hampshire looks to
be make-or-break for McCain, 62, taking his last, best shot.
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore served in the Vietnam era, and George W. Bush the
Younger flew National Guard training missions in Texas. But
McCain's the man for veterans who feel they'd prefer someone who
mirrors their own life experience and sacrifices for the purposes
of patriotism. The fact that McCain does not demagogue his story or
mock those who've not been called upon to make the kinds of
sacrifices he had to face makes him attractive to a broad range of
voters who do not necessarily share his views on a wide range of
issues. He's managed to raise enough money to compete despite
alienating the deep-pocketed lobbyists who bankroll the campaigns
of others.
</P>
<P>
   McCain's is in the middle of the small-medium-large candidacies,
where none but Bush's is large among the Republicans. But in the
money chase, for '99's first six months, McCain is a respectable,
if distant, fourth overall. The heavy lifters siphoning $1,000
checks are Bush, $23 million; Al Gore, $18 million; Bill Bradley,
$11 million; and then way behind him McCain at $4.3 million, with
Elizabeth Dole and Dan Quayle around $3 million each. Absent from
this list of mendicants is Steve Forbes, most of whose money comes
from his vast personal stash.
</P>
<P>
   For McCain, whose jihad against the corruption of the current
campaign finance system wins him few friends among the professional
lobbyists, this is a solid showing. ``The system has become
corrupted by the influence of soft money, and average Americans are
not represented any longer. And we need to clean it up,'' he told a
Nashua audience Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   But the GOP voters who flock behind Bush's poll ratings seem
more comfortable with Bush's cash-drenched front-runnership than
McCain's hair shirt. Winnability is the Bush bottom line. The
latest Des Moines Register poll pegs Bush at 40 percent among Iowa
Republicans, Dole 13, and Forbes, off his most recent $10 million
ad outlay, at 10, with all other Republican candidates below 5
percent. McCain is spurning a $25-a-head Iowa straw poll at Ames,
calling it a lobbyists' hog fest.
</P>
<P>
   McCain has to sneak up on Bush in New Hampshire, solidify that
showing in flag-waving South Carolina, then gallop into California
on the white stallion of reform, a warrior back from the wars
vowing to clean out the stable in D.C.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1335EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
