<HEADER>
A7212 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-GULLIKSON-BOS &LR;      07-02 1632
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-GULLIKSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A SPIRITED TIME FOR GULLIKSON AS DAVIS CUP NEARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Technically, he is here among the ancients, playing in
the 45-and-over gentlemen's doubles. But Tom Gullikson's real
business is to keep an eye on his immediate tennis future. And no
matter how he fares among Wimbledon's senior citizens, the American
men in the main draw are giving him reason to frolic.
</P>
<P>
   The 47-year-old US Davis Cup captain has watched two of his
players, Todd Martin and reborn team man Pete Sampras, advance to
the quarterfinals in this rain delay wrapped around occasional
serves and volleys. The third member of the American contingent
that will face Australia in the Cup quarterfinals at Longwood July
16-18, Jim Courier, came within a whisker of joining them before
Tim Henman put an end to his heroic performance in a five-set
fourth-rounder, one of three Courier matches to go the distance.
``At least I didn't have to look for a court to practice on for the
Davis Cup,'' Courier observed after his surprisingly long stay
here.
</P>
<P>
   And for what it's worth, a once and perhaps future Gullikson
patriotic protege, Andre Agassi, is also in the quarters, most of
which were washed away Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jimbo played great,'' Gullikson says. ``Todd, Pete, and Andre
are playing great, too. It's great for US tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   Pardon Gullikson if he seems stuck on one adjective. He tends to
see things only in terms of superlatives these days, ever since his
cast of supposed rejects _ Courier, Martin, and Martin's doubles
partner, Alex O'Brien _ scored a titanic upset of host England with
a 3-2 first-round Cup victory at Birmingham in April. It was a
blockbuster series _ decided when Courier outlasted favored Greg
Rusedski, 8-6, in the fifth set of the concluding match _ and it so
revitalized the Davis Cup's stature that even the players became
interested in it again. Now that, Gullikson will tell you, was
really great for American tennis.
</P>
<P>
   ``For those of us who were there,'' he says, ``it was something
special we'll always share. Those who saw it wished they were
there.''
</P>
<P>
   For instance, a certain Greek-American kid tuning in at home in
Orlando, Fla., who happens to be the No. 1 singles player in the
world, perhaps in history. In January, Sampras, who had been guided
to the top by Gullikson's twin brother, Tim, resisted Tom's
entreaties to play in Birmingham _ or anywhere else the Cup would
be contested in 1999. A week after the latest American revolution,
he was on the phone to Gullikson, asking if the captain might be
able to use him in Boston _ in doubles only, so he wouldn't step on
Martin's and Courier's toes.
</P>
<P>
   Talk about team spirit . . .
</P>
<P>
   And over here, the red, white, and blue have been coated in
saccharine. Courier, Martin, Sampras, and Agassi _ all in their
late 20s, all basically fierce rivals and occasional uneasy Cup
allies throughout their careers _ have been bonding with a
vengeance. They have attended each other's matches, rooted one
another on, enthused over each other's victories. As Sampras puts
it, ``There's a lot of love in the air.'' Including Agassi, who has
vowed never to play Davis Cup again after the dismissal of team
physician George Fareed this year, though Gullikson holds out hope
for a change of heart, even if not this year: ``You never say
never.''
</P>
<P>
   Of the Four Musketeer spirit, Gullikson says, ``I think they're
at a place where their place in tennis is secure. There's not that
intense competition of earlier days. They can relax and enjoy
themselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And the catalyst was Birmingham.
</P>
<P>
   ``Of all the Davis Cup ties in my six years as captain,'' says
Gullikson, ``this is the most talked-about.''
</P>
<P>
   It has eclipsed even the peak achievement of his Cup reign, the
victory over Russia in 1995 that gave the United States the
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was in December,'' says Gullikson. ``There was football,
basketball, hockey going on. We got hardly any coverage.''
</P>
<P>
   Now one measly first-round melodrama has transformed the Cup
into an Event. When the United States tries to raze Rafter _ and
Philippoussis and Woodforde and Woodbridge _ at Longwood, Gullikson
gleefully anticipates unprecedented attention.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's why they sold out all the seats at Longwood in 51
minutes,'' he says. ``That's why they had something like 20,000
calls in the first two hours after tickets went on sale. I've never
seen anything like it.''
</P>
<P>
   Interest is so great that Gullikson can't escape it. Before
coming here, he took his family on a cruise to the British Virgin
Islands _ ``My Wimbledon warmup,'' he says _ and he couldn't walk
into a pub without someone wanting to belly up to the Cup. ``The
people all were talking about it,'' he says. ``Especially the
American sailors.''
</P>
<P>
   Not that he's complaining. This is an idyllic time to be the
Davis Cup captain, usually a thankless position. The situation is
almost perfect for Gullikson. Only one thing could make it better,
but he knows he can't have that.
</P>
<P>
   Tim won't be there.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Even by the standards of twins, they were inseparable. Tim and
Tom Gullikson basically were weaned on tennis. Tom remembers that
at age 5, when they became particularly rambunctious, their mother
would haul them across the street to the La Crosse branch of the
University of Wisconsin, which featured eight courts and a practice
wall _ the perfect toys to keep the boys from driving her crazy.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the time we were 8, we were pretty good,'' says Tom. ``We
became court rats. We had each other to play with.''
</P>
<P>
   Always, and in all sports. They didn't focus on tennis, playing
baseball, football, and basketball in season, in La Crosse and then
Onalaska, where the family moved when they were 12. At Northern
Illinois University, both played freshman basketball. And in
tennis, they became All-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   But playing it for a living didn't occur to them, as much as
they loved the game. Tom coached his alma mater for a year, then
moved to the Chicago area as a teaching pro. Tim also was a
teaching pro, but he supplemented his income by playing _ and
winning _ some local events, whose fields included the occasional
ATP touring pro. Eventually, he persuaded some local businessmen to
bankroll him on the major league circuit.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Tom saw that his brother was experiencing some
success and figured, ``I can do that.'' He bet the house on his
ability, for there were no sponsors for him. He and his wife,
Julie, a schoolteacher, used the money they'd set aside for a
mortgage to fund Tom's ATP endeavor.
</P>
<P>
   They became decent journeymen despite their late start. Between
them, they won five singles titles _ Tom's came at Newport in 1985
_ and a dozen doubles. Tim reached the No. 18 ranking in singles;
Tom peaked in the 30s. In doubles, they cracked the Top 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what helped us was having been teaching pros,'' says
Tom. ``Nobody had coaches traveling with them back then; there
wasn't enough money in it. But as teaching pros, we'd look for
players' weaknesses, discuss them, decide how to attack them.''
</P>
<P>
   They split for a year in 1982, ``when we got sick of one another
for a while,'' says Tom, but for the most part, the tour was just
an extension of La Crosse and Onalaska for them. They were together
more often than not.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tim was the extremist,'' says Tom. ``He was always reading
books, trying new things. Every day with him was an adventure.''
</P>
<P>
   They became known for their hustle and diligence, as players who
always gave it their best, never tanked. ``The Midwestern work
ethic,'' says Tom. ``I think that's what helped us as coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   That was their career path after their playing days ended in the
late '80s. Tom joined the US Tennis Association teaching program,
tutored the likes of Courier and Martin, and after Tom Gorman
announced his retirement as Davis Cup captain at the US Open in
1993, he got the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember my first tie as captain was in India in '94,'' he
says. ``Pete and Andre took a pass. I wondered who in the world I
could get to go. I called Jimbo, and the first thing he said was,
`Who else can we get?' He and Todd were there. They've always been
there for me.''
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Tim assumed an even higher profile. He took
over as Sampras's coach, developed his grass game, and transformed
him into a Wimbledon champion, a Grand Slam perennial, the finest
player in the world.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1995, the separation process began for the brothers, and
there was no stopping it.
</P>
<P>
   At the Australian Open, Tim began experiencing savage headaches.
Eventually, he couldn't leave his hotel room to attend Sampras's
matches. Finally, he flew home, where his condition was diagnosed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Four inoperable brain tumors,'' says Tom.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras wept openly on a court in Melbourne after hearing the
news. Tom spent as much time as he could with his brother for the
next year and a half.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was very tough, seeing him deteriorate,'' says Tom. ``I
couldn't do anything for him. I felt helpless.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim died May 3, 1996, six months after Tom captured the Cup. In
his memory, Tom established the Tim and Tom Gullikson Foundation to
assist brain tumor patients and their families. As a further
memorial, he continues to run the Davis Cup team ``year by year,''
he says. ``As long as the players want me, I'd like to do it. If
they don't, I'll graciously step aside. I like the tennis, but not
the politics and recruiting calls.''
</P>
<P>
   There's one thing he won't abandon, no matter what his position.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think of Tim every day,'' says Gullikson. ``I draw
inspiration from him every day.''
</P>
<P>
   So his team will have a surplus at Longwood.
</P>
</TEXT>
