<HEADLINE>
BAUMHAUER LEADS ANOTHER CHARGE UP HAMBURGER HILL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVEN SYRE AND CHARLES STEIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As any diner or investor will tell you, there is steak and then
there is hamburger. This is a story about hamburgers.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year after he resigned as chief executive of Unique
Casual Restaurants Inc., William Baumhauer has returned to again
lead the struggling Danvers, Mass. company. It isn't clear whether
that makes his biggest shareholder very happy.
</P>
<P>
   In the brief time he has been gone, Unique shares have sunk
further and management just barely headed off a proxy fight with
dissident stockholders who wanted to dismantle what was left of the
company and turn off the lights.
</P>
<P>
   Baumhauer was the man who built Unique and its predecessor, Daka
International Inc., into a modest food-service empire that included
more than 200 dinner-on-a-budget Fuddruckers restaurants and
watched it later run into serious trouble. Like other Unique
executives, he did not return our calls this week.
</P>
<P>
   Baumhauer resigned last year to play an unusual long shot:
turning around the imploding Planet Hollywood International Inc.,
an eatery with glitzy movie-star investors but terrible business
fundamentals.
</P>
<P>
   He hired on as Planet Hollywood's president, working for chief
executive Robert Earl, with a compensation package that was highly
dependent on a stock turnaround.
</P>
<P>
   Baumhauer loaded up on 750,000 stock options with an exercise
price of $5 each. When Planet Hollywood shares continued to sink,
the options were repriced at $2.50 by the end of last year. If that
sounds like a sweet deal, consider Planet Hollywood's closing price
Thursday: 75 cents per share.
</P>
<P>
   Other executives have been jumping ship ever since Planet
Hollywood blew a $15 million interest payment on April 1. The
company negotiated with lenders to restructure terms of its secured
debt.
</P>
<P>
   Now Baumhauer, an accountant by training, is presented with
perhaps the strangest turn of all since he got into the food
business 17 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   He joined a young Fuddruckers business as its chief financial
officer in 1982, helped bring the company public the next year and
became president in 1985.
</P>
<P>
   Boom and bust cycles followed and by 1988 he merged the company
with a small Massachusetts food service company and hotel business
to form what became known as Daka International. If you work at a
big company in Greater Boston, Daka may have once run your office
cafeteria.
</P>
<P>
   Daka stock soared in the mid-1990s thanks to aggressive
expansion but fell hard in 1996, when it became clear the company
had overextended itself with an arrangement to provide food service
for Kmart Corp.'s stores, which numbered more than 1,800 at the
time. The deal fizzled before it ever got off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Then next year, Baumhauer sold off the company's contract for
business to British caterer Compass PLC for $195 million in cash
and assumed debt. Unique Casual Restaurants was formed as a public
company to own the rest of the business, principally the
Fuddruckers restaurants.
</P>
<P>
   It was hardly a runaway success, and two weeks after Baumhauer
jumped to Planet Hollywood, Unique announced plans to sell its
204-store Fuddruckers group for $43 million. The announced goal was
to put more money into another, smaller budget restaurant chain it
owned in the Midwest, Champps Americana, but analysts immediately
speculated on the breakup of the company.
</P>
<P>
   Unique's chief financial officer, Donald Moore, was put in
charge of the company on an interim basis and Bear Stearns &AMP; Co.
was brought in to help figure out what to do with the rest of the
business.
</P>
<P>
   Moore quickly ran afoul of his largest shareholder, Atticus
Partners of New York, which owns about 16 percent of the company
and believed the interim CEO was getting too comfortable with his
new job and improved salary.
</P>
<P>
   Atticus Partners launched a proxy fight to take control of the
board, complaining that Moore appeared to be working on _ gasp! _ a
plan to rebuild the company.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do not want to see the company's coffers, full of
stockholders' money, depleted in an ill-conceived plan proposed by
a manager with little experience running, much less quickly
growing, this type of business,'' wrote Timothy Barakett, a
managing member of Atticus Holdings. Barakett did not return our
call Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The proxy fight was headed off by compromise in March. The board
was expanded by two to accommodate Barakett and another
Atticus-picked director. Barakett and one director from the
existing board would form a strategic committee of two to plot the
future of the company and its top executives.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Unique says it has decided to remain independent, with
Moore back to his old job. And Baumhauer has his work cut out for
him.
</P>
<P>
   Pass the ketchup.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Red Herring
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On fire? The initial public stock offering of Yankee Candle Co.
hit the market Thursday and jumped 34 percent to 24 1/8. The
Whatley, Mass. company, which makes and sells scented candles,
ended its first day of trading with a stock market value of about
$1.3 billion.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Steven Syre and Charles Stein can be reached by e-mail at
boscap(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
