<HEADLINE>
YOU CAN STILL FIND ESCAPE IN THE NORTH COUNTRY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By TONY CHAMBERLAIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   So you pull into God's Country Acres campground ready for a
little wilderness therapy and the Winnebego next to you (parked so
close you and they can't open doors at the same time) keeps a TV
blasting. And those Jay Leno jokes are even lamer in summer reruns.
</P>
<P>
   Or you pitch your tent and get ready to snooze under the stars
and the whoops of a kegger orgy down on the riverbank rise to a din
when a battle ensues over whether the Knicks are a basketball team
or a bunch of thugs.
</P>
<P>
   Is that what's bothering you just a little bit as this last
summer of the millennium gets underway?
</P>
<P>
   The fact is there aren't many places in New England where the
traditions of simplicity, quality, and beauty have not been glommed
over by fast-junk restaurants, trendy T-shirt shops, and ``trading
posts'' dealing authentic made-in-Taiwan Indian goods.
</P>
<P>
   Not that theme parks and scenic railroad rides don't have their
place in The Great American Vacation. But some souls still long for
the real unbesmirched outdoor experience where man meets a nature
that can still humble him, fill him with awe and unconditional
appreciation. There are still a few such places left. Here's a
six-pack:
</P>
<P>
   --While much of the Cape and the islands suffer from the
ceaseless development pressure caused by the effects of the
10-thou-Dow, there are a few getaways protected from Bochanization
of all places desirable.
</P>
<P>
   Although Provincetown is a summer tourist mecca with the best
restaurants on the Cape, the beaches of the National Seashore are
devoid of crowds in proportion to how far one is willing to walk
the beach. At some points along the 26-mile stretch from the
Province Lands Visitor Center and Nauset Beach in Orleans, the
walker is utterly alone with the open Atlantic, whose rhythmic
surging roll invites the muse that inspired writers from Thoreau to
Jack Kerouac, Eugene O'Neill, and Tennessee Williams, all of whom
stayed in squatters' shacks.
</P>
<P>
   Roughing it away from the crowds means hiking the strand, taking
your entire life-support needs with you, and that should include
lots of water. There are developed beaches _ Head of the Meadow
(Truro), Newcomb's Hollow (Wellfleet) along the way _ but the
passage between them is many miles where almost no one goes.
</P>
<P>
   --Every traffic jam that occurs after every ferry that arrives
at Martha's Vineyard reminds one of the hungry hordes of barberi
who swarmed across the frozen Rhine River trying to get their own
piece of beauteous Rome. Their sheer numbers changed unalterably
that which they desired.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, for this reason, Vineyard natives have restricted their
best beaches (Lucy Vincent and Squibnocket) to pass holders.
Temporary passes are available at some hotels.
</P>
<P>
   But travelers looking for the best Vineyard experience should
leave cars home and bike their way to the On Time _ Chappaquidick
Ferry. From here the Wasque Reservation and beach is quite nice,
generally uncrowded, and like the Cape Cod National Seashore, lends
itself to a long walk away from this world, temporary living on the
shore of Nantucket Sound. Repeat suggestion: Do not bring a car.
Buses and sandals can take you anywhere.
</P>
<P>
   --Nantucket's turf war is between the super-rich and the
mega-rich, but in stark contrast to the Vineyard the island has
managed to keep more than 100 miles of its coastline open to the
public. Despite the growing tackiness of downtown Nantucket, there
are still beaches on this island that rate as true getaways. Cisco,
on the southwest shore, is not one of them, but the stretch from
there west to Madaket boasts the best surf in Massachusetts,
perhaps New England. The farther west you walk, the more alone you
will be, where the pounding surf often deters families and large
groups with children.
</P>
<P>
   This 4-mile stretch between Cisco and Madaket is a more private
experience, and a better body surfing one than even Surfside Beach
itself, which gets crowded. Siasconset is tamer, and very
beautiful. Again, to enjoy the Nantucket experience, leave the car
at home. Bikes are perfect transportation here. Get it while it
lasts!
</P>
<P>
   --Leaping north, we find a New England enclave as beautiful as
it is poor. The late Vermont senator, George Aiken, named the
``Northeast Kingdom'' _ a tract of wilderness and farmland bordered
on the east by the Connecticut River and west by the 4,000-foot Jay
Peak, which stands out sharply like an obilisk. Mephremagog, a deep
30-mile long glacial lake that runs between Newport, Vt., well into
Quebec, draws the northern border, and the town of St. Johnsbury
and its environs mark the south.
</P>
<P>
   While Newport is a well-traveled region, drop down through the
rolling countryside to magnificent Lake Willoughby along Route 5A.
This is another deep lake surrounded by fabulous wilderness camping
once you wander away from the development surrounding the immediate
shore.
</P>
<P>
   Willoughby has a natural fjord at its southern end, created by
the abrupt rise of two mountains _ Pisgah and Hor. Hiking and
camping on these heights is as good as it gets. There's plenty of
room to park and leave a vehicle to hike into the woods. Do use
maps (DeLormes are best). The nearby towns of Island Pond, Orleans,
and Barton are also gateways to tremendous wilderness camping and
hiking.
</P>
<P>
   --Leave New Hampshire's Six Gun City and other White Mountain
blights at your back as you head north along Routes 145 and 3, way
up into the narrow neck of the state that inserts itself between
the forestland of Quebec to the west and Maine east.
</P>
<P>
   This lyrical land of green hills and deep water is the rise of
the 400-mile Connecticut River that runs south through four states
to Long Island Sound. The stars swing low here at night, for there
are no motel lights, curbside malls, nor even curbs or
streetlights, for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   The camping opportunities range from authentically rustic
fishing camps to organized camper parks, to random wilderness
everywhere. Hike into the Quebec borderland around Fourth Lake for
a real getaway _ accessible from Route 3. Or trek along the east
shore of First Connecticut Lake or Lake Francis for some of the
most beautiful unspoiled lakeside tenting, canoeing, fishing,
hiking you will find anywhere. Again, use topo maps and talk to the
locals.
</P>
<P>
   --The most effective conservationist in New England history was
Percival Baxter, who, in his tenure as governor of Maine, amassed a
tract of 201,000 acres of prime wilderness in central Maine and
made it a gift to his beloved state. The deed required only that
the land, Baxter State Park, be maintained forever in its natural
state. This very mandate makes Baxter, not an undiscovered
backwater, but an unspoiled region with many opportunities for
privacy and wilderness getaways.
</P>
<P>
   The overwhelmingly dominant feature of the park is mile-high
Katahdin, a mountain that invites hiking by experts and
intermediates as well. Lots of hikers _ including Appalachian Trail
through-hikers _ are found around Katahdin, but those looking for
solitude should make tracks farther north into the vast lake
country known as Allagash Wilderness Waterway that offers getaway
camping and hiking almost at every turn.
</P>
<P>
   The big North Woods country is a serious undertaking, and should
be planned and well-mapped. Gravel-packed logging roads allow
access to the woods for nearly 100 miles north of Baxter. The
Forest Service and lumber companies that own this country will
require sign-in/sign-out for autos, and Baxter has a daily quota,
so call ahead.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Tony Chamberlain writes about the outdoors for The Boston Globe.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
