<SLUG> BC-HANDYMAN-HOTTON-$ADV04-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ANTS NOT THE CAUSE OF SAGGING FLAGSTONE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 04, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER HOTTON  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Q. Our exterior flagstone terrace sags because ants diligently
remove sand from under the flat stones. Stonemasons have no
suggestions. A plastic layer on top of the sand would hold water,
and freeze. How about a layer of poison under the stones? What
poison?
</P>
<P>
   NAT PULSIFER, Ipswich, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. First, don't use a poison; it will not last long enough to be
of help. Second, I don't think it's the work of the ants that is
causing the sagging, but rather the sand was not tamped enough when
the stones were installed, so the stones dropped. I think the
solution is to lift the stones, install more sand and compact it
very thoroughly, then relay the stones.
</P>
<P>
   Plastic under the stones will deter the growth of weeds, but it
won't deter the ants. If you use plastic, use perforated plastic
for water to drain through, or an agricultural cloth, which also
allows water to drain. If you want to keep ahead of the ants, and
they are obvious on the terrace or their little hills are obvious,
douse them with boiling water twice a day.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. In the new house I am buying, the contractor used a Masonite
clapboard, rough side out and painted. Is that material any good,
or is there anything wrong with it?
</P>
<P>
   PAT LANGUZZI, Waltham, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. Masonite is a brand name for hardboard, a composite of ground
wood and epoxy pressed into a thin, hard sheet or board. There are
several other brands. It has a lot of good uses, but not, in my
opinion, as siding. As with all ersatz siding, it does not work as
well as wood, and must be kept heavily painted to stand up to the
weather. It is particularly susceptable to water. In fact, some
manufacturers are defendants in class-action suits over premature
failure and decay of the material. The above are opinions, but if I
were you, I would not buy that house, although you could take a
chance and hope the hardboard will last 15 or 20 years (not long
for siding). Then rip it off and put up cedar clapboards, red cedar
shingles and stain them, or white cedar shingles and let them
weather without treatment.
</P>
<P>
   Manufacturers have been struggling for years to find a good
substitute for wood, cedar in particular. First they tried asphalt
siding (double ugh!), then asbestos cement (a health hazard if not
left alone), aluminum siding (it dents and loses its paint over
time), and vinyl (just ugly). Even now they are making an
asbestos-free mineral siding (clapboards and shingles), and the
publicists are singing its praises. It ain't wood.
</P>
<P>
   There are concerns that we are running out of wood, but other
sources say there is still plenty, and more can be grown. The only
substitute for wood is brick, and it is not really a substitute. If
you have a chance to buy a brick house, and can afford it, do so.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. I have a place on Cotuit Beach with a driveway and some areas
with 3/4-inch crushed stone. Weeds are growing like crazy through
it. I tried Roundup (an herbicide) but it lasts only two months. A
friend suggested using rock salt. What will work?
</P>
<P>
   JOE CALLAHAN, Belmont, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. You could put agricultural cloth or perforated black plastic
under the crushed stone. This may last a while, but not forever.
Don't use salt; it will contaminate everything it touches. Bleach
will work, but you'd have to use a lot of it; bleach breaks down to
a harmless element when it comes in contact with the earth, but I
am not convinced it is that safe.
</P>
<P>
   So, try vinegar. It has worked for many persons with weeds
coming up through brick and flagstone patios. It is like acid rain,
but vinegar in the ground is probably least hazardous to the
environment and nearby plants. A treatment in the spring, when the
weeds emerge, should last all summer.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My husband stained our red cedar shingles. First he washed
them down with bleach and water, which splattered on the windows,
causing indelible stains. I tried Clearvue (a super cleaner)
without success. Also unsucessful was Fantastic, paint thinner,
ammonia, and Spic and Span. Now what?
</P>
<P>
   JOAN LOVELY, Salem, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. About the ony thing left is vinegar. Or Bug &AMP; Tar Remover,
designed to remove things from auto chrome and finishes. Or, as a
last result, try Never Dull Magic Wadding, sold in hardware and
building stores. It is designed to clean metal, but will also work
for glass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. My gas burner for central heating is original with the house,
built 45 years ago. It's working OK, and a gas man said as long as
I clean it regularly, it will last forever. A plumber disagreed
with this advice, suggesting that I replace it when I can. Who's
right.
</P>
<P>
   G. McCULLOCH, Roslindale, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   A. They both are. How's that for evading the question?
``Forever'' is a long time, but as long as the burner is working
well, and the heating bills are tolerable, keep it. It ain't broke,
so you don't have to fix it. On the other hand, a burner 45 years
old is probably not as efficient as modern burners, so the option
is to replace it when you feel like it or can afford it. I don't
think the need is urgent.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Globe Handyman on Call Peter Hotton will answer reader questions.
Write him at the Boston Globe, Boston, Mass., 02107.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
