<HEADER>
A7226 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOOK-RADCLYFFE-BOS &LR;      07-02 0861
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOOK-RADCLYFFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE BRAVE, UNYIELDING RADCLYFFE HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ELLEN CLEGG  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE TRIALS OF RADCLYFFE HALL 
By Diana Souhami 
Doubleday, 458 pp., illustrated, $27.95 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Radclyffe Hall had ambitious plans for ``The Well of
Loneliness,'' her grim saga about a woman who loves other women.
Used to the power and control conferred by independent wealth, she
was also ready to give polite society a poke in the eye. ``Having
attained literary success I have put my pen at the service of some
of the most persecuted and misunderstood people in the world. In a
word I have written a long and very serious novel entirely upon the
subject of sexual inversion. . . . So far as I know nothing of the
kind has ever been attempted before in fiction.''
</P>
<P>
   But Hall was still not entirely prepared for the controversy
that erupted when her novel was published in England in 1928. The
British courts deemed it obscene, and copies were destroyed.
Support from the era's literary lights was tepid: Virginia Woolf
called it a ``meritorious dull book'' and E.M. Forster questioned
its literary worth. And Hall, who had been awarded the Prix Femina
for her novel ``Adam's Breed,'' was knocked off balance and would
never write anything as famous _ or infamous _ again.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Souhami's tart, witty biography gives Hall her due in the
pantheon of gay and lesbian pioneers, but isn't about to nominate
her for sainthood. Truth and detail can be hard on heroes, and
Radclyffe Hall, known as ``John,'' is no exception. Entitled,
eccentric and reactionary, she adopted all the trappings of
Victorian patriarchy, down to the tweeds and sexual conquests. She
abjured feminism and modernism, yet she shocked the British
literary establishment by refusing to change pronouns or bend
gender. That wasn't enough to make her a great writer _ her plots
are sometimes implausible and her prose is tedious _ but it was
enough to keep ``Well of Loneliness'' in print for 70 years, and to
pave the way for bolder efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1880, Marguerite Radclyffe Hall was unwanted, uneducated
and dyslexic. Her parents divorced; her stepfather sexually abused
her. ``Dark forces informed her early years,'' Souhami writes.
``Abandonment elided with insecurity, hatred of her mother with
aggrandizement of herself. Unfairness called for justice and
violence for revenge.'' The patterns of her adult life began to
jell when she was 18, and her father died, leaving her a small
fortune. Already smitten by the young women who came to her
stepfather's house to take voice lessons, Hall used her money to
attain a kind of sexual freedom. ``She preferred to be known as
Peter, a sobriquet that did not stick. She swept her hair back from
her face, wore tailored clothes, wide-brimmed hats and plain but
expensive jewels. . . . Unmistakably lesbian, she was not going to
pretend a passing interest in men.''
</P>
<P>
   Hall pursued the life of a country squire and wrote sheaves of
bad poetry. Her life seemed unmarked by ambition or drive. In
August 1906, however, a trip to see a women's tennis tournament
changed her life. Watching the Wimbledon champion, Dorothea
Chambers, play a lesbian friend, Hall was introduced to Mabel
Batten. A buxom socialite with taste for luxury (and a closet full
of shoes), Batten was known for her very public misbehavior with
Edward, Prince of Wales. On holiday together with significant
others, Batten and Hall fell in love. The relationship would help
sustain Hall _ Batten edited Hall's first short stories _ until
Batten's death in 1916. It was Batten who gave Hall the name John,
which she used for the rest of her life.
</P>
<P>
   But Batten, like other lovers in Hall's life, was doomed to be
one leg of a triangle. Hall carried on openly with Batten's cousin,
Una Troubridge, who ultimately usurped the role of amanuensis and
helpmeet. All her life, Hall seemed to build up stable
relationships in order to fracture them. Impulse control was never
a strong suit: She moved from country estates to London flats and
back again. She traveled Europe with a kind of moneyed mania, the
Lady Troubridge in tow. A Catholic convert, she indulged a lifetime
interest in the spirit world and consulted regularly with a psychic
medium. It's a wonder any writing got done at all.
</P>
<P>
   Like Oscar Wilde, Radclyffe Hall refused to wither away when
straight society condemned her. More than 70 years later, her
determination to defend her art and her own identity ring with a
clarity of purpose. She had the money and hubris to fight back.
Cast in the fine light of history, her testimony before a packed
gallery at Bow Street Magistrates Court looks courageous. ``Well of
Loneliness'' was published in Paris, and in the United States,
where the Society for the Suppression of Vice lost a censorship bid
in 1929. In fact, the book sold briskly.
</P>
<P>
   Hall lived until 1943. The fame she craved was forever tinged
with notoriety, but she holds an important place in the struggle
for the freedom of art and the freedom of thought. It's an
elevating legacy for a difficult and not always admirable woman.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
