<SLUG> BC-BEAM-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARKEY`S CYNICAL V-CHIP CHARGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ALEX BEAM  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Congressman Ed Markey tried, unsuccessfully, to surf the
nuclear-freeze fad into the White House during the 1980s. Now he's
got a brand-new bag: dialing up the hype on the dopey ``V-chip,''
allying himself with prominent Democrats who are cynically preying
upon parents' insecurities after the Columbine High School
massacre.
</P>
<P>
   Markey claims to have coined the term ``V-chip'' six years ago.
The V stands for ``violence,'' which the little semiconductor is
supposed to filter out of television broadcasts. After years of
wrangling, Markey and like-minded social engineers have browbeaten
the networks into adopting a ``voluntary'' ratings code. As of
Thursday, half of the TV sets made in America had to have the chip.
By January, all US televisions will have the device.
</P>
<P>
   Now Markey and newly minted family-value-crats like Connecticut
senator Joseph Lieberman (who, as Hartford Courant columnist Colin
McEnroe points out, pushes his ``values'' agenda in between the
anti-Semitic jokes on the Don Imus radio show) are trying to
Mau-Mau major newspaper publishers into printing the ratings codes.
In letters sent out earlier this week, Markey &AMP; Company urge
publishers to hop on the V-chip bandwagon, ``to assist parents in
your circulation area.'' By inference, newspapers that decline to
play along with Markey's charade will be deemed ``anti-family
values.''
</P>
<P>
   Only two major papers _ The Los Angeles Times and USA Today _
carry the full boat of age and content codes that the childless
Markey deems so important for parents to know about. (The V-chip
can be programmed without knowing the newspaper codes, a point that
Markey doesn't emphasize.) ``Dallas'' is content-coded ``LSV,''
alerting viewers to problems with language, sex, and violence. The
1955 Oscar-winning William Holden weeper, ``Love Is a Many
Splendored Thing,'' is coded ``violent'' on the American Movie
Classics channel. Give me a break!
</P>
<P>
   Some papers, like the Globe and The New York Times, print
partial parental guidelines. But other publishers have seen through
the hoax. Not only are the ratings ridiculous, the V-chip itself
has no supporters other than professional advocacy groups and
publicity-crazed politicians. According to a spokesperson, The
Washington Post's television editor has had two, possibly three,
inquiries about the V-chip ratings in the past 2 1/2 years. The
Post does not print the ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Susan Bischoff, assistant managing editor of the Houston
Chronicle, says, ``We decided to see how the codes actually worked,
and how the readers would react'' before including them in TV
listings. Not only have the codes proved to be controversial, she
says, but ``we have not had one request from a reader to include
them. Not one educator, one parent, or one church group has written
or called any of us.'' Other than Ed Markey, of course.
</P>
<P>
   But wait, it gets better. Despite reams of free publicity, the
V-chip is a complete bomb with consumers, too. ``No one cares,''
says Tweeter spokeswoman Anne-Marie Boucher. At her company's 26
New England stores, ``no one's coming in and asking for it.'' No
computer chip can substitute for legitimate parental controls. The
V-chip makes for good politics and jazzy press releases, but it has
nothing to do with parenting.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A conservative's compassion
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Elsewhere on the ideological spectrum, we find right-wing
talk-show host Michael Savage of San Francisco threatening to sue
president-assumptive George W. Bush for hijacking the moniker
``compassionate conservative.'' According to his Web site, Savage
published a book entitled ``Savage Nation: The Compassionate
Conservative Speaks,'' and he has also conducted four
``compassionate conservative'' conventions in the San Francisco Bay
Area since 1995. For the moment, Bush spokesman David Beckwith has
been able to laugh off Savage.
</P>
<P>
   Here's what passes for conservative compassion. In an interview
with the Christian Science Monitor, Savage shared his feelings
about San Francisco's homeless population: ``I hate panhandlers'
guts.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Alex Beam's e-dress is beam(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
