<SLUG> BC-MOVIE-LOLA-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRIPLE-FUN `LOLA' MAKES ALL THE RIGHT MOVES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAY CARR  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
RUN LOLA RUN 
Written and directed by: Tom Tykwer 
Starring: Franka Potente, Moritz Bleibtreu, Herbert Knaup, Armin
Rohde 
Running time: 81 minutes 
Rated: R (some violence and language) 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Run Lola Run'' puts the motion back in motion pictures. The
only special effect it needs is Franka Potente's sweet, spirited,
and infinitely energetic Lola, who not only carries the film from
the figurative pop of the starter's gun but keeps on running the
race. She carries the film to giddy realms of zippy fun that no
Nike commercial ever dreamed of. Essentially, the film plays out
three versions of the same simple thriller: Lola's boyfriend, a
sweet dummkopf named Manni (Moritz Bleibtreu), bungles a drug drop
while trying to work his way up the criminal food chain and loses
100,000 deutsch marks to a homeless man. Knowing he'll be killed if
he doesn't hand the money over to his boss, who expects it in 20
minutes, he desperately phones Lola.
</P>
<P>
   What then unfolds are three alternative scenarios, each
following hard on the heels of the last, one ending tragically when
Manni decides to hold up a supermarket. What stays the same from
variation to variation is Potente's rush through the streets,
stopping each time at the bank her father runs, with three
different results. The fun actually begins when she gets the phone
call, and we instantly glimpse from the expression on her face that
she knows Manni is dumb, loves him anyway, and speaks from
experience when she tells him not to even think of doing anything
until she gets there. Obviously, he's used to handing off his
problems to her, and she's used to solving them.
</P>
<P>
   The outcome hinges on what happens when Lola is nearly hit by a
car, or stops at a casino, or when Manni spots the derelict who
picked up his bag of money and made off with it. Not much, really,
in eventfulness, but writer-director Tom Tykwer, on his best
multimedia behavior, makes getting there more than half the fun.
The only real danger faced by ``Run Lola Run'' is that it risks
stumbling over its own cleverness as Tykwer dissolves the line
between film and video games. He films Lola and Manni in 35mm, but
otherwise hopscotches all over the media map, using video, black
and white, animation and a cascade of punchy visuals mixing
split-screen shots, quick montage, rapid successions of still
photographs, and even title cards.
</P>
<P>
   They're all pumped along by spiffy editing, a virtuosic
cinematographic melding of the various media and a boppy techno-pop
score. Yet ``Run Lola Run'' has more than technical slickness going
for it. It also achieves an emotional dimension, and that comes
almost entirely from what Potente manages to project as she hurtles
breathlessly through the streets of Berlin. She's scared, but she's
also unhesitatingly heroic, a strong, determined woman who trusts
her own brains, resourcefulness, and courage enough to shoulder the
job of saving her lover's life. ``Run Lola Run'' is worth seeing
just for the mix of brainsand heart shining from beneath Lola's
punked-out features. But the film also flies. Just the other day I
was complaining about the lack of smart , light summer
entertainment. Well, here it is. Go, go, go.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1350EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
