<HEADER>
A7237 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUSIC-CLIFF-BOS &LR;      07-02 0767
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUSIC-CLIFF-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RHYTHM OF THE FUTURE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE MORSE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He was the first reggae artist to perform in Africa, the first
in South America, the first in Japan. Jimmy Cliff has earned his
title of ``Reggae Ambassador.'' Ever since the film ``The Harder
They Come'' made him a star in the '70s, Cliff has carried his
peace-and-love vibe throughout the world.
</P>
<P>
   It figures, then, that he's also the first reggae act to make a
broad millennium statement. His opinions and hopes for the next
century are expressed in his new album, ``Humanitarian,'' which
came out this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a record about bringing out the better side of our
humanity which, going into this new time, is going to be a
necessity,'' Cliff says from a Virginia Beach tour stop. ``The
motivating factor coming into this new time is not going to be
money. It's going to be man's humanity to man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The album also talks about family, about one-to-one love,
about empowering yourself as an individual, and rising up as an
individual and achieving your goals, whether they be spiritual or
material.''
</P>
<P>
   These, of course, are not new topics for Cliff, the Jamaican
idealist who is perhaps best known for the hit, ``You Can Get It if
You Really Want,'' from ``The Harder They Come'' film, which itself
was about rising up from oppression.
</P>
<P>
   And no Cliff album would be complete without an antiwar message.
It comes in the new song, ``How Long,'' with such cogent lyrics as
``How long can this war go on? Every time I look and see another
baby cry/Every time I see another missile fly/How long can this war
go on?''
</P>
<P>
   ``It could be about war in Liberia, or in Kosovo, or in Uganda,
or someplace else on the planet,'' Cliff says.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, Cliff sounds revitalized _ and he credits this to an
exotic, four-week vacation/spiritual pilgrimage that he took
earlier this year _ the first long vacation he has taken during his
career.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to Egypt to check out the temples in Luxor, and that
was a very spiritual place,'' he says. ``And I went to Iran,
because I wanted to see the ancient ruins of Babylon. And I went to
South Africa, which had a profound effect on me spiritually.
</P>
<P>
   ``I almost thought that I wanted to stop doing my music, so I
could travel for the rest of my life to historical places and
explore my soul within these places,'' he says. ``But after I came
back to Jamaica, I started getting that itch to do music again.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff's itch has also been scratched by having a new record
label, Eureka Records, which is solidly behind him. Eureka is a
small indie based in Los Angeles. It's a pleasant change from the
days when Cliff was on a major label (Columbia Records) and felt
lost in the shuffle.
</P>
<P>
   ``I actually started out originally on a small label _ Island
Records in England _ and I've found through the years that working
with a small company is better for me,'' Cliff says. ``There is
more direct communication. It's not a big machine where you can't
really talk with people to find out what's going on. So I prefer
this kind of arrangement.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff has recorded for three decades, which allows him to speak
of himself as an ``epoch artist.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not an artist of one period. I expand over the periods,''
says Cliff, whose roots-reggae music has grown to incorporate
dancehall influences, Brazilian samba, and Caribbean soca. ``I
respect the music that we did a decade or two decades ago, but at
the same time, I stay in tune with what is happening today. Where
is the spirit of the people at this time? I try to make my music
fit in with the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Cliff is now 50 years old, but if you ask how old he is, he
replies impishly, ``I'm living. I'm living and learning. I try not
to look at `Oh, I'm 50 or 52.' I just try to stay healthy and keep
a positive mind. And what gives me the most satisfaction is to be
creative, to make music, and to stay with the times.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the current state of reggae music, Cliff says it is
evolving, too. He points to the influx of new artists _ one being
Shevell Franklin. She's known for singing the hit ``Dancehall
Queen'' with Beanie Man.
</P>
<P>
   ``The music scene in Jamaica is healthy,'' Cliff says. ``We are
at a stage now where I feel the music will shift to a new kind of
rhythm. Reggae music has always been an evolving music _ from ska
to rock-steady to rubba-dub to ragamuffin to dancehall _ and now
it's a stage where people are feeling for something new. It usually
happens at the end of a decade, going into a new decade.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
