<HEADER>
A7243 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TV-HOOP-LIFE-BOS &LR;      07-02 0609
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TV-HOOP-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CREATORS FOUL OUT WITH TRITE `HOOP' 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW GILBERT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
THE HOOP LIFE 
Starring: Mykelti Williamson, Dorian Harewood, Rick Peters, Cirroc
Lofton, Dan Lauria, Raymond Anthony Thomas 
On: Showtime 
Time: Sunday night at 10 
Rated: TVMA 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Showtime's ``The Hoop Life'' should be good TV. For one thing,
it's a ``Levinson/Fontana Production,'' meaning it comes to us from
the shop of Barry Levinson and Tom Fontana, producers of two
extraordinary TV dramas, ``Oz'' and ``Homicide.'' And for another
thing, it arrives at a moment when cable TV is raising the bar on
series television, as HBO productions like ``The Sopranos,''
``Oz,'' and ``Sex and the City'' are showing up network programming
for the shoddy compromise that it is. If every network had three
series _ only three series _ at the quality level of ``The
Sopranos,'' well then, TV critics could moonlight as ministers in
the church of good vibes.
</P>
<P>
   Alas, ``should'' may be the most overrated word in the English
language. ``The Hoop Life,'' which premieres as a two-hour movie
Sunday at 10, is the sort of disappointment that reminds us of just
how very hard it is to create a series that's even halfway
original. The Showtime drama has not a hint of Fontana/Levinson
magic, as it dribbles through overfamiliar tales of a basketball
world ridden with corruption, hedonism, sexism, egoism, and the
occasional act of heroism. The characters are exactly the kinds of
cliches you'd expect to find in a sports-world soap opera, from the
innocent rookie and the sports groupies to the grumpy coach and the
philandering players. And the plot lines go through the motions of
salary disputes and media craziness with absolutely no finesse, no
mystery, and no comic relief. A far cry from ``Homicide'' or
``Oz,'' ``The Hoop Life'' resembles cheesy soft-core melodramas
like the WB's ``Rescue 77,'' or ABC's ``Push,'' both of which were
short-lived.
</P>
<P>
   The action revolves around a fictional team, the New England
Knights, and a fictional NBA-like organization called the United
Basketball Association. (In keeping with the show's generic tone,
the specific location of the Knights is kept vague.) The team's
superstar guard is Marvin Buxton, whose uncontrollable brawling may
get him kicked out of the UBA. Teammate Greg Marr is a cocky
frat-boy type whose extramarital game-playing has gotten him thrown
out of the house. And Leonard Ferro is the gruff coach who is
forever having to defend his decisions to the general manager.
Meanwhile, a high school basketball phenom named Curtis Thorpe is
about to turn pro and get picked up by the Knights. But his
hard-drinking manager, who is also his uncle, gets him into some
serious contract problems. As the show jumps from one story to
another, only the business about Curtis and his uncle has any
resonance, hackneyed though it may be.
</P>
<P>
   The acting is better than the script. As the hotheaded Marvin,
Mykelti Williamson comes out of his compulsive fights without
looking too cartoonish, or, worse, too much the lovable lug with a
temper. And Cirroc Lofton tries to add some mystery to his Curtis,
as the innocent phenom learns hard lessons about the high-paying
world of sports. In the middle of a crisis regarding his future, he
sits by a hotel swimming pool looking effectively stricken. For a
moment, in a show that offers no surprises, you actually wonder
what Curtis will do. But most of the actors are defeated by the
mediocrity, unable to turn their underdeveloped, stereotypical
characters into anything like real people.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
