<P>
   &UR; FINANCIAL &LR;  (``f'' code)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy created more jobs than
expected last month, as average hourly earnings continued to rise,
the Labor Department reported. The economy added 268,000 jobs last
month, more than analysts' forecasts of a 217,000 gain. During May,
payrolls fell 5,000, a revision from the previously reported gain
of 11,000 jobs. Workers' average hourly earnings rose 0.4 percent _
or 5 cents _ to $13.23 in June following an increase of 0.3 percent
during May. Analysts had expected earnings to rise 0.3 percent. The
unemployment rate rose to 4.3 percent from 4.2 percent. By Slyvia
Nasar.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   CONGRESS-BANKING (Washington) _ A look at the sticking points in
the House's financial overhaul bill following Thursday night's
vote. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   WALMART-INTERNET (Undated) _ When Wal-Mart announced late last
month that it had hired Fingerhut Cos., a subsidiary of Federated
Departement stores, to do behind-the-scenes order processing and
distribution for its Internet site, it sent a delicious little jolt
through the retail community. The vagaries of e-commerce mean that
Wal-Mart, the world's largest retailer, will soon be giving its
real-world competitor Federated, whose chains include Macy's,
Bloomingdale's and Burdines, a little cut of every on-line purchase
for the next three years. By Leslie Kaufman.
</P>
<P>
   MARKET (New York) _ At 11 a.m., stocks are slightly higher. Both
the Dow Jones industrial average and the S&AMP;P 500 are up 0.37
percent, while the Nasdaq composite is up 0.71 percent. The 30-year
bond is yielding 5.99 percent. European markets are modestly
higher. London is flat while Frankfurt is up 0.71 percent. Hong
Kong surged 4.82 percent. The Nikkei closed up 0.42 percent. By
Jonathan Fuerbringer.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-SALES (Detroit) _ GM, Ford Motor and others report June
sales. By Michelle Krebs.
</P>
<P>
   With graphic.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-BANK (Sao Paulo) _ In a move to avert the failure of
Latin America's largest bank, the 191-year-old Banco do Brasil, the
Brazilian Senate has approved a divisive measure transferring
roughly $3.4 billion of worthless securities on the institution's
books to the federal Treasury. By Simon Romero.
</P>
