<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THOMPSON-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH CAN GO WHEREVER HE WANTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BILL THOMPSON 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   There was George W. Bush on the TV screen, and you almost
expected to hear the familiar unseen announcer ask the familiar
question: ``Hey, Gov. Bush, you've just locked up the Republican
presidential nomination. What will you do next?''
</P>
<P>
   And the winner's reply: ``I'm going to Disneyland.''
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor didn't visit Disneyland on Thursday, but he
was in California, adding to the unprecedented $36 million-plus in
campaign contributions that had rolled into the Bush-for-president
coffers as of Wednesday. If his mind-boggling money-raising hasn't
already guaranteed Bush the top spot on the GOP ticket in next
year's presidential election, it certainly has magnified his status
as the runaway front-runner for the nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised more money than Republican nominee Bob Dole
collected during the entire primary campaign in 1996. He has rung
up more campaign contributions than all his Republican opponents
combined. And he has raised more than the combined total of
Democratic candidates Al Gore and Bill Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has raised so much money that he may not find it necessary
to accept federal matching funds during the primary season. Which
means that he can campaign all-out in several states at once
without worrying about overly restrictive spending limits. Which
means that a mostly self-funded candidate like Steve Forbes won't
be able to do to Bush what he did to Dole: beat him up with a
barrage of attack ads while the front-runner is effectively
silenced by spending limits.
</P>
<P>
   The amazing outpouring of financial support for Bush must be
demoralizing to all the Bush detractors who have been insisting
that his gigantic lead in the presidential preference polls is a
mirage. One of the TV pundits said Thursday that the Bush
campaign's burgeoning bankroll indicates that the GOP's world-class
fund-raisers have decided that a Bush nomination is inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe this is one of those chicken-or-the-egg conundrums. Is
money pouring into the Bush campaign because his nomination is
inevitable, or is Bush's nomination inevitable because money is
pouring into his campaign?
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it doesn't much matter which came first or what caused
what. The bandwagon is rolling. Get on or get out of the way.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's closest rival for the Republican nomination _ and we use
the word ``closest'' very loosely here _ is Elizabeth Dole, who
keeps saying she's in the race to stay despite the polls and
despite the fund-raising reports. The problem for Dole and most
other GOP candidates is that they will have to get by on whatever
money Bush spills on the way to the bank.
</P>
<P>
   About the only Republican hopefuls who aren't adversely affected
by Bush's money monopoly are Pat Buchanan, who has made a career
out of running presidential campaigns on a shoestring, and Forbes,
whose personal fortune can keep him afloat indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   But guess what? Neither Buchanan nor Forbes has a prayer of
defeating Bush.
</P>
<P>
   So. The Bush-haters _ whoever and wherever they may be _ must
rededicate themselves to the proposition that Bush will defeat
himself, that he will make some horrendous gaffe or otherwise
reveal himself to be unsuited to hold the highest office in the
greatest nation on the planet.
</P>
<P>
   Here is some advice for those who are barking up that tree:
Don't hold your breath.
</P>
<P>
   As he has emphatically demonstrated in two successful campaigns
for governor, George W. Bush is a disciplined and determined
candidate who is simply not prone to self-destruction. His
opponents and the media can bait, badger and attack him till their
lungs give out and their Web sites crash; he will not be
intimidated, entrapped or tricked into dumb mistakes.
</P>
<P>
   His opponents' best hope now is that Bush will succumb to
overconfidence. But it's a slim hope, for Bush proved during a 1998
gubernatorial campaign that amounted to little more than a walkover
that he never takes a single vote for granted _ that he is
committed to running as if there's a chance he could lose.
</P>
<P>
   Even when he couldn't lose if he tried.
</P>
<P>
   (Bill Thompson is a columnist for the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can contact him at (817) 390-7787. Visit the Star-Telegram's
online services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
