r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FILM-REIVEW-SAM-HNS &LR;      07-02 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FILM-REIVEW-SAM-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`SUMMER OF SAM': HOT, BUT NOT QUITE A SCORCHER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By STEVE BARNES  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Heat and fear rise palpably from the screen in ``Summer of
Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   Spike Lee's 13th picture is an astonishing, virtuosic film. It's
also a jarringly effective time machine nearly as lurid and
evocative a creation of New York in a specific, conflicted time as
Martin Scorsese's ``Taxi Driver.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer of Sam'' leaves you reeling, invigorated by the sheer
aesthetic thrill of watching a craftsman at his best or, when
slightly less than that, a filmmaker who's a whole lot of fun even
when just showing off.
</P>
<P>
   Lee plunks you down right in the middle of the blistering summer
of 1977, where the pavement shimmers and polyester shirts cling to
the skin after a mere minute of disco dancing. Along with the heat,
New York City is in the grips of economic bleakness, blackouts,
looting and, of course, a serial killer armed with a powerful
pistol and deranged urges to kill women with long, dark hair.
</P>
<P>
   Lee heightens the off-balance feel by shooting the daytime
scenes with blurry darkness at the center, the edges hazily flared
with white light, replicating the effect of looking right into the
sun.
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer of Sam'' is less about David Berkowitz _ a.k.a. the Son
of Sam _ than about the climate he helped create in the baking Big
Apple. Another director likely would have turned the tale into a
conventional thriller. We know that story: A psycho with a handgun
spatters the brains of brunette beauties across the interiors of
their boyfriends' jacked-up Camaros, while tense cops chew
toothpicks and drink coffee from paper cups wile working to capture
a killer who has been humiliating them by eluding capture and
writing eloquent letters to the tabloids. Not Spike Lee.
</P>
<P>
   Lee instead finds his story in an outer-borough ethnic
neighborhood, mapping their intimate stories against expansive
historic backdrops. As in his 1989 film, ``Do the Right Thing,''
the writer-director turns his camera on a close community of
vulgar, exuberant people whose friendships are frayed when new
external pressures exacerbate long-held internal frictions and
bigotries.
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the picture is Vinny (John Leguizamo), a
hairdresser who overcompensates for his profession with a
blustering masculinity. Although married to Dionna (Mira Sorvino),
Vinny finds satisfying sex only extramaritally and spends most of
his time with the gang of buddies he grew up with in their
Italian-American Bronx neighborhood. They smoke and swear on their
walled-off street while standing beneath a ``Dead End'' sign (for
those needing their metaphors translated).
</P>
<P>
   Inchoately fearful of the outside world and its changes, these
guys strut with ease on their own turf. Lee, always able to summon
the best from actors, relishes showing us their cock-of-the-walk
confidence, their brutal passions unmediated by a gentling,
self-reflective intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   Things start to deteriorate at the reappearance of Vinny's
childhood friend Ritchie (Adrien Brody), who returns to the
neighborhood from Manhattan adorned with the affectations of punk
music. His friends mock his spiky hairdo and British-flag shirt,
but they're more deeply disquieted by the outside influences he
represents: If this can happen to one of their own, what's next?
</P>
<P>
   As the summer's heat and the city's Son of Sam fear both rise,
Vinny and friends behave ever badly, and Lee crafts the downward
spiral of their lives with vigor and flair.
</P>
<P>
   A writer and director with an acute comprehension of human
behavior, Lee also understands actors, and his cast clearly trusts
him. From Leguizamo, Sorvino and Brody on down to the bit players
(notwithstanding the annoying Jimmy Breslin, playing himself), the
actors give exposed-nerve performances. The loves and betrayals all
make sense, and the characters' capacity for violence simmers so
near the surface that its brutal boilovers are inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Lee shoots much of the picture in grainy, sun-bleached colors,
heightening the realism, and further boosts the effect by matching
onscreen brutality with a happy pop soundtrack.
</P>
<P>
   A couple cuddling in a Lincoln Continental is murdered while
ABBA's ``Fernando'' plays, and a nasty fight between Leguizamo and
Sorvino following a misadventure in a Manhattan sex club is
accompanied by the same group's ``Dancing Queen.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee is less in command of his script (co-written by Lee, Victor
Colicchio and Michael Imperioli, the film's executive producer and
cast member of TV's ``The Sopranos''). While the constant
f-this-ing and f-that-ing echo how some people really talk, in a
movie it gets tiresome, and you wish the actors had been given
sharper lines.
</P>
<P>
   The story drags toward the end of its 140-minute running time,
and it's a testament to Sorvino's fierce portrayal of a woman doing
anything to save her marriage that you don't immediately see how
thinly conceived her character is. Had Lee edited the picture and
the screenplay with the rigor he applies to acting and
cinematography, the power of ``Summer of Sam'' would be a real
scorcher.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1440EDT &QL; 
