<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STAPLES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LITTLE RESEARCH CAN BE A BAD THING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GRACIE BONDS STAPLES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   This one will surely get me in trouble, but here goes.
</P>
<P>
   I was scanning the news wire last week when I spied a story that
sent me into convulsions.
</P>
<P>
   I'm still laughing.
</P>
<P>
   A group of researchers _ studying female responses to different
types of male faces _ have concluded that we women are attracted to
more manly faces when we are ready to conceive. This, they said,
might suggest practical advice for men on the prowl. Something
about ``If at first you don't succeed, try, try again.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it would never occur to a man that he's being
rejected because he has bad breath or because the object of his
affection simply isn't interested.
</P>
<P>
   No. A man can now blame a woman's menstrual cycle. And just to
prove they're still irresistible, they'll spend money on such
useless information.
</P>
<P>
   But, hey, PMS is as good a reason as any to explain why Julia
Roberts would marry Lyle Lovett.
</P>
<P>
   The study suggests that ``When a woman is ovulating or ready to
conceive, she is likely to prefer men with more masculine features.
When she is menstruating, or least likely to get pregnant, she is
apt to prefer softer, more feminine looks.''
</P>
<P>
   The first thing I'd like to say is that there are a lot of
reasons to prefer a man with more masculine features, and ovulating
isn't one of them.
</P>
<P>
   I can say this because I'm a woman, and what I prefer in a man
isn't femininity. Come to think of it, when I'm ovulating I prefer
to be as far away from men as I can. Well, maybe not if Denzel's in
the room.
</P>
<P>
   Last Sunday, I was at my sister Jo's place for dinner. We were
in the midst of doing our usual number on men when I started to ask
her about the study. Or more specifically, if there are times when
she finds her significant other more attractive.
</P>
<P>
   She said yes and told me there are also times when she looks in
the mirror and likes what stares back at her more than other times.
And she knows, she added, the exact moment when she's looking
particularly good to him.
</P>
<P>
   Before I can ask the second part of my question, she said: ``I
know what you're going to ask me. I saw that story. I don't want
NOTHING with feminine features.''
</P>
<P>
   So there. In my family, it's unanimous.
</P>
<P>
   Now let me explain how you might get more accurate results from
a study like this. The researchers call when you are ovulating and
bloated from water weight gain. You have cramps and a blemish on
the tip of your nose that surfaces at the same time every month.
You're not exactly in a good mood.
</P>
<P>
   Then, your husband comes home from work and wants some
attention. What will you do?
</P>
<P>
   (a) Run him a hot bath, where you'll be joining him?
</P>
<P>
   (b) Make him a bed of rose petals, where you'll be joining him?
</P>
<P>
   (c) Tell him that you're not his mother and that he should
pamper himself?
</P>
<P>
   (d) Cry.
</P>
<P>
   Oops, forget that last answer. I don't want to seem too
immature.
</P>
<P>
   After two weeks, roll the tape again. The blemish is gone and
you no longer look like you're two months pregnant. You're feeling
pretty good about yourself. Your husband comes home from work, and
he wants some attention.
</P>
<P>
   The researchers are calling again. What will your reaction be
this time to your husband's request?
</P>
<P>
   That's what I thought.
</P>
<P>
   (Gracie Bonds Staples is a columnist for the Fort Worth
Star-Telegram. You can call him at (817) 390-7791, or e-mail:
gbs(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online services
on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
