<SLUG> BC-JAIL-RESTRAINTS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INMATE'S DEATH PROMPTS CHANGE IN RESTRAINT POLICY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By RENDAN LYONS  
 c.1999 Albany Times Union  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ALBANY, N.Y. _ Unruly inmates at the Albany County jail will no
longer be strapped face-down in their cell bunks, a change prompted
by the death of a mentally ill inmate who was physically restrained
by guards and injected with a powerful tranquilizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Effective immediately, if a situation exists where it becomes
necessary to restrain an inmate for his or her own protection, a
device called a restraint chair will be used,'' Sheriff James L.
Campbell said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The policy change comes as the state Mental Health Association
has asked Gov. George Pataki to expand the investigation of the
incident to include the State Police and other agencies.
</P>
<P>
   Caroline Quartararo, a Pataki spokeswoman, said the
investigation would continue to be handled solely by the Commission
of Correction.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their purview,'' she said. ``We have full faith and
confidence in their ability to carry out these responsibilities.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell said sheriff's investigators also are investigating the
death. Autopsy results to determine the exact cause of death won't
be available for several days, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Gregory Lee Richardson, 42, of Brooklyn was found unconscious in
his cell on the jail's mental health tier Monday night about 30
minutes after a nurse had given him an injection of Haldol, a
tranquilizer used by correctional facilities statewide to calm
inmates, Campbell said.
</P>
<P>
   Guards checked on Richardson shortly after he was injected with
the drug but a nurse then found him unconscious 10 minutes later,
the sheriff said. He had vomited, and immediate attempts to revive
him failed, the authorities said.
</P>
<P>
   The guards violated procedures if they left Richardson
unattended while he was strapped in his bunk, Campbell said.
Procedures require that inmates be kept under constant observation
if they are being restrained, he explained.
</P>
<P>
   For reasons that are still being investigated, Richardson was
strapped face-down in his bunk by jail guards to prevent him from
harming himself. But now, inmates will only be strapped in their
bunks if there are no restraint chairs available, Campbell said.
Even then, guards have been told to begin restraining inmates only
on their sides, which is considered safer than on the stomach or
back, the sheriff said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is very hard for me,'' said Richardson's mother, Ruby. ``I
was surprised he was in such a facility and was not recognized
immediately as someone who should be in a facility for the mentally
ill.''
</P>
<P>
   He was diagnosed a paranoid schizophrenic nearly 20 years ago,
she said, and has been taking medication for his condition for
several years.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson was arrested June 10 after leading the police on a
high-speed chase.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1454EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
