<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HILLARY-YANKEES-CUBS-NYTSF </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YUP, HILLARY ... IT'S POLITICS, NOT SPORTS 
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     (This has already moved to clients of Richard Roeper's popular
weekly columns, now being offered as a regular New York Times
Syndicate feature. For a bio &AMP; photo _ as well as special contract
rates _ please contact your sales representative:
 &HT;    (--U.S. and Canada: DEBRA WEYDERT in New Jersey at 732-390-4480;
fax, 732-390-4697. 
 &HT;    (--Latin America: OLIVIA VASQUEZ in Los Angeles, 310-798-0970;
fax, 310-798-7338.) 
 &HT;    
 By RICHARD ROEPER  
 c.1999 The Chicago Sun-Times  
<TEXT>
 &UR; (Distributed by New York Times Special Features) &LR;  &QC;
<P>
   CHICAGO _ New York Mayor Rudolph Giuliani was in Chicago
recently as a guest of Illinois Gov. George Ryan. There was a
fundraiser to attend and backs to be slapped, but there was another
purpose to Giuliani's mission.
</P>
<P>
   He was here to stick it to Hillary Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   As you'll recall, the first lady _ a native of the Chicago
suburb of Park Ridge and a lifelong fan of the Cubs and the Bulls _
recently pulled a brazenly cynical flip-flop when she abandoned
both teams for their New York rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Knicks fan now,'' said Clinton in an appearance at an
elementary school in East Harlem. It was her own personal Ich ein
Berliner.
</P>
<P>
   A reporter asked, ``What happened to the Bulls?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What did happen to the Bulls _ good question,'' she replied.
</P>
<P>
   Later that same day, Clinton happily donned a New York Yankees
cap and posed for photos at a White House ceremony for the 1998
World Series champions. (Her husband, ever the diplomat or perhaps
afraid of looking like a dork in a suit and a baseball cap, donned
the cap briefly, but held it by his side for the picture-taking
session.)
</P>
<P>
   The next day, Mrs. Clinton reiterated her newfound loyalties
during an appearance on the ``Today'' show.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a Cubs fan,'' she said. ``But I needed an American League
team, because, when you're from Chicago, you cannot root for both
the Cubs and the Sox ... So as a very young girl, I became very
interested and enamored of the Yankees.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh please. NOBODY from Chicago has EVER rooted for the Yankees.
It would be like David's family rooting for Goliath.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, it's not the switcheroo that offends me so much as the
condescending notion that any voter would fall for this ploy _ or
for that matter, that anyone would make an election choice based on
a candidate's favorite team. Why doesn't Clinton just come out and
say she thinks voters in New York state must be stupid rubes? Look
you silly people, I'm wearing your team's hat, I'm one of you!
</P>
<P>
   Serves her right that the scheme has backfired horribly, as the
savvy Giuliani has returned her serve with a series of perfect
backhanded sound bites. Before leaving New York for Chicago, he
told reporters, ``I want to go to see how the Chicago Cubs play. I
have never been to Wrigley Field, and this will be a great
opportunity to see Wrigley Field for the first time. But since I
don't come from there and never worked there, never lived there, I
never was a Cubs fan and won't pretend to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Ouch.
</P>
<P>
   When Giuliani arrived at Wrigley Field to see the Cubs take on
the Milwaukee Brewers, he faced the media pack surrounding him and
gleefully awaited the inevitable questions about team loyalties.
His response: Hillary is most welcome in the family of Yankees fans
_ but isn't it odd that even though he's been to hundreds of
Yankees games over the years, he's somehow never run into her, not
even once?
</P>
<P>
   The day after Giuliani's visit, Hillary's husband _ what was his
name again? _ swooped down on Chicago for a $500,000 fundraiser and
a speech on Medicare. He also made a stop at Wrigley Field _
reportedly even showering in the Cubs locker room that afternoon
before zipping off to that big fundraiser. (One presumes the Secret
Service cleared the showers before the president soaped up. The
idea of the most powerful person in the world saying, ``Hey
Morandini, got any shampoo I can borrow?'' is just too weird for
words.)
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton dutifully posed with home run hero Sammy Sosa,
Cubs jacket in hand, but he grew a bit surly when reporters chided
him about his wife's recent flip-flop. Asked if he at least was
still a Cubs fan, Clinton replied, ``Yeah, and so is (Hillary) ...
Don't go playing press games here. This is sports, not politics.''
</P>
<P>
   Huh?
</P>
<P>
   I'm not even sure what that means, but I'd like to remind the
president that it was his wife who started all this nonsense in the
first place. If she had simply said, ``Look, I'm considering a run
for the senate in New York, but I don't want to insult the
intelligence of New Yorkers by pretending I'm suddenly dumping the
Cubs and Bulls in favor of the Yankees and Knicks,'' she might have
scored a few points for honesty and loyalty. That kind of
I-won't-B.S.-you attitude is respected by Chicagoans and New
Yorkers.
</P>
<P>
   So you're wrong Mr. President. It is politics, not sports. And
on that playing field, your wife is getting her tail kicked by Mr.
Giuliani.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; (Richard Roeper is a columnist for the Chicago Sun-Times, a
radio host and a commentator for Fox News in Chicago _ and has
appeared on programs such as ``Nightline,'' ``The CBS Evening News
with Dan Rather,'' ``Oprah'' and ``The Drudge Report.'') &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ------------- &QC;
</P>
