<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BROWN-COMPUTER-COLUMN-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LEARNING CHESS WITH A LITTLE HELP FROM BORIS 
</HEADLINE>
   By LONNIE BROWN   
 Lakeland (Fla.) Ledger   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   For the past several months, Boris and I have met frequently so
he could impart his knowledge of chess to me.
</P>
<P>
   Boris is as good a name as any for a chess-playing computer who
speaks in mostly clear, but measured, computer speech. I decided to
call him that because it's more personal than his formal title:
Chess Academy from Saitek Inc.
</P>
<P>
   Boris will take the beginning player, teach him about each
piece, its relative value, how it moves and captures, and how it is
governed by the rules of chess. He will then take the
more-knowledgeable beginner by the hand to the opening game,
indicating which pieces to move through light-emitting diodes on
each of the chessboard's 64 squares.
</P>
<P>
   He'll lead players down the right path, then have players back
the pieces up to show what could have happened should they have
moved to the wrong squares or attacked with the wrong piece.
</P>
<P>
   He's a lightweight to carry (about three pounds of board,
computer brain and playing pieces, which are stored in a
compartment underneath the board), but a heavyweight to play _
estimated rating of about 2000 at 40 moves in two hours.
</P>
<P>
   The 2000 rating means that he plays around the expert-master
level. The rating of the average United States Chess Federation
tournament player is about 1450.
</P>
<P>
   Boris, however, has 100 playing levels, including 60
fun/handicap levels that give beginners and intermediate players a
crack at winning a game every once in a while. In addition, there
are 10 casual levels, 10 tournament levels, 10 blitz levels, one
tactical and one infinite level and eight levels for solving setups
where mate is unavoidable.
</P>
<P>
   The board measures 8-by-8 inches; the entire machine measures
16-by-11 inches and is about two inches thick. The pieces are
silver and black; the king is two inches high. The playing surface
is pressure sensitive, and moved pieces are shown both by LEDs on
the board and by a LCD display to the right of the board. The
machine draws power either from an adapter or six C-size batteries.
</P>
<P>
   The big selling point about Chess Academy (a.k.a. ``Boris'') is
that it not only instructs beginning and intermediate chess, but it
talks as well _ and it talks a lot. There are 10 basic learning
categories, with 10 lessons in each category.
</P>
<P>
   Players can go through the lessons at their own pace, but they
take a minimum of about eight or 10 minutes each to move through.
So that works out to be a minimum of 13-plus hours of audio
instructions in a chess computer.
</P>
<P>
   Chess Academy isn't the cheapest dedicated chess-playing
computer around. You can find them for as little as $25, and they
play better than the average tournament player. Chess computers
that play at the 2200 level cost a bit more _ about $60 to $80 is
an entry-price range. The lowest retail price I've found for Chess
Academy is $157.50 (www.icdchess.com).
</P>
<P>
   For 13 hours or more of chess instruction, the price works out
to be about $12 an hour for chess instruction _ and that doesn't
take into account that there's a strong chess opponent left over
long after the instructions are finished. From that standpoint, the
price appears in the ballpark for a dedicated chess computer for
the casual home player.
</P>
<P>
   Chess Academy's competition on the teaching side, of course,
comes from chess software. ChessMaster 6000 from Mindscape Inc.
offers instructions for beginners, top-ranked play, and even voice
commentaries on games played against the computer. The software
costs about $30 to $45.
</P>
<P>
   Add $600 or more to that price if you don't have a computer
system on which to run the software. In addition, chess software
ties up the system, while a dedicated chess machine doesn't.
Players who learn on a computer screen's two-dimensional board
sometimes discover it's a different game when played in a 3-D
setting, too.
</P>
<P>
   Another advantage for the self-contained chess game: It's
portable, not even needing an external power supply; travels
easily; and packs away out of sight.
</P>
<P>
   Lessons begin with the rules of moving pieces, explore openings,
end games, tactics, mating combinations and other aspects of the
game.
</P>
<P>
   After each topic, players can play the computer and put their
knowledge to work in a game. A ``chess coach'' can be called upon
to automatically point out careless or poor moves to beginners. And
when the computer is set on its easiest mode, even an inexperienced
pawn-shover can manage a victory. Nudging the computer's
intelligence level up a notch provides for a more challenging game,
and helps the beginner gain experience.
</P>
<P>
   Saitek also offers smaller chess computers at lower prices. And
the company has a good way of grouping computers for novice,
intermediate and experienced players. It's as simple as A, B, C.
</P>
<P>
   The Alpha series is for beginners. All the computers in the line
begin with ``A.'' The Benchmark series has the Bullet, Blade and
Barracuda for players who want a stronger game. And the Connoisseur
line has names beginning with ``C.'' The Chess Adademy is in that
grouping.
</P>
<P>
   For more information, visit the company's Web site
(www.saitek.com).
</P>
<P>
   (Lonnie Brown is The Ledger's associate editor. He can be
reached by e-mail at LonnieB001(AT)aol.com. His recent computer
columns are on the Internet at
http://www.theledger.com/business/tech/)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
