<HEADER>
A7349 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      07-02 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ELLIS-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHY I WON'T WRITE ANY MORE ABOUT THE PRESIDENTIAL CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN ELLIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One of the great stories of modern journalism concerns R.W.
``Johnny'' Apple, the veteran national political correspondent of
The New York Times. In his younger days, Apple reported on New York
State politics and in the process scooped virtually all of his
colleagues in the Albany press corps.
</P>
<P>
   Back in those days, the Albany press corps used to gather after
work to play poker. Every night at the poker game, they would talk
obsessively about Apple, whose high performance and high octane
personality they both admired and despised.
</P>
<P>
   After a time, they decided such talk was counter-productive, so
they instituted a rule.
</P>
<P>
   The rule was that if you were going to talk about Apple at the
poker game, you had to pay five dollars for the privilege. For four
days thereafter, the poker game proceeded in stony silence.
Finally, on the fifth day, one of Apple's colleagues from the Times
marched into the room, threw fifty dollars down onto the table and
unburdened himself of a week's worth of Apple outrage.
</P>
<P>
   Some things must be said, regardless of the cost involved.
</P>
<P>
   And some things can't be said, because loyalty supercedes
candor. I am loyal to my cousin, Texas Governor George Bush. I put
that loyalty ahead of my loyalty to anyone else outside of my
immediate family. That being the case, it is not possible for me to
continue writing columns about the 2000 presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   A columnist's allegiance must be to the reader. This is an
annoying and pretentious thing that journalists say, but it is, in
fact, true.
</P>
<P>
   Columns depend upon trust. The reader must know that the writer
is saying what he or she really thinks. A column is good to the
degree that it communicates real beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   I am convinced that genomics will fundamentally change science
and the global economy, so when I write columns that say that,
based on case studies that are relevant, you know on some level
that I am telling you the truth (as I see it). I am convinced that
Internet technology will fundamentally change the way we interact
and transact, so when I write columns that say that, I am telling
you the truth (again, as I see it).
</P>
<P>
   But there is no way for you to know if I am telling you the
truth about George W. Bush's presidential campaign because, in his
case, my loyalty goes to him and not to you. And there is no way
for you to know if I am telling you the truth about Al Gore's
presidential campaign because he and Bill Bradley are the only men
standing between my cousin and the White House.
</P>
<P>
   There will inevitably come a time when the Bush campaign does
something that I think is wrong. I won't write about it because I
am never going to write a column about my cousin that is not
sympathetic. He's family and I'm for him today, I'm for him
tomorrow, I'm for him as long as he's running for office.
</P>
<P>
   If for some reason he doesn't make it and decides to get out of
politics, then I'm for his brother Jeb from that day forward.
</P>
<P>
   Such a stance is antithetical to the columnist's first
obligation, which is to be of use to the reader. A columnist is
useless if his or her loyalty resides elsewhere. This is why the
Globe's Hiawatha Bray is such a good columnist. He doesn't care
whether Microsoft wins or loses. The only thing he cares about is
that you get the best available information about computer hardware
and software and are thus enabled to make smart choices about what
to buy and what not to buy.
</P>
<P>
   For a number of years now, readers have complained to the Globe
about my Clinton columns (and, more recently, my columns about
Governor Bush). In the case of Clinton, it was argued that I
loathed him because he defeated my uncle, President George Bush, in
the 1992 election. The truth is, I loathed and loathe him because
he is loathsome.
</P>
<P>
   But the complaints about my Bush columns, all five of which I
thought informative and accurate, are not so easily dismissed. The
truth is I don't look at Governor Bush the way I look at Microsoft
or Putnam Investments or former Governor Weld. On some level, I
can't be honest about his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   I want him to win not because I am convinced he would be a
better president than Al Gore (although I am convinced of that). I
really want him to win because I really want him to win.
</P>
<P>
   That said, I reserve the right to throw fifty dollars down on
the table from time to time and have at the latest outrage from the
Clinton team. And I will continue to write about political issues
and campaigns. But as a rule, those looking for commentary on the
year 2000 presidential election should look elsewhere. I'm out, due
to a prior commitment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(John Ellis is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
