<HEADER>
A7357 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUSH-BUSINESS-HNS &LR;      07-02 1162
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BUSINESS-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH RECORD IN TEXAS IMPRESSES SILICON VALLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ZACHARY COILE  
 c.1999 San Francisco Examiner  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ If Silicon Valley leaders want to know how
George W. Bush would handle technology issues as president, they
should look no farther than Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's entrepreneurial heaven,'' Bush told 500 supporters
Thursday morning at a fund-raiser in Palo Alto.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's record on technology issues as governor of Texas has been
so pro-business, particularly on the thorny issue of tort reform,
that critics have questioned whether he has the best interests of
consumers in mind.
</P>
<P>
   But his drive to cut regulation and taxes on the industry has
won the support of the growing ranks of technology entrepreneurs in
Texas, and he is fast gaining friends and allies in the Silicon
Valley.
</P>
<P>
   In his speech to 500 donors in Palo Alto, Bush preached to the
choir, supporting the technology industry's long-standing wishes to
get a permanent federal research and development tax credit, and to
allow more foreign workers into the country.
</P>
<P>
   On the issue of the export of encryption technology, he said he
would allow companies to sell products overseas as long as products
could be just as easily bought from suppliers abroad.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's record in Texas could be his strongest weapon as he seeks
money and votes in Silicon Valley, which has already become a key
battleground among candidates, Democratic and Republican, in the
2000 presidential race.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton captured the support of many Silicon Valley
executives in 1992 and again in 1996. Democrats have been hoping
that Vice President Al Gore's work on technology issues would gain
him the favor of the region's donors and opinion leaders.
</P>
<P>
   But the early buzz in the valley, as elsewhere, is about Bush.
In April, 55 executives from the area took out a full-page
newspaper ad urging him to run for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   This week, technology leaders packed into his Bay Area
fund-raisers. Bush aides estimated that half the $1.7 million
raised at two major events in San Francisco and Palo Alto had come
from Silicon Valley.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you have this on the first (campaign) trip, I think it's a
very good sign,'' Gerald Parsky, chairman of Bush's California
campaign, said of the fund-raising totals.
</P>
<P>
   Before Bush was elected governor in 1994, he had little exposure
to the technology industry. He began his career in the oil and gas
business in west Texas and made his fortune selling his interest in
the Texas Rangers baseball team.
</P>
<P>
   He came to power just as the technology sector in the Lone Star
State was hitting full bloom. Between 1990 and 1996, more tech jobs
were created in Texas than in any other state. The state is home to
such corporate heavyweights as SBC Communications, Dell Computer,
Texas Instruments and the Compaq Computer Corp.
</P>
<P>
   Steve Papermaster, an Austin software executive and Bush
supporter, recalls that the governor struggled at the start to
understand the needs of the complex industry, from the
telecommunications companies concentrated north of Dallas to the
software start-ups of Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``He definitely had a learning curve regarding technology,''
Papermaster said. ``But he did not have a learning curve regarding
being an entrepreneur, and understanding how to grow companies
quick.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, Bush tapped executives for his Science and Technology
Council, which he used to develop initiatives to help the industry
keep growing. Several of the group's recommendations were approved
by the Legislature, including a research and development tax
credit, expanded advanced placement classes at high schools, and a
beefed-up technology curriculum for the state's community colleges.
</P>
<P>
   ``The results are still coming in'' from the council's efforts,
said Al Wargo, president and chief executive of the
Microelectronics and Computer Technology Corp., a consortium that
includes two dozen technology companies. ``Clearly, as far as
education goes, I think Bush does have a fairly nice track
record.''
</P>
<P>
   This spring, Bush signed legislation to reduce a state tax on
Internet access. The bill will keep residents from paying tax on
the first $25 of monthly Internet access costs.
</P>
<P>
   The flourishing economy allowed Bush and the Legislature to make
more significant cuts in the state's sales tax and in property
taxes, as well as an estimated $464 million in business tax cuts,
according to the governor's office. But in 1997 Bush was forced to
abandon a more ambitious tax reform effort that was strongly backed
by the technology industry.
</P>
<P>
   Texas has no personal income tax, and its state franchise tax,
or business tax, does not apply to companies designated as
partnerships, including law firms, doctors' groups and consulting
firms. As a result, technology and other companies feel they bear
an unfair share of the business tax burden.
</P>
<P>
   Bush tried to address the issue by proposing cuts in property
taxes, while requiring the partnerships to start paying the
business tax.
</P>
<P>
   ``It opened up a can of worms,'' said Jon Roberts, an economist
at Angelou Economic Advisors in Austin, which is now working for
Bush's economic development commission. Trial lawyers and doctors'
groups lobbied hard against the proposal, and the Legislature
blocked the reforms. But the effort signaled to technology
companies a desire by Bush to meet its policy goals, Roberts said.
</P>
<P>
   No single issue has endeared Bush more to the technology sector
than the governor's work on tort reform. Technology companies, in
Texas and in Silicon Valley, have long argued that they are at
higher risk from frivolous lawsuits, especially from shareholders
angered when a company's stock price drops. Bush has successfully
pushed legislation making it easier for courts to toss out
frivolous suits, and to limit damage awards.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Bush signed a Y2K bill, one of the first in the nation,
to limit liability to companies if their products or computer
systems go haywire starting Jan. 1, 2000. The bill requires
companies to alert customers about possible problems, and requires
a 60-day cooling off period before any lawsuits can be filed.
</P>
<P>
   Bush told the crowd of 500 Silicon Valley supporters, ``I will
take the side of innovation over litigation every single time.''
</P>
<P>
   But some consumer advocates in Texas say Bush has gone too far
in his push for tort reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's been more responsive to the needs of business than to the
needs of private individuals and consumers,'' said Reggie James,
director of the Southwest regional office of Consumers Union in
Austin.
</P>
<P>
   ``A few of those things had to happen, especially (the
restrictions) on frivolous lawsuits,'' James said. ``But most of
their stuff was business interests that said, we're losing too much
money in these cases, so we need to do something to change the
playing field. That's not good public policy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
