<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7359 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MEANS-COLUMN-$ADV04-H     07-02 0794
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MEANS-COLUMN-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPIN THAT WHEEL 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, July 4)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARIANNE MEANS  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ A federal government study has just told us what we
want to hear. Legalized gambling is okay. Games of chance won't
bring down the republic.
</P>
<P>
   The message: Relax and enjoy playing the odds, if you wish. You
might get lucky.
</P>
<P>
   A young Minnesota woman claimed a $150 million Powerball lottery
jackpot July 1, beating odds of 80 million to one. Tens of
thousands of eager players had waited patiently in long lines from
coast to coast in the days before the drawing for a shot at the
prize. The losers were out a few bucks but they did share a brief
anticipation of realizing their wildest dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Not that anyone was really worried that the blue ribbon
commission that spent three years and $5 million to write a
340-page report would order the casinos to close and the lotteries
to shut down. The political fix was in.
</P>
<P>
   As the fastest growing industry in the country, gambling is an
800-pound gorilla perfectly capable of protecting its interests
against government meddling, thank you. Congress and the White
House like the industry's hefty campaign contributions. State
governments like it because they get a piece of the take. And the
public likes it because it is nonviolent, easily accessible
entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   Those hypocritical moralists who routinely posture against sin
in Congress didn't blink an eye at the commission's benign
attitude. If there were enraged sermons from pulpits, nobody
noticed.
</P>
<P>
   A nationwide Gallup Poll last week showed that 63 percent of
American adults approve of legalized gambling. Another study in
Demography magazine found that three in four church-goers regard
casino gambling as harmless adult fun.
</P>
<P>
   The National Gambling Impact Study Commission labored mightily
to agree. Gambling in many forms is here to stay and we may as well
get used to it.
</P>
<P>
   It's a free country, after all.
</P>
<P>
   Don't get me wrong. I am not interested in gambling. It is not
my thing.
</P>
<P>
   I once peered into the great casino at Monte Carlo and I have
wandered through flashy shipboard casinos. But I never have sat
down to play the wheel or any other game. I am not a poker-player.
Pulling the lever on a slot machine strikes me as boring.
</P>
<P>
   But neither am I a prude. I bet on horse-racing, although if I
pick the wrong horse in the Kentucky Derby for the umpteenth time
again next year, I may give it up. I have enjoyed bingo since as a
child I learned to play several cards simultaneously under the
tutelage of my parents in the Danish Hall in Sioux City, Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   I barely know Frank Fahrenkopf Jr, the former Republican
national committee chairman who is head of the American Gaming
Association. He's also its chief lobbyist.
</P>
<P>
   But so long as federal regulations keep the industry crime-free,
as it now seems to be, I cannot see any cultural danger in it.
Gambling is a voluntary activity. Nobody is forced to enter a
casino or pick up a playing card. If you disapprove, don't do it.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, a few people become addicted to gambling and blow the
family fortune. This is tragic. But occasional self-inflicted
financial irresponsibility is no reason to kill the whole system.
</P>
<P>
   The special commission put the number of pathological gamblers
at no more than 1.5 percent of the U.S. adult population. It
sensibly suggested treatment for them.
</P>
<P>
   The commission also warned that the industry is growing so
rapidly that it needs to be carefully monitored. Fine. A few new
limitations such as a ban on betting on amateur sports and raising
the gambling age to 21 make good sense.
</P>
<P>
   But the commission also took a poke at state lotteries, on the
grounds that government services should not be financed largely on
the backs of the low-income minorities and other poor people who
are the heaviest players. The commission urged states and
communities to consider a moratorium on new lotteries until the
social consequences can be further evaluated.
</P>
<P>
   Fiddlesticks. That is bleeding-heart liberalism at its
bloodiest. Lotteries are a clean way to get people to do
voluntarily what they resent doing through mandatory taxes, which
is to pay for education and other public necessities. If lotteries
offer impossible hope against insurmountable odds, so be it. A buck
is a cheap price to pay for a dream, however temporary.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the federal government ought to consider expanding
rather than constricting the lottery concept. How about a
nationwide lottery to help finance Social Security and Medicare?
Don't laugh. Think about it.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Marianne Means may be reached by e-mail at
means(at)hearstdc.com.)
</P>
</TEXT>
