<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTS-NYT-BUDGET </SLUG>
  
 Attn Sports Editors:  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sports stories from The New York Times News Service for
 &UR; SATURDAY &LR; , July 3.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; SPECIAL REPORT &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TOUR-DE-FRANCE (Paris) _ An air of profound pessimism hangs over
the sport of cycling these days, and it hangs heavier than usual
with the Tour de France, which begins Saturday, for it was during
last year's race that the cover was blown off the sport's
far-reaching drug problem. Since then, cycling, the sport that for
Europe has been a cultural treasure as well as a formidable
commercial enterprise, has suffered a collapse in credibility so
great that many of its riders, organizers and sponsors fear for its
future. A Special Report by Christopher Clarey and Samuel Abt.
(3000 words and a 1500-word abridged version.)
</P>
<P>
   With map.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OTHER SPORTS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   TEN-ARATON-COLUMN (Wimbledon, England) _ Sports of The Times
column on Andre Agassi, who is in the Wimbledon semifinals after
yet another reinvention. By Harvey Araton.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN (Wimbledon, England) _ Pete Sampras, down by
one set in his quarterfinal match, advances when his opponent, Mark
Philippoussis, must quit because of an injured knee. Sampras will
next face his semifinal opponent of last year, Tim Henman, the
British hope. In the other semifinal, Andre Agassi will face Pat
Rafter. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN (Wimbledon, England) _ Two teen-age
qualifiers are in the women's semifinals: Alexandra Stevenson and
Mirjana Lucic. Stevenson, in her professional debut tournament,
defeated Jelena Dokic, the teen-ager who had defeated Hingis and
Pierce. Lucic, who next plays Graf, saved match game against her in
defeating last year's finalist, Nathalie Tauziat. By Robin Finn.
</P>
<P>
   BBN-METS-BRAVES (New York) _ Atlanta at the Mets, 7:40 p.m. EDT
start. By Joe Drape.
</P>
<P>
   BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES (New York) _ Baltimore at the Yankees, 7:35
p.m. EDT start. By Buster Olney.
</P>
