<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7384 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-GORE03-COX     07-02 0622
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GORE CAMP SHAKEN BY GROWTH OF BUSH, BRADLEY WAR CHESTS
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (p) politics categories.
 &HT;    By SCOTT SHEPARD
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Midyear funding reports have sent shock waves
through Vice President Al Gore's presidential campaign, sparking a
staff shakeup and nervous reassessments of his chief challengers in
both parties.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has added a new media consultant, policy adviser and
pollster to his campaign inner circle.
</P>
<P>
   Carter Eskew, a former partner of longtime Gore media adviser
Bob Squier, is joining the Gore team, apparently as the campaign's
lead strategist. Squier, who had that role in addition to
responsibility for campaign ads, will now concentrate on media.
</P>
<P>
   Veteran pollster Celinda Lake will join Mark Penn's polling
operation, with special attention to the development of messages
related to family and women's issues. And Lauren Choi, a senior
official at the Treasury Department, will provide policy advice.
</P>
<P>
   The additions of Eskew and Lake pose some interesting dynamics
in the organization. Squier was miffed by Eskew's departure to form
his own firm following the 1992 presidential election. Last year,
their relationship was further frayed by Eskew's involvement in the
tobacco industry's effort to kill anti-smoking legislation backed
by the Clinton-Gore administration. Similarly, Lake has promoted
more liberal positions than has Penn.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's new campaign chairman, Tony Coelho, denied that the staff
additions amounted to a shake-up of the Gore inner circle. ``We're
adding strong members to the team when appropriate,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But the moves followed fund-raising reports this week that
suggest the vice president faces a real challenge from former Sen.
Bill Bradley of New Jersey for the Democratic nomination.
</P>
<P>
   Although Gore continues to hold comfortable polling leads over
Bradley, ``we obviously have some stiff competition, and we want to
deal with it,'' said Roger Salazar, deputy press secretary for Gore
2000.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley raised $11.5 million through the first half of 1999. And
while Gore collected $18.5 million, Bradley has enough in the bank
to mount a strong challenge against the vice president, despite
Gore's backing from a popular president and the White House
political machine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've shown we can raise the funds we need to run a credible
race,'' said Anita Dunn, a Bradley strategist.
</P>
<P>
   Gore aides said the vice president would prevail in the
Democratic contest despite Bradley's fund-raising prowess.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not surprised Bradley can raise money,'' said Gore adviser
Kiki Moore. ``But going into the third quarter, things get much
more difficult with no message and no ideas to propel him beyond
that.''
</P>
<P>
   But this week's funding reports signal worse problems down the
road.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp was stunned by the record-shattering $36.2 million
raised by Gov. George W. Bush of Texas, raising worries that the
GOP front-runner could have enough money left over after securing
his party's nomination to begin media attacks on his Democratic
opponent well before the general election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton-Gore re-election campaign followed such a strategy
in 1996 against Bob Dole, who was forced to look on helplessly
after spending every campaign dollar to secure the Republican
nomination in the face of the $37 million challenge waged by
billionaire publisher Steve Forbes.
</P>
<P>
   Forbes is seeking the GOP nomination again, and Bush's
aggressive fund-raising seems aimed not so much at Gore as at
enabling him to respond to Forbes in the primary campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
