<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7386 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RADIO-FUTURE04-COX     07-02 0360
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RADIO-FUTURE04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Unlimited expansion may be wave of future
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 4
 &HT;    By Miriam Longino
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two frontiers loom on radio's horizon that may very well change
it more in the next 100 years than anything it has already seen.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  COMPUTERS: Home computers have opened up a whole new way to
listen to the radio. With a simple click of the mouse and a pair of
headphones, millions of Americans are listening to live broadcasts
of country music from Nashville's WSIX-FM, New Orleans' jazz on
WWOZ-FM, adult album alternative on San Francisco's KFOG-FM and
traffic reports from KFI in Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   According to the Radio Advertising Bureau, of the 10,500 radio
stations licensed in the United States, 4,300 have an Internet
presence. Of those, 1,100 feature audio, including Atlanta's WSB,
Jazz Flavors 104.1, WGST, Star 94, 96rock, 790/The Zone and 99X.
Even longtime local broadcasters Don Kennedy and Ludlow Porch have
jumped into cyberspace with Internet sites featuring big band music
and folksy chat.
</P>
<P>
   The impact on the industry is still unclear, though both
broadcasters and advertisers are licking their chops at the revenue
and promotional possibilities of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   &QR;  SATELLITES: Technology now exists that allows a radio station
to be beamed off a satellite and broadcast coast to coast _ in
homes, cars and portable receivers. The arrival of this technology
is imminent. In June, General Motors Corp. and Ford Motor Co.
signed a deal with XM Radio that will offer 100 satellite radio
channels of news, music and entertainment in cars in the next
decade.
</P>
<P>
   Think about it. A teenager riding around the suburbs of Atlanta
may very well be singing along to the same song as a kid in Seattle
_ at the very same time. Satellite technology opens the door for
the possible creation of national radio stations, reaching not just
thousands of listeners, but millions. By 2005, industry experts
forecast that the satellite radio market will be more than a $2
billion industry.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1605EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0140 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 16:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7387 &Cx1f; tad-z
r e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ROCK-MUSICALS04-COX     07-02 0887
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-MUSICALS04-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Retro musicals mine '70's oldies in quest for Broadway goldies
 &HT;    Eds: Embargoed for Sunday, July 4
 &HT;    By Dan Hulbert
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ Millions of Americans have fond memories of the British
rock invasion of the '60s. But are we ready for a retro '70s
onslaught?
</P>
<P>
   Three London stage musicals are merrily thumping along with
25-year-old pop hits of loud, steady backbeats. One show even
features lapels as wide as bat wings and women's hair as poufy and
frosted as Farrah Fawcett's in her heyday.
</P>
<P>
   It's ``Saturday Night Fever'' (adapted from the 1977 film) that
will begin previews on Broadway in September. It features
electrifying dance (but not much else) to recommend it. ``Mamma
Mia'' is a sure bet to follow across the pond. This out-of-nowhere
hit tells a sweet, appealingly goofy family tale by ingeniously
cobbling together old hits of the Swedish group Abba, inspiring Gen
X'ers and boomers in jeans and business suits to stand up and
boogie to reprises of ``Dancing Queen'' (Don't laugh: It's better
than you remember).
</P>
<P>
   ``Soul Train'' is also running, and judging from publicity
posters (``Afros'' that could barely fit through a door) the revue
lampoons '70s style as much as it celebrates such hits as ``Sexual
Healing.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the key to the '70s mini-craze: tunes. The theater is now
reclaiming, under the banner of nostalgia, the generation of
pop-rock songwriters it lost a quarter-century ago. After ``Hair''
and ``Jesus Christ Superstar'' spun Top 40 radio hits, theater
music and pop-rock hits went separate ways. They're beginning to
come back together as aging '70s hitmakers (Elton John and his
``Aida,'' Paul Simon and ``The Capeman'') shift styles and venture
into the riskier waters of theater.
</P>
<P>
   There's less risk in repackaging old hits, as in the Bee Gees'
``Fever'' and Abba's ``Mamma Mia.'' Especially now that a graying
baby-boom generation, raised on rock more than theater, has the
disposable income for theatergoing (top London tickets cost
``only'' $55, about $20 behind Gotham rates).
</P>
<P>
   In ``Saturday Night Fever,'' the hits indeed keep on coming:
``Stayin' Alive,'' ``How Deep Is Your Love.'' The Brooklyn accents
are so well done you'd never guess this is a mostly British cast.
Director-choreographer Arlene Phillips brings the explosive energy
and cool control seen in her direction of ``Lord of the Dance.''
With a very large (47) cast, ``Fever'' slams you with a spectacle
of movement in the mirror-ball bedazzlement of the disco floor.
</P>
<P>
   But what the show has gained in athleticism, it's lost in heart.
The campy book by American Nan Knighton (``The Scarlet Pimpernel'')
makes Tony Manero (Ben Richards), the working-class Everyman who
lives to dance, even more of a sexist jerk than John Travolta was
at the beginning of the movie (``When can we make it, Tony?''
pleads one of his female admirers, in the sexual euphemism of the
day). Tony's redemption becomes even more jarringly sentimental,
unconvincing. Richards is an incredible dancer but lacks Travolta's
vulnerability and charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fever'' shapes up as Broadway's next ``Footloose'': a soulless
retread of a teens-in-mischief movie. An exercise in human motion,
not emotion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mamma Mia'' has it both ways. It taps the decade's melodic
treasure chest without getting stuck in '70s camp. Catherine
Johnson's disarming book uses two time frames. In the present,
Sophie (Lisa Stokke), a 21-year-old English girl, plans a wedding
at the Greek isle hotel of her single mother (Siobhan McCarthy).
She secretly invites the three men who were involved with her
mother during the summer of her birth, one of whom might be her
father.
</P>
<P>
   The wedding reunites the mother with pals from a '70s singing
group (Louise Plowright as the peroxide bombshell; Jenny Galloway
as the short, funny one), and the women playfully reprise ``their''
hits as if they'd been the lead singers of Abba.
</P>
<P>
   The theatrical context creates new dimension for Benny
Andersson-Bjorn Ulvaeus songs that used to sound so bubble-gummy,
almost creepily antiseptic, on the radio. ``Name of the Game''
becomes a poig-
</P>
<P>
   nant query from Sophie to the man who may be her father. When
chubby yet lusty Galloway challenges a hunky male to ``Take a
Chance on Me,'' the audience roars its delighted surprise. As we
wonder how Johnson will fit these old songs into her new story, the
book becomes a kind of Easter egg hunt for adults.
</P>
<P>
   The '70s and the '90s generations are symbolically reconciled in
the cross-generational blowout of the wedding reception, to the
soaring strains of ``Dancing Queen.''
</P>
<P>
   If the show can keep the special chemistry of the British cast
(in other words, if Actor's Equity will loosen the hiring rules
that blocked ``Oklahoma!'' from crossing to New York), ``Mamma
Mia'' could be one of the most surprising of Broadway hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Saturday Night Fever,'' ``Mamma Mia''
</P>
<P>
   ``Fever'' at the Palladium, ``Mamma'' at the Prince Edward
Theatre, London. Open-ended runs.
</P>
<P>
   The verdict: ``Fever'' is Broadway bound, but it's the far less
familiar ``Mamma Mia'' that would win Gotham cheers.
</P>
<P>
   Dan Hulbert writes for the Atlanta Journal-Constiution.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1605EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 16:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7388 &Cx1f; tad-z
r l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REDCROSS-BULLO03-COX     07-02 0812
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REDCROSS-BULLO03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Red Cross chief: 'Job needs to be done'
 &HT;    By Derrick Henry
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Steve Bullock was beginning his career at the American Red
Cross nearly four decades ago, he jokingly told colleagues that the
``folks at headquarters should get out of my way so I can run this
organization.''
</P>
<P>
   His joke has become reality. Earlier this year, Bullock was
appointed acting president of the American Red Cross, an
organization with an annual budget of $2.2 billion, a paid staff of
32,000 and a volunteer base of 1.3 million people.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock, 62, was an unlikely choice to fill the vacancy created
when Elizabeth Dole resigned the position. Not only was he the
first African-American to head the organization, he was the first
president to have worked his way up as an insider.
</P>
<P>
   Bullock joined the Red Cross because the organization's
humanitarian mission ``aligned'' with the work he wanted to do. The
Red Cross ``is in business to save lives and prevent and relieve
human suffering,'' he said during a recent visit to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   He has wasted no time making an impact on the organization. ``My
time with you will be defined by action and tangible results,'' he
told Red Cross members this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has not taken the position to baby-sit it,'' says Carol
Rittenhouse, chief operating officer for the Georgia Red Cross and
a colleague of Bullock's for more than two decades. ``He has
already done an awful lot.''
</P>
<P>
   Rittenhouse calls Bullock a ``walkabout'' person _ someone who
likes to be on the front line, willing to try new things.
</P>
<P>
   ``He is also a great listener, with a very caring way about
him,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   To ensure that the Red Cross can consistently deliver on both
its emergency disaster services and everyday health and safety
services, Bullock stresses the need for stepping up its volunteer
programs. ``We need to be smarter and more creative in our efforts
to recruit volunteers and to make more effective use of those
volunteers. Volunteers are critical to our success.''
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Bullock wants to reach youth _ elementary school
kids through college students. ``I want to raise to a high level of
priority our involvement of and service to young people,'' he says.
``I want to return to the days (around 1940) when we had 20 million
members in the Junior Red Cross.''
</P>
<P>
   As the face of America changes, so must the inclusiveness of the
Red Cross, argues Bullock. ``We want our staff and volunteers to
look like the communities we serve.''
</P>
<P>
   When Bullock started at the Red Cross as a caseworker in 1962,
it was inconceivable that a black person might one day lead the
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Red Cross was part of the culture of those days,'' he
says. ``Blacks went to Brooklyn for their training, whites went to
Charlottesville, Va. There were certain jobs that (blacks) couldn't
hope for.''
</P>
<P>
   But in 1976 Bullock was appointed executive director of the St.
Paul area chapter _ the first African-American to become a Red
Cross chapter head. In 1982 he was appointed chief executive
officer of the Greater Cleveland chapter, a position he still
holds.
</P>
<P>
   His accomplishments are all the more remarkable considering the
humbleness of his background. Growing up in Enfield, N.C., a
farming town of 6,000, he was the youngest of 22 children _ his
father was born in 1865 and lived into his 90s.
</P>
<P>
   ``I learned early about the importance of community,'' Bullock
says.
</P>
<P>
   And today the American community is covered by the Red Cross _
Bullock guarantees the organization ``will be there'' for any
disaster anywhere in the country. Now he wants to increase the
organization's international involvement. A trip to Macedonia two
months ago had a profound impact on him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of (the refugees') stories would tear your heart out,''
says Bullock. ``People walked over dead bodies. They saw family
members killed, saw their homes burned over their shoulders, and
were told not to turn back or be killed.''
</P>
<P>
   Yet in the midst of atrocity after atrocity, the best side of
people also emerged, he says. ``The human spirit is powerful, and I
see it everywhere I go.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why _ though his position takes him from one disaster
scene to another _ Bullock never expects to experience burnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``The job needs to be done. You feed on seeing you can make a
difference.''
</P>
<P>
   VOLUNTEER OPPORTUNITIES
</P>
<P>
   Red Cross volunteers are needed for the organization's blood
drives, disaster action teams and community disaster education
programs. Mental health professionals also are needed to provide
counseling services for victims of disasters and administrative
support. For additional information, call 404-876-3302 or log onto
the Red Cross Web site at www.redcross.org/atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
