<P>
   WASHINGTON NEWS (``w'' category)
</P>
<P>
   NUCLEAR-SECURITY (Washington) _ An Energy Department
investigation finds that months after allegations of Chinese
espionage at America's nuclear laboratories, foreign scientists
without security clearance continued to have full access to the
main computer system at the Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory.
That system may have contained classified nuclear information. By
MARK HELM.
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   AIR-FORCE-RECRUITING (San Antonio) _ For the first time since
Jimmy Carter was president, the Air Force won't find enough
recruits to fill its enlisted ranks. The service says it will fall
2,500 recruits short of its goal in the fiscal year ending Sept.
30. By SIG CHRISTENSON.
</P>
<P>
   BUSINESS/FINANCIAL NEWS (``f'' category)
</P>
<P>
   WORKING-COLUMN (Atlanta) _ The ``bathrobe syndrome'' occurs when
a recovering employee, who is hurt in a non-job-related injury,
languishes at home alone during the day. Jerry Boyer, president of
the Precertification Center in Camp Hill, Pa., has a few ideas on
how to help these workers. By L.M. SIXEL.
</P>
<P>
   COMPUTER-COLUMN (Undated) _ If you're using e-mail, Eudora is
the way to go. It's better than Netscape's Messenger; Microsoft's
Exchange, Outlook Express and Outlook; America Online's e-mail
component; even Pegasus, the other top free mail software program.
The latest version of Eudora Pro, 4.2, is the best yet. Its new
features are so compelling and so well done that this is more than
just a minor upgrade. It puts Eudora Pro in a class by itself. By
DWIGHT SILVERMAN.
</P>
<P>
   With: COMPUTER-HELPLINE
</P>
<P>
   SPORTS (``s'' category)
</P>
<P>
   BBN-ASTROS (Cincinnati) _ Less than week after being swept out
of the Astrodome by the Cincinnati Reds, the Houston Astros will
try to turn the tables this weekend as they open a four-game series
at Cinergy Field. Pitcher Jose Lima will be going for his 12th
victory of the season in the series opener against a red-hot
Cincinnati team that is seeking its 11th consecutive victory.
JOSEPH DUARTE.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-WIMBLEDON (Wimbledon, England) _ Coverage of the men's and
women's quarterfinals at the Wimbledon tennis championships. By
DALE ROBERTSON.
</P>
<P>
   With: TEN-ROBERTSON-COLUMN
</P>
