<P>
   WEDDINGS-GAYS (New York) _ ``For gay people, weddings are always
a reminder of being outsiders,'' said Charles Silverstein, a New
York psychologist and the author of several books about
homosexuality. ``Even when people are welcoming, as they usually
are these days, weddings can be extremely alienating experiences.
They raise all sorts of ambivalence and take on a meaning far
greater than any party ever should.'' By Bob Morris.
</P>
<P>
   HOUSING-FOR-MODELS (New York) _ The biggest threat to a New York
City model's well-being isn't bugs in her group-living housing
environment. Far more serious are the perils of light-fingered
fellow models, boredom when work is slow, too much partying _ and
men. The big modeling agencies in New York that provide group
apartments (almost all do) intend them as protected towers to guard
their Rapunzels, mostly from would-be boyfriends and cutthroat
party promoters, who bear no resemblance to Prince Charming. By
Angela Treibelli. Photo.
</P>
<P>
   FASHIONISTAS (New York) _ Stylish? Who, me? Stylish is exactly
how stylish New Yorkers don't describe themselves. By Penelope
Green.
</P>
<P>
   NITEOUT-GUBELMANN (New York) _ Marjorie Gubelmann, who by day
helps invest her family's fortune, is earning a reputation as an
accomplished hostess, following in the footsteps of her grandmother
Barton Gubelmann, a society doyenne in Newport, R.I., and Palm
Beach. By Monique P. Yazigi.
</P>
<P>
   GARDEN-COLUMN (Undated) _ To some people, the phrase ``American
blues'' conjures up images of smoky nightclubs and B.B. King
wailing away. To me, it brings to mind a stunning array of native
perennials. These flowers look effortlessly beautiful in their
natural habitats across the country. By Patricia A. Taylor.
</P>
