<P>
   BLACKS-EDUCATION (Evanston, Ill.) _ Across the country,
educators and researchers are just beginning to focus on this
sensitive, explosive conundrum: Why black students, even from
middle class and upper-income families, do worse than whites and
Asians of comparable levels of income or family educational
background. They score lower on tests, get poorer grades and attend
college at a lower rate. By Pam Belluck.
</P>
<P>
   (May hold if not selected for Page One.)
</P>
<P>
   CAR-PHONE-BAN (Brooklyn, Ohio) _ It is illegal to drive while
talking on a cell phone in this Cleveland suburb, apparently the
only place in America with such a ban. Mayor John Coyne, 82, who is
in his 52nd year in office, and who can recall a time when people
survived without driving automobiles or talking on telephones, let
alone doing both at once, believes it is just a matter of common
sense. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   DREAMWORKS-STUDIO (Los Angeles) _ After nearly four years of
planning, DreamWorks SKG has pulled out of a controversial project
to build a film studio near sensitive wetlands, citing changes in
financial plans. By Todd S. Purdum.
</P>
<P>
   NY-MRSCLINTON (New York) _ If where you live defines who you
are, Hillary Rodham Clinton, the likely Senate candidate, is on a
difficult search. Because just as Brooklyn defined Senator Charles
E. Schumer and Nassau County defined former Sen. Alfonse D`Amato,
where Mrs. Clinton decides to live will give voters a strong clue
to who Mrs. Clinton is, or would like to be. By Elizabeth Bumiller.
</P>
<P>
   FINANCIAL
</P>
<P>
   (Will move in ``f'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   ECON-REPORT (Undated) _ The economy created more jobs than
expected last month, as average hourly earnings continued to rise,
the Labor Department reported. The economy added 268,000 jobs last
month, more than analysts' forecasts of a 217,000 gain. During May,
payrolls fell 5,000, a revision from the previously reported gain
of 11,000 jobs. Workers' average hourly earnings rose 0.4 percent _
or 5 cents _ to $13.23 in June following an increase of 0.3 percent
during May. Analysts had expected earnings to rise 0.3 percent. The
unemployment rate rose to 4.3 percent from 4.2 percent. By Slyvia
Nasar.
</P>
