<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7400 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSING-FOR-MODELS-AR     07-02 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-FOR-MODELS-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAFE HOUSING FOR YOUNG WOULD-BE MODELS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4)  
 (af)  
 By ANGELA TRIBELLI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Two pretty, young women were lazing in their sparsely
decorated living room, watching an ``X-Files'' video and
contemplating the evening's options. Go to the club of the moment?
A restaurant with an unlisted number? That new Stephen Dorff movie?
</P>
<P>
   Suddenly, a third roommate of improbable beauty materialized at
the top of the stairs, luggage in hand, and though she caused a
racket dragging her suitcases down the steps, no one seemed to
notice, or care much, that she was moving out.
</P>
<P>
   The apartment door flew open, and three more beauties entered.
One bounded across the room to answer a cell phone call from home.
The others discussed the latest domestic disaster: someone had put
regular soap instead of powdered in the dishwasher and had flooded
the kitchen with bubbles.
</P>
<P>
   If it seemed these women were too good-looking, too
sophisticated and yet too domestically challenged to be true,
that's because this is no ordinary apartment. It's a model
apartment, a three-story town house in Murray Hill rented by the
Elite modeling agency to house its newest recruits, and one of many
such agency-run dwellings around Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   In these dormlike apartments, young women sleep four or six to a
bedroom, roommates last as long as a carton of soy milk, and
privacy is a pipe dream. If a supermodel's measure of success is
her own duplex in TriBeCa and a pied-a-terre in Paris, then these
upstart models in New York are still a few notches below a ``Brady
Bunch'' bedroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bugs, in general, are a huge problem,'' said Conor Kennedy, a
director of development at the Company Management model agency, who
is in charge of finding and overseeing new talent. ``Teen-age girls
come to New York City for the first time and don't realize the
hazards of leaving cheese out for a week.''
</P>
<P>
   The biggest threat to a model's well-being isn't bugs, though.
Far more serious are the perils of light-fingered fellow models,
boredom when work is slow, too much partying _ and men.
</P>
<P>
   The big modeling agencies in New York that provide group
apartments (almost all do) intend them as protected towers to guard
their Rapunzels, mostly from would-be boyfriends and cutthroat
party promoters, who bear no resemblance to Prince Charming.
</P>
<P>
   Newly signed models arrive every week in Manhattan from small
towns or foreign countries, often as young as 15 and away from
parents for the first time. They are too new to the business to
earn enough to pay for their own places, and so agencies provide
group lodging usually in doorman buildings and supervised by
chaperones.
</P>
<P>
   Visiting a handful of the model apartments in the city, one
would expect a glamourous scene out of ``Breakfast at Tiffany's.''
But it's more like ``The Facts of Life,'' only with thinner
characters.
</P>
<P>
   A peek into the refrigerators of the apartments reveals yet
another potential threat to the occupants. At the Company
Management apartment in the Lower East Side the other day, the
refrigerator contained Boost lactose-free nutritional shakes,
organic blue cornflakes, salsa, mustard and three varieties of Eazy
Cheeze.
</P>
<P>
   But despite appearances, models are never forced to choose
between paying rent and eating. Most agencies simply keep track of
how many weeks the young women live in an apartment, and then
deduct rent _ $200 to $350 a week, depending on the unit _ from
their future earnings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The model's apartment is always an advance, and the rent is a
debt to us,'' Kennedy said.
</P>
<P>
   For the models, the trade-off for flexible housing in a doorman
building is overcrowding and a lack of privacy. Single-occupancy
rooms are rare. Bunk beds are more common, and blow-up mattresses
serve in a pinch. Severine, a French model who lived in Elite's
apartment early in her career, recalled some of the difficulties of
stacked sleeping quarters.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a strange experience,'' she said. ``You're asked to live
with maybe 10 girls, and you don't know them. I remember one girl,
she was calling, you know, sex on the phone all night. It was so
weird, you know, because in the bunk bed you can hear everything.
And I just wanted to sleep.''
</P>
<P>
   Unless the women bond quickly, there is little incentive for
them to be held accountable to their roommates. ``The biggest
problem in a models' apartment is stealing,'' Kennedy acknowledged.
``There can be no decorations or adornments of any kind in the
apartment. Anything will be stolen.''
</P>
<P>
   Even eggs. ``One time a girl ate six eggs at once,'' recalled
Celesta Shanti Hodge, an up-and-coming star at Company Management,
who lived in the agency apartment. ``I went out, and 20 minutes
later, all my eggs were gone! Two-dollar falafels? I ate those
things every day. We really were starving models.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelly Cole, a former owner of Spy, a lounge in SoHo that was a
big model scene, once dated a model who was living in the
Wilhelmina International agency's apartment. ``This one girl who
was stealing everything was just (italics)out of control,''(end
italics) he said, drawing out the syllables. ``Eventually the
agency sent her back to Croatia, or wherever she was from. But
after she left, all the other girls woke up the next morning to
find out that she had taken all their designer shoes and split.''
</P>
<P>
   If an apartment houses more than four models, agencies often
hire a live-in chaperone. Straight men, of course, are out of the
question. Gay men are a better option, but women are preferred by
both the parents and the agencies.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1617EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
