<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 16:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7401 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOUSING-FOR-MODELS-AR     07-02 0824
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOUSING-FOR-MODELS-ART-2NDTAKE-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NEW YORK: the agencies.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's not easy to find the ideal chaperone,'' Kennedy said.
``What normal person wants to live with four teen-age girls from
Dubuque?'' Company Management forbids girls younger than 16 to live
in the models' apartment without a female relative.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought I'd be the mother of eight daughters,'' said
Karen Lee, the chaperone at the Elite town house. The other
morning, she knocked on the second-floor bathroom door, and
reminded the shower's occupant about an early appointment.
</P>
<P>
   Then she opened the door to one of the bedrooms, which held two
sets of bunk beds. Between the beds, an entire wall was covered
with fashion photos and beauty-product advertisements clipped from
magazines. On the wall beside a pillow, someone had scrawled in
crayon, ``I Love Curt Thompson.''
</P>
<P>
   Most agencies have extensive lists of rules for their
apartments' young tenants. David Grilli, who was hired by
Wilhelmina to straighten out its apartment three years ago when
several models were breaking house rules, remembered the strict
rules he devised. ``If they were under 18, they had to be in by 10
on weekdays, 11 on weekends,'' he said. ``No smoking, no drugs or
drinking, and no loud music. And no men were allowed, not even
their brothers or their fathers.''
</P>
<P>
   At ID Models, which has three apartments, all new models are
required to sign a document, agreeing to comply with house rules.
One item advises, ``Avoid lengthy conversations'' while on
bookings.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Like most agencies, ID considers its models valuable
commodities, and it doesn't want them becoming too friendly with a
rival agency employee who might try to poach them.
</P>
<P>
   But it is night life that worries Paolo Zampolli, the president
of ID, the most. ``When they start to go out, they're gone,'' he
said flatly. ``They don't work the next day. One girl that goes out
every night is enough to destroy the apartment.''
</P>
<P>
   Going out is a bigger temptation for models who aren't working,
because those who do a full day's work are exhausted by 6 p.m.
Consequently, the models' schedules are designed to keep them busy.
Every morning, fledgling models call their bookers to confirm the
day's appointments, a full day of five to 10 casting calls, photo
shoots and ``go-sees,'' which are appointments at which models meet
prospective clients. Car services are reserved for the ``big
girls,'' the more established models.
</P>
<P>
   ``These girls spend nine hours a day walking and taking the
subway everywhere,'' Kennedy said. ``They can't even afford cabs
yet.''
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the day, models are encouraged to go to the gym,
rent a movie or collapse in exhaustion. That's when the phone
begins to ring.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was here before we changed the number, we used to have
promotions people from clubs call every night,'' said Leigh-Anne
Knight, a resident of the Company apartment. Over the last year,
Company has had to change its apartment's phone number three times.
</P>
<P>
   Club promoters, the worthy opponents of agency management in a
chess match for the models' attention, are paid to bring them into
clubs. They bombard agencies with faxed invitations, befriend
bookers and pay extra attention to newcomers, who are more likely
to let slip the apartment's phone number.
</P>
<P>
   Soon, a half-dozen promoters are calling for the same model,
who's probably moved out of the apartment by then.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember this one promoter, his name was Unik,'' Ms. Knight
said. ``He would ask for someone, and we'd say, `Oh, she's not
here,' and he'd say: `Well are you a model? Come to the club,
you'll get in free! Bring all your friends!'''
</P>
<P>
   To Lyndsay, who at 19 is one of the oldest models living in the
Elite town house, model-chasing men are old news. ``We had a couple
of incidents with people in the trees outside,'' she said, smoking
a cigarette on the terrace with Siobhan, one of her apartment
mates. ``But it hasn't happened recently.''
</P>
<P>
   Lyndsay has been modeling since she was 13. ``In the last couple
of days, we've gotten five new girls, and they'll probably all be
gone by next week,'' she said. ``Unfortunately, not everyone
understands that you can't give away the apartment's phone
number.''
</P>
<P>
   Any safe distraction that encourages the teen-agers to stay home
and away from the clubs is promoted by the agencies. They knit tube
tops and purses. VCRs are de rigueur in the apartments, and the
films the models choose to rent can be revealing. While ``Something
About Mary'' seems to be a universal favorite, the Elite models
can't get enough of ``Beautiful Girls.''
</P>
<P>
   At the apartment belonging to Karin's, another modeling agency,
the popular flick has been ``Gia,'' a made-for-cable hit about one
model's losing battle against heroin and AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's real-life movie,'' explained Nanda Hampe, a German model
living in the apartment. ``It was not a movie where you could
laugh.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
