<HEADER>
A7403 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-HOMESICK-KOSOVARS-ART     07-02 0848
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMESICK-KOSOVARS-ART-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REFUGEES IN US STRUGGLE WITH CHOICE TO STAY OR LEAVE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ART ADV.: A photo is being sent to NYTNS clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchases by calling 212-556-4204 or -1927.)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RYAN DAVIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Worcester, Mass. _ The silver key dangles from a nail just
inside the door of Naim Bujubaj's barren flat in a working-class
neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   For Bujubaj, a 26-year-old refugee, it is unclear whether it is
the key to his past or his future.
</P>
<P>
   It opens the door to his apartment in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to use it,'' he said, squinting to try to hide his
tears. ``But I'm 90 percent certain that I will never be able to
use it again.''
</P>
<P>
   Bujubaj's dilemma _ whether to return to his home or build a new
life in the United States _ has taken on new urgency in recent
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Since NATO troops moved into Kosovo June 12, a growing number of
Kosovo refugees _ including many of the 329 who have resettled in
Massachusetts _ are considering returning home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go back, but I don't know how,'' said Zahir
Bacaliu, another Kosovar who recently settled in Worcester. ``If I
go back now, my house is burned and I don't know where I'd live.
</P>
<P>
   Those working with the refugees say Kosovars have a visceral tie
to their homeland.
</P>
<P>
   ``Historically, they have fought so much for Kosovo,'' said
Albana Orgockacq, a social worker at the International Institute of
Boston, which has resettled about 65 Kosovars. ``If something could
change, they have to go back and be a part of it.''
</P>
<P>
   About 9,000 Kosovars have arrived in the United States since the
conflict began, said Eyleen Schmidt, a spokeswoman for the US
Immigration and Refugee Service, a branch of the Department of
Justice.
</P>
<P>
   Another 7,000 Kosovars in Macedonia have been approved to come
to the United States, but thousands of those refugees have returned
home instead, Schmidt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything I have in my life is in Kosovo,'' Bacaliu said.
</P>
<P>
   Bacaliu24, left his corn farm in Kijeva, Kosovo, in May with his
mother, wife, two children, cousin and cousin's family after Serb
soliders ordered them to leave.
</P>
<P>
   Their next journey, the Bacalius hope, will be a return to
Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like America, but I like my place more,'' said
XhemalBacaliu, Zahir's 27-year-old cousin.
</P>
<P>
   Several Bay State social service agencies, including Lutheran
Social Services of New England, Catholic Charities and the
International Rescue Committee, have provided Kosovar refugees
financial assistance, temporary housing, job leads, and English
instruction.
</P>
<P>
   Once NATO declares Kosovo a safe place, the United States will
allocate enough funds for the return trip home for all refugees who
choose to go back, Schmidt said. The free flight offer, however,
expires six months after Kosovo is deemed safe.
</P>
<P>
   The refugees will have the right to apply for permanent resident
status.
</P>
<P>
   Luan Shala, 47, a music teacher and trombone player from
Pristina, Kosovo's capital, won't go back no matter how safe NATO
makes Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would like to live here and start a new life,'' said the
refugee who arrived in Worcester on June 23. ``I'm very afraid of
mines.''
</P>
<P>
   Shala was forced to leave his Pristina apartment May 5. ``The
paramilitary came with machine guns and told us to go to the
railroad station,'' said Shala, who continues searching for
information about his missing brother in Kosovo. ``They took our
money, our passports, any documents we had.''
</P>
<P>
   They gave him five minutes to gather all his belongings.
</P>
<P>
   That's three minutes longer than Naim Bujubaj had to pack his
bag.
</P>
<P>
   Bujubaj knew his departure was imminent. Just days before he
left, he found a cross in front of his door with the word ``dead''
scrawled across it. As he lay down to sleep that night, he thought
to himself, ``I think tomorrow I will be dead.''
</P>
<P>
   Seven weeks ago he, his sister, and his 24-year-old cousin,
Abediu Bujubaj arrived at Fort Dix, N.J., each with one bag holding
everything they now own.
</P>
<P>
   In better times, at the University of Pristina, Naim Bujubaj
studied economics while Abediu Bujubaj studied computers and
telecommunications.
</P>
<P>
   They want to further their education in the United States so
they can master English. But they withdrew from Worcester
Polytechnic Institute because the aid they are receiving can barely
cover food costs, $550 a month rent, and utilities. They have
nothing left for tuition.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd like to stay here now,'' Abediu said. ``After this, we
will see what we want to do.''
</P>
<P>
   Like many of the refugees, the Bujubaj cousins fear returning
while Russian troops remain in their country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Serbian people and Russian people are the same,'' Abediu said.
</P>
<P>
   Naim doesn't know if his apartment back home is still standing
or _ as he believes likely _ was torched or looted by Serb forces.
</P>
<P>
   But he still won't throw away the key.
</P>
<P>
   ``The day I escaped was the second time I was born,'' Naim said.
``I'd like to take the key to remember.''
</P>
</TEXT>
