<HEADLINE>
ALL THE FORMALITIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sun., July 4)  
(jt) 
 By MONIQUE P. YAZIGI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Marjorie plays like a 30-year-old and entertains like
a 50-year-old,'' said Earl Crittenden, a political writer and law
student, who was awaiting his dessert at a dinner last Saturday
night. Marjorie Gubelmann was the hostess.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gubelmann had taken over a room and the terrace at Club
Colette, a year-old Southampton satellite of a private eating club
in Palm Beach, Fla., to entertain 65 of her friends. And while the
club's core group of 400 members are mostly older Palm Beach
families, Ms. Gubelmann draws the younger set. She does so,
strangely enough, by giving parties in a staid and formal style
more familiar a couple of generations ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gubelmann, who by day helps invest her family's fortune, is
earning a reputation as an accomplished hostess, following in the
footsteps of her grandmother Barton Gubelmann, a society doyenne in
Newport, R.I., and Palm Beach.
</P>
<P>
   When Marjorie Gubelmann was a little girl in Palm Beach, she
used to sneak upstairs to raid her grandmother's jewelry box, then
return to show off at parties whose guest lists included King
Hussein of Jordan and the Duke and Duchess of Windsor.
</P>
<P>
   At 30, Ms. Gubelmann still loves to wear her grandmother's
jewels. She has been dubbed B.I.T, or Barton-in-Training by Quest
and Hamptons magazines. And she entertains just the way her
grandmother did, the old-fashioned way, except that she is clad in
a shimmering lace over chartreuse satin Versace dress and has a
slightly different idea of royalty. Her guest list last Saturday
included Shoshanna Lonstein, Mark Gilbertson and Nicole Miller.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a person who floats in many different groups,'' she said,
standing by a candlelighted pink table, overlooking the seating in
the room. She likes to mix them up. ``It may be a little dangerous,
edgy, but it's more fun,'' Ms. Gubelmann said, playing with her
20-carat tanzanite ring, a gift to herself for her 30th birthday.
</P>
<P>
   Before her party, she carefully placed her thick gold-edged
monogrammed place cards (with fleurs-de-lis in the corners) for a
formal seated dinner.
</P>
<P>
   She learned the art of seating from Glamma, as she calls her
grandmother. ``For spice,'' she says, ``you mix the great cellist
with the gay decorator. You mix up old boyfriends with former
girlfriends. And you put one fabulous person on one side, and one
person that no one wants to sit next to on the other, so the guest
is not completely punished.''
</P>
<P>
   Dinner that night: lobster vinaigrette and rack of lamb. ``I
don't think people should be fed mesclun salad and chicken
breast,'' she said, adding that she doesn't believe in giving her
guests a choice about what they eat. ``My grandmother would serve
grits and oxtail stew at a formal dinner, and if you didn't like
it, well then you ate more beans or you went home and ate a peanut
butter and jelly sandwich.''
</P>
<P>
   She is equally opinionated about hors d'oeuvres. ``In Newport,
we serve cheese or bacon-wrapped water chestnuts,'' she said.
``Here, it's more about sushi.''
</P>
<P>
   After spending most of her summers in Newport, Ms. Gubelmann now
prefers the Hamptons, where, she says, the social life has more
variety. ``You can go to the Meadow Club and you can go to Puff
Daddy's,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
