<SLUG> BC-INVEST-EMERGING-MARKETS-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEUTRAL FED STANCE AND A WARY EYE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve is not in the business of trying to confuse
investors. With testimony, speeches and comments from its chairman,
Alan Greenspan, and other Fed officials, the central bank's
leadership has done its best to telegraph all its moves in recent
years.
</P>
<P>
   That is why there was no surprise when the Fed announced on
Wednesday that its short-term interest rate target was rising a
quarter of a percentage point, to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the other half of the announcement was a surprise, and it
left many investors scratching their heads _ which ought to add to
market volatility on the road to the Fed's next policy meeting in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Along with the rate increase, the Fed said it changad changed
its outlook on interest rates from a bias toward higher rates _ a
stance adopted at the May policy meeting _ to neutral.
</P>
<P>
   For investors, the first question is what the switch means. The
second is why the Fed made it. Surely, the policy-making Open
Market Committee knew that the change would be interpreted
positively by investors and give the stock market a boost, making a
gentle slowing-down of the economy _ the ostensible purpose of
raising rates _ that much harder to achieve. Sure enough, all three
major market indexes hit new highs by week's end.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors saw the switch to neutral as a signal that one
rate increase would be enough to brake economic growth and curb
inflation. But that is hard to believe, given recent economic and
price data.
</P>
<P>
   Some 268,000 nonfarm jobs were created in June, the Labor
Department reported on Friday, while hourly earnings rose 3.7
percent over the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   The manufacturing sector _ whose earlier slump had helped
restrain wage pressures _ is rebounding and gaining momentum. With
the stock market now recovered from its spring selloff and consumer
confidence at a 30-year high, it is difficult to conclude that
consumers, the backbone of this expansion, are about to rein in
spending.
</P>
<P>
   The new surge in oil prices, which last week jumped above $19 a
barrel, should raise inflation concerns. With that jump, and a
rebound in industrial commodity prices, we could be in for another
shocking leap in the Consumer Price Index.
</P>
<P>
   The 0.7 percent surge in April helped prompt the Fed's bias
toward higher interest rates in May and the actual increase that
followed.
</P>
<P>
   A look at the Fed's recent history shows that a move to neutral
does not rule out another rate increase, or even indicate that the
outlook for tamer inflation and growth is improving.
</P>
<P>
   For example, the Fed went to neutral after each rate increase in
the 1994-95 run-up, a period when the federal funds rate, the
overnight interest rate on loans between banks, jumped from 3
percent to 6 percent in seven separate moves.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the language used to explain the shift to neutral
after the Fed's previous quarter-point rate increase, in March
1997, makes clear that the neutral bias referred only to the next
few weeks, until the committee is scheduled to meet again. ``While
additional policy tightening might be needed at some point, it did
not appear very likely that developments during the inter-meeting
period would require a further policy move,'' the minutes of the
committee meeting said.
</P>
<P>
   According to the minutes, members who argued for a bias toward
higher rates said they could accept the neutral stance as long as
there was ``careful monitoring of new developments for any signs of
the need for prompt action.'' In other words, nothing was ruled
out.
</P>
<P>
   An echo of that emphasis on vigilance appeared in last week's
announcement, in which policy makers said they must ``be especially
alert.''
</P>
<P>
   Which leaves the question of why the Fed spoke up about its
shift to neutral, knowing that investors would put the most
positive spin possible on the news.
</P>
<P>
   One explanation is that the Fed was locked in by its new
disclosure policy. In the past, such a change in stance was not
divulged until after the subsequent policy-making meeting, about
six weeks later. But beginning this year, the Fed has announced
changes in its leanings on interest rates immediately when the
moves were considered significant.
</P>
<P>
   Or the Fed may be trying to slow the economy with as little
disruption as possible. Greenspan said last month that he was not
aiming to prick any stock market bubble. He also said it is not the
Fed's practice to plan a series of interest-rate increases in
advance. Both goals were advanced by the return to a neutral stance
on the rate outlook.
</P>
</TEXT>
