<SLUG> BC-GARDEN-COLUMN-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THE SUMMER, FLOWERS TO MATCH THE OCEAN AND THE SKY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday July 4)  
(jt) 
 By PATRICIA A. TAYLOR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   To some people, the phrase ``American blues'' conjures up images
of smoky nightclubs and B.B. King wailing away. To me, it brings to
mind a stunning array of native perennials. These flowers look
effortlessly beautiful in their natural habitats across the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Their siren songs start in early-spring shade settings, where
the striking sky-blue flowers of Virginia bluebells and the soft
blue blossoms of American Jacob's ladder open. In late April,
fragrant swaths of blue woodland phlox sashay through my borders.
With their similar heights of one to two feet, the three are lovely
companions.
</P>
<P>
   In May, Amsonia flowers create a melody of blues in sunny to
bright shade areas. I have three kinds _ A. hubrectii, A. montana
and A. tabernaemontana. While their heights vary from one to four
feet, all feature two- to three-inch bouquets of tightly clustered
light blue flowers at the tops of their stems.
</P>
<P>
   Two more native blues, each with a hint of violet in their
color, tune up in summer borders situated in sunny to partly shaded
areas.
</P>
<P>
   Stokesias are two-foot-tall plants covered with two-inch wide,
asterlike flowers from late June into early September. Big lobelias
feature spires shooting up three to four feet, which are clustered
with half-inch flowers in August.
</P>
<P>
   All these reliable performers are available in garden centers or
mail order catalogs. There are four more, however, that are equally
handsome and carefree but little known.
</P>
<P>
   With their beguiling color tones, they are striking in summer
and fall borders.
</P>
<P>
   The first to bloom features sprays of royal blue flowers from
early summer through light frost. It has an unattractive popular
name, and perhaps this has contributed to its obscurity. Who wants
to brag about having HOARY SKULLCAP (Scutellaria incana) in their
garden? Yet, it is a member of the mint family, which loosely
translates into its being unappetizing to most munching animals. It
is native to dry, open woods and does well in full sun to bright
shade.
</P>
<P>
   Growing from two to three feet tall, hoary skullcap looks like a
cross between two other mint family members, with its foliage size
and shape similar to that of bee balms and its
three-quarter-inch-long flowers akin to those of salvias. Unlike
bee balms, however, hoary skullcaps are neither invasive nor prone
to mildew.
</P>
<P>
   The warmer the growing area, the earlier the bloom period for
AMERICAN ALPINE SPEEDWELL (Veronica wormskjoldii). In North
Carolina, for example, it usually flowers by the Fourth of July. In
my central New Jersey gardens, its rich blue six-to-eight-inch
spikes bloom for a four-week period starting in late July, a
refreshing sight in the humid heat.
</P>
<P>
   In bare spaces, unstaked plants look like contortionists: the
12-to-15-inch stems are not sturdy enough to bear the weight of the
flowers, which insist on remaining upright. Interspersing American
alpine speedwell among other sun-loving perennials will hide this
convoluted appearance. In my garden, its spikes, called racemes,
pop up among pale yellow Moonbeam coreopsis and blazing orange
butterfly weed, creating a colorful showcase.
</P>
<P>
   Botanists just can't seem to agree on what Latin nomenclature to
use for BLUE SAGE , a salvia with brilliant sky-blue flowers from
late August until frost. While all its botanical names start with
salvia, various books and catalogs list one or more of the
following as second or even third names: azurea, grandiflora or
pitcherii. Any of those names will steer you to a stunning blue
beauty that looks particularly handsome in full sun settings.
</P>
<P>
   One reference book says this plant forms arching fountains, a
graceful way of explaining that it, too, flops if not staked.
Unlike American alpine speedwell, which bends in almost a
right-angle formation, the thin three-to-five-foot stems of blue
sage tend to curve out before touching solid ground. I prop them up
by interspersing them with other late-season perennials like golden
Maryland aster and cerise-pink Alma Poetschke aster. This salvia's
stems and intensely blue one-inch flowers are so light that they
appear to float atop the other plants.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the cool tones found in the other little-known blues, the
flowers of BOTTLE GENTIAN (Gentiana andrewsii) are a warm
robin's-egg blue. They are extremely unusual in that they never
open, and for this reason are also known as closed gentian. They
have the shape of a one-to-two-inch football.
</P>
<P>
   Everything I've read about this plant, which grows one to two
feet tall, says it is supposed to be grown in moist soils. But I
wasn't paying attention when I placed it in a rather dry sunny
border. That setting hasn't bothered it one bit in the seven years
I've grown it. I suspect that the foliage of surrounding
perennials, which provide protection from the sun's drying rays,
has helped.
</P>
<P>
   Though frost lays low most flowers by mid-October, it seems to
bring bottle gentian to life. Its clusters of chubby blossoms, the
color of late-day summer skies, irradiate increasingly bare
surroundings for almost a month.
</P>
<P>
   And the melody lingers even after the blue color fades. Thin,
tan flower husks remain as a sculpture before snows banish the last
remnant of American blues and close down the garden show for the
year.
</P>
<P>
   Hoary skullcap is available from the Primrose Path, R.D. 2, Box
110, Scottdale, Pa. 15683; (724) 887-6756; catalog, $2.
</P>
<P>
   American alpine speedwell is sold by Forestfarm, 990 Tetherow
Road, Williams, Ore. 97544; (541) 846-7269; catalog, $4.
</P>
<P>
   Blue sage seed and bottle gentians are available from Prairie
Moon Nursery, Route 3, Box 163, Winona, Minn. 55987; (507)
452-1362; free catalog.
</P>
</TEXT>
