<HEADER>
A7427 &Cx1f; ttj-z
r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIR-FORCE-RECRUITING-     07-02 0561
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIR-FORCE-RECRUITING-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AIR FORCE FALL SHORT OF RECRUITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SIG CHRISTENSON  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ For the first time since Jimmy Carter was
president, the Air Force won't find enough recruits to fill its
enlisted ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force says it will fall 2,500 recruits short of its goal
in the fiscal year ending Sept. 30, something that hasn't happened
since 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Solomon P. Ortiz, D-Texas, said readiness could be
jeopardized if the shortages aren't reversed, and he suggested that
Congress might have to take a fresh look at a draft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be a good possibility that if this trend continues,
we're going to very seriously look at the draft, at reviving the
draft again,'' said Ortiz, a member of a House Armed Services
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The service has been in a prolonged recruiting slump and fell
2,578 recruits short of its year-end target of 33,800 personnel in
May, the San Antonio-based Air Force Recruiting Service said
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The Pentagon has blamed the strong economy for the shortfall,
which has hammered the Army as well. The Army was shy of its
recruiting goal by 7,639 soldiers as May ended. The Navy and Marine
Corps exceeded their quotas.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a booming economy, which we are grateful to see, but
it does mean that we have the lowest unemployment in about 30 years
and fierce competition for talented young people,'' said Lt. Col.
Tom Begines, a Pentagon spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are lots of opportunities in today's job market,''
Acting Air Force Secretary F. Whitten Peters said. ``Competition is
tough.''
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz and Rep. Ciro Rodriguez, D-Texas, see a continued
recruiting slump as a threat to readiness. Rodriguez, also a member
of the Armed Services Committee, predicted more reservists would
have to be called to active duty.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force met its recruiting goal last year by accelerating
the introduction of enlistees in the delayed-entry program, said
Sgt. John Hancock, a spokesman with the Air Force Recruiting
Service.
</P>
<P>
   This year the service began a first-ever paid television ad
campaign. The 18-month, $54 million broadcast campaign will run
through September 2000. A series of 30-second spots will air in
large media markets starting July 12.
</P>
<P>
   To slow the exit of service members, the Air Force has limited
the amount of time anyone can be deployed overseas to 120 days. It
also has dangled cash incentives to keep men and women in uniform,
offering re-enlistment bonuses in a wide number of job specialties.
</P>
<P>
   Rodriguez said he wants the Air Force to sign up more Hispanics
with high school equivalency degrees, or GEDs. The service allows
only 1 percent of its recruits to hold GEDs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of the people with GEDs are sharper than the ones who
graduated from high school,'' said Rodriguez, who dropped out in
the ninth grade but later graduated.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock said the Air Force's problem is rooted less in
recruiting than retention woes. He said Air Force recruiters are
doing as well as they did last year but can't keep up with the loss
of veterans.
</P>
<P>
   The Air Force so far this year, however, has met its monthly
recruiting goals just twice, in October and June.
</P>
<P>
   Hancock said the service wouldn't give up. ``You're not going to
see a white flag from us,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
