<HEADLINE>
SAN FRANCISCO TREATS: TADICH GRILL, AQUA NEAR EACH OTHER, BUT
WORLDS APART 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Monday, July 5) 
 
By DAI HUYNH  
 c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Here's the hook: Both restaurants dish up
seafood.
</P>
<P>
   Now the catch: The Tadich Grill turned 150 this year; neighbor
Aqua, 8.
</P>
<P>
   Beneath the moody fog, the old meets the new in the 200 block of
California Street in San Francisco's Financial District. But more
than years separate two of the biggest fishes in this West Coast
dining pond. Although located only a few doors from each other, the
popular restaurants are miles apart in style and attitude. Think
Ralph Lauren vs. Sears or Daddy Warbucks vs. Homer Simpson.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not fancy,'' admits Bob Buich, whose family has owned
the Tadich Grill since 1933. ``But we're fast. The service is good,
but it can be abrupt at times.''
</P>
<P>
   Founded in 1849 by three Croatian immigrants, San Francisco's
oldest restaurant attracts locals and tourists alike. An unknowing
visitor might construe the waiters, dressed like stern doctors in
starched white overcoats, as downright rude.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's because people are waiting to get in,'' Buich
explains.
</P>
<P>
   Regulars know this. ``They're efficient,'' businessman Charles
Morton says. ``Their brusqueness stems from necessity, not by
choice.''
</P>
<P>
   The Tadich Grill doesn't take reservations, and during the lunch
rush, the wait may range from 15 to 30 minutes. Most customers work
nearby in the bustling Financial District, and the experienced
waiters know these people have little time to kill. Hence the rush
to place the orders. Diners, however, can take their sweet time
chowing down on the pan-fried petrale sole fillet, deviled crab or
poached salmon with chopped egg sauce. But most are in and out in
half an hour.
</P>
<P>
   Over at Aqua, the wait can run 45 to 90 minutes without a
reservation. But time is less important here. Patrons compare
dining at this upscale seafood mecca to the restaurants in France
and Italy, where meals can last two hours or more. The plush,
silk-upholstered chairs were fashioned for long-term comfort.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked three days in the design of the chairs so you can
really feel comfortable if you want to sit for three or four
hours,'' says Charles Condy, who co-owns the restaurant with
executive chef Michael Mina.
</P>
<P>
   As for the wait staff?
</P>
<P>
   ``They really pamper you here. They would wash your feet if you
asked them,'' a regular customer says as she leans over to smell
the elaborate flower arrangement in the ladies room.
</P>
<P>
   That smooth service comes with a price tag that leaves many
wallets feeling lighter. Lunch can run $40 and dinner $80 per
person, and this may not include a glass of wine.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not the most expensive restaurant in town,'' Condy
insists, ``but in order to do everything we do, there's a cost.''
</P>
<P>
   Aqua has 110 employees, including a human resources director,
rarely found in the restaurant industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a labor force that reflects the care in the
preparation of the food. For instance, you'll never get a lobster
or a shrimp in a shell,'' Condy says.
</P>
<P>
   Nor are patrons likely to find any tartar sauce on the premises.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't do that type of dishes,'' says 31-year-old Mina, who
received the Rising Star Chef Award from the James Beard Foundation
in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   From the modest-sized kitchen emerge dishes with fusion flair,
such as flawlessly wrapped Japanese gift packages of ahi tuna,
smoked salmon, Chilean sea bass and dungeness crab. The
restaurant's signature appetizer is the $55 Caviar Parfait. The
3-inch-tall creation layers a light, spicy potato cake; chopped
eggs and onion; in-house-smoked salmon; lemony crme frache; and
Russian osetra caviar.
</P>
<P>
   For a main course, there are the Medallions of Rare Ahi Tuna,
surrounded by an intensely rich pinot noir sauce and served with
seared Hudson Valley foie gras. By the way, foie gras rules here,
making appearances on many of the dishes. Not to your liking? Then
opt for the Pecan-Crusted Loin of Hawaiian Swordfish, framed by
pancetta-wrapped shrimp dumplings and sweet corn pudding. Of
course, there's always the crowd-pleasing Lobster Pot Pie for $49
to consider.
</P>
<P>
   ``The dishes are complex,'' Mina admits. ``My whole theory
behind cooking is balancing all the ingredients. So, if you're
going to use heat, then you must also use acidity and sweetness to
balance it out.''
</P>
<P>
   Aqua's neighbor has a less complicated view on seafood.
</P>
<P>
   At the Tadich Grill, patrons can have charcoal-broiled or
pan-fried rex sole, petrale sole, Pacific red snapper, rainbow
trout, halibut, salmon or swordfish. They're all reasonably priced
with few frills or thrills. You won't find truffle-infused oils at
this old-fashioned restaurant. Just the fish, a light butter sauce,
Long Branch potatoes and ... tartar sauce.
</P>
<P>
   Many old favorites from the Gold Rush days can be found here.
There's cioppino, a popular San Francisco stew similar to
bouillabaisse made with clams, shrimp, scallops and white fish in a
slightly spicy tomato broth. And then there's the notorious
Hangtown Fry, the scrambled eggs, bacon and oysters frittata named
in memory of the outlaws who requested it as their last meal.
</P>
<P>
   ``They would pick the hardest things to find to delay the
hanging, and eggs and oysters were very hard to come by in those
days,'' Buich says.
</P>
<P>
   For more than 40 years, Jack McGinity has eaten at the Tadich.
</P>
<P>
   ``I come here Monday through Saturday. They're closed Sunday,''
says the 70-year-old native San Franciscan. ``It's a guy's place. A
gal's place is next door at Aqua, where it's modern and sleek. Gals
go there, talk all day and sip their wine.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking around, it's easy to see why the Tadich was once
considered a stomping ground for the fellows. It hasn't changed
much over the years _ lots of suits sitting along the long bar that
doubles as a lunch counter. White-clothed tables line the walls,
and paneled booths offer privacy for the countless political,
financial and movie deals struck over the decades at this clubby
establishment. It's old San Francisco: feisty, boisterous and
in-your-face.
</P>
<P>
   Like many legendary restaurants, the Tadich has attracted
politicians, such as George Bush, Ted Kennedy and current San
Francisco Mayor Willie Brown; financiers; and movie stars,
including Cary Grant, Danny Kaye, Bing Crosby and Doris Day.
</P>
<P>
   Aqua has served its share of luminaries, including the Rolling
Stones, Bill Gates and Ralph Lauren. But the real stars are the
oversized flower-filled urns casting shadows on the bare mocha
walls.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a mistake to overdecorate a joint,'' Condy says. ``In the
beginning, we decided that there wasn't going to be lot of artwork
here because we were going to let our guests decorate the
restaurant, and they do. We have a really good-looking clientele.''
</P>
<P>
   Although there's no dress code, Aqua's patrons easily could have
walked off the pages of GQ or Vogue. But this isn't the Helmut Lang
or Dolce &AMP; Gabbana crowd; it's Ralph Lauren's traditional chic and
Donna Karan's all-American.
</P>
<P>
   As for the Tadich, clothes are a non-issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, we don't talk about that here,'' says San Francisco
native Treut Sperry, 76. ``Now, if you want to talk about the old
days, I can tell you anything. I was here during the strike of
1944. I remember the feud between the Lees and the Wongs in
Chinatown.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hello, Susie! Where have you been?''
</P>
<P>
   Just think of ``Cheers,'' and you'll get the idea.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
------------------ &QL; 
INFORMATION BOX &QL; 
------------------- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   _ Tadich Grill: 240 California St.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: 11 a.m.-9:30 p.m. Mondays-Fridays and 11:30 a.m.-9:30
p.m. Saturdays. Closed Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations not accepted. For information, call 415-391-1849.
</P>
<P>
   _ Aqua: 252 California St.
</P>
<P>
   Hours: 11:30 a.m.-2:30 p.m. Mondays-Fridays, 5:30-10:30 p.m.
Mondays-Thursdays and 5:30-11:30 p.m. Fridays-Saturdays. Closed
Sundays.
</P>
<P>
   Reservations recommended. For information, call 415-956-9662.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
