u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS &LR;      07-02 0797
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WORKING-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MANAGING INJURIES KEEPS DOWN COSTS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By L.M. SIXEL 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A few years ago, companies got concerned about their
rising workers' compensation costs and launched aggressive
campaigns to get their employees back to work.
</P>
<P>
   The programs, which include assigning light-duty work and
continually monitoring injured workers, have allowed companies to
cut their workers' compensation expenses by 30 to 50 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But many companies don't use that same careful medical
management when employees suffer a non-job-related injury or
illness, such as an arm broken on a skiing holiday or chronic heart
disease.
</P>
<P>
   Those employees fall through the cracks, said Jerry Boyer,
president of the Precertification Center in Camp Hill, Pa., who was
trying to sell his nonoccupational management services at the
recent conference of the Society for Human Resource Management in
Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Bosses and co-workers start to forget about them if they're off
for a long time, said Boyer, who set up a booth to lure human
resource managers to listen to what is becoming one of the hottest
topics in benefit management. Boyer calls it the ``bathrobe
syndrome'' _ the result of a recovering employee languishing at
home alone during the day.
</P>
<P>
   To combat it, Boyer said, his firm immediately contacts the
doctor who is treating an employee after an injury or illness is
reported and discusses how long the employee should be off from
work. That way, instead of just accepting an eight-week recovery,
the Precertification Center nurse can ask the doctor to initially
approve just two weeks and later re-evaluate the employee's medical
progress.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
BRINGING EMPLOYEES BACK &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The more time that goes on, the less likely the employee will
return to work, said Richard Pimentel, senior vice president of
Milt Wright &AMP; Associates, an organizational design consulting firm
based in Chatsworth, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   An employee who has been off for three months is 75 percent
likely to return to work. That falls to 50 percent after six
months. After a year, the chance an employee will return to work
falls to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Pimentel, who designs return-to-work programs from his office in
Las Vegas, said it's becoming critical for employers to design such
a program because aging baby boomers are needing more medical care.
In this tight labor market, employers can't afford to lose them.
</P>
<P>
   But few employers have taken that step. When Pimentel asked the
300 human resource managers who attended his presentation on
retention strategies how many actively manage the return of their
employees who are out on workers' compensation, most of the hands
shot up. But only a few _ four or five _ popped up when he asked
about active management of nonoccupational injuries.
</P>
<P>
   David H. Miller, an internist with an office in the Texas
Medical Center in Houston, has had plenty of experience dealing
with employers on workers' compensation cases. There are several
forms to fill out regarding acceptable light duty, expected return
to work and expected time of full recovery.
</P>
<P>
   But an off-the-job injury? Miller said he can't remember an
employer calling to suggest light-duty work or asking to speed the
employee's return.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
KEEPING IN CLOSE TOUCH &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Bridgestone/Firestone Warren Plant in Morrison, Tenn., is
rare among companies in the way it handles such injuries. A company
representative calls every employee who is off with an injury or
illness, whether or not it's work-related, to let them know the
plant is concerned, said Fran R. Jones, organizational development
consultant. Each absent worker is also carefully tracked: Each
week, the health services and benefits coordinator meet to update
the status of each employee who is out on injury or illness.
</P>
<P>
   And all employees are eligible for restricted duty because the
plant wants people back to work, Jones said.
</P>
<P>
   It's extremely shortsighted for companies to offer light-duty
work exclusively to employees who have been injured on the job,
Pimentel said, referring to the case of the pregnant Continental
Airlines ticket agent whose doctor said she couldn't lift more than
20 pounds. The Houston ticket agent asked the airline for a
temporary job change but Continental refused.
</P>
<P>
   The airline industry doesn't have many light-duty positions
available and at Continental Airlines, the airline reserves the few
it has to those who have been injured in the line of duty, said
Continental spokeswoman Julie Gardner.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL; 
L.M. Sixel can receive electronic mail via the Internet. Address
your comments and questions to lm.sixel(at)chron.com, or call (713)
220-2000 and enter access code 1002. &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
