<HEADER>
A7447 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-MORTGAGE-RATES-$A     07-02 0897
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-MORTGAGE-RATES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HUNTING THE BETTER MORTGAGE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Texas, N.Y.)   (af)  
 By BARBARA WHITAKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Abby Rodgers is not one to haggle. She buys cars at list. In
early April, in need of a mortgage, she turned to a large lender,
accepted tentative terms just under 7 percent, with no points, and
went away happy.
</P>
<P>
   But a few weeks ago, when she went to lock in her rate, she was
told that the interest rate had gone up by more than a point, to 8
percent, adding $350 to her monthly payment, plus the lender was
charging one point (an upfront fee of 1 percent on the loan
amount). She decided to shop around.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within 24 hours, I was finding things in the low sevens,''
said Ms. Rodgers, a marketing director with the Coca-Cola Co. in
Houston.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months, mortgage rates _ which held steady at
about 7 percent over the winter _ have lurched up by three-quarters
of a percentage point, to their highest level in two years.
</P>
<P>
   The mortgage market, like the bond market, was ahead of the
Federal Reserve, which, in a long-anticipated move, increased the
overnight lending rate on Tuesday by a quarter of a percentage
point, to 5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Higher rates have yet to affect home sales, but they have
crushed the refinancing market and made it a wary time for buyers
in general. ``We've definitely been putting out fires,'' said Seth
Cohen, managing director of the Home Mortgage Acceptance Corp., a
Manhattan lender.
</P>
<P>
   Still, with a little work, caution and creativity, home shoppers
may be able to trim their costs.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Rodgers found her lower rate through www.bankrate.com, a Web
site that tracks loan rates. She and her husband, Andrew Pickens, a
lawyer with Gibbs &AMP; Bruns in Houston, gave their initial lender an
opportunity to match the better rate, but it declined to do so.
</P>
<P>
   At 7.25 percent, with 1.125 points, her new mortgage is still a
good deal when compared with average rates over the last decade.
Since 1990, the average for 30-year fixed-rate mortgages has been
8.27 percent, according to HSH Associates, a financial publisher in
Butler, N.J., that tracks the market. The average since 1995 has
been lower, at 7.69 percent.
</P>
<P>
   For most consumers, the monthly payment is the bottom line. On
each $100,000 of a loan, the difference between 7.25 and 8 percent
means a payment increase of about $50.
</P>
<P>
   For those who find fixed rates too costly, or who need a lower
initial rate to qualify for a given house, an array of
adjustable-rate mortgages are available, including hybrids with
initial rates, often still under 7 percent, that can be adjusted
after 3, 5, 7 or 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   With its low initial rates, an adjustable-rate mortgage can save
money for a buyer who does not plan to live in a house for a long
time. But a consumer should be careful to calculate whether the
savings would cover refinancing, should that be necessary down the
line.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier in the year, the rate difference between 30-year fixed
mortgages and five-year adjustables had been about half a
percentage point, but the margin has widened.
</P>
<P>
   According to HSH, the average interest rate for a 30-year,
fixed-rate mortgage hit a 1999 peak during the week ended June 18,
at 7.78 percent, plus nearly one point. The average was 6.99
percent for a five-year adjustable-rate loan and 6.09 percent for a
one-year adjustable, both with less than a point.
</P>
<P>
   On a $200,000 loan, the difference between the monthly payments
on a 30-year fixed and a five-year adjustable would be about $109.
(The 30-year would be $1,436 a month for principal and interest;
the adjustable would have initial payments of $1,327.)
</P>
<P>
   A typical adjustable can go up or down two points at a time,
with a lifetime cap of six percentage points. But Keith T.
Gumbinger, an HSH vice president, cautioned consumers to check the
fine print, because many longer-term adjustables allow an initial
change of up to five points. Changes are typically tied to the
rates on Treasury securities.
</P>
<P>
   Home buyers with extra cash can also cut their interest rates by
paying additional points. Each point will bring the rate down by an
eighth to a quarter of a percentage point, HSH said.
</P>
<P>
   Another alternative is to make a bigger down payment or to
consider a ``floatdown'' option: For a fee, typically an eighth to
a quarter of a point, a consumer's rate can be adjusted downward if
prevailing rates fall during a given initial period.
</P>
<P>
   Buyers using the Internet should keep in mind that what is
advertised might not be what is available when they call.
</P>
<P>
   ``Use the Net as a tool,'' Gumbinger said, ``but don't neglect
looking in your local marketplace.''
</P>
<P>
   HSH and other mortgage experts predict that rates will ease as
the year progresses, but they say there is still much uncertainty.
</P>
<P>
   Gumbinger sees some similarities with the situation in early
1994, when rates were hovering around 7 percent before the Federal
Reserve pushed them higher. By midyear, a 30-year mortgage was at
about 9.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of people got caught,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But he also sees some differences now, both in consumers and the
economy.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is certainly greater awareness of alternative
products,'' Gumbinger said. ``Consumer confidence is higher, and
there is less fear of higher interest rates.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
