<HEADER>
A7490 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RYAN-COLUMN-SUB-BOS &LR;      07-02 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RYAN-COLUMN-SUB-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FIELD OF DREAMS' ENABLES ABCD TO GRANT SOME WISHES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Corrects phone number in last graf)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Dow keeps floating way above 10,000. It's hard to get a
dinner reservation at your favorite chic South End restaurant. And
isn't it time to think about trading in that '97 sedan you're
driving for a gadget-laden SUV?
</P>
<P>
   These are not concerns for the clients of Action For Boston
Community Development, otherwise known as ABCD. The economy is
chugging away at a record rate, but a few people have been left
back at the station. They are honest and hard-working, but for one
reason or another no one has punched their ticket. And that's where
ABCD, America's oldest-running anti-poverty organization, has been
stepping in for more than three decades. From Head Start to Fuel
Assistance, to Elderly Assistance, to dozens of valuable programs,
ABCD tries to be there for forgotten Americans of all races.
</P>
<P>
   With government funding not as reliable as it once was, ABCD
needs fresh sources of income to service its constituency. The
group found one last year. It was entitled ``Field of Dreams,'' and
it was a huge success in every way. Thanks to the extraordinary
generosity of Red Sox CEO John Harrington, a long-time ABCD
supporter, Fenway Park was made available. A dozen corporations
brought teams to play in a round-robin softball tournament. It is a
very safe statement to say that a good time was had by all, so much
so that most of the people who put teams out there last year are
looking forward to Aug. 6, when ``Field of Dreams II'' will take
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had a blast,'' says David Newton, who played first base for
Prudential Securities. Newton, an industrial bond salesman, put his
team together by securing interested people from his best clients.
``My only problem was that we got beat early,'' he says. ``This
year we're coming back with a stronger team.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, competition. This supposedly benign affair does bring out
the Ty Cobb in the investment people, doctors, lawyers, and even
professional athletes (e.g. the Colorado Avalanche's Chris Drury,
who played for Preferred Temps) who will come together at Updike's
``lyric little bandbox of a ballpark'' five weeks hence.
</P>
<P>
   ``No question,'' says Newton. ``We had guys sliding headfirst
into home plate.''
</P>
<P>
   Just being on the field where Babe Ruth, Ted Williams, Yaz, and
Nomar have roamed brings out the little boy in just about
everybody. ``We had the feeling Fenway Park was ours,'' points out
Dr. George Thibault, the vice president of Clinical Affairs for
Partners Health Care, who proudly wore a number 6 last year in
honor of Stan Musial. ``It's a shrine to many of us who once
aspired to be ballplayers.'' This year's Partners team will be
co-captained by Dr. Denny Ausiello, the chief of medicine at
Massachusetts General Hospital, who caught for Harvard; and Dr. Pat
O'Gara, the director of clinical cardiology at Brigham and Women's
Hospital, who co-captained the Yale nine.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Thibault's team played in the first game last year shortly
after 8 a.m. ``It was a magical moment,'' he reports. ``It's one
thing to see the ballpark at night, but another to see it early in
the day.''
</P>
<P>
   A major event like this doesn't just happen. Start with the Red
Sox, of course. Then factor in the superb organizational skill of
the Massachusetts Sports Partnership and the tireless efforts of
Becky Collet, the manager of sports marketing at John Hancock. This
year's tri-chairmen are Lou Eisenberg of Cosgrove, Eisenberg and
Kiley; Fred Bertino of Hill, Holliday; and the ubiquitous John
Sasso of Advance Strategies.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to give the players and corporations more bang for
their playing buck, the format has been altered this year. Rather
than a round-robin tournament, each team will play one six-inning
game, which will result in everyone getting a couple of at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   Twins Enterprises will donate hats. JUGGS will provide two
softball pitching machines. Franklin will supply the softballs and
batting gloves. Aramark will provide a full menu at the concession
stand behind home plate. MASCO will take care of parking.
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox even go so far as to provide a complete Fenway Park
batting experience. As each man comes to the plate, his picture
will be posted on the big screen in center field. How's that for
goose bumps?
</P>
<P>
   ``For my anniversary,'' says Eisenberg, a stalwart ABCD
supporter, ``my wife gave me photos of me at third base, me at the
plate, and my photo up on the board. How about that?''
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the depth of someone's baseball interest, the day
can be a spiritual experience. Take, for example, Charlie Orcutt,
president of Preferred Temps. ``You get to warm up in the visiting
bullpen. I was thinking, `This is where Al Luplow made that
phenomenal catch off Dick Williams in '65,' '' he says. It is
almost a given that Orcutt is the single most passionate CEO who
will be fielding a team. He attended Dave Morehead's no-hitter, and
he insists when the game started on that September afternoon there
were no more than 1,700 people in attendance.
</P>
<P>
   There are other revelations in store. ``I learned that the
infield dirt isn't as soft as you might think,'' says Eisenberg.
``It's more like cinder.''
</P>
<P>
   But what makes it all work is the fact that the ultimate
beneficiary is ABCD. ``We feel very strongly about ABCD,'' says
John Hancock president David D'Allesandro, whose team will be back
for a second year. ``I'm not saying that universities, for example,
aren't worthy recipients of donations, but endowments are up
everywhere, whereas federal dollars are hard for someone like ABCD
to come by.
</P>
<P>
   ``And I've never been one who believes in just writing checks,''
D'Allesandro continues. ``That's why the `Field of Dreams' is so
good for us. I feel when you can get employees involved, everyone
benefits. I think the people who play will get a lot more out of it
knowing they are helping a great cause. We at John Hancock have
literally hundreds of people who would like to be stepping on that
grass.''
</P>
<P>
   Call 617 357-6000, ext. 238. Meghan Sayce might be able to help
your Fenway-worshipping employees step on that grass.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Bob Ryan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
