Knuckle-Dragging Mouth-Breathing Humps
</P>
<P>
   1. It's This or Field Hockey
</P>
<P>
   &UR; CITY STREETS &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, I was driving a car with New York plates in
San Francisco. I stopped for gas at a large self-service station on
one of the city's main streets. As I pulled up, I noticed a couple
of young men, not employed by the station, working as ``windshield
cleaners,'' as often seen on street corners in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Each man was busy wiping windshields, going right to work on
cars as they pulled in. One of them soon walked up to me but
instead of cleaning the windshield, he stood off a few feet in
front of my car. I was prepared to tell him I wasn't interested in
his ``services'' when he said, ``If the car has New York plates, we
always ask first.'' I said, ``No thanks,'' he nodded and said,
``Fine'' and went off to work on cars with California licenses. I
wonder what kind of New Yorker he met that made him decide it was
necessary to ask first!
</P>
<P>
   _DAVID B. GOLDENSON
</P>
<P>
   Alene Marx's 5-year-old granddaughter, Isabel Phemayotin,
complained to her mother that her almost 3-year-old sister had
called her ``stupid.'' Her mother explained that her younger sister
had probably heard the word from bigger children and very likely
didn't even know what it meant. ``Do  &UR; you &LR;  know what `stupid'
means?'' her mother asked Isabel. ``Oh yes,'' she replied. ``It
means that you are a really bad driver.''
</P>
<P>
   Over the last couple of years, two doves have made the adjoining
fire escapes of Robert Roth and Karen Ogulnick their breeding
ground. They come back periodically to lay their eggs, sit on their
nest and wait for their babies to hatch. Recently, Mr. Roth and Ms.
Ogulnick saw two men scraping away the rust on the fire escapes and
they also noticed that the nest had been abandoned except for one
egg. When the workers left, one of the birds returned to sit on the
egg. Two days later, when a newborn dove was in the nest, the
workers came back, this time to paint, and one of them mentioned
that the mother dove had been flying back and forth, looking at
them.
</P>
<P>
   The next day, the workers returned to put on a second coat of
paint. Mr. Roth and Ms. Ogulnick wondered if the baby dove could
survive all this and looked to see if there was any sign of life in
the nest. They were pleasantly surprised to find that the workers
had improvised a makeshift shelter _ a canopy made of cardboard,
wire and string that was protecting the dove from dripping paint.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Feinberg went to his health plan's Web site to look for a
participating dermatologist. That evening he told his wife, Toby,
that he had found some dermatologists in Manhattan with interesting
names. Had he found a listing for I.C.A. Rash, she asked in jest.
No, he said, but he did find a Dr. Leonard Bernstein, a Dr. Doris
Day and a Dr. Alan Greenspan.
</P>
<P>
   Skipp Porteous and his wife, Barbara Simon, were walking along
Ninth Avenue between 46th and 47th Streets one recent Saturday when
they noticed a letter carrier stop in front of a four-story
walk-up. The man honked a bicycle horn attached to his mail caddy
and then entered the building. Curious about the procedure, they
waited for him to emerge. He said his name was Al Gibson, that
elderly people lived in the building and that he always honked the
horn to let them know that their mail had arrived. It saved them
fruitless checking and difficult trips up and down the stairs.
</P>
<P>
   The young executive on a sidewalk on the Upper East Side was
speaking emphatically into his cell phone. Was it a critical moment
in an important deal? As Hattie Gottlieb Bradlow got closer, she
heard his end of the conversation: ``Listen to me now. You'd better
calm down or you're not going to get any ice cream for a very,
very, long time!''
</P>
<P>
   My husband and I had tickets to a concert at Carnegie Hall, but
he was unable to go. It was a cold night, and I shivered as I tried
to sell the ticket for the $20 it cost. With no takers, I offered
it to an elderly gentleman standing close to me for $15. He said,
no, too much money. A little later I asked whether he would pay
$10. The answer was still no.
</P>
<P>
   As the starting time drew near, I decided to give the old man
the ticket, went into the concert hall and took my seat. In a short
time, a huge young man sat down next to me. I asked if he would
mind telling me where he got his ticket. ``Not at all,'' he
replied. ``A little old man sold it to me for $20.''
</P>
<P>
   _Adele Shapiro
</P>
<P>
   It was a beautiful, sunny afternoon. There was a light breeze,
and the fountain at Lincoln Center sparkled. Three of us,
concertgoers, were enjoying the weather and the view when we were
approached by a man in jeans, carrying a camcorder. He handed us a
picture and explained that it was of his Aunt Lily and Uncle Tony
and that they were celebrating their 50th wedding anniversary. He
was photographing people around New York asking them to wish Lily
and Tony ``Happy Anniversary.'' We were happy to accommodate, held
the picture, waved and called ``Happy Anniversary, many more, good
luck, good health.'' The nephew thanked us, packed up his equipment
and went on to get further greetings. We felt we had contributed to
a New York moment and become an integral part of an interactive art
piece.
</P>
<P>
   _Vida Cohen
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUOTABLES FROM NBC'S `LATE NIGHT WITH CONAN O'BRIEN' &LR;
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the news that happened over the weekend: President
Clinton said that there is no truth to the rumor that Hillary is
going to leave the White House early and move to New York. The
President then said `But hey, I am keeping my fingers crossed.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to a new study, breast implants are not as dangerous
as once thought, but they are responsible for women suffering from
infection. They're also responsible for `Melrose' lasting eight
seasons.''
</P>
<P>
   ``A woman in California is trying to get a referendum on the
ballot that would make infidelity a crime. So far, she's gathered
three signatures.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The Royal Family didn't like the way that Prince William
looked in his uncle's wedding photos, so they had his face
digitally replaced with one where he's smiling. The picture looks
much better, because they also replaced the Queen's face with Ricky
Martin's.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Toys `R US is being criticized for selling children a talking
Austin Power's doll that asks `Do I make you horny?' Toys `R US
claims the doll only started saying that when it was placed on the
shelf next to the Tarzan doll.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In Belgium, Coca-Cola is recalling thousands of cans of their
soft drink because it was making people light headed and nauseous.
Not taking any chances, they've also recalled Michael Bolton.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yesterday, the man running Dan Quayle's campaign resigned
because he is involved in a love triangle. Apparently, when Quayle
found out about the love triangle, he wanted to know the names of
the four other people involved.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven Seagal announced that he's coming out with a solo
album. When asked about it, Seagal said `I want to show people that
I can do a lot more than just not act.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to the success of the Ricky Martin concert, on the `Today'
show, `Good Morning America' has announced that they're going to
air a live concert by Barry Manilow. It's all a part of their out
of touch with the rest of the world week.''
</P>
<P>
   ``According to a new study, once people are over the age of
thirty-five, they start dreaming more about retirement than they do
about sex. The study also says that if you're the president, you
dream about retiring so you can have more sex.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Political pollsters are now conducting polls on the Internet
instead of the traditional way, by telephone. Not only that,
pollsters also described the average voter as a fourteen-year-old
horny male.''
</P>
</TEXT>
