<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Saturday, July 3, 1999, sent to computer graphics clients of The
New York Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
(jt) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of potent thunderstorms will erupt across the upper
Middle West Saturday as very humid air surges northward across the
Plains. A system of storms will develop early Saturday across the
eastern Dakotas, southern Minnesota and northern Iowa as a
fast-moving stream of humid air from the south converges over the
region. Heavy rain and severe weather are possible. Rainfall
exceeding two inches is possible and large hail and winds gusting
to 60 miles an hour or more are also possible. Storms will rumble
into the western Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   Another cluster of heavy thunderstorms will develop later
Saturday across eastern Montana and the Dakotas. Severe weather is
possible, with tornadoes also posing a limited risk. Storms will
spread to Minnesota and the western Great Lakes.
</P>
<P>
   A volley of heavy thunderstorms will soak parts of Florida as
upper-level disturbances moving westward over the Atlantic combine
with developing sea-breeze fronts to lift very humid air. Isolated
thunderstorms will accompany the leading edge of the sea breeze
along the Gulf Seaboard from the upper Texas to the western Florida
coasts.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, clusters of heavy thunderstorms will erupt across
parts of the Ohio Valley and central Appalachians as very warm and
humid air interacts with a weak but efficacious disturbance moving
eastward from the Middle West. The Northeast Seaboard, after the
broken line of thunderstorms moved across the region Friday, will
be relatively rain-free, even though humidity will be moderate to
fairly high.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Focus: Rain-maker &LR;
</P>
<P>
   More than 25 inches of rain fell at the Coral Springs Aquatic
Complex in southeast Florida during June, the salient monthly total
in the water-logged region of the state. While rain from tropical
systems can enhance summer rains, there would be no definitive
rainy season in Florida without the faithful sea breeze. Because
the sun heats the sea and land unevenly, a sea breeze frequently
develops along Florida's Atlantic and Gulf Coasts. As it moves
inland, the leading edge of the sea breeze lifts steamy air over
land, often sparking thunderstorms that can make the rainy season
very rainy.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
