<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-JONES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PRESBYTERIANS DEBATE, BUT DON'T DECIDE, ROLE OF GAYS IN CHURCH
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM JONES 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Presbyterians meeting in Fort Worth had lunch at Billy Bob's,
billed as the world's largest honky-tonk. They had other surprises,
including a musical program at the new Bass Performance Hall and an
appearance by one of Cowtown's favorite sons, concert pianist Van
Cliburn.
</P>
<P>
   But there were no surprises when delegates to the Presbyterian
Church (U.S.A) General Assembly got down to business. Once again,
the role of gays in the church dominated their discussions.
</P>
<P>
   And they settled nothing. They rejected an attempt to remove
language from the church Book of Order banning gay ordinations. But
they also voted to study the matter and take it up again in 2001.
</P>
<P>
   ``We opted again for a cooling-off period,'' said the Rev.
Christopher Harris of Garden City, Mich.
</P>
<P>
   This year's assembly was marked by unusual consideration for
opposite points of view on gay issues. I watched those on both
sides arguing their views. Then they would join hands in a circle
to pray for God to give them the right decision.
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Goss, a youth delegate from Elmwood, N.J., emotionally
pleaded for inclusion of gays.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been black, or a woman, or homosexual, but I feel
their pain when they feel excluded from the real life of the
church,'' said Goss. ``I don't think anybody should have to feel
that pain.''
</P>
<P>
   But Marvin Donaldson of Warren, Ohio, declared: ``Should we
twist the truth to fit our own lifestyles?''
</P>
<P>
   Freda A. Gardner, a retired Princeton Seminary professor who was
named moderator, the church's highest elective office, praised the
way the gay issues were debated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we Presbyterians are trying harder than ever to live
together in our diversity,'' she said after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   Church spokesman Jerry Van Marter, who has attended 24 General
Assemblies, thinks he knows why delegates debating gay issues were
more conciliatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many realized for the first time that we could really split
over this, and it frightened them,'' Van Marter said.
</P>
<P>
   Gay advocates had urged deleting a church law adopted in 1996
that bans gay ordinations. It says ministers, elders and deacons
must live in ``fidelity within the covenant of marriage between a
man and a woman, or chastity in singleness.''
</P>
<P>
   Delegates voted to keep the gay ordination ban. But they asked
for creation of new materials on gay issues and for churches to
begin intense study of whether gays should be ordained. The matter
is to be taken up again two years from now.
</P>
<P>
   George Pepper of Fort Worth, an assembly observer, said he
wishes the denomination had settled the gay ordination question.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can delay, delay, delay, and you never resolve anything,''
said Pepper. He favors the right of local congregations to make the
decision on whether gays should be ordained.
</P>
<P>
   Gay rights activists were pleased by some developments.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Janie Spahr, a Presbyterian minister who is a lesbian,
was honored with a Women of Faith Award for her work with a
national ministry to gays and lesbians called ``That All May Freely
Serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Even though it was defeated on the convention floor, gay
advocates saw it as a small victory that the Committee on Church
Orders and Ministry voted 24-14 to recommend removal of the
``fidelity and chastity'' section prohibiting gay ordinations.
</P>
<P>
   Conservative Presbyterians believe the gay controversy finally
will be settled in their favor.
</P>
<P>
   ``For more than 20 years in a row we've supported language
prohibiting ordination of gays and lesbians, and we will continue
to do it,'' said the Rev. Carmen Fowler, pastor of the Rabun Gap
Presbyterian Church in Rabun Gap, Ga. She is a member of the
Presbyterian Coalition, a conservative organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a movement of people in the pews, and I think we stand
for what most people in the church stand for,'' Fowler said.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Marty, a renowned observer of American religion who spoke
at a breakfast during the convention, urged patience on gay issues.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes the church 250 years to settle anything,'' Marty
said, noting that in 1950 the meeting he was addressing would have
been all-male and all-clergy. He said people can't predict what the
church will be like in the 21st century.
</P>
<P>
   ``But a loving God is in control.''
</P>
<P>
   (Jim Jones is religion editor of the Fort Worth Star-Telegram.
You can call him at (817) 390-7707, or e-mail:
jimjones(at)star-telegram.com. Visit the Star-Telegram's online
services on the World Wide Web: www.star-telegram.com) nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1727EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0174 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 17:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7540 &Cx1f; taf-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-WEDDINGS-GAYS-$ADV04-     07-02 0808
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEDDINGS-GAYS-$ADV04-800(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AT A WEDDING, IT'S STILL NOT IN TO BE OUT 
FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4)
</HEADLINE>
 (af) 
By BOB MORRIS  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ So it's 1999 and you're gay. So what? Your boss is
gay. Ellen's gay. Will of ``Will and Grace'' is gay. Rupert
Everett, who is gay and played a gay man in ``My Best Friend's
Wedding,'' is now playing Mr. Right in ``An Ideal Husband.'' The
media understand you. Your neighbors do, too. So do your parents.
You're well integrated and well connected. In fact, without being
boring, you're as self-actualized as any post-modern urban gay
person can be.
</P>
<P>
   Then one day _  &UR; poof! &LR;  _ you're reduced to a quivering mass of
neuroses. You've been invited to a wedding. Not a commitment
ceremony for same-sex couples. But a straight wedding, where you're
seated with some pleasant, provincial people who want to know which
side _ bride or bridegroom? _ you're on, and then start asking your
partner question after question about what he's doing there until
they force him to declare, for all to hear, that he's not your
 &UR; business &LR;  partner.
</P>
<P>
   ``For gay people, weddings are always a reminder of being
outsiders,'' said Charles Silverstein, an Upper West Side
psychologist and the author of several books about homosexuality.
``Even when people are welcoming, as they usually are these days,
weddings can be extremely alienating experiences. They raise all
sorts of ambivalence and take on a meaning far greater than any
party ever should.''
</P>
<P>
   It seems more ironic than romantic that June, the month for
weddings, is also the month for gay pride. Nothing tests gay pride
more than straight weddings, many gay men and women say. For those
who live in any of the nation's ever-so-inclusive gay-friendly
cities, weddings provide that increasingly rare opportunity to feel
ashamed, or at least self-conscious.
</P>
<P>
   Marriage, of course _ from Romeo and Juliet, Henry VIII and the
Duke of Windsor to Dennis Rodman and Adam Sandler in ``The Wedding
Singer'' _ is a frequent source of trauma, and wedding anxiety is a
nondiscriminatory phenomenon that crosses religious and sexual
lines. But for gay men and women, the quintessential rite of
heterosexual life presents a unique set of anxieties.
</P>
<P>
   Kamal Ayyildiz, a Manhattan writer, was invited to be a member
of a wedding party by a bride he had known since the fifth grade,
but the bridegroom's parents were not happy when they learned he
was bringing his companion. At the rehearsal dinner at a country
club in Roanoke, Va., Ayyildiz said, he and his boyfriend were the
only two of the 40 guests not assigned seats. They ended up
circling around and around the room, to their mounting
embarrassment.
</P>
<P>
   ``It turned out that the groom's mother had panicked at the idea
of a gay couple and didn't have places for us,'' Ayyildiz said.
Eventually, the bride's parents offered seats at their table.
</P>
<P>
   Ayyildiz's experience was an exaggerated example of what most
gay people report at weddings, where brushes with overt homophobia
are rare; much more common are subtle, often unintended _ and
sometimes self-inflicted _ causes for uneasiness. ``When you're
around people who aren't around gay people that often,'' said
Steven Druckman, a freelance writer, ``you start watching
everything you're doing, even how you lean back in your chair and
put your arm around your boyfriend's shoulder.''
</P>
<P>
   Druckman and his partner are recuperating this weekend after an
entire month of weddings, where, he said, he endured more than a
few withering looks. ``Often one of the families doesn't want you
there, so you end up feeling like pariahs,'' he said. ``I wanted to
dance with my boyfriend, but he said he didn't think it was right.
You can't just assert yourself at such a large social gathering.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Ronald Hellman, an openly gay Manhattan psychiatrist, who
was united in a big family-oriented commitment ceremony last month
with his male lover, a Reform rabbi, could not quite work up the
nerve to dance at a straight wedding held the week before his.
``We're about as out as we can be, but we couldn't dance,'' Dr.
Hellman said. ``Dancing is very ritualistic, and it's very heavy.
You need to know you're in a safe gay space before you do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Brad Bessey thought he was safe when he was invited to walk a
bride down the aisle at a recent wedding. Then the bridegroom's
family objected because he was gay. So the bride decided to defuse
their anxiety by seating Bessey, a producer for ``Entertainment
Tonight,'' with her fiance's family at the rehearsal dinner. He
didn't flinch. Rather, he turned up the charm.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm at a wedding,'' he said, ``I will do everything in my
power to make sure that people feel good about each other.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In modern society, in fact, from Oscar Wilde to Isaac Mizrahi,
gay people have often developed senses of humor as defense
mechanisms, making them particularly entertaining as hosts and
guests. They are often called upon at weddings to serve as
toastmasters, or to offer last-minute style tips about the bride's
bouquet or the bridegroom's mother's shade of lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It always seems to be our job to loosen things up and provide
a spark,'' said Ted Kruckel, a press agent, who also believes that
gay men buy the best presents. ``Weddings are by their nature
staid. Gay people bring a sense of levity to the event because it's
so irrelevant to our lives. And of course, we're needed. I often
find myself being asked to make a toast that will be a nice tonic
to the tedium of the proceedings.''
</P>
<P>
   Wayne Nathan recalled working with the florist Robert Isabell on
the splashiest New York wedding of the late 1980s, that of Laura
Steinberg and Jonathan Tisch, in the Metropolitan Museum of Art.
</P>
<P>
   Gayfryd Steinberg called a week before her stepdaughter's
wedding to say it was ``too formal and stuffy,'' Nathan said. To
counteract the pomposity, he hired a Brazilian band on stilts and
booked a snow machine to blow white feathers around. ``That was my
great contribution as a gay man to New York culture,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan's sardonic tone is echoed by other gay men and women, who
say they are subtly irked by what they perceive as a double
standard: called upon to enliven the weddings of others, they are
legally forbidden, of course, from having weddings of their own.
Druckman, who is getting back in the saddle for another wedding
next weekend, said that as much as he hates the affairs, he
wouldn't mind having one of his own if they become legal. ``That
way, I can get my own blender,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   When her brother announced that he was getting married, Ann
Northrup felt a little resentful as well. ``There I was in a
relationship for 15 years, and my brother was telling me that there
are so many economic advantages to marriage that it seemed like the
smartest thing to do,'' said Ms. Northrup, an Act Up member and a
host of a cable show called ``Gay U.S.A.'' ``I cursed him out, and
he ended up apologizing for the next 20 minutes.'' At his wedding
reception, she made a toast that got her a laugh. ``I announced
that my brother and I shared the same taste in women,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The playwright Jon Robin Baitz, meanwhile, recalls being in the
middle of a toast at his brother's wedding, when he noticed that he
was speaking to a sea of frozen faces. ``I was joking about
maturity and commitment,'' said Baitz, who has been in a gay
relationship for many years. ``I thought I was just being honest.
But I guess I didn't realize that I was talking about love in a
cynical way that was very gay and inappropriate. I often end up
feeling like I've stubbed my toe at weddings.''
</P>
<P>
   Many gay people feel uneasy when they are not invited to take a
companion to weddings. One New Yorker has been invited to a wedding
this month by a woman he has known for years. But the bridegroom's
family is pressuring the bride to discourage him from bringing
anyone with him. ``I completely want to participate in her
wedding,'' he said. ``But all my other friends have been invited to
bring a guest. You don't want to make a fuss when people are
already stressed out to the extreme with family politics at a
wedding. But I really don't want to go alone. I guess the book of
etiquette hasn't been written for people like us.''
</P>
<P>
   Ann Landers may not be able to give gay marriage her full
support (``It flies in the face of cultural and traditional family
life as we have known it for centuries,'' she has written). But
salespeople at Tiffany's, Macy's and Barneys are doing everything
they can short of breaking into song to make gay people feel good
about registering for commitment ceremonies. Barneys even has a
form to fill out that doesn't use the words bride and bridegroom,
but rather partner and partner. There's a new book called ``The
Essential Guide to Lesbian and Gay Weddings.'' There are clergy
members who will officiate (although not necessarily in an official
capacity) and a vast segment of society that is looking for ways to
open up to same-sex couples and wish them well. Still, many gay
people aren't interested in aping the ceremony and social
institution of marriage until it becomes legally binding.
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately, for all their resentment and paranoia (not always
justified), many gay people know that weddings are a trial that
everyone must bear, gay and straight. Dan Savage, who writes a
syndicated advice column, ``Savage Love,'' gets lots of letters
about weddings. ``They've become so institutionalized that they're
hollow and empty and depressing for everyone,'' he said, ``and not
just for the gay people who feel slighted because they can't have
their own legal wedding that's hollow and empty and depressing,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Savage went to the wedding of his boyfriend's
fundamentalist Christian brother in Spokane, Wash. He arrived ready
to explode at the slightest offense, and ended up feeling, in
addition to bored, welcome and at ease. ``These days, tolerance is
the norm,'' said Savage, who chronicled his experience for Out
magazine. ``So spending all your time at a wedding trying to figure
out who really likes you and who doesn't is exhausting and
paranoid. I think that in the absence of the real tolerance we hope
to find, the appearance of tolerance can be just as good.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcy Blum, a well-known wedding planner, agrees. ``If gay
people are acting paranoid or unhappy at weddings,'' said Ms. Blum,
who often finds them acting otherwise, ``it doesn't help an already
tense situation.'' While she says she has never seen any homophobia
at the weddings she has planned, Ms. Blum has seen lots of
bridesmaids who look as if they were ready to kill or die, often
both.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, it's not easy being a gay person in a straight world,''
said Ms. Blum, who is 45 and divorced. ``But it's not easy being a
single woman, either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
