<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INVEST-INSIGHT-Q&AMP;A-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKHORSE UTILITIES GET ANOTHER LOOK  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By KENNETH N. GILPIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The world is often a strange place, but the marketplace is
supposed to be rational.
</P>
<P>
   Consider, then, the counterintuitive move in utility stocks,
which because of their high dividend yields and low growth rates
are often seen as bonds dressed up as equities.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last few months, bond prices have fallen like a stone,
and interest rates have shot up. Yet, since the end of March, the
Standard &AMP; Poor's Utilities index has risen by 12.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   On its face, that sort of move doesn't make a lot of sense.
Rising interest rates should make bonds more competitive with
utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Are utilities still a good proxy for bonds? What is going on in
this $300 billion industry? Steven I. Flieshman, an electric
utility analyst at Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co., took some time last week to
discuss these and other issues. Here are some excerpts: &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Isn't it unusual for utility stocks to do well in a
period of rising interest rates?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Well, the group as a whole is still down for the year, so
it's not like we are doing great. And until two or three months
ago, the electric utility index had acted pretty much in tandem
with the bond market.
</P>
<P>
   We were somewhat surprised that happened because deregulation is
changing the industry and fewer companies are paying high
dividends. So I am not surprised there has been some delinkage. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Is that to say there are no ties between utilities
and bonds?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Utility stocks can often be a leading indicator of where the
bond market will go.
</P>
<P>
   We look at the spread between the 30-year Treasury bond yield
and the 55 utility stocks we follow. Historically, that spread has
averaged between 50 basis points and 60 basis points. Currently,
the spread is about 130 basis points, which is as high as it has
been since late 1994. So you could speculate that bond yields may
have risen too much. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Market rates have been rising because of
expectations that the Federal Reserve is going to raise short-term
rates. Why are rising rates good for utility stocks?(end italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. As a group, since the mid-1980s, utilities tend to perform
worst after periods when the Fed eases rates and best in the months
ahead of Fed tightenings.
</P>
<P>
   That's because, as the Fed starts to tighten, the desired
outcome is to slow the economy, which makes growth sectors like
technology less attractive.
</P>
<P>
   Also, in times of higher interest rates, it is better to own
shorter-duration securities than longer-duration ones. In that
environment, higher-yielding utilities are a better performing
asset than a growth stock. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Speaking of growth, hasn't deregulation prompted a
number of utilities to look beyond their original markets?(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The industry is splitting.
</P>
<P>
   Some companies are exiting the power generation part of the
business, which is the part that is turning very competitive, and
are just focusing on distribution, which remains regulated.
</P>
<P>
   The distribution companies are lower-risk, and more predictable.
Consolidated Edison is a company that sold off most of its power
generation and is focusing on distribution. It is one of the few
big companies that is going in that direction, and it is a pretty
low-risk, unsexy sort of investment.
</P>
<P>
   The second group is focusing on the competitive power generation
and related businesses, like marketing the power to both the
wholesale and retail buyer. The focus of these companies is clearly
to boost their growth rates. The split between these two groups has
accelerated over the last year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Are there stocks you like in both camps?(end
italics) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. On the growth side, we like companies like Duke Energy, Peco
Energy and Texas Utilities. Part of the Peco and Texas Utilities
stories is restructuring, which is happening as deregulation occurs
in their states. My price target for Duke is the mid-60s, and the
low 50s for Texas Utilities. (The stocks closed on Friday at
$55.4375 and $42.4375, respectively.)
</P>
<P>
   On the distribution side, Sierra Pacific Resources and Nevada
Power are merging, a deal which should close in late July. Because
they are in the nation's highest customer-growth state in terms of
electricity sales, they are good bets.
</P>
<P>
   Another category we are looking at is telecommunications. A lot
of utilities had fiber in the ground themselves, and many have
rights of way that allow them to put it in the ground. They are not
huge competitors to the regional Bells, but, over time, if the
values of the telecommunication franchise don't get brought out in
the price of the utility stock, these telecom properties will be
spun out.
</P>
<P>
   The big story in this area is Montana Power, whose stock price
has about tripled. But I rate it ``accumulate'' with a price target
of $80. A stock we still like is Conectiv Inc., with a target of
$29. (Montana Power and Conectiv closed on Friday at $70 and
$25.1875, respectively.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
