<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NYHAN-COLUMN-$ADV04-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS IT ABOUT PROSPERITY AMERICANS CAN'T SEEM TO LOVE? 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 04, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID NYHAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Our lovely, rambunctious country on this, her birthday, has
never been better off when it comes to our prosperity, standing in
the world, military might, cultural influence (OK, for good or for
bad), public health and life expectancy, and a dozen other measures
you could think of.
</P>
<P>
   But in the heart, the soul or the gut, depending on where you
locate any kind of national sense of emotional well-being, our
dread notion of something missing looms large. It's not just
because the Republicans hate Bill Clinton and blame him for
everything from corn blight to halitosis. And it's not just because
the various news media make their money by encouraging audiences to
cringe on a daily or hourly basis.
</P>
<P>
   Uncle Sam, it appears, is having a senior moment, a bit of a
bout of self-doubt. The old guy is dwelling more on what he doesn't
have than what he has. Maybe you could call it a revolution of
risen expectations. We're the richest, the most powerful, the
least-threatened people in history. Our economy market is the envy
of the world. The stock market, now more Main St. than Wall St., is
in nose-bleed territory.
</P>
<P>
   We just won a war where, for the most altruistic of reasons _
stopping mass murder, rape and pillage of Hitlerian scale, in a
remote land that could do us not one bit of good _ and we did it in
total synch with civilized Europe, and, remarkably, with not one
combat casualty.
</P>
<P>
   If you had dared forecast eight years ago that on the eve of the
millenium, the economy would be booming, home ownership at record
levels, inflation barely flickering, the Dow over 11,000, Europe in
the palm of our hand, all the Asian economies taking their cue from
us, and no other nation in any kind of position to do us anything
in the way of serious harm, you'd have been mocked. No one would
have believed it possible.
</P>
<P>
   The federal budget in balance? A monstrous federal surplus
piling up, just begging to be divvied up? A national anti-smoking
crusade that is saving thousands of lives annually? A head start on
curbing the curse of indiscriminate gun availability? A genuine
economic revolution _ the Internet _ that promises to put more
power, choice and efficiency in the hands of the common citizen?
All this and more, but no balm for the soul.
</P>
<P>
   Like spoiled children, egocentric kids who always got what they
whined for, we grump about whatever we feel like grumping about.
This manifests itself most commonly _ that is to say with
mind-numbing regularity _ when any Republican strays within
shouting distance of a cable television sound boom. The rude
reception given victorious Gen. Wesley Clark by Republican senators
cheap-shotting our Kosovo victory shows just how petty Washington
is now.
</P>
<P>
   Surely there are no sentient beings left in America who are not
thoroughly familiar with the sins, mortal or venial, of omission or
comission, of Senor Clinton. But just as surely, the dire
predictions of his enemies have fallen woefully wide of the mark.
</P>
<P>
   The Republican consensus in Congress was that Clinton would:
wreck the economy; destroy the military; alienate our allies; be
too tough, not tough enough, or weathervane-ish in handling Russia,
China, Japan, Mexico, Canada, you-fill-in-the-blank. In fact,
Clinton's biggest problem came from trying to weasel out of a
tawdry romantic liason with a young woman of colossal ditziness. Of
course, he should have known better. It reminds us that in
politics, as in life, the most painful and regrettable wounds are
those that are self-inflicted.
</P>
<P>
   It is the wounds our country inflicts on itself that are most
painful. Battlin' Billy C. is the Olympic champion of
self-inflicted wounds. He wins, hands down. But President Pinocchio
soldiers on. Left for dead a dozen times in his reign, he proved
anew in Kosovo he's still the most important player, period.
</P>
<P>
   But falling on one's own sword is not Clinton monopoly. Exhibit
B has to be Kenneth Starr, the independent counsel whose rampage so
disheartened everyone that his job classification is being
obliterated. Exhibit C in the Hall of Self-Inflicted Wounds has to
be the Republican leadership in DC. Those Krazy Kops in Kongress
have lost one House speaker (Newt Whatsisname), a second was
defenestrated before seizing the gavel (Dr. Bob Livingston, I no
longer presume), and the third should have his mug on a milk
carton, he's been missing in action so long (Dennis Hastert, if
you're keeping score).
</P>
<P>
   Exhibit D would be the news media, collectively, for constantly
performing worse than the public expects us to. TV ratings are
down, newspaper circulation is going the wrong way, and our
collective product has been trivialized, dumbed-down and cheapened.
But for every seller there has to be a buyer, and therefore I
annoint the news-consuming public as Exhibit E in the Dept. of
Self-inflicted Impairment.
</P>
<P>
   So vast is the catalogue of self-inflicted wounds as our dear
old land treads millenium-ward that it makes no sense to keep
going. But there is a final point: it's what happens after the
self-inflicted wound that matters.
</P>
<P>
   In this category, Clinton is a master. We know a lot less about
the ability of his putative successors in this realm. George W.
Bush is the man of the moment. The Texas governor's harvest of $36
million in campaign loot over just six months marks him as the GOP
Golden Boy. But we've yet to see how he handles himself in the
clinches.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's success in shaking down the plums from the money tree is
so great, I say he should skip the election and go straight to Mt.
Rushmore. But nobody gets that kind of free ride. Why the
Republicans expect Bush to escape the sort of media acid that
bathed Clinton is beyond rational explanation. Do they think it
only rains on the other guy?
</P>
<P>
   Overcoming unexpected setbacks is what separates the survivor
from the roadkill. Bill Clinton, for all his sins, is a survivor.
George Bush has not been tested. If he's only half as good as
Clinton in the survival game, that would probably be good enough.
Same for Al Gore, or any of the rest of them.
</P>
<P>
   The eventual winner will be the one who figures out how to lead
a country that doesn't want to be led. There are a dozen
Republicans running on variations of the
boy-is-this-country-in-bad-shape theme. The America my father grew
up in couldn't stand Depression. My America seems to find
prosperity intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Nyhan is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1738EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0179 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 17:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7551 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SUESS-POLITICS-NYT &LR;      07-02 0679
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SUESS-POLITICS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OH, THE PLACES HE WENT! WHEN DR. SUESS TOOK HIS WHIMSY TO WAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(jt) 
 By JONATHAN ROSEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a world that still reverberates with the conflicts of World
War II, it isn't really surprising to learn that Dr. Seuss, beloved
creator of ``Hop on Pop'' and ``Horton Hears a Who,'' sharpened his
artistic skills drawing political cartoons of Hitler and Mussolini.
Nevertheless, it is fascinating to realize that the shadow of
fascism lurks beneath the shell of Yertle the Turtle and that Uncle
Sam is a distant antecedent of the Cat in the Hat. Whether these
discoveries say something about the seriousness of Dr. Seuss or the
cartoonish nature of American culture is another question.
</P>
<P>
   Born Theodor Seuss Geisel in 1904, the author was in midcareer
when World War II came along. He had published his first children's
book, ``And to Think That I Saw It on Mulberry Street,'' in 1937,
but that book, which had been rejected by 27 publishers, was only
modestly received, as were several others that followed.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Seuss was far better known in those days as an illustrator
of Flit bug spray advertisements. His years creating cheerful
depictions of insect extermination, combined with the sensibility
of a children's author, served him well when he turned his
attention in 1941 to political cartoons for the newspaper PM. Now,
for the first time, these cartoons are to appear in one volume,
``Dr. Seuss Goes to War,'' a book published by The New Press and
edited by Richard H. Minear that should be in stores in September.
</P>
<P>
   An innovative left-wing tabloid that accepted no advertisements
(which helps explain why it folded after eight years), PM
flourished briefly in a New York newspaper culture that boasted
seven dailies. Geisel brought himself to the editors' attention
with an unsolicited cartoon attacking Virginio Gayda, the Fascist
editor of Il Giornale d'Italia. Soon Geisel was a PM regular,
zipping off hundreds of cartoons from 1941 to 1943 condemning U.S.
isolationism, appeasement, anti-Semitism and racism; attacking the
Rev. Charles E. Coughlin as anti-Semitic and Charles A. Lindbergh
as pro-Nazi, and, most of all, urging that the United States enter
the war. (Dr. Seuss' liberalism did not save him from falling into
occasional ethnic generalizations, like depicting
Japanese-Americans as an ``honorable fifth column.'')
</P>
<P>
   These cartoons bear the unmistakable stamp of Dr. Seuss' zany
style, a hyperanimated world where animals and people seem
interchangeable and quaint complex machines (like a pedal-operated
tank for Mussolini) roll comically along. There is, as in his
children's books, a pervasive geniality, a sense of whimsy, a
feeling that Norman Rockwell characters have fallen through the
looking glass, but no farther.
</P>
<P>
   This is not the dark side of Dr. Seuss. In a cartoon dated Dec.
9, 1941, titled ``The End of the Nap,'' a beleaguered American
eagle in an Uncle Sam hat is rudely awakened by tiny, identical
Japanese soldiers variously shooting a slingshot, wielding a
mallet, giving Uncle Sam a hotfoot. They all look like naughty boys
in need of a spanking _ this, two days after some 2,300 Americans
died at Pearl Harbor. But of course stark depictions of treachery
are not always useful in getting men to enlist.
</P>
<P>
   All four of Geisel's grandparents emigrated from Germany in the
19th century, and he grew up in Springfield, Mass., far from the
world of Grimm's fairy tales, in which children push old crones
into ovens and there's a wolf in grandma's bed. For all their
outrage and urgency and honest indignation, Dr. Seuss' political
cartoons often display an American ease, a calm conviction that the
war will be won, that goodness will triumph and that disorder, like
the mess the Cat in the Hat makes, will eventually be cleaned up.
They're a useful reminder of how necessary childish fantasies
really are.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1744EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0180 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 17:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7553 &Cx1f; var-z
u v &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      07-02 1000
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, July 4, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   MEDICARE-CLINTON-REVIEW (Washington) _ President Clinton's new
Medicare proposal seemed to be something more than another
ritualistic exercise in policy-making by a waning administration.
It seemed, instead, to be one last attempt to come to grips with a
nation's conflicted, contradictory needs and desires on the shape
of its health care system _ and an acknowledgment of recent
history's painful lessons. In fact, many of the tensions and
faultlines that have marked one of the main political conflicts of
the 1990s, the battle over health care, were present. By Robin
Toner. (`a' category)
</P>
<P>
   BRAZIL-SOCCER-REVIEW (Rio de Janeiro) _ Soccer may be the king
of sports here, but only the men's version of the game seems to
wear the crown. Not one of this year's matches of the Brazilian
national women's team has been televised live, sponsors have shied
away from any association with them, and hard-core fans who can
recite the entire roster of the 1950 men's World Cup squad are hard
pressed to name even one player on the current women's team. By
Larry Rohter. (`i' category)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   DEBT-REVIEW (Washington) _ In announcing that the federal budget
surplus would be even more than anticipated, President Clinton
likened the government to a profligate consumer suddenly endowed
with the means and discipline to get out of debt and save for the
future. The actual American consumer, however, is not nearly so
fiscally virtuous. Minutes before Clinton's announcement, the
Commerce Dept. released data showing that consumers are headed in
the other direction by spending more money than they earn. By
Richard W. Stevenson.
</P>
<P>
   MOTHERS-POLITICS-REVIEW (Washington) _ Democrats are
increasingly portraying health care, gun control and drug abuse as
women's issues on the grounds that mothers worry about their
children. This represents a peculiar paradox: The party that fought
hard to make sure women were not defined simply as the bearers and
rearers of children is now casting women in those terms, or at
least appealing to their maternal instincts along those lines. By
Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET-HEALTH-REVIEW (Washington) _ At a time when managed
care has put greater distance between doctors and their patients,
the Internet is filling the gaps. Millions of Americans are going
online for medical information, mostly about specific diseases and
drugs, fueling a free-for-all on the Web, where thousands of sites
are offering some type of health information. Investment money is
pouring in. By Sheryl Gay Stolberg.
</P>
<P>
   BALLPARKS-REVIEW (Undated) _ A look at the ongoing demise of old
baseball stadiums and the advent of new ones. Ballparks don't evoke
the same wistful nostalgia as they did a generation or two ago.
Mention the demolition of Ebbets Field in 1960 and many
Brooklynites still weep. But with five new major league stadiums
set to sprout up around the U.S. in the next 12 months,
sentimentality has been put on waivers. By Alan Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-FUNDRAISING-REVIEW (Undated) _ Even though he has done it
faster than anyone else, George W. Bush is not the first Texan to
raise several gazillion dollars to run for president. He is the
seventh. But money doesn't always buy the White House _ of the
seven Texans, only Lyndon Johnson in 1964 and George Bush in 1988
actually won presidential elections. By Adam Clymer. (NOTE: story
is tentative and may be held or recast with broader focus)
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week, leading
with the Honduras teen's hoax and Russia's alcohol-related
drownings.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-EVIDENCE-REVIEW (Djakovica, Yugoslavia) _ Kosovo is a
huge crime scene, and the evidence seems obvious. But meeting the
exacting standards of a court of law _ even an international
tribunal _ is a different matter. There are still specific criminal
acts to be proved and a chain of evidence to be established before
Yugoslav leaders can be held to account. And there are cold scenes
_ bodies burned, deteriorated, buried or in some instances even
stolen by departing Serbs. The sites themselves have been open to
the elements, sometimes for more than two months. By John Kifner.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-DECOYS-REVIEW (Washington) _ A major surprise of the NATO
air campaign against Yugoslavia Serbia was the extent to which the
Yugoslav military was able to successfully use ground decoys such
as fake tanks to cause NATO to strike targets that weren't real. By
Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   TURKEY-KURDS-REVIEW _ A solution for Turkey's tensions with the
Kurds may seem obvious: reach an accommodation, as done in Northern
Ireland, the Israeli-Palestinian conflict and elsewhere. But for
centuries, Turkey's territory has been steadily shrinking. Fear of
losing more worries many Turks, and when they hear Kurds demand
autonomy or cultural rights, they sense the start of secession. By
Stephen Kinzer.
</P>
<P>
   NAZI-LAWS-TEXT-REVIEW (Undated) _ The Nuremburg Laws of Hitler's
Germany rank among the most chilling documents of the 20th Century:
They helped set the Holocaust in motion by legally excluding Jews
from German life. But until the opening last week of an exhibit at
the Jewish-oriented Skirball Cultural Center in Los Angeles, they
had never been put on public display. Some excerpts.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
