<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 17:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7556 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-MANAGERS-ART-     07-02 1085
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-MANAGERS-ART-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE SMOKESTACKS ARE BACK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Pa., Texas, Conn.)   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4)  
 (af)  
 By CAROLE GOULD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   An oil driller, a maker of industrial cutting tools, an
acquisition steel producer and a paper company. Those were the
kinds of blue-collar stocks that fueled returns of the
top-performing mutual funds in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Such value stocks, as well as small-capitalization issues, came
roaring back during the spring, shoving aside the large-company
growth stocks that had dominated the market for so long.
</P>
<P>
   The managers of three of the top-performing funds talked about
the quarter just ended and looked ahead to the rest of the year. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``After a year of emphasis on growth and large-cap companies,
when investors were not at all interested in value or small-cap
companies, valuations simply reached the extremes,'' said Dennis
Delafield, 63, co-manager of the $102.1 million Delafield fund with
Vincent Sellecchia, 47. Delafield, which owns small- to mid-cap
value stocks, was the No. 15 performing United States diversified
stock fund for the quarter, up 28 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors might not care about the companies we own, but
industrialists do,'' he said. ``They look at companies with free
cash flow and modest valuations, and they acquire or invest in
those companies. And that's what happened.''
</P>
<P>
   Delafield made money when Getronics, a Dutch company, acquired
Wang Laboratories, in which he owned shares. The company, based in
Billerica, Mass., was known for word-processing systems but now
services desktop computer systems and networks. Getronics bought 91
percent of the company in mid-June for $29.25 a share, a 50 percent
premium to its price at the start of the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Another winner was Kennametal, a Latrobe, Pa., maker of
industrial cutting tools. Its earnings for the fiscal year ended in
June 1998 were depressed because of a troublesome acquisition and
the market's general disregard for such stocks last year, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The stock has rebounded 76 percent since March as a cost-cutting
program began to bear fruit and the company named a new chief
executive.
</P>
<P>
   Delafield is now looking for clues to the direction of the world
economy. ``What happens the rest of the year depends on what
happens in Europe and to interest rates,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``The market is going through a rotational correction,'' said
Jim Crabbe, 54, co-manager of the $98.7 million Liberty-Crabbe
Huson Special fund with John Johnson, 62. The fund, a small-cap
blend fund, returned 29.6 percent in the quarter, for ninth place
among domestic diversified equity funds. ``Some parts of the market
are still very overpriced, but there are some tremendously good
bargains, particularly among smaller companies,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fund's performance surge stands in stark contrast to its
five-year return through June 30 _ negative 1.08 percent,
annualized. The fund had been hurt severely because it shorted big
stocks; it stopped doing so about a year ago, but that didn't solve
the fund's problems. Last year, he said, ``we owned a lot of
economically sensitive stocks, and we got our clocks cleaned.''
</P>
<P>
   Among Crabbe's biggest recent winners was Marine Drilling, a
Houston company that performs offshore drilling for the oil and gas
industry. The company's share price plummeted when oil stocks were
pounded at the end of last year. But that changed this spring.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a cutback in drilling for quite some time,'' he
said, ``but as people saw the price of gas increasing, they
anticipated the company would start drilling again.'' The stock
gained 24 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Another successes for the fund was Ispat International, a Dutch
steel producer, up 56 percent. Ispat bought Inland Steel, the
American steel company, in the spring of 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Crabbe expects the stock market's gains to continue broadening,
reaching more small stocks. And the economy, he said should keep
growing. ``There doesn't seem much danger that it won't continue
plugging along at a pretty rate,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   --- &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Investor optimism about the world economy was a big factor in
fund performance for the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors started becoming more aware that the U.S. economy
was very strong and that world economies, especially Asia, were
flat to getting better,'' said Robert J. Martorelli, who runs the
$547.2 million Merrill Lynch Phoenix fund, a mid-cap blend fund
that took the No. 12 place among domestic diversified equity funds,
returning 29.1 percent. ``In that kind of environment, cyclical
companies tend to perform well.''
</P>
<P>
   Martorelli, 42, said he was buying oil and gas and other
cyclical stocks at the end of 1998 and early 1999 ``because that's
where the value was.''
</P>
<P>
   Among his biggest winners was the LTX Corp., of Westwood, Mass.,
a maker of equipment for the semiconductor industry. LTX
experienced slackening demand during the economic debacle in Asia
last fall, but its stock rebounded as Asian economies stabilized,
Martorelli said.
</P>
<P>
   He added that he liked LTX because demand for its new type of
chip-testing device was growing rapidly along with the market for
multifunctional chips used in increasing numbers of products. The
stock rose 177 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Another success was Champion International, the paper company
based in Stamford, Conn. Martorelli said he bought the stock in
March because it was selling for the biggest discount to asset
value among companies in its industry. Nothing happened in company
operations to cause the subsequent rise in the stock price, he
said, but investors thought paper prices had bottomed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Champion has a lot of earnings leverage, so a relatively small
gain in paper prices produces incrementally larger gains in
earnings,'' he said. Champion shares rose 17 percent in the
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Martorelli expects value stocks to continue climbing as the
economy keeps growing. ``Strong economic expansion takes the
cyclical risk out of our stocks, so investors can look at paper,
chemical and steel companies and know that the demand for the
products will be there,'' he said. ``Besides, relative to the
growth stocks that we had to watch grow endlessly over the last
three to four years, these stocks are just cheap.''
</P>
</TEXT>
