<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 17:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7557 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYT     07-02 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOUTHERN-EXPOSURE-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PARTIES PLOW INTO FIGHT OVER FARMERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CARL HULSE and SEAN LOUGHLIN   
 N.Y. Times Regional Newspaper Group   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Democrats and Republicans are in a political range
war over which party is the true friend of the nation's rural
communities.
</P>
<P>
   Capitalizing on a top Democrat's ill-advised comment that his
party was writing off rural America in the 2000 elections,
Republicans have plowed into the opposition.
</P>
<P>
   They have gleefully noted that the ``writing-off'' remark was
made by Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., while his father, Sen. Edward
Kennedy, D-Mass., was busy filibustering the farm spending bill in
the Senate over an unrelated health care issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``The farming community in America is hurting,'' said Sen. Jeff
Sessions, R-Ala., at a GOP rally staged in front of gleaming farm
equipment. ``And when they find out that Patrick Kennedy has
written off rural American and Ted Kennedy is attempting to block
the passage _ through a hostage procedure _ of a legitimate and
effective farm bill, I think they are going to be even more
angry.''
</P>
<P>
   A Democratic spokesman said the comment by the younger Kennedy,
who chairs the party's House campaign committee, was made in the
context of gun control. He quickly retracted it, but the damage was
done.
</P>
<P>
   In response to the GOP assault, farm-state Democrats complain
that Republican critics wouldn't know a ``corn cob from a corn
dog'' and that the GOP has been behind hefty cuts in farm programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``In 1996, House Republicans voted for the original Freedom to
Farm Act, which eliminated the safety net that protects farmers
when prices collapse,'' said the House Democratic organization in a
position paper. ``Today, with commodity prices at record low
levels, farmers have come to deride the GOP plan as the `Freedom to
Fail Act.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In some respects, the evolving fight is as much about image as
it is congressional races since farmers don't have the numbers to
swing all that many elections. Yet both parties are eager to be
tied to the values many Americans still associate with small-town
life.
</P>
<P>
   YOU SHOULDN'T HAVE
</P>
<P>
   This is one honor that Sen. Fritz Hollings, D-S.C., could have
done without.
</P>
<P>
   Public Campaign, a watchdog group devoted to reforming campaign
finance laws, recently award Hollings its annual Golden Leash
award, which symbolizes captivity to special interests, for his
support of a banking overhaul the group says would hurt consumers.
</P>
<P>
   Ellen Miller, the group's director, suggested Hollings supported
the Financial Modernization Act of 1999 because of roughly $250,000
in campaign contributions the banking industry gave his Senate
campaign last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What else would explain his puzzling anti-consumer position on
this important bill from a senator who has a long history of
pro-consumer stands?'' Miller asked.
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for Hollings dismissed the award as meaningless,
noting that the senator was honored last year as a ``hero'' by the
Consumer Federation of America. Spokesman Maury Lane said Public
Campaign should focus on the problem of gimmicky budget practices
instead.
</P>
<P>
   PRAYER AND POLITICS I
</P>
<P>
   Hoping to reassert itself in the political arena, the Christian
Coalition kicks off a massive voter registration drive this holiday
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The religious right group, founded by Pat Robertson, wants to
register 1 million conservative voters by the November 2000
election. The campaign will focus on thousands of churches across
the country.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pro-family voters will be the crucial swing voters in the
upcoming election,'' Robertson said.
</P>
<P>
   That may be wishful thinking. The Christian Coalition has
watched its fund- raising efforts falter and has struggled with
some key staff departures in recent years. At the same time, the
group recently lost a battle with the Internal Revenue Service over
its disputed claim that it is a nonpartisan group entitled to
tax-free status. The coalition has long supported Republican
candidates, a fact that seems unlikely to change.
</P>
<P>
   PRAYER AND POLITICS II
</P>
<P>
   Following up on their endorsement of the Ten Commandments, House
Republicans tried to push a bill through Congress calling for a
national day of ``prayer, fasting and humiliation before God.''
</P>
<P>
   Although the measure won a majority of votes, it failed to
garner the two-thirds margin needed for passage under the special
rules governing the resolution.
</P>
<P>
   The measure won 275 votes with 140 opposed and 11 voting
present. Several Southern Democrats were among those who voted
present.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Eva Clayton, D-N.C., said her present vote indicated her
support for the idea of prayer in general, but also reflected her
unease with the idea of government-sanctioned prayer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we have a right to tell people how or when to
worship,'' Clayton said.
</P>
<P>
   (Compiled from reports by Sean Loughlin and Carl Hulse in the
Washington Bureau of the New York Times Regional Newspaper Group.
This article was distributed by The N.Y. Times News Service.)
</P>
</TEXT>
