<SLUG> BC-GRIMES-HUMOR-COLUMN-$ADV05-NYTR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AD SLOGANS CAN BE DANGEROUS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Monday, July 5)  
(mk) 
 By DAVID GRIMES   
 Sarasota (Fla.) Herald-Tribune   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   While recent news stories may suggest otherwise, guns are really
quite safe.
</P>
<P>
   At least that's the message (I think) in the ad campaign of the
National Shooting Sports Foundation, which is trying to get
Americans to think of guns as sporting equipment rather than
murderous weapons that were used to kill 10,744 Americans in 1996,
4,643 of whom were children or teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   In an article in the Wall Street Journal, Doug Painter of the ad
firm Porter Novelli suggested that the whole gun control
controversy really boils down to an image problem. (How many tragic
stories have we read in the newspaper of a child being rushed to
the emergency room with a 9-mm image lodged in his chest?)
</P>
<P>
   For many urban Americans, says Painter, guns are associated with
``crime and violence as opposed to hunting and skeet shooting.''
</P>
<P>
   Painter, unfortunately, does not explain why so many urban
Americans deliberately overlook their many fine hunting and
skeet-shooting opportunities. Perhaps they are too busy playing
cricket and polo or ironing their whites for their next croquet
tournament. Either way, it is clearly a matter in need of further
study, financed, of course, by a nice, fat federal grant.
</P>
<P>
   To correct this shocking display of ignorance on the part of
urban Americans, the NSSF has come up with a thrillingly original
ad to explain why guns are safe when used properly.
</P>
<P>
   Against the backdrop of a Ruger shotgun are the words, ``The
very fact that it can be dangerous is what makes it safe.''
</P>
<P>
   If you inhale enough bus fumes I think you'll agree with me that
this is a terrific slogan, perhaps the best since chicken baron
Frank Perdue's slogan ``It takes a tough man to make a chicken
tender'' was mistranslated in Spanish to read ``It takes a hard man
to make a chicken aroused.''
</P>
<P>
   Rereading this slogan, the first thing that pops into my mind,
other than the notion to eat a lot less chicken, is: Why didn't the
tobacco industry think of this first?
</P>
<P>
   Imagine how many more people would take up smoking if the
tobacco companies had come up with a slogan like, ``The very fact
that 400,000 Americans die horrible, agonizing tobacco-related
deaths each year is exactly what makes smoking safe!''
</P>
<P>
   When questioned about the statistics, an ad man could decry the
fact that many Americans associate cigarette smoking with lung
cancer and emphysema and death rather than beach parties, ski
vacations and casual sex with attractive 21-year-old models, which
is really what smoking is all about.
</P>
<P>
   The spokesman might add that cigarettes are safe if smoked
responsibly and that a teen who's got his hands occupied lighting a
Marlboro is a teen who's not slamming another clip into his AK-47.
</P>
<P>
   This, of course, might create some ``bad blood'' between the
tobacco industry and the gun lobby, but I doubt that it's anything
they couldn't overcome. Indeed, once the American public comes to
accept the fact that the more dangerous something is, the more safe
it is, it's just a matter of time before the proponents of other
hazardous activities are making use of the same slogan.
</P>
<P>
   The coal industry would get all the miners it needs with a
slogan like, ``Sure, there's a risk of explosion and black lung's
pretty much a sure thing and let us not ignore the very real
possibility that you'll drown or be buried alive under 10,000 tons
of rock, but, what the heck, that's what makes mining safe!''
</P>
<P>
   Rattlesnake milking, bomb defusing, tornado spotting _ all are
activities that could enjoy an image boost with the help of a
carefully worded ad campaign.
</P>
<P>
   And I bet inner-city polo would start getting the respect it
deserves, too.
</P>
<P>
   (The Sarasota, Fla., Herald-Tribune is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
