<HEADLINE>
FILLING A SKILL SHORTAGE, CLOSE TO HOME  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif., Ill., S.D., Ariz. N.Y.)   (af)  
 By AMY HARMON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   When Dan Lopez was a freshman at Oak Grove High School in San
Jose, Calif., a teacher asked his class if anyone was interested in
being the first to try a new program that would prepare students
for careers in the travel and tourism industry.
</P>
<P>
   It sounded like a lot of work. There would be extra classes and
internships in the field over the summers. But the internships were
paid, and Lopez, whose parents had not attended college, hoped
participating would improve his chances.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it would open up another avenue that would be
possible not just in the here and now but in the future,'' said
Lopez, who followed through and joined the program, sponsored by
the National Academy Foundation. Now 23, he is working this summer
as a manager at a Homewood Suites hotel and will be a senior at San
Jose State University in California in September.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez is also looking forward to meeting President Clinton this
week, as the foundation gets a high-profile endorsement for its
pioneering work linking high schools and corporations to prepare
students for jobs in growth industries.
</P>
<P>
   The president is scheduled to announce plans on Thursday for an
Academy of Information Technology, to be financed in part by Lucent
Technologies and based on the model established by the foundation,
a nonprofit organization founded and championed by Sanford I.
Weill, the chairman of Citigroup.
</P>
<P>
   Since the establishment of a financial services academy in 1982
at John Dewey High School in Brooklyn, nearly 20,000 teen-agers,
most of them from minority groups, have graduated from academy
programs, which now involve about 300 schools across the country.
About 90 percent of the graduates go on to college.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a great believer that this country has been an incredible
place for creative people and entrepreneurs, and I think it's very
important that people who have that kind of opportunity give back
to our society and make it a better place,'' Weill said by
telephone. ``The things that work best are when you get the private
and public sector working together in concert.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a theme that resonates with the president's agenda this
week. Clinton is planning to visit several of the nation's most
economically distressed regions with industry executives who are
already investing in them in some way _ and who will exhort others
to do the same.
</P>
<P>
   Gene Sperling, director of the White House's National Economic
Council, said the goal is to prompt corporations to see
underdeveloped communities as new markets, rather than focuses of
charity. ``The focus of this trip is untapped potential,'' he said.
``We are exhorting corporations to understand that these are
mutually beneficial programs. Giving disadvantaged youth the
opportunity to learn job skills is as critical for future economic
growth as it is for social fairness.''
</P>
<P>
   The president is scheduled to start the visits Monday in
Appalachia. Then, in East St. Louis, Ill., he will meet with Hugh
McColl, the chairman of Bank of America. Later, Clinton will go to
Pine Ridge, S.D., and Phoenix. The last leg of the trip will take
him to Watts in Los Angeles and to Anaheim, Calif., where the
National Academy Foundation will hold its annual teacher training
session and awards ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   The plan for the technology academy comes on the heels of a
Commerce Department report affirming the frequent complaints of
information technology executives that there are not enough
qualified workers to meet the demand. The industry has also come
under criticism recently from Rep. Jesse Jackson Jr., D-Ill., and
others for not employing more blacks and Hispanics.
</P>
<P>
   ``Information technology is a complicated area of curriculum
that most schools are not focusing on,'' said David Ford, president
of the Lucent Technologies Foundation. ``We believe this will help
address the industry's need.''
</P>
<P>
   Lucent has agreed to donate over $1 million, or one-quarter of
what it will cost the National Academy Foundation to develop the
program. The plan calls for 10 schools to start the pilot program
in September 2000. But the foundation will first have to solicit
the remainder of the funds from other information technology
companies, in an industry whose newest companies are not exactly
known for philanthropy.
</P>
<P>
   Weill and Lucent's chairman, Richard McGinn, who are close
friends, plan a meeting to encourage other donors to step forward.
</P>
<P>
   The technology academy would be the third theme curriculum for
the foundation. The first, which trains students for jobs in the
financial services industry, was created by Weill in 1981, when he
was chairman of Shearson Loeb Rhoades.
</P>
<P>
   The Academy of Finance opened in 1982 and expanded in 1986 to
include an Academy for Travel and Tourism. Citigroup contributes
about $2 million annually to the foundation's programs. Other
underwriters include American Express, the Merrill Lynch &AMP; Co.
Foundation, Bloomberg LP, Sallie Mae, the McGraw-Hill Companies and
Marriott International.
</P>
<P>
   The formula, which also requires active participation by local
business executives, appears to have worked.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before I was in the academy, I thought business was only one
thing, like being in an office all day with a bunch of numbers,''
said Eloisa Chavez, 18, a graduate of the Academy of Finance and
Martin Luther King Jr. High School in Manhattan. Ms. Chavez, of the
Bronx, who now attends Williams College, said an internship at
Standard &AMP; Poor's taught her that business is as much about people
as it is about math.
</P>
<P>
   The academy provided other kinds of training, too. ``Every
Wednesday, our Academy of Finance coordinator would tell us to
dress up as though you were going to a business job,'' she said,
``and if you didn't dress up, he would get on your case.''
</P>
</TEXT>
