<HEADLINE>
ROOSEVELT'S CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, July 04, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID WARSH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   On the last Fourth of July celebration of the century, what, if
anything, can be said with confidence about the path that has
brought the United States to its present point?
</P>
<P>
   To veterans of the political wars of the last quarter-century,
the news last week was slightly dizzy-making. Growth has been so
much more robust than anticipated that the White House predicted
that budget surpluses over the next 15 years will be much greater
than expected _ an extra $1 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Medicare can be extended, Social Security preserved, taxes
trimmed _ and the entire federal debt eliminated by 2015, according
to Office of Management and Budget calculations.
</P>
<P>
   Nor do others disagree with the numbers _ not private
economists, the Federal Reserve Board, or even Republicans. Stock
markets set records on the news. So did presidential fund-raising
by George W. Bush.
</P>
<P>
   To check my bearings, I went back and looked at the article with
which I enlisted as a foot soldier in the tax revolt 25 years ago.
It was a cover story in Forbes magazine, illustrated by pies sliced
variously, each labelled with little flags: US, USSR, China, Japan,
Great Britain.
</P>
<P>
   The tag line asked, ``How Big A Slice Should Government Take?''
</P>
<P>
   In those days, we had to fight hard to get that article into
print. The editor explained: Since Franklin Roosevelt's New Deal
had become the basic social compact of US life in the early 1950s,
it was considered impolite _ slightly crackpot, even _ to complain
about taxes.
</P>
<P>
   I was given a partner, a Rhodes scholar whose duty was to keep
the story respectable. (He quoted his Oxford tutor, J.R. Lucas:
``Poverty is an evil and great poverty is a great evil, but it is
not the same evil as lack of freedom.'')
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, the article concluded jauntily, ``The tax
rebellion of the mid-Seventies may look like the old, simple
pocketbook issue. In fact it is the beginning of a fight to keep
the US from becoming another Britain or Argentina.''
</P>
<P>
   There was a lot of this sort of thing around in those days. The
Dow Jones Industrial average was struggling to stay above 1,000.
Inflation was nearly 10 percent a year and rising. Politicians
around the world were struggling towards some kind of realignment _
no one yet knew exactly along what lines.
</P>
<P>
   All kinds of analyses were offered, high and low: Friedrich
Hayek and Milton Friedman, James Buchanan and Ronald Coase, Martin
Feldstein and John Taylor, Howard Jarvis and Barbara Anderson,
George Gilder, David Stockman and Jude Wanniski.
</P>
<P>
   (My friends and I jokingly called our crude variant ``T&AMP;P,'' for
taxes and prices. We meant what economists soon enough would again
be calling political economy. The lesson I took away was that there
was no thought in a journalist's head that some economist somewhere
wasn't also working on, more clearly and more deeply.)
</P>
<P>
   One thing almost all of us had in common: We felt we were
fighting against a dominant political and economic consensus whose
shorthand was ``the New Deal. Most of us still liked FDR, but we
considered that his principles of coalition-building were impeding
economic growth.
</P>
<P>
   Then Paul Volcker was appointed chairman of the Federal Reserve
Board by Jimmy Carter. Ronald Reagan was elected president in 1980.
The rest, as they say, is history.
</P>
<P>
   The expansion started in 1982, and by the time it is finally
interrupted by the next recession, there will have been 20 years of
nearly continuous growth. Nor has it been just the United States.
The rest of the world has grown, too, and rapidly become more
integrated.
</P>
<P>
   The Cold War ended. There was worldwide boom.
</P>
<P>
   How then to understand what had happened? The ``tax revolt''
quickly became half a dozen schisms: there were tax-cutters,
privatizers, de-regulators, re-moralizers, globalizers, good
housekeepers, creative destructionists, and those of us interested
in putting a narrative on the whole.
</P>
<P>
   The Rhodes scholar went to The Washington Post. I came to The
Boston Globe.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, we concentrated on the inflection points in US
history. The 1980 election was like that of 1932 _ the beginning of
broad political consensus that would last a half century. And
indeed it was a generationally-based expression of the ``zig-zag of
politics,'' in Robert Nozick's phrase.
</P>
<P>
   For a time, too, we experimented with a more global view. The
economic revolution of the 20th century was like the democratic
revolution of the 18th or the social revolution of the 19th _ a
worldwide movement of irresistible and irreversible force. This
also seemed to be true.
</P>
<P>
   Increasingly in the 1980s it was clear that there would be no
turning back the clock. Ronald Reagan had his own messages:
deregulation, privatization, and open markets. But in social
matters, and with respect to the architecture of the mixed economy,
he was a steward for Roosevelt's programs: federal withholding,
Social Security, conservation and national parks. Reagan possessed
a temperament like that of Roosevelt; routinely professed
admiration for him; from certain angles he even looked like him.
</P>
<P>
   The 20th century was the century of Roosevelt. His presidency
dominates it as clearly as that of Lincoln commands the 19th.
Lincoln saw the national government as responsible for the
preservation of the Union and put the proposition that ``all men
are created equal'' at the center of its policy.
</P>
<P>
   Roosevelt accepted the government's ultimate responsibility for
the well-being of the market economy, and wrote a new freedom _
freedom from want _ into the national charter. ``The New Deal'' was
a short-term political coalition among interest groups whose
ability to galvanize commitments lasted the usual two generations.
But Roosevelt's deeper vision of the community is still with us.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan understood this. So did George Bush. Bill Clinton,
whose stewardship of the Republican mandate in the '90s has turned
out to be not very different from Dwight Eisenhower's willingess to
carry out the program of the New Deal in the '50s, was educated
from childhood in the New Deal. George W. Bush seemingly
understands, and that accounts for his presumed electability.
</P>
<P>
   And the 21st century? Put me down among those who think the
great struggle of the 21st is going to be about greater equality in
distribution, starting with education.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(David Warsh writes about economics for The Boston Globe. His
e-mail address is warsh(at)globe.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
