<HEADLINE>
ARRESTS POINT TO GROWING USE OF TEENS FOR DRUG SMUGGLING 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By DANE SCHILLER  
 c.1999 San Antonio Express-News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LAREDO, Texas _ After catching a 16-year-old girl speeding
through the streets here with $32 million worth of cocaine openly
stacked in the bed of her pickup truck, authorities believe drug
smugglers are enlisting teen-agers in increasing numbers to skirt
adult laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many kids do you know that drive around with seven hundred
pounds of cocaine in their pickup?'' Doug Krockenberger, head of
U.S. Customs Service investigations here, asked Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no fear; it was so brazen,'' Krockenberger said.
</P>
<P>
   That incident unfolded late Wednesday when the girl pulled off a
road leading from the Rio Grande and cut in front of a Customs
agent heading home.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, Customs officials in Laredo arrested a 17-year-old
boy and charged him with smuggling 24 pounds of cocaine worth an
estimated $1 million.
</P>
<P>
   The trend has caught the eye of officials in El Paso, where the
number of juveniles arrested on marijuana-smuggling charges is
expected to climb 50 percent in 1999 over the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have seen a dramatic increase in the number of cross-border
cases involving juveniles,'' El Paso County Attorney Jose Rodriguez
said. ``The trend is alarming.''
</P>
<P>
   El Paso officials expect juvenile smuggling arrests to top 150
this year, as compared to fewer than 100 the previous year.
</P>
<P>
   The situation has gotten so out of hand in far West Texas that
Rodriguez is working with television stations to produce public
service announcements warning juveniles not to risk a smuggling
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Adult smugglers are reluctant to put themselves on the line,''
Rodriguez said. ``There is a perception out there that juveniles
get a slap on the wrist'' if they get caught.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of years or decades behind bars in a federal prison
system that has no parole, they face probation or a tour at the
Texas Youth Commission followed by deportation, Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike El Paso and most other border cities, juveniles caught in
Laredo with significant loads of drugs are taken to federal court
rather than being turned over to country prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Adult smugglers frequent Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, discos to enlist
teen-agers to drive loads into El Paso or sneak them through narrow
drainage tunnels running between the United States and Mexico, he
said.
</P>
<P>
   For a 200-pound load, which would be worth $100,000 on the
streets of El Paso, a teen-ager could earn $500, Rodriguez said.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the 16-year-old driving the truck was taken before
U.S. Magistrate Marcel Notzon and ordered held at the Webb County
juvenile detention facility.
</P>
<P>
   She was caught after a brief chase that ended abruptly when she
pulled into a dead end street in South Laredo.
</P>
<P>
   And the 17-year-old was arrested at an international bridge here
after a dog sniffed the 25 pounds of cocaine wrapped in foil and
hidden in the quarter panels of the car he was driving.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
