<HEADLINE>
(HLW)
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the stories that New York Times editors are planning
for the Page 1 of Saturday, July 3. The N.Y. Times News Service
supervisor is Henry Louis Warnken. The final FRONTPAGE will move
later in the evening.
</P>
<P>
   For copy info: (888) 346-9867.
</P>
<P>
   For graphics, map, photo info: (888) 603-1036.
</P>
<P>
   ISRAEL-ORTHODOX (Bnei Brak) _ With the laboriously negotiated
permission of rabbis, a dozen ultra-Orthodox Israelis are stepping
out of their cloistered religious universe to train in a three-year
social work program at one of the two largest Israeli universities,
Bar Ilan. It is almost unheard of in Israel. By Deborah Sontag.
</P>
<P>
   TOUR-DE-FRANCE (Paris) _ An air of profound pessimism hangs over
the sport of cycling these days, and it hangs heavier than usual
with the Tour de France, which begins Saturday, for it was during
last year's race that the cover was blown off the sport's
far-reaching drug problem. Since then, cycling, the sport that for
Europe has been a cultural treasure as well as a formidable
commercial enterprise, has suffered a collapse in credibility so
great that many of its riders, organizers and sponsors fear for its
future. A Special Report by Christopher Clarey and Samuel Abt.
(3000 words and a 1500-word abridged version.)
</P>
<P>
   NIRELAND-TALKS (Belfast, Northern Ireland) _ Northern Ireland
talks resume in what is believed to be a final make-or-break
session. By Warren Hoge.
</P>
<P>
   NJ-POLICE-REPORT (Trenton, N.J.) _ New Jersey issues its
long-awaited report on the State Police force, calling for a major
reorganization to meet complaints of racial profiling and other
abuses. By David Kocieniewski.
</P>
<P>
   CAR-PHONE-BAN (Brooklyn, Ohio) _ It is illegal to drive while
talking on a cell phone in this Cleveland suburb, apparently the
only place in America with such a ban. Mayor John Coyne, 82, who is
in his 52nd year in office, and who can recall a time when people
survived without driving automobiles or talking on telephones, let
alone doing both at once, believes it is just a matter of common
sense. By Dirk Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-RUSSIA (Washington) _ Developments in the continuing
controversy over the proper Russian role in the Kosovo peacekeeping
effort. By Eric Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   TEN-STEVENSON-ERVING (Undated) _ Former Philadelphia 76ers
All-Star Julius Erving said he is the father of tennis sensation
Alexandra Stevenson. Erving said in a statement that all matters
concerning Stevenson have been handled privately through a counsel
since her birth. He said it would be his first and only statement
about her.
</P>
</TEXT>
