<HEADER>
A7590 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SERIAL-KILLER-ELPASO-     07-02 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SERIAL-KILLER-ELPASO-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RESIDENTS QUIVER AT THOUGHT OF SUSPECTED SERIAL KILLER RETURNING TO
EL PASO AREA 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, July 4) 
 
(Eds.: Virginia Resendiz de Maturino is cq) 
 
By MICHAEL RILEY 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL PASO, Texas _ While the accused serial killer Rafael
Resendez-Ramirez has sent a shiver across an entire nation, the
possibility that he might return to this border town in the West
Texas desert has created something close to panic.
</P>
<P>
   Families have begun to bar their doors at night and skittish
residents have claimed to see the train-hopping Resendez-Ramirez
around every corner.
</P>
<P>
   FBI officials say that in the last two weeks, they have received
more than 100 reports from people in El Paso claiming to have seen
the accused killer. Resendez-Ramirez's mother lives in a modest
house in Ciudad Juarez, Mexico, just across the border.
</P>
<P>
   Most of those calls have come since the admission by the U.S.
Border Patrol that they arrested him near here just a month ago,
then mistakenly let him go.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody is pretty paranoid,'' said Cynthia Acosta, 24, who
runs a sandwich shop in downtown El Paso.
</P>
<P>
   She said that because her father is away, her 12-year-old
brother has nailed all the windows shut and props up a chair behind
the front door at night.
</P>
<P>
   ``How come the authorities can track down anybody with a simple
parking ticket, but they can't find a guy who is supposedly not in
full control of his senses?'' Acosta asked.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez has slipped through a massive national manhunt
involving thousands of federal, state and local law enforcement
authorities.
</P>
<P>
   In El Paso, however, he seems to be everywhere.
</P>
<P>
   One woman, making a panicky call from a back bathroom, believed
Resendez-Ramirez was playing pool in the barroom out front, say
police. Another person saw him standing in the check-out line at
the local grocery store.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can understand that there are legitimate concerns on the
part of the public,'' said Special Agent Al Cruz of the FBI's El
Paso office. But, he added, ``there has been nothing to
substantiate or confirm the fact that he was here during some of
the reported sightings.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Resendez-Ramirez's mother lives in Juarez and that
authorities believe he once held a steady job at a packing plant
there are helping to spread the worry.
</P>
<P>
   Resendez-Ramirez has been linked through fingerprints and other
physical evidence to the deaths of eight people in Kentucky,
Illinois and Texas. Police in one Northeast Texas community think
strongly that he killed there. The murders occurred near railway
tracks, and authorities believe that he is traveling primarily by
train.
</P>
<P>
   El Paso sits on a major east-west rail corridor, and has rail
lines leading into Mexico. The wide plane of tracks that cuts
through the city has suddenly become, at least in residents'
imagination, a way Resendez-Ramirez might try to make it back to
his native Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   ``People in town, especially those who live near the railroad
tracks, are very concerned. Who wouldn't be?,'' said Dan Williams,
city editor of the El Paso Times. ``The guy's family lives right
across the border. If you live near the train tracks, you're going
to lock your door.''
</P>
<P>
   Authorities here are taking it a little more in stride.
</P>
<P>
   The El Paso police aren't devoting any special resources to look
out for Resendez-Ramirez. Some of the sightings authorities have
checked out; others they eliminated quickly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people call in and say `I saw him, but I don't remember
where.' That doesn't help us much,'' said Detective Armando
Fonseca.
</P>
<P>
   Across the border in Juarez, Resendez-Ramirez is hardly
well-known. Most express surprise that the suspected killer has any
connection with this booming industrial city. Authorities say he is
not considered a suspect in any of the string of homicides
involving young women this decade.
</P>
<P>
   His mother's neighbors say they have never seen Resendez-Ramirez
visiting. He was reared by an uncle in central Mexico. The only
children the neighbors have seen at the house belong to
Resendez-Ramirez's stepfather, a retired military man.
</P>
<P>
   Barraged by the media, Resendez-Ramirez's mother _ Virginia
Resendiz de Maturino _ has secluded herself in the house, said
Manuel Rosas, 35, who runs a tiny corner store.
</P>
<P>
   ``She's a regular customer, but in the last couple of days, we
haven't seen her. The last time was just after the news about her
son came out. She looked worn out and very sad,'' said Rosas.
``This kind of thing always hits the mother hardest.''
</P>
<P>
   But with the horror of Resendez-Ramirez's supposed crimes,
neighbors say they are still a little nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the doors around here are locked tight at night,'' said
Elva Porras, 44, talking under the shade of a tree on the narrow
street where Resendez-Ramirez's mother lives. ``There are some
tracks near here. We're all a little worried he might come around
to see his mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Rosas said he believes the precautions are a little more active.
</P>
<P>
   ``I bet under every bed or behind every door, there's a pole or
a stick,'' he said. ``Just in case he comes back.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1811EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
