<P>
   FORD REWARD _ WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ It's been said that good
words are worth much, and cost little. So often, the opposite also
holds true. Take, for example, the case of Kathleen Ford, who is
fighting with three jewelers over a $1 million reward she offered
to find the crooks who stole $6.2 million in jewelry from her Palm
Beach, Fla., house. The jewelers, who tipped police to two men
charged with taking her jewels over state lines, have sued Ford,
saying she's now trying to back out of the deal. Ford says the
reward is still on the table, that it was intended for the arrest
and conviction of whoever burglarized her house _ a distinct
statute that the two men have not been charged with, though both
were in possession of her stuff, and police think they did it. The
dispute has led to an agonizing and often silly parsing of words
among lawyers in depositions taken last month. ``We could probably
spend hours with the semantics,'' Ford's lawyer complained. Also,
one of the crooks is making a claim for the reward himself.
(Hiaasen, Palm Beach Post). 20-25.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-MIXEDCOUPLE _ PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ When Bafti married
Gordana 35 years ago, their love was unremarkable. Today, it seems
unimaginable. He is an ethnic Albanian and she is a Serb. Very
infrequently in Kosovo one hears of mixed couples. They are almost
always in their 60s, married in an era when secular Communism
papered over ethnic and religious divisions. Now, most fear that
that any discussion of their love will channel toward their
doorstep the ethnic hatred that has left a wake of mass graves and
burned villages throughout the province. But, Bafti and Gordana
Miftari, both 60, are sturdy grandparentswith a lot to say. Their
simple words seem to defy the hateful gravity of a place where
people matter-of-factly toss out blanket racial epithets about
``wild animals'' or ``terrorists.'' (Kaplow, Cox News Service).
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
