<SLUG> BC-BIZ-ECON-COLUMN-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NAME THAT INTEREST RATE: SORTING OUT THE ECONOMY'S SIGNALS  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Mass., Ky., Maine, Ill.)   (af)  
 By LOUIS UCHITELLE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The inflation debate has been whittled down to a single issue.
</P>
<P>
   No longer does anyone fret much about shortages in the great
array of goods and services that Americans consume. Sure, there can
be temporary scarcities and bottlenecks, and short-lived price
spikes.
</P>
<P>
   But in the eyes of the Federal Reserve, only one kind of
shortage has the potential to be inflationary in the late 1990s: a
labor shortage. And that, too, may be losing its teeth.
</P>
<P>
   There is indeed a labor shortage. The statistics are clear, the
main one being the unemployment rate, which came in Friday at 4.3
percent for June. People are getting jobs everywhere, even in the
inner cities where entrenched joblessness is finally giving ground.
</P>
<P>
   In Boston, for example, inner-city people ride streetcars to the
last stop, then take taxis the final few miles to jobs at suburban
companies. To get the workers, the employers pay the taxi fares.
</P>
<P>
   Such tactics, which allow companies to tap the nation's
remaining pools of idle workers, help postpone the day when
corporate America might really have to bid up wages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things are definitely better in the inner city,'' said
Katherine S. Newman, an anthropologist at Harvard's Kennedy School
of government who works in such neighborhoods. ``But you would have
to see the lines of the unemployed shrink by a lot more than they
have before you would see major increases in wages.''
</P>
<P>
   By past standards, after 24 months with the unemployment rate
under 5 percent, those major increases ought to have appeared
already, if not in the inner cities then elsewhere in the country.
Pay is rising, of course, but not yet by enough to force companies
to try to raise prices. Until that happens, the Federal Reserve
cannot justify pushing up interest rates sufficiently to slow the
hiring by slowing the economy.
</P>
<P>
   There are those who argue that a significant acceleration in
wages is just around the corner. But strangely, even though the
unemployment rate has fallen below 4.5 percent since last November,
wages and salaries have risen more slowly in recent months. There
is deceleration, not acceleration.
</P>
<P>
   The same deceleration also applies to the corporate cost of
health insurance and other benefits. And economists are scrambling
to explain the anomaly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no smoking gun,'' said Jared Bernstein, a labor
economist at the Economic Policy Institute.
</P>
<P>
   For starters, everyone agrees that companies have become a lot
more agile at fending off wage increases, while labor's bargaining
power has declined along with union representation. As one
substitute for raises, companies offer stock options, which do not
show up in the Labor Department's employment cost data. And
one-time signing bonuses lure workers without obliging an employer
to raise the pay of comparable workers already on the payroll.
</P>
<P>
   Labor productivity is clearly part of the explanation. It has
risen smartly in the last two or three years, which means that
workers are producing more for the same hourly pay, at least for
the time being.
</P>
<P>
   At a grittier level, service companies, particularly telephone
call centers, distribution centers and clerical operations, have
become more mobile. For example, dozens have relocated to northern
Kentucky, where unemployment was relatively high, and to towns in
Maine where shuttered shoe factories and paper mills left pools of
not-very-expensive workers. Government subsidies also encourage
companies to move.
</P>
<P>
   In a new study, two labor economists, Alan B. Krueger of
Princeton and Lawrence F. Katz of Harvard, find that the
unemployment rate may be kept artificially low by the very sharp
rise in the male prison population. Prisoners are not counted as
either employed or unemployed; if they were on the street, many
would show as unemployed.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the aging of the work force; older workers are
less likely to be unemployed. And don't forget the growing
temporary-help industry, which keeps people off unemployment rolls
between permanent jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Adjust today's unemployment rate for these three factors, and it
would be around 5 percent, the study finds.
</P>
<P>
   On a different plane, some experts explain the deceleration in
wage growth by arguing that workers have become used to a low
inflation rate and therefore settle for smaller raises, which seems
strange when people are so much in demand.
</P>
<P>
   Or perhaps job insecurity inhibits them. The National Opinion
Research Center at the University of Chicago asks people how likely
they think they are to lose their jobs. ``The percentage of those
who answer `very likely' has not fallen all that much since the
last recession,'' said Thomas Smith, director of the center's
General Social Survey.
</P>
<P>
   The list of explanations will certainly grow if the nation's
tight labor market keeps failing to push up wages significantly. No
one will collect these explanations with greater interest than the
Federal Reserve's policy makers. They cannot push up interest rates
much beyond last week's quarter-point rise without a significant
rise in labor costs as justification.
</P>
</TEXT>
