<HEADER>
A7608 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-NYT     07-02 0816
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-MEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAS A VICTOR AS PHILIPPOUSSIAS WITHDRAWS; AGASSI, HENMAN,
RAFTER GAIN 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBIN FINN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ A day late, but definitely not short on
talent, Wimbledon's four male semifinalists took advantage of a
break in the interminable drizzle that has made a scheduling
nightmare of this Grand Slam tournament's second week and
identified themselves Friday. They took a variety of routes to
arrive at their shared destination.
</P>
<P>
   Pete Sampras, the defending champion, squeaked into the semis
thanks to an injury default by his swift-serving opponent, Mark
Philippoussis. Patrick Rafter, wearing his customary white war
paint to ward off the sunshine, slipped through on adrenaline. Tim
Henman, carrying the burden of the host nation's expectations,
soldiered into the last four for the second straight year. And
Andre Agassi, so bald and clean-shaven that he has begun to
resemble a newborn from the shoulders up, outwitted Gustavo Kuerten
and the Graveyard Court in straight sets.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras, the five-time champion on the hunt for a place in the
record books alongside the all-time Grand Slam singles leader Roy
Emerson and his dozen majors, backed into the semis when the
seventh-seeded Philippoussis defaulted with a left knee injury 52
minutes into their match. Sampras was trailing 4-6, 1-1 when the
Australian heard ``a click'' in his knee after hitting a backhand;
then he felt the knee seize up as Sampras launched his seventh ace
to put him ahead 2-1 in the second set. It was later determined
that Philippoussis sustained torn knee cartilage and will be out
4-6 weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't sit here and say I really fended off Mark today,''
said Sampras, who doublefaulted three times in his opening service
game en route to dropping his first set of the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Sampras will next face his golfing buddy and doubles partner,
the sixth-seeded Henman, in a rematch of last year's semifinal. The
American, 5-0 against Henman, will again assume a villain's role in
front of a rabidly partisan audience that hasn't seen a homegrown
Wimbledon men's champion since Fred Perry in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Against Philippoussis, Sampras came away feeling like a bit of
an unintended villain. ``I mean, he was outplaying me, and I can't
sit here and feel good about it,'' Sampras said. ``It's kind of a
mixed emotion.''
</P>
<P>
   Henman, the British No. 1, used 19 aces to thump 38th-ranked
Cedric Pioline, the only unseeded quarterfinalist, 6-4, 6-2, 4-6,
6-3, and later expressed pleasure about the opportunity to tackle
Wimbledon's incumbent champion.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if you want to win the tournament, you also want to
beat the very best, and when you look at Pete's record here, you
know it's second to none,'' Henman said of Sampras, who has lost
just once here in the last six years and has a lifetime record of
51-5. ``I think that record is self-explanatory; he's one of the
best players, for sure, that's played this game and I've learned a
hell of a lot from him.''
</P>
<P>
   Henman will, weather permitting, turn from a Sampras fan to a
Sampras foe on Saturday. ``When you put it in simple-man's terms,
there are two things that are going to happen,'' the Englishman
said. ``I'm either going to win or I'm going to lose, it's as
simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   The second-seeded Rafter, a two-time defending U.S. Open
champion who hadn't passed Wimbledon's fourth round until this
year, reached the semifinals with a run-and-gun performance against
the eighth-seeded Martin.
</P>
<P>
   Today, Martin served for the fourth set at 5-4, but
doublefaulted. In the subsequent tiebreaker, Rafter quickly grabbed
a match point with a sweeping backhand pass and celebrated a 6-3,
6-7(5-7), 7-6(7-5), 7-6(7-3) victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a pretty big milestone for me, and I want to keep it
going,'' said Rafter, who next collides with Agassi, the 1992
Wimbledon champion.
</P>
<P>
   The stakes of the Agassi-Rafter match include the No. 1 ranking
as well as a place in the Wimbledon final. Agassi is currently on a
12-match unbeaten streak that began with last month's title at the
French Open, where he became the first man to complete a career
Grand Slam since Roy Emerson did it in 1964, and just the fifth man
in his sport's history, to win all four slams. (Laver won his
second Grand Slam in 1969.) Friday, Agassi punished Kuerten, 6-3,
6-4, 6-4.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to be in the semis these days and not feel good
about your game,'' said Agassi who, at 29, was the oldest of the
semifinalists. ``I'm never happy until it's over, as far as being
comfortable goes, but I felt good about the way I executed.''
</P>
<P>
   As for facing Rafter, a player he defeated here in the third
round in 1993 but who has won three of their last four meetings,
Agassi was sanguine. All except for one thing. ``It is a little
distracting playing someone with a ponytail,'' he joked.
</P>
</TEXT>
