<HEADER>
A7610 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CYBERSCENE06-COX     07-02 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYBERSCENE06-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Patriotism available in many flavors
 &HT;    EDS: EMBARGOED for Sunday, July 4
 &HT;    By Bill Husted
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The Southern way to celebrate the Fourth of July is
with watermelon, barbecue, fireworks and pride. It's not a
cyber-holiday.
</P>
<P>
   In the true spirit of America, it's important to remember that
the holiday means different things to different people. Whether
you're a veteran, a historian, a patriot or just curious, the whole
idea is that your point of view is just as good as the next
person's. That may be about as close as you can get to the real
meaning of the Fourth of July.
</P>
<P>
   With that in mind, let's make our first stop at a site called
Free-Market.Net's Fourth of July Features at
www.free-market.net/features/july4/. Along with some other features
that we'll discuss in a minute, there's a section where you can
record _ for others to see _ your own thoughts on the Fourth of
July.
</P>
<P>
   You'll have some hefty competition since, in that same section,
you'll be able to read what Thomas Jefferson had to say about the
Fourth. Many historians consider Jefferson the most learned of the
presidents. You can read his complete remarks, made June 24, 1826,
but in part, he said that the creation of America was: ``the signal
of arousing men to burst the chains under which monkish ignorance
and superstition had persuaded them to bind themselves, and to
assume the blessings and security of self-government. That form
which we have substituted, restores the free right to the unbounded
exercise of reason and freedom of opinion. All eyes are opened, or
opening, to the rights of man.''
</P>
<P>
   On the same page, you'll find patriotic images (the owners of
the site make it clear you are welcome to copy any of the images
for use on your own page), a selection of patriotic documents
including the Declaration of Independence, a list of books on
American independence and the Fourth of July, and various contests
built around a patriotic theme.
</P>
<P>
   Our next page also helps provide some context for the holiday.
It's called the American Heritage Page, located at
www.infoporium.com/heritage/. You'll find a gallery of the
presidents where biography and history on each president is
provided, as well as a section on various politicians _ a truly
diverse group ranging from Davy Crockett to Sen. Joseph McCarthy.
</P>
<P>
   But maybe you want fireworks instead of politicians. If that's
the case, you'll find a page simply called Fourth of July a good
place to visit. You'll find this page at
www.netm.com/4th/index.htm. The first thing you'll see is a Java
animation of fireworks bursting in air.
</P>
<P>
   Then, if you have fireworks in mind as part of your own Fourth,
you'll find some good tips for family safety around fireworks
(although the best tip probably is to leave the fireworks to
professionals ... and to note that setting off fireworks is illegal
in many areas).
</P>
<P>
   The patriotic importance of the holiday also is covered on the
page, with everything from facts about the American flag to a copy
of the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, because food and picnics long have been part of the
day, you'll want to visit a page called Mr. Dell's Potato Salad.
You'll find the page at www.mrdells
</P>
<P>
   .com/s5.htm.
</P>
<P>
   With the notion that most people don't need help or a recipe to
grill hamburgers or ribs, this page provides a fine recipe for
potato salad.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
