A7611 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN03-CO     07-02 0435
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Renewing respect, not subservience
 &HT;    By Stebbins Jefferson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Old Woman: ``Hey, little girlies, have you seen my
turkey?''
</P>
<P>
   Group: ``Yes, ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   Old Woman: ``Which way did he go?''
</P>
<P>
   Group: ``So, so.''
</P>
<P>
   Old Woman: ``Will you help me find him?''
</P>
<P>
   Group: ``Yes, ma'am.''
</P>
<P>
   Old Woman: ``Get ready, let's go.''
</P>
<P>
   Thus began the call-and-response chant of a game we played when
I was a child. We began by choosing a leader, who was designated
the ``old woman.'' She would stand before a group of us as we stood
behind a line drawn in the sand. When she finished asking the
prescribed questions and ordered us to follow her, we all sang out
repeatedly, ``Shoo, turkey!'' and chased the leader, who magically
became the runaway bird. The person who caught her then became the
next leader, with the authority to ask the questions and direct the
chase.
</P>
<P>
   Though oblivious to it at the time, I now realize this game
incorporated fundamental manners and discipline so ingrained in our
behavior that, even in play, once one of us had been declared an
adult, the group graciously acknowledged that status with ``ma'am''
or ``sir,'' even if that adult later turned out to be a turkey.
</P>
<P>
   We had been taught at home and school to show civil deference to
all adults for no other reasons than that they were older and in
charge. Within these parameters, we enjoyed a certain freedom. We
understg three miles to a library. For that matter, I cannot
imagine, in today's world, letting them do it.
</P>
<P>
   We even had a few books at home, but not a third of what my
children have today. Unfortunately, most of them were novels that
were beyond my ability to read. We did have a full set of Rudyard
Kipling, however, which I read until the covers fell off.
</P>
<P>
   By far the best reading material around my house were the
National Geographic where I not only learned about the world, but
the human body.
</P>
<P>
   Still a third of my summers were spent at my grandmother's
house, where the only thing to read were the comic strips on the
backs of cereal boxes. I read them each about a billion times
during the course of that few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Without computers, it was a cinch that we wouldn't have computer
games. The closest thing was testing your television vacuum tubes
at the drug store. After four or five hours, that lost its thrill,
too.
</P>
<P>
   Even outdoors wasn't as good in my day. I didn't live near any
park, baseball diamof the Marshall (Texas) News Messenger. His
e-mail address is platham(at)coxnews.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
</TEXT>
