<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 18:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7616 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-$ADV04     07-02 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-$ADV04-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL PARTIES STAKE OUT AGENDAS IN WAKE OF PROJECTED BUDGET
SURPLUS 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, July 4) 
 
By NANCY MATHIS 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Pity the poor deficit hawks circling these days
over the White House and Congress, both places now giddy at the
prospect of untold riches with which to satisfy constituents either
hungry for tax cuts or new programs.
</P>
<P>
   The fiscal contrarians calling for caution can hardly get a word
in edgewise in this great debate that so many politicians here
never thought they would witness: What to do with the burgeoning
federal surplus?
</P>
<P>
   Last week, both the White House and the Congress announced new
revised budget surplus figures that projected an extra $900 billion
to $1 trillion over 15 years. The brightest scenario would mean the
federal surplus would accumulate to nearly $6 trillion by 2015.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who plans on spending these `guesses,' either on tax
cuts or spending programs, has no right to call himself either a
conservative or responsible,'' said Rep. Charles Stenholm, D-Texas,
who has long championed fiscal restraint.
</P>
<P>
   But, the view of Stenholm and other conservative ``Blue Dog''
Democrats that Congress deal with the debt and Social Security
before committing itself to spending money it doesn't yet have,
likely will lose out. The pleas by Republican moderates that its
conservative leaders take a deep breath on tax cuts appears headed
for the same fate.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, both political parties last week staked out their
agendas for the summer, and each side thinks it has a blockbuster.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton and many Democrats want to set money aside to
save Social Security, pay off the national debt, expand Medicare
with a new prescription drug program, provide targeted tax cuts to
encourage savings, provide relief for child care and long-term
care, and increase spending for education and a handful of other
programs.
</P>
<P>
   Many Republicans want to set aside money for Social Security,
pay down the debt, reform Medicare, and give the rest of the money
_ an estimated $1 trillion over 10 years _ back to voters in the
form of tax cuts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Big surpluses make all of those things possible, which is a
nightmare for fiscal conservatives,'' said Robert Bixby, policy
director of the bipartisan Concord Coalition, the budgetary
Cassandras since 1992. ``We're concerned that all you're doing is
sowing the seeds for a very big deficit down the road.''
</P>
<P>
   Bixby noted the forecasts project that half of the expected $6
trillion surplus comes in the final five years, 2010 through 2014.
And, the idea that anyone can forecast that far ahead is
questionable. ``Any economist will tell you you're in a dream
world,'' Bixby said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the nation's economic boom, which has poured unexpected
billions into federal coffers, still provides an unprecedented
landscape for politicians.
</P>
<P>
   Ann Lewis, a senior adviser to Clinton, said the surplus is
``the dramatic symbol of the transformation that Bill Clinton has
presided over. We have gone from having the largest deficit in our
history to having the largest surplus.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton renewed his call last week that America take stock of
its challenges and meet them while the strong economy enables the
government to respond. For the past couple of years, Clinton
repeatedly has cited as a moral duty tackling the systemic problems
of health care and poverty.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Clinton will tour pockets of poverty, from the
Kentucky mountains to the Mississippi Delta, from an Indian
reservation to the Watts section of Los Angeles, to highlight the
business opportunities there for corporations searching for new
markets.
</P>
<P>
   ``The surplus is the hard-earned product of our fiscal
discipline,'' the president said last week as he announced the
revised figures. ``We should use it to prepare for the great
challenges facing our country _ caring for our parents, caring for
our children, freeing our nation from the shackles of debt so that
we can have long-term sustained economic prosperity.''
</P>
<P>
   But conservatives see the surplus as the hard-earned product of
too many taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``The president is trying desperately to spend the surplus
before we have it,'' said Sen. Phil Gramm, R-Texas, who favors
returning to the taxpayers all the money not earmarked for Social
Security or Medicare reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's clear that either we give it back to people in
the form of tax cuts or it's spent in Washington,'' Gramm said.
</P>
<P>
   He argues that, with tax cuts, if Congress' predictions turn out
wrong the money can be recouped later. If new programs are created
they remain on the books indefinitely.
</P>
<P>
   Gramm maintained Republicans are united on the tax cut issue,
but in the House, the GOP members in charge of appropriations
repeatedly have complained this year that internal spending caps
have made it impossible to adequately fund necessary government
programs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to have real conflict in the House,'' predicted
Rep. John Kasich, R-Ohio, House Budget Committee chairman.
``Because many of us are getting tired of them (moderate
Republicans) coming into this House saying they want smaller
government and then at the same time trying to figure out how they
can break the agreement and break the caps. It's not up to the
Republicans to unilaterally disarm, and increase Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   The unexpected windfall should provide the nation with an
opportunity to take stock and decide what kind of country it wants
to be as it steps into a new century.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis predicts the debate over the fiscal direction of the
nation will be a major dividing line for the 2000 elections.
</P>
<P>
   But Bixby has his doubts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really sense a grand philosophical debate. What I
sense is people saying now we have a big surplus, let's go back to
what we were doing before. Republicans want big tax cuts, and
Democrats want to create new entitlement programs. It's sort of a
revert to form rather than a rethinking of the wheel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are dangerous times for a deficit hawk,'' Bixby said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
