<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7620 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-LONGLINE-FISHING-1stL     07-02 0724
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LONGLINE-FISHING-1stLD-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;    
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    PORTIONS OF ATLANTIC AND GULF MAY BE CLOSED TO LONG-LINE FISHING
 &HT;    EDS: Recasts lede
 &HT;    Moving in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
 &HT;    By JONATHAN HALL
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an effort to protect migratory species such as
swordfish, shark and tuna, portions of the Atlantic Ocean and Gulf
of Mexico may be closed to long-line fishermen by the end of the
summer.
</P>
<P>
   How long they would be closed could vary from a month in some
places to 10 years in others. The size of the areas and length of
time for each closure will depend on how much the government wants
to reduce the excess harvesting of young fish.
</P>
<P>
   The problem has been caused by American and foreign fishermen
who use lines baited with as many as 3,000 hooks that can reach up
to 30 miles and are dragged behind vessels for 12 to 16 hours.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1992, an average of 35,000 juvenile swordfish per year are
caught and released dead. That's 30 percent of the total catch,
according to the National Coalition For Marine Conservation, an
independent conservation group. Swordfish are the most common
victims of the ``bycatch'' _ fish that are undersized, underage or
illegally caught.
</P>
<P>
   The only continuous zone being considered for closure by the
National Marine Fisheries Service would extend from Charleston,
S.C., through the Florida Keys. In addition, parts of the Gulf of
Mexico from the Florida Panhandle to Louisiana might be closed.
</P>
<P>
   Rebecca Lent, chief of fisheries service's division for
management of highly migratory species, said she hoped a final
determination of what areas will be closed will be made by the end
of summer.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this summer, the fisheries service, a part of the
National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration, considered closing
an area of the Florida Straits to reduce swordfish bycatch, but
Lent said the proposed area was too small.
</P>
<P>
   ``In order make it effective, we're going to have to go for a
larger area,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ken Hinman, president of a marine conservation coalition that
has been pushing for extensive closures, said long-line fishing may
have to be banned for a long time in some areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you want to reduce the bycatch by 50 percent, then that
area might have to be closed for 10 years,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The fisheries service has been revising the plan for closures
since it began public hearings last October.
</P>
<P>
   A 21,000-square-mile area off the coast of New Jersey was closed
for the entire month of June in order to protect undersized bluefin
tuna.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, long-line fishermen are working on a proposal to get
the federal government to buy them out.
</P>
<P>
   Since last November, the Blue Water Fisherman's Association,
which represents Atlantic long-line fishermen, has been working
with Sen. John Breaux, D-La., on a $15 million voluntary government
buyout of between 47 to 60 commercial vessels.
</P>
<P>
   Although no legislation has been introduced, Breaux said in a
statement, ``I have strongly encouraged the commercial and
recreational fishing groups to work together to find a common,
scientifically justified solution to reducing the bycatch of
juvenile swordfish and billfish in these fisheries while
recognizing very important economic issues for the fishermen.''
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. commercial fishermen argue that they are being
penalized for overharvesting by other countries. If U.S. waters are
going to be closed, they say, it's only fair for the government to
buy them out.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are offering voluntary buyouts for these boats,'' said
Nelson Beideman, executive director of the fishermen's association.
``This is long-term. We need to get this in the national arena so
it could eventually impact international fishermen who are
over-harvesting and catching these bycatch species.''
</P>
<P>
   Beideman said the ``bad players'' in long-lining are other
countries _ particularly Taiwan and Spain _ that haven't adhered to
quotas set up by the International Commission for Atlantic Tunas, a
25-member council that meets once a year and allocates specific
catch limits to each country.
</P>
<P>
   Hinman, of the conservation coalition, said he wants to see the
conservation plan implemented before buyouts are authorized.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
