<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7621 &Cx1f; tad-z
u k &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MONTYPYTHON-MEANING03     07-02 0868
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTYPYTHON-MEANING03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Still in Python's clutches
 &HT;    By Jim Yoakum
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A recent thread on a popular Internet newsgroup
included phrases like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``Your mother was a hamster and your father smelled of
elderberries!''
</P>
<P>
   ``Dinsdale!''
</P>
<P>
   ``This thread is getting too silly.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Shall we stop then?''
</P>
<P>
   ``OK. Ya poofta!''
</P>
<P>
   To the uninitiated, this exchange may appear weird, baffling and
perhaps even insulting. But to the regular posters over at
alt.fan.monty-python it's nothing special, just a typical day on
the Web discussion board that's devoted to the silliest group of
Britwits ever assembled: Monty Python's Flying Circus.
</P>
<P>
   What is it about this 30-year-old comedy troupe (the brainchild
of Graham Chapman, John Cleese, Terry Gilliam, Eric Idle, Terry
Jones and Michael Palin) that continues to attract _ and encourage
_ nonsensical behavior?
</P>
<P>
   What causes these seemingly normal people to spend hours online,
engaged in heated Dadaesque debates on things like ``the
differences between African and European swallows,'' or ``the pros
and cons of Spam''? Is it just the sheer silliness?
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps. Silliness, it seems, knows no era or boundaries. But to
dismiss Python fans as a bunch of people goofing around is too easy
an answer.
</P>
<P>
   There have been many other silly TV shows throughout history,
from ``Green Acres'' to ``Seinfeld,'' but none of them has inspired
the same manic, cultish hold that Monty Python exerts over its
fans. So, if it's not strictly the silliness, then what is it?
</P>
<P>
   In the late 1960s, there was a popular expression that went
``The revolution will not be televised.'' Well, little did we know
then, but not only was the revolution televised, it was called
Monty Python's Flying Circus.
</P>
<P>
   To the wizened Python fan, the series is more than just a funny
sketch program. It represents a social and cultural revolution as
important as the advent of Beatlemania. To these fans, Python did
more than make jokes about dead parrots, funny walks and
lumberjacks. It was an insurrection that came to us disguised as a
television comedy series.
</P>
<P>
   Monty Python was subversive, a ``revolution in the head'' that
forever changed the way its fans viewed the world and their place
in it. Sure, Monty Python made us laugh, but it also made us think
and then question; question society, ourselves, why we laugh and
what we laugh at. Monty Python was more than just funny, it was
dangerous because it attacked ideas.
</P>
<P>
   The following is a brief example of Python's power to provoke
while still tickling our funny bone. The setting is a darkened and
somber television studio dressed for what appears to be a religious
discussion program.
</P>
<P>
   The interviewer, played by John Cleese, sits with a monsignor in
full clerical garb with skull-cap. Opposite him sits a
tweed-suited, old Oxford don figure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good evening, and welcome once again to the Epilogue,'' Cleese
says. ``On the program this evening we have Monsignor Edward Gay,
visiting pastoral emissary of the Somerset Theological College and
author of a number of books about belief, the most recent of which
is the best-seller, `My God.' Opposite him we have Dr. Tom Jack:
humanist, broadcaster, lecturer and author of the book, `Hello
Sailor.' Tonight, instead of discussing the existence or
nonexistence of God _ they have decided to fight for it.'' (Stage
lights come up, curtains open. A wrestling ring is in the
background.)
</P>
<P>
   Though the idea of two religious figures fighting to prove the
existence, or nonexistence, of God appears on the surface to be
simply a silly sketch, Terry Jones (Python writer/actor and a
well-respected medieval historian) once pointed out that it was
this same basic principle that was the idea behind the Crusades.
Silly? You decide.
</P>
<P>
   Like many fans, I first became aware of the power of Python in
1974, when PBS began broadcasting the television series. Never
before had I seen a show so willing to take chances and push at the
boundaries of convention.
</P>
<P>
   Like that scene in ``The Wizard of Oz'' where Dorothy steps from
her bleak black-and-white world into the Technicolor tapestry of
Oz, Monty Python was a revelation. Monty Python not only colored my
world view, it cemented my budding desire of becoming a writer. (I
was later fortunate to meet and befriend many of its cast members,
and was privileged to briefly be writing partners with the late
Graham Chapman.)
</P>
<P>
   Now here it is some 25 years after my initial introduction to
Python, and 30 years after the show's formation. After all this
time, after shows like ``South Park'' and ``Beavis and Butthead,''
there has yet to be a show that is as radical, as ``completely
different,'' as Monty Python's Flying Circus.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Yoakum of Atlanta is director of the Graham Chapman
Archives, author of the new book ``The Non-Inflatable Monty Python
TV Companion'' (Dowling Press) and co-author of ``Graham Crackers:
Fuzzy Memories, Silly Bits and Outright Lies by Monty Python's
Graham Chapman'' (The Career Press). His e-mail address is :
whitebike1(at)aol.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
