<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-WEATHER-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOSCOW ROASTS UNDER RECORD HEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Forest fires marching on Moscow, gloomy forecasts for
the harvest, and a rapidly mounting death toll in the waterways
around the city.
</P>
<P>
   These are the bitter fruits of the best summer weather in memory
in Moscow, where a month of record-breaking hot and dry weather has
wrought havoc in this normally chilly northern clime.
</P>
<P>
   Temperatures in the Russian capital have approached 90 nearly
every day for almost a month. New Englanders, suffering through a
heat wave of their own, may think this is nothing to write home
about. But consider that June was the hottest month in Moscow since
Russia started keeping such records 118 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   It has also been one of the deadliest for swimmers who have
flocked to the city's swimming holes to beat the heat. Police said
140 people drowned in Moscow last month, just 10 fewer than the
death toll for all of last summer.
</P>
<P>
   The unusually arid weather has helped create a fire hazard
unseen here in years. Hundreds of acres of woodlands outside Moscow
are burning uncontrollably, with over 50 new blazes each day. Most
of the fires are in areas with large peat bogs, which are hard to
extinguish. No matter how much water firefighters pour on the
blazes, the peat quickly dries out and begins burning again in the
heat.
</P>
<P>
   Vladimir Rubtsov, fire chief of the region surrounding Moscow,
said his troops were lacked equipment and manpower to put out the
blazes and were concentrating on keeping them from consuming
villages. Even that is not always possible.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to stop it'' from spreading to a local
settlement, ``but we are running out of water,'' Lieutenant Renat
Kirillov, in charge of firefighters battling a blaze in a region
southeast of Moscow, told NTV television as thick smoke billowed
behind him. ``We need about two weeks of rain.''
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts indicate he will not get it. July promises to be only
slightly cooler, and while there will be some rain, the hot and dry
pattern is expected to persist.
</P>
<P>
   That is bad news for Russia's farmers, who are facing a second
poor harvest in as many years. Russian agricultural officials are
predicting a disappointing 55 million tons of grain, a tad better
than last year's disastrous crop, but far less than the 70 tons
they had hoped for. Crops were dealt a one-two punch by
unseasonably cold temperatures in late spring _ it snowed in Moscow
on May 15 _ and now the heat wave.
</P>
<P>
   Beleaguered Muscovites, no fans of prolonged stretches of hot
weather even without the fatalities and other bad news, have
struggled to explain the unusual heat and the grim news it has
brought.
</P>
<P>
   ``Clearly there is a geo-magnetic disorder,'' said Olga
Nikolayeva, a former aerospace engineer.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no scientific explanation,'' commented the popular
daily Moskovsky Komsomolets on this week. ``There is nothing left
to do but look for some paranormal phenomenom.''
</P>
<P>
   As far as the deaths and fires are concerned, carelessness
appears to be a more likely factor. Firefighters say 90 percent of
the fires are started by picnickers who forget to put out their
campfires. Police say alcohol is involved in most of the drownings,
many of which have been registered in areas not designated safe for
swimming. Muscovites frequently disregard ``no swimming'' signs and
plunge into ponds and rivers around the city that are unguarded,
polluted, or otherwise unfit for bathing.
</P>
<P>
   Health officials have warned that children, elderly, and people
with heart troubles ought to stay out of the heat. Gennady
Osipenko, Russia's first deputy health minister, called the
situation ``extreme,'' and while he denied press reports of an
increase in strokes and heat-related illnesses, he said ``we can
expect unpleasant things.''
</P>
<P>
   It would be wrong to say everyone is unhappy about the weather.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this rate, who needs southern France?'' asked Marina
Serova, a topless sunbather in a hilly park in a western Moscow
suburb. It is not unheard-of for Muscovites in secluded parks like
this one to bare all in their bid to catch a few rays, and Serova
was no exception.
</P>
<P>
   Others are profiting from the heat.
</P>
<P>
   ``My business, it goes without saying, is booming,'' remarked
Vladimir Kovalyov, who sells air conditioning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
