<HEADER>
A7628 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ZELL-WHITEHOUSE03-COX     07-02 0467
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZELL-WHITEHOUSE03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton to give Miller foreign investment post
 &HT;    By Maria Saporta
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ President Clinton plans to nominate former Gov. Zell
Miller to serve on the board of the Overseas Private Investment
Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The appointment to OPIC's 15-member board is the first offer
from Clinton that Miller has accepted. Before Miller left office in
January, the Clinton administration had offered to name him
secretary of the Navy, according to U.S. Sen. Max Cleland, who
serves on the Senate Armed Services Committee.
</P>
<P>
   The OPIC appointment was attractive to Miller because it will
not require him to move to Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``I like working in public-private partnerships,'' Miller said.
``I can't confirm (the appointment), but it is the kind of
public-private partnership that appeals to me. OPIC is one of the
best examples of a public-private partnership in the federal
government.''
</P>
<P>
   OPIC encourages economic growth in developing countries and
emerging markets by financing and protecting U.S. investment
overseas. OPIC has accumulated reserves of more than $3 billion and
has supported investments worth nearly $112 billion in developing
countries.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was the first one that the governor has bit on,'' Cleland
said. ``It's wonderful news for Georgia because Georgia has more
and more companies that want to invest overseas. I will be glad to
lead the nomination, and we hope to get the governor confirmed in
record time.''
</P>
<P>
   The White House refused to comment on reports of the job offer.
</P>
<P>
   Miller, one of the first of the nation's governors to strongly
support Clinton's presidential aspirations, played a key role in
getting the Arkansas governor elected to the White House. Georgia
was the first state to deliver a Clinton victory during the
Democratic primaries in 1992. Miller also delivered the keynote
address at the 1992 Democratic National Convention, which nominated
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The OPIC appointment finally gets Miller officially working in
the Clinton administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Clinton feels so strongly about Zell as a public
servant and someone who has helped him so much, he wanted to have
him on his team,'' Cleland said. ``Governor Miller has declined
other offers. I think now the president and the governor have found
a perfect match.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton almost had found a match when he offered Miller the post
of Navy secretary. Miller, a former Marine, has told friends the
Navy post appealed to him. He had also been mentioned as a possible
secretary of Education, a post that would have allowed him to draw
on his experience as a college professor and his work with HOPE
scholarships and pre-kindergarten programs.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
