</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0213 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7636 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KEEGAN-HISTORY-2TAKES     07-02 1081
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KEEGAN-HISTORY-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MILITARY HISTORIAN PUTS VIVID CAST ON WORLD WAR I 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By MEL GUSSOW   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During World War II, John Keegan and his family were evacuated
from London to Taunton in the western English countryside. While
German bombs fell on London, he grew up listening to stories about
his father's service in World War I. ``He was a very gentle person,
a most unlikely soldier,'' Keegan said in an interview, ``but it
was the most important experience of his life.'' And hearing about
it became one of the most important experiences of his son's life.
</P>
<P>
   There never was a possibility that Keegan might one day find
himself in battle. A bout with tuberculosis in his teen-age years
left him partly lame, disqualifying him for the military. Now 65,
he says he has never regretted not being a soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was a child of the war and I was fascinated by it,'' he
said. ``I took a tremendous interest in what was going on around me
and was old enough to read news magazines.'' Later, after studying
military history at Oxford University and teaching at the Royal
Military Academy at Sandhurst, he followed a natural course and
became a military historian.
</P>
<P>
   For years he has been considered one of the best, a master of
war and military tactics. With his 14 books and his experience as a
military correspondent of The Daily Telegraph in London, he has
devoted his life to the single subject of war.
</P>
<P>
   His 1976 book, ``The Face of Battle,'' which focused on the
common soldier and the common officer, is a cornerstone of military
history. In his other works he has analyzed conflicts from the U.S.
Civil War to World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Now, in his new book, ``The First World War,'' which has
received enthusiastic reviews, he deals in depth with an event that
has recently become an object of greater public attention in novels
as well as in nonfiction.
</P>
<P>
   ``The First World War was a tragic and unnecessary conflict'' he
writes. It ``ended the lives of 10 million human beings, tortured
the emotional lives of millions more, destroyed the benevolent and
optimistic culture of the European conflict'' and led directly to
World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Without it, he said during a recent visit to New York,
``Bolshevism and Fascism would have been minor movements,'' and
``Hitler might have lived out his life as a Viennese dropout.''
</P>
<P>
   What distinguishes Keegan's work from that of other historians
is that he has approached his subject not as an academic but more
as an investigative journalist, one with a novelist's eye for
conjuring the atmosphere and immediacy of men in battle. ``The
First World War'' is a vivid, step-by-step account with, in typical
Keegan fashion, a strong sense of narrative. If the book seems to
the reader like reliving the war, it was even more disturbing for
the author to write.
</P>
<P>
   As it came time to write about each skirmish, he was always
aware of the approaching loss of life. He said that he would think
to himself, ``Here come another 200,000 casualties.'' This was
particularly true when he reached the battle of Passendale in
Belgium. In his book, he calls this 1917 clash ``the most notorious
land campaign'' of the war.
</P>
<P>
   ``I knew exactly what was coming up,'' he explained as he sipped
a glass of bourbon at his Manhattan hotel. The rugged looking
writer speaks with the self-assurance of a television commentator.
``It was a dreadful battle because it was fought in West Flanders,
very near the sea. More than three years of shelling had destroyed
the drainage system. So when it rained, and it rained heavily in
the fall of 1917, the ground became a swamp. You get these awful
descriptions of men plodding forward up to their thighs in mud. The
soldiers get hit, they fall down and they drown in mud.'' Nearly
70,000 British soldiers died in that battle and 170,000 were
wounded.
</P>
<P>
   Although Keegan writes with astonishing immediacy, he confessed
in ``The Face of Battle'' that his was an outsider's view of war:
he had very little idea of what it was like to be on the front
lines.
</P>
<P>
   Now, several wars and many books later, does he still feel that
way?
</P>
<P>
   ``If anything, it must be worse than my imagination suggested,''
he said. In his work for The Telegraph he has occasionally been
near battles, once in Lebanon, another time on maneuvers on the
U.S. battleship Missouri. More often he has visited battlefields of
the past, a necessary part of his research. He has been everywhere
from Gettysburg to Gallipoli, hoping to find something unexpected.
For example, he was surprised to discover the smallness of
Gallipoli: so much fighting in so limited a space.
</P>
<P>
   Keegan says that many of his early images of war came from films
and novels. One of his criticisms of Stanley Kubrick's World war I
movie ``Paths of Glory'' is that the film was ``too neat and
tidy.'' In contrast, he said, ``the first half-hour of `Saving
Private Ryan' is the most terrifying, realistic thing ever done in
the cinema.''
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to fictional representations of battle, one of his
favorites is ``A Farewell to Arms'': ``It is an absolutely
marvelous book. Professional historians who read it can't shake off
the influence.''
</P>
<P>
   His new book paints detailed portraits of men at war. One of the
most intriguing characters is British general Douglas Haig, who
managed to ignore the casualties and ``to be untouched by the
suffering.'' ``He was a strange man, a very cold fish,'' Keegan
said. ``A good general but a defective person.''
</P>
<P>
   Keegan wrote his book at his home in a farming village in
Wiltshire, a calm, bucolic environment. Nevertheless, he had to
fight his own depression and ``overcome a series of emotional
barriers'' as he wrote about such horrendous events. But he pushed
on, always keeping his equilibrium about his research. ``Dr.
Johnson said the writing of history only involves powers of the
lower imagination. Its demands are much less than those made by
lyric poetry.''
</P>
<P>
   Each of his books has been preoccupied with a central theme. He
wrote ``about groups of men'' in ``Six Armies in Normandy'' (1982)
and about generals in ``The Mask of Command'' (1987). Then he moved
from naval history to ``The History of Warfare'' (1993) and ``The
Second World War'' (1990), which was pegged to the 50th anniversary
of that conflict. He viewed that war as ``a great morality play, a
story of good against evil which isn't true at all about the First
World War.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1840EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0214 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7637 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BOSNIA-MUSLIMS-BOS &LR;      07-02 1239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOSNIA-MUSLIMS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER YEARS OF STRIFE, MUSLIMS CAN LIVE OPENLY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES A. RADIN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARAJEVO, Bosnia and Herzegovina _ Early in each broiling day,
late into each cool night, the calls-to-prayer of the muezzim echo
across the city with an intensity that is noticeably greater now
than in the years before ethnic warfare reshaped Bosnia.
</P>
<P>
   In the streets outside the mosques, far more women wear
traditional Muslim dress than when Bosnia was an ethnically
integrated place. But, perhaps of equal import, they often are
arm-in-arm with friends in sharp European fashion _ clothes which
would not pass the modesty test in many Muslim countries.
</P>
<P>
   Here no one blinks, save admiring young men.
</P>
<P>
   Three years of bitter fighting against Orthodox Christian Serbs
and Roman Catholic Croats has electrified the consciousness of
Bosnia's Muslims, who after nearly a century of repression now have
a rare chance to freely express their religion and culture.
</P>
<P>
   How they do it will be important not just for their futures
here, but also for prospects for peace and reconcilliation
throughout the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
   If they become insular, alienated, or more orthodox, the dream
of foreigners and former Yugoslavians to restore a multi-ethnic
society in the region is likely doomed. If, despite all the Bosnian
Muslims have suffered, they continue to embrace Europe as well as
Islam, they could create in Sarajevo the new capital of the
Balkans, a city untainted by the nationalistic histories and
animosities of Belgrade and Zagreb.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tolerance and reconciliation are favored words
internationally,'' says Raisu-L-Ulama Mustafa Ceric, Islam's
leading scholar-priest in the Balkans. ``We need more than that.
First we need understanding and acceptance of each other as we
are.'' He stresses the last three words, and uses them often.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, though, the basics of Bosnian Muslim identity have
changed as a result of the war, in which Serbia and Croatia tried
to divide Bosnia between themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Before the war, ``Muslims were the most indifferent of the
religions, the most open to other communities,'' says Seid Smaikic,
the mufti of Herzegovina, a southern part of the country which
still is bitterly contested between Muslims and Croats.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got nothing for giving up our identity, for the mixed
marriages, for all the efforts of the Muslim community to meet the
others half way,'' Smaikic says. ``We gained nothing in their eyes.
It came to the point where you had to say `I am what I am' and
return to your own religion.''
</P>
<P>
   Jacques Klein, a Franco-American diplomat active in postwar
reconciliation efforts both in Bosnia and Croatia, says before the
war Muslim faith was ``a thin veneer. People ate pork, drank,
whatever.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war made them think `Why are we being killed here?' So
they asked for help, and the Arabs and Persians saw an opening to
build a foothold into Europe.''
</P>
<P>
   The awakening of a more-heartfelt identity and the offers of
assistance from the Islamic world both had the potential to change
profoundly the focus of Bosnian Muslims. But the foreign alliances
did not take, and the religious resurgence seems entirely moderate.
</P>
<P>
   Several thousand Afghans, Libyans, and other would-be holy
warriors showed up, and some film footage from the war shows them
leading charges into almost-certain death. But they could not
inspite the local Muslims to follow suit.
</P>
<P>
   Funds still flow from some Arab states to Muslim units of the
Muslim-Croat army, much as Croatia supports Croat units; the
massive support for schools and mosques also is coming in,
principally from Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   The funds for support of religious institutions are refurbishing
buildings and reviving communities devastated in the war but, as in
the case of the military aid, they are not changing Bosnia's
Muslims deeply.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state has no right to prescribe how one will dress,'' says
Ceric, whose wife wears traditional Muslim clothes and whose
daughter does not. ``Neither will we be prescribed to by some
circle in Iran. The principle in the Koran is there is no
compulsion in religion. But also there is no compulsion in
secularization.''
</P>
<P>
   Hermann F. Eilts, a Boston University specialist on the Middle
East and Islam, says such independence of thinking and practice,
along with their ethnic roots and geographical location, combine to
keep Bosnia's Muslims on the periphery of the Islamic world.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is sympathy for them, but they don't really fit into the
mainstream,'' says Eilts. ``First they are Slavs'' whose ancestors
converted to Islam during the 500-year rule of the Ottoman Turks in
Bosnia. ``Second, they are often lumped together with all the rest
of Europe as past of the `Crusader experience.' There is suspicion
of them, and of the Kosovars, because they don't follow the dress
codes and religious practices'' strictly enough.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Bosnian and Kosovar Muslims also have been
viewed with suspicion by European leaders because of their
religion, a reality that Serb abnd Croat politicians have sometimes
used effectively against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe (the late French President Francois) Mitterand is
suffering in hell now for what happened in Bosnia,'' Ceric says. He
and other leaders of Western Europe in the early 1990s were ``only
too willing to believe (Yugoslav President Slobodan) Milosevic
telling them that we were fundamentalists, and that he would finish
the job (of repression) quickly.''
</P>
<P>
   Though the war almost four years in the past and many parts of
Bosnia are humming with reconstruction activity, Muslims are
sharply divided in their understanding of the current state of
affairs.
</P>
<P>
   In Mostar, in the south, there are separate universities,
electric companies, water companies _ everything between Croats and
Muslims is separated.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't even have a soccer match without it being a political
question,'' says Mufti Smaikic, whose whitewashed office in an
restored riverside mosque is decorated with sumptuous carved woods
and beautiful, pastel-tinted caligraphy donated by foreign Muslims.
``All this was destroyed during the war,'' he says. ``The
aggressors were trying to destroy our heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, he says, the Muslim perception is that the Croats ``want
the European Union, the West, to tire of this, and pull out. Then,
they think, they will take over... and the Muslims will
disappear.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ceric, the leading Muslim of the whole region, says the
trends are positive for his faith.
</P>
<P>
   ``The concept of dividing Bosnia between Serbs and Croats is
still there, but it is weaker now than a year ago, and it will be
weaker still a year from now,'' he says. ``These forces are
losing.''
</P>
<P>
   He cites a host of developments, such as the rebuilding of
mosques in Banja Luka and the return of Muslims to Prijedor, as
signs that ``the prospects are better.''
</P>
<P>
   But most important, he says, upcoming generations will be better
able than their parents and grandparents to understand the unique
position of Bosnia's Muslims, and accept it as it is.
</P>
<P>
   ``I trust more the young people than the old ones,'' Ceric says.
Based on their experience in this war, ``generally speaking, this
younger generation understand that they have one foot in the
European circle and one in the Islamic circle. They won't give up
either.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
