<HEADLINE>
HISTORY AND TIGERS AND THE 4TH, OH MY! 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By JOHN LEVESQUE  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As Bullwinkle used to say, there's nothing up my sleeve. But
just watch how I weave the Declaration of Independence and a bunch
of Siberian tigers into the same column.
</P>
<P>
   The act of a desperate critic during TV's annual summer swoon,
you say? Perhaps. But even if they're as dissimilar as moose and
squirrel, ``The Declaration of Independence'' and ``In the Shadow
of the Tiger'' do share a dubious distinction: a Saturday night
time slot on a holiday weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It's not exactly the kiss of death in programming circles. That
would be Sunday at, say, 10 a.m. But let's call it the kiss of a
near-death experience, which actually might be appropriate for
Christina and Joseph Pontecorvo. The Seattle-based filmmakers are
the producers of ``In the Shadow of the Tiger,'' airing as part of
Discovery Channel's ``Wild Discovery'' series. The documentary
required three trips to the Russian Far East, and at least one
encounter with a not-too-happy Siberian tiger.
</P>
<P>
   Though the tiger was ensnared (so it could be fitted with a
signal-transmitting collar), a filmmaker usually has one or two
what-the-heck-am-I-doing-here moments before the animal is
tranquilized. For the Pontecorvos, it was when they and a couple of
scientists working with the University of Idaho's Hornocker
Wildlife Institute approached the slightly annoyed tiger and really
got its fight-or-flight juices going.
</P>
<P>
   With only two toes caught in the cable snare, the tiger lunged
left, then right, and then directly at the camera Joseph Pontecorvo
was holding a few yards away. Happy to report the cable held fast,
and the Pontecorvos succeeded in completing their first
documentary. As nature specials go, it's fairly standard stuff. Not
exactly in the National Geographic stratum, but worthy of an animal
lover's attention. Even though a disclaimer at the end mentions
that some of the actual tiger footage was obtained at a breeding
enclosure and not in the wild, Joseph Pontecorvo's camera work is
arresting and exceptionally well lit. The writing, for which both
Pontecorvos take credit, is not as scintillating, leaning more to
the cliched than to the adventurous.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the hourlong film, narrated by actor Peter Coyote, nobly
takes viewers into a little-known environment where a few hundred
magnificent animals are struggling to keep going while the world
around them keeps putting up stop signs.
</P>
<P>
   For a much less esoteric topic, The History Channel uses old
movie clips, unexpected background music and those now-familiar
``dramatic re-creations'' to keep people awake through a one-hour
look at the Declaration of Independence.
</P>
<P>
   This entry in the ``Save Our History'' initiative will probably
satisfy history buffs and trivia freaks, but the casual channel
surfer may have a hard time staying glued to it. Harry Smith
narrates in between the offerings of talking-head historians who
enthusiastically share what they know about the declaration, but
it's about 30 minutes more than this history lover could handle
without a nap.
</P>
<P>
   The ``original'' Declaration doesn't exist, or at least it
hasn't shown up yet on ``Antiques Roadshow.'' The manuscript
ratified on July 4, 1776, from which a Philadelphia printer typeset
150 ``broadsides,'' has never surfaced, though 25 of the parchment
broadsides still exist in various museum and library collections.
Meanwhile, the handwritten parchment copy hanging in the National
Archives is a facsimile ordered by the Second Continental Congress
on July 19, 1776, and signed by 56 delegates on or after Aug. 2.
</P>
<P>
   Good thing they stayed with the Fourth of July for the holiday.
Celebrating the Second of August just doesn't have the same oomph.
Besides, it's too close to Labor Day.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
