<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-SECURITY-1STLD-WRITETHRU-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PROBE FINDS SECURITY BREAKDOWNS AT LIVERMORE LAB 
</HEADLINE>
   (EDs: SUBS 5thgraf, Along with, to clarify potential attack;
pickup: The team's)  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By MARK HELM  
 c.1999 Hearst Newspapers  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Months after allegations of Chinese espionage at
America's nuclear laboratories, foreign scientists without security
clearances continued to have access to the main computer at the
Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory, according to an Energy
Department investigation.
</P>
<P>
   The investigation's findings, parts of which were released
Friday, also said that Livermore scientists may have mistakenly
placed classified nuclear information on that computer system.
</P>
<P>
   The breakdown in security at the lab in Livermore, Calif., was
uncovered by an investigative team from the new office of security
oversight set up by Energy Secretary Bill Richardson in response to
allegations of Chinese spying at Livermore and at Los Alamos
National Laboratory in New Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The DOE team discovered the lax security in early May.
</P>
<P>
   Along with discovering weaknesses in computer security, the
investigation also found that the lab failed to properly protect
nuclear materials and was inadequately prepared in the event of a
terrorist attack.
</P>
<P>
   The team's findings were presented Thursday night in a
classified briefing to members of the House Commerce Committee,
which plans to conduct its own review of the nation's nuclear
weapons research complex.
</P>
<P>
   The special DOE audit found that foreign scientists working with
the lab but based abroad could dial-up the Livermore computer
system even though they lacked security clearances, according to
Rep. Tom Bliley, R-Va., chairman of the Commerce Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley said the department also found that:
</P>
<P>
   _ Livermore scientists may have mistakenly placed classified
nuclear information on that computer system.
</P>
<P>
   _ The department had failed to adequately monitor e-mail.
</P>
<P>
   _ The lab's security forces did not have an adequate plan to
counter potential attacks by terrorists. Reaction time was slow and
not all ``pathways'' for potential access were adequately covered.
</P>
<P>
   ``The American people should know that their nuclear secrets are
not yet safe and secure,'' Bliley said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the investigation raised ``serious doubts'' about the
quality of day-to-day management and oversight of the lab.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Energy Department owns the Livermore facility, the
University of California manages it under contract to the
department.
</P>
<P>
   ``It should not take an inspection by the Energy Department's
independent oversight office to find some of these serious security
problems,'' Bliley said.
</P>
<P>
   Bliley and other key Republicans have expressed skepticism that
Richardson can solve the department's counterintelligence and
security problems without the creation of a semiautonomous agency
within the Energy Department to oversee all aspects of its nuclear
program. Richardson has strongly resisted such a move.
</P>
<P>
   Questions about security at nuclear weapons facilities arose in
March as details from a congressional investigation began to
surface describing the loss of nuclear secrets to China in the
1980s and into the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   The controversy intensified after Richardson directed the firing
of a scientist at the Los Alamos lab in early March after he had
been under investigation for possible espionage since 1996. The
scientist, Wen Ho Lee, has not been charged with any crime and has
denied giving nuclear secrets to anyone.
</P>
<P>
   The Energy Department's security review at Livermore was
conducted by inspectors from the new Office of Security Oversight.
Similar inspections will be made at the Los Alamos and Sandia labs
in New Mexico in the coming weeks, department officials said.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to conducting top-secret nuclear weapons research,
the Livermore lab also has nuclear weapons material on site.
</P>
<P>
   &UR;  &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Mark Helm can be reached at 202-298-6920 or at the e-mail
address mark(at)hearstdc.com)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
