<HEADLINE>
PASSIONS' CREATOR IS VETERAN OF DAYTIME DRAMA 
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
(For release Sunday, July 4 or thereafter)  
By CAROL BIDWELL  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The idea of setting a soap opera in history-rich
New England had been rattling around in soap guru James E. Reilly's
mind for a long time.
</P>
<P>
   There'd be all that atmosphere to draw on _ white churches with
steeples, town squares, spooky graveyards, the fall colors. The
characters could range from the haves and the have-nots to the
wanna-bes and the never-will-bes, with a few off-center townsfolk
thrown in for good measure.
</P>
<P>
   And Reilly being Reilly (he was ``Days of Our Lives''' head
writer when Marlena, possessed by the devil, burned the town church
and levitated above her bed), he might also throw in a touch _ or
more _ of the supernatural.
</P>
<P>
   Thus was born ``Passions,'' NBC's newest soap opera, which
debuts Monday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over 20 years in daytime (TV), without realizing it, I was
probably making mental notes for this,'' said Reilly, who moved
from New York to Los Angeles to supervise the first year's
production for the new show, which films in Studio City. Location
scenes will be shot in Camden, Maine, and in the Fisherman's
Village waterfront area of Channel Islands Harbor in Oxnard. For a
few initial scenes, three actors and a camera crew went all the way
to Paris.
</P>
<P>
   ```Passions' is going to be a classic soap that's been
repackaged for the next millennium,'' Reilly promised. ``It's going
to be about family, and it's going to be romantic. And it's going
to have lots of secrets; secrets provide surprises.
</P>
<P>
   ``On the surface, it's serene and calm, like the swans swimming
on the town pond. But underneath, it's totally different, as it is
in any small town.''
</P>
<P>
   NBC has given Reilly _ who over the past two decades has either
been head writer or part of a writing team on eight soap operas on
all three major networks _ unprecedented say in getting the new
soap off the ground. He's been the man behind everything from
choosing the locale to selecting the music for the opening credits.
</P>
<P>
   ``About the only things I haven't had anything to do with are
makeup and costumes,'' Reilly said with a laugh. ``But I've lived
with this (show) in my head for so long. I tend to visualize my
scenes. I have to have a working model in my head. I will close my
eyes and I will see these characters coming in to a restaurant, so
the restaurant must have a certain look.''
</P>
<P>
   It's unusual to give a series creator/head writer that kind of
power. But this !ital!is!off! the script doctor who's turned a
half-dozen flagging series around, luring new viewers with one
outrageous plot turn after another.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think NBC has complete confidence in Jim,'' said
``Passions'' executive producer Lisa Hesser, who sees herself as a
facilitator, a sort of operations manager to make Reilly's tales
come alive on screen. ``He has a proven track record, and I think
any network would have loved to have him come and tell his story
there. The key to a successful soap is a singular vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Some of Reilly's most important decisions, besides locale, have
been naming the series and casting 22 contract players, plus actors
to play recurring characters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The name `Passions' came to me literally at the last minute,''
he said. ``Finally, I asked myself, `What basically is happening on
this show?' If you had to put it down to one word, it really
!ital!is!off! passions of all kinds _ love, hate, life, hope.''
</P>
<P>
   Unwittingly, Reilly scored a major casting coup: He hired Liza
Huber, 23-year-old daughter of soap diva Susan Lucci (``All My
Children's'' Erica Kane), to play socialite Gwen Hotchkiss, whose
boyfriend happens to be the heir to the town's old-money fortune.
</P>
<P>
   Huber was one of a slew of actresses who auditioned, and ``she
fit the character best,'' Reilly said. ``I didn't know she was
Susan Lucci's daughter until after she was hired.''
</P>
<P>
   But he's glad to have her aboard. In addition to having
impeccable credentials _ a degree in film production from the
University of North Carolina, acting studies at the Lee Strasberg
Theatre Institute in New York and rave reviews in her off-Broadway
debut in ``Four Dogs and a Bone'' last fall _ Huber has grown up
around soap operas and knows the grueling work that's involved,
Reilly said.
</P>
<P>
   Huber said she's thrilled to have a sizable role on the new
soap.
</P>
<P>
   ``They never would have hired me if they didn't like my work,
but to know I got it on my own is wonderful,'' Huber said. The work
has been nonstop so far, ``but I've grown up on sets, seeing how
busy it is, so I have no trouble with that. And I love it. I
!ital!love!off! it! It's like doing a play a day. It's quick, but
we're trying to get in as much rehearsal as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   While Huber's famous mom is overjoyed to see her offspring snag
a prime soap role, she's staying in the background so her daughter
can shine on her own.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only advice she gave me is what you'd expect: Be honest
with (delivering) your lines, be gracious to the people you work
with, be professional, and do your best,'' Huber said.
</P>
<P>
   Like Huber, most of the new soap's cast members are relative
unknowns. But Reilly hired a veteran actress _ Emmy winner Juliet
Mills, who starred in the early 1970s prime-time series ``Nanny and
the Professor'' _ for a pivotal role.
</P>
<P>
   Some people might consider Mills' character, Tabitha Lenox, a
witch. Reilly describes her as ``the town oddity. All I can say is
she's someone who manages to do things that other people can't ...
Of course, it !ital!could!off! turn out to be more sinister.''
</P>
<P>
   Ah, there's that supernatural theme again.
</P>
<P>
   And what better place to lure the spirits out than a fictional
town founded in the mid-1600s?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been the center of great loves, great hates, great
passions for 350 years,'' Reilly said of Harmony, the town he
created in his head. ``It's the one area of the country where you
wouldn't be surprised to see ghosts. I think there's a reason
Stephen King has placed most of his works in New England. It lends
itself to that, ever since Ichabod Crane and the Headless
Horseman.''
</P>
<P>
   But Ichabod Crane may have had an easier time of it than this
new show, which replaces just-canceled ``Another World'' after a
35-year run.
</P>
<P>
   On the Internet and in fan magazines, the most vocal of ``AW's''
2.5 million longtime fans have soundly denounced NBC for canceling
their favorite show, vowing never to watch another NBC soap,
especially ``Passions.''
</P>
<P>
   Reilly knows he's facing an uphill battle to secure the new
daytime series a place in viewers' hearts.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is that negative element, which we can't help,'' Reilly
said. ``But we'd like `Another World' fans to stick around to see
what we have to offer, and we want to bring in young viewers, too,
so they can grow up with `Passions' like their mothers and
grandmothers did with `Another World.' We hope they'll just give us
a chance _ and we hope we'll be around for decades to come.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
