<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SAMPRAIS PASSES INTO SEMIFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB DUFFY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ No, it wasn't a hallucination. This really was
Wimbledon. It just looked like the Davis Cup.
</P>
<P>
   The men's singles quarterfinals Friday were spiced by a couple
of potential previews of the US-Australia match at Longwood in two
weeks. On the court, the Americans and Australians split. In the
trainer's room and the interview room, the United States earned an
edge.
</P>
<P>
   Top seed Pete Sampras, who has vowed he would play only doubles
at Longwood so as not to horn in on the US incumbents, got a pass
into Saturday's semifinals when No. 7 Mark Philippoussis was forced
to withdraw with a left knee injury while leading, 6-4, 1-2. After
an MRI and an examination by an orthopedic specialist, the injury
was diagnosed as a torn cartilage that will sideline Philippoussis
for 4-6 weeks, meaning he won't be in Boston. In his place,
Australian captain John Newcombe named 17-year-old Lleyton Hewitt,
who has traveled with the Davis Cup entourage for two years but
hasn't played a match.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, No. 8 Todd Martin _ for whom the official Wimbledon
term ``gentlemen's singles'' was coined _ dropped a gritty 6-3,
6-7, 7-6, 7-6 decision to No. 2 Patrick Rafter, then offered to
relinquish his Cup singles position to Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   Of more immediate import, the main order of business _
determining the champions of the world's most prestigious tennis
tournament _ is at last coming into focus. Belatedly, to be sure,
because rain has wreaked havoc with the schedule, which means both
men's and women's semifinals will be Saturday and the finals
Sunday, wretched weather permitting.
</P>
<P>
   At least the final fours have been determined. Andre Agassi,
looking untouchable since his astounding French Open triumph,
ruined the Brazilian festival on Court 2 by brushing aside No. 11
Gustavo Kuerten, 6-3, 6-4, 6-4. And Tim Henman, the Great Wight
Hope _ and the rest of Britain's, too _ banished former finalist
Cedric Pioline, 6-4, 2-6, 6-4, 6-3. So it will be Sampras-Henman
and Agassi-Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   Among the women, Alexandra Stevenson became the first survivor
of the qualifying tournament ever to reach the Wimbledon semis,
dispatching fellow qualifier Jelena Dokic, 6-3, 1-6, 6-3. Unseeded
Mirjana Lucic was the second long shot to cash in, ousting 1998
runner-up Nathalie Tauziat, 4-6, 6-4, 7-5, rallying from a 3-5
deficit in the deciding set. The two kids _ Lucic, 17, and
Stevenson, 18 _ will be overwhelming underdogs against the No. 2
and 3 seeds, Steffi Graf and Lindsay Davenport, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of gallant gestures, Martin aced the field. After his
grueling loss, he was asked if there were any way Sampras might
wind up playing singles at Longwood, especially if he wins this
tournament for the sixth time in seven years. Sampras, remember, is
a late-comer, having bypassed the United States' first-round Cup
match at Birmingham, England, where Martin, Jim Courier, and Alex
O'Brien posted a stirring 3-2 triumph that has inspired
unprecedented American interest in the competition. Sampras then
asked in, but only to play doubles, because he didn't feel it would
be fair to displace Martin or Courier.
</P>
<P>
   Friday Martin said, ``I would volunteer'' to defer to Sampras in
singles. ``I think Pete should be playing singles, and I don't know
if Pete thinks that, I don't know if Gully (US captain Tom
Gullikson) thinks that, and I don't know if Jim thinks that, but I
want our best team out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Martin somewhat couched his noblesse oblige, saying, ``I
don't necessarily feel like I'm the one that should not be
playing.''
</P>
<P>
   But he also knows there's no way Gullikson will sit out Courier,
whose five-set triumphs over England's finest, Henman and Greg
Rusedski, paced the Americans at Birmingham and who had a
spectacular run here before losing to Henman in a five-set
fourth-round match. So guess who that would leave out.
</P>
<P>
   Gullikson said Thursday that the players' preferences won't be
the deciding factors, anyway. ``All I'll say is that Pete is on the
team,'' he said. ``He gives us the maximum amount of options and
flexibility. I'm the captain and I reserve the right to make the
decision. We'll at least have a team discussion.''
</P>
<P>
   No matter what, Martin's willingness to play only doubles would
make that discussion a lot less tense.
</P>
<P>
   That's no surprise for those familiar with Martin, whose talent
is exceeded only by his courtliness. That was evident Friday during
one of the biggest matches of his life when he several times
overruled calls by umpire Andreas Egli and awarded points to
Rafter.
</P>
<P>
   The most critical _ and noble _ occurred at 2-2 in the fourth
set with Martin serving at 15-30. As his serve landed, he noticed a
ball from an adjacent court drop on Rafter's side and immediately
called a let because he felt Rafter could be distracted and the
point should be replayed. Rafter never saw the ball and fired a
return that eluded Martin. Egli called the let, Rafter protested _
and Martin concurred, telling Egli, ``I wouldn't have gotten to
that ball, anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   There was no such fortune for Rafter's would-be Australian
teammate, Philippoussis, who clearly had Sampras in trouble on
Centre Court after the first set.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question he was outplaying me,'' said Sampras.
</P>
<P>
   But at 1-1, deuce, in the second, Philippoussis lunged one way
for a backhand volley and his right knee went the other.
Philippoussis played out the game, but on Sampras's ensuing serve,
he stood stone still _ and not by choice. After being examined by
the trainer, he was forced to abandon the match.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I landed, I sort of fell awkwardly,'' he said. ``I felt
like I landed OK, but I heard a click and I grabbed it and I
thought nothing of it until he hit a serve. Then when I sort of
jumped forward to split-step, my knee just gave way and I heard a
huge click. And then again on the second serve, I split-stepped and
I heard a big click again, and I obviously knew right there. I
mean, I was extremely worried, and it just got stiffer and stiffer,
and then when the (trainer) came out, I thought there was no
chance.''
</P>
<P>
   Newcombe, who was broadcasting the match on Australian TV, had
to cope with the fact that he won't have Philippoussis to face the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it hurts our confidence,'' he said. ``But
certainly we would have been going in hoping Philippoussis could
win at least one of his two singles. I'd have to say the odds have
shifted slightly to the US instead of being 50-50.''
</P>
<P>
   But first they have to take care of the final details over here.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
