<HEADLINE>
BERGOMI TO STAY HOME AND NURSE AILMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By FRANK DELL'APA  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Revolution player-coach Walter Zenga has something in common
with Sunday's opponent, the New York/New Jersey MetroStars.
</P>
<P>
   Zenga returned for Friday's practice at Babson College without
the high-profile Italian player that he has been seeking. But,
unlike the MetroStars, Zenga's team appears to be galvanizing for a
playoff campaign _ with or without foreign intervention.
</P>
<P>
   Giuseppe Bergomi, the former Inter defender who announced he
would visit the Revolution this month, apparently is out of the
picture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Beppe wants to stay in Italy and rest because he has some
physical problems,'' said Zenga, who traveled to Italy after the
Revolution's 2-0 loss to Dallas Saturday. ``The door will always be
open for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Zenga hoped to use his relationships with former opponents and
teammates to replace Dutch defender Richard Goulooze, who left the
team this week. But Zenga was hampered by the low wages of Major
League Soccer and the fact that MetroStars general manager Charlie
Stillitano had approached potential candidates first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I checked with a lot of players in Italy,'' Zenga said. ``And
every time, they said the same thing: `Walter, you are in America
now, do you know Stillitano in New York? Because he has already
talked to me.' New York must have talked to 1,000 players.''
</P>
<P>
   But Zenga has adopted a realistic attitude about the combination
of modest budgets and unambitious acquisition policies of the MLS.
He added Mario Gori, a 26-year-old Argentinian defender, from Miami
in exchange for veteran midfielder Edwin Gorter last week. And the
Revolution are expected to next week audition JoJo, a Mozambican
wing midfielder whose full name is Jorge Miguel Moreira Larrouy
Fernandes. JoJo, 28, has played for Boavista, Penafiel, and
Belenenses in Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whether it is a big name or not, we want a good player,''
Zenga said. ``You have to choose what is best for your team. And
the player has to understand my philosophy. The important thing is
for them to have a good attitude about playing with us in the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are looking for one foreign player and we have three or
four possibilities. We want to be 100 percent certain. We have 20
good players now and we have a great lockerroom, and everyone knows
what we want to accomplish this season.''
</P>
<P>
   The Revolution (15 points, 15 games) hold a 3-point lead over
fourth-place Tampa Bay in the Eastern Conference. They have home
games against the MetroStars and Los Angeles (July 11) before the
All-Star break.
</P>
<P>
   ``We only got 3 points but we deserved 9 points against
Columbus, Tampa Bay, and Dallas,'' Zenga said. ``The days will come
when we can play bad and still get 3 points in a game. But I am
happy with the mentality and philosophy of the team. If we keep
playing like this, the results will come soon.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Foxboro Stadium is a candidate for an Aug. 8 CONCACAF Gold Cup
playoff involving Canada, Cuba, El Salvador, and Haiti . . . Jamar
Beasley scored for New Hampshire in a 3-2 loss to Raleigh in an A
League game Wednesday night. Beasley and midfielder Paulo Dos
Santos are expected to join the Boston Bulldogs for a Tuesday match
against the Toronto Lynx.
</P>
</TEXT>
