<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 18:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7661 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-$ADV0     07-02 0838
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-5-QUESTIONS-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON'S MEDICARE PLAN: A SOLID STEP ONE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   President Clinton promised to issue his own plan to reform
Medicare when his appointees to a bipartisan federal commission,
whose chairman was Sen. John B. Breaux of Louisiana, blocked
agreement last March.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made good on that promise last week, releasing a plan
that he says would cover prescription drugs for the first time;
eliminate co-payments and deductibles on preventive services like
cancer screening; raise deductibles for clinical laboratory and
physician services, and inject more competition from private
managed-care plans. In general, Democrats reacted approvingly and
Republicans suspiciously.
</P>
<P>
   Jeffrey Lemieux, who was a senior economist on the Breaux
commission, now has the same title at the Progressive Policy
Institute, which is affiliated with the centrist Democratic
Leadership Council. He discussed the plan's strengths, weaknesses
and prospects last week. Here are excerpts. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Would the Clinton plan provide adequately for the
elderly?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Clinton makes an important start by bringing drug coverage
into the Medicare benefit package. But Medicare benefits would
still be skimpy.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, Medicare would cover about $2,000 of the
first $5,000 of pharmaceutical costs. Patients would pay all drug
costs above $5,000 a year. Nor would the Clinton plan provide
stop-loss protection _ a cap on out-of-pocket medical costs _ which
is offered as part of many private-sector plans. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Would the Clinton plan bring soaring Medicare costs
under control?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Clinton proposes to raise Medicare outlays even higher over
the next 10 years, though by a small amount. Breaux's plan would
have brought Medicare costs down a bit.
</P>
<P>
   I prefer Breaux's proposal because it would put a cap on the
contribution of general tax revenues to total Medicare spending.
Clinton's idea of tossing $800 billion of general tax revenues into
Medicare over the next 15 years could make Congress complacent,
willing to sit back while the program is flush rather than make
tough decisions to control costs as the baby boomers begin to
retire. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q (italics)What are the Clinton plan's strengths?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. Its best point is an intriguing proposal to create
competition among the government fee-for-service plan and private
managed-care plans by allowing beneficiaries who choose inexpensive
plans to pay lower monthly premiums. The elderly cannot do that
under the current setup. No matter which plan you pick, you pay a
full premium of about $45 a month.
</P>
<P>
   Under the Clinton plan, you could receive a discount, even a
complete waiver of the monthly premium. This would be very
important to the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   The president also wisely proposes to raise the deductible for
physician services at the pace of inflation. That's important for
controlling costs over time. Though he could have gone further _
perhaps by combining all Medicare deductibles into one _ his plan
would make a good start. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)What changes would make the Clinton plan better?(end
italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. He could adopt some good parts of the Breaux plan. The
government agency that runs Medicare, HCFA, has a conflict of
interest. It supervises the private Medicare plans. It also runs
the government's fee-for-service plan. The danger is that by
setting the rules of competition, it could disable the private
plans. The answer to this problem is to set up a separate board to
supervise the private plans, leaving HCFA to focus its attention
solely on running the best fee-for-service plan possible.
</P>
<P>
   Another suggestion would be to provide a more generous drug
benefit for families most in need, perhaps by excluding higher
income families from government subsidies. If future budgets allow,
we could add more subsidies later. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Q. (italics)Is there hope for action this year?(end italics) &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A. The president gave Congress political cover for taking up an
issue that it has traditionally been scared to touch.
</P>
<P>
   The big news is that the budget constraints have been partially
lifted. New budget estimates have handed Congress an extra $1
trillion over the next 15 years. Even with the new money, real
reform will be painful, requiring Congress to impose new limits on
the elderly. Clinton made a start when he proposed raising some
deductibles and co-payments.
</P>
<P>
   Some Democrats feared the Breaux plan would hurt the elderly.
Republicans are suspicious of the cost of the Clinton plan.
Hopefully, there will be room for compromise.
</P>
<P>
   As the president knows, the most important thing we can do for
the future is pay down the national debt. Second is improving the
big entitlement programs like Medicare and controlling their costs.
With solid proposals from the president and Breaux, there is no
excuse for failing to enact Medicare reforms this year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
