</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BRAZIL-BANK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOVERNMENT INTERVENES TO KEEP BRAZILIAN BANK SOLVENT
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By SIMON ROMERO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAO PAULO, Brazil _ The Senate has approved a measure that
erases $3.4 billion in questionable securities from the books of
Banco do Brasil, a move that may have averted insolvency at the
191-year-old bank, Latin America's largest.
</P>
<P>
   But the measure, which transferred responsibility for the
securities from the bank to the federal treasury, has raised
considerable concern among investors about how such large amounts
of risky securities could be so easily shuffled around in Brazil by
high-ranking officials with little accountability.
</P>
<P>
   The measure, approved by the Senate late Wednesday, reversed an
earlier decision that had made Banco do Brasil responsible for the
questionable bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Originally issued by the city of Sao Paulo years ago during a
period of rampant fiscal mismanagement, the bonds have a face value
of $3.4 billion. But the bonds are considered highly risky and
perhaps worthless because they may have been issued illegally and
it is unclear whether Sao Paulo will honor them.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is horrific to find such a skeleton lurking around,'' said
Winston Fritsch, the president of Dresdner Kleinwort Benson's
Brazil subsidiary.
</P>
<P>
   The transfer of the bonds to the federal government could lead
to a closer examination of how Brazil manages its financial
institutions.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports by local news organizations, the municipal
authorities in Sao Paulo used a loophole in fund-raising
legislation to sell bonds for the purpose of honoring debts
resulting from lawsuits. In effect, however, city officials used
proceeds from these securities for such purposes as paying civil
servants or financing public works.
</P>
<P>
   Sao Paulo authorities used a close relationship with Banespa, a
bank then under control of the state government, to make this
practice feasible. While other banks avoided the bonds, Banespa
bought them. Banespa nearly failed in 1995, and the federal
government subsequently took it over. The bonds were later
transferred to Banco do Brasil, which is also run by the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Exactly how and why that happened remains unclear. But some news
reports have suggested that President Fernando Henrique Cardoso's
administration offered to wipe Banespa's slate clean of the
securities in exchange for the political support of Paulo Maluf, a
former Sao Paulo mayor and presidential hopeful.
</P>
<P>
   As part of such an agreement, the reports have said, the city of
Sao Paulo, where the current mayor is a protege of Maluf, would be
freed from honoring the bonds. And Maluf, with an eye on his own
political future, would be freed from the stigma of having issued
billions of dollars of bonds that might be worthless.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for both Cardoso and Maluf have denied that such an
orchestrated agreement was made. Still, the result, in which
federal funds must now be used used to cover fiscal mismanagement
in Brazil's largest and wealthiest city, has caused concern.
</P>
<P>
   ``Imagine New York sold bonds to pave its roads, pay its police
and so on,'' said Raul Velloso, an independent economic consultant
specializing in public finances. ``Then New York said it couldn't
honor the bonds and the rest of the country was told to do so.
Would you be upset?''
</P>
<P>
   The Senate measure allowing Banco do Brasil to transfer the
portfolio to the federal ledger is not expected to worsen an
already worrisome budget deficit because the loss from the
securities on the municipal and state levels was already accounted
for in previous deficit estimates, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The real fear is of discovering huge problems like this in the
future,'' said Masaru Nakayasu, the chief economist at the
Brazilian unit of Bank of Tokyo-Mitsubishi.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
