<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARKET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCKS ADVANCE STRONGLY, INVESTORS UNDAUNTED BY RATE HIKE 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JONATHAN FUERBRINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On a day when investors and traders had their sights
set on the long holiday weekend, the Dow Jones industrial average
rose almost 73 points Friday, reaching a new high for the first
time in seven weeks. The two other marquee stock indexes set
records for the third consecutive day.
</P>
<P>
   In the bond market, where pre-holiday trading finished early, at
2 p.m., prices were unchanged to slightly higher, although the
Labor Department reported stronger-than-expected job growth in June
and said that hourly earnings had jumped 3.7 percent in the last 12
months.
</P>
<P>
   For the stock market, this week's rally seemed more like one
that would follow a Federal Reserve rate cut, rather than the
quarter-point increase in its short-term interest rate target that
central bank officials announced Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow finished up 5.6 percent for the week, its best
performance since October 1998, when the recovery began from the
stock selloff during the height of last year's global financial
crisis. The NASDAQ composite index rose 6.8 percent for the week
and the Standard &AMP; Poor's index of 500 stocks climbed 5.8 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Many investors seemed to be buoyed by the other Fed announcement
this week _ that it had shifted its interest rate outlook from a
bias toward higher rates to neutral.
</P>
<P>
   The Dow finished Friday at 11,139.24, up 72.82 points, or 0.7
percent. The S&AMP;P 500 rose 10.26 points, or 0.7 percent, to
1,391.22. The NASDAQ climbed 34.83 points, or 1.3 percent, to
2,741.01.
</P>
<P>
   But in the bond market, there is much more concern about the
Fed. While the stock market is at new highs, interest rates _ even
after falling sharply this week _ are still above where they were
in May, when the Fed first indicated that a rate increase was in
the offing.
</P>
<P>
   The price of the 30-year Treasury bond was unchanged at 100
11/32. The bond's yield, which moves in the opposite direction,
stayed at 6 percent. On Wednesday, the yield had dipped to 5.96
percent. The yield on the two-year note, which is more sensitive to
Fed interest rates moves, was unchanged 5.56 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Friday's report that 268,000 new nonfarm payroll jobs were
created last month led analysts to say that another rate increase
was still likely _ although in the immediate wake of the Fed
announcement Wednesday, many had thought one rate increase might be
enough to slow economic growth and curb inflation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Nothing the Fed said told me that a rate increase was off the
table,'' said Thomas Connor, head government trader at J.P. Morgan
Securities, adding that upcoming data, including June's Consumer
Price Index and July's jobs report, will be crucial.
</P>
<P>
   William Dudley, the chief U.S. economist at Goldman, Sachs,
agreed. ``The conditions that prompted the Fed to act this time,''
he said, ``will probably be in place at their next meeting'' in
August.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts had a hard time, however, explaining why the bond
market did not sell off after the jobs report was released. Trading
was light and that often results in distorted moves. And although
another rate increase may be ahead, the statement the Fed made on
Wednesday led some investors to conclude that the central bank will
not have to raise interest rates sharply to slow the economy, as it
did in 1994. In seven moves then, the Fed raised the federal funds
rate _ its short-term interest rate target _ to 6 percent from 3
percent.
</P>
<P>
   And if no big interest rate run-up is expected, then rates may
be near their peak, which would make buying now attractive to many
bond funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Investors are more inclined to be buyers on the dips'' in bond
prices, Connor said, because they think that interest rates will
not move much higher.
</P>
<P>
   Explaining the stock market performance is a little easier. The
healthy economy is good for corporate earnings and interest rates
have not moved high enough yet to cloud the outlook. If the Fed
gets the economy to slow with just two or three quarter-point rate
increases, interest rates should begin to decline again, giving
stocks some added support.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interest rates are not high enough to kill off the very
positive outlook for corporate earnings in the second, third and
fourth quarters,'' Hugh Johnson, chief investment officer at First
Albany Corp., said.
</P>
<P>
   But because Friday's rally came on below-average volume on a day
when many traders were away, a new look on Tuesday could make some
investors take a pause at these new highs.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1901EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
