<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 19:02 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7673 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-N     07-02 0904
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-WIMBLEDON-WOMEN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENSON BECOMES FIRST QUALIFIER TO REACH WIMBLEDON SEMIFINALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (jt) 
 By ROBIN FINN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ With a curtsey in every direction and a
giddy grin on her face, 18-year-old Alexandra Stevenson, the San
Diego phenom who selected Wimbledon for her professional coming-out
party, Friday became the first female qualifier ever to reach the
semifinals here, a coup she achieved by defeating another
qualifier, 129th-ranked Jelena Dokic of Australia.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson used an abundance of power and sheer determination to
overwhelm Dokic, the 16-year-old Belgrade-born stylist, in the
resumption of their rain-wracked quarterfinal, 6-3, 1-6, 6-3. Dokic
had been serving for the second set Thursday when drizzle and
darkness postponed its resolution overnight. And Friday Stevenson,
whose controversial run here now includes official confirmation
from the basketball Hall of Famer Julius Erving that he is her
biological father, was by far the stronger contender.
</P>
<P>
   An unlikely semifinalist also emerged from the day's other, and
somewhat overlooked, quarterfinal when 17-year-old Mirjana Lucic
recovered from a 4-6, 3-3 deficit against eighth-seeded Nathalie
Tauziat and, when their rain-postponed encounter resumed Friday,
upset last year's runner-up, 4-6, 6-4, 7-5. The 134th-ranked Lucic,
who now tackles the seven-time champion Steffi Graf, became the
lowest-ranked player to reach a Wimbledon semi in the Open Era.
</P>
<P>
   Like Stevenson, Lucic is no stranger to parent-generated
controversy. After losing in the second round here last year, Lucic
fled Zagreb and relocated in Florida with her mother and siblings
after accusing her father/coach, Marinko, of physical and emotional
abuse. But Lucic has put her family strife behind her and, assisted
by coach Joe Giuliano, has focused on fine-tuning the power game
that not only won her comparisons to Graf but two years ago carried
her to a title in her first professional event.
</P>
<P>
   Now both Lucic and Stevenson, now coached by Craig Kardon,
Martina Navratilova's final mentor, hope to disrupt the progress of
the two veterans who stand between them and an all-teenage finale
on Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was always my favorite player, definitely, but she
definitely won't be my hero tomorrow,'' said Lucic of Graf, who
holds a 2-0 edge in their head-to-head meetings. Graf, the
30-year-old German, seems to be hitting yet another zenith
following last month's French Open championship, which brought her
a 22d career slam.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson made it clear that Sampras, and not third-seeded
Lindsay Davenport, her semifinal opponent, has always been her
favorite player: ``I didn't really follow her,'' said Stevenson.
``I mostly followed Pete Sampras and the guys. I just think it will
be a great match; it's going to be good for American tennis.''
</P>
<P>
   The 6-foot-1-inch Stevenson, groomed for greatness since she was
3 by the same succession of coaches who mentored the five-time
Wimbledon champion Sampras, was assisted by 15 aces, one shy of the
women's record at Wimbledon, in her defeat of the equally
precocious Dokic.
</P>
<P>
   Friday Stevenson nailed down her spot in the semifinals by
breaking Dokic in the sixth game of the final set. Dokic started
the game with a doublefault, popped out another to trail 15-40, and
blooped a forehand volley long to fall behind 4-2. Though Stevenson
doublefaulted on her first match point, she converted her second
when Dokic sent a forehand crosscourt out of bounds.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully, you'll see a bit more of Dokic in the future,''
said Dokic afterwards. ``It's tough to say for both of us if this
is a once-in-a-lifetime tournament or if from here you're actually
going to go on. I'm not worrying who's going to be there; I'm sort
of waiting for myself to get there.''
</P>
<P>
   Davenport, the 1998 U.S. Open champion who's probably the least
controversial player on the tour, and Stevenson, arguably the most
controversial since John McEnroe made his bombastic debut here 22
years ago, actually do have a few things in common: their high
school diplomas and games grounded on unadulterated power.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've always hit the ball, just gone for it and, I mean, to
win, to win you have to just go for it, and over the years I've
gotten more control, so that's better,'' said Stevenson. Too, the
prodigy said her tunnel vision on winning this title has enabled
her to block out distractions ranging from much-quoted remarks
allegedly made by her sportswriter/mother, Samantha, on the
proliferation of racism and lesbianism on the women's tour to the
news media feeding frenzy about Erving's paternity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite oblivious to most of it,'' said Stevenson, who has
supported her mother's opinions but has so far refused comment on
her father's identity. When pressed about her heritage, Stevenson
has referred to herself as African-American and Caucasian.
</P>
<P>
   About the most remarkable, and remarked-on, trip to a Wimbledon
semifinal since McEnroe rose out of the qualifying rounds in 1977,
Stevenson waxed patriotic: ``I think it's right that it's been two
Americans,'' she said. ``I think it's awesome.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory vaulted the self-assured Stevenson into her first
career semifinal at her first career Grand Slam event. Besides
Stevenson, only Chris Evert in 1972 and Anna Kournikova in 1997
have attained the semifinals in their Wimbledon debut.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
