<TEXT>
<P>
   Here are the business news stories the Los Angeles Daily News
plans to move for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs
of July 3 and thereafter. The stories will carry the ``f''
financial news category code unless otherwise noted. For questions
about stories, contact Jeremy Bagott at the Daily News, (818)
713-3702.
</P>
<P>
   YORK-AUTONATION (Los Angeles) _ Terry York's auto retailing
empire, which stretches from the Santa Clarita Vallley to
Huntington Beach, is being bought by a Florida-based company that's
been expanding in Southern California. Terms were not disclosed.
The purchase by Auto Nation Inc. of Fort Lauderdale makes that
company the dominant player at the Valencia Auto Mall. By Greg
Wilcox. (Will move in the ``f'' financial news file.)
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 1906EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0236 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 19:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7686 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ISRAEL-ORTHODOX-2NDTA     07-02 0840
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-ORTHODOX-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 BNEI BRAK, Israel: modern world.'''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   David Ribner, a modern Orthodox Jew who directs the social work
program at Bar-Ilan, said the haredi community's readiness to
recognize its own problems _ from child abuse and neglect to
domestic violence _ was crucial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, they are ready to present an image to the world that
doesn't have to be holier than the pope,'' Ribner said.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the students are already involved in charity or social
work in their community, although they have no formal training.
They are a very open, gregarious bunch. Although even an interview
with this newspaper had to be negotiated with the rabbis _ via a
liaison in New York _ the men themselves were completely
comfortable talking and burst with pride in their pioneering
venture.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's dangerous and risky, this exposure,'' Rabbi Berger said.
``But it's part of the process of the haredi community becoming
part of the Israeli reality.''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   As part of the screening of applicants, Professor Ribner said,
men were asked to imagine the feelings of a religious woman who had
given birth to a baby with severe defects. If the applicants could
not consider the possibility that the woman might be angry at God,
they were not accepted because it was believed that their dogma
would get in the way.
</P>
<P>
   Mayevsky said he feels comfortable navigating between two
worlds, because he grew up as a religious Zionist and served in the
army before he ``went black,'' in his words. After finishing his
yeshiva studies, he studied Torah for 12 years in a kollel, an
advanced Torah studies institute for married students who get by on
a state stipend and the earnings of their wives.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Mayevsky said he has always been concerned with the number of
wayward youths among the haredi whose problems, like sexual
offenses, were being ``swept under the carpet.'' Often, haredi
families are unwilling to acknowledge mental illness, for instance,
because it is considered to taint their daughters and make them
undesirable marriage partners.
</P>
<P>
   He helped start a residential school in Rosh Haayin for
teenagers with problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was when I first realized that I was handicapped without
a degree,'' he said. ``The Labor and Welfare Ministry officials
said, ``Who are you? You're not trained.' They felt we would be
opening up a lower-level facility.''
</P>
<P>
   The school hired a few professionals, either haredi women who
had trained abroad or modern-Orthodox men. Mayevsky said he was
upset that he himself was relegated to administration.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the dream of my life to work with this population,'' he
said. ``I was born to help. Still, when I started this program, it
was mostly to get the degree so I had the official sanction of
government authorities. Then, slowly, I realized that I had
something to learn.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayevsky said his life has turned upside down, emotionally, as
the course work has demanded that he explore his feelings for the
first time.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have conflicts in my head that go back 30 years,'' he said.
``Now I'm struggling through all this confronting. If I had done
this earlier, I probably would have conducted my own life very
differently.''
</P>
<P>
   Mayevsky and Rabbi Berger said the fact that their community
distrusts social workers from the outside world makes it harder for
problems to be addressed and resolved. An outsider might bring with
him value judgments about community norms, seeing certain
traditions _ like arranged marriages _ as pathologies.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The men said they would obey the law and report criminal
behavior in their community to the police. But, Rabbi Berger said,
the police often do far less than the community would.
</P>
<P>
   For instance, he said, a haredi man ``known for starting up with
young male children'' was recently reported to the police, who
conducted a half-hearted investigation and dropped the matter. A
group of rabbis then paid him ``a friendly visit,'' Rabbi Berger
said, and told him that if he didn't seek help, ``we would
publicize his situation.''
</P>
<P>
   According to Rabbi Berger, this worked.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In his field work at a psychiatric hospital, Rabbi Berger, who
exudes calm and compassion, took on a suicidal patient that none of
the credentialed professionals could reach. The patient, a homeless
ultra-Orthodox man, had set a specific time and way to kill
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe _ I know _ that my presence in this case as a haredi
man gave this person the faith to work on,'' Rabbi Berger said.
``The problem came after many months, when he was much better. I
was forced to separate from him, because that is the dictate of my
new profession. He was very hurt and angry, and I felt guilt.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked what had been the biggest hurdle as they breached the wall
between their community and the outside world, Mayevsky and Rabbi
Berger conferred, stroking their beards.
</P>
<P>
   The rabbi spoke for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Multiple choice tests,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
