<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7694 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-PROP227-SCHOOLS-$ADV0     07-02 1685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PROP227-SCHOOLS-$ADV05-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEBATE RAGES OVER HOW TO MEASURE SUCCESS OF CALIFORNIA SCHOOL LAW 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Monday, July 5) 
(Eds.: See optional trim) 
 
By KIM COBB 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ A year after California's voters threw out
bilingual education for non-English speaking students in favor of
``English immersion,'' school districts are interpreting the law
widely, and the political debate now rages over measuring its
success.
</P>
<P>
   A county grand jury reported last week that the Los Angeles
Unified School District, the largest and most influential in the
state, is abusing the anti-bilingual education law by continuing to
teach large numbers of children in their native language under the
guise of a program called ``Structured English Immersion Model B.''
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury report came on the heels of a statistical foul-up
in the compilation of statewide achievement test scores,
invalidating, at least temporarily, what looked like promising
academic gains this year for many of the state's 1.4 million
children with limited English.
</P>
<P>
   As state officials try to sort out how well the students with
limited English actually performed on those tests, a bill is
working its way through the State Assembly that would remove a
large percentage of limited-English students from the testing
program.
</P>
<P>
   Ron Unz, the Palo Alto software tycoon behind Proposition 227,
which ended bilingual education, says the move to exempt limited
English students from the achievement test program is outrageous.
</P>
<P>
   But Unz is not concerned about the varying levels of compliance
across the state, predicting parents will force stricter compliance
from reluctant teachers and administrators if they see stricter
enforcement producing results in other school districts.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this first year of massive change, I'm reasonably
satisfied,'' Unz said. Unz was still crowing about some of the
Stanford 9 achievement test results for limited-English students,
even though the company which administers the test has admitted
that it garbled the numbers.
</P>
<P>
   In measuring the students' progress, the testing company lumped
the scores of children still classified as ``limited English
proficient'' along with those who would be redesignated as fluent,
artificially inflating the scores of those learning English during
this first year under Proposition 227.
</P>
<P>
   Unz says he's cautiously optimistic that the scores of
limited-English students still will show dramatic improvement once
the test scores are corrected. ``Assuming the (Stanford 9) numbers
hold up, I think we'll see a sea change in people's attitudes about
bilingual education across the country,'' Unz said.
</P>
<P>
   Unz says he may yet pursue legal action to force better
compliance in districts such as Los Angeles, where the grand jury
charged teachers and administrators who oppose the law have mounted
active campaigns to circumvent it.
</P>
<P>
   The San Francisco school district is still operating the same
bilingual program it ran before Proposition 227 passed, having
successfully argued for an exemption under a previous federal court
order.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the loudest and most consistent critics of Proposition
227, the leadership of the Mexican American Legal Defense and
Education Fund, argue that Stanford 9 test scores, accurate or not,
are not a good measure of Proposition 227's effectiveness.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's been a quiet revolution in education in California,''
said Theresa Fay-Bustillos, MALDEF vice president of legal
programs. She cited new phonics-based reading programs instituted
at the early grades, class size reduction, after-school programs
and tutoring programs for both students and parents as other
factors that could be expected to affect achievement test scores.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think testing, per se, is a bad idea,'' Fay-Bustillos
said. ``But how much of any gain in test scores can you attribute
to 227?
</P>
<P>
   ``Do those (scoring) spikes really mean that child has kept up
with fluent English peers _ not necessarily,'' she said. ``Does it
mean they've gained enough English literacy skills to compete in an
English-only classroom? Not necessarily.''
</P>
<P>
   The Oceanside Unified School District near San Diego was being
touted as a remarkable Proposition 227 success story with double
and even triple-digit academic gains before the problem with the
test scores surfaced. Superintendent Kenneth Noonan says his own
district statistician has rerun the numbers accurately, ``And we
still look pretty good. The percentage of gain is different. But in
the primary grades, especially, we look good.''
</P>
<P>
   With the amended comparison of scores, Noonan said, it looks
like limited English students in the second grade (for example)
showed a 92 percent gain in reading when compared to second-grade
scores the year before. The incorrectly inflated figures showed
that group making a 100 percent gain in reading.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been told any percentage gain over five to 10 percent is
significant,'' Noonan said. But what makes Noonan's district
interesting, beyond what the children score on standardized tests,
is the superintendent's history and political background.
</P>
<P>
   Noonan was the founding president of the California Association
of Bilingual Educators and opposed Proposition 227, but decided
after the vote that he had no choice but to enforce the new law.
</P>
<P>
   Districts across the state have enforced the law as they have
seen fit because they got little guidance from the state, Noonan
said.
</P>
<P>
   But granting waivers to parents who wanted native-language
instruction for their children, he decided, was a provision the law
allowed only for special cases. Other districts in the state have
granted waivers generously, resulting in some districts with large
numbers of students continuing in traditional bilingual classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The Berkley school district sued the state for permission to
waive the English-only requirement for their entire limited-English
population. And the grand jury report released last week charged
that anti-Proposition 227 administrators and staff in the Los
Angeles district mounted active campaigns to promote the waivers.
</P>
<P>
   About 10 percent of the district's limited English students
received those waivers and were taught in traditional bilingual
classrooms.
</P>
<P>
   The grand jury also charged that the district's ``Model B''
track for limited English students continued to teach 117,000
children their core academic subjects in their native language.
</P>
<P>
   In Oceanside, Noonan got about 150 requests for waivers. But the
superintendent and a specially formed committee granted only five
in Oceanside, not enough to form a single bilingual classroom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did have some political pressure in town,'' Noonan said.
</P>
<P>
   Upset parents, led by community activists, marched on the school
board. And Noonan said the first few months of English immersion
were tough on the children as well as his teachers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a struggle. I watched these teachers, and I wanted to
cry for 'em. I have a master's degree in bilingual education. Some
of them did, too,'' Noonan said. ``We just took a real tough line.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were dire predictions _ that kids would not progress, go
into culture shock. But the test results (even with less dramatic
gains) show quite the opposite.''
</P>
<P>
   And Noonan said part of his evaluation of the new approach is
based on what he has observed. By the second semester, the
landscape in his school district had changed. ``I always kneel down
(in the classrooms) and ask individual students to read to me,''
Noonan said. ``I noted a significant increase in their ability to
read.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could see as the year went on things would be better than we
expected.''
</P>
<P>
   Fay-Bustillos says the true measure of Proposition 227's success
will be whether students can become sufficiently fluent in English
after one year to compete with their English-speaking peers. That's
best determined by the number of students who are redesignated by
school officials as fluent in English at the end of a school year,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Some Orange County school districts that abandoned bilingual
education even before Proposition 227 passed saw their
redesignation rates drop this year. Unz argues that there is no
statewide standard for redesignation, and that schools are
frequently not aggressive about testing children for redesignation.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS) &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Unz is aware of the bilingual education debate emerging in the
Houston Independent School District, and is full of questions about
the public attitude toward native language instruction in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But while Unz is helping activists in Arizona who are attempting
to outlaw that state's bilingual program, he says he's not involved
in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the reasons we haven't focused on Texas is they don't
have the initiative process,'' Unz conceded.
</P>
<P>
   But if California students enrolled in English immersion classes
score well on standardized tests, he argues, Texas parents will
notice the results.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those leaders in Houston and elsewhere may finally re-evaluate
their position on bilingual,'' Unz said.
</P>
<P>
   Houston school trustees voted last month on a bilingual
education policy that emphasizes ``the ability to read, write and
speak English as rapidly as possible.''
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the proposal have labeled it ``an advocacy vehicle
for the English-only movement.'' But the board members promoting it
say it is designed to move children into English-speaking classes
once they've achieved reading proficiency in English.
</P>
<P>
   Manuel Rodriguez, president of the Parents for Public Schools of
Houston, said that Houston parents will have an opportunity to
speak out about the proposal at a meeting sponsored by the
organization July 14 at the Museum of Fine Arts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are not for the proposal, we are not against the
proposal,'' Rodriguez said. ``Right now, we are trying to
understand how the public feels about this and take that input to
the board for their consideration.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
