<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 19:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7697 &Cx1f; tad-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-EAGLE3-COX     07-02 0999
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EAGLE3-COX </SLUG>

<TEXT>
<P>
   EAGLE RECOVERS FROM EXTINCTION IN TIME FOR HOLIDAY
</P>
<P>
   850&AMP;ADD
</P>
<P>
   By Bob Deans
</P>
<P>
   Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton kicked off the Fourth of July
weekend Friday by
</P>
<P>
   proclaiming that the nation's living symbol is no longer
threatened, marking the bald eagle's dramatic recovery from the
edge of extinction.
</P>
<P>
   The once ravaged eagle population has increased fourteen fold _
enough to ensure its survival well into the next century _ during
three decades of aggressive environmental management, Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
   The eagle's comeback illustrates the value of continued
environmental vigilance, said Clinton, whose multi-billion-dollar
proposals to expand protections for wildlife and natural areas have
come under fire by a budget-conscious Congress.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton made his remarks on the White House lawn, as a
magnificent brown-feathered eagle crowned with ivory plumes looked
on from a rope-wrapped brass perch framing an American flag.
</P>
<P>
   He used the announcement to press for congressional support for
a White House plan to spend $7.8 billion over the next 20 years to
restore the Florida Everglades. Decades of development have
destroyed or threatened thousands of acres of the irreplacable
watershed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to think of a better way to celebrate the birth of a
nation than to celebrate the rebirth of our national symbol,'' said
Clinton, moments before a military band played America the
Beautiful as a row of flags rimming the south portico billowed in a
refreshing summer breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now that we have the bald eagle back,'' said Clinton, who
survived the threat of political extinction himself, ``let's get
the spirit behind the bald eagle back, and put America back on a
bipartisan course of conservation of our natural resources.''
</P>
<P>
   His remarks were sporadically punctuated by the haunting screech
of Challenger. The celebrity eagle is familiar to Atlanta Braves
fans for his breathtaking flights from the upper seats at Turner
Field to home plate during the singing of the Star Spangled Banner.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's done three season openers at the Braves games,'' said
Challenger's trainer, Al Cecere. ``He flies into the stadium and
lands on my glove.''
</P>
<P>
   The living symbol of American freedom and might, the bald eagle
once seemed to be almost everywhere _ on the back of dollar bills,
capping schoolyard flagpoles and even fronting the presidential
seal _ except in the wild.
</P>
<P>
   By 1963, hunters, pesticides and encroachment upon nesting and
feeding grounds had so devastated eagle populations that only 417
breeding pairs remained in the United States, outside of Alaska and
Hawaii.
</P>
<P>
   Four years later, eagles and their habitat began receiving
federal protection under the legislative precursor to the 1973
Endangered Species Act. In 1972, the country banned the use of DDT,
a pesticide that wrought havoc on eagle eggs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most important of all, we made the Endangered Species Act the
law of the land,'' said Clinton, ``declaring that extinction is not
an option _ not for the eagle, not for other creatures put here by
God.''
</P>
<P>
   By 1995, the eagle had recovered sufficiently to be taken off of
the endangered species list and assigned the less critical denotion
of ``threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   At last count, there were nearly 5,800 breeding pairs of eagles
across the lower 48 states. Clinton said Friday that the U.S. Fish
and Wildlife Service has proposed taking the bald eagle off of the
list of threatened species.
</P>
<P>
   The public has 90 days to comment on the proposal. The agency
would then evaluate the public's remarks and consider whether to
formally delist the eagle a year from now.
</P>
<P>
   The eagle would remain protected under the provisions of a
70-year-old federal ban on killing or trapping eagles.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will be legally no less protected,'' said Resse Collins,
director of the center for birds of prey for the Florida Audubon
Society. ``You can't harm the birds themselves, nor can you harm
their habitat.''
</P>
<P>
   In addition to pressing Congress to support his Everglades
initiative, Clinton called for support for his proposals to
increase by at least $2 billion a year federal spending to protect
natural areas and greenspaces.
</P>
<P>
   He's waging an uphill battle. Committees in the Republican-led
House and Senate have both voted to slash his requests by more than
half.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton vowed Friday to fight for the increase and Collins, one
of several environmental activists invited to attend Friday's
announcement, said the eagle's comeback proves that investing in
environmental protection pays off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a victory that they came back, but it's because we
cleaned the water, we cleaned the habitat we cleaned the land,''
said Collins, of Maitland, Fl.
</P>
<P>
   BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM
</P>
<P>
   Florida is home to some 1,000 mating pairs of eagles, more than
the other lower 48 states. There are 37 mating pairs in Georgia, 62
in Texas and 47 in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Challenger is a striking if unique example of the bird of prey
that symbolizes strength and freedom to millions of Americans.
Blown from his nest in the Louisiana woodlands before he knew how
to fly, Challenger has spent his life in the care of other
predators _ humans _ and has never mastered the unforgiving art of
living off the land.
</P>
<P>
   ``He doesn't know how to hunt,'' said Cecere, Challenger's
trainer and president of the National Foundation to Protect
America's Eagles, located in Pigeon Forge, Tenn. Challenger has
been released twice in the countryside, only to quickly find his
way back to the nurturing bosom of society, said Cecere.
</P>
<P>
   Now it's his job to keep Challenger off the dole.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feed him quail, trout, a little beefheart sometimes,'' he
said, as Challenger looked on from the shadow of the White House,
his black and golden talons sheathed in the thick leather manacles
that bind him earthbound to Cecere, civilization and celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ENDIT
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
