<HEADER>
A7704 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-LIFE-BOS &LR;      07-02 0901
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-LIFE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN KOSOVO, A SLOW RETURN TO NORMALCY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CHARLES M. SENNOTT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ Slowly, life is returning.
</P>
<P>
   Cafes do brisk business amid the NATO tanks, a hair salon opens
in the rubble, a bar restocks beer, and people are once again
crowding the streets of Kosovo's provincial capital.
</P>
<P>
   There are reunion scenes on every corner, especially the
open-arm greetings of friends and neighbors and families thrilled
to see each other alive.
</P>
<P>
   Stacatto conversations rattle through cafes as people recount
their ordeals of survival and harrowing tales of escape. And then
there are the sad silences _ the shakes of the head in recognition
of someone who was lost, or perhaps still missing, of homes burned
and businesses destroyed.
</P>
<P>
   After three months in the hunger and cold of a mountain pass
near Albania, Nejmia Luma, 28, finally made it home this week. On
Thursday, she celebrated her freedom in a chair at Menda's Salon,
which was packed with women awaiting the same treatment.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a mess,'' said Luma, an accountant. ``We lived like
animals. They tried to reduce us to that.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at me,'' she said, facing the mirror, her face leathered
by sun and wind and her hair thickly matted. Luma winced as a
female hairdresser pulled hard with a brush, trying to tease the
tangles out of her long, black hair.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly a year, Luma had been too fearful to walk Pristina
streets that were increasingly dominated by Serb paramilitaries.
Even in the months before the war, she said, she would go downtown
only for necessities, such as food shopping and seeing family, but
nothing so extravagant as having her hair done. On March 26, two
days after the NATO bombing began, she and her family fled.
</P>
<P>
   Living under plastic tarps and huddling under the few blankets
they had, she and some 20 members of an extended clan were
surrounded by Serb paramilitary units for three months. The Serb
forces had placed land mines around the camp, making it impossible
to leave. It was only Wednesday that she had been helicoptered out
of the pass by international aid workers.
</P>
<P>
   She checked on family and friends first. She ate a decent meal.
But the first thing she did on the first morning after her return
was get her hair done. The first time in 10 months.
</P>
<P>
   ``I felt like I had to look like a human being again,'' she
explained. ``I want to be able to hold my head up.''
</P>
<P>
   Kosovar Albanian refugees are flooding back at a rate faster
than they fled the Serb forces' terror. An estimated 550,000 of the
800,000 refugees have come home, UN and aid workers say.
</P>
<P>
   The towns of Djakovica, Drenica, and Pec were hard hit by Serb
forces. There are more land mines and mass graves. But the capital
is relatively in tact, and it is remarkable how quickly it is
flowering anew amid the ashes.
</P>
<P>
   But the NATO tanks rumbling past are a constant reminder things
are far from normal. So are the mine clearance teams in heavy
kevlar uniforms, and the British paratroopers walking in formation
with machine guns drawn.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, a solemn procession for some 2,000 Kosovar Albanian
prisoners still missing wound its way through the streets. Mirdita
Sorej, 25, led the march, carrying a large white placard that was
left blank. Her brother, Ali, 22, is among the missing. His
four-year-old daughter walked alongside Mirdita holding a
wallet-size picture of her father, who was arrested on his way home
from work at a grocery store on March 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``Their lives will go on,'' Sorej said, looking in the direction
of the crowded cafes and bars along Pristina's main street. ``But
not ours. Not until our brothers and fathers come home.''
</P>
<P>
   Kadrush Sulejmni, 59, a writer and editor for several of
Kosovo's news magazines, was among that crowd getting on with life.
He was elated as he sat at his favorite cafe and ordered a
cappucino served in elegant white china cups with saucers.
</P>
<P>
   On March 28, a Serb neighbor he had known for 20 years guided
paramilitaries to his home, and his family was forced out at
gunpoint. His wife and their three sons fled to Macedonia, but he
stayed in Pristina and kept a journal for the 79 days he was on the
run. He slept in one empty house after another and foraged for
food.
</P>
<P>
   Now he was smiling as he plunked four sugar cubes into his
coffee at Cafe Koha, saying almost guiltily as if he were talking
to his dentist, ``No sugar in three months.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We are a hard-working people,'' he said. ``We will get our
feet back on the ground.''
</P>
<P>
   Evidence of that surrounded him.
</P>
<P>
   A grocery store was replacing glass windows that had been
smashed. At a clothing store, a man was straightening up female
manequins that had been knocked over and stripped of their clothes.
A restaurant owner was sweeping out the rubble from inside a fire-
blackened dining room. There was a handwritten sign that read, ``We
will serve soup tomorrow.''
</P>
<P>
   Safete Rogova, 38, a well-known actress in Kosovo's provincial
theater, she had just returned after fleeing to Macedonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is like the curtain opening on a play,'' she said to a
friend as they marvelled at the streets just starting to bustle
with action. ``The characters begin moving. The set comes alive.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought we would never return,'' she says. ``I can't believe
my eyes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
