<HEADER>
A7718 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MOON-ICE-HNS &LR;      07-02 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOON-ICE-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEXAS SCIENTISTS HOPE CRASH WILL INDICATE EVIDENCE OF ICE ON MOON 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  By MARK CARREAU 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HOUSTON _ Against admittedly long odds, a team of scientists
from the University of Texas has devised an experiment that could
provide evidence that caches of ice are hidden on the moon.
</P>
<P>
   On July 31, ground control teams plan to maneuver NASA's Lunar
Prospector probe out of orbit around the moon and send it on a
high-velocity, terrain skimming plunge into a large crater at the
south pole. Using the Hubble Space Telescope and other space and
Earth-based observatories, scientists hope to detect evidence of
water vapor in the impact plume.
</P>
<P>
   Growing evidence of ice left in permanently shaded craters by
ancient comet strikes has revived interest in future human
development of the moon.
</P>
<P>
   By coincidence, the experiment coincides roughly with the 30th
anniversary of the first manned moon landing, the Apollo 11
mission, July 16-24, 1969.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are well aware that if there really was water ice there,
the area becomes some of the most valuable real estate in the solar
system,'' said David Goldstein, associate professor of aerospace
engineering at the University of Texas who proposed the experiment.
</P>
<P>
   ``From a human exploration of space point of view, I've
certainly had dreams of going to space and expanding the human
horizon. I think it would be nice to participate in that, in some
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Lunar Prospector slipped into a polar orbit around the moon a
few days after its launching June 6, 1998. At $63 million, it is
one of the least expensive and most successful missions undertaken
by the National Aeronautics and Space Administration.
</P>
<P>
   Within weeks, principal investigator Alan Binder reported the
probe's instruments had found concentrations of hydrogen around the
lunar poles high enough to imply ice in the crater recesses
</P>
<P>
   Before the end of the mission's first year, Binder's team
estimated the moon may harbor the equivalent of up to 26 billion
gallons of water. Restricted to the unshaded equatorial regions of
the moon, the Apollo explorers did not report evidence of water
from their half-dozen landings.
</P>
<P>
   After 18 months, however, the 350-pound Lunar Prospector is
starting to run out of fuel.
</P>
<P>
   A longshot, Goldstein's proposal is a bid to turn the probe's
inevitable crash to the surface into weighty new evidence for
Binder's original claim.
</P>
<P>
   The target is a 38-mile wide, 2.5-mile deep crater within a few
dozen miles of the moon's south pole. Hydrogen readings collected
by the orbiting Lunar Prospector suggest the depression is
potentially a bountiful target.
</P>
<P>
   Much has to go right for the experiment to work, so much so that
Binder has estimated the chances of success at just 10 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The low-flying spacecraft must clear the surrounding crater
wall, then slam into the ice bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``We come in at a very shallow angle. The topography of the moon
is only known to a certain accuracy. We plan to clear the near rim
of the crater by a kilometer (0.6 miles), and the topography is not
known within an accuracy of a kilometer,'' said Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   ``We could easily hit a dry spot,'' he said. ``There could be
beautiful, white ice 10 feet deep right next to where we hit, but
if we happen to hit a rock or a dry spot, we will never know.''
</P>
<P>
   If the crashing Lunar Prospector hits dry terrain, the probe's
previous findings are not diminished.
</P>
<P>
   With the most fortunate of circumstances, the probe would strike
the equivalent of a Colorado snow bank with the force of a two-ton
pickup striking at more than 1,000 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   It's more likely that ancient ice deposits have been pummeled
over the years by micrometeorites, mixing it into the lunar soil.
</P>
<P>
   So, even if the impact zone contains as little as five gallons
of water, the collision would generate enough heat to create a dust
and vapor cloud that would rise for 15 minutes into the airless
realm of the moon's weak gravity. The cloud should settle for
another 15 minutes, giving the space telescope and instruments at
the McDonald Observatory in West Texas time to look for evidence.
</P>
<P>
   Once sunlight strikes the rising cloud, the interaction should
break the molecules of water into its molecular constituents,
hydrogen and hydroxyl.
</P>
<P>
   Instruments aboard the Hubble and at the McDonald observatories
will be tuned to detect the hydroxyl.
</P>
<P>
   ``A positive spectral detection of water vapor or its
photo-dissociated by-product, (hydroxyl), would provide definite
proof of the presence of water ice in the lunar soil,'' said
Goldstein.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
