   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SERIAL-KILLER-ELPASO (El Paso, Texas) _ While accused serial
killer Rafael Resendez-Ramirez has sent a shiver across an entire
nation, the possibility that he might return to this border town in
the West Texas desert has created something close to panic.
Families have begun to bar their doors at night and skittish
residents say they have seen the train-hopping Resendez-Ramirez
around every corner. By MICHAEL RILEY. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   MILLENNIUM-GENETICS (Houston) _ Custom ordering children may be
the ultimate shopping experience of the next millennium, like
ordering a sunroof or leather seats from a car dealer. One eminent
biologist describes a future in which parents engineer their
children to possess, say, the olfactory powers of dogs or the night
vision of owls. But even the tamest alterations promise to open a
Pandora's box of ethical questions. By TODD ACKERMAN. (Filed
Tuesday. Photo and graphic available on NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   TEEN-DEATH-TODDLER (Austin, Texas) _ Lacresha Murray is home
now, her nightmarish incarceration for the murder of a toddler
behind her, at least temporarily. The Austin girl, who just turned
15, has been convicted twice in connection with the death of
2-year-old Jayla Belton. But flaws in the prosecution prompted
national media attention and ultimately an appellate court
overturned her conviction. Tuesday is the deadline for prosecutors
to ask the Texas Supreme Court to reverse the appellate court and
uphold her conviction. By POLLY ROSS HUGHES. (Photo available on
NYT database.)
</P>
<P>
   INTERNATIONAL NEWS (``i'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-TUITION-REVOLT (Mexico City) _ Wearing camouflage
fatigues, his waist-long hair in a ponytail and a Fu Manchu
mustache offsetting dark eyes, Ivan Alcantar, 24, looks the part of
a moody young revolutionary. Since April 20, the history and
philosophy major has been part of a student strike that began over
plans to charge tuition at the National Autonomous University of
Mexico, the largest in Latin America with nearly 270,000 students.
By SUSANA HAYWARD. (Filed Thursday.)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   THOMPSON-COLUMN (Washington) _ ``Shoot if you must this old gray
head, but spare your country's flag,'' she said. Thus did Barbara
Frietchie cry out against desecration of Old Glory as Stonewall
Jackson marched his Confederate soldiers through Frederick, Md. We
have other symbols with equally powerful meanings. One of them is
the First Amendment. By ROBERT E. THOMPSON. (Filed Wednesday.)
</P>
<P>
   For Monday:
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL NEWS (``a'' category)
</P>
<P>
   PROP227-SCHOOLS (Los Angeles) _ The superintendent of the
Oceanside Unified School District laughs when he says he doesn't
want to become anyone's poster child. But after fighting
California's Proposition 227 before it passed, he's seen the
children of his district thrive in English-immersion programs. But
many school districts across the state are doing business just the
way they always did _ in Spanish, Japanese, Chinese and Russian _
before passage of the initiative that seeks to do away with
bilingual education. By KIM COBB. (Filed Friday)
</P>
<P>
   COMMENTARY (``k'' category)
</P>
<P>
   MEANS-COLUMN (Washington) _ A blue ribbon commission studying
the gambling industry issued a report last month that disappointed
the alarmists who charge that casinos and other games of chance are
corrupting society. The study sensibly concluded that gambling is
here to stay and we might as well get used to it. The messsage:
relax and enjoy gambling, if you want. You might get lucky. By
MARIANNE MEANS. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
<P>
   FOOD (``d'' category)
</P>
<P>
   SEAFOOD-EATERIES (San Francisco) _ The Tadich Grill and Aqua are
two San Francisco treats. They are seafood restaurants that are
miles apart in style and attitude. Think Ralph Lauren vs. Sears or
Daddy Warbucks vs. Homer Simpson. By DAI HUYNH. (Filed Friday.)
</P>
</TEXT>
