<SLUG> BC-MEXICO-REFORMS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MEXICO'S RULING PARTY KILLS PACKAGE OF ELECTION CHANGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By JULIA PRESTON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MEXICO CITY _ Lawmakers from Mexico's governing party have
killed a package of new election rules to monitor spending in
presidential primary campaigns now under way and to allow Mexicans
expatriates to vote in national elections next year.
</P>
<P>
   The measures passed the lower house of the legislature, which is
controlled by the opposition, in April. But senators from the party
of President Ernesto Zedillo, the Institutional Revolutionary
Party, or PRI, mobilized their majority in the upper house to stun
the opposition on Thursday by blocking the reforms from even coming
to the floor for debate.
</P>
<P>
   The session ended in a shouting match, with opposition senators
yelling, ``Cheaters! Cheaters!'' and the PRI senate leader banging
down his gavel and marching out abruptly.
</P>
<P>
   The opposition defended the changes as crucial to fortifying the
democratic framework for the presidential elections on July 2,
2000, which will be the most competitive ever held in Mexico. The
senators from the PRI, which has won every presidential election
since the 1920's, denounced most of the measures as
unconstitutional and said they had simply moved to spare themselves
a politically damaging but ultimately meaningless public debate.
</P>
<P>
   PRI senators adopted the tactic of simply staying away from
Thursday's session, using the strength of their numbers to prevent
the senate from reaching a quorum. Under the rules of the special
session, with no quorum there could be no debate and no second
chance, so the measure was pronounced dead-on-arrival.
</P>
<P>
   The legislature has been in a special session for the last
month, after the end of its regular term, primarily to try and pass
some form of electoral reforms. Friday, one year before the
presidential election, was the last day the bill from the lower
house, the Chamber of Deputies, could be approved by the senate to
take effect in time for that vote.
</P>
<P>
   The PRI softened the measures in the lower house, but eventually
voted against them anyway. They were expected to be defeated in the
senate, where the PRI holds 75 of 127 seats.
</P>
<P>
   But the opposition senators were counting on the debate to give
the public their view of the changes the PRI rejected.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are in a democratic transition where reforms to open up and
scrutinize the system are of paramount importance,'' said Luis H.
Alvarez, a senator from the right-of-center National Action Party,
known as the PAN. ``We especially wanted to tighten campaign
financing to keep drug-traffickers out of the elections. But the
PRI didn't agree, and they stopped us in an incredibly heavy-handed
way.''
</P>
<P>
   One measure would have authorized the Federal Elections Council
to draw up plans for Mexicans living outside the country to vote in
the presidential election. As many as 10.1 million Mexicans who
live in the United States might have been eligible to vote.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials have said that it would be a logistical
nightmare to set up a voting system for so many people by next
July, and warned that it could antagonize American citizens and
elected officials to see so many Mexicans displaying their
allegiance to their home country's politics.
</P>
<P>
   PRI senators insisted that it would take a constitutional
amendment, not just a new law, to authorize the expatriate vote.
Opposition leaders argued that the PRI opposed the measure because
most Mexicans in the United States are believed to oppose the
governing party, blaming Zedillo and his allies for creating the
economic hardship which forced them to leave Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   The proposals would also have created campaign finance limits
and reporting requirements during primary season. Mexico's
political parties are holding primaries to pick their presidential
candidates for the first time ever.
</P>
<P>
   Another measure would have made it easier for opposition parties
to form coalitions. Even though polls show that opposition voters
are the majority in most states, the PRI continues to win elections
because the opposition is split between the PAN and the
left-of-center Party of the Democratic Revolution.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some coalitions are already legal under Mexican law,'' said
Eduardo Andrade Sanchez, a PRI senator. ``But if the opposition
thinks we are going to make it even easier for them to gang up
against us, they're crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition wanted a reform tailored to its interests,''
Senator Andrade said. ``And when they didn't get it, they wanted to
tangle us in a debate to accuse us of being opposed to change. So
we didn't let them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
