<SLUG> BC-OBITUARY-PUZO-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MARIO PUZO, 78; WROTE `THE GODFATHER' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK FEENEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Mario Puzo, whose 1969 novel ``The Godfather'' became a
publishing sensation and went on to inspire an epic film trilogy,
died Friday at his home in Bay Shore, N.Y., apparently of heart
failure. He was 78.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has energy and I lucked out by creating a character that
was popularly accepted and genuinely mythic,'' Mr. Puzo once wrote
of ``The Godfather'' and its hero, Mafia chieftain Vito Corleone.
</P>
<P>
   The novel was Mr. Puzo's third. He went on to publish four
others (a fifth, ``Omerta,'' is to appear next July). The author of
two works of nonfiction and a children's book, Mr. Puzo also
collaborated on eight screenplays. Among them were such well-known
films as ``Superman'' (1978) and ``The Cotton Club'' (1984). But
the impact of all his other work paled before that of ``The
Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   The novel has sold more than 21 million copies. Francis Ford
Coppola's film adaptation (1972) was for several years the
highest-grossing movie of all time. Mr. Puzo wrote the screenplay
with Coppola and won an Academy Award. He won another for ``The
Godfather, Part II'' (1974). Considered as a single work, the two
``Godfather'' films have been praised as the greatest achievement
of post-Studio Age Hollywood. A third film, released in 1990, met
with considerably less success. Mr. Puzo and Coppola also
collaborated on that screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   As an American epic, ``The Godfather'' rivals ``Gone With the
Wind,'' another best-selling novel that gave rise to an even more
popular film. Like Margaret Mitchell's book, which evoked such
classic American themes and experiences as race, the South, and the
Civil War, Mr. Puzo's book dealt with such enduring concerns of
20th-century US life as immigration, violence, and the nature of
power.
</P>
<P>
   More than any novel of the postwar era, perhaps, ``The
Godfather'' entered the public consciousness. Part of that was
attributable to the success, both artistic and popular, of the
first two films. Much of it, though, is owing to the novel itself.
</P>
<P>
   Ostensibly a crime story, ``The Godfather'' is also a
rags-to-riches saga (the story of an immigrant family, the
Corleones), a show biz novel (Hollywood and Las Vegas figure as
prominently as Sicily and Little Italy), and a roman a clef (Frank
Sinatra and mobster Bugsy Siegel are the most obvious examples of
real-life personages who appear only lightly disguised in its
pages).
</P>
<P>
   Within the novel, Mr. Puzo offers a kind of shadow history of
the first half of the American century, touching upon everything
from the assimilation of ethnics (Corleone's youngest son, Michael,
is a Dartmouth man) to the rise of the Sun Belt (the family moves
from New York to Nevada at the novel's end).
</P>
<P>
   What stands revealed is a tainted society in which business and
crime are interchangeable and Mafia chieftains can be seen as being
more honorable than police or politicians. Mr. Puzo's dark vision
struck a chord with readers disillusioned by the social strife of
the '60s. At least two of his coinages _ ``I'll make him an offer
he can't refuse'' and ``A lawyer with a briefcase can steal more
than a hundred men with guns'' _ almost immediately entered the
vernacular. It's no coincidence they bespeak a kind of cynicism
previously unknown in the culture at large.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Puzo was born in New York City on Oct. 15, 1920, the son of
Antonio Puzo and Maria (Le Conti) Puzo. Both were immigrants from
near Naples. His mother was the dominant figure in the family, and
Mr. Puzo later confessed she provided the inspiration for Vito
Corleone. ``Whenever the Godfather opened his mouth, in my own mind
I heard the voice of my mother.''
</P>
<P>
   Growing up in the Hell's Kitchen neighborhood of Manhattan, ``I
had the usual dreams,'' Mr. Puzo once wrote. ``I wanted at the very
least to be a footloose adventurer. Then I branched out and thought
of being a great artist, and then, getting ever more sophisticated,
a great criminal.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Puzo served in the Army during World War II and later worked
as a civilian administrator in Germany. His experiences formed the
basis for his first novel, ``Dark Arena'' (1955), which earned
favorable comparisons to the work of Saul Bellow and Bernard
Malamud.
</P>
<P>
   Ten years later Mr. Puzo published his own favorite among his
books, ``The Fortunate Pilgrim.'' Gay Talese praised its
semi-autobiographical account of New York life during the interwar
years as ``perhaps the best novel ever written about Italian
immigrants in America.'' Despite such praise, it sold poorly. Mr.
Puzo resolved to reach the bestseller list. He wrote a 10-page
outline of a story about a Mafia family. His current publisher
rejected it, but another offered him a $5,000 advance. It became
``The Godfather.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Puzo's other books include the novels ``Fools Die'' (1978),
``The Sicilian'' (1984), ``The Fourth K'' (1991), and ``The Last
Don'' (1996); the nonfiction works ``The Godfather Papers and Other
Confessions'' (1972) and ``Inside Las Vegas'' (1977); and the
children's story ``The Runaway Summer of Davie Shaw'' (1966).
</P>
<P>
   ``I am another Italian success story,'' he wrote in ``The
Godfather Papers.'' ``Not as great as DiMaggio or Sinatra but quite
enough. It will serve.''
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Puzo's wife, Erika (Broske) Puzo, died in 1978. He leaves a
companion, Carol Gino; a sister, Evelyn Murphy; a brother, Anthony
Cleri; five children, Anthony, Dorothy, Eugene, Virginia, and
Joseph; and nine grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   A private service is planned for Monday.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
