<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-CENSUS-HOUSE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CENSUS PROBABLY WON'T COST BAY STATE A HOUSE SEAT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By EUN LEE KOH  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Massachusetts is in ``much less danger'' of losing
one of its 10 seats in the House of Representatives after the 2000
Census, according to a study by the Congressional Research Service
that bolsters members' claims the seat was not in jeopardy.
</P>
<P>
   The research arm of the Library of Congress found that the
state's 10th seat in Congress is ``less vulnerable'' than the seat
it lost after the 1990 census found the state's population had
decreased.
</P>
<P>
   Representative Martin T. Meehan, a Massachusetts Democrat, said
Friday that the report ``reassures me that Massachusetts is in no
danger of losing a representative as a result of the 2000 Census.''
</P>
<P>
   Representative J. Joseph Moakley, a Bay State Democrat who
requested the study, is ``not concerned at all'' about losing a
House seat, said his spokesman, Fred Clark. ``There's always the
possibility if there is a poor count, but we're still in great
shape,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the state's congressional delegation met with the
Democratic Party's national census experts and were assured the
state would not lose a House seat as a result of the census.
Moakley asked for the study after Massachusetts Secretary of State
William F. Galvin warned members last month the state might lose a
seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``At this writing, Massachusetts appears to be in much less
danger of losing a House seat in 2002 than it was at a similar
point in the decade prior to the 1990 Census,'' the report said.
</P>
<P>
   Using three types of analyses of the state's projected
population, the study expected Massachusetts' 10th seat to rank
between 417 and 421 _ for the 435 seats in the House _ after next
year's census.
</P>
<P>
   In these projections, if all other state populations remain the
same, Massachusetts would need a drop of 225,650 people or as many
as 301,339 to lose a seat.
</P>
<P>
   Galvin said Friday he still believes Massachusetts could lose a
House seat.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd be thrilled, ecstatic if I was wrong,'' he said. ``But the
gap between 421 and 436 isn't all that big.''
</P>
<P>
   Galvin said his remarks last month were not to pit himself
against the congressional delegation, but to urge local government
officials to conduct thorough census counts. With the recent
Supreme Court ruling ordering an actual head count for the census,
instead of using statistical sampling, he is convinced the threat
of losing a seat is very real.
</P>
<P>
   ``We can't just sit back, because the rules have changed,'' he
said. ``The enumeration issue has changed everything. Estimates
don't count anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The study itself lists numerous caveats. ``Because population
projections are imperfect, they provide a very rough basis for
anticipating what representation in the House may be after the next
reappointment,'' it states.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
