u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PRIZREN-BOS &LR;      07-02 0866
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PRIZREN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TRAUMATIZED SEEK SHELTER IN MONASTERY SAFE HOUSE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN MILLIGAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRIZREN, Yugoslavia _ More than a week after peace formally came
to Kosovo, Maria Filipovic returned from shopping to find that
someone had jammed a heavy knife in the back of her husband's neck,
killing him.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe he was targeted because he was a Serb. Maybe someone
suspected their family of cooperating with a hated paramilitary
group. The horrific episode sent the tiny, 59-year-old Filipovic to
the area's only safehouse, a Serbian monastery donated to shelter
those too afraid to stay at home _ and too feeble to leave Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   People residing here survived the war, but fear they will not
make it through the peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to stay here. It's like being in prison,''
Filipovic said. But life outside _ despite the strong presence of
NATO peacekeeping troops _ is still too risky, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Overwhelmingly Serb and largely elderly, the some 130 people who
sought a haven in the historic Orthodox monastery are refugees in
their own city. Many tell of being imprisoned by the Kosovo
Liberation Army shortly after NATO forces came in and Serbian
troops left.
</P>
<P>
   Their frail, bruised bodies bear witness to their reports of
severe beatings.
</P>
<P>
   For Janko Jankovic, the violence started when the German Kosovo
Force (KFOR) troops arrived _ the same day Serb troops started
leaving and the KLA took over the local police station.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was at my son's apartment, visiting. Then when I left the
apartment, the KLA kidnapped me and took me to the police
station,'' Jankovic, 68, said. ``Every hour, they beat me _ on my
ribs, my kidneys, my chest and my head,'' he said, exposing his
purple bruises and a head wound the size of a grapefruit.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why the KLA would attack him, Jankovic shrugged, then
winced from the pain of his fractured rib.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were looking for weapons. What I had, I gave to them,''
he said. ``But then they said, `Why don't you speak Albanian? You
must know Albanian,''' and started to beat him, Jankovic said _ a
turnabout on the Serb military assaults during the war. Many
Albanians who survived attacks by Serb forces say the Serb soldiers
demanded they speak in Serbian, or recite Serbian slogans.
</P>
<P>
   The monastery also houses a few Albanians and gypsies. Many of
these people were suspected, rightly or wrongly, of collaborating
with the Serbs, shelter administrators say.
</P>
<P>
   The aid group Relief International runs an on-site clinic for
the residents, some of whom are still recovering from beatings, and
others who suffer from chronic health problems.
</P>
<P>
   Since the residents can't leave the monastery _ guarded
around-the-clock by German KFOR soldiers _ they can't get to the
hospital. Some of the patients also might not feel comfortable
being cared for by Albanian doctors, who for nearly a decade were
virtually shut out of Serb hospitals.
</P>
<P>
   Jim Schermerhorn, an American physician's assistant with the
National Institutes of Health, gave up a month's vacation time to
volunteer for the job, and he has a full caseload. There is a
little girl whose teeth are rotted to the bone. A 73-year-old
Serbian man is so gaunt after being abused in prison, his entire
rib cage is visible.
</P>
<P>
   A young Albanian mother, who reported that she was raped by five
different Serb soldiers when they came to take her husband away,
lives here with her 8-month-old daughter. Another woman,
Schermerhorn believes, is schizophrenic, but he has no
anti-psychotic drugs to prescribe for her.
</P>
<P>
   Schermerhorn doesn't take much note of people's ethnicities, and
he doesn't ask who caused their injuries. ``I only ask where they
were beaten and with what,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The monastery residents aren't so background-blind. Serbs and
Albanians at the safe house have segregated dormitories, and the
adults of each ethnic group rarely speak to each other in the
monastery's courtyard garden.
</P>
<P>
   The children, too traumatized at first even to speak, now play
together _ but that ``is the only interaction between people
here,'' Schermerhorn said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither the aid workers nor the residents know when people will
be able to leave. Typically, Schermerhorn said, the elderly people
there were the ones who were left behind to tend the animals, while
their adult children found refuge elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the Serbs had sons in the army or paramilitary, and when
these men left Kosovo with the military pullout, their parents were
left behind, vulnerable.
</P>
<P>
   Outside the monastery walls, Prizren has largely returned to its
pre-war condition. Cafes are open, and there is food on the shelves
in stores. Considered the most ethnically harmonious of Kosovar
cities before the war - Prizren has a lively mix of Serbs,
Albanians, and Turks - the city was barely damaged during the war.
</P>
<P>
   Even the mosques were left untouched, a remarkable omission in a
war in which so many of the oldest, most culturally-cherished
structures were burned to the ground.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just can't go home yet,'' said 66-year-old Nadelzhda
Marjanovic. ``Here, at least we are alive.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
