<HEADER>
A7736 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-JUNKBONDS-ART     07-02 0857
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-JUNKBONDS-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR THOSE WHO DARE, SOME PEARLS IN THE JUNK-BOND SEAS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ala., N.Y., Ill.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4)  
 (af)  
 By ABBY SCHULTZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In some ways, it is a paradox: high-yield bond funds performed
better than any other type of fixed-income funds in the first half
of the year, yet investors continued to shun them.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the rate of defaults on high-yield bonds, better known as
junk bonds, has been rising steadily since last year, the first
sustained climb in more than five years. And many bond dealers are
refusing to handle junk bonds because of the risk.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, the lack of demand has left the yield premium, or
spread, between high-yield bonds and Treasury issues at 4.9
percentage points at the end of the second quarter, more than a
point above the historical average.
</P>
<P>
   But some analysts say that the spread is likely to narrow,
moving closer to the average, and that prices may rise.
</P>
<P>
   This year through June 30, high-yield bond funds delivered a
total return of 3.0 percent, on average, compared with a decline of
1.8 percent for the average intermediate-term government bond fund,
according to Morningstar Inc., the fund publishers in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   Still, junk bonds have not fully recovered from their
near-collapse last fall, when investors fled from them and other
high-risk securities. For the most part, their yields remain higher
than their stated coupon rates.
</P>
<P>
   Junk bonds pay higher interest rates than investment-grade
corporate bonds, because they are issued by companies that for
various reasons have risks in their financial outlooks. Maybe the
company is new, or has an aggressive business plan, or has had
financial difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Some investors like junk bonds because of the higher returns,
but also because they can diversify a portfolio. Junk bonds are
less likely than most other bonds to be affected by general
economic news, although their prices, and thus their yields, which
move in the opposite direction, are very sensitive to the issuers'
fortunes.
</P>
<P>
   Most individual investors buy high-yield bonds through mutual
funds, and some investors might find them especially appealing now,
with the market relatively inexpensive. On June 30, the yield on
the average junk bond tracked by the Merrill Lynch High-Yield
Master II index was 10.7 percent, versus 5.8 percent for the
10-year Treasury note.
</P>
<P>
   That 4.9-point spread is hardly typical. From Jan. 1, 1993,
through Dec. 31, 1997 _ a time of relative stability _ the spread
was 3.68 percentage points, on average, according to Merrill Lynch.
The current gap, however, is still much smaller than the 6.8 points
on Oct. 16, 1998, just after the Federal Reserve lowered short-term
rates for the second of three times last year in the face of global
financial turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   Last week, the Fed, as expected, raised short-term rates a
quarter of a percentage point. But surprisingly, it indicated it
was not leaning toward another increase in the near future.
</P>
<P>
   Many bond analysts expect yields on junk bonds to return to
their historical relationship to Treasuries. If so, prices may
rise.
</P>
<P>
   ``We still think there's room to grow in terms of capital
appreciation,'' said Stewart H. Welch 3d, a financial planner in
Birmingham, Ala. ``And you are still picking up the yield.'' Welch
expects the high-yield market to have total returns _ price
appreciation and coupon income _ in the range of 12 percent to 14
percent by the end of 1999.
</P>
<P>
   But there are reasons for caution _ and some experts think
prices could go still lower in the short term.
</P>
<P>
   The current spread between junk bonds and Treasuries is a
reflection of market risks, said Martin Fridson, senior high-yield
strategist at Merrill Lynch. He noted that defaults by companies
that issue junk bonds are up; according to Moody's Investors
Service, the bond rating agency, such defaults rose to 3.68 percent
for the 12 months ended March 31, the highest level since 1993.
</P>
<P>
   Another problem is that many bond dealers are unwilling to buy
high-yield securities, Fridson said. Typically, dealers step in to
buy junk bonds because investors are not always readily available.
</P>
<P>
   In the past, dealers bought junk bonds hoping to sell at a
profit before a downturn. But after being hurt last fall by the
selloff of risky securities, many dealers will not commit capital
to the junk-bond market, Fridson said. ``You should get extra yield
to compensate you for the fact that you have a much greater roach
motel risk,'' he said. ``You can get in, but you can't get out.''
</P>
<P>
   Roger King, manager of Dreyfus High-Yield Securities, the
best-performing junk-bond fund in the first half of this year,
agreed that prices, unsettled as the market is, might go lower.
``One of the problems with high yield is that there is always an
imbalance between supply and demand,'' he said, resulting in too
many bonds for the market.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Investors, meanwhile, have continued to leave junk-bond funds.
For the eight weeks ended June 30, $1.4 billion flowed out of such
funds, according to AMG Data Services, which tracks fund sales,
though there was one week of net inflows in June.
</P>
<P>
   A lot of the outflow probably represents selling by market
timers trying to take advantage of short-term price movements,
Fridson said. They may have been unnerved by rising interest rates
and default rates, he added.
</P>
<P>
   Market timers can have a big impact on high-yield bond funds.
The Strong High Yield Bond fund shrank to $420 million in assets
last fall, from $720 million, as the high-yield market collapsed.
The fund's co-manager, Thomas Price, estimates that only half the
loss was a result of the market's slide; the rest was caused by
investors' pulling money out of the fund.
</P>
<P>
   To discourage timers, the fund now charges a 1 percent
redemption fee to investors who withdraw their money within six
months, Price said.
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the high-yield market is still a bit shaky. But it may
nonetheless be attractive for long-term investors seeking high
income and possible capital appreciation. ``I think it's wise to be
in junk bonds,'' said Eric Jacobson, a fixed-income analyst at
Morningstar. Depending on their risk tolerance, he said, investors
may want 5, 10 or 15 percent of their portfolios to be in junk
bonds.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Jacobson agreed with Fridson that yield spreads
were wide for a reason and that buyers should be cautious.
</P>
<P>
   One consideration in selecting a high-yield bond fund is its
investment style. Some funds, of course, are riskier than others,
investing in lower-quality issues with higher yields. The
portfolios of funds with the highest-quality junk bonds will
typically have weighted average credit ratings of double-B from
Standard &AMP; Poor's, a major ratings agency; those of riskier funds
will have weighted average ratings of single-B, or below.
</P>
<P>
   ``One type of fund isn't better than another; you just need to
know what you're buying,'' Jacobson said.
</P>
<P>
   Dreyfus High Yield Securities, for instance, favors bonds with
no ratings or with ratings of single-B or lower, and subjects them
to intensive research before buying. The fund lost 15.84 percent in
1998. But for the first half of this year, it was the
best-performing high-yield fund, with total return of 15.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   King, its manager, views high-yield bonds as long-term
investments and makes no apologies for the wild swings. ``There are
other high-yield investments that are less volatile,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Fidelity High-Income, up 6.8 percent in the first half of this
year, had an average annual return of 11.3 percent for the three
years through June 30. The fund relies on a team of 16 high-yield
analysts, including its manager, Thomas Soviero. Though it has a
weighted average credit rating of single-B, it still ended 1998
with a gain of 3.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Soviero said he expects the performance of high-yield bonds to
improve; he is not worried about the rise in default rates. Indeed,
he said, the market nervousness creates opportunities to find bonds
that others may overlook. ``We should be able to avoid those
defaults and find the pearls,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
