<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7742 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CONTROLLER-FAILURE-BO     07-02 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CONTROLLER-FAILURE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTNING STRIKE LEAVES AIR TRAFFIC IN NORTHEAST ON ITS OWN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATTHEW BRELIS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   A lightning strike at the cavernous air-traffic facility in New
Hampshire, where controllers direct high altitude planes in
airspace over New England and upstate New York, knocked out radar
and radio communications with airplanes Friday and brought holiday
air travel in the region to a halt.
</P>
<P>
   At 3:41 p.m., on one of the busiest travel days of the year,
lightning struck Federal Aviation Administration's Boston Air Route
Traffic Control Center in Nashua, N.H., causing widespread delays
throughout the nation's air system and affecting travel over the
North Atlantic.
</P>
<P>
   When radar screens went dark, controllers had to rely on a
slower back-up system that requires them to handwrite identifying
information about flights and pass the notes from one controller to
the next as the planes traveled across New England.
</P>
<P>
   The back-up system was in use for two hours and 49 minutes until
the regular system went back on line at 6:30 p.m. But residual
delays were expected to last for the rest of the day, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   For nearly three peak hours, all jet airplanes were restricted
from taking off at airports throughout New England, including
Boston's Logan International Airport. And the effects of the outage
and slower back-up system rippled throughout the nation as planes
across the country headed for Boston, Providence, Manchester, N.H.,
Hartford, Burlington, Vt., and Portland were all told to stay put.
</P>
<P>
   Flights inbound to New York from Europe were rerouted around the
affected air space, and flights at New York's airports headed for
Europe were also unable to take off, said FAA spokeswoman Arlene
Salac. The Boston Center handles virtually all Europe-bound
aircraft departing from anywhere on the Eastern Seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   Officials could not begin to estimate the number of planes and
people affected, but controllers at the Boston Center _ which has
experienced numerous outages over the years _ said Friday's was
among the worst.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has the potential to be the most serious outage they have
ever had,'' said Mike Blake, the regional vice president for the
National Air Traffic Controllers Association. ``It is a summer
holiday weekend, there are thunderstorms in the area, it is a busy
time of day. This is a big one.''
</P>
<P>
   At Logan, the scene was one of long lines, short tempers and
plans for quick getaways for the holiday weekend vanishing with
each tick of the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are going to have extensive delays,'' groaned Massport
spokesman Jeremy Crockford. ``We are landing planes that are in the
air, but there are holds on in other cities. Flights inbound will
be delayed hours.''
</P>
<P>
   The only bright spot was small propeller planes flying
passengers to and from the Cape and Islands and some northern New
England destinations. They were permitted to take off because they
fly under 10,000 feet and are not tracked by controllers in the
Boston Center.
</P>
<P>
   But even on the Cape and Islands, delays were of historic
proportions.
</P>
<P>
   Consider Nantucket Airport, which on the July 4th weekend often
handles as many planes as Logan Airport. Usually, planes on final
approach to Nantucket are separated by 2.5 miles or 3 miles. Friday
afternoon and early evening, planes flying into Nantucket were
separated by 35 miles, controllers said.
</P>
<P>
   There were no bright spots for the controllers in the Boston
Center, whose job it is to maintain safe separation among planes
hurtling across the sky at speeds that can exceed 500 miles per
hour.
</P>
<P>
   Blake said all the radar screens in the center went blank for
about a minute, forcing controllers to transition to the slower
back-up system.
</P>
<P>
   ``During the transition, it gets very excited. As a controller,
it is one of those times you count on the system and when you don't
have it, it places you in a very uncomfortable position.''
</P>
<P>
   Howard Sevey, one of the controllers who was working in the
building at the time of the lightning strike and a union
representative at the facility said ``you could feel the building
shake. It either hit the building _ which is built like a fallout
shelter _ or one of the antenna.''
</P>
<P>
   In at least two sectors, the radar screens failed completely.
</P>
<P>
   Working quickly, controllers working in sectors adjacent to
those who lost radar coverage, expanded their coverage area so the
blind controllers could cobble together a working picture of the
planes under their responsibility.
</P>
<P>
   To communicate with the planes, the controllers used a back-up
radio system they are not familiar with. ``I've been a controller
for 18 years and I have never used it,'' Sevey said.
</P>
<P>
   The Boston Center is one of 21 high-altitude air-traffic control
centers around the country operated by the FAA. Its air space
extends north to Canada, south of Long Island, east into the
Atlantic and west to Western New York state.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA has consistently maintained that the nation's
air-traffic system is safe because of the redundancies built into
the system, and while outages may cause delays, planes stay safely
separated because there are fewer of them in the air and the
separation between them is increased.
</P>
<P>
   While controllers said they were not aware of any mishaps or
close calls because of Friday's outage, a computer outage at the
Boston Center late last year resulted in two Europe-bound jumbo
jets nearly colliding off Long Island. On Dec. 6, a British
Caledonian L-1011 with 271 people on board heading from Montego Bay
to Manchester, England, and a Delta Airlines Boeing 767 going from
Atlanta to Zurich with 101 on board came within a mile of each
other while both were traveling at an altitude of 33,000 feet and a
speed of more than 500 miles per hour.
</P>
<P>
   At that altitude, safe separation is considered to be 2,000 feet
vertically or 5 miles horizontally. On board computers that are
programmed to alert pilots to other traffic in the area directed
the two planes to alter their course.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA could not immediately say what lightning prevention
equipment is built into the Boston Center and whether it worked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
