<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 19:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7747 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-PERFORMANCE-A     07-02 0829
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-PERFORMANCE-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SO WHERE'S THE PARTY? TRY THE OTHER SIDE OF THE TRACKS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Ill., N.Y., N.J.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4)  
 (af)  
 By EDWARD WYATT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Rarely have investors received a clearer warning about the
danger of chasing after hot-performing mutual funds.
</P>
<P>
   Take a look at the list of the worst-performing funds in the
second quarter. It's includes many of the same portfolios that were
the best performers in 1998 _ funds like Janus 20, Excelsior Large
Cap Growth and Smith Barney Large Cap Growth, all of which soared
last year as investors flocked to big, liquid stocks, particularly
in the technology sector.
</P>
<P>
   Now check the list of the best performers in the second quarter.
You will find the types of funds that investors shunned last year
and for much of the last several years: funds like Liberty-Crabbe
Huson Special and Goldman Sachs Small Cap Value, which specialize
in finding hidden gems among small-capitalization stocks.
</P>
<P>
   As those ranking suggest, the world in which investors had grown
so comfortable over the last few years was turned on its head in
the second quarter, as the air leaked out of the Internet balloon,
while sectors and funds that had been written off for dead suddenly
came to life.
</P>
<P>
   Remember real estate? Funds that specialize in the sector lost
16 percent of their value last year, on average, but gained more
than 10 percent in the second quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Does energy evoke any memories? Funds that invest in
natural-resource stocks lost 17 percent, on average, last year, but
surged more than 15 percent in the quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Recall Garrett Van Wagoner? His funds performed poorly in 1997
and 1998, but the Van Wagoner Micro Cap and Emerging Growth funds,
shot up on the last day of the second quarter, to the top of the
rankings.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you have a period of extended performance in one
direction or another, you get to a point where people take profits
and expectations start to become a little more realistic,'' said
Russel Kinnel, mutual funds editor at Morningstar Inc., the Chicago
financial publisher that provided those statistics and other
performance data for this quarterly report.
</P>
<P>
   ``Likewise, after a period, some things get so cheap that people
start to take advantage of the low prices,'' Kinnel said. ``That is
what you expect to happen. The bigger surprise is that the recent
trend lasted as long as it did.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, while the average American diversified equity fund
gained nearly 9 percent in the second quarter, the results varied
widely according to the size of the companies a fund contained.
Large-cap growth funds, which have made up the best-performing
category of funds over the last one- and five-year periods, gained
just 4.2 percent in the quarter, while small-cap funds, laggards
over the longer periods, racked up double-digit gains.
</P>
<P>
   The relatively poor performance of many large-cap stocks allowed
equity fund managers, on average, to outperform the Standard &AMP;
Poor's 500-stock index, which gained a bit more than 7 percent in
the second quarter, including reinvested dividends.
</P>
<P>
   The same trends evident in Morningstar's broad fund categories
can be seen in the lists of the best-performing individual funds.
Consider the Internet Fund, an aptly titled portfolio that invests
in companies that make their living exploiting the economic
potential of cyberspace.
</P>
<P>
   The fund led the pack in the year ended June 30, with a gain of
252.6 percent. Rarely has a mutual fund tripled its money in a
year, but the last 12 months have been no ordinary time for
Internet stocks, or for the funds that invest in them.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with those gains is that relatively few investors
have actually enjoyed them. On June 30, 1998, at the beginning of
its spectacular 12-month run, the Internet Fund had just $1 million
in assets. Even as recently as Dec. 31, the fund's coffers
contained only $22 million.
</P>
<P>
   Since the beginning of this year, however, the Internet Fund has
taken in roughly $600 million in new cash from investors. AMG Data
Services, a fund-tracking company, said the biggest flows, at a
rate of about $100 million a week, came in April _ just as the
Internet sector was peaking.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Fund's net asset value hit $38.08 a share on April
13; it then fell 12 percent during the rest of the quarter, to
$33.49. In other words, recent investors in the fund would have
fared better somewhere else.
</P>
<P>
   If the recent sluggish performance were not enough worry for
shareholders, there is now another unknown: how the fund will fare
under new management. Ryan Jacob, who had managed the fund since
the end of 1997, resigned last month after a planned sale of the
company that managed the fund's portfolio fell through.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The fund is now managed by a team including Peter Doyle, a
co-founder of the fund and chairman of Kinetics Asset Management of
North Babylon, N.Y., which holds the contract to manage the
portfolio, and Steven Tuen, who is also director of research at the
IPO Value Monitor, a research service in New York.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet Fund is not the only fund of its type to show up on
the list of winners. Munder Net Net, the largest Internet fund,
surged to become one of the top performers among specialized funds
during the last 12 months, with a return of 116 percent.
</P>
<P>
   But the fund gained a mere 3 percent in the second quarter, a
slowdown that was unexpected for investors who poured money into
the fund in April at a rate of $200 million a week.
</P>
<P>
   The confluence of large flows of money into a fund and a
downturn in performance is not unusual, financial professionals
say. In fact, the link is seen beyond the Internet field.
</P>
<P>
   The Janus 20 fund, one of last year's top performers, took in
nearly $7 billion in new assets in the year's first four months,
including $2 billion in April alone, then shut its doors to new
investors. The fund lost about 4 percent of its value in the second
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   ``Americans like to buy everything on sale except stocks,'' said
David H. Bugen, a financial adviser whose firm, Bugen, Stuart, Korn
&AMP; Cordero, is based in Chatham, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, mutual fund investors, much like investors who buy
stocks directly, seem to prefer buying what has already gone up the
most. Emerging-markets funds, which gained more than 70 percent, on
average, in 1993, took in more than $1 billion a month the next
year. But in the five years that ended June 30, those funds lost
money, on average.
</P>
<P>
   The calamity that hit emerging markets in 1997 and 1998 all but
dried up investor interest. So how many investors were around to
enjoy the 21 percent gain over the last year _ or the 26 percent
gain in the second quarter? Far fewer, to be sure.
</P>
<P>
   There are several reasons for those crossing currents. For
starters, unlike most items bought by consumers, financial products
are expected to appreciate in value. In contrast, when someone buys
a refrigerator or a car, it is expected that the value will
decrease over time. It makes sense, then, that a buyer would want
to pay as little as possible for a Kelvinator that will be hard to
resell at some point down the road.
</P>
<P>
   But a more basic instinct also plays a part: greed. Few people
turn down a chance to get rich quickly. In an investing environment
like the current one, where it seems that everyone has a friend or
relative who hit it big on an Internet stock, it is tempting to
chase after the hottest-performing funds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The trick is, the big bucks are usually made by doing the
opposite,'' Kinnel said. ``That is, buying when everyone else hates
something and sticking around until it goes up.''
</P>
<P>
   It takes discipline to keep buying when a sector is
underperforming, said Bugen, the financial adviser. The average
investor is faced with such a situation more often than not. ``It's
not unusual to have one asset class lead the way,'' he said. ``So
you have to develop a strategy and adhere to it, and rebalance back
to your target allocations. Over the long term, you'll end up
buying low and selling high. You're not saying this asset class is
undervalued or doing market timing; you're just sticking with a
discipline.''
</P>
<P>
   That can be particularly difficult when, for example, large-cap
mutual funds are gaining more than 20 percent a year and small-cap
funds are barely breaking even, if that. Putting a bigger portion
of new investments in the underperforming groups, to keep an
overall portfolio weighting constant, can be painful.
</P>
<P>
   ``People feel as if they're missing out on the party if they're
not totally invested in the best-performing groups,'' Bugen said.
``But if one has a strategy and stays with it, in the long run
you'll have less volatility, and your compounded returns will be
higher.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
