<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COKE-POLAND-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COKE RECALLS BOTTLED WATER IN POLAND AFTER BACTERIA ARE FOUND 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In its second beverage recall in Poland this week, Coca-Cola Co.
said Friday that it was removing all half-liter bottles of its
Bonaqua Plus purified water from stores because Polish government
scientists had detected coliform bacteria in the product.
</P>
<P>
   About 180,000 bottles of the water had already been distributed
by the bottler, Coca-Cola Beverages, and were being pulled from the
market, a Coca-Cola spokeswoman, Sonya Soutus, said. All of them
will be destroyed, along with thousands more bottles that were in
warehouses awaiting shipment, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Soutus insisted that the coliform bacteria found in Bonaqua
Plus _ a new product that was introduced June 15 and so named
because it has more minerals added to it than the regular Bonaqua
bottled water that Coke sells _ was not harmful. But she would not
say whether it was the E-coli variety, which is often traced to
human or animal feces.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the best assumption, but they have not told us that
directly,'' she said, adding that at a news conference Friday,
Polish officials mentioned the possibility. ``We're doing our own
testing.''
</P>
<P>
   Some types of E-coli have caused outbreaks of severe illness and
even death, particularly among young children, the elderly and
others with limited immune systems. The presence of E-coli ``is an
indication there was fecal contamination somewhere along the
line,'' said Dennis Juranek, associate director of the division of
parasitic diseases at the Centers for Disease Control. He said more
than 99 percent of all E-coli are harmless.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Soutus said Coke had begun the recall on its own, after
being informed on Tuesday that the government tests had turned up
``some questionable results.'' She added: ``At that point, we
decided to look at what we needed to do in the current
environment.'' Once the coliform was confirmed Thursday, the
government told Coke to continue its recall, though Ms. Soutus said
there was no sense of urgency about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``The bottom line is, since it's non-pathogenic and not
hazardous, there is not a rush on it,'' she said. ``It's not
harmful to anyone's health.''
</P>
<P>
   The news was the latest development in what has become a
European ordeal for for Coke this year. In June, the company was
ordered to remove all its bottled and canned soft drinks from
Belgium after hundreds of people reported feeling ill after
drinking Coke and Fanta. Luxembourg enacted a ban as well, while
France ordered the closing of a huge bottling plant in Dunkirk and
the Netherlands banned Coke products produced in Belgium. Most of
the bans were lifted last week.
</P>
<P>
   No illnesses have been reported in Poland as a result of
drinking Bonaqua Plus, Ms. Soutus said. The fault lies with the
operator of the bottling plant in Sroda Slonska, she said, adding
that he apparently ran the plant for more than 48 hours without
stopping to clean it. ``Our belief is that the bacteria accumulated
in the line because it was running constantly around the clock for
two and half days,'' she said. ``It was a violation of procedure.''
</P>
<P>
   Coke said Tuesday that it was recalling Bonaqua in .33-liter
glass bottles throughout Poland after mold was discovered by a
consumer in one bottle. That recall was widened Wednesday to
include all Coke brands in that size bottle. They are being
replaced with the same size bottle in plastic.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
