<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREA HALTS TALKS WITH NORTH
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ERIK ECKHOLM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BEIJING _ South Korean officials said Friday that they were
suspending talks with North Korea because it had refused to discuss
reuniting families divided by the Korean War of the early 1950s.
</P>
<P>
   The talks here began on June 22, with South Korea's seeking
progress on its longstanding goal of uniting millions of aging
people who have not seen their relatives since the war. North
Korea, suffering from an economic collapse and famine, wants
increased aid from the South.
</P>
<P>
   The South promised 200,000 tons in fertilizer and delivered half
of that before the talks began. But three meetings over 11 days
have gone nowhere.
</P>
<P>
   The talks were soured by a naval confrontation, apparently
caused by North Korean testing of maritime borders. On June 15,
South Korean naval forces sank a North Korean torpedo boat, killing
at least 20 sailors. The South said the North Koreans had fired
first.
</P>
<P>
   In the talks here, the North has demanded that South Korea
apologize for the clash and that it deliver the rest of the
fertilizer. The South refuses to apologize and says it will not
deliver the other 100,000 tons of fertilizer until the North
discusses the family issue.
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday the two sides met only briefly and Friday, the South
Korean delegation announced that it was leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is meaningless to go on like this so we are heading home,''
said Yang Yong-sik, the chief South Korean delegate.
</P>
<P>
   In South Korea, the naval clash and the stalled talks on family
unification have led to increased criticism of President Kim Dae
Jung's ``sunshine policy'' of opening economic and political
contacts with the North.
</P>
<P>
   American officials have also reported evidence that North Korea
may be preparing to test a ballistic missile. Such a test would
likely scuttle an American proposal to improve economic ties with
North Korea in exchange for restraint on weapons tests and sales.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
