<SLUG> BC-JAWS-ANNIVERSARY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLANDERS RECALL THE MAKING OF `JAWS' 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and e coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By THOMAS FARRAGHER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was the summer of blood in the water, dark fins on the
horizon, and terror in the sand dunes. It was Tinsel Town on
Nantucket Sound.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago this summer Steven Spielberg came to
Martha's Vineyard to do for body surfing what Alfred Hitchcock had
done for hot showers.
</P>
<P>
   And in the shops of Menemsha and the inns of Edgartown, the
pulsating theme of ``Jaws'' _ the fish-bites-man film that drove
grown men to shrieks of terror _ still brings smiles to the
islanders who mingled with the stars.
</P>
<P>
   ``They told the extras not to wear red because they planned for
the colors in the movie to gradually blend from the blues and the
greens at the beginning of the movie to the bloody reds at the
end,'' said Janice Hull, an assistant to the local casting
director. ``Boy, that was a big summer.''
</P>
<P>
   None bigger. The Spielberg blockbuster, the first movie ever
filmed on the island, grossed more than a half a billion dollars.
And its story about a killer shark off fictional Amity Island is
credited with helping create a cachet that today makes the Vineyard
one of the country's most exclusive pieces of real estate.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's sort of an ironic mixed blessing about `Jaws,' '' said
Lee Fierro, who played the role of a young shark victim's mother in
the movie's opening sequences. ``It's given the island a great deal
because people come and spend money. But on the other hand, it had
added to the hordes and hordes of people who are drawn here.''
</P>
<P>
   What drew filmmaker Spielberg, then a 20-something director who
had yet to achieve mega-mogul status, was pristine landscapes and
breathtaking ocean vistas that he would make the backdrop for a
bloody excursion with a hungry shark.
</P>
<P>
   He asked the local villagers along for the ride.
</P>
<P>
   ``They wanted a dirty old character who gets eaten up by a
shark,'' recalled Craig Kingsbury, 86, who played the role of Ben
Gardner, whose bobbing skull provides the movie's first cinematic
jolt. ``The lady testing guys for the part took one look at me and
said: `Seek no more.' Now, how the hell that shark spit that head
back in the boat after he bit it off, I'll never know.''
</P>
<P>
   Kingsbury's daughter, Trina, said her mother, needlessly,
reminded her children that the skull scene in the movie was from a
cast made of their father's head _ not the real thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've seen that movie five or six times now and every time
dad's head pops out of that hull _ Woooeee! _ I hit the ceiling,''
Kingsbury said. ``That still gets me.''
</P>
<P>
   The top-grossing movie of all time until ``Star Wars'' knocked
it off two years later, Jaws virtually turned Martha's Vineyard on
its ear. Originally scheduled for several weeks of shooting
beginning in the spring, production instead stretched throughout
the summer and into the fall.
</P>
<P>
   The Fourth of July parade was filmed in May, a blessedly sunny
day, that helped make it appear a little more summer-like despite
the fact that tree limbs were bare. Some beach scenes were shot in
June when the surf's temperature was bone chilling. And that darned
shark _ actually three different mechanical ones _ kept breaking
down. They nicknamed it Bruce.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems one of the guys got drunk one day and stole one of
the sharks and he towed it around Edgartown Harbor on one of those
floating dry docks,'' said Edith Blake, who covered the making of
the movie for the Vineyard Gazette and later wrote a book about it.
``My mother woke up one morning in her little waterfront boathouse
and found herself staring at it and she thought: Good God!''
</P>
<P>
   The more human encounters are the ones most islanders recall.
</P>
<P>
   Virginia Poole, who helped the local casting director, said she
wondered for days what her father-in-law, Donald Poole who played
the harbor master, and Spielberg talked about each morning as they
sat on the set.
</P>
<P>
   ``He'd have to go down to the set early each morning and they'd
have these long conversations each day and finally I said to him:
`What is it that you and Steven Spielberg talk about every day?'
And he said, `Who is Steven Spielberg? I've been meaning to ask you
what that man's job is.' ''
</P>
<P>
   If Spielberg had yet to attain marquee status, the film's stars,
Robert Shaw, Roy Scheider and Richard Dreyfuss, needed no
introductions to the onlookers, extras, and those who managed to
win bit parts.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had done the scene where I slap Roy Scheider and we had done
a couple of takes when he came up to me, put his hands on my
shoulder and complimented me with incredible enthusiasm,'' Fierro
said.
</P>
<P>
   Fierro, who played the grieving and black-veiled Mrs. Kintner,
said she at first turned down the role after it required her to
utter vulgarities that was uncomfortable with.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was not about to swear and say four-letter words, especially
ones that begin with F, on the big screen,'' said Fierro, a local
theatrical actress. ``They got the writer to rewrite the scene in a
different way. And they decided they liked it better that way after
all.''
</P>
<P>
   If the film itself evokes warm memories from those associated
with it, other islanders recall the tumult associated with the
filmmaking more coolly.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of people complaining about the noise, and
closed streets, and the trucks,'' Blake said. ``They wanted to
build Robert Shaw's house over in Menemsha. And they were only
going to need it for a week or two but the stupid islanders made
them conform with all the local zoning laws. It was awfully petty.
Since then, they don't make movies here.''
</P>
<P>
   She said producers for the new Kevin Costner movie, ``Message in
a Bottle,'' briefly considered making it on the island, but took a
pass.
</P>
<P>
   If Martha's Vineyard never became Hollywood-East, the memories
of its big-time hit lingers.
</P>
<P>
   Fierro said, while she knows it's silly, she can't stop thinking
about the dangers of shark attacks each time she approaches the
shoreline.
</P>
<P>
   And that tingling hesitation all goes back to the summer of '74.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll never forget that summer,'' Virginia Poole said. ``I
remember it from a mother's perspective. That was the summer a lot
of mothers discovered that their small kids were suddenly afraid to
go into the water.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
