<HEADER>
A7762 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-FOUNTAIN-BALLET-NYT &LR;      07-02 1147
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FOUNTAIN-BALLET-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LONG TRIP TO THE MET FOR A TATAR LOVE STORY 
</HEADLINE>
   (Editors: first four grafs should be italicized)  
 (bl)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``The Fountain of Bakhchisarai,'' one of the most famous ballets
created in the Soviet Union, will be presented for the first time
in the United States when the Kirov Ballet performs it on Tuesday,
Wednesday and next Saturday at the Metropolitan Opera House in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   Until now American impresarios have been shy about importing a
work that so strongly embodies the principles of Socialist Realism.
Yet today that doctrine's emphasis on reaching a mass audience with
uplifting themes makes this dance-drama, created in Leningrad in
1934, a historical curiosity.
</P>
<P>
   Choreographed by Rostislav Zakharov to a score by Boris
Asafiyev, ``The Fountain of Bakhchisarai'' was based on Alexander
Pushkin's poem of the same title and remained in the repertory of
many ballet companies throughout the Soviet era. Galina Ulanova,
who became the supreme ballerina of that time, was the original
Maria, the Polish princess abducted by a Tatar chief in the ballet.
Ulanova wrote that her Stanislavskian identification with Maria and
the ballet's realism impelled her to add new ``meaning'' to her
performances in ``Giselle'' and ``Swan Lake.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert A. Rupen, professor emeritus of political science at the
University of North Carolina, Chapel Hill, has researched the
political context of the ballet and the locale in which it is set.
</P>
<P>
   By ROBERT A. RUPEN &QC;
</P>
<P>
   Today the fountain, the palace and the town of Bakhchisarai, 20
miles northwest of Yalta in the Crimea, are tourist attractions.
Thanks to Pushkin's poem, Bakhchisarai has become a permanent part
of Russian culture. Indeed, the poem probably saved the name and
some important aspects of the place in the face of powerful forces
for Russification and the ravages of Stalinism.
</P>
<P>
   Pushkin published the poem in 1823. It was immediately
successful, and the words were set to music as early as 1825.
Attempts to base a ballet on it were made in 1838, 1854 and 1890 (a
pantomime with dance), and in 1892 a religious-mystical version
called ``The Victim of Jealousy'' appeared. It was staged by Thomas
Nijinsky, father of the famous dancer, Vaslav Nijinsky. But the
Soviet production, first performed in September 1934 with music by
Asafiyev (1884-1949), became the standard.
</P>
<P>
   That production reflected an important political and cultural
shift in Stalin's Russia. The assassination of the political boss
of Leningrad, Sergei M. Kirov, heralded intensified political
control and before long extensive purges. Culturally, Socialist
Realism triumphed, including fearful and dull conformity. Russian
nationalism was also encouraged, and Russian classics provided a
degree of protection as the terror developed.
</P>
<P>
   In this version of the ballet, the Crimean Tatar chief, the
Giray Khan, leads ``Mongol hordes'' to Poland, and among other
despoliation, uses a spectacular fire to destroy a Polish
aristocrat's manor house. Maria, a lovely survivor, is snatched up
by the Khan and brought back to his harem at the Bakhchisarai
palace. Zarema, the harem favorite, becomes fiercely jealous and
kills Maria. Inconsolable, the Khan erects the famous fountain,
still commonly called the Fountain of Tears.
</P>
<P>
   In truth, the Giray Khans, who ruled from the early 15th century
until 1783, were respected throughout the Islamic and
Mongol-Tibetan world as the legitimate successors of the Chinggis
Khan (Genghis Khan). Even the rulers of the Ottoman Empire bowed to
the Crimean Tatar Khans' Chingizid legitimacy.
</P>
<P>
   Although the original Crimean Tatar Khan's palace was built in
1518, the man who inspired Pushkin was Kirim Giray Khan, who led
the Crimean Tatars on raids into Europe in the 1760s. Kirim Giray
Khan ordered the construction of the Fountain of Tears and
dedicated a tomb to his Georgian consort.
</P>
<P>
   The rest of the story, including Maria, was added by Pushkin,
however. The original Crimean Tatar palace, for example, was burned
by Russian soldiers in 1735, 25 years before Kirim led the Crimean
Tatars.
</P>
<P>
   In 1787 Catherine the Great planned a visit to Bakhchisarai as
part of a triumphal victory tour marking Russia's defeat of the
Ottoman Empire and related expansion to the South. Catherine wanted
to survey her new possessions, and Potemkin, her adviser and lover,
called the royal architect, Charles Cameron, to rebuild the palace.
She slept in the rebuilt palace for three nights in 1788, then
ordered the castle properly maintained in its existing Oriental
style. Potemkin, in his memoirs, described it as ``a compound of
Moorish, Arabian, Chinese and Turkish architecture.''
</P>
<P>
   Over time, the palace was neglected, however. In 1820 Pushkin
visited and was inspired to write the poem. (He also complained
about its poor condition.) Later, Catherine's grandson, Czar
Alexander I, restored the palace.
</P>
<P>
   In the 18th-century wars with the Turks, Gen. Alexander V.
Suvorov, the commander of the Russian forces, used the palace as
his military headquarters; thus the Bakhchisarai palace became a
symbol for Russian nationalism as well as an object of Crimean
Tatar identity.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, the German Wehrmacht occupied the Crimea,
including Bakhchisarai. (One of the German Stuka dive bombers who
was shot down by the Russians in the attack before the Nazi
invasion was Joseph Beuys, who later became a well-known artist. He
remained convinced that the imprecations and incantations of a
Crimean Tatar shaman saved his life.)
</P>
<P>
   Soon after the Russians drove the Germans out of the Crimea in
April 1944, Stalin declared that the Tatars had helped the German
occupiers. The Crimean Tatars became one of the so-called punished
peoples, non-Russian minority ethnic groups exiled to Central Asia.
</P>
<P>
   The Bakhchisarai palace, which had been damaged during the war,
eventually became a military museum and memorial, with a T-70 tank
on a pedestal in the courtyard and an eternal flame to honor the
Red Army soldiers killed. The museum also commemorated Suvorov and
the earlier Crimean War.
</P>
<P>
   In 1954, Nikita Khrushchev transferred the Crimea from the
Russian Republic to the Ukraine, further complicating the area's
identity.
</P>
<P>
   With the collapse of the Soviet Union and all the post-Soviet
changes, about a quarter of a million Crimean Tatars have returned
to the Crimea. Mustafa Jemiliev, the longtime political leader of
the Crimean Tatars, lived in Bakhchisarai for many years and
sometimes worked in the palace, which includes a Suvorov Room, a
Pushkin Room and a Historical and Archaeological Museum.
</P>
<P>
   Although a majority of the Crimean population is ethnic Russian,
Ukraine intends to hold onto it. Meanwhile, the returning Crimean
Tatars stake their claim to independence from both Russians and
Ukrainians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
