<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DREAMWORKS-STUDIO-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAMWORKS QUITS PLAN TO BUILD NEW STUDIO COMPLEX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 By TODD S. PURDUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ In a move that reflects a mood of industry
retrenchment and ambivalence about its own grandest ambitions,
Dreamworks SKG has abandoned its plan to build Hollywood's first
new studio complex in more than 60 years. The company cited
difficulties in arranging acceptable financing to create its
planned campus of state-of-the-art sound stages as part of a
sprawling 1,000-acre development near Los Angeles International
Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The $250 million sound-stage project was the brainchild of
Steven Spielberg and his fellow moguls Jeffrey Katzenberg and David
Geffen, the three of whom founded Dreamworks five years ago and
with great fanfare announced plans for the studio, to be built on
the site of Howard Hughes' old aircraft factory. But from the
beginning the proposal was plagued by financial and political
wrangling, environmental lawsuits and doubts about its viability,
and Dreamworks threatened to abandon the site last year in a
dispute with the developers over the price of land.
</P>
<P>
   Late Thursday the studio's co-founders said they were dropping
the project at the new development, known as Playa Vista, because
of the problems with financing, together with rising interest rates
and construction costs, and Friday morning's headline in Daily
Variety, the industry journal, summed up the mood: ``Hasta La Playa
Vista, Baby.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We have learned a great deal during the past four years, and
it is clear that the move is no longer in Dreamworks' best
interest,'' Katzenberg said in a statement. ``It was simply not
meant to be.''
</P>
<P>
   But three of the Dreamworks investors _ Geffen, Spielberg and
Paul Allen, co-founder of Microsoft Corp. _ are billionaires and
could have arranged the money necessary to build the new studio,
had they chosen and had their company been generating a stronger
cash flow. So Hollywood executives were abuzz Friday with the
conviction that Dreamworks' decision to abandon the project
signaled a broader rethinking of the fledgling studio's goals.
</P>
<P>
   Though Spielberg said in his own statement that ``not building
at Playa Vista in no way deters us'' from the goal of building a
new studio, Dreamworks officials said that in the short term, the
company would probably simply expand its offices on the Universal
Studios lot in the San Fernando Valley, and at the Dreamworks
animation campus in nearby Glendale. Spielberg's partners _
especially Geffen, who made his fortune in the recording business,
with its low overhead costs _ have long been thought to harbor less
enthusiasm for building their own movie production complex than for
just renting existing sound stages.
</P>
<P>
   ``The financing was the last straw,'' one Dreamworks official
said. ``But it was the combination of all the delays, the
uneasiness about the financing, the increases in construction
costs, the changes in the industry and the changes in our own
thinking.''
</P>
<P>
   In its short history, Dreamworks has had mixed results,
producing hit movies like ``Saving Private Ryan'' and ``Antz'' and
the successful television sitcom ``Spin City,'' but also
disappointments like the movie ``In Dreams'' and the series
``Ink.'' Further, in the four years since the project was
announced, production activity in Hollywood itself has cooled
considerably, as studios have shifted filming abroad to save costs.
That has freed up once-overcrowded sound stages in Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fact is we've never had any trouble getting a stage for
any of our pictures,'' the Dreamworks official said.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the Dreamworks partners are said to be most
happy with the financial performance of their Gameworks unit, which
operates upscale computer-game arcades in shopping malls and was
created without the benefit of any elaborate headquarters campus or
fancy fiber-optic network of the sort envisioned for Playa Vista.
</P>
<P>
   The Playa Vista developers, which are backed by a consortium of
investors led by Morgan Stanley Dean Witter &AMP; Co. and Goldman,
Sachs &AMP; Co., said they would proceed to build their own sound
stages for lease on what would have been Dreamworks' 47-acre
parcel, using as a base the old hangars where Howard Hughes built
his flying boat, the Spruce Goose. Already, movies like
``Titanic,'' ``Men in Black'' and ``Independence Day'' have been
filmed in part on the Hughes site.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The phone is ringing off the hook this morning, to be quite
honest with you,'' said a spokesman for Playa Vista, David Herbst.
``We will retrofit the Hughes buildings, but we will also build
others. We're dusting off our plans and re-examining them to see
what the needs are.''
</P>
<P>
   The Playa Vista site, which is also scheduled to include 3,200
residential units and 3.2 million square feet of commercial office
space in its first phase, is one of the last remaining large tracts
of undeveloped land in greater Los Angeles. City officials spent
considerable effort to help the developers lure Dreamworks to the
project as anchor of a planned media campus, rewarding them for
success in that task with $35 million in job tax credits. The
developers will now lose that money, but plan to reapply to the
city after developing their own studio plan, Herbst said.
</P>
<P>
   Mayor Richard Riordan, who strongly backed the Dreamworks plan,
said the studio's decision ``is a disappointment, considering the
efforts which have gone into making this project real.''
</P>
<P>
   Dreamworks closed on a $20 million purchase of its Playa Vista
land in April, and the effort to build the first wholly new studio
since Warner Brothers moved to the San Fernando Valley in the 1930s
appeared to be back on track. But, Dreamworks officials said, they
were ultimately unable to settle on financing terms for building
the studio complex with investment partners, including Union Labor
Life Insurance Co., a labor pension fund group. Negotiations
produced too many roadblocks, including a provision specifying that
if the project came in over budget, Dreamworks could lose control
of the land to the other investors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were far too many controls on the deal and our ability
to coordinate it,'' one official said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Dreamworks will retrench in its existing operations,
with live-action feature production based at Spielberg's longtime
Amblin Entertainment outpost on the Universal lot; animation at the
17-acre Glendale animation campus, built while Playa Vista was tied
up in delays, and the Dreamworks Records operation in Beverly
Hills, which is Geffen's bailiwick. There are now five buildings on
the Glendale site, with room to build two more, which would
probably house offices.
</P>
<P>
   The larger Playa Vista project, meanwhile, has been beset by
lawsuits from a handful of environmental groups, who contend that
it would despoil wildlife habitats in the Ballona Wetlands, one of
the area's last remaining coastal marshes. Other environmental
groups have strongly backed the developers' plan to restore a
portion of the wetlands, and this week a Los Angeles Superior Court
judge rebuffed the latest attempt by the project's opponents to
block construction.
</P>
<P>
   The opponents had seized on Dreamworks' involvement in the
project to generate publicity, protesting at the openings of
Spielberg's films. But a Dreamworks official said the
environmentalists' protests had played little role in the company's
decision.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
