A7765 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-IRELAND-TALKS-BOS &LR;      07-02 1195
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-IRELAND-TALKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LATEST MOVE WOULD CREATE POWER-SHARING CABINET 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN CULLEN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BELFAST _ Unable to get the parties in Northern Ireland to reach
an agreement among themselves, the British and Irish governments
stepped in Friday, saying they would trigger the formation of a
power-sharing cabinet here July 15 and expect paramilitary groups
to begin disarming soon after.
</P>
<P>
   If Protestant unionists refuse to sit in government with
Catholic nationalists, or if the Irish Republican Army balks at
turning in its weapons, the political institutions created by the
Good Friday Agreement of 1998 will be suspended, effectively ending
the peace process, the governments said.
</P>
<P>
   Neither a breakthrough nor a breakdown, the plan offered by the
two governments tries to steer a way through a political minefield
in which neither unionists nor republicans want to be seen as
giving too much to the other side.
</P>
<P>
   British Prime Minister Tony Blair and his Irish counterpart,
Bertie Ahern, acted decisively after five days of talks failed to
produce a compromise between Sinn Fein, the IRA's political wing,
and the Ulster Unionists.
</P>
<P>
   Convinced that public opinion will force the politicians here to
accept their plan and save the peace process from drift and a
potential return to widespread violence, Blair and Ahern said the
various parties had agreed to consult their constituencies before
deciding whether to accept their proposals.
</P>
<P>
   But Blair left no doubt what he thought they should do, saying,
``This is the only way forward for Northern Ireland.''
</P>
<P>
   In a scene reminiscient of April 10, 1998, when they announced
the Good Friday Agreement on the same steps of the office building
where it was reached, Blair and Ahern stood under a drizzle and put
the best face on an outcome that their aides admitted was not the
preferred one.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein voiced support for the plan, while unionists said it
was unfair to them. Ulster Unionist leader David Trimble said he
had ``several doubts about these proposals'' because they would
punish democratic political parties if terrorist groups held onto
their arms.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams said, ``We have collectively taken
an historic step tonight. There are difficult days ahead of us.
There are those who bitterly reject and who will oppose our
efforts. We must stand firm.''
</P>
<P>
   The unionists, representing mostly middle-class Protestants, had
insisted that the IRA begin turning in weapons before they would
consent to the formation of a government in which Sinn Fein would
hold two of 12 seats in a power-sharing cabinet.
</P>
<P>
   In an attempt to break the impasse, Sinn Fein promised it would
try to persuade the IRA to begin disarming as soon as the
power-sharing government was formed, but the unionists refused to
accept their word.
</P>
<P>
   In an extraordinary commitment of time and energy, Blair and
Ahern ensconced themselves in Castle Buildings here on the grounds
of Stormont in East Belfast even longer than they had while
brokering the Good Friday Agreement that created the political
process which is now under threat.
</P>
<P>
   But while the two leaders got Sinn Fein to publicly say it would
try to get the IRA to disarm, the unionists would not budge, saying
they would accept nothing short of weapons up front, or a statement
from the IRA, which has steadfastly refused to countenance
disarming.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with unionist intransigence, and Sinn Fein's insistence
that it could compromise no further, the two leaders unveiled a
two-page document called ``The Way Forward.'' According to the
plan, the British government will trigger the formation of a
power-sharing government headed by a 12-member cabinet on July 15.
The next day, the British Parliament will be asked to transfer
power to administer Northern Ireland from London to the Northern
Ireland Assembly, taking effect July 18.
</P>
<P>
   Blair said he expected the process of disarming the paramilitary
groups to begin ``within days'' of devolving power to Northern
Ireland, and the handing over of weapons within weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The British government will put forward legislation that would
suspend the assembly and other political institutions created by
the Good Friday Agreement if either side reneges on commitments to
share power or disarm.
</P>
<P>
   Blair and Ahern stressed that the legislative safeguards make it
a low-risk exercise for both sides, but Blair acknowledged ``there
is a challenge for everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Adams is to convince his constituents,
particularly those in the IRA, that giving in weapons is worth
achieving political power.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble, meanwhile, has to convince mainstream unionists that
the prospect of getting the IRA to disarm is worth allowing former
IRA leaders like Martin McGuinness, Sinn Fein's chief negotiator,
to sit in the cabinet that will decide Northern Ireland's future.
</P>
<P>
   The governments' attempt to break the logjam came as Northern
Ireland enters the most volatile weekend of its ``marching
season,'' when Protestants hold thousands of parades to commemorate
17th century military victories over Catholics. Tomorrow's Orange
Order parade in Portadown, which is barred from passing through a
Catholic neighborhood, is the most contentious and has triggered
violence for the last five years.
</P>
<P>
   Sinn Fein's pledge to get the IRA to disarm was seen by the
British and Irish governments as a giant concession, but unionists
were unmoved, saying they wanted a pledge from the IRA itself.
</P>
<P>
   The unionists, however, became increasingly isolated Friday
after a commission set up by the governments to oversee the
disarming of paramilitary groups said it believed that the
decommissioning of weapons could be accomplished by the May
deadline set by the Good Friday Agreement.
</P>
<P>
   John de Chastelain, a retired Canadian general who heads the
disarmament commission and whose report was held back for four days
while Blair and Ahern tried to broker a deal, concluded that all of
the parties linked to paramilitary groups were prepared to assist
in the decommissioning of weapons.
</P>
<P>
   Early Friday, Sinn Fein released a written declaration in which
it promised to persuade the IRA to turn in its arms.
</P>
<P>
   ``We believe that all of us, as participants acting in good
faith, could succeed in persuading those with arms to decommission
them in accordance with the (Good Friday) Agreement,'' the
declaration said.
</P>
<P>
   De Chastelain said the Sinn Fein declaration ``offers promise
that decommissioning by all paramilitary groups may now begin. The
commission expects that Sinn Fein's proposal will be endorsed by
the IRA and reciprocated by loyalist and other republican
paramilitary groups.''
</P>
<P>
   Trimble said he had asked Sinn Fein to change a single word in
its declaration, from ``could'' to ``will'' or ``must'' so that
there would be an imperative in its plege to disarm the IRA, but
that Sinn Fein refused.
</P>
<P>
   Trimble rejected claims that his party did not want to work with
Catholic nationalists.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are ready to work with Sinn Fein,'' he said, ``if they
commit themselves to democracy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
