<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ISRAEL-PALESTINIANS-525&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISRAELI LEADER PLANS A MEETING WITH ARAFAT
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By DEBORAH SONTAG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   JERUSALEM _ Prime Minister-elect Ehud Barak, who will be sworn
in on Wednesday, seems to be emerging from behind the scenes to
take his place as Israel's leader.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he telephoned Yasser Arafat, the Palestinian leader,
for their first official conversation since Barak won election six
weeks ago. They made a date to meet ``soon'' and to restart the
stagnant peace effort.
</P>
<P>
   Barak also ended six weeks of total public silence on policy to
reproach President Clinton for making seemingly offhand remarks
about the rights of Palestinian refugees.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton stepped into a minefield of sensitivities when he said,
``I would like it'' if Palestinian refugees ``were free to live
wherever they liked, wherever they want to live.'' His comments set
off a firestorm of public debate here Friday because they seemed to
represent a new position by the United States on one of the
thorniest issues between the Israelis and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton's stance on the matter of the right of
return, as it might be understood from his remarks yesterday in
Washington, is unacceptable to Barak,'' his spokeswoman, Merav
Parsi-Tzadok, said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, who formed his coalition government on Wednesday after
six weeks of political negotiations, said through a spokeswoman
that he believed Clinton probably misspoke. Still, his office said,
the White House should have ``clarified and corrected'' his
remarks. In fact, administration officials on Thursday denied that
Clinton had meant to alter U.S. policy on refugee resettlement,
which says the Israelis and Palestinians should resolve the issue
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   And an Israeli television station Friday showed a letter on
White House stationery, dated Thursday, from Sandy Berger,
Clinton's national security adviser, to the American Israel Public
Affairs Committee, saying, ``There should be no misunderstanding:
there has been no change in our policy.'' The ultimate disposition
of Palestinian refugees has been left for the final status talks,
which have not yet begun.
</P>
<P>
   Even a high-ranking official in the Palestinian Authority, Ziad
Abu Zayyad, seemed to think the president had gone out on a limb on
this issue.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking on Israeli radio, Abu Zayyad hinted that the
Palestinians themselves were not insisting on the right of return
of all refugees. The fate of the refugees needs to be negotiated,
he said, and the Palestinians are eager to make peace.
</P>
<P>
   ``We won't ask the Israelis to commit suicide,'' he said. ``We
won't ask them to give up their state and turn it into a state of
an Arab majority.''
</P>
<P>
   Ron Pundak, a professor who was one of the architects of the
Oslo peace agreement, tried to explain Clinton's remarks to
Israelis Friday, giving Clinton every benefit of the doubt.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I think that Clinton was trying to say was that anything
that is agreed upon between the Israelis and Palestinians is OK
with him,'' Pundak said. ``I do not believe _ nor do I think that
anyone in the American government believes _ that there will be any
right of return for refugees into Israel proper except perhaps for
some symbolic agreement.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Moshe Arens, the outgoing defense minister, was not quite as
empathetic.
</P>
<P>
   ``President Clinton's remarks are very serious indeed because,
as we know, if we implement the right of return of refugees, this
will mean the end of the state of Israel as we know it,'' he said.
``It could be that the president does not understand this.''
</P>
<P>
   It was the second time Clinton had offended Israelis with casual
remarks. In December, in an address to the Palestinian National
Council in Gaza, he likened the pain of Palestinian children whose
fathers were being held in Israeli prisons to that of Israeli
children whose fathers had been killed by Palestinian terrorists.
</P>
<P>
   Barak, in his conversation with Arafat, said he planned to
continue on the path to peace of his mentor, the late Yitzhak
Rabin.
</P>
<P>
   David Zisso, another spokesman for Barak, said, ``The prime
minister-elect and Arafat agreed to arrange a meeting shortly after
the government is presented to the Parliament.''
</P>
</TEXT>
