<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CYC-TOUR-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOUR DE FRANCE LOOKS TO REINVENT IMAGE AFTER 1998 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SUSAN BICKELHAUPT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Tour de France, which begins its 86th edition Saturday faces
a challenge that is bigger than the Alps, the Pyrenees, or the more
than 2,200 miles the race will cover. It has to climb out from
under the cloud of drug scandals that cast a pall over last year's
race when the focus was on the controversy instead of the race.
</P>
<P>
   But it won't be easy. The past three winners won't be returning
_ one because of an ejection in last month's Tour of Italy, the
other two because of injuries. The major sponsor, Credit Lyonnais
bank, is considering pulling out. And the Tour banned almost 20
riders and coaches two weeks ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a challenge for us, and anything else is totally
secondary,'' said race director Jean-Marie Leblanc, when he
announced the bans. His goal, he said, is to have an ``open, clean,
transparent Tour de France.''
</P>
<P>
   His hopes for a clean start were short-lived, though.
</P>
<P>
   This past week, the Union Cycliste Internationale, cycling's
governing body, reinstated French rider Richard Virenque, who now
rides with Italy's Polti team, and Manolo Saiz, manager of the ONCE
team. Virenque was the leader of the Festina team that was
disqualified last year, and Saiz was director of the Spanish ONCE
team. They were the only ones to appeal the ban.
</P>
<P>
   Virenque, 29, runner-up in the 1997 Tour and four-time winner of
the mountain-climbing jersey, is a favorite not just among the
French, but among other riders.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's good that he's back in, he's such a big figure in
France,'' American Tyler Hamilton said.
</P>
<P>
   But the Tour did not feel the same way. Directors were left
reeling, and said the UCI move was ``in contempt of the defense of
fundamental sporting values.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year's problems began even before the race started when
French customs officers discovered drugs in a car driven by the
Festina team. The team was expelled after team director Brian
Roussel admitted his squad was guilty of drug abuse. Virenque, who
never failed a drug test, denied using them.
</P>
<P>
   As the Tour went on, French authorities stepped up their
investigation and raided team hotels. Some riders were held for
questioning, and later complained of how they were treated, thus
prompting the Tour riders to stage a protest and ride, but not
race, one stage.
</P>
<P>
   Two teams quit that day, and three more followed the next. When
the race reached the finish in Paris, just 96 of the original 189
cyclists were there.
</P>
<P>
   The crackdown continued over the winter, with more
investigations, and 14 arrests in connection with an alleged drug
distribution ring.
</P>
<P>
   In June, Italian rider Marco Pantani, who won last year's Tour,
was expelled from the Tour of Italy after he failed a blood test.
He opted not to enter the Tour de France.
</P>
<P>
   Also absent will be 1997 winner Jan Ullrich and 1996 winner
Bjarne Riis.
</P>
<P>
   All of which should bode well for the American Tour contingent.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely wide open,'' said Hamilton, of Brookline, who
will be riding his third Tour with the US Postal Service team.
</P>
<P>
   After Saturday's 5-mile time trial in western France that serves
as the Tour's prologue, the 180 riders on 20 teams will head north,
then east, touching the borders of Belgium and Luxembourg. After a
travel day, the cyclists will enter the Alps, finishing one day in
Italy, then travel west and south into the Pyrenees. After one more
day of rest, the riders will travel north through Bordeaux, and
after a time trial on the second-to-last day, arrive in Paris July
25.
</P>
<P>
   Hamilton, who finished second in the Tour's first time trial
last year, spent the spring training in the Alps with teammates
Lance Armstrong and Kevin Livingston.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like my fitness is a step above last year at this
time,'' Hamilton said by telephone from France.
</P>
<P>
   The team of seven Americans and two Europeans is led by
Armstrong, who won stages in 1993 and 1995, but sat out the last
two Tours after cancer surgery. He'll come into the race on a high
note, having won the last leg in the the Route du Sud stage race
last month.
</P>
<P>
   Rounding out the team are: George Hincapie, who came close to
wearing the leader's yellow jersey in the first week of last year's
Tour; Jonathan Vaughters, who won the Route du Sud; seven-time Tour
veteran Frankie Andreau; Livingston, who finished 17th in last
year's Tour when he rode with a French team; newcomer Christian
Vande Velde; Frenchman Pascal Derame; and Dane Peter Meinert.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the favorites of Spaniard Abraham Olano, Russian Pavel
Ronkov, and Michael Boogerd of the Netherlands, is American Bobby
Julich, who rides with the French Cofidis team.
</P>
<P>
   Julich finished third last year, and might well make another
trip to the podium, considering all the defections.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
