<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH AIDE CHOSEN TO LEAD KOSOVO REBUILDING EFFORT 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By JUDITH MILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ Describing the challenge as awesome,
Secretary-General Kofi Annan chose the French health minister on
Friday as his chief representative to run the United Nations' vast
civilian operations to be set up in Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Annan picked an American diplomat as the principal deputy.
</P>
<P>
   U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard announced at a news conference that
Annan had selected Dr. Bernard Kouchner, 59, co-founder of Doctors
Without Borders, to supervise the rebuilding.
</P>
<P>
   His main deputy will be James Covey, 55, a former diplomat who
has worked on the Balkans for the White House and the United
Nations.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats had expected that a European would be given the top
post, because the European Union is expected to pay for most of the
reconstruction. But the selection was repeatedly delayed by
intensive haggling over the top posts.
</P>
<P>
   As Annan's special representative, Kouchner will have sweeping
authority in what diplomats describe as the daunting task of
rebuilding on a broad front, restoring order and the rule of law,
providing housing and basic services, and re-establishing civil
institutions like the courts, the police and the remainder of local
governments.
</P>
<P>
   Countless Albanians have returned to Kosovo homeless,
impoverished and intent on revenge against the Serbs.
</P>
<P>
   Annan said the United Nations might have to administer Kosovo or
parts of its operations for 10 years or longer.
</P>
<P>
   Diplomats described Kouchner, a socialist who is deputy chairman
of the small Radical Party in France, as an unusual choice.
Although admired for impassioned and compassionate advocacy,
Kouchner has been innovative and independent minded in many crises.
But he has little administrative or U.N. experience. Critics have
portrayed him as driven by publicity, an erratic loner and
politically ambitious.
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner seems to enjoy defying stereotypes. A lengthy profile
of him in Le Figaro, the conservative daily newspaper, once
described him as a combative, generous, seductive, naive free
spirit and, alternatively, on the make, a name dropper and a
``grande gueule,'' or gourmand.
</P>
<P>
   In the U.N. action in Somalia in 1992 and 1993, he was
criticized for having posed on a beach in Mogadishu carrying a sack
of rice on his shoulder. In the early '90s, he embarrassed the
French government by calling President Mobutu Sese Seko of Zaire a
``walking bank safe in a leopard-skin hat.''
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner's biography lists his humanitarian experience before
his political posts, along with books, plays and screenplays, many
written under pseudonyms.
</P>
<P>
   Eckhard said Annan had chosen Kouchner because he had ``the
qualities the secretary general was looking for,'' ``vision and
ability to manage.''
</P>
<P>
   France also lobbied heavily for the appointment. Having learned
that Annan intended to appoint President Martti Ahtisaari of
Finland, the Kosovo negotiator, President Jacques Chirac of France
telephoned Annan to argue that the post was so important that
Ahtisaari should resign as Finland's president to devote full time
to Kosovo. Ahtisaari then withdrew his name, U.N. officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Covey, a retired American foreign service officer who is a
visiting fellow at the National Defense University in Washington,
is known as a skilled but blunt professional who knows the Balkans
well.
</P>
<P>
   He was deputy high representative in Sarajevo in December 1995
and remained involved in Balkan affairs on the National Security
Council, where he was President Clinton's special assistant for
carrying out the Dayton peace accords until August 1998. He also
held senior foreign posts, mostly in the Middle East.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
