<SLUG> BC-TEN-ARATON-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: SLAMMIN' SAMPRAS, A FOOTNOTE 
</HEADLINE>
 (jw) 
 By HARVEY ARATON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WIMBLEDON, England _ In case anyone has forgotten, Pete Sampras
is here, too, back on his favorite surface, trying to win a
record-tying 12th Grand Slam tournament. I thought I should mention
this before we discuss the big news of the Wimbledon day, which
wasn't that the sun finally shone.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Pete, so easily ignored in the swirl of personalities at
most Grand Slam events, and particularly at this one. At the
noisiest Wimbledon in years, Sampras has become a serve-and-volley
footnote to all the tennis headliners, past and present, from Boris
Becker to Tim Henman, from John McEnroe to Steffi Graf. Tennis moms
and dads are making more news here than the world's top-ranked
male, and an 18-year-old qualifier is drawing more attention for,
among other things, using Sampras' serve and strokes.
</P>
<P>
   That's just the way it is in sports and games. Some stars make
headlines, and some headlines make stars. Alexandra Stevenson _
taught those aforementioned strokes by one Pete Fischer, who was
also Sampras' coach _ will never again be just a tennis player. She
has become the first qualifier at Wimbledon to reach the women's
semifinals, not to mention on the day her famous biological father
was publicly revealing himself.
</P>
<P>
   Moments after Stevenson finished dissecting her 6-3, 1-6, 6-3
victory over Jelena Dokic for reporters Friday came a well-timed
news break from the United States that Julius Erving admitted to
being her father and to having provided financial support. Frankly,
I don't think it is anyone's business, when consenting adults
apparently have an agreement to keep such information private, and
I'm not for rummaging through personal documents in search of a
scoop.
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Stevenson's stunning success here probably
made the issue of parentage an inevitability. Her mother, Samantha
Stevenson, didn't exactly assist her daughter through the early
rounds in focusing on the feel-good themes of high school
graduation and her natural charm. The result: Stevenson plays
Lindsay Davenport Saturday on Center Court, days after she awoke in
the morning and wandered into her mother's room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I dreamt I beat Lindsay Davenport last night,'' Alexandra
said.
</P>
<P>
   Said her mother, ``Well, I hope it was on grass.''
</P>
<P>
   In the long and notorious Fleet Street tradition, there has
never been a more sensational debut for any athlete anywhere.
Alexandra Stevenson's best friend and childhood hitting partner,
Eric Basica, has cancer and is sending her e-mails asking that she
win Wimbledon for him. The former coach, Fischer, is a doctor in
jail on charges that he molested child patients. The next opponent,
Davenport, once kicked Stevenson's tennis bag out of her path,
according to Samantha Stevenson, who had such catty stuff in mind
when she spoke recently of the need to protect her daughter in the
locker room _ comments that were then misrepresented in the London
tabloids to imply that lesbianism was rampant in the women's game.
</P>
<P>
   This all preceded the unearthing of the birth certificate
containing the name Julius Winfield Erving II.
</P>
<P>
   Somewhere in this tabloid carnival it should be noted that the
6-foot-1-inch Stevenson does indeed have a powerful serve, a wicked
forehand and an impressive one-handed backhand. And it's true that
her power game was molded by Fischer in the image of his other star
pupil _ what's his name? _ whose advancement into the semifinals
came in the form of a thrilling injury default by Mark
Philippoussis.
</P>
<P>
   Wouldn't you know it? Bearing down on Roy Emerson, Sampras will
be greeted Saturday on Center Court by a crowd that most certainly
wishes him gone. Sampras plays Henman, the English hope, whom he
beat in a semifinal last year. If Sampras does so again, he is not
likely to be the crowd favorite in the final against Patrick Rafter
or Andre Agassi, who has spectacularly reinvented himself.
</P>
<P>
   Tennis, anyone? Another story line that played out Friday was
the defeat of the 16-year-old Dokic, whose father, Damir, was
arrested for drunken and disorderly conduct at a recent tournament.
Also, 17-year-old Mirjana Lucic, who last year fled the father she
accused of abusing her, advanced to play Graf, whose own father
landed in a German prison some years ago for not paying income tax
on her earnings.
</P>
<P>
   Serving as commentator to it all is McEnroe, who practiced with
Lucic Friday and later won another mixed doubles match with Graf.
``It's all great for the game,'' McEnroe crowed, including his own
return to Center Court.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Pete. What's 12 Grand Slam titles against all this?  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
