<HEADLINE>
WORLD NEWS IN BRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   EUROPE
</P>
<P>
   France: Diana Inquiry Nears End
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ An appeals court rejected requests for further
investigations into the car crash in Paris that killed Diana,
Princess of Wales, her companion, Mohamed ``Dodi'' al-Fayed, and
their French driver on Aug. 31, 1997, leaving investigating judges
and prosecutors to decide later this year whether to bring charges
in the case. Nine photographers and a photo agency motorcyclist are
under investigation for possibly contributing to the crash by
pursuing the car at high speed.
</P>
<P>
   France: Corsica Official Freed
</P>
<P>
   PARIS _ Bernard Bonnet, dismissed as the chief administrative
official on Corsica this spring after police there set fire to
seaside cafes built without official permission, was released from
Sante Prison in Paris but will remain under investigation as an
accomplice to arson. ``I'm the victim of a judicial frameup,''
Bonnet told reporters.
</P>
<P>
   Spain: Call to Close Election Loophole
</P>
<P>
   The government's chief spokesman said election laws should be
rewritten to prevent a repetition of what he called the repugnant
situation when a convicted murderer from the Basque separatist
group ETA was allowed by a court to be sworn in to his elected seat
in the Navarre regional parliament. Jose Luis Barrios, 26, was not
allowed to take part in the legislative session and was taken back
to jail after it began.
</P>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS
</P>
<P>
   Uncertainty on Libya
</P>
<P>
   In a report to the Security Council, U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan said he could not yet determine whether Libya had complied
with the U.N.'s conditions for permanently lifting sanctions
imposed after the downing of a jetliner over Lockerbie, Scotland.
Annan said that although Britain and France seemed satisfied that
Libya was moving to fulfill the conditions, the U.S. wanted further
evidence that it was honoring its pledges to the Council to stop
sponsoring and aiding terrorism.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
