<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 20:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7788 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-2TAKES-     07-02 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-RUSSIA-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.S. AND ALLIES PREVENT FLIGHTS OF RUSSIAN TROOPS INTO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
  (rm) 
 By ERIC SCHMITT   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The United States and its NATO allies have blocked
Russia from flying hundreds of troops into Kosovo this weekend,
before details of Russia's role in the NATO peacekeeping force
could be worked out, administration officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   In the past 48 hours, Russia asked Hungary, Romania and Bulgaria
for use of their airspace to fly 10 planeloads of peacekeepers on
Sunday into Pristina, the provincial capital, the officials said.
But those countries rejected the request after consulting with top
American and NATO officials, the administration officials said.
Hungary is a new member of NATO, while both Romania and Bulgaria
would like to join the alliance.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian point of view was, `Let's get our troops in there
while we work out the arrangements,''' said an administration
official. ``Our view is, `Let's get the details down before we have
them deploy more troops.'''
</P>
<P>
   Two weeks after an agreement reached in Helsinki, Finland,
Russian military negotiators this week sought to alter it by having
their troops in Kosovo take orders only from Russian officers,
rather than be under the formal command of NATO. Russia also wants
to station forces in the Italian as well as French, American and
German sectors of Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   Given Russia's surprise deployment of 200 troops to Pristina
airport last month and an unusual military exercise last week in
which American F-15 jets intercepted Russian fighter-bombers near
Iceland, administration officials said Friday they wanted no more
surprises from Russia over the July 4 holiday weekend, when many
senior American officials plan to be on vacation.
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright, vacationing in Europe,
today called her Russian counterpart, Igor Ivanov, to explain
NATO's objections to continuing the deployment of 3,600 Russian
troops into Kosovo until several sticking points are resolved, a
State Department official said.
</P>
<P>
   Allied officials had expected to settle the details of Russia's
peacekeeping role at high-level military talks in Mons, Belgium,
this week. Anticipating this, Russia had scheduled to fly 10
hulking Ilyushin Il-96 cargo planes full of troops and equipment
into Pristina to join about 400 Russian troops already there.
</P>
<P>
   But the talks struck an impasse and were not set to resume in
Belgium until next week. When Russia signaled that it was preparing
to send its troops to Kosovo anyway, American and NATO officials
quickly intervened.
</P>
<P>
   Samuel R. Berger, President Clinton's national security adviser,
spoke to his Russian counterpart while NATO Secretary-General
Javier Solana and his top aides consulted with officials in
Hungary, Romania, Bulgaria and Russia, American officials said.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Russian planes were not on the runway ready to launch,''
said a senior military official. ``But calls were made to Hungary,
Bulgaria and Romania to coordinate our response'' if anything
happened.
</P>
<P>
   A senior administration official said, ``The deal is, the
technical details of the Helsinki agreement must be worked out
before they send in more troops. Those details have not been worked
out.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, NATO's military commander, Gen. Wesley Clark,
flatly ruled out the Russian proposals, but did not give any hint
at the tense, behind-the-scenes brinkmanship unfolding.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were various efforts made by the Russian side to present
modifications or new interpretations of issues previously agreed at
Helsinki,'' Clark told the Senate Armed Services Committee. ``We
deflected those attempts.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The agreement reached in Helsinki on June 18 outlined ways for
the Russian troops to cooperate with French, German and U.S.
forces, as well as control ground operations at the Pristina
airport, which is in the heart of the British sector.
</P>
<P>
   The Russian zone in the German sector borders on the Italian
sector in western Kosovo, and allied officials say that the
Russians want to operate in that sector as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want to draw the lines along in areas that they would
feel more comfortable in operating in,'' Defense Secretary William
Cohen told reporters on Thursday. ``We feel it's very important
that we stay within the existing map as it was drawn.''
</P>
<P>
   Any changes in the patrol areas would require approval by NATO's
political arm, the North Atlantic Council, and the Russian
Federation. ``Some concern was expressed by some of the Russians on
the ground, having seen the KLA up a little close and personal,
that maybe the sectors they picked weren't the most convenient
sectors for the Russian forces to be in,'' Clark told reporters on
Thursday, referring to the Kosovo Liberation Army. ``They'll have
to come back through proper channels if this is going to be
adjusted.''  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Helsinki agreement also calls for Russian peacekeepers to
have their own commander, Col. Gen. Viktor Zavarin, and liaison
officers with the French, German and American commanders up the
allied chain of command.
</P>
<P>
   While the Russians would not formally report to NATO commanders,
they are expected to follow allied military operational
requirements, a delicate distinction.
</P>
<P>
   The chief Russian negotiator, Vice Adm. Valentin Kuznetsov,
appears to be seeking permission for Russian troops to operate
under their own rules, not NATO's, American and NATO officials
said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``We intend to keep this strictly within the bounds agreed at
Helsinki, including unity of command,'' Clark said.
</P>
<P>
   Clark, who said Russian troops would examine their assigned
operational areas in Kosovo in the next few days, expressed
optimism that impasse could be resolved by next week.
</P>
<P>
   ``Russian elements are going to do on-the-ground
reconnaissance,'' Clark said. ``They're going to come back an see
us again at my headquarters next week, where we're going to
finalize the details of Russian participation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
