<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 20:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7792 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL     07-02 0784
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MUTFUND-INTERNATIONAL-ART-2TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER A DARK YEAR, THE ASIAN SKY IS FILLED WITH FIREWORKS
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
(af) 
By VIRGINIA MUNGER KAHN  
c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   What a difference a year makes. Last Fourth of July weekend,
American investors were basking in the glory of 22.9 percent and
30.4 percent gains in their domestic and European stock funds,
respectively, over the previous 12 months. But Asia funds were down
more than 52 percent.
</P>
<P>
   This year, it is the Asian funds that are lighting up investors'
eyes, amid sentiment that most of the region's financial crisis has
passed.
</P>
<P>
   In the last 12 months, funds that invest in the Pacific Rim
outside of Japan soared 69.35 percent, on average, including 38.17
percent in the second quarter alone, according to Morningstar Inc.,
the financial publisher in Chicago. Funds that invest in Japan
alone were also up substantially _ an average of 55.81 percent over
the last year for the 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, domestic equity funds rose 14.6 percent in the 12
months and 8.98 percent in the second quarter, while European funds
were down 4.72 percent for the year, including a 2.61 percent gain
in the quarter. Over all, international stock funds rose 11.3 and
10 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   The portfolio managers of three top performers among funds that
buy foreign stocks discussed the turnaround _ as well as new
opportunities and possible red flags.
</P>
<P>
   A good gauge of how far up, and how far down, Asian markets have
been recently is the Matthews Korea I fund. It was the
top-performing international stock fund for the second quarter and
the last 12 months, according to Morningstar, with gains of 69.73
percent and 278.5 percent, respectively.
</P>
<P>
   But in 1997, the year the Asian crisis erupted, the fund, which
has virtually all of its assets in South Korea, was down 64.75
percent.
</P>
<P>
   The South Korean stock market was among the hardest hit during
the crisis and one of the earliest to bounce back strongly, said G.
Paul Matthews, manager of the fund. A big reason for the rapid
rebound was the government's aggressive economic restructuring.
</P>
<P>
   Three types of companies have driven the fund higher:
manufacturing exporters that have benefited from a weak currency,
including Samsung Electronics; financial services companies that
have adopted Western business practices or sought foreign capital,
including Kookmin Bank and Hana Bank, and companies tied to
domestic consumption, including phone companies, department stores
and utilities.
</P>
<P>
   Matthews particularly likes Korea Telecom, the largest telephone
company in South Korea. It is already fairly efficient, because the
government held down rate increases in recent years. And in a newly
deregulated environment, the company will be able to raise phone
rates, Matthews said.
</P>
<P>
   The only drawback for prospective investors, he added, is that
the company's American depository receipts are now selling at a
premium to the local shares, because of limits on foreign ownership
of local shares. He bought the ADRs when they were first offered in
May at $27.56 each, representing half a local share. The ADRs ended
the quarter at $40. The local shares, meanwhile, gained 84.6
percent in the quarter, to end at 76,800 won, or $66.35.
</P>
<P>
   Another favorite is the Korea Electric Power Co., or Kepco, the
monopoly electric utility in South Korea. The fund has owned local
shares since December 1996, when it paid 37,193 won each. They rose
62.5 percent in the quarter, ending at 48,100 won, or $41.56.
</P>
<P>
   Another top-performing fund focused on the Pacific Basin,
although with a broader approach, was Montgomery Emerging Asia. In
the last 12 months, the fund, with most of its assets in Hong Kong,
Thailand, South Korea and Taiwan, has soared 97.44 percent, up
61.16 percent in the second quarter alone.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Chiang, the fund's manager, said performance was spurred
by sharp declines in interest rates that have sent money into the
stock markets.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the biggest gainers have been financial services stocks;
Chiang's holdings include Thai Farmers Bank and the Industrial
Finance Corp. of Thailand. He bought shares of Thai Farmers Bank in
October at 20 baht.
</P>
<P>
   The shares rose 50 percent in the quarter, ending at 114 baht,
or $3.09. And he made 300 percent, including currency and capital
gains, on Industrial Finance since he bought it at 9 baht a share
in January 1998, when the baht was weak. For the quarter, the stock
doubled, ending at 23.5 baht, or 64 cents.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Chiang said he thought financial stocks would continue to profit
as the Asian recovery accelerated.
</P>
<P>
   A current favorite is HSBC Holdings, the global, London-based
bank with roots in Hong Kong and Shanghai. It has not only
weathered the Asian economic storm; it has gained strength by
expanding its business in South Korea. He first bought the stock in
1996 at $140 (Hong Kong) a share. It rose 17.7 percent in the
quarter, ending at $286 (Hong Kong) or $36.86 (United States).
</P>
<P>
   Some fund managers who scour the world for opportunity are
increasing their commitment to Asia.
</P>
<P>
   ``Asia looks better today than I've seen it in 10 years,'' said
Paul C. Warren, senior portfolio manager at the Putnam Diversified
Equity fund, one of the best-performing global funds over the last
five years. It has returned 20.87 percent, annualized, since
mid-1994 and is up 19.24 percent in the last 12 months.
</P>
<P>
   In the last five years, the majority of its assets have been in
the hot United States stock market, but Warren is redeploying some
money to Asia. At year-end 1998, 51 percent of the fund was in
domestic stocks, 41 percent in European and 5.5 percent in Asian;
it now has 42 percent in the United States, 37 percent in Europe
and 13 percent in Asia. (The rest is in Latin America and Canada.)
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, Warren said, three factors were at work: interest
rates in much of Asia were a lot higher than in the United States;
Asian countries were running large current account deficits _ in
essence, borrowing heavily from abroad _ and Asian companies had
overdiversified.
</P>
<P>
   Now, interest rates in Asia are as low as or lower than those in
the United States, current accounts are in surplus and Asian
companies are restructuring. As such, ``we have a
better-than-Goldilocks scenario,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Among Warren's favorites is Nikko Securities, the third-largest
brokerage firm in Japan. Eighteen months ago, it hired a new
president, who is cutting costs. As the Japanese economy recovers
and retail investors return to the market, ``this stock has the
potential to be one of our biggest gainers,'' he said. The fund
first bought the stock in late 1998 at around 400 yen a share. It
rose 41.8 percent in the quarter, ending at 780 yen, or $6.44.
</P>
<P>
   In light of the outsized recent gains for Asia-Pacific funds,
investors should be wary, the managers said.
</P>
<P>
   A big part of those returns, they noted, came as local
currencies rose from depressed levels. Also, it is still early in
the region's recovery, and Asian companies have yet to prove that
their reorganizations will translate into consistently higher
profits.
</P>
<P>
   Finally, despite the recent surge, many investors who have held
Asia-Pacific funds over the last five years still have net losses.
The average diversified fund is down 0.22 percent in that period.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
