<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-INTERNET-HACKERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HACKERS BREAK INTO COMPUTERS OF INTERNET'S GOVERNING GROUP 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By JERI CLAUSING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Hackers broke into network computers run by the Internet's new
governing body Friday in an apparent attempt to fan the flames of
an ongoing struggle for control of the lucrative business of
assigning Internet addresses known as domains.
</P>
<P>
   Officials with Network Solutions, the company that has a
monopoly in the business of registering Internet addresses, said
Friday that the FBI was looking into the attack, which the
company's chief technology officer, David Holtzman, said had been
traced to an Internet service provider in Marina del Rey, Calif. He
said that company, SoftAware, is in the same building as the global
network's new oversight organization, Internet Corporation for
Assigned Names and Numbers, or Icann.
</P>
<P>
   SoftAware officials confirmed the attack was made through one of
their machines, but said all the records that might trace it had
been erased. Icann, meanwhile, confirmed that its server had also
been disrupted for several hours Friday. Brian O'Shaughnessy, a
spokesman for Network Solutions, declined to speculate on a motive
for the attack.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the motive, it is likely to add to the political drama
being played out between Network Solutions and Icann, which is in
the process of opening the company's business to competition and
which is working on plans to move the Internet's main root server
from the company's headquarters in Herndon, Va., to its offices in
California.
</P>
<P>
   Icann was picked by the federal government last year to take
over administration of the global network, which had previously
been handled by Network Solutions and the University of Southern
California.
</P>
<P>
   But the transition process has been contentious, and Network
Solutions has been a major critic of Icann and the policies it has
adopted. The company has refused to sign an agreement recognizing
Icann's oversight authority, and it has been lobbying for
congressional review of the decisions Icann has made and of the
authority that created the nonprofit group.
</P>
<P>
   O'Shaughnessy said the company discovered the break-in Friday
morning after receiving numerous reports that traffic to three of
the company's Web sites was being rerouted to Icann's Web site and
the Web site of a group that has led the fight to break up Network
Solutions' monopoly on the domain name registration business, the
Internet Council of Registrars, known as CORE.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
