<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-ARRESTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FRENCH SEIZE WAR CRIMES SUSPECT IN KOSOVO; OTHER ARRESTS ALSO
REPORTED 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MITROVICA, Yugoslavia _ The French police arrested a Serbian
paramilitary leader and war crimes suspect in this Kosovo town on
Friday, raiding his apartment in the early hours of the morning and
confiscating weapons and ammunition.
</P>
<P>
   Serbian police and military personnel were supposed to have left
Kosovo two weeks ago; the arrest was one of a series indicating the
lingering presence of Serbs viewed by NATO as provocateurs.
</P>
<P>
   The man, Dragan Marjanovic, also known as Cujla, is one of those
who have been blocking the main bridge in the northern town of
Mitrovica in an attempt to divide the city and create a Serbs-only
quarter.
</P>
<P>
   A few hours earlier, six other Serbs, thought to be plainclothes
police officers, were detained in the town of Orahovac in
southwestern Kosovo. The men, who had weapons, radio equipment and
computers, were detected sending radio signals.
</P>
<P>
   Five Yugoslav army soldiers were also apprehended Thursday by
U.S. troops after straying into Kosovo on a foot patrol. The
commander of NATO forces in Kosovo has written Belgrade demanding
an explanation for the men's presence inside the province boundary,
a NATO spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations' special representative, Sergio Vieira de
Mello, said he was sure the Serbs were acting to provoke violence
and tension, and he urged local Serbian leaders to condemn the
troublemakers.
</P>
<P>
   Vieira de Mello spent most of Friday in an emergency meeting
with Serbian and Albanian leaders of Kosovo to draw up a statement
calling for the end to the extensive violence.
</P>
<P>
   Widespread looting, burning of houses and intimidation have
continued across Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This must not be allowed to exist,'' Vieira de Mello told
reporters just before the meeting. ``There is a need for the
leaderships to speak out. This includes the Serb side. I am sure
there are agents provocateurs especially in the north part of
Mitrovica and upwards of there.''
</P>
<P>
   After seven hours of negotiation, and four hours later than
planned, the group issued the statement condemning the ``crimes of
the Milosevic regime in Kosovo'' and saying that those ``suspected
of war crimes and crimes against humanity shall be brought to
justice.''
</P>
<P>
   Four Albanian leaders, signatories of the peace accord signed in
Rambouillet, France, were present, including the Albanian leader of
the Kosovo Liberation Army, Hashim Thaci. Among those representing
Kosovo Serbs were Bishop Artemije, the leader of the Serbian
Orthodox Church in Kosovo, the liberal priest Father Sava and an
opposition politician, Momcilo Trajkovic.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Artemije said that the head of the Serbian Orthodox
Church, Patriarch Pavle, supported the statement, as did all the
Church.
</P>
<P>
   But the only other Serbs supporting the statement were local
leaders. Zoran Andjelkovic, Belgrade's representative in Kosovo
since last October, is still in Pristina but was not invited to
join the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   The French have accused radical Serbs of creating the tension
that has forced a division of Mitrovica into Serbian and Albanian
sectors.
</P>
<P>
   Marjanovic had been under surveillance for some time as one of
the organizers of the blockade on the bridge. He is a well-known
figure, a cafe owner who is said to be a member of the
ultranationalist Serbian Radical Party.
</P>
<P>
   He is also under investigation for more serious crimes committed
in the last few months of the war, including four rapes and the
murder of two girls who were handcuffed and burnt alive. Col.
Claude Vicaire, the commander of the French police force in
Mitrovica, led the dawn raid himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``We arrested one of the chiefs of the paramilitaries who are
blocking the bridge,'' he said. The French police said they found
military weapons, grenades and ammunition in his apartment.
</P>
<P>
   The gendarmes moved in to arrest Marjanovic after he assaulted
two Albanians in the street Thursday. It was the first day that
Kosovo has an operating judiciary; judges and prosecutors are now
running a mobile court to attend to the growing number of people
detained by NATO forces.
</P>
<P>
   They will be imposing a 1976 version of Yugoslav law, except in
cases where it is incompatible with international standards of
human rights and civil liberties. Under the law, Marjanovic can be
detained without trial for 14 days. Until now, the French were
operating under French law and would have had to release him after
24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   ``We will be holding him for a long time,'' Vicaire said as he
stood on the bridge, watching a noisy demonstration of young
Albanians.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
