</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-CELEBRATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KOSOVARS MARK THEIR OWN DECLARATION
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Kosovo _ This city exploded into celebration Friday
night as thousands of Kosovar Albanians turned out in the streets
to celebrate the anniversary of their declaration of independence,
the first since the NATO air war returned Albanians to Kosovo, free
from Serbian rule.
</P>
<P>
   Bursts of automatic gunfire rattled out, and red tracer fire
soared into the sky, as illegal weapons emerged from hiding places
to mark the occasion. British paratroops patrolled the streets but
did not intervene.
</P>
<P>
   On July 2, 1991, in the town of Kachannik in southern Kosovo,
Albanian members of Parliament, outlawed and dismissed from their
posts by President Slobodan Milosevic of Serbia, made the daring
and ambitious statement of independence.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years later, if the Albanians had not achieved actual
independence, they were celebrating openly nonetheless, for the
first time since NATO troops arrived in Kosovo. The festivity
indicates the relaxed atmosphere that is settling in after weeks of
tension.
</P>
<P>
   Whole families came outdoors, including old women in head
scarves and children in cars, their faces pressed against the
windows and their hands showing the victory sign.
</P>
<P>
   They chanted the initials of the Kosovo Liberation Army, the
guerrilla force that spearheaded the fight for independence.
Uniformed soldiers of the rebel army were not in evidence, but it
was clear that many of those celebrating were members.
</P>
<P>
   Trucks of young men roared round the city. Some wore military
caps or Kosovo Liberation Army badges. They leaned out and slapped
one another's hands or gave a fisted salute.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am so happy,'' said a mother of two, clutching her
children's hands and watching the cavalcade of cars. ``You cannot
believe what this means to us after so many years of suffering
under the Serbs.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2021EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0294 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 20:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7804 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-STEVENSON-BOS &LR;      07-02 1323
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-STEVENSON-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STEVENSON STORY PUTS SPIN ON WIMBLEDON BALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BUD COLLINS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LONDON _ She is traveling fast on the biggest feet remaining at
Wimbledon, taking gigantic strides into no-woman's land, trying to
jump to the moon. Alexandra Winfield Stevenson is doing so even
amid the soap opera swirling around her, climaxed by Friday's
confirmation that she is Julius Erving's daughter.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson's only stated focus is winning the title at the Big W,
and after Friday's decisive victory, she is in unchartered
territory for a qualifier in this 122-year-old tennis bash _ only
two wins away. Two wins from a tall Monday morning headline:
DEBUTANTE STEALS THE BALL.
</P>
<P>
   An out-of-the-swamp qualifier ranked No. 86, she is _ presto! _
The Story of the day. Not only because Stevenson is doing
previously undone things with a racket, but because of the report
Friday that followed by minutes her post-victory press conference.
In a statement to the Associated Press from Philadelphia, Erving
confirmed reports that he'd previously denied: The resident of the
Basketball Hall of Fame is her father, having had a brief liaison
with Alexandra's mother, former Boston television reporter Samantha
Stevenson, in 1980.
</P>
<P>
   If you're 18 years old, taking a rookie cut at Wimbledon merely
three weeks after high school graduation, and find yourself bumping
heads in the final four with US Open champ Lindsay Davenport, the
eternal Steffi Graf, and another teen-age phenom, Croat Mirjana
Lucic, it might be reasonably hard to concentrate. To keep your
nerves from sounding like Big Ben. Meanwhile the ferocious London
tabloids are howling about your illegitimacy, and every reporter in
town is in pursuit.
</P>
<P>
   Does that sound like a carefree holiday in London?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's all great fun,'' Stevenson said after acing another
enfant terrible, 16-year-old Jelena Dokic of Australia, out of
action, 6-3, 1-6, 6-3, to crash the semifinals, a precinct never
before invaded by a female qualifier. ``I'm oblivious to everything
but playing tennis, and I want this championship.''
</P>
<P>
   Her brown eyes popping with that little kid-at-Christmas look,
the 6-foot-1-inch Alexandra appears to have those size-12 sneakers
planted firmly on Wimbledon's revered sod.
</P>
<P>
   So, how does she feel about her father?
</P>
<P>
   ``No comment.''
</P>
<P>
   That's the stock, recurring answer from her and her mother to
questions regarding parentage, delivered with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, in his statement, Erving said, ``my wife (who has
known from the beginning) and children are aware of this situation.
All matters concerning Alexandra since her birth have been handled
privately through counsel. I am pleased to see Alexandra, at 18,
doing so well and I applaud her mother's efforts and courage.''
</P>
<P>
   Erving also said that he has met Alexandra just once, when she
was 3, at a basketball clinic and said it was ``her call'' whether
they would meet again.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha, once a TV reporter at Boston's Channel 7 and an
occasional correspondent for the New York Times, said, ``I hope
this inspires single mothers. I want them to know it's worth all
the work to bring up a child alone. It isn't easy.'' Surely, Erving
has helped the San Diego twosome financially.
</P>
<P>
   Alexandra graduated from a fine private school, La Jolla Country
Day, and went to the prom _ the kind of upsets accomplished by few
tennis prodigies, although her foe Saturday, fellow Californian
Davenport, pulled the same rare double. The next day Alexandra and
Samantha were on a 7 a.m. plane headed east to London.
</P>
<P>
   ``She wanted to play the French as her first major,'' said
Samanatha, ``but that would have meant missing graduation, and I
said no. Alexandra still had to miss all the post-graduation
parties, but this is a pretty good trade-off.''
</P>
<P>
   UCLA tennis coach Stella Sampras, Pete's sister, held her breath
when she handed the kid a letter of intent for a full-ride
scholarship, feeling that Alexandra might want to run away with the
pro circus instead.
</P>
<P>
   ``Stella understands that I won't be going to college now,''
Alexandra said. ``Not for a while. Not to play tennis. Not after
this. But she said I had until September to decide.''
</P>
<P>
   The decision to go for the dough was made when she knocked off
11th-seeded Julie Halard-Decugis, a seasoned pro from France, in
the third round. That was only Stevenson's 17th match on grass, a
surface not usually kind to novices. Chris Evert made it to the
semis in her Wimbledon debut in 1972 at age 17, but she had a track
record: semifinals at the US Open the year before.
</P>
<P>
   Not since a feisty 18-year-old named John McEnroe jimmied his
way into Wimbledon through the spiky qualifying tournament with
three wins 22 years ago has one of these back-door entries
performed so spectacularly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's great,'' said McEnroe, a TV babbler and this year
a moonlighting comebacker, linked with Graf in the semis of the
mixed doubles. ``What Alexandra's done gives hope to the people
down there in the qualifying. They figure they've got a shot, too.
And I like the way she plays. My kind of game.''
</P>
<P>
   It's an attractive attacking game that bent four players ranked
above her, and, in the crunch, the stubborn pony-tailed baseliner,
No. 129 Dokic, also a novitiate and qualifier.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have to go forward, get to the net,'' Stevenson said. She
has the serve and volleys, the smooth backhand approach to get away
with a gangbusters style that seems to have gone out with Martina
Navratilova. ``I lost my focus in the second set. I was backing up,
and Dokic took over.''
</P>
<P>
   Thursday's rains sent them home to brood through perhaps a
sleepless night, the match far from decided, Stevenson leading,
6-3, 1-5. On resumption Friday, Dokic quickly took the second set.
But, ``I went right after her then,'' said Stevenson, who blasted
to a 4-2 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Then she skidded to 15-40, two break points. And coolly she
extricated herself with a fiery run of four points: ace, backhand
swoop-and-volley, a cap of two service winners. In match game she
led off with a 15th ace, one shy of the tourney record, flicked a
backhand winner to 40-15. Two match points.
</P>
<P>
   Double fault. Uh-oh.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wanted to close it with an ace,'' she said, ``so I went for
one on the second ball . . . like Pete (Sampras) does. He's my
hero. We had the same coach, Pete Fisher.''
</P>
<P>
   Risky? ``Oh, I won it on the next point. I knew I would.'' After
the handshake, she curtsied all around to the audience of 11,429
filling Court 1. That's her crowd-saluting version of Andre
Agassi's bows and kiss-blowing. She's got a theatrical, as well as
sharp-volleying, touch.
</P>
<P>
   Poised, well-spoken, and loving the moment, Alexandra must be
chuckling inwardly (although she'd never admit it), at upstaging
her pal Venus Williams. For a couple of years, she's been thought
of as a sort of tag-along with the self-assured, sometimes
intimidating, Sisters Sledgehammer, Venus and Serena. Serena stayed
home and Venus got beat in the quarters by Graf.
</P>
<P>
   From the slums of qualifying to the penthouse is a flight not
yet accomplished. McEnroe was stopped in the semis by Jimmy
Connors. Stevenson may go no further, but she's in for at least
$160,000 and world-wide notice, continuing at 7 a.m. EST Saturday.
Could she someday get more exposure than Papa J, and even become
known as Dr. A?
</P>
<P>
   Right now it's dream time, and take your best shot at No. 3-seed
Davenport. It's a reach, and they've both got it in the loftiest of
all major women's semis: Davenport being 2 inches taller than
Stevenson at 6-3.
</P>
<P>
   In a high school production of ``Grease,'' Stevenson played a
supporting role as a cheerleader. She had wanted the lead, wanted
to sing, ``Look at Me, I'm Sandra Dee!''
</P>
<P>
   But this is better. Look at her, she's Alexandra Winfield
Stevenson, the debutante who might steal the ball.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
