u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUM     07-02 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-SHAUGHNESSY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FISK '75 HOME RUN BALL SURFACES FOR AUCTION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAN SHAUGHNESSY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Who knew? Who knew that ordinary baseballs someday would be
horsehide Hope Diamonds?
</P>
<P>
   On Oct. 22, 1975, at thirty-four minutes after midnight, Carlton
Fisk cricled the bases, John Kiley played the ``Hallelujah
Chorus,'' and Peter Gammons started typing, ``the ball was there,
like the Mystic River Bridge, suspended out in the black of
morning.''
</P>
<P>
   There was bedlam in the stands at Fenway Park and church bells
rang across New England.
</P>
<P>
   And while all that was going on, Cincinnati Reds left fielder
George Foster trotted over and picked up a dented hardball that had
clanged off the left-field foul pole.
</P>
<P>
   Next Thursday, that baseball will be auctioned, and probably
will go for something in excess of $100,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was standing right there and it hit the foul pole,'' recalls
Foster, who now lives in Florida. ``The game was over and it was
late and I put it in my glove and left it in my locker overnight.
The next night, Cesar Geronimo caught the last out of Game 7 and
said he was going to keep the ball. So I figured I'd hold on to
this one. There wasn't any thought at that time that it was going
to be valuable or anything.''
</P>
<P>
   Times change. Nine-dollar baseballs become precious gems if they
are in the right place at the right time. Mark McGwire's 70th home
run ball last winter was auctioned for $2.7 million. Sammy Sosa's
66th went for a bargain basement $150,000. The first ball Babe Ruth
hit out of Yankee Stadium went for $125,000. Even the Vatican has
gotten involved. A ball autographed by Catholic Hall of Famer Pope
John Paul II will be auctioned July 21 at a Collectors Convention
in Atlanta. Pontiff ball bidding starts at $10,000.
</P>
<P>
   And who can forget the tragic tale of the ground ball that
dribbled between the legs of Bill Buckner? The ball was originally
retrieved by umpire Ed Montague, who gave it to then-Mets traveling
secretary, Arthur Richman. Richman held on to the ball for six
years, then put it up for auction, where it fetched $93,500 from a
famous collector named Charlie Sheen.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk's ball is bound to go higher. It represents one of the most
celebrated moments in baseball history. Footage of Fisk waving the
ball fair was selected by TV Guide as the greatest moment in the
history of sports television. The video can be seen at the
Smithsonian Institute in Washington, and discussion of Fisk's blast
highlighted a crucial clip in ``Good Will Hunting.'' It's the scene
when Robin Williams tells Matt Damon he skipped Game 6 because he
had to ``go see about a girl.''
</P>
<P>
   Damon, a Cambridge, Mass. homeboy who co-wrote and starred in
the movie, is participating in next Sunday's celebrity home run
hitting contest at Fenway and rumored to be a candidate to bid for
the Fisk ball. The folks at Leland's auction house sent their
brochure to Damon's PR person. Damon did not return a call from the
Globe.
</P>
<P>
   Fisk isn't too happy about the sale and has doubts about the
ball's authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pudge says he's seen George 25 times over the years and George
never mentioned that he had it,'' says Fisk's agent, Jack Sands.
``I called George myself. He claims that he was originally confused
because there was no World Series logo on the ball. Then he found
out that in '75, there was no Series logo on the ball. I told him I
thought it was be appropriate for him to donate it to the Hall of
Fame. I think Pudge is upset that the ball is not being donated to
the Hall.''
</P>
<P>
   Fisk, in Boston Thursday for a baseball clinic, told WBZ-TV's
Gary Tanguay, ``I have no idea whether it's the ball. My only
question is timing, that's all. Twenty-five years and now the ball
has surfaced without any mention of it? I've inquired about that
ball for 20 years and not heard one word until recently. It could
be. It could not be. There could be ways to find out, though.
</P>
<P>
   ``I never thought about it. It could possibly be the ball, but
if it hit the foul pole, there should be some indication of that. I
don't know how scientific you want to get about it. It would be
nice if it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Marty Appel, who is handling public relations for Leland's,
says, ``Leland's is satisfied by Foster's story and the video that
shows Foster retrieving the ball. It's a Lee MacPhail signature
(MacPhail was American League president in 1975). It's got two
scuff marks, indicating the bat and the foul pole.''
</P>
<P>
   The Fisk ball is part of a memorabilia sale that also includes
the New York Yankees home uniform worn by Lou Gehrig on Lou Gehrig
Appreciation Day at Yankee Stadium July 4, 1939. The minimum bid
for Gehrig's uniform is $295,000.
</P>
<P>
   Foster won't say what he'll do with the money. He worked briefly
as an instructor with the Tampa Bay Devil Rays last spring, but is
currently out of baseball. He says the ball has been at his
mother's home in California since he brought it back from the '75
Series. Foster will not attend the auction.
</P>
<P>
   ``A friend suggested I do this,'' says the former Reds slugger.
``I guess knowing what the Buckner ball went for entered into it.
I've never talked to Fisk about it. I never volunteered to say that
I had it and I hadn't heard any interest that he wanted it. I
didn't realize it was historical until they started listing the
greatest home runs in history and it was in there.''
</P>
<P>
   If you want to bid, call 212-254-2555. But remember, hardball
history doesn't come cheaply. Bidding for the Fisk ball starts at
$25,000.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(Dan Shaughnessy is a Globe columnist.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2028EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
