A7816 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-YORK-AUTONATION-LADN     07-02 0518
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YORK-AUTONATION-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AUTO RETAILING GIANT BUYS SOUTHERN CALIFORNIA GROUP
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
BY GREGORY J. WILCOX  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Terry York's auto retailing business, which
stretches from the L.A.'s Santa Clarita Valley to Huntington Beach,
is being bought by the world's largest auto retailer as it attempts
to become a major force in the Southern California market,
officials said Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Terms of the purchase of Los Angeles-based Terry York Automotive
Group by AutoNation Inc. of Fort Lauderdale were not disclosed.
</P>
<P>
   York, a longtime philanthropist, said he had been negotiating
with AutoNation, formerly known as Republic Industries, for about a
year.
</P>
<P>
   The deal calls for his management company to continue to run the
dealerships. ``For all practical purposes as far as the operation
of the dealership and the employees everything is exactly the
same,'' said York, who started his automotive career as a file
clerk at a dealership. He and a partner set up their first
dealership in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we have just about everything there we would be
interested in buying,'' said AutoNation spokesman Oscar Suris.
</P>
<P>
   Suris said a definitive purchase agreement has been signed but
did not know when the deal would close.
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation is also getting York's Land Rover franchise in Encino
and a Ford store in Huntington Beach. All of the facilities will
retain the York name.
</P>
<P>
   AutoNation, which is controlled by Florida billionaire H. Wayne
Huizenga, owns nearly 400 new vehicle dealerships and 45 used-car
megastores across the country along with the Alamo-Rent-A-Car and
National rental car chains.
</P>
<P>
   The company is building a unique, multilevel retail business.
New cars are leased or sold on AutoNation's new lots or rented
through its rental companies and then sold or leased later as used
cars on its used car lots.
</P>
<P>
   So far, investor enthusiasm has waned in the three years since
the company was created. Shares of AutoNation have dropped more
than 25 percent in the last 12 months because of losses reported in
the used-car business.
</P>
<P>
   It now owns nine auto dealership groups in Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a big market with lots of potential car buyers. That's
why we are committed to having a major presence in Southern
California and the only way you do that is through acquiring
franchises,'' said Suris.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just demographics. People with disposable income are the
folks who buy autos and that's what we are looking for,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   York's sale to AutoNation is part of a consolidation trend in
the industry. Still, some independent dealers are not worried about
the increased competition from chains.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just continue to do business as usual. They are always
trying different things in the marketplace. They are bigger, but I
don't know if they are successful. There are sure a lot more of us
independents than the consolidated guys,'' said Steve Livingston,
owner of Livingston Motor Car Co. in Woodland Hills, which sells
Pontiac and Buick models.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
