u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-MARATHON-SAIL-BOS &LR;      07-02 0635
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MARATHON-SAIL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOWNEAST   SAILOR HOPES TO BEST ATLANTIC SPEED RECORD 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (a and s coding)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By CINDY RODRIGUEZ  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   With dolphin sightings in the distance and the spray of salt
water on his face, Cam Lewis of Maine zips through the choppy
waters of the Atlantic with one thought on his mind: breaking
another world record.
</P>
<P>
   In 1993, Lewis, 42, sailed around the world with four French
sailors in less than 80 days _ beating the previous record by 30
days.
</P>
<P>
   That record no longer stands in the frenzied world of sailboat
racing, where better technology and feverish activity keep sailors
rushing to the next challenge.
</P>
<P>
   This time, it's a scramble to Lizard's Point at the mouth of the
English Channel. Lewis and a crew of five others rushed to sea
Tuesday morning from New York Harbor. To beat the 1990
trans-Atlantic sailing record, they must arrive at ``The Lizard''
before 10:43 p.m. EST Monday. So far, they are making record time.
</P>
<P>
   And, as sailors have come to expect, there's always a snafu.
</P>
<P>
   On day one, the crew discovered their engine compartment filled
with water.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had to get it pumped out and get the engine cleaned up in a
hurry,'' Lewis wrote in an email from the vessel. Without the
engine, which runs communications equipment they probably wouldn't
reach their finish line in time.
</P>
<P>
   But it didn't stop them. As a hired hand pumped the water out
for two hours, Lewis kept speeding along, keeping a 20-knot pace.
</P>
<P>
   The Foncia, a 60-foot-long trimaran, looks like something out of
Star Wars. It's nearly as wide as it is long; the outer amas span
56 1/2 feet. Unlike other kinds of sailboats, it doesn't heel much.
It's ride is steady and stable.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not particularly dangerous. These boats are designed to
go fast,'' said Keith Taylor, publicist for the crew.
</P>
<P>
   But it's a jerky ride, like a ``trolley car run amok,'' Taylor
said. And there's always the possibility that random debris could
smash against the vessel. But those on the Foncia are in constant
touch with the world.
</P>
<P>
   Via satellite phones and computer e-mail, Lewis keeps in touch
with three weather routers in New Hampshire and five in France.
Using the Global Positioning System, the routers get hourly reports
of the exact location of the Foncia, its speed and heading.
</P>
<P>
   Friday morning, after completing 72 hours, the Foncia had
covered 1,470 nautical miles and had another 1,449 miles to go.
Taylor said if the Foncia continues at its current clip, it will
finish the 2,888-mile voyage in six days total, about half a day
faster than the record.
</P>
<P>
   The existing record, set in June 1990 by French skipper Serge
Madec sailing the 75-foot catamaran Jet Services V., made it across
the Atlantic in 6 days, 13 hours, 3 minutes, and 32 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   In the end what will make the difference is lighter and stronger
equipment, and a passion for winning. But that comes easy to Lewis,
who lives in Lincolnville, Maine, and grew up in Sherborn, Mass.
He's been sailing since age 4. He won his first race at age 6.
</P>
<P>
   Since then, he's won a slew of championships, including two wins
of the Finn Gold Cup and twice winning the 505 world title.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the real rock star of sailing,'' said Larry Rosenfeld,
46, his long-time friend and business partner. The two have started
their own company, Team Adventure USA, which is is building a
vessel to compete in The Race, the simply titled name of a race
around the world which will begin Dec. 31, 2000.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld said the co-skippers aboard the Foncia _ Swiss
brothers Yvan and Laurent Bourgnon _ are among the best sailors in
the world.
</P>
<P>
   ``The brothers are like the Michael Jordans of France,''
Rosenfeld said. ``They are on TV all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
