<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MISTER-FAN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Little Mister making fans of hot people everywhere
 &HT;    By Meredith Moss
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Her family was vacationing in Williamsburg, Va.,
and though it was only June, the heat index registered 102 degrees.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were outdoors touring the historic sites and my face was
getting fiery red,'' recalls Barbara Mason, who has fair and
sensitive skin. ``I decided I needed something and stopped at a
drugstore to see what might help.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Harrison Twp. woman spotted a Mister Fan combination
spray bottle and small fan, she remembered seeing others use
similar products and decided to buy one.
</P>
<P>
   Now she's sold on what she's dubbed her ``spritzer.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I used it for the next three days through the heat wave, and I
loved it!'' Mason says. ``It kept cooling me down.''
</P>
<P>
   With temperatures and humidity soaring this holiday weekend,
chances are you'll see lots of folks with the little spray-bottles
in tow.
</P>
<P>
   The concept is simple: Fill the bottle with tap water and
squeeze it periodically to release a fine mist. To add to the
cooling effect, there's a battery-operated fan with an on/off
button. Similar products have names such as Mist N Cool and Misty
Mates.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the personal misters sell for less than $10 and use two
double-A batteries.
</P>
<P>
   Erin Foster, 18, bought a Squeeze Breeze last summer at the ATP
Tennis Tournament in Cincinnati. ``It was hot and I saw people
using them so we went to a booth and got one,'' says Foster, who is
from Clayton.
</P>
<P>
   A camp counselor at Sinclair Park, Foster says she keeps the
gadget in her trunk for hot-weather emergencies. Her campers like
them, too.
</P>
<P>
   There are fancier, and bigger, versions. ``It's something we
just started carrying this year,'' says Josh Huthmacher of Sears
Hardware Store in Kettering. His store sells The Mist Stand, a
free-standing portable cooling system that attaches to a hose and
sprays mist from nozzles that can be clamped onto umbrellas or
above a patio to cool a crowd. It's $15.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to enjoying the fountain spray at Paramount King's
Island, lots of visitors have been grateful for the theme park's
giant mister aimed at patrons who are waiting in line to ride The
Beast roller coaster.
</P>
<P>
   And a patented cart-mounted misting system, the Cool Cart,
allows golfers to enjoy play on the hottest days.
</P>
<P>
   The misting folks may be missing one last bet, especially with
baby boomers.
</P>
<P>
   A Menopause Mister would sell like hot cakes year-round.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
