<HEADER>
A7822 &Cx1f; tad-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-STOCKS03-COX     07-02 1127
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STOCKS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Investors acting as if expansion has just begun
 &HT;    By Tom Walker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The stock market is in the midst of one of those
occasional, but fundamental, shifts that cause investors and
portfolio managers to rethink their holdings _ and to make major
adjustments in them.
</P>
<P>
   Based on what they are now buying, investors seem to think this
is the first year of an economic expansion instead of the eighth.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter describe the situation
this way: ``The investment preference for big, richly valued growth
stocks that has been in vogue since 1997 reversed abruptly in
April, and investors began shifting aggressively into cyclical,
value and small-cap stocks.''
</P>
<P>
   The latter typically outperform the market in the early stages
of the business cycle, when the economy is coming out of a
recession and demand for goods and services is strong.
</P>
<P>
   According to Standard &AMP; Poor's, the industry groups with the
biggest second-quarter share price gains were basic materials
(aluminum, chemicals, iron and steel), energy (oil and gas
exploration, drilling services), capital goods (construction,
electrical equipment, machinery, office equipment) and utilities
(electricity, natural gas).
</P>
<P>
   Almost all of those industry groups were money-losers in 1998,
and in the first quarter did not perform as well as the technology
sector, transportation or consumer cyclicals (autos, textiles,
retailing, home building).
</P>
<P>
   Explanations of this turn of events vary, but most of them add
up to this: The U.S. economy is still strong, some of the world's
economic trouble spots are improving (Southeast Asia especially),
corporate profits are better than expected and investor sentiment
is upbeat. By any standard, that's a formula for stock market
growth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Almost anything that benefits from greater growth and pricing
power and rising commodity prices _ especially oil and natural gas
stocks _ has taken center stage,'' said Stephen Leeb, editor of
Personal Finance. ``As long as growth continues, these trends will
remain in place.''
</P>
<P>
   Most money managers recommend investors continue to favor value
and cyclical stocks this year, especially capital goods, phone
companies, consumer cyclicals, energy and technology.
</P>
<P>
   But as long as Treasuries are yielding close to 6 percent,
analysts also suggests investors hold about 30 percent of their
portfolios in bonds. The consensus asset allocation recommendation
is another 59 percent in stocks and the rest in cash, according to
a Bloomberg News poll of strategists.
</P>
<P>
   That's the consensus. The range for stock allocation runs from
35 percent to 80 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Despite this seemingly positive outlook, the things that bearish
analysts have worried about for most of the '90s are still in
place. The most serious is that stocks are overpriced relative to
profit growth, with the Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 index starting the
third quarter at 34 times earnings against a historical norm of
about 15 times.
</P>
<P>
   IBES International, which tracks earnings forecasts and other
data, said its ``equity valuation model'' for June indicated stocks
were overvalued by 39.5 percent compared with only 4.4 percent in
December.
</P>
<P>
   The same index had a reading of 39.8 percent overvalued in
August of 1987, just two months prior to the market's worst-ever
crash.
</P>
<P>
   Market breadth, or the number of stock groups moving higher, has
improved this year, but on balance trading is still dominated by a
relatively small number of big stocks, on the order of the Nifty
Fifty of the 1970s.
</P>
<P>
   There's also the rise of 30-year Treasury yields above 6
percent, the biggest negative for the market this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Reserve's quarter-point increase in the federal
funds rate on June 30 momentarily rallied the bond market, sending
the yield back below 6 percent. But some bond analysts are
concerned that the Fed's adoption of a neutral stand on rates
suggests it really isn't serious about fighting inflation _ a
sentiment that could keep upward pressure on yields.
</P>
<P>
   It's important since rising yields _ especially above the
psychologically important 6 percent level _ make bonds highly
attractive to investors who may be seeking safety as well as good
returns. That means money that could go into stocks, or that was in
stocks, could be diverted to bonds.
</P>
<P>
   The rise in consumer debt _ especially margin debt, which is
used to buy stocks _ also concerns analysts.
</P>
<P>
   In a bizarre sort of way, the Fed's concern about inflation may
have been a plus for the market, since it suggests the economy, far
from heading for recession any time soon, will eventually go on to
set an all-time expansion record.
</P>
<P>
   Many analysts now look for the market to go to new highs
following the Fed's lone rate hike and neutral stance.
</P>
<P>
   Robert S. Robbins, market strategist for Robinson-Humphrey in
Atlanta, looks for a ``summer rally,'' which he said is ``typically
the market's second-strongest seasonal rally of the year'' after
the year-end upturn.
</P>
<P>
   Other analysts are more cautious.
</P>
<P>
   Ned Davis Research analyst Tim Hayes said the market is unlikely
to move to new highs ``without substantial interest rate declines,
significant improvement in the earnings outlook, or a broadening of
market activity.''
</P>
<P>
   What happens to the market in the second half may be determined
by the next barrage of corporate earnings reports, due over the
next five or six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   After declining in the third quarter of 1998 for the first time
since 1990, and ending the year basically flat, operating earnings
of Standard &AMP; Poor's 500 companies rose almost 10 percent in the
first quarter.
</P>
<P>
   That was the strongest quarterly gain since the Asian crisis
began in mid-1997, and far better than analysts anticipated.
</P>
<P>
   Forecasts for full-year 1999 profit growth vary widely, from
about 10 percent by analysts at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter to as
much as 17 percent at Standard &AMP; Poor's.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, most forecasters are fairly modest in their
projections for the stock market in 1999. Forecasts of 11,500 for
the benchmark Dow Jones industrial average are common, but that is
only 393 points above the Dow's all-time high set on May 13.
</P>
<P>
   Bearish forecasts range as low as 9,000, however, such as that
by Gail Dudack of Warburg Dillon Read. Few analysts are that
pessimistic, however.
</P>
<P>
   Another scenario favored by some analysts is that stocks will
trade within a range in the second half. Stocks will make new highs
but also suffer modest corrections (under 10 percent) as investors
move in and out of favored industry groups _ but not out of the
market.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
