<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HARVARD-PORN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARVARD PRESIDENT BACKS OUSTER OF DIVINITY DEAN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JAMES BANDLER AND ROSS KERBER  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BOSTON -- In his first public comment on the matter, Harvard
President Neil L. Rudenstine has defended his university's role in
the forced resignation of the Harvard Divinity School dean who
stepped down last fall amid allegations of pornography use on his
office computer.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine vociferously rejected criticism in the press that
divinity school technicians had violated the privacy of Dean Ronald
Thiemann by notifying authorities about the presence of pornography
on his office computer.
</P>
<P>
   ``At no time did any Harvard personnel violate Professor
Thiemann's privacy,'' Rudenstine said in a written statement
released Thursday,
</P>
<P>
   He said the role of the university's technology staff had been
reviewed at the most senior levels of the university. He said there
was nothing invasive or inappropriate about the technology staff's
actions.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rather, staff members repeatedly and over a period of more
than a year carried out tasks that the dean directed them to
perform, consistent with their official duties, in a place that had
clearly become part of their professional work environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``In so doing, they were unavoidably and involuntarily exposed
to inappropriate materials which they found to be not only
offensive, but severely distressing.''
</P>
<P>
   Thiemann, who presided over the divinity school for nearly 13
years, stepped down in November citing personal and professional
reasons.
</P>
<P>
   He has not commented publicly on the matter since the
pornography allegations were publicized.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer, Harvard Law School Professor Charles Ogletree, said
Thiemann was profoundly disappointed by Rudenstine's statement. He
said that it was difficult to understand why the university had not
contacted Theimann about the allegations earlier if they really had
been problems for a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dean Theimann has made every effort to respect and maintain
the privacy for him and his family and has avoided any public
comment on the allegations,'' Ogletree said. ``After 13 years of
unprecedented success surving as dean of the divinity school, there
is a strong feeling that he is now being kicked in the stomach when
he's down, while the University continues to protect the privacy of
those who have made allegations against dean.''
</P>
<P>
   Sources at Harvard said the pornographic material was discovered
in October on Thiemann's Harvard-owned computer after he requested
a new hard drive to replace his existing hard drive, which was
full. The computer was in the office of Thiemann's Harvard-owned
residence.
</P>
<P>
   In new revelations, sources said that an explicit pornographic
image was on the computer screen when a technician walked into the
room. Ogletree said the incident didn't happen.
</P>
<P>
   In a process that involved down-loading the files from the old
hard-drive to the divinity school's mainframe to the new
hard-drive, the technician saw sexually explicit file names
crossing the screen, according to sources.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the presence of so many image files, the file
transfer process took an entire work-day, the sources said. When
the technician's supervisor inquired why the transfer was taking so
long, he did not want to answer, the sources said, but eventually
did.
</P>
<P>
   Rudenstine said in his statement that staff members were
``reluctant to report the matter,'' and eventually spoke only to
senior officers at the divinity school. After consultation, the
senior officers reported the facts to the university president's
office, Rudenstine said.
</P>
<P>
   After the pornography scandal was disclosed this spring,
Thiemann became something of a reluctant cause celebre among
internet privacy rights activists. Boston Phoenix media critic Dan
Kennedy on Thursday singled out Rudenstine in his annual ``Muzzle
Awards,'' a list of people who Kennedy said undermined free speech.
</P>
<P>
   Harvard, for the most part, declined to respond to the attacks.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the recent remarks of Harvard Law Professor Alan
Dershowitz that prompted the university to defend its beleaguered
information technology staff after he referred to them as
``snoops'' and ``peeping toms.''
</P>
<P>
   In other Harvard news, the university said its technicians on
Wednesday removed from school computers an independently-produced
web site after receiving a complaint that it contained offensive
material.
</P>
<P>
   University spokesman Joe Wrinn said the site was operated by a
group known as PacketStorm Security, led by a site administrator in
North Carolina. Harvard had recently made an unusual agreement to
host the popular site in order to help distribute software security
tools.
</P>
<P>
   But in addition, the PacketStorm's site included graphic sexual
images and other material apparently intended to satirize a rival
website devoted to software-security matters, known as AntiOnline.
</P>
<P>
   According to a letter to Harvard from AntiOnline founder John
Vranesvich, the PacketStorm site included ``a large archive of
libelous and, to put it bluntly, sick material,'' including
``images ranging from people engaged in homosexual activities, to a
nun that appears to be covered in seminal fluid.''
</P>
<P>
   The descriptions were accurate, said Harvard spokesman Wrinn,
prompting the University to remove the entire site from its
computers because it violated school polices. Harvard is now in the
process of returning the data to PacketStorm administrator Ken
Williams in North Carolina, Wrinn said.
</P>
<P>
   Williams couldn't be reached for comment, but in a letter posted
on a different site on the Web he denied that his site had posed a
threat to Vranesevich and complained that in shutting down the site
Harvard acted inapropriately, because ``no laws or rules were
broken on my part.''
</P>
</TEXT>
