<HEADER>
A7827 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CURSEFREE-TV03-COX     07-02 0623
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CURSEFREE-TV03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    When V-chips are down, curse-free gadget will clean up TV trash
talk
 &HT;    By Steve Gushee
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WEST PALM BEACH, Fla. _ Less is more for many Christian homes.
</P>
<P>
   Now there's a gadget that will do away with offensive words on
television and let the show go on. V-chips are out. Curse Free TV
is in.
</P>
<P>
   A computer with a 100-word dictionary and a sense of moral
outrage allows families to hear their favorite adult programming
free of profanity, cursing and the Lord's name taken in vain.
V-chips block the entire show. This gimmick cuts out swearing only.
</P>
<P>
   ``When insulting language comes into the home, it's a kind of
violation,'' said Pamela Culbreath, a self-described born-again
Christian from Boynton Beach, Fla., who is an area representative
for the invention. ``I feel violated when I have to either listen
to garbage like that or turn the program off.''
</P>
<P>
   Curse Free TV solves both problems. The small device attaches to
the television set and monitors all programs and videotapes.
</P>
<P>
   The computer reads the closed captioned script embedded in all
programs, compares each word to the dictionary of foul language,
mutes the bad words and flashes a neutral substitute on the screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are mandated biblically not to allow it (curse
words) into our homes,'' said the Rev. Jonas Robertson, president
of the Curse Free TV company and pastor of the Church of Abundant
Life in New Orleans. ``This has liberated us to stand up for our
convictions and still enjoy great movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson's promotional material claims there are 13 offensive
words in the movie E.T., 32 in Kindergarten Cop, 21 in Mrs.
Doubtfire and 17 in Jurassic Park.
</P>
<P>
   Curse Free TV users can watch those programs safely. No naughty
words will escape the vigilance of technology.
</P>
<P>
   And the faithful are assured that the misuse of the words
Christ, God and Jesus will be muted as well _ unless they want to
hear them.
</P>
<P>
   If an actor uses the name of Jesus offensively, the machine will
mute the word and substitute something like ``Old Man,'' Culbreath
said.
</P>
<P>
   But a special religion switch cancels that censorship and allows
religious words to be heard when, for example, watching Christian
programming, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The device does not work for live programs, news or sports. The
closed caption script trails the audio on those programs. But for
most shows, Curse Free TV will be vigilant and effective.
</P>
<P>
   Culbreath is just getting started in her territory, defined by
the 561 area code. She plans to enlist distributors and market to
churches and individuals, selling Curse Free TV for $149.95.
</P>
<P>
   The device evolved from an earlier, less rigorous electronic
censor called TV Guardian produced by Principle Solutions in
Rogers, Ark.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson tried TV Guardian in November and soon realized it
would not meet the needs of Christian homes, he said.
</P>
<P>
   It had a tolerance switch that allowed mild cursing to come over
the airwaves. Some words used as substitutes for cursing such as
jerk or idiot were also offensive to Robertson's ear. And TV
Guardian used close word association for substitutions that he
found objectionable.
</P>
<P>
   ``For instance, `kick your ---' would become `kick your rear.'
That's a word that invokes the very word in your mind (you don't
want to hear). We use, `toe.' We don't want close word
association.''
</P>
<P>
   Robertson modified TV Guardian for Christian homes and was given
the license to sell Curse Free TV through churches and Christian
stores.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an opportunity to help families with something we feel
is really important,'' Culbreath said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
