r a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRFORCE-IMMIGRANTS-S     07-02 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRFORCE-IMMIGRANTS-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPECIAL PROBLEMS FACE LEGAL IMMIGRANTS IN U.S. MILITARY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ED OFFLEY  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   McCHORD AFB, Wash. _ Joachim and Lizette Camacho, each 21 years
old, are highly regarded professionals in the Air Force, but they
face a bureaucratic dilemma that could abort their military careers
before they get off the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The married couple are not U.S. citizens. They were born in
Mexico and emigrated to the United States, where they obtained
permanent immigrant status. Under military regulations, Joachim and
Lizette Camacho were qualified to enlist in the Air Force, but they
face discharge should they fail to become U.S. citizens by the end
of their four-year enlistments.
</P>
<P>
   At the time of their enlistments, the Camachos fully expected to
gain citizenship before their terms ended and continue on with
their Air Force careers. But a major backlog in processing
naturalization requests at the Immigration and Naturalization
Service has put their hopes in jeopardy, as well as more than 2,500
military members awaiting naturalization.
</P>
<P>
   Current regulations prohibit enlistees such as the Camachos from
any assignment in the Air Force requiring a secret or top secret
security clearance. Thus, pending their naturalization, they are
excluded from two-thirds of the jobs and career paths in the Air
Force, including any assignments working on aircraft, weapons or
high-tech communications.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is harder'' for non-citizens, says Lizette Camacho, a
senior airman who works in the personnel office as a human
resources staffer at the 62nd Mission Support Squadron at McChord.
</P>
<P>
   The Camachos in all other respects are a typical military
couple, said McChord spokesman 1st Lt. Lars Anderson.
</P>
<P>
   They met as high school students at their home town of Glendale,
Calif., and decided after graduation and marriage to join the
military for its professional opportunities. Today, they live in a
cozy duplex on base and enjoy their life in the Pacific Northwest.
</P>
<P>
   Joachim, who said he has always been fascinated by airplanes,
was surprised to enjoy one of the least likeable aspects of
military life _ the regimented 12 weeks of recruit boot camp. ``I
liked the challenges,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lizette said she, too, was intrigued by the opportunities and
challenges of military service, turning down a college scholarship
to join the Air Force. After hours, she attends Pierce College
courses in pursuit of an associate degree in human resources.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are valuable people we are glad to see serving in the
U.S. Air Force,'' Jim Wolfe, a special assistant to acting Air
Force Secretary F. Whitten Peters, said of recruits such as the
Camachos. ``There is no separate standard _ these are people who
have the potential for a full career in the Air Force.''
</P>
<P>
   Although still a relatively small number overall, immigrant
enlistments in the U.S. military have steadily risen from 5,267 _
3.1 percent _ of all first-term enlistments in 1995, to 8,171
recruits _ 4.6 percent overall _ last year, according to Wolfe.
</P>
<P>
   One traditional benefit of active military service for legal
immigrants is that the waiting period for naturalization is three
years in contrast to the five-year term for civilians. Wolfe said
that historically the shorter waiting period has helped military
immigrants because enlisted personnel do not normally require
higher security clearances and classified technical training until
their second four-year enlistments.
</P>
<P>
   But a serious problem threatening the military careers of the
Camachos and other legal immigrants in the military cropped up
several years ago when the INS experienced a dramatic increase in
applications for naturalization, said Don Crocetti, associate INS
commissioner for immigration services. Changes in federal welfare
eligibility for legal immigrant residents caused a six-fold jump in
citizenship applications.
</P>
<P>
   The backlog in processing naturalization applications
immediately put many military applicants in a serious bind.
</P>
<P>
   ``People were getting to the end of their (initial) enlistments
without the paperwork being complete,'' Wolfe said. ``The waits
were getting awfully long for (INS citizenship) interviews.''
</P>
<P>
   For Lizette Camacho, who emigrated to the United States from
Guadalajara, Mexico, with her mother at the age of 13 in 1991, the
security regulations have resulted in her assignment to the
personnel office as a human resources staffer. While she enjoys the
work, Lizette said, her goal is to serve as a cargo loadmaster on
one of the McChord Air Force Base's C-141 or C-17 aircraft.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are opportunities here that you can't get outside as a
civilian,'' she said. ``But with citizenship we will have a bigger
choice of jobs in the Air Force.''
</P>
<P>
   Under the three-year rule, Lizette will become eligible for
naturalization at the end of this year, while Joachim will be
eligible in mid-2001.
</P>
<P>
   Joachim Camacho, who was born in the southern Mexico town of
Sinaloa before emigrating with his mother to the United States at
the age of eight, said his long-term goal is to work in aircraft
maintenance, another excluded position. For now, he works at the
McChord passenger terminal.
</P>
<P>
   Wolfe and Crocetti said that an outcry from military personnel
squeezed by the INS backlog led to a joint task force of Pentagon
and INS officials that last month devised a plan to fast-track
military applications for citizenship under the three-year waiting
rule. Under the plan, each of the military services is setting up a
system to assemble the paperwork, interviews and background checks
for each applicant, then delivering the packages directly to an INS
office that will expedite final processing.
</P>
<P>
   ``We aren't doing anything in the military to judge whether or
not the person should become a citizen,'' Wolfe said. The goal is
to avoid an inadvertent loss of service by a qualified military
applicant simply because his or her application is bogged down in
the pipeline.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the recruiting climate we have now, we would not want to
lose such a group of people,'' Wolfe said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
