<HEADLINE>
SHORT ITEMS ON PEOPLE AND PERSONALITIES  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Helpful Hint To the government &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For much of his 35 years in Britain, Mohamed al-Fayed, the
Egyptian-born owner of Harrod's department store, has been waiting
in vain to be admitted to British citizenship and issued a British
passport, apparently because some British officials questioned the
circumstances of his purchase of Harrod's.
</P>
<P>
   So last week, Fayed _ never slow to tweak the British
authorities and remind them of his plight _ seized a chance to help
others facing delays with their passports. Huge lines have been
building at government offices because of computer problems and a
new rule requiring parents to obtain separate passports for their
children.
</P>
<P>
   British citizens, who had been able to obtain passports in about
10 days, now must wait about eight weeks. The backlog has reached
500,000 applicants.
</P>
<P>
   In London, Fayed dispatched one of Harrod's distinctive,
green-liveried vans, laden with tea, coffee, sodas and water, to be
handed out to some of those standing in line. ``I just wanted to do
something to show solidarity with the long-suffering public and do
something to ease their burden,'' he said. &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Programmer's Playtime &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What did Mark Eppley, creator of Laplink, the most popular
software for transferring files between personal computers, do on
his 21-month vacation? ``I got into diesel equipment,'' he said at
a party during the recent PC Expo in New York. ``A tugboat, a
bulldozer and a crane. I built a yurt, a treehouse and a stage.''
(A yurt is a circular canvas structure most common in Mongolia.)
</P>
<P>
   Why the time out? ``Hey, I needed a break,'' he said. ``I've
been in the software business 20 years, and that's equivalent to at
least two full careers with a normal job.'' What's more, the
business was no longer as much of a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   The newly constructed stage is the setting for his annual
Spamjam party and rockfest, on his farm in Snohomish, Wash. About
200 friends, including veterans of Eppley's Team Spam adventures,
attended last year's gathering.
</P>
<P>
   This year's dates are July 31 and Aug. 1; musical selections
will be on Laplink's Web site. Insiders know that Spam alludes not
only to unwanted e-mail, but also to a 1996 outing when Eppley
lugged a Spam windsock, playing cards, boxer shorts and an
umbrella, plus the canned product, up Mount Rainier.
</P>
<P>
   Eppley, chairman of Traveling Software Inc., which produces
Laplink, estimated with a laugh that his product has about 20
million users, but only 6 million paying customers.
</P>
<P>
   As for work, the challenge is back and, since October, so is
Eppley, busily developing new products for use over the Internet.
``The Internet changes everything,'' he said. ``And that's
exciting.'' &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Juggling Jobs by Jet &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For Roger Penske, there's the weekday job, as chief executive of
the Penske Corp., a truck-leasing, auto-retailing and
engine-manufacturing company that operates around the world. And
then there's the weekend job, as chairman of Penske Racing Inc.,
the most successful Indy car racing team in history, with 99 wins
at tracks around the nation.
</P>
<P>
   How does he coordinate his two careers? Interviewed by telephone
last weekend at the Medic Grand Prix in Cleveland, he said he takes
the Penske Corp.'s Gulfstream IV jet for foreign jaunts and a
Citation X for most domestic trips.
</P>
<P>
   The week before, for example, he flew back from Italy to the
Detroit area (his headquarters and home) on the Gulfstream, then on
the Citation from there to Portland, Ore., for the Budweiser G.I.
Joe's 200. He flew home to Michigan Sunday night, then on the
Gulfstream overnight on Monday in time for a meeting Tuesday in
Bologna, Italy. Then to Stuttgart and Friedrichshafen, Germany, for
meetings on Wednesday, then overnight back to Detroit by Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, it was back onto the Citation, bound for Cleveland.
On other weekends he has returned for races from as far away as
Tokyo.
</P>
<P>
   He says his commuting method lets him squeeze in extra work,
particularly on trips from Asia. (Never mind that any hours picked
up on one leg of a trip have to be lost somewhere else.) ``You gain
time,'' he said. ``It gives you eight days in a seven-day week.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Sasha Cavender &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
