<HEADER>
A7836 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BIZ-JAPAN-TV-INVEST-$     07-02 1164
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIZ-JAPAN-TV-INVEST-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 ON JAPANESE TV, THE ABCs OF MONEY   (af)  
 By STEPHANIE STROM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TOKYO _ The world of high finance could hardly believe the news
on the front page of The Financial Times last month. Goldman, Sachs
&AMP; Co., as snooty as Wall Street's notoriously snooty white-shoe
firms get, was sponsoring a TV program for Japanese homemakers?
Surely someone had confused the firm with Procter &AMP; Gamble.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on the last Saturday afternoon in June, there it was. TV
Tokyo broadcast a one-hour special to introduce ``Money Angels,'' a
weekly half-hour drama that unlocks the mysteries of financial
planning for Mrs. Watanabe and her neighbors. And every so often,
up popped an ad for Goldman's mutual funds. At least for a
half-hour on Saturday afternoons in Tokyo, the firm is trading its
white shoes for house slippers.
</P>
<P>
   Despite a title that evokes Farah Fawcett, the program is a
serious attempt to explain the basics of household financial
planning in a country where many consumers are baffled by compound
interest, never mind dividends or debentures.
</P>
<P>
   In American eyes, sponsorship of such a program might seem silly
and out of character for a firm like Goldman, but in the context of
Japan, it is an ambitious example of a company paying more than lip
service to the widely touted mantra, ``Think globally, act
locally.''
</P>
<P>
   ``In this market, we think this is going to be an interesting
and potentially very successful way of reaching the consumer,''
said Mark Schwartz, who was recently promoted to head Goldman's
business in Asia. ``We would never do something like this in the
U.S. because it's not appropriate there, but here it makes a lot of
sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Why? For one thing, Japanese homemakers have a tight grip on the
country's $11.1 trillion in household assets. They determine how
their household budget is allocated, where savings are deposited
and what, if any, investments are made.
</P>
<P>
   For another, Japanese consumers are hungry for basic
information. ``There is a very high level of interest here, not
specifically in investing but in what this world of investing and
financial planning is all about, and especially how it works,''
said Yasuyo Yamazaki, Goldman's ebullient head of asset management
in Japan. Some 90,000 people attended the 600 investment seminars
Goldman held in Japan last year.
</P>
<P>
   People here are acutely aware that as they are living longer,
the population is aging, and both public and private pension
systems are grossly underfunded. Less understood, and harder to
explain in a country where prices are falling, not rising, is the
notion that piling up cash in a savings account that earns less
than 1 percent interest _ the going rate here _ will not likely
assure a comfortable retirement.
</P>
<P>
   Mention concepts like risk and reward, portfolio diversification
and asset allocation to a typical Japanese homemaker, and be
prepared for a bewildered stare tinged with ever-so-slight
disapproval: In Japan, risk is a four-letter word.
</P>
<P>
   The program revolves around three women, Hinako, Yuko and
Kuroda-san, the ``money angels,'' who are meant to function as
consumer advocates. A well-known actress, Fukumi Kuroda, plays
Kuroda-san, the head of a consulting firm whom clients often ask
about financial matters.
</P>
<P>
   In the first episode, a mother and father tell their stunned
children that they should not expect any inheritance, since the
parents will not be able to finance their own retirements. The
children appeal to the money angels for help, and so begins a
series of visits to real-life financial consultants and others who
demystify market principles by explaining ways to pump up savings.
</P>
<P>
   ``The topics are deliberately broad,'' Yamazaki said. ``The most
important thing is for this show to educate the viewers, because
the more intelligent they are, the better it will be for us.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Goldman has no retail brokerage outlets of its own, and
must rely on Japanese brokerage firms and banks to sell its funds,
Yamazaki's operation is the sixth-largest mutual fund company in
Japan, and 5 of the country's 10 most popular funds are Goldman's,
according to one survey.
</P>
<P>
   Yamazaki, a born showman, has achieved that by using unorthodox
marketing methods _ unorthodox at least for Goldman. He and his
sales force spend a lot of time roaming the banks and brokerage
firms that sell Goldman's funds. He writes a column, ``Asset
Management with Zack Yamazaki,'' for a weekly newspaper read by
more than six million people, and receives about 500 letters a
month from readers.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman was receptive when TV Tokyo, the station loosely
affiliated with Japan's leading financial daily, Nikkei Shimbun,
approached it with the idea for ``Money Angels'' last year, because
Goldman had already sponsored a program on a satellite channel and
was pleased with the response.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not as if we didn't approach Japanese firms at all,''
said Masato Ikeuchi, executive vice president of Television Tokyo
Channel 12 Ltd. ``But their reaction was, well, dull. They
understand where the industry is heading, but they've not yet
reached the point where they want to spend money on advertising and
marketing.'' In any case, in their present state few Japanese
financial institutions could afford it.
</P>
<P>
   One viewer's reaction illustrates what ``Money Angels'' is up
against. Tazuko Makio, 72, who lives with her retired husband, said
the program was clear and informative, if a bit stiff, and
illustrated issues from the consumer's side better than news
programs did.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Makio won't be buying any mutual fund shares. ``Those
things are for people with a lot of money,'' she said; her nest egg
will stay in accessible, riskless savings accounts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Money Angels'' represents more than just an innovative
approach to an idiosyncratic market. It is also one more sign of
Goldman's adaptation to the rigors of being a public company. In
order to smooth out its earnings stream, Goldman is trying to build
up its asset management business, which lags far behind those of
its rivals, Merrill Lynch and Morgan Stanley. But the effort is
likely to scuff its white-shoe image a bit.
</P>
<P>
   Schwartz denies that backing ``Money Angels'' raised any
eyebrows at the firm. But others say Goldman's executive committee
is sensitive about how its support for the program will be
interpreted.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts say stepping out in new directions will be good for
Goldman, whatever the impact on its traditional image. A more
homespun demeanor may help the firm cultivate a whole new crop of
clients to add to its roster of blue-chip corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Goldman may even be taking a lesson from the very companies that
have long sought its advice. ``Look, the mutual fund business is
very different from the other businesses of Goldman, Sachs,''
Yamazaki said. ``It's a consumer business, and we're learning from
Sony, Tiffany, even McDonald's.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
