<HEADLINE>
401(K) ADVICE ONLINE  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4) 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: Calif.)   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Are you ever nervous about the choices you've made in investing
your 401(k) money? And have you ever calculated how big your
account is likely to grow by the time you reach retirement?
</P>
<P>
   Three services, Financial Engines, Directadvice.com and Standard
&AMP; Poor's Personalwealth.com are among a handful of companies that
have sprung up to help investors answer such questions on line.
</P>
<P>
   Investors can get a free estimate of a portfolio's value upon
retirement at the Financial Engines' site,
www.financialengines.com. For $14.95 a quarter, they receive
recommendations on how to allocate cash among the funds offered in
their 401(k)s.
</P>
<P>
   ``We provide specific recommendations on funds to find the
highest expected return for a given level of risk,'' said Jeff
Maggioncalda, president of Financial Engines, based in Palo Alto,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The company was founded by William F. Sharpe, a Stanford
professor and Nobel laureate in economics.
</P>
<P>
   The computer model looks at criteria like fund expenses,
consistency of performance and appropriateness of investment style,
given the individual's other holdings. It then makes
recommendations. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   (Bloomberg News)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
