<SLUG> BC-NYC-COL-PICKLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COLUMN: LIFE IS A BARREL OF PICKLES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JIM YARDLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The rain fell in fat, wet drops on Thursday morning,
splattering atop the 15 orange barrels outside Lower East Side
Pickles as the proprietor, Joe Davide, squinted at the sky and
pronounced business ``sour.''
</P>
<P>
   It was not much of a day to move ``the product,'' as Davide
calls his barrels of sour tomatoes, sweet red peppers, hot cherry
peppers, marinated mushrooms, pimento olives, black olives and,
most of all, pickles. He has sour pickles and three-quarter-sour
pickles and half-sour pickles. He has sweet pickles and large
pickles and small pickles. He even has specially spiced pickles.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is something that everybody don't have,'' Davide said,
lifting the hard plastic cover of a barrel to reveal spicy pickles
swimming in the brine.
</P>
<P>
   New York, Davide is quick to remind, is a pickle town. The
pickle might not enjoy the glamour of the bagel or the acclaim of
the knish, but just imagine a pastrami and rye without one. Yet if
the pickle is everywhere in New York, it is also practically
nowhere. The old pushcart pickle district on Essex Street on the
Lower East Side has dwindled to a single store as most people now
buy their pickles from jars in grocery stores.
</P>
<P>
   But if the writing was on the wall, Davide didn't read it. He
had stumbled into the business 25 years ago as a delivery driver at
Guss's Pickles on the Lower East Side, but 18 months ago he left
Manhattan to open his own store on East 19th Street off Avenue M in
Midwood, Brooklyn. He taped a notice of rabbinical approval to his
front window to assure residents in the predominantly Orthodox
Jewish neighborhood that though he is Italian and a gentile, his
pickles are kosher. He then sat back in a plastic chair on the
sidewalk and waited in vain for what might be described as the
pickle theory of economics to take hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``Who don't eat pickles?'' he asked. ``Everybody eats pickles.''
</P>
<P>
   During his years at Guss's, he learned how to make the brine of
salt water, garlic and spices, and how to properly age cucumbers
for the right degree of sourness. It was a living, but not always
an easy one.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the beginning,'' conceded Davide, who is now 47, ``it was
embarrassing. `What do you do?' `I make pickles.' I was young then.
At that age, who wanted to be a pickle man?'' But now he takes a
certain pride in his life of pickles. When the telephone rings
inside the shop, he answers, ``Pickles!'' He says customers shout
to him on the street, ``How do you do, Pickles?'' or ``Pickle
man!'' He just smiles and stuffs pickles into plastic quart
containers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We call him the pickle packer,'' snickered Joe Miller, his
brother-in-law and employee.
</P>
<P>
   Miller is helping out for the summer and his specialty seems to
be marketing and public relations (``Miller, like the beer, like
I'm high on life because I can't afford any better,'' he said by
way of introduction). He's talking about a Web site and formulating
plans to ship special orders of pickles nationwide. Davide listens
to all this, but he isn't convinced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I already worked 25 years in the business,'' he said. ``I
don't want to kill myself.''
</P>
<P>
   His pickle shop shares a bathroom with Anything Goes, a discount
ladies undergarment boutique on the corner, and, fortunately, the
owner, Mark Bayarsky, likes pickles. Often, Bayarsky sends
customers armed with bags of frilly things around the corner for a
pickle on him. ``When we open up the store in the morning, my whole
store stinks of pickles,'' he said. ``But I don't care. I love
pickles.''
</P>
<P>
   Davide knows that pickles will never make him rich. He charges
$4.25 for a quart of pickles, pricier than grocery pickles, but he
says quality is the difference. He is picking up business from a
few restaurants and delis, and Ellen Freudenheim, the polymath of
all things Brooklyn, included the shop in her new book about the
borough, ``Brooklyn! A Soup-to-Nuts Guide.'' His peak times are
Friday afternoons before the start of the Jewish Sabbath.
</P>
<P>
   But on slow days he or Bayarsky will run to the store for a few
beers. They usually get a sampler, tasting different brands with
different pickles in the name of market research. He knows there is
not much future in pickles, but he has come to realize that it is
good to be a pickle man.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, pickles are popular,'' he proclaimed.
</P>
<P>
   And with that he reclined in his plastic chair and waited for a
customer.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
