</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SLEEPING-BALLET-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`THE SLEEPING BEAUTY': RETURN TO 1890 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JENNIFER DUNNING   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Kirov Ballet's new production of ``The Sleeping
Beauty'' has been the subject of intense discussion this week. Much
of the talk has centered on the authenticity of detail and spirit
in this attempted return to the 1890 original and on what Sergei
Viharev's restaging has to offer to audiences of the 1990s. (It
takes some getting used to a ``Beauty'' whose Lilac Fairy looks, in
her historically correct costume, like Boadicea.)
</P>
<P>
   Irma Nioradze, who performed the title role on Wednesday night
at the Metropolitan Opera House, in some ways embodies these
issues. Hers was an interpretation that relied for the most part on
the dancing itself rather than any obvious acting to tell the story
and reveal the character of the young princess Aurora and her
awakening to womanhood.
</P>
<P>
   More naturally a frail, sad Giselle, Ms. Nioradze gained
radiance and suggested youthful excitement through her beautifully
poised carriage flashing legs and quick, darting attack. She
seemed at times to skim the ground. This was an Aurora animated by
music rather than steps or emotions, with fleeting glimpses of a
grandeur that belied Ms. Nioradze's slight build.
</P>
<P>
   Her speed robbed the Vision Scene of some of its poetry, though
Ms. Nioradze's quick, articulated footwork and fluid arabesques did
have a dreamlike quality. And the partnering looked underrehearsed
in the culminating grand pas de deux, danced with Igor Zelensky.
There was little rapport between the two dancers.
</P>
<P>
   One great pleasure of the charming, vivid production was the way
these 20th- century dancers' bodies projected 19th-century ballet
poses, to sometimes haunting effect. Sofiya Gumerova stood out for
her expressive use of her upper torso. Other standout performers
included Vladimir Ponomarev as an empathic King Florestan; Yana
Selina and Yuri Fateyev, the blessedly unkitschy White Cat and
Puss-in-Boots; Svetlana Ivanova and Vasily Sherbakov, full of
youthful Kirov presence in the Bluebird Pas de Deux, and Elvira
Tarasova, Tatyana Nekipelova, Yelena Koziyakova and Yuliya
Kasenkova in the Pas de Quatre.
</P>
<P>
   The lead cast was completed by Darya Pavlenko, a radiant Lilac
Fairy, Islom Baimuradov as Carabosse, and Polina Rassadina and
Maxim Khrebtov. Gianandrea Noseda conducted the sumptuously
performed Tchaikovsky score. Aleksandr Vasiliyev was the violin
soloist.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
