<HEADER>
A7867 &Cx1f; taf-z
u e &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BALLET-GISELLE-REVIEW     07-02 0531
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BALLET-GISELLE-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`GISELLE': SEDUCTION STRIPPED TO THE ESSENTIAL
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ANNA KISSELGOFF   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ ``Giselle'' has many faces, as the Kirov Ballet
reminded us on Thursday night when Diana Vishneva and Andrian
Fadeyev, as a young village lass and an unusually innocent seducer,
triumphed in this first of six performances that the Kirov is
presenting (Sunday excepted) through Monday night at the
Metropolitan Opera House.
</P>
<P>
   The current production still has the costumes of a staging by
Oleg Vinogradov, who apparently retains his title as the Kirov
Ballet's artistic director although Makharbek Vaziev actually runs
the troupe with the title of director of the ballet company.
</P>
<P>
   In any event, the dramatic detail, always played down in the
Kirov's ``Giselle,'' has been whittled down to the minimum. The
production has a ritualistic air: the dancers do what is expected
of them, and their characters are less real than emblematic.
</P>
<P>
   Much is taken for granted. The ``Peasant Pas de Deux'' was
performed with no introduction. The likable Vyacheslav Samodurov
and the precise Irina Zhelonkina danced the more difficult Soviet
version but there was no major character onstage to watch it. The
first act speeds along and includes an understated mad scene, not
necessarily unwelcome, by Ms. Vishneva.
</P>
<P>
   The production's treasure remains Act II, with the corps
delivering a superb stylistic unity. Two of the wilis, ghosts of
jilted maidens, still fly above on wires, and the green lighting by
Mikhail Federov and Vladimir Lukasevich gives the Romantic tutus of
the wili corps a true menace. Tatyana Amosova, as Myrtha, queen of
the wilis, is a dancer of great power and surprising sharpness.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Vishneva and Fadeyev received a long and delirious ovation
at the end of their performance. Given the schematic outline in Act
I, they accomplished wonders. In the Soviet era, the landmark
``Giselle'' was Leonid Lavrovsky's 1944 staging for the Bolshoi.
Its mix of realism and passionate romanticism, however, has always
been at odds with the Kirov version, which was more stylized and
often looked old-fashioned.
</P>
<P>
   Now that it is stripped to bare essentials, the Kirov version
offers little depth of characterization. Ilya Kuznetsov kept to a
suffering image as Hilarion, the rival to Fadeyev's Albrecht. Ms.
Vishneva, a sparkling dancer who molds every movement into a
sculptural shape, and Fadeyev, a pure and unaffected classicist,
seemed to be opposites yet danced in harmony.
</P>
<P>
   The first act looked overcoached. Nonetheless Ms. Vishneva's
perfect execution of her solo was a pleasure to watch. She held the
arabesques that many today omit and it is rare to see a dancer sail
through a double turn in attitude with such fluency and confidence.
</P>
<P>
   Nor has one often seen such a whirlwind of hops and turns by
Giselle's spirit right after her entrance in Act II. Fadeyev's
repentant sinner, sensing Giselle's presence at the start, had a
poetic veneer that he sustained right down to his perfect air turns
and to the moment Giselle's hand slipped out of his at the end.
Boris Gruzin was the fine conductor.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2114EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0324 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 21:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7869 &Cx1f; taf-z
u f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUBIN-VIDEO-NYT &LR;      07-02 0742
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUBIN-VIDEO-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`FREE BOB': RUBIN IS KIDNAPPED, AND THE CROWD ROARS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In his last 24 hours as Treasury secretary, Robert
Rubin scolded Congress for legislation that would make life easier
for money launderers, cleaned out his office, and then watched in
mock horror as President Clinton's closest advisers played out
their fantasy: That Rubin had been captured by Japan's Ministry of
Finance and held for a bizarre ransom.
</P>
<P>
   The kidnapping was the plot of a video entitled ``Free Bob: A
Documentary,'' which premiered in the state dining room on Thursday
night during a farewell party thrown by President Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   The White House was working Friday to make sure that the first
showing was also the last. But it will be hard to keep bootleg
copies from leaking out: This may be the only economic thriller to
ever star, playing themselves, Federal Reserve Chairman Alan
Greenspan, National Security Adviser Samuel Berger, Defense
Secretary William Cohen and Jesse Jackson, who is called in,
naturally, to negotiate Rubin's release.
</P>
<P>
   The video opens with NBC White House correspondent David Bloom
reporting that Rubin is being held hostage in Tokyo by retired
officials of the proud Japanese bureaucracy who demand that he say
something _ anything _ positive about the Japanese economy. It is
only a slight leap of the imagination, because last year Japanese
officials repeatedly complained that Rubin's searing criticism of
Japan's economic mismanagement was undercutting the Japanese
government, destabilizing its markets and contributing to the
ouster of a prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Cut to the White House, already in crisis management mode.
Rubin, according to intelligence reports relayed back to the CIA,
won't bend. Under intense questioning by the Japanese, he will only
repeat: ``My name is Bob Rubin. I am a U.S. citizen. Markets go up
and markets go down. I have nothing more to say.''
</P>
<P>
   An options memo is prepared for the president, but first there
must be a turf war between the White House national security team
and the White House economic team. Berger argues with Gene
Sperling, the chairman of the National Economic Council and the
producer of the video _ not about how to rescue the imprisoned
Treasury secretary, but over whose name goes on top of the memo.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is a foreign policy matter,'' Berger deadpans in his
office. ``Japan is a foreign country.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of this'' shoots back Sperling, playing out a battle
that occurs, presumably in slightly more subtle fashion, every week
in Washington. ``The demands the Japanese are making are
economic.'' Berger concludes the scene by saying, ``If we can't
agree on this, then let him fry.''
</P>
<P>
   (Sperling, in addition to his acting role, was the producer,
director and screenwriter. ``I don't want to be called the
president's economic adviser anymore,'' he said Friday. ``I do
film.'')
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the administration's arguments, the president's press
secretary is sent out to assure the world that ``we're working as a
team.'' Meanwhile, Clinton is trying to finish a crossword puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   Cohen appears in the Pentagon press room to offer up the entire
Navy budget, $82 billion, to pay for Rubin's hotel room bills at
the Okura Hotel, his luxurious prison across from the U.S. Embassy
in Tokyo. (It might take that much: Getting a shirt pressed at the
Okura runs about $20, and an informal lunch for two at the sushi
bar downstairs easily tops $250.) Greenspan finally appears to deal
with Japan's demands for America's gold reserves.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where would you like it delivered,'' he inquires.
</P>
<P>
   ``Alan Greenspan and Woody Allen have one thing in common,'' one
of Clinton's top economic advisers said Friday, assessing the Fed
chairman's acting abilities while insisting on anonymity. ``They
both know how to play only one character.''
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Jackson is appointed as a special envoy to mediate a
solution, and goes off to Japan talking about finding ``common
ground between the yen and the yang.'' When his mission is
accomplished, he declares: ``Free at last, free at last. Thank God
almighty, Bob's free at last.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed he is. Lawrence Summers, Rubin's longtime deputy, was
sworn in as the next Treasury secretary Friday in the Oval Office.
Summers has already received congratulations on his new post from
Japan's Ministry of Finance.
</P>
</TEXT>
