<SLUG> BC-LAMB-COLUMN03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Area hospitals challenge norms and break new ground
 &HT;    By Kevin Lamb
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTON, Ohio _ Later this summer, the for-profit Dayton Heart
Hospital on nonprofit Franciscan Medical Center's grounds will be
the country's first partnership of its kind. Before that was
arranged, Dayton was the first area with active opposition to a
MedCath heart hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Ours was the first market to force a Medicare HMO to change its
mind about leaving. That happened because Anthem Senior Advantage
was the first Medicare HMO to give six months' notice that it was
pulling out.
</P>
<P>
   While Cleveland's biggest hospital systems are fighting efforts
to measure their quality, employers and hospitals here are well on
their way toward establishing a report card. While hospitals and
the Internet often go together like ketchup and waffles, seven
Greater Dayton Area Hospital Association members use a budding
information network to help plug holes in the medical records of
people with more than one hospital.
</P>
<P>
   An even more high-falutin' network, the first of its kind
anywhere, enables a doctor at Kettering Medical Center to look at
the heart scans of a patient at Middletown Regional Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   While alternative medicine is dismissively branded a wave of the
future east of California, Franciscan Medical Center's growing
holistic center is among few in the country with alternative guru
Dr. Dean Ornish's heart program, and Children's and Miami Valley
hospitals practice the low-tech benefits of touch for premature
newborns. Instead of bucking the trend toward MedCath-type
specialty hospitals, local hospitals have established their own for
cancer at Good Samaritan, orthopedic surgery at Miami Valley,
obstetrics and gynecology at Southview, eye surgery at Kettering,
even primary care at Sycamore.
</P>
<P>
   A market of Dayton's size can't have nationally renowned centers
for treating grave illnesses, but it can find different ways of
reaching more people and keeping them healthy.
</P>
<P>
   That's a particularly valuable knack in this era of cataclysmic
changes in the way health care is delivered. As hospitals, health
plans, doctors and patients keep grumbling about new health-care
rules that are costing them all money and comfort, Dr. A. Patrick
Jonas calls all that confusion a great opportunity for innovations
in health care.
</P>
<P>
   ``It forces everybody to think differently,'' and as long as
change is inevitable, the advantage will go to those who change
sensibly, says Jonas. Founder of the new Center for Innovation in
Family and Community Health, Jonas himself is changing to a solo
practice in Beavercreek after his hospital-owned practice became
part of Kettering's cutbacks.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Healthy Communities (CHC) is a grass-roots
innovation that established one of the country's first networks of
community health advocates 10 years ago. Instead of groaning about
how many people fall through the cracks of the social safety net,
these advocates reach into those cracks to pull people back out.
They are neighborhood residents who know the community resources
that might keep downtrodden folks out of the emergency room.
</P>
<P>
   The center has helped set up programs to provide convenient
exercise programs in urban neighborhoods, support and treatment for
the generally ignored morbidly obese, and research and advocacy for
grandparents raising grandchildren. The grandparents program has
found many problems previously obscured by grandmothers' loving
hugs, one being that the state gives almost three times the
financial support to foster grandparents as to biological
grandparents.
</P>
<P>
   A Planned Parenthood program is showing how culture and
compassion can prevent teen-age pregnancy, and Miami Valley
Hospital is the country's only commercial site for a program for
turning around young mothers. Sinclair Community College is one of
three colleges nationally with credited courses in community-health
advocacy, Kettering is the only hospital that owns a school for
health professionals and Wright State was one of the first schools
where psychology students work with real patients from the time
they start grad school.
</P>
<P>
   Why here? Cooperation among social service agencies sure helps,
says CHC director Kate Cauley. So do the relative smallness of the
market and newness of the med school, she and Jonas agree.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're such a heartland city. It's the place where they test
whether corn flakes will sell with honey on them,'' Cauley says.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
