<SLUG> BC-HEALTHCARE-FRAUD-450&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TWO FOUND GUILTY OF HOSPITAL FRAUD CHARGES
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Fla.)  (jw) 
 By KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Two executives of the Columbia/HCA Healthcare Corp. were found
guilty Friday of defrauding federal health care programs through
the submission of bogus expense claims to the government in the
first jury verdicts stemming from the investigation of potential
wrongdoing at the company.
</P>
<P>
   The two executives, Jay Jarrell and Robert Whiteside, were found
guilty by a federal jury in Tampa, Fla., of six counts of fraud
each. A third executive, Michael Neeb, was acquitted, while the
jury was unable to reach a verdict for a fourth defendant, Carl
Lynn Dick.
</P>
<P>
   The four executives, all of whom have worked with Columbia/HCA's
Florida division, were charged with conspiring for more than a
decade to overstate expenses at one hospital, Fawcett Memorial
Hospital in Port Charlotte, Fla. Because of complex federal
reimbursement rules, such overstatements would illegally increase
compensation from programs like Medicare. As a result, the hospital
_ one of hundreds in the Columbia/HCA network _ defrauded Medicare
and other federal programs of more than $1.7 million, according to
the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   The trial of the four executives has been closely watched by
health care providers and law enforcement officials around the
country, because it has been widely viewed as a test run of the
government's theory of prosecution in the investigation of
Columbia/HCA, the world's largest health care company. While an
executive was acquitted, the verdict establishes that a crime did
indeed occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``The verdicts will have significant implications concerning how
health care providers do business with the government,'' said
Charles Wilson, the U.S. attorney for the Middle District of
Florida, whose office tried the case. ``Clearly, I think it will
have implications on the Columbia investigation.''
</P>
<P>
   Some lawyers in the case said Friday that they expected the
verdict would finally force both the Justice Department and
Columbia/HCA to reach a settlement of the potential charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has the chance of unlocking what, up until now, has been
a gridlock in resolving the case,'' said Stephen Meagher, a lawyer
who represents the whistle-blower who brought the Florida case to
the attention of the government. ``Columbia clearly must get the
message that the jury was unanimous that crime was committed here,
and that some of its executives participated in it.''
</P>
<P>
   But a Columbia/HCA executive said the company viewed the
implications of the verdict as limited. ``This is a very specific,
complex interest expense issue for one hospital,'' said Victor
Campbell, senior vice president with Columbia/HCA. ``But it does
not directly relate to the settlement discussions that we have with
the Department of Justice.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   In court records, federal investigators have said that in their
broader investigation of the company, they uncovered evidence that
similar frauds occurred at hospitals across the Columbia/HCA
system. As part of that investigation, teams of federal agents
seized documents in more than half a dozen states relating to the
company's cost reporting and other business practices.
</P>
<P>
   The criminal charges were among the highest ever brought in the
area of cost reporting, an arcane part of the federal Medicare
system that results in billions of dollars in federal expenditures
each year and hundreds of millions of dollars to Columbia/HCA
alone.
</P>
<P>
   Through the federal cost reporting system, Medicare partly
reimburses hospitals and other health care providers for certain
expenses. The cost reports also help determine total compensation
for outpatient services like home care.
</P>
<P>
   In its investigation, the government obtained critical evidence
from second sets of cost reports and work sheets maintained at
Columbia/HCA hospitals that contained significantly lower expenses
than were reported.
</P>
<P>
   In essence, the Columbia/HCA hospitals were reserving money in
the event that auditors challenged questionable expense claims;
once the period in which an audit could be conducted had passed,
the hospitals booked those reserves as revenue, people involved in
the case said.
</P>
<P>
   In this case, the government charged that the executives
conspired to misrepresent certain expenses that were related to
hospital administration as actually being costs for capital
improvements. Such improvements usually involve purchases of
medical equipment and other expenses that have a direct effect on
patient care.
</P>
<P>
   But administrative costs are reimbursed at a lower level than
capital expenses. By misrepresenting administrative costs as
capital costs, a hospital would illegally increase its federal
compensation.
</P>
<P>
   The expenses related to interest payments on a long-term debt
owed by Fawcett Memorial Hospital. In its reports, Fawcett
represented the debt as 100 percent related to capital
expenditures, the indictment says. But only 39 percent of the debt
involved capital costs; the rest was for administrative
expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   The misrepresentation in the cost reports resulted in the entire
interest payment's being reimbursed at the higher rate for capital
expenses, according to the indictment.
</P>
<P>
   Over the course of a year, that meant a significant amount of
money for the small Florida hospital. In 1992, the
misrepresentation resulted in an overpayment by Medicare of
$539,984, the indictment charges. The following year, the hospital
obtained $1,215,676 in overpayments from the same scheme, it says. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
