u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-RUN-PEACH03-COX     07-02 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUN-PEACH03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Murphy's law: Carrying on the legacy at Peachtree
 &HT;    By Michelle Hiskey
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sixteen-year-old Sarah Murphy on Sunday will run her
fourth consecutive Peachtree Road Race, not counting the first time
she traveled down the course. That happened in 1983, when her
mother Laura, one of Atlanta's top female runners at one time,
slipped a bathing suit and T-shirt over her rotund belly and, nine
months pregnant, ran the 6.2 mile course for fun. Sarah was born
the next day.
</P>
<P>
   On Sunday, mother will cheer daughter from their home in
northeast Atlanta. Laura Murphy, 47, can barely walk these days.
She has Lou Gehrig's disease, an illness that progressively steals
her ability to move her muscles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think I have to be her,'' said Sarah, a member of the
cross-country team at Woodward Academy, ``but I do think of me
running as a continuum of her.''
</P>
<P>
   Two decades ago, Laura took up running after graduating from
Emory's law school, and she loved to get up early in the morning
and join friends for a long run. She finished well in local races
and was asked to join the Atlanta Track Club's competitive team.
She eventually took charge of keeping the team organized as it
traveled around the country to races.
</P>
<P>
   She raced everything from 5Ks to marathons and owned a sub-40
minute time for a 10K, ranking among the five-fastest local women
at that distance. With a gregarious personality, she made a lot of
friends among other runners and was particularly thrilled to help
women who had never exercised much finally finish a race.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd have to go out of your way not to become a friend with
her,'' said Kirk Rosenbach, a masters runner and longtime friend of
the Murphys. ``Laura was so encouraging and always had a good word
for everyone and was very supportive.''
</P>
<P>
   Those are big reasons why Laura loved the Peachtree Road Race.
She ran in it until the late '80s, until she was no longer
competitive. She didn't like to run back in the pack, so she began
volunteering at the finish line. As one of the ``Welcome
Committee,'' she helped identify the top female runners and steered
them into the proper chute, a difficult task given the speed of the
first wave of finishers. ``We still don't have anyone who can
replace her,'' said Penny Kaiser of the track club. ``No one can do
the job Laura was able to do.''
</P>
<P>
   As Sarah grew up, Laura's running rubbed off on her. ``I
remember every single morning, my dad would make breakfast, and
then my mom would come in all sweaty'' from her morning run, Sarah
said.
</P>
<P>
   Laura took her along to local races. Sometimes, Sarah would do
the fun run.
</P>
<P>
   Laura, who has difficulty speaking, typed in an e-mail message,
``She was so sweet and cute (not that she isn't now) and I liked
having her along and my friends liked seeing her. When it became
apparent she had some natural ability, I was pretty happy about
that.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 4, 1995, a fellow finish-line volunteer at the Peachtree
noticed Laura's speech was a bit slurred. That started her on a
nearly year-long quest to find out what was happening to her body.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was so gradual that for us who were around her every day,
we didn't notice,'' said Rosenbach, who with Laura was part of a
group that met at 6 a.m. to run as many as 12 miles several times a
week. ``She had more trouble going up hills, and her breathing was
more labored. She got a little slower. It was very subtle, but
clearly, something was wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Around that time, Sarah decided to get serious about running,
and she set her sights on the 1996 Peachtree. She would train with
her mother, who refused to slow down to her daughter's pace.
</P>
<P>
   ``She would run back and forth across the street to stay at my
pace and I found it incredibly insulting,'' Sarah said. ``I would
think, 'I can't do this! I hate you!' It was a mother-daughter
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   But, she also said, ``I don't think I'd have ever done it if she
hadn't done it. I definitely think my interest in running came from
her.''
</P>
<P>
   In June, 1996, doctors at the Mayo Clinic told Laura she had
amyotrophic lateral sclerosis (ALS), also known as Lou Gehrig's
disease, a fatal neurological disorder that attacks nerve cells and
pathways in the brain to the spinal cord, cutting off the brain's
ability to start and control muscle movement.
</P>
<P>
   The last times she and Sarah ran together remain happy memories.
Laura remembers the Ekiden relay in the fall of 1996, handing off
to Sarah the Japanese sash that serves as a baton in that event.
Sarah recalled the Avon 5K, in which they ran and walked through
the pouring rain. ``I had no idea it would be the last one,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   In January, Laura retired from her job as a lawyer with the
Georgia Supreme Court. As her illness has progressed, her friends _
many runners among them _ have formed a group called ``Share the
Care'' to help her. Laura has relied on her running friends to help
Sarah, not only by ferrying her around before she got her driver's
license this week but also to help her with her running. When Sarah
got shin splints, Laura asked a family friend to show her exercises
to do to help it heal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am the luckiest woman alive. Or close to it,'' Laura said,
adding that she is grateful that she is not in pain and that she
can read and write. The disease does not affect her mind. ``I have
a wonderful husband and daughter. And extraordinary friends. And
many of those are running friends. My friends are a steady reminder
that I am not my disease.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
