<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 21:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7881 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-NYT &LR;      07-02 1230
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUDGET-SURPLUS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUDGET PRIMER: IS $1 TRILLION WINDFALL AS EPHEMERAL AS A BREEZE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICHARD W. STEVENSON with MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Where did Congress and the Clinton administration
find $1 trillion?
</P>
<P>
   The White House released a new analysis of the federal budget
this week that projected a windfall of more than $1 trillion over
the next 15 years on top of the previously anticipated $4.9
trillion cumulative surplus in that time. The Congressional Budget
Office then released a similar study that looked at the fiscal
picture over shorter periods and closely paralleled the
administration's estimates.
</P>
<P>
   For members of both parties, the news that the surplus was
continuing to swell beyond what had been projected just a few
months earlier was a little like winning the lottery jackpot and
then having Ed McMahon appear at the door the next morning with a
check from Publishers Clearing House. There is so much money on the
table that they do not quite know what to do with it.
</P>
<P>
   Rest assured that they will figure something out.
</P>
<P>
   But it is hard to contemplate the pile without wondering where
it came from and whether it is for real.
</P>
<P>
   The answers lie deep in the economy, with factors like business
efficiency and the huge gains being generated by Wall Street, and
deep in the government bureaucracy, where teams of analysts make
educated guesses about fiscal trends.
</P>
<P>
   Early each year the White House's Office of Management and
Budget and the Congressional Budget Office separately produce
estimates of what the government's fiscal condition will be over
the subsequent 10 or 15 years, based on their best assessments of
how much tax revenue the economy will generate and how much
spending current programs will require. Each of them then updates
its estimates each summer.
</P>
<P>
   The data that go into making the predictions rarely change
substantially within a single year. But because the U.S. economy is
so big, and because any changes affect the outlook for years to
come, even tiny changes can yield huge swings in revenue and
spending projections, and therefore in the size of projected
surpluses or, until recently, deficits. So algebra, not economics,
drove much of the improvement in the new forecasts. Chalk that up
to the magic of compound interest taught to every high school
student.
</P>
<P>
   Yet on the new projections hang all kinds of policy and
political decisions, like how big a tax cut the country can afford
and of what kind, how much money is available for education and
health care and what can be done to shore up Social Security and
Medicare.
</P>
<P>
   The debate over arcane budget matters is so intense, said
Rudolph Penner, a former director of the Congressional Budget
Office, because ``adjustments that are small to professional
economists can have immense political importance.''
</P>
<P>
   Take the most recent round of changes included in the
administration's economic forecast. They seem technical, even
arcane, and their link to federal budget surpluses might seem
tenuous. But they get at some fundamental improvements in the U.S.
economy and its ability to create the jobs and profits that
generate tax revenues. They include an increase in the
administration's estimate of growth in productivity, or how much
each worker can produce in a given period. When productivity
improves, so does the economy's ability to expand without inflation
_ and therefore to generate a steady increase in tax revenues.
</P>
<P>
   In its new analysis, the administration estimated that
productivity growth would be 1.6 percent annually through 2002, up
from 1.3 percent in the analysis it prepared in February. Over the
longer run, it estimated that productivity growth would slow
somewhat, to 1.4 percent annually, a figure that is still higher
than its previous long-range estimate of 1.3 percent annually. The
CBO made similar increases in its productivity estimates.
</P>
<P>
   The growth in productivity also helped fuel the administration's
new estimates of economic growth. From this year through 2004, the
administration is estimating the economy will expand by an annual
average of 2.5 percent, up from 2.2 percent in the administration's
last budget analysis in February. Moreover, the economy is already
bigger at this point than the administration or Congress had
predicted early this year.
</P>
<P>
   There is a hint of how the changing economy affects revenues _
and where the flood of new money is coming from _ in the experience
of the last few years. Most of the surge in revenues is coming from
individual income taxes. For next year, for example, the
administration now expects individual tax receipts to total $921
billion, up more than $21 billion since the February estimate.
Corporate income tax receipts are expected to come in somewhat
lower than previously anticipated, reflecting slower profit growth.
</P>
<P>
   One reason the individual tax take is rising is that more people
are working, and wages are rising at a healthy pace. But part of
the growth in individual income tax receipts stems directly or
indirectly from the long bull market on Wall Street. Individuals
are reaping substantial capital gains, and more and more people are
being compensated with stock or in ways that reflect the
performance of their employers' shares.
</P>
<P>
   The effect of the rising stock market can be clearly seen in
receipts from inheritance taxes levied on estates, many of which
contain big holdings of stocks and bonds that have appreciated in
value tremendously in recent years. The administration estimated
that estate and gift tax revenue next year would be $31.4 billion,
up from $27 billion in its February estimate.
</P>
<P>
   As for the accuracy of the surplus projections, there are two
issues: whether Congress or the administration is slanting its
estimates for political reasons and whether even the best
nonpartisan economists can predict fiscal results even a year
ahead, much less a decade or more.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties present the figures in ways that advance their
agendas. President Clinton has introduced 15-year projections this
year in part so he can allocate tax revenues from the distant
horizon to deal with long-term problems like Social Security while
leaving money available to deal with other issues sooner. Before
this year, no one had tried anything longer than a 10-year
forecast.
</P>
<P>
   But because there are two competing sets of projections, neither
the administration nor Congress could tinker much with its
projections and get away with it. In fact, they often come up with
remarkably similar results; their forecasts this week for the
cumulative 10-year surplus were within $20 billion of each other, a
tiny rounding error.
</P>
<P>
   That is not to say, however, that either of them is likely to be
correct. Their long-term forecasts have proved to be wildly
inaccurate, and even their short-term forecasts often prove to be
off by tens of billions of dollars. Three months ago, the
Congressional Budget Office predicted a government surplus of $111
billion this year. It recently increased the estimate to $120
billion.
</P>
<P>
   So no one can count on the projections. Still, the
administration and the CBO can claim that their assumptions and
projections are reasonable, which may be as good as it gets for the
purpose of policy decisions whose implications play out over
decades.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2123EDT &QL; 
