u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-HATCH-APPOINT     07-02 0643
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-HATCH-APPOINT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AGREES TO DEAL WITH HATCH ON FEDERAL JUDGE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Utah)  (mk) 
 By NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton has finally agreed to an unusual
bargain that obliges him to nominate as a federal judge a Utah
Republican who is vigorously opposed by several environmental
groups, congressional and administration officials said this week.
</P>
<P>
   In exchange, Sen. Orrin Hatch, R-Utah, the chairman of the
Senate Judiciary Committee, will remove his months-long blockade of
the president's judicial nominees, smoothing the way for at least
10 of those choices to be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   The officials who have been involved in the negotiations said
the Clinton administration recently sent the name of the Utah
candidate, Ted Stewart, to the American Bar Association and the FBI
to consider his qualifications, as is customary before a nomination
is announced.
</P>
<P>
   Under the agreement, if the bar association rates Stewart as
``qualified'' to serve as a federal trial judge and the FBI finds
no personal problems in his background, the nomination will go
forward.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, a lawyer who headed the Utah Natural Resources
Department, has been a harsh critic of the president's land-use
policies and politics and, in turn, has been opposed by major
environmental groups. He is now chief of staff to the state's
governor, Michael Leavitt, a Republican.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials defended the deal, saying they would
get more than an acceptable amount in return for nominating
Stewart, whom they acknowledged would not be chosen for the federal
bench by a Democratic president under ordinary circumstances.
</P>
<P>
   Hatch, a friend and admirer of Stewart, has been able as
chairman of the committee to block all of Clinton's judicial
choices until the White House made a decision on Stewart.
</P>
<P>
   If Stewart is nominated, he will face an intensive campaign to
block his confirmation from environmental lobbyists.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Wetstone, program director for the Natural Resources
Defense Council in Washington, said the nomination of Stewart would
be ``an unconscionable departure from this administration's record
on environmental and natural resources.''
</P>
<P>
   Wetstone said lobbyists for several environmental organizations
would oppose the nomination at any confirmation hearings, citing
their concern that Stewart, as a state official, demonstrated his
``opposition to the landmark laws that protect our natural
heritage.''
</P>
<P>
   The environmental groups opposing the nomination include the
Wilderness Society, the Sierra Club, the Natural Resources Defense
Council, Defenders of Wildlife, Friends of the Earth, the National
Environmental Trust and the Environmental Defense Fund.
</P>
<P>
   It remains unclear, however, if the removal of Hatch as an
obstacle to the administration's judicial choices means that they
will ultimately be confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Other Republicans on the Judiciary Committee and in the Senate
as a whole have been mobilizing to block Clinton's judicial
choices. Last week the committee only narrowly voted to recommend
to the full Senate the nomination of Marsha Berzon, a San Francisco
labor lawyer, to an appellate court seat, despite Hatch's support.
</P>
<P>
   And as Clinton moves closer to the end of his presidency,
Republicans are also seeking to keep as many judicial seats vacant
as possible in the hope that they might be filled by a Republican
in the White House after next year's election.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's nomination has proved an especially difficult issue
for Vice President Al Gore, who is seen by the environmental groups
as their greatest supporter in the administration.
</P>
<P>
   Gore, administration officials said, has insisted that if the
Stewart nomination goes forward, the White House must be able to
demonstrate that it received a good bargain in return.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
