u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-OBIT-MARS-NYT     07-02 0913
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-MARS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CANDY MAKER FORREST MARS DIES AT 95
</HEADLINE>
 
(ATTN: Va., Pa., Fla.)  (jw) 
 By CONSTANCE L. HAYS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Forrest Mars Sr., creator of the M&AMP;M, died Thursday at his home
in Miami. He was 95 years old.
</P>
<P>
   In a final nod to Mars' lifelong desire for secrecy, a
spokeswoman for his company, Mars Inc., refused to provide details
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   While Mars ardently sought to avoid the limelight, he routinely
ended up on lists of the wealthiest Americans. The company he
built, and turned over in 1973 to his sons, now sells some $20
billion worth of candy, snacks and pet food annually, according to
Joel Glenn Brenner, author of ``Emperors of Chocolate,'' which was
published earlier this year and chronicles Mars' life. Along with
M&AMP;M's, Milky Way, Snickers, Three Musketeers and Skittles, the
company, based in McLean, Va., owns the Combos, Kudos and Twix
brands; Uncle Ben's rice, and Kal-Kan and Pedigree pet food.
</P>
<P>
   Mars was often called a recluse, an eccentric or worse. When
Fortune magazine named him to its Business Hall of Fame in 1984, it
praised him as ``one of this century's most brilliant and
successful entrepreneurs,'' and derided him as ``an irascible candy
maker with a fetish for privacy'' and ``a driven personality given
to terrifying outbursts of temper.''
</P>
<P>
   Mars did not respond.
</P>
<P>
   Born in 1904, he inherited the privately held company from his
father, Frank, who developed the Milky Way candy bar in the 1920s
and quickly had a hit on his hands. Forrest Mars, however, is
credited with suggesting some ingredients for the candy.
</P>
<P>
   The two ended up squabbling, and Forrest Mars went to England,
where he marketed the Milky Way with some variations in the
formula. During World War II, he returned to the United States and
introduced a candy-coated chocolate that he named M&AMP;M's, based on a
popular European product.
</P>
<P>
   In 1964, he merged his company, known as Food Manufacturers,
which was responsible for, among other things, the invention of
Uncle Ben's converted rice, with Mars Inc. Fortune reported that at
his first formal meeting with Mars executives, he announced that he
was a religious man and then dropped to his knees, intoning, ``I
pray for Milky Way; I pray for Snickers.''
</P>
<P>
   Mars, who in 1922 had declared a goal of making his father's
already-successful candy company a global powerhouse, ran Mars with
a system of clear penalties and rewards. Employees were to keep
their desktops neat and clean; he once hurled a basket of papers
off a senior executive's desk, Ms. Brenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Managers who failed to meet growth and profit targets were
dismissed. To this day, employees who arrive on time all week
qualify for a 10 percent bonus in their paychecks, while those who
arrive late are docked 10 percent. Everyone, from the executive
suite on down, punches a time clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was legendary for his extreme temper, and his fanatical
behavior,'' Ms. Brenner said in an interview.
</P>
<P>
   That temper and that behavior could be exhibited upon the
discovery of a less than perfect Mars product. ``He would call up
sales associates in the middle of the night if he found a packet of
M&AMP;M's where the `M' wasn't printed exactly in the middle of the
candy, and he would order the candy recalled,'' Ms. Brenner said.
</P>
<P>
   Mars is also credited with coming up with a processing method
for rice that extended its shelf life, simplified its cooking and
increased its nutritional value. He marketed the rice as Uncle
Ben's. At one point he decided that people could be persuaded to
buy food specially processed for their pets, Ms. Brenner said, and
thus created the pet food category.
</P>
<P>
   His inspiration for M&AMP;M's was a lentil-shaped, candy-coated
chocolate that he saw soldiers eating while on a visit behind the
lines during the Spanish Civil War. He was traveling with a member
of the Rowntree family, Ms. Brenner said, and Rowntree went on to
make Smarties, a candy similar to M&AMP;M's.
</P>
<P>
   The name came about because, with World War II under way and
America's involvement only a matter of time, Mars felt he needed
help with the product, especially if sugar and chocolate were to be
rationed. So he approached William F.R. Murrie, then the president
of Hershey, and they agreed to become partners. Hence the M&AMP;M
stands for ``Mars and Murrie,'' according to Ms. Brenner. Today,
Hershey and Mars are archrivals in the American candy market.
</P>
<P>
   Although he officially retired in 1973, and began unaffiliated
businesses selling boxes of chocolates and plant food, among other
things, he continued to look in on the business and to call his
sons on the carpet for any problems he detected; until recently the
sons were co-presidents of the company. This, too, could lead to
extreme behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has continued to call and harass them when he saw things
that were not to his liking,'' Ms. Brenner said. When the company's
performance in 1992 disappointed him, she said, he arranged a
meeting with the chairman of Nestle SA to orchestrate a buyout.
</P>
<P>
   A series of trusts that control the ownership of the company
prevented his three children from selling the company until his
death, Ms. Brenner said. Now, she added, the company may well go
public.
</P>
<P>
   His survivors include his sons, Forrest Jr., who, Ms. Brenner
said, stepped down as co-president in April, and John, who remains
president; his daughter, Jacqueline Mars Vogel, and 10
grandchildren. His wife, Audrey, died in 1989.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2129EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0331 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 21:32 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7888 &Cx1f; taf-z
s f &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BEAR-STEARNS-HARRITON     07-02 1006
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BEAR-STEARNS-HARRITON-ART-3TAKES-$ADV04-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A BEAR STEARNS MANAGER, HUMBLED BY THE COMPANY HE KEPT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Attn: N.Y., Calif.)   (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.)  
 (FOR RELEASE SUNDAY, JULY 4)  
 (af)  
 By GRETCHEN MORGENSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Profane and imperious, Richard Harriton has for two decades run
Wall Street's biggest clearing operation, the Bear Stearns
Securities Corp., with an iron hand. A tough guy up from the
streets of Brooklyn, N.Y., his us-against-them view of the world
meshed nicely, associates say, with Bear Stearns's macho culture
and obsession with the bottom line.
</P>
<P>
   But Harriton apparently failed to recognize that when the
``them'' shifted a few years ago, from his competition on Wall
Street to securities regulators and prosecutors, the game changed.
</P>
<P>
   As authorities increased their scrutiny of the small, dubious
brokerage firms among Harriton's clients, he dug in his heels. And
the clearing house's parent, the Bear Stearns Companies, with as
much as a third of its revenues riding on Harriton's business,
stood behind him.
</P>
<P>
   Now, though, Bear Stearns is waving the white flag. On Monday,
the firm agreed in principle to settle securities fraud charges
that the Securities and Exchange Commission has been preparing to
bring against Harriton's unit.
</P>
<P>
   The case concerns Bear Stearns' dealings with A.R. Baron, a
brokerage firm that Manhattan prosecutors labeled a criminal
enterprise after it failed in 1996, leaving investors with $75
million in losses.
</P>
<P>
   And Harriton, who as recently as five months ago told a
colleague that he thought the worst of his troubles were behind
him, is on his own. Privately, top Bear Stearns executives are
toning down their full-throated defenses of his conduct.
</P>
<P>
   His lawyer is trying to negotiate a separate settlement with the
SEC. Meanwhile, two criminal investigations continue into the
unit's business and Harriton's management of it. According to a
colleague, the imposing 6-foot-3 banker has lost his optimism _ and
30 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   More important, the clearing business _ the highly profitable
backwater of Wall Street where the paperwork of customers' trades
is processed and where small brokerages turn for day-to-day
financing _ will never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   New rules have already been instituted by the SEC, requiring
every clearing firm to more closely police its brokerage firm
customers. These and additional rules on the drawing board will
almost certainly cut profits for the clearing firms, because of the
additional staff that must be hired.
</P>
<P>
   The changes will most likely be greatest at Bear Stearns, which
says it clears 10 percent of all trades on the New York Stock
Exchange _ more than any other firm, but down from 12 percent two
years ago, when the government investigations first came to light.
</P>
<P>
   Settlements like the one proposed in the Baron case typically
call for bringing in an outside consultant to make sure that a firm
stays on the straight and narrow. For a brokerage firm like Bear
Stearns, which prides itself on its aggressive, entrepreneurial
manner, that may sting much more than the $5 million fine and $20
million in restitution to A.R. Baron customers it has offered to
pay. The settlement still must be approved by the SEC.
</P>
<P>
   The road that brought Bear Stearns to the SEC's bargaining table
last week has many twists and turns, but it inexorably leads back
to Harriton, 64. How could a smart man have made the series of bad
judgments that put his firm and his career at peril? Why did he
agree to clear trades for some of the most troubled brokerage firms
in America _ not just A.R. Baron, but also Rooney Pace and Stratton
Oakmont, all of which have been closed down? Why did he give these
firms Bear Stearns' imprimatur, even as securities regulators were
turning up the heat on them?
</P>
<P>
   Harriton's lawyer, Howard Wilson of Rosenman &AMP; Colin, declined
to comment on his client's negotiations with the SEC and said
Harriton would also have no comment. Harriton has maintained
throughout the investigations that he has done nothing wrong.
</P>
<P>
   A Bear Stearns spokeswoman also declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   Although largely unknown to the public, Harriton is a big man on
Wall Street, where he has remained the president of Bear Stearns
Securities throughout the government inquiries, operating _ as is
typical at the firm, according to former employees, customers and
others who know it well _ with near autonomy.
</P>
<P>
   As the clearing operation grew in size and profitability over
his two-decade stewardship, Harriton became even more prized at the
firm, the nation's fourth-largest publicly traded securities
concern. He was elected to the board of directors in 1989. And
though he left the board in 1997, when its size was reduced, he
remains on the firm's powerful management and compensation
committee, which meets weekly and recommends, among other things,
how much should be paid to employees below the level of senior
managing director.
</P>
<P>
   People who have worked with Harriton over the years as
associates or customers invariably describe him as arrogant,
pompous and tough. He bullied customers and upbraided his staff,
even once screamed expletives at a junior member of a regulatory
team assigned to watch over a client firm, according to a person
who witnessed the tongue-lashing.
</P>
<P>
   Many people who know him say that Harriton could never quite
outgrow the street-player persona he developed during a
working-class childhood in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   Although he lives on Manhattan's Upper East Side in a penthouse
with sumptuous river views, Harriton, the son of a bakery supply
salesman, ``couldn't get out of the old neighborhood,'' according
to one former associate. ``He didn't graduate to the big leagues
and learn that he's got to protect himself and his firm. He didn't
care who he dealt with, just as long as they paid the clearing
charges.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Another person who knows Harriton characterizes him this way:
``He divides the world into friends and nonfriends. He has his
friends from the old days, and he has his allies. And then he has
the rest of the world.''
</P>
<P>
   And so Bear Stearns finds itself not only in settlement talks
with the SEC, but also under investigation by Robert M. Morgenthau,
the Manhattan District Attorney, who prosecuted the Baron case.
Federal prosecutors in the office of Mary Jo White, United States
Attorney for the Southern District of New York, are also
investigating Bear Stearns, in its role as clearing firm for
Sterling Foster, a defunct New York brokerage firm.
</P>
<P>
   A federal grand jury indicted two men closely associated with
Sterling Foster last fall on charges that they and the firm
manipulated the stocks of six small companies it underwrote in the
mid-1990s, bilking investors out of $100 million. Both men have
denied wrongdoing; the case is pending.
</P>
<P>
   In the days before the A.R. Baron mess, Bear Stearns approached
its clearing business with a can-do attitude. Advertisements for
its services read, ``We clear almost anything for almost anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   And Harriton embodied that spirit. One brokerage firm executive
recalled a meeting a few years ago of a committee of the National
Association of Securities Dealers on which Harriton sat. Pending
before the committee was whether to bring a disciplinary case
against one of Bear Stearns's client firms. Rather than recuse
himself from the vote, Harriton voted against initiating the
proceeding.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns now says it clears trades for 2,400 firms, up from
725 in 1987. Most are hedge fund operators and professional
traders. The remainder are mainly smaller firms dealing with
individual investors.
</P>
<P>
   These clients, known in the industry as introducing firms, have
several reasons for clearing their trades through a larger
brokerage like Bear Stearns. The relationship allows a smaller firm
to operate without putting up as much capital as would be required
if it processed its own trades.
</P>
<P>
   And the administrative duties that a clearing firm provides _
like sending out trade confirmations and customer statements _ are
headaches that many small firms are happy to farm out.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the smaller the firm, the more likely that it will
want its customers to know their transactions are backed by a
powerhouse like Bear Stearns.
</P>
<P>
   For clearing firms, the business is a gold mine. They require
introducing firms to put up a deposit, usually around $250,000.
They also levy a so-called ticket charge, generally $10 to $25, on
each trade that the introducing firm conducts for its clients.
</P>
<P>
   Clearing firms also charge interest, typically 1 percent a
month, on the margin loans that introducing firms make to their
customers.
</P>
<P>
   The clearing firms also have access to the cash that sits in the
accounts of the introducing brokers' customers, on which they pay
only nominal interest. And Bear Stearns, like other clearing firms,
requires that its clearing customers funnel all their trades to its
trading desks. Another brokerage firm would pay perhaps 2 cents a
share for this order flow, but the clearing firm gets it gratis.
</P>
<P>
   All this business has historically come with little downside.
The risk that an introducing firm might fail, leaving the clearing
firm exposed, can virtually be eliminated, if the clearing firm
uses its access to its clients' books to keep a careful watch over
their operations.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, until recently, clearing firms have generally not been
held legally responsible for problems _ like unauthorized trades _
experienced by their clients' customers. Instead, those have been
the legal responsibility of the introducing firms.
</P>
<P>
   Although the law has not changed on this issue, the regulators'
view of a clearing firm's responsibilities has shifted.
</P>
<P>
   ``The cases have been very kind to the clearing firms over the
years,'' said Norman S. Poser, a professor at Brooklyn Law School
specializing in securities regulation. ``I think that is changing
and more responsibility is being placed on clearing firms. To some
extent, that is coming out of the A.R. Baron situation.''
</P>
<P>
   Only the old, nonjudgmental approach to the clearing business
could explain some of the relationships Harriton established for
Bear Stearns, putting a Wall Street giant in business with some of
Wall Street's most marginal players.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first clearing customers he brought to the firm when
he joined in the late 1970s was Rooney, Pace, whose co-founder,
Randolph Pace, remains one of Harriton's closest friends.
</P>
<P>
   That would not be remarkable, except for the fact that Pace has
been censured by regulators three times. The NASD expelled Rooney
Pace in 1987, saying it manipulated securities. And though Pace was
barred from the securities industry, prosecutors say that he
secretly controlled Sterling Foster, whose trades Bear Stearns
cleared until the firm closed its doors in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   Pace now is awaiting trial on securities fraud charges in the
Sterling Foster case. He did not return phone calls seeking
comment.
</P>
<P>
   Harriton's son Matthew, meanwhile, is an officer or investor in
three companies that prosecutors say have ties to Pace, though they
are not known to figure in any investigations: the Embryo
Development Corp., Superior Supplements and the Phlo Corp. Embryo
Development, which markets biomedical devices, was underwritten by
Sterling Foster. Superior Supplements, a maker of dietary
supplements, and the Phlo Corp., a beverage maker, are companies
whose investors include Pace or a company controlled by him. The
stocks of all three companies trade for pennies a share.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Matthew Harriton, who has not been accused of any wrongdoing,
did not return phone calls seeking comment.
</P>
<P>
   It was the failure of another of Harriton's client firms, A.R.
Baron, that opened wide the door to the clearing world.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns had cleared trades for A.R. Baron back in 1992, but
Harriton stopped doing business with the firm that summer.
According to a former Baron executive, Harriton was worried that an
initial public offering that A.R. Baron was planning to underwrite
for a San Diego-area drug maker called Cypros Pharmaceutical would
flop. That might have left Bear Stearns vulnerable, if Baron's
deposit did not cover losses resulting from the underwriting.
</P>
<P>
   Yet in July 1995, Harriton welcomed the firm back into the Bear
Stearns fold. He agreed to lend the capital that A.R. Baron needed
to operate _ despite the fact that the firm was unable even to
secure an Exxon credit card, according to records that became
public when Baron later went bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   Bear Stearns' reunion with A.R. Baron seemed especially odd,
given that it came just three days after Baron settled a case with
the NASD in which regulators accused it of executing trades for
customers at unfair and unreasonable prices. A.R. Baron paid $1.5
million in fines and restitution to settle the charges; the firm's
chairman, Andrew Bressman, personally paid $35,000.
</P>
<P>
   Almost immediately, A.R. Baron got into trouble again. In
September 1995, the firm's capital fell below the minimum required
by regulators. Later that month, a Baron customer notified Bear
Stearns of unauthorized trading in its accounts _ a complaint that
Bear Stearns ignored, according to an arbitration case that the
customer has lodged against the firm.
</P>
<P>
   In October, Baron's capital again fell below the required
levels. This time, Bear Stearns injected $1.1 million of its own
capital into Baron, keeping it afloat.
</P>
<P>
   The SEC ordered A.R. Baron to halt operations in May 1996. The
firm filed for bankruptcy protection that July. The Manhattan
District Attorney's office convened a grand jury to investigate the
failure in January 1997.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost certainly decisions by Harriton that kept A.R.
Baron in business as long as it was. According to a former Baron
executive, well before the firm failed, one of Harriton's top
lieutenants wanted to again cut the smaller firm's ties to Bear
Stearns. Harriton said no _ a decision he very likely regrets now.
</P>
<P>
   If Harriton leaves Bear Stearns as a result of the A.R. Baron
fiasco, his likely replacement will be Richard R. Lindsey, the
former director of market regulation at the SEC. Lindsey joined
Bear Stearns in January as a senior managing director and No. 2
person at the clearing subsidiary. Trained as an engineer, Lindsey
is said to be a aficionado of technology.
</P>
<P>
   People who know the clearing world say that it is changing from
a business based on relationships to one where technological
prowess drives the bargain. A world where Lindsey may fit better
than Harriton.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2132EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
