<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7901 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-POLICE-REPORT-2TAK     07-02 0909
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-REPORT-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIAS INFECTS N.J. STATE POLICE, WHITMAN ADMITS 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID KOCIENIEWSKI   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Three months after acknowledging that New Jersey
state troopers systematically discriminated against black and
Hispanic drivers, Gov. Christie Whitman conceded Friday that the
police force had also mistreated its own employees by tolerating a
culture of racial discrimination and sexual harassment.
</P>
<P>
   Saying there was evidence of ``disparate treatment'' of some
troopers by their co-workers and supervisors, the governor released
a report by the attorney general blaming the state police
leadership for failing to aggressively recruit female and minority
troopers and awarding promotions and choice assignments to white
male officers in disproportionate numbers.
</P>
<P>
   The report also cited evidence that police commanders frequently
did nothing to deter or punish white male officers who openly used
racial slurs or crude sexual terms in talking about co-workers
while on the job.
</P>
<P>
   The report did not mention any commanders or other officials by
name, but the new attorney general, John Farmer, held out the
possibility that some individuals would be disciplined in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   The report also mentioned the Internal Affairs Bureau of the
Division of State Police, saying troopers had complained that it
had been used by commanders to retaliate against officers who had
filed discrimination complaints. The bureau's credibility has
become so tarnished that some female and minority troopers no
longer bother to report discrimination, the report said.
</P>
<P>
   In releasing the report, the governor said she had ordered the
attorney general to reform the division by devising new guidelines
for promotions, revamping Internal Affairs and reshuffling the
division's command structure. Most significant, Whitman said she
would assign an assistant attorney general to monitor complaints by
troopers and help reshape a state police force that has
historically operated as a quasi-independent entity.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be nice to be able to narrow it all down and say,
`One person is responsible, and it happened over a short period of
time,''' the governor said. ``This is something that has been,
frankly, happening over the course of state police history.''
</P>
<P>
   Civil rights leaders criticized the report, saying Whitman was
belatedly trying put a favorable political spin on a problem she
can no longer dismiss.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Al Sharpton, who has scheduled a demonstration on the
Atlantic City Expressway for Saturday to protest the governor's
response to discrimination complaints, said the report would do
little to convince minority residents that the state police would
be forced to enact meaningful reforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Whitman: Her administration now admits to the
practice of racial profiling as well as racism in hiring and
promotion,'' Sharpton said at a news conference in Manhattan. ``She
was the one in denial, and we were correct all along.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Reginald Jackson, director of the Black Ministers
Council of New Jersey, said he was disappointed that the governor
stopped short of calling for the creation of a civilian review
board to monitor the Division of State Police.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. Justice Department has been investigating
discrimination complaints against the force for three years, and
Jackson said the attorney general's report had confirmed his
resolve to ask the federal government to install an outside monitor
to oversee the state police.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson also complained that the report failed to name anyone
who had tolerated or participated in discrimination or harassment.
And he said the report's description of unchecked racism within the
force had convinced him that Whitman must find someone from outside
the division to fill the vacant position of state police
superintendent. The previous superintendent, Col. Carl Williams,
was fired by the governor in February after making insensitive
comments about black and Hispanic people.
</P>
<P>
   ``This report, weak as it is, documents the failure of
leadership in the New Jersey State Police,'' Jackson said. ``If
they are going to make no personnel changes in that leadership,
then this report isn't worth the paper it's printed on.''
</P>
<P>
   Whitman has told aides that she is considering an outsider to
reform the division, and has reportedly offered the job to one
outside candidate who has not made a decision yet. But she has
faced intense pressure from within the state Senate, which has the
power to reject her nomination, because many senators want the
governor to promote someone from within the ranks.
</P>
<P>
   The report was the result of an investigation of the state
police that Whitman had ordered in response to complaints of
discrimination, which have dominated New Jersey's political agenda
since troopers shot and wounded three unarmed minority men during a
traffic stop in April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   The shootings brought waves of criticism from New Jersey
residents and elected officials, and since then 12 troopers have
filed lawsuits against the state claiming racial and sexual
discrimination. The governor ordered the attorney general to
evaluate the force, and three months ago, she became the first
state official ever to acknowledge that New Jersey troopers had
engaged in racial profiling _ the illegal tactic of singling out
drivers based on the color of their skin.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
