<P>
   &UR; RETAIL  &LR; _ Scheuer Linens, just off of Union Square, is an
old-fashioned business that maintains highly personal relationships
with its customers as it sells San Francisco's elite $1,000 bed
sets and hand-embroidered napkins. The business was founded by
Rosel and Samuel Scheuer, who fled Hitler's Germany in the 1930s.
By Carol Emert
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0340 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7903 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NJ-POLICE-REPORT-2NDT     07-02 0519
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-POLICE-REPORT-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 TRENTON: their skin.  
<TEXT>
<P>
   As she released the attorney general's findings Friday, the
governor avoided using the word ``discrimination,'' but offered
statistics showing that women now make up just 3 percent of the
2,700-member force and that 14 percent of the troopers are black or
Hispanic.
</P>
<P>
   Minority representation on the force has dropped significantly
since 1992, when the Justice Department ended a 17-year consent
decree that had forced the state police to hire more women and
members of minority groups.
</P>
<P>
   The report also noted the high number of troopers who have filed
lawsuits charging a similar pattern of discrimination, racial slurs
and hostility at work, but it offered few specific examples.
However, Phil Moran, a lawyer who represents many of the minority
troopers who have sued, said the attorney general's office had
reviewed court papers from several of his clients.
</P>
<P>
   Moran said the clients whose complaints were reviewed included:
female troopers who said their commander had referred to them using
vulgar descriptions of female genitalia, black officers who said
they had been frequently demeaned by racial slurs, and a Hispanic
officer who said he had been verbally harassed and abandoned on a
roadway after having been stripped down to his underwear by fellow
troopers.
</P>
<P>
   Troopers' mistrust of their leadership has become so widespread
that last month 65 female and minority officers formed their own
fraternal organization to defend themselves against any retaliatory
disciplinary charges.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you hear what these people have been through, it's hard
to believe we're even talking about this century,'' said Moran, who
represents the minority troopers' association.
</P>
<P>
   Although the report did not identify commanders who were likely
to be disciplined, one administration official, who asked not to be
identified, said the attorney general's office was still reviewing
some of the most serious complaints against supervisors who turned
a blind eye to discrimination. If the charges are substantiated,
the supervisors could face disciplinary charges or dismissal.
</P>
<P>
   But Whitman said the fundamental purpose of the report was to
chart a path toward reforming the state police, not to single out
individual offenders.
</P>
<P>
   The governor said she would allocate money for the division to
buy computers to track complaints against officers and act as an
early warning system against those with repeated disciplinary
problems.
</P>
<P>
   The division will also be compelled to recruit more minority and
female cadets, Farmer said.
</P>
<P>
   The state police will also establish a toll-free telephone
number to accept complaints of trooper misconduct and open three
walk-in centers outside state police barracks so civilians can file
reports in person.
</P>
<P>
   ``The state police risk their lives each and every day to keep
us safe, and in carrying out their work need our full support,''
the governor said.
</P>
<P>
   ``That is why we cannot rest until we bolster the public's
trust. The report we're releasing today is a first step in renewing
that trust.''
</P>
</TEXT>
