</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-HAWKS-GUARDS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Coles quickly gets to point of his many roles for Hawks
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ A couple of stories about point guard Bimbo Coles,
acquired Tuesday by the Hawks in the package deal for Mookie
Blaylock:
</P>
<P>
   Coles, who made his first visit to Atlanta on Friday as a member
of the Hawks, was the primary playmaker last season at Golden
State, which fell just short of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   One night in April, Coles played 25 minutes against Dallas and
scored two points. A radio reporter asked Coles how he thought he
played.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we win?'' Coles asked him.
</P>
<P>
   The reporter answered, ``Yes.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Then I played great,'' Coles said.
</P>
<P>
   A week or so later, the Warriors went up against runaway Pacific
Division winner Portland. Coles scored 16 of his 24 points in the
fourth quarter when the Warriors overcame an eight-point deficit
and scored on their final 12 possessions.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, he noted that the two games reflect his philosophy.
He will do whatever is required to win.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dive to get loose balls. Ask me to score. Take a charge. Pass
to Smitty and Dikembe. Whatever it takes to win games. I hate to
lose. You will see that. I don't take losing very well.''
</P>
<P>
   At age 31, with nine years in the league, Coles knows too much
about losing. His Golden State teams went through coaching changes
and roster upheaval, along with the Latrell Sprewell choking
incident, which tore the squad apart in the fall of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   At his previous layover, Miami ran a revolving door out of the
locker room, allowing players like Steve Smith, Grant Long, Rony
Seikaly and Glen Rice to leave.
</P>
<P>
   This is Coles' third stop. ``A good trade for me,'' he called
it. ``For one thing, I'm coming to a team and organization that I
think are committed to winning. I'm working for a Hall of Fame
coach in Lenny Wilkens. I can't wait to play for him. We talked for
10, 15 minutes, and I got excited. Plus, I'm on the same team with
great players like Dikembe Mutombo and Steve Smith.''
</P>
<P>
   No one ever confused Coles with greatness. But he has been a
scrappy player throughout his career. ``I can't think of another
guard who is better on defense,'' Miami Heat coach Pat Riley said
before trading Coles to the Warriors in the Tim Hardaway deal in
1996.
</P>
<P>
   Coles said he expects to contribute to his new team, even with
the Hawks drafting point guard Jason Terry out of Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lenny told me every position is open, that you earn your
minutes and earn your role. I'm going in to earn my spot.''
</P>
<P>
   He likes the role of mentor to Terry and lightly-experienced
Anthony Johnson. ``I've always wanted to coach. (This is an)
opportunity to work on those skills,'' he said. ``It's good to be
around young guys.''
</P>
<P>
   Coles was conducting a youth basketball camp in Lewisburg,
W.Va., where he lives, when he awakened to news of the trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I called the guy who helps me train,'' Coles said, ``and told
him, 'Let's go to the gym _ right now.'''
</P>
<P>
   Hawks notes
</P>
<P>
   With the 52nd pick of the draft, the Hawks took Roberto
Bergeson, a 6-foot-6 guard from Boise State, then revealed that
they had been acting as a surrogate for the Portland Trail Blazers.
Officially, the Hawks did it for ``cash considerations.'' However,
the Portland Oregonian reported those considerations as $500,000.
Going from one of the world's wealthiest men, Paul Allen, to
another, Ted Turner, that's a nice token of thanks. That sum, by
the way, pays 71 percent of Dion Glover's rookie salary of
$700,000. ... Hawks rookies and free agents will be at Life
University for practice and games on July 12. Young veterans
Roshown McLeod and Johnson will participate. Former Hawk Ivano
Newbill also has been invited. ... When the games start July 15,
three of the top rookie point guards from the draft could be
playing _ the Hawks' Terry (No. 10), Cleveland's Andre Miller (No.
8) and Charlotte's Baron Davis (No. 3). In addition, Orlando will
bring Corey Magette, the 13th pick acquired from Seattle.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
