<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Cope can't qualify for 7th time in 16 races
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Daytona Beach, Fla. _ Derrike Cope's tough season got even worse
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Cope, the 1990 Daytona 500 winner, failed to qualify for
tonight's Pepsi 400 at Daytona International Speedway. It was
Cope's seventh DNQ of the season and his third in the last six
events.
</P>
<P>
   Cope, 41, is 42nd in points and hasn't been higher than 40th
since finishing 18th in the season-opening Daytona 500.
</P>
<P>
   Robert Pressley, who is 40th in points, was the only other
Winston Cup regular who failed to qualify. Also missing the race
were Hut Stricklin, Ken Bouchard and Stanton Barrett.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin Lepage made the race, but he lost nine starting spots
because of an oversight. Lepage's No. 16 Ford team missed Friday's
5:35 p.m. deadline to notify NASCAR officials they were standing on
their time from Thursday night's first-round qualifying, which
would have put him in the 31st starting position.
</P>
<P>
   Since Lepage missed the deadline, NASCAR officials ruled that he
had to drive in second-round qualifying. Lepage elected not to run
and took the fourth of seven provisionals and will start 40th.
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Burton, who is fourth in points and only 240 behind leader
Dale Jarrett, also didn't attempt to qualify Friday. Burton didn't
complete his two qualifying laps Thursday after the engine in his
No. 99 Ford blew up. He took the first provisional and will start
37th.
</P>
<P>
   Here's looking at you
</P>
<P>
   Jerry Nadeau's No. 9 Ford is sporting a new paint job for
tonight's race, with pro wrestling star Bill Goldberg painted on
the hood. Nadeau, whose primary sponsor is the Cartoon Network,
will also have an Atlanta Braves paint job later this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an honor to have your likeness on the hood of a car,''
Goldberg said. ``I've had a lot of dreams come true during the last
couple of years and this is one of the them. The next one is
driving. I've got to talk to NASCAR about the weight limit.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcis running strong
</P>
<P>
   Dave Marcis, who missed last week's race at Sears Point because
of injuries suffered in a crash at Pocono on June 20, starts 22nd
tonight.
</P>
<P>
   Marcis, 58, will attempt to break Richard Petty's records for
most laps and miles completed in the Pepsi 400. Marcis, who has the
most career starts at Daytona with 60, needs to complete 133 laps
and 372.5 miles to surpass Petty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not ready to retire as a driver,'' Marcis said. ``I enjoy
racing as much as anyone else.''
</P>
<P>
   Running strong in front
</P>
<P>
   Jeff Gordon became only the seventh driver to win the Daytona
500 from the pole on Feb. 14. In the previous 40 races at Daytona
in July, the front-row starters have accounted for 11 victories.
The last driver to win the Pepsi 400 from the pole was Dale
Earnhardt in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt fastest in practice
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt, who finished second in the Daytona 500, had the
fastest average speed in Friday's practice. Earnhardt covered the
2.5-mile oval in 47.371 seconds, an average speed of 189.99 mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``I noticed Earnhardt's car has spent most of the time covered
up,'' Bobby Labonte said. ``That's a good sign _ for him.''
</P>
<P>
   Sterling Marlin was second-fastest at 189.865 mph, followed by
Bobby Hamilton, Jerry Nadeau and Jeremy Mayfield.
</P>
<P>
   Among the drivers struggling were Jeff Burton (32nd), Kyle Petty
(37th) and Ernie Irvan (42nd).
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
