<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Pepsi 400 a prime test for NASCAR
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   DAYTONA BEACH, Fla. _ Earlier this season, NASCAR retained
television negotiating rights from track promoters, and it will
package all of its Winston Cup races to a major network when the
current contracts expire.
</P>
<P>
   While the new deal, which could be worth as much as $500
million, won't be announced for several months, NASCAR executives
could get a good gauge tonight of just how valuable their sport is
to network television.
</P>
<P>
   Barring inclement weather, tonight's Pepsi 400 at Daytona
International Speedway will be the first auto race broadcast live
in prime time on network television.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, which will televise tonight's race, was supposed to
broadcast last year's Pepsi 400 in prime time, but the event was
postponed until Oct. 17 because of area wildfires. Lights weren't
installed above the storied track until May 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's another milestone for motor sports, for NASCAR, and it's
certainly a compliment to the sport,'' NASCAR president Bill France
Jr. said.
</P>
<P>
   CBS was the first network to broadcast a NASCAR race live in
1979, when the Daytona 500 drew a 10.5 rating, its highest rating
ever.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until that time, the races had been joined in progress, maybe
with taped highlights of the first half, if that,'' France said.
``Most of the broadcasters didn't know if they could keep the
attention for 3 1/2 hours. The fear was always (cars just going)
'round and 'round.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS's coverage of this year's Daytona 500 drew a national rating
of 9.6, its highest rating since 1987 and a 12 percent increase
from last year. CBS and NASCAR officials are looking for a rating
around 5.0 tonight since ratings on Saturday are usually the lowest
of the week.
</P>
<P>
   That figure would match the 5.0 rating the Indianapolis 500 drew
on ABC on May 30, the lowest rating ever when the open-wheel race
was run on a Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I was 18 years old, I'd be on a date (Saturday) night,
hopefully,'' NASCAR driver Bobby Labonte said. ``But that was
before I had this life. Seriously, I think it's great the race is
on prime time.''
</P>
<P>
   CBS's coverage certainly won't be lacking in storylines.
Two-time defending Winston Cup champ Jeff Gordon will attempt to
become only the fifth driver to win both events at Daytona in the
same season. Gordon, who starts 11th, also would become the fifth
driver with consecutive victories in the Pepsi 400.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Nemechek and Ricky Rudd, ranked 37th and 38th in points,
respectively, will start on the front row.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
