<SLUG> BC-SOC-CUP-SEMIS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tension mounting for U.S.
 &HT;    By Wendy Parker
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALO ALTO, Calif. _ How can the United States and Brazil
possibly top their scintillating wins in the Women's World Cup
quarterfinals? By playing each other, which is exactly how the draw
has worked out for Sunday's semifinal at Stanford Stadium that
could escalate the tensions even higher.
</P>
<P>
   Given the way they had to pull out those victories on Thursday,
and the success of their high-powered offenses thus far in the
tournament, such fireworks are virtually assured. The Americans
held off Germany 3-2 at Jack Kent Cooke Stadium after trailing 2-1
at halftime, then watched Brazil squander a 3-0 lead before winning
4-3 in overtime against Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
   ``We weren't very good against Germany,'' U.S. coach Tony
DiCicco said. ``I give Germany a lot of credit, but it was not a
classic performance for the U.S.''
</P>
<P>
   The four teams largely predicted to reach this point have done
so. On Sunday night in Foxboro, Mass., defending champion Norway
meets powerful China in a matchup of the Americans' principal
rivals.
</P>
<P>
   Brazil, which finished fourth in the 1996 Olympics, is trying to
join that elite group. Although defensive problems have been
exposed in their past two matches, the so-called Samba Queens have
plenty of offense, including midfielder Sissi, who leads the World
Cup with seven goals. She scored the winner Thursday on a superb
free kick.
</P>
<P>
   After sleepily arriving on the West Coast on Friday afternoon,
U.S. players acknowledged the heightening anxiety of living up to
the attention and expectations of reaching the finals. In three of
their four matches, the Americans either have given up an early
goal or allowed foes to get off good shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not the feeling you get when your stomach is turning
because you're on your first date,'' said defender Brandi Chastain,
who scored an own goal for Germany and later tied the game in the
second half. ``But when you go out in front a big crowd, where
people have their faces painted red, white and blue, you're excited
about the opportunity to show them a high level of soccer. It's an
energy level that's been hard to control.''
</P>
<P>
   That scenario should present itself on Sunday, Independence Day,
with a possible capacity crowd of 80,000 on hand. ``The U.S. is a
team without weaknesses,'' Brazil coach Wilson de Oliveira Rica
said. ``But we are certain this will be the best game of the
championship.''
</P>
<P>
   China and Norway are playing better as the tournament goes
along. China had no problems beating Russia 2-0, and 18-year-old
midfielder Pu Wei got a goal to demonstrate greater depth on a team
where striker Sun Wen has scored five times.
</P>
<P>
   Norway trounced Sweden 3-1, getting all three goals in quick
succession. Both teams also criss-crossed the country, playing in
San Jose, Calif., on Wednesday night. But unlike China, which has
been grumbling about having to make three cross-country flights,
Norwegian players don't seem to be bothered by the travel demands.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, we don't worry,'' captain Linda Medalen said. ``It's nice
to go to Boston. We have a lot of friends there.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
