<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RETAIL-RETAIL </SLUG>
 _ SF CHRON  
 AT SCHEUER LINENS, HIGH-CLASS THREADS COUNT  &HT;     By Carol Emert 
 &HT;     c.1999 San Francisco Chronicle  
<TEXT>
What is the primary difference between a towel monogram and a sheet
monogram? What size napkin is appropriate for lunch and what
dimensions are recommended for dinner?
<P>
   If you can't answer these questions, you can't work at Scheuer
Linens, an old-fashioned, family-owned, home-textiles boutique off
of San Francisco's Union Square.
</P>
<P>
   Mark Scheuer, the grandson of the shop's founders _ a German
Jewish couple who fled Hitler's Europe in the 1930s _ instructs all
new hires in the age-old customs of table, bed and bath linens.
Trainees must pass a 25-question examination before they may wait
on their first customer.
</P>
<P>
   Rosel and Samuel Scheuer, dry goods merchants from Heldenbergen,
Germany, settled in San Francisco after escaping Europe in 1936.
</P>
<P>
   Working out of a small Nob Hill apartment, they began calling on
the city's wealthy German Jewish residents with samples of
tablecloths, towels and sheets. Rosel would check the wedding
announcements each morning and immediately send a congratulatory
note that included an offer to handle the bride's gift registry.
</P>
<P>
   Rosel and Samuel's son Manfred _ Mark's father _ joined the
business in 1950, and the family opened its first store on Stockton
Street three years later. The shop got bumped by Niketown, and
Scheuer Linens moved in 1995 to a larger space on Sutter Street.
</P>
<P>
   Despite growing up in such a genteel business, both Manfred and
his son Mark were rough-and-tumble young men. In the 1930s, while
Manfred's parents sold linens from their apartment, their
twentysomething son worked on San Francisco's docks, getting into
fistfights when ordered to work on Jewish holidays.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s, Mark Scheuer spent his free time smoking pot on
Haight Street. He graduated from the University of Washington in
Seattle in 1967 with a degree in advertising, spent three years
avoiding the draft and wound up serving one year in Vietnam,
returning to San Francisco in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   He never intended to join the family business, although he was
not immune to the allure of quality linens. His one request from
home while serving in Vietnam was a good bath towel. His parents
shipped him a tasteful olive drab set, monogrammed in black.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Mark Scheuer went to work for his father,
expecting to leave the business after he had figured out what to do
next. But he never left. When Manfred Scheuer died in 1982, his son
took charge of the shop.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his initial lack of enthusiasm for selling linens, Mark
Scheuer came to love the business. He now relishes the time he
spends explaining to shoppers the difference between a satin weave
and a twill weave, or helping them select a set of fine napkins
from Portugal.
</P>
<P>
   Scheuer said he has passed up opportunities to open additional
stores because he prefers the intimacy of running a single shop.
``I like being out on the floor with customers,'' he said. ``I
never saw myself as an executive sitting behind a mahogany desk.''
</P>
<P>
   Longtime shoppers describe Scheuer Linens as the pinnacle of
customer service.
</P>
<P>
   ``We always know that if there's a glitch or we need to borrow a
sample, they will be very accommodating,'' said Judy McBride, an
interior designer with San Francisco's Wiseman Group. Scheuer has a
broader selection of merchandise than some other specialty stores
in town and much better service than chains, McBride said.
</P>
<P>
   The store's advice is eminently trustworthy, said shopper
Katherine James, who is such a textile purist that she irons her
bed linens by hand. On a recent visit, James said, Mark Scheuer
recommended the less expensive of two pillows because he thought
the smaller one would be more comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco socialite Susie Tompkins Buell, who has patronized
Scheuer since she accompanied her mother there as a child decades
ago, said she relies on Scheuer for advice on how to fold her
linens and where to get them laundered.
</P>
<P>
   Like Buell, a co-founder of the Esprit clothing chain, the
majority of the store's customers are well-heeled women in their
40s and up. A typical afternoon finds shoppers sitting at three
small tables on the sales floor, placing orders with Mark Scheuer
or a sales assistant.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers can ask questions about esoteric matters such as thread
count or leaf through fabric samples. About one-third of the shop's
sales are custom ordered.
</P>
<P>
   The average purchase tallies $200, but sales of $1,000 bed sets,
which include sheets, pillowcases, a duvet cover and a sham, occur
every day, said Mark Scheuer. The most popular sheet, a queen-size
Italian variety called Celeste, retails for $146 on sale, $183
regularly. The most expensive flat sheet, a Swiss model, goes for
about $700.
</P>
<P>
   It seems like a lot for a few yards of cotton. But cost is not a
big deterrent to Scheuer's loyal shoppers. ``I don't know (how
their prices compare) because I don't really shop other places,''
said James.
</P>
<P>
   As independent merchants of all types fold by the dozen, Scheuer
is a rare survivor. Only 2 percent of bedding sales are rung up by
single-store independents like Scheuer, according to Home Textiles
Today, a trade magazine.
</P>
<P>
   The majority of sales, 39 percent, go to discounters like
Wal-Mart. Other major outlets are department stores, with 19
percent of sales; specialty chains like Bed Bath &AMP; Beyond, with 16
percent; and catalogs, with 12 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The competition isn't a huge worry to Scheuer, since his elite
customer base isn't likely to defect to J.C. Penney. His main
concern is that his company may get too big to be fun.
</P>
<P>
   The business is outgrowing its 3,000-square-foot retail space,
as well as the 3,000-square-foot basement where catalog orders are
filled. The catalog, which is mailed to 50,000 people, accounts for
makes up &LR;  about 35 percent of total company sales.
</P>
<P>
   Scheuer Linens' store and catalog revenues rose a robust 12
percent last year and have grown at least 10 percent for each of
the last three years, with bedding accounting for about 60 percent
of sales.
</P>
<P>
   ``If it gets any bigger, I might have to open a warehouse,''
Scheuer said.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
