<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROGRAM-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DILEMMA FOR DEMOCRATS IN CLINTON PLANS
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Just as the 2000 campaign is in full swing at
living-room coffees in New Hampshire, it is engulfing Washington,
too. As many people are asking how President Clinton's Medicare,
Social Security and budget proposals will play politically as are
asking how they will work or whether they are good ideas.
</P>
<P>
   Would Vice President Al Gore's chances in November _ assuming he
wins the nomination _ be better if a version of the president's
plan is passed and he can claim a share of the credit? Or would he
be better off if he can campaign against what he might call
hard-hearted Republicans denying their grandparents prescription
drugs?
</P>
<P>
   Putting the question directly to Gore does not provide much
enlightenment. He would only say, ``I support the proposals the
administration has made for Medicare and Social Security.''
</P>
<P>
   A more eloquent version of the politically appropriate nonanswer
was offered by Tony Coelho, Gore's campaign chief. He said:
``Providing our seniors, our mothers, our grandparents with
prescription drugs is something that Al Gore strongly believes in
and that he will fight for without reservation. If the American
people want to reward someone for that, so be it.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, they may believe that, as Rep. Martin Meehan,
D-Mass., put it, the president's ``message is more important than
the next election.'' And even if they do not believe it, they can
hardly be expected to say that they wish Clinton had found
something else to propose, or that they hope the Republicans in
Congress kill the plan and leave them with the issue.
</P>
<P>
   But others will say it for them. Most Republicans and some
Democrats, speaking anonymously, are sure that Gore would prefer
the politics of attack and the chance to run, if he is nominated,
against not only the Republican presidential candidate but also
against ``the worst Congress in history,'' as one prominent
Democrat here visualized a Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Eddie Mahe, a Republican consultant, said it was simple: ``You
give Gore a choice _ he'd damn well rather have that as an issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, it might not make a huge difference either way. Bill
Kristol, editor of The Weekly Standard, a conservative magazine,
contended that an agreement would help the reputations of Clinton
and the House Republicans. But he said it was not clear that
Republicans would suffer from being seen as denying the elderly a
new benefit.
</P>
<P>
   Geoffrey Garin, a Democratic pollster, said Gore could profit
``under all circumstances.'' He might claim another
``Clinton-Gore'' policy success or he could blame the Republicans,
Garin said, adding that ``there is more force to it if the
Republicans don't succumb.''
</P>
<P>
   In any case, there is little Gore can do but speak up for the
president's plan and push for its passage.
</P>
<P>
   But what about members of Congress?
</P>
<P>
   The impact on the Senate is murky, because only rarely do
national issues affect many Senate elections. But the Republican
majority of 11 in the House is at risk next year. So would the
Republicans be more likely to retain control of the House if they
scaled back their tax cut proposals enough to legislate with the
president on Social Security and Medicare?
</P>
<P>
   ``If Social Security is off the table, it helps Republicans
generically,'' Mahe said without hesitation.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Thomas Davis III of Virginia, chairman of the House
Republican campaign committee, does not speak as definitely. He
conceded that an agreement on Medicare would deflate ``a
potentially hard-edged issue that sometimes works against us.'' And
he acknowledged that ``to the extent that we're acting like
grown-ups, that helps everybody in office.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said Republicans need not ``chase shadows'' in fear over
these issues, and should be satisfied with their alternatives. On
Clinton's prescription drug proposal, for example, he said that
``we will have our argument in terms of where we will give them
their pills.''
</P>
<P>
   The reality for Davis and other Republican leaders is that
talking compromise and accommodation is tricky for a party whose
most conservative 40 to 50 members usually call the tune in the
House. One of them, Rep. Tom Coburn of Oklahoma, went out in the
glaring sun on Thursday afternoon to denounce the Medicare drug
plan as unsound, unnecessary and too big.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if Republicans might not find it politically profitable to
seek compromise rather than risk a fight over Medicare, he replied,
``Doing the truthful thing sometimes is risky.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
