<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 21:58 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7935 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-CLINTON-PROGRAM-2NDTA     07-02 0428
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-PROGRAM-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WASHINGTON: is risky.''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   But the political odds are for Republicans to make a deal, and
outside the House most Republicans think they will. For example,
Brian Kennedy, who manages Lamar Alexander's presidential campaign,
said, ``I bet they come up with a compromise program, because it's
clear that when they have cut these deals with Clinton they do
better.''
</P>
<P>
   One Republican candidate's adviser, insisting on anonymity,
said: ``It's always in everybody's best interest to legislate
successfully. The public is in a mood for accommodation, not
confrontation.''
</P>
<P>
   House Democrats may fear that the president is paying more
attention to his place in the history books than their
circumstances in the polling booths but, like Gore, they can do
little about it. They have little influence in the decisions of the
House, and they have a natural inclination as Democrats to
legislate.
</P>
<P>
   Some talk about their worries. Meehan of Massachusetts said,
``There is always the political danger that congressional
Republicans will get a boost and it will be hard for Democrats to
give voters a reason to change the House.'' To avoid that, he said,
``It's important that the president not compromise too much.''
</P>
<P>
   In that one hears an echo of the bitter resentment many House
Democrats feel over the deals Clinton struck with Republicans in
1996 and 1997 over welfare, children's health care and the budget.
Many believe they would have regained control of the House by now
if he had not compromised and given Republicans results to brag
about. Still, there is little they can do about it.
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Patrick Kennedy, D-R.I., chairman of his party's campaign
committee, said without hesitation that legislation was better for
Democrats than confrontation. Making a virtue of necessity, he
said: ``We're much better off when our issues are being discussed.
These are Democratic programs. Continued success of these programs
will only accrue credit to the Democrats.''
</P>
<P>
   Rep. Jim McDermott, D-Wash., said that despite their fears,
Democrats have to legislate. ``There is, I think, a real necessity
for the Democrats to face the fact that we have to be
responsible.'' Speaking of Medicare, he said: ``We're not going to
get the perfect benefit. We'll take as much as we can get.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said the issues could not be considered abstractly.
Politics is a heavy player, he added, and ``everything that has
happened in the last six months has been directed at the 2000
election; nothing has been without its 2000 reference point.''
</P>
</TEXT>
