<HEADLINE>
TEEN WHO TRAVELED WITH TALL TALE MAY HAVE TB 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Fla.)   (bl)  
 By MONTE WILLIAMS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The 13-year-old Honduran boy who duped many people
with a tale about a 3,200-mile solo odyssey to search for his
father here is being treated for tuberculosis at University
Hospital and Medical Center at Stony Brook on Long Island.
</P>
<P>
   The boy, Edwin Daniel Sabillon, tested positive in a skin test
for tuberculosis while he was undergoing medical examinations. He
was hospitalized Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   The skin test indicates that he might have been exposed to the
disease, but it does not necessarily mean he is infected with it.
But it is ``standard to start therapy for the disease while
completing the evaluation,'' said Dr. Sharon Nachman, his attending
physician, who specializes in pediatric infectious disease.
</P>
<P>
   If Edwin does have tuberculosis, doctors said, he is expected to
recover.
</P>
<P>
   Asked about the boy's spirits, Nachman said he was in isolation,
but seemed to be doing fine. ``He didn't like the lunch food, so we
promised him Spanish food for dinner, and he spent the afternoon
playing Nintendo, just like any other 13-year-old,'' she added.
</P>
<P>
   The boy has been placed with a Spanish-speaking foster family in
Suffolk County. Members of the family have visited him in the
hospital, wearing protective face masks.
</P>
<P>
   At a press conference Friday with Mayor Rudolph Giuliani,
Nicholas Scoppetta, the commissioner of the Administration for
Children's Services, tried to allay fears that the boy might have
passed tuberculosis on to others. The diagnosis is ``not confirmed
at all,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this week, Edwin fooled politicians, police officers and
members of the press alike with his story: that he set out from his
hurricane-wrecked village in Honduras to find his only living
relative, his father, Grevi Sabillon Vasquez.
</P>
<P>
   He told the authorities that his mother was killed by Hurricane
Mitch, and that he had never seen his father. In fact, his mother
is alive, but gave the boy up when he was 3 months old. His father
died of AIDS in October. Relatives have said that even though Edwin
attended his father's funeral, he has had a difficult time
accepting his death.
</P>
<P>
   The boy had been living with an aunt, Aurora Sabillon, 23, in
Hialeah, Fla., when he ran away to New York City. Ms. Sabillon has
said she does not think she can rear him because she is expecting a
baby and she lives in a modest two-bedroom house.
</P>
<P>
   Edwin's grandmother, Paula Vasquez, who lives in Honduras, has
expressed interest in having Edwin live with her.
</P>
<P>
   At the press conference, Scoppetta said that Edwin might be
returned to live with relatives in Florida, but that there were
conflicting reports about their desire to have him back. ``Another
option is that he can be returned to Florida child welfare, even if
there is not a home there,'' Scoppetta said. ``He can also stay
here if conditions indicate that that is what's best for him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
