<SLUG> BC-NY-MRSCLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTONS LEARN THAT SUBURBS ARE COSTLY 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   If where you live defines who you are, Hillary Rodham Clinton,
the likely Senate candidate, is on a difficult search.
</P>
<P>
   For the last six weeks, a handful of friends, an exclusive real
estate agent and the White House social secretary, Capricia Penavic
Marshall, have canvassed the expensive northern Westchester County
suburbs _ from Katonah to Armonk to Mount Kisco to North Salem _
looking for a home the Clintons can afford. Friends say the
president and Mrs. Clinton want to rent, not buy, and pay no more
than $10,000 a month. It has not been easy.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think anybody had any concept that costs would be so
high,'' said a friend of the first lady. ``This is not a
millionaire president.'' Last year, the Clintons reported $504,109
in income, but they have an estimated $10 million in legal bills.
</P>
<P>
   So far, friends say Mrs. Clinton likes an 18-room, $3.8 million
house on Mills Road in North Salem, but was said to be worried that
it was too grand and that the rent, more than $20,000 a month, was
too high.
</P>
<P>
   Although political aides to Mrs. Clinton dismiss her
house-hunting as a minor matter _ ``I don't do the house,'' two
advisers replied, a tad haughtily, to a reporter's questions this
week _ it is far from a trivial concern. Just as Brooklyn defined
Sen. Charles Schumer, D-N.Y., and Nassau County on Long Island
defined former Republican Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, Mrs. Clinton's
address, even if she rents, will create an image in the minds of
voters about who she is, or would like to be.
</P>
<P>
   Living in Westchester would put Mrs. Clinton in the land of Girl
Scouts, car pools, professional women and, not least, crucial
voters. The once solidly conservative county now has more
registered Democrats than Republicans, a large number of
independents and a history of picking every winner in a statewide
election for the last 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   But Mrs. Clinton's advisers insist that privacy and security,
not politics, are the prime considerations in the house hunt.
Friends say the Secret Service is asking that the house be on at
least two acres of land, which eliminates most of the more crowded
suburbs of southern Westchester within a half-hour commuting
distance of the city.
</P>
<P>
   So she has focused largely on the rolling horse country of
northern Westchester. But friends say this has created another
problem: putting Mrs. Clinton, who presumably will be telling
voters she understands their problems, in the middle of some of the
most celebrity-saturated real estate in the country.
</P>
<P>
   North Salem, a town in the far northeastern corner of the
county, is obscure enough that it seems safe, for now, from
chicness. Although it is home to David Letterman and the composer
Alan Menken, it is largely a rural outpost of horse corrals, no
sidewalks and only two traffic lights.
</P>
<P>
   The town supervisor, Sy Globerman, a Republican, did not seem
especially welcoming Friday of the Clintons. ``It's not a question
of Republican or Democrat,'' he said. ``The problem is, they're
very high profile, and it kind of creates a disturbance in the
town.''
</P>
<P>
   The $3.8 million North Salem house that Mrs. Clinton likes is
owned by James Kohlberg, of Kohlberg &AMP; Co., an investment firm he
started with his father, Jerome Kohlberg, a founder of the
leveraged buyout firm Kohlberg Kravis Roberts &AMP; Co. Jerome Kohlberg
is also a Democratic contributor.
</P>
<P>
   Whether it is the Kohlberg house or another one, friends say the
Clintons' representatives hope to negotiate a rich owner down to
what one friend called a ``reasonable'' rent _ with the unspoken
argument that the Clintons will add cachet and increase the market
value of the house.
</P>
<P>
   Kathy Sloane, a real estate agent with Brown Harris Stevens, is
advising the Clintons.
</P>
<P>
   Friends add that closeness to the Westchester County Airport,
New York City and a golf course for the president are crucial.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the homes are videotaped for Mrs. Clinton to look at
later, but on Monday the first lady and the Clintons' daughter,
Chelsea, spent the day in New York City and Westchester looking
themselves.
</P>
<P>
   One thing is certain: This is Mrs. Clinton's search, not her
husband's. Friends expect the president to have his say after Mrs.
Clinton narrows down what she likes.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, on a trip back to Washington from New York, Clinton
was asked by reporters how his wife's house-hunting went. The
president smiled sheepishly, then said, ``I'm not the spokesperson
for that operation.''
</P>
</TEXT>
