<SLUG> BC-BIZGLANCE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSINESS AT A GLANCE 
(HLW) 
</HEADLINE>
  c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAJOR MARKET GAUGES CLIMB AS NUMBER OF JOBS GROWS
</P>
<P>
   Despite another big drop in factory jobs, the nation's employers
added more than a quarter of a million new workers to their
payrolls in June. The total gain, of 268,000 jobs, followed a
decline of 5,000 in May.
</P>
<P>
   The nation's unemployment rate edged up slightly to 4.3 percent
in June from 4.2 percent in May. The figures helped spur the major
market gauges to new highs. The Dow Jones industrial average
finished up 5.6 percent for the week, its best performance since
October 1998. The Dow closed at 11,139.24, up 72.82 points, or 0.7
percent. The Standard &AMP; Poor's 500-stock index rose 10.26 points,
or 0.7 percent, to 1,391.22. The Nasdaq composite index climbed
34.84 points, or 1.3 percent, to 2,741.02.
</P>
<P>
   GM AND FORD SALES INCREASE IN JUNE
</P>
<P>
   General Motors and Ford reported that their car and truck sales
edged higher last month, as the entire auto industry recorded its
best June in history and its second-best month ever. Sales, at 1.6
million vehicles, were 2 percent above levels of a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
   INTERNET COMPUTERS ARE BREACHED
</P>
<P>
   Hackers broke into network computers run by the Internet's new
governing body, the Internet Corporation for Assigned Names and
Numbers, in an apparent attempt to fan the flames of a continuing
struggle for control of the lucrative business of assigning
Internet addresses known as domains. The FBI was said to be
investigating.
</P>
<P>
   BRAZILIAN SENATE AIDS BANK
</P>
<P>
   Brazil's Senate approved a measure erasing $3.4 billion in
questionable securities from the books of Banco do Brasil, possibly
averting insolvency at the 191-year-old bank, Latin America's
largest. But the measure, which transferred responsibility for the
securities from the bank to the federal treasury, has worried
investors.
</P>
<P>
   BELO BUYS SOME MAC ASSETS
</P>
<P>
   A.H. Belo, which publishes The Dallas Morning News and The
Providence Journal, said that it would buy $315 million in assets
from MAC America Communications. The acquisition will include KTVK,
an independent television station in Phoenix, and the right to
operate KASW, an affiliate of the WB television network in Phoenix,
through a local marketing agreement. The acquisition will also
include a 50 percent interest in the Arizona News Channel.
</P>
<P>
   COCA-COLA IN SECOND POLISH RECALL
</P>
<P>
   Coca-Cola is removing all half-liter bottles of its new
mineral-fortified Bonaqua Plus purified water from stores in Poland
because government scientists have detected coliform bacteria in
the product. About 180,000 bottles of the water had already been
distributed by the bottler, Coca-Cola Beverages. The recall was
Coca-Cola's second in Poland this week.
</P>
<P>
   DREAMWORKS SKG ENDS STUDIO PLAN
</P>
<P>
   Citing financing difficulties, Dreamworks SKG has abandoned its
plan to build Hollywood's first new studio complex in more than 60
years on the site of Howard Hughes' aircraft factory near Los
Angeles airport.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT TECHNICIANS CRITICIZE FAA
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of technicians who maintain the nation's air traffic
control computers picketed at 53 airports, handing out leaflets
accusing the Federal Aviation Administration of causing big delays
by botching its modernization program, not hiring enough
technicians and not consulting them on the new equipment.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. MARKETS CLOSED
</P>
<P>
   The stock market and other financial markets in the United
States will be closed Monday in observance of the Fourth of July.
Most overseas markets, however, are open. U.S. markets will reopen
on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
