<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOREA-U.S.-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON AND S. KOREAN LEADER WARN NORTH AGAINST TESTING MISSILES 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By DAVID E. SANGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ President Clinton and President Kim Dae-jung of
South Korea used a brief meeting in Washington on Friday to make a
show of solidarity against North Korea and to warn it against
testing another long-range missile in coming weeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are maintaining close coordination on all issues, on
economic issues as well as security issues,'' said Kim, the onetime
dissident who was elected president just as South Korea plunged
into its economic crisis two years ago. ``And I do hope that this
close cooperation sends a clear message to North Korea.''
</P>
<P>
   For all the talk of cooperation, a senior Clinton administration
official, briefing reporters on condition of anonymity, refused to
discuss South Korea's own expanding missile program. It has become
the subject of increasing tension between Washington and Seoul,
with Clinton administration officials fearing that the North will
regard it as a provocation.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not prepared to discuss anything about a South Korean
missile program,'' the senior official said testily after being
pressed by reporters.
</P>
<P>
   A week ago the administration warned North Korea that a test of
its long-range Taepodong missile would result in ``very serious
consequences.'' The official speaking Friday said such a test would
create ``serious obstacles to peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how the United States, South Korea and Japan _ the last
test flew over Japanese territory _ might respond, he ruled out
suspending oil shipments or aid to the North in building
light-water nuclear reactors, part of a 1994 deal under which the
North is supposed to freeze its work on nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The official said it would make no sense for the United States
to violate the 1994 accord and invite the North to do the same by
resuming its weapons project.
</P>
<P>
   Later in the day Kim met with former Defense Secretary William
Perry, President Clinton's special envoy for North Korean affairs,
for an update on Perry's recommendations to the White House for
dealing with the North. Last month Perry went to Pyongyang, the
North Korean capital, to offer a deal under which the United States
would gradually lift economic sanctions that have been in place
since the Korean War of 1950-53.
</P>
<P>
   In return the North would have to agree to stop testing and
exporting missiles and to end military provocations against the
South. The State Department described North Korean officials as
interested in Perry's proposal. But only two weeks later, a dispute
between North and South Korean fishing boats turned into a naval
firefight in disputed waters west of the Korean Peninsula. More
than 20 North Koreans were killed.
</P>
<P>
   Kim also came here to proclaim that his country's economic
troubles appeared to be well on their way to ending. Clinton
congratulated him, but the White House description of the meeting
made it clear that U.S. officials remained worried that the process
of reforming South Korea's economy had bogged down.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2215EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0372 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 22:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A7958 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-ST-PETE-RACE-2TAKES-N     07-02 1019
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ST-PETE-RACE-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EFFORT TO HEAL OLD RACIAL WOUNDS BRINGS NEW DISCORD 
</HEADLINE>
   (bl)  
 By RICK BRAGG   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Fla. _ The painting had hung in St. Petersburg
City Hall all of Joe Waller's life, an eight-foot-long racial
caricature that showed black people happily entertaining white
picnickers. Every time Waller, a young black man, saw it, anger and
humiliation scorched him deep inside.
</P>
<P>
   In December 1966, he tore it down. With police officers in
pursuit, he ran through St. Petersburg's downtown, the ripped
painting flapping in his clenched fists like the captured flag of
some oppressive government. To him, it was.
</P>
<P>
   Some historians in this city on Tampa Bay have called his action
the start of the civil rights movement in St. Petersburg.
</P>
<P>
   ``That damn mural, that insulting thing,'' said the man who
ripped it down, who is now known as Omali Yeshitela. He has gray in
his hair, but the contempt in his voice, after all this time,
sounds brand new.
</P>
<P>
   Now, almost 33 years later, members of the St. Petersburg City
Council say they believe that their predecessors were wrong to have
hung the painting in the first place, and they recently put forth a
motion to hang a plaque in City Hall, in apology.
</P>
<P>
   But when some Council members learned that the wording in the
first-draft for the plaque also included an apology to the man who
tore down the painting, the motion, which had first seemed as
simple as honoring a retiring school teacher or allocating money to
plant palms, floundered.
</P>
<P>
   The painting, which had hung for decades, was hurtful to blacks
here, everybody on the Council agreed, but some members questioned
whether Yeshitela's overall legacy in St. Petersburg entitled him
to be immortalized in a plaque for that single long-ago deed.
</P>
<P>
   In a recent City Council meeting, the chairwoman, Bea Griswold,
said she had sworn an oath to the U.S. Constitution upon taking
office and would not honor Waller because he had once favored
overthrowing the U.S. government. Another councilwoman, Kathleen
Ford, said words attributed to Yeshitela on a Web site sounded like
treason.
</P>
<P>
   The divided Council, made up of two blacks and six whites, could
not reach an agreement and has not acted on the matter since.
</P>
<P>
   After his history-making act, for which he served three years in
prison, the man who was Joe Waller stayed mad, advocating not just
greater freedom for black people but also independence. He became
Omali Yeshitela and founded the African People's Socialist Party,
which advocates black self-determination, and, in a time when many
other black leaders spoke of racial harmony, he wanted nothing from
white power brokers or from the black leaders who sought to build
bridges. A lifetime of urging blacks to fight back against the
police branded him a radical, as someone not to be taken seriously
by the white and black establishments.
</P>
<P>
   In 1996, after the shooting death of a young black man by the
police in St. Petersburg, Yeshitela and his followers here, the
Uhuru Movement, were accused by the police of inciting a riot. A
SWAT team surrounded the Uhuru headquarters in the predominantly
black neighborhood in South St. Petersburg and fired tear gas into
it as people looked on in anger. The incident won Yeshitela support
among blacks, but whites were aghast. A riot in sleepy St.
Petersburg had been unheard of.
</P>
<P>
   The other day, sitting at a table in the Uhuru headquarters,
Yeshitela said he did not need words cast in bronze or plaster to
validate his life.
</P>
<P>
   But to ignore the fact that the racist painting had been torn
down by a black man, Yeshitela said, ``is designer history.''
</P>
<P>
   ``History is powerful,'' he said. It should, he said, be told
right.
</P>
<P>
   The man The St. Petersburg Times referred to once ``this city's
ultimate outsider'' now has the ear of Mayor David Fischer and
police officials. The clash with the police in 1996 forced a
meeting between the outsider and insiders, and Yeshitela even
serves on planning committees intended to bring better jobs and a
decent standard of living to the city's poorest residents.
</P>
<P>
   Yeshitela would still prefer to see black neighborhoods improve
without aid from the outside. But ``I'm not a nihilist,'' said
Yeshitela, a tall, powerful-looking man dressed in light-gray. ``I
am not an anarchist.''
</P>
<P>
   He is, however, still angry, say people who know him, and know
the world he came from. Fischer, who is white, called Yeshitela's
actions of 1966 a reflection of the anger of the time and ``a
watershed moment for the civil rights movement.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this person's name should be attributed,'' Fischer
said. ``It is part of history.''
</P>
<P>
   In some ways, Yeshitela had been preparing for it all his life.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in St. Petersburg on Oct. 9, 1941. His father was a
laborer on the railroad. His mother was a nurse and a beautician,
who ran her own shop.
</P>
<P>
   One of the first things he remembers is the green benches here.
The city was known for them, quaint, old-fashioned benches where
the tourists could sit and listen to the palm fronds rattle in the
breeze.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you were white,'' Yeshitela said, smiling faintly.
</P>
<P>
   A grandmother urged him to read when he was still in diapers.
``You've got to learn,'' she told him, ``for the race.''
</P>
<P>
   Teachers, too, told him to better himself, for the race.
</P>
<P>
   As soon as he was old enough, he joined the Army, which sent him
to Berlin as a tank mechanic. He remembers sitting in a tank at
Checkpoint Charlie at the Berlin Wall, then dividing East from
West, facing a Soviet tank, as a disk jockey on the other side spun
propaganda records.
</P>
<P>
   ``The voice would say, `And that was Louis Armstrong, playing
`Peace Down South,' but there is no peace down South, now that the
civil rights movement has started.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``And there I was, freezing in a tank in West Berlin,''
Yeshitela said, ``I read about it all, in Stars and Stripes. And I
remember thinking that when I went home I would die, because there
was no way I could put up with what was happening there.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   He returned in 1962, when he was 21. As he was traveling south
in an Army caravan from Fort Benning, Ga., to a base near Coco
Beach, Fla., he said a Florida waitress refused to serve him.
</P>
<P>
   Back home in St. Petersburg, the racist painting still hung in
City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   In 1966, he and a small group of blacks marched on City Hall to
protest the way a federal grant was being used by the city. An
elderly woman, who had joined the march, began to speak, but the
police and others there made fun of the way she talked, Yeshitela
said. He lost his temper.
</P>
<P>
   He rushed to the painting, ``grabbed it, tore it down,'' he
said. `` `We're going take this to the black community and see what
they think about it,''' he shouted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was running down Central Avenue,'' Yeshitela said, with the
police close behind. It was hard to keep the painting off the
ground, and one police officer jumped on it, to stop him. ``I
snatched it, and the cop went flying,'' he said, and now the smile
is on full.
</P>
<P>
   The city never rehung the painting, leaving the wall bare. It
still is.
</P>
<P>
   As the civil rights movement wore on, Yeshitela was a constant
critic of a police department that had historically had poor
relations in black neighborhoods.
</P>
<P>
   Then came the riot, when genuine anger in blacks found a voice
in him.
</P>
<P>
   City leaders had to listen, and suddenly Yeshitela had a place
at the table, however uncomfortable that may have felt. Among other
things, he convinced city officials that city money for economic
development would do more to fight crime in poor neighborhoods than
a beefed-up police presence, and even the head of the police union
agreed with him. Fischer has praised him for his work since the
riot, as have other city officials.
</P>
<P>
   But it is his legacy as a separatist, not a negotiator, that
stands in the way of Yeshitela's inclusion on the city hall plaque.
</P>
<P>
   But no matter what the council decides about his legacy,
Yeshitela said, one thing is certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They didn't take it down,'' he said. ``I did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
