<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Thursday, 07/02/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT18) WASHINGTON -- July 2, 1999 -- AIRPORT TECH PICKETS, 7-02
-- Ron Maisel, a member of the Professional Airways System
Specialists, who maintain the nation's air traffic control
computers, passes out fliers to travelers and airport employees at
National Airport on Friday. The pamphlet listed the union's
grievances against the FAA. (Shana Raab/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT17) LOS ANGELES -- July 2, 1999 -- DREAMWORKS-STUDIO, 7-02
-- The Playa Vista project, with downtown Los Angeles in the
distance, will be lacking one expected occupant: a Dreamworks SKG
studio. In a move that reflects a mood of industry retrenchment and
ambivalence about its own grandest ambitions, Dreamworks SKG has
abandoned its plan to build Hollywood's first new studio complex in
more than 60 years. (Kim Kulish/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT16) LIRONG, China -- July 2, 1999 -- TIBET-SKY-BURIAL-2,
7-02 -- After dismembering the body of a woman who just died, a
monk uses a sledge hammer to crush bone into fragments small enough
so that vultures, perched in the background at left, can consume
the body in a ritual known as sky burial. Deep in the mountains of
the Tibetan plateau, even in this part that spills into half of
Sichuan Province, Tibetans still carry out ancient rituals like sky
burial every day. It bespeaks a timeless adherence to old ways of
life, and death, unaffected by the changes that are so rapidly
affecting the rest of China. (Seth Faison/New York Times Photo)
LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT15) LIRONG, China -- July 2, 1999 -- TIBET-SKY-BURIAL-1,
7-02 -- Vultures swarm where a body was just dismembered for a
``sky burial.'' For Tibetans it is a widely accepted way to dispose
of the dead. Deep in the mountains of the Tibetan plateau, even in
this part that spills into half of Sichuan Province, Tibetans still
carry out ancient rituals like sky burial every day. It bespeaks a
timeless adherence to old ways of life, and death, unaffected by
the changes that are so rapidly affecting the rest of China. (Seth
Faison/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) SAN MATEO, Calif. -- July 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY
4 -- AMERICA-ONLINE-2, 7-02 -- Stephen M. Case, America Online's
chairman, in New York recently. An astounding 39 percent of
Americans' time online is spent using services the company controls
- 10 times the share of its nearest competitor, Microsoft. (Ruby
Washington/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) SAN MATEO, Calif. -- July 2, 1999 -- ADV. FOR SUN., JULY
4 -- AMERICA-ONLINE, 7-02 -- Barry M. Schuler, the head of
interactive services, is helping AOL's chairman, Stephen M. Case,
work toward expansion. Schuler joined AOL in 1995, when the company
bought his firm, called Medior, which designed games and CD-ROMs.
Until a recent promotion, his job was to run the AOL service, and
he used his designer's eye to help give it a cleaner, more
consistent look. (Peter DaSilva/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) PRISTINA -- July 2, 1999 -- KOSOVO, 7-02 -- Ethnic
Albanians celebrate ``Kosovo Day,'' Friday night. Thousands of
mostly young Kosovo Albanians flooded the streets of the provincial
capital to celebrate publicly for the first time the day they call
``Kosovo Day,'' a celebration banned in the past by the Serbs. On
July 2, 1990, ethnic Albanian members of the provincial assembly
voted to declare Kosovo ``an equal and independent entity within
the framework of Yugoslavia.'' (Tyler Hicks/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) BNEI BRAK, Israel -- July 2, 1999 -- ISRAEL-ORTHODOX-2,
7-02 -- Orthodox Jewish students in a class on social work at Bar
Ilan University earlier this week. With the laboriously negotiated
permission of rabbis, a dozen ultra-Orthodox Israelis are stepping
out of their cloisstered religious universe to train in a
three-year social work program at Bar Ilan, one of Israel's two
largest universities. (Rina Castelnuovo/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) WASHINGTON -- July 2, 1999 -- RUBIN-VIDEO, 7-02 -- Gene
Sperling, left, head of the National Economic Council, argues with
Samuel Berger, President Clinton's national security advisor, about
rescuing Treasury Secretary Robert Rubin during a spoof video
played at a farewell party for Rubin on Friday. In the video, Rubin
has been kidnapped by Japan's Minister of Finance. ``Let him fry,''
Berger says about Rubin's fate. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- July 2, 1999 -- FAMOUS-AMOS, 7-02 -- Wally
Amos, founder of Famous Amos cookies, who lost his business and the
right to its name several years ago, back promoting the cookies for
a new owner at a supermarket in Harlem. The Keebler Company, the
new owner of Famous Amos, offered Mr. Amos a two-year contract in
March to promote his old brand. And Keebler was willing to let him
use his name for his own business. (Jeffery A. Salter/New York
Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) UNDATED -- July 2, 1999 -- SUESS-POLITICS-2-B&AMP;W, 7-02 --
Political cartoons by Dr. Seuss, which appeared in the newspaper PM
during World War II. Dr. Seuss, beloved creator of ``Hop on Pop''
and ``Horton Hears a Who!,'' sharpened his artistic skills drawing
political cartoons of Hitler and Mussolini during the war. This
cartoon will be included in ``Dr. Seuss Goes to War,'' to be
published by The New Press. (The New Press/New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) UNDATED -- July 2, 1999 -- SUESS-POLITICS-1, 7-02 -- A
political cartoon by Dr. Seuss, which appeared in the newspaper PM
