<P>
   (NYT6) PRISTINA -- July 2, 1999 -- KOSOVO, 7-02 -- Ethnic
Albanians celebrate ``Kosovo Day'' on Friday. Thousands of mostly
young Kosovo Albanians flooded the streets of Pristina Friday night
to celebrate publicly for the first time the day they call ``Kosovo
Day,'' a celebration banned in the past by the Serbs. On July 2,
1990, ethnic Albanian members of the provincial assembly voted
outside the locked assembly building to declare Kosovo ``an equal
and independent entity within the framework of Yugoslavia.''
(Stephen Crowley/New York Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) NEW YORK -- July 2, 1999 -- JULYFOURTH-FLOATER, 7-02 -- A
traveller hoists his luggage into the back of a taxi outside the
Port Authority Bus Terminal on Friday. In the yearly Independence
Day ritual, millions of Americans across the country set out on
vacations to take advantage of the long weekend. (Earl Wilson/New
York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) EVANSTON, Ill. -- July 2, 1999 -- BLACKS-EDUCATION, 7-02
-- Marta Fernandez, right, teaches her Spanish honors class in
which Akilah Rogers, 17, center, is a student. Rogers is one of a
few black students at the school who is scoring high grades. Across
the country, educators and researchers are just beginning to focus
on why black students, even from middle class and upper-income
families, do worse than whites and Asians of comparable levels of
income or family educational background. (Cynthia Howe/New York
Times Photo) LITE
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) BNEI BRAK, Israel -- July 2, 1999 -- ISRAEL-ORTHODOX,
7-02 -- Reuven Berger, left, and Chaim David Rosenbaum, both social
