<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-NOTES03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Mets-Braves pitch expectoration talk
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Mike Remlinger hit town and walked straight into a
spit fight with New York Mets manager Bobby Valentine, who
insinuated the Braves reliever doctors the baseball.
</P>
<P>
   The episode is an offshoot of last weekend's experience with
Mets reliever Dennis Cook, who has an ongoing three-year history
with the Braves' coach Pat Corrales. Prompted by Atlanta requests,
umpires twice last Sunday checked the ball while Cook was on the
mound at Turner Field, which led to Valentine's comments.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do I think Mike Remlinger was fooling with the ball? I do,''
Valentine was quoted as saying earlier this week. ``He pitched for
me and he was always experimenting. I don't know. He's a good guy.
I don't think he does but he was always experimenting.''
</P>
<P>
   Remlinger, who pitched one-half season for Valentine in 1994 at
Class AAA Norfolk, has been one of the few players do say he
enjoyed working with the current Mets manager. But he rejected the
comments out of hand, particularly since he didn't even face the
Mets once last weekend, and insinuated Valentine was only trying to
divert attention from Cook.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this is something old, why didn't he say something in the
past?'' asked Remlinger, who denies he alters the ball. ``If this
is something new, then how would he know because I haven't pitched
against him?
</P>
<P>
   ``It just seems odd, for a guy who admitted to liking him, to
come out and make something up in the paper.''
</P>
<P>
   Corrales accused Cook of working up the seams in 1997, when Cook
pitched in Florida. Cook has resented it ever since and this issue
invariably comes up every time he faces Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz throws
</P>
<P>
   No one seems to think John Smoltz will make his regular start
Sunday night except the Braves and Smoltz. The right-hander, who is
scheduled to face Orel Hershiser in the third game of the series,
threw what he called a ``normal'' 15-minute side session in an
indoor cage at Shea Stadium and while he would not say his elbow
felt good, he said, ``Ready to go Sunday. Felt normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Smoltz (8-2) went just five innings last Tuesday before the
elbow stiffened and manager Bobby Cox pulled him. Since coming off
the DL June 1, Smoltz has made it past the sixth inning only once
in six starts.
</P>
<P>
   Medical update
</P>
<P>
   Tom Glavine had a sore left palm Monday and still bore a mark
from the seam of the ball that Montreal's Marty Martinez sent back
to the box Thursday. The pain was localized between the third and
fourth finger joints but Glavine said, ``I think we'll be ready,''
for his next start Tuesday against the Marlins. Shortstop Walt
Weiss made his second consecutive start Friday night after coming
off the disabled list Thursday and reported no discomfort.
</P>
<P>
   Lopez lingers
</P>
<P>
   The club remains uncertain on Javy Lopez's immediate future.
Though eligible to come off the DL next Tuesday, the Braves do not
know if his right knee sprain has healed sufficiently to allow him
back into action. He has remained in Atlanta to take daily therapy
at Dr. Joe Chandler's office at St. Joseph's Hospital.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
