<TEXT>
<P>
   These are the stories The San Francisco Chronicle Business
section plans to move for Monday, July 4, on the New York Times
wire. For questions, please call August Maggy at 415-777-7218 or
the business desk at 415-536-5172.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; KIDED &LR;  _ We look at organizations such as OpNet of San Francisco,
Plugged In of East Palo Alto, the Eastmont Computing Center of
Oakland and others that are offering computer training to youth who
are versed in surviving the mean streets on which they live, not
the information superhighway. By Benny Evangelista
</P>
<P>
   &UR; OPEN  &LR;  _ A seemingly arcane debate over how consumers will
access the Internet has exploded into controversy with some of the
biggest names in the communications industry taking potshots at one
another, lobbyists putting on a full-court press and local
regulators resigning in protest over the issue. The brouhaha stems
from this question: Should AT&AMP;T be required to let competitors use
its cable TV lines to offer high-speed Internet access to
consumers? By Deborah Solomon
</P>
<P>
   &UR; PHOENIX  &LR; _ For Internet sites and service providers, an icon on
the PC desktop may translate into thousands of users and millions
in new revenue. That's why some of the biggest names on the Net
have jumped at a new technology that will let them make their mark
on millions of previously inaccessible PCs. By Henry Norr
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NETFILES &LR;  _ ICANN or I can't? The Internet Corporation for
Assigned Names and Numbers _ a nonprofit concern created to relieve
the federal government of the task of dispensing Web addresses _
has been anything but master of its own domain names. After three
years of planning, haggling and negotiations by government
officials, computer geeks and private businesses, ICANN was
supposed to break Network Solutions Inc.'s monopoly for registering
domain names ending in .com, .net and .org. Now, there is a power
struggle between NSI, which appears reluctant to relinquish
control, and ICANN, which has drawn accusations of making major
policy decisions behind closed doors. By Jon Swartz
</P>
<P>
   &UR; BIOSCOPE &LR;  _ On its surface, President Clinton's proposal to add
a drug benefit to Medicare would seem to give the biotech sector a
boost, making more money available for new remedies. But industry
lobbyists are leery of the plan's nuances, and even more fearful of
what might happen as Congress has its say on a bill. By Tom Abate
</P>
</TEXT>
