<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 23:08 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8073 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-DEATH-TODDLER-AR     07-02 1142
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-DEATH-TODDLER-ART-$ADV04-2T-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WITH TWO CONVICTIONS OVERTURNED, TEXAS TEEN AWAITS WORD ON THIRD
TRIAL 

</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  (For release Sunday, July 4) 
 
(Eds.: Photo available on NYT datasbase) 
 
By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
c.1999 Houston Chronicle 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, TEXAS _ For the past three years, LaCresha Murray says
her life has been filled with those she considers ``different,''
such as the older locked-up girls who threw chairs and attacked the
guards.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, there are the other types of ``different'' folks,
such as Mike Wallace of ``60 minutes,'' who interviewed her last
December.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's outspoken. Whatever he thinks, he talks _ whatever it is.
How it comes out is how it comes out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Murray has just celebrated her 15th birthday and is back at her
grandparents' tidy brick home now, her nightmarish incarceration
for the beating death of a 2-year-old girl behind her, at least
temporarily.
</P>
<P>
   In starts and stops she speaks, often unable to express her
feelings as the youngest child ever charged with capital murder in
Texas, as the child hounded by media when she had just turned 12,
as the girl who was twice convicted on lesser charges in the 1996
slaying of Jayla Belton.
</P>
<P>
   Murray said she didn't like being hauled into juvenile court
pretrial hearings wearing handcuffs, shackles and jailhouse
clothes. The food ``didn't taste right,'' and she was scared.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Murray becomes animated when recalling the final hours of
her three-year imprisonment, which ended after an appellate court
threw out her second conviction this spring. She had called her
grandmother, Shirley Murray, three times that morning from a Texas
Youth Commission prison in Giddings.
</P>
<P>
   She remembers exactly that it was 12:30 p.m. when her
grandmother finally told her of the court's decision to set her
free. She was so happy to leave the Giddings facility, though, that
she didn't bother to change clothes.
</P>
<P>
   ``She didn't even have time to get out of her orange suit,''
said her grandfather, R.L. Murray. ``She wore it home. They called
for it, but we haven't sent it back yet.''
</P>
<P>
   She's home, but no one knows for how long.
</P>
<P>
   Found guilty by two juries, prosecutors continue to hold her
responsible for little Jayla's murder. The second jury handed down
a 25-year sentence for Murray for injury to a child. &UR;  &LR; The young
teen was facing the prospect of spending the rest of her youthful
days locked up.
</P>
<P>
   She insists, as do her attorneys and a swelling number of
supporters, that she is innocent.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, certain questionable tactics of the prosecution team
prompted national media attention, particularly from New York Times
columnist Bob Herbert, who wrote seven columns attacking Travis
County District Attorney Ronnie Earle and others.
</P>
<P>
   ``We welcome anybody looking as close as they want to look at
the evidence and doing an analysis of whatever was done in this
case,'' Earle said. ``What I strongly object to is someone
beginning that process with a conclusion in mind and using only
such pieces of information as buttress that conclusion. That is
intellectually dishonest.''
</P>
<P>
   Ultimately an appeals court overturned Murray's second
conviction because state District Judge John Dietz allowed the
prosecution to include in the evidence a statement Murray gave
police in a 2 1/2-hour interrogation _ without her grandparents'
knowledge and without a lawyer present.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's supporters decried the police grilling of the
11-year-old as a gross infringement of the child's rights. The
court ruled that because she was interrogated at a children's
shelter where police had taken her, she was in fact, ``in
custody,'' thereby requiring that certain steps be taken to protect
her rights.
</P>
<P>
   The nature of the interrogation itself, conducted five days
after Jayla's death, drew outrage and protests from civil
libertarians and is reprinted in its entirety at a Web site called
www.peopleoftheheart.org. Murray repeatedly denied that she was
angry at the toddler or that she understood why Jayla Belton had
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``At one point, when they've figured out that she doesn't know a
thing, that she even tells them at one point, `I don't know what
happened, my family doesn't know what happened, nobody knows what
happened,' they start feeding her their scenario of what
happened,'' said an incensed former legal secretary, Barbara Taft.
``Then they start insisting that if she just, you know, tells them
this, then it's over.''
</P>
<P>
   Taft, who created the Web site for Murray's case, worked for
years for Judge Dietz's attorney-wife at the law firm of Fulbright
and Jaworski. A transcript of Murray's police interrogation bears
Taft out:
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``I didn't do nothing. I promise to God.''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Ernesto Pedraza: ``LaCresha, it's OK. Listen.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``Y'all going to take me to jail or something?''
</P>
<P>
   Pedraza: ``No. We're not taking you to jail. We're taking you
back to your shelter. You can go back. We just want to get to the
truth. It's all going to be OK ... And I want you to talk to us, so
we can get everything straight. All right? Once we get the story
straight ... it's over. OK?''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``Yep. But I didn't do nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   At several points, such as this one, detectives suggest
scenarios to Murray:
</P>
<P>
   Pedraza: ``I know it's real hard, LaCresha. It's hard when
something like this happens, but you know there's a reason, there
might be a reason why this happened, you know, you might have been
carrying the baby and the baby might've fallen from your arms, or
fell off of the bed or something like this, and there's a lot of
reasons why something happened, but until we hear it from you, we
won't know. We'll just have our opinion.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``You have ours, too.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedraza: ``Right. And we need to get your side of the story
also.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``I just told you.''
</P>
<P>
   Finally, Murray says that as she was running with Jayla to her
grandfather, the baby did fall ``a little bit'' and her head hit
the floor. She picked her up and kept running. Later, police
suggest maybe she accidentally kicked Jayla as she tried to pick
her up. Then they try to establish an answer for why LaCresha
Murray might want to kill Jayla.
</P>
<P>
   Pedraza: ``So, you didn't have nothing, no anger at her?''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``What would she do to make me mad?''
</P>
<P>
   Pedraza: ``I don't know. Tell me.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``Nothing.''
</P>
<P>
   Pedraza: ``OK, then, who was it?''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``Nobody!''
</P>
<P>
   Detective Al Eels: ``Do you just get angry for no reason?''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``I wasn't even angry.''
</P>
<P>
   Eels: ``Was it for fun then, did you enjoy it?''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``What?''
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was one particular exchange, as Murray helped officers
with preliminaries for her official statement, that especially
alarmed her staunchest supporters:
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
(MORE) &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
