u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEEN-DEATH-TODDLER-AR     07-02 1446
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEEN-DEATH-TODDLER-ART-$ADV04-2N-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 
AUSTIN, TEXAS: her staunchest supporters:
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``What's that word? Home-a-seed?''
</P>
<P>
   Pedraza: ``Yeah, we work in there, homicide.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``Homicide?''
</P>
<P>
   Pedraza: ``There you go.''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``What's that?''
</P>
<P>
   Pedraza: ``Understand it?''
</P>
<P>
   Murray: ``Is that how you spell her name?''
</P>
<P>
   Pedraza: ``Jayla? Yeah, J-a-y-l-a . . .''
</P>
<P>
   The interrogators never explained in the course of considerably
more questioning what that strange word ``homicide'' actually
meant. Meanwhile, Tuesday is the deadline for Travis County
prosecutors to ask the Texas Supreme Court to reverse the appellate
court and uphold the legal validity of Murray's statement to
police.
</P>
<P>
   Without the statement, a third trial would hinge on conflicting
medical testimony alone. Prosecutors have expressed a desire to try
Murray a third time but remain undecided about whether they will.
Murray's defense lawyers, meanwhile, say they now have additional
medical evidence no jury has yet seen that they believe will clear
her.
</P>
<P>
   The lawyers said they wanted to meet with prosecutors, but last
week that seemed unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   District Attorney Earle, criticized as conducting an overzealous
prosecution and accused of making Murray into a ``poster child for
juvenile crime,'' chafes at such attacks and insists his motives
are in the best interest of abused children.
</P>
<P>
   ``How I feel about this is (that I'm) sad for LaCresha,'' he
said. ``She killed Jayla Belton, and she is being encouraged by
irresponsible adults to deny that.''
</P>
<P>
   Earle says Murray's case came on the heels of a similar slaying
in San Antonio, and he points to a case three weeks ago in Dallas
of an 11-year-old beating a baby she was watching. The problem, he
contends, is inadequate child care and stressed-out children being
put in charge of baby-sitting other children.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the real issue in this case. What really concerns me is
that by encouraging LaCresha to deny her responsibility in this
matter, that enables the whole country to remain in denial about
the absence of adequate child care,'' Earle said.
</P>
<P>
   Murray's crusading supporter, Barbara Taft, eventually quit the
law firm and made Murray's cause her own, recently winning an
American Civil Liberties Union award for her efforts in pushing
through state legislation restricting &UR;  &LR; the way children can be
interrogated.
</P>
<P>
   Taft said the record shows it is ludicrous for Earle or anyone
else to claim that Murray was baby-sitting that day. Jayla Belton's
mother and live-in boyfriend who brought the toddler to the Murray
home had been told not to bring her that day, because Shirley
Murray _ LaCresha Murray's grandmother, who did the baby-sitting _
wouldn't be there that day.
</P>
<P>
   He did anyway, forcing 17-year-old Shawntay Murray to watch
Jayla. When Shawntay went to work, she told her grandfather, R.L.
Murray, to check on the baby, one of several children at the house
that day. R.L. Murray, who is paralyzed from the waist down, wasn't
worried because Jayla was sleeping most of the day.
</P>
<P>
   Taft believes Earle refuses to seek the truth because he wants
to protect his reputation and his job. She is especially troubled
because she believes Earle is allowing a guilty adult to go free.
</P>
<P>
   ``Ronnie Earle was running for election. He was opposed. He
needed a handle. He needed a headline. He saw an opportunity. He
saw a photo-op. And an 11-year-old charged with capital murder!''
she said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Austin's own child-killer case at a time when school
shootings and other heinous crimes by the young had stirred a
national hysteria, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``What they did was they made up a story and they presented it
to the public, just like a movie,'' Taft continued. ``They
presented LaCresha Murray. She's black and she's big. So you go up
and round up every 153-pound girl and charge her with murder? They
had no physical evidence, they had no witnesses, they had no proof
that anything happened to that child in that house.''
</P>
<P>
   At Murray's first trial, held in August 1996, her
court-appointed lawyer put up little defense, saying he thought the
prosecution's case was so weak it would fall on its own accord.
Yet, attorney Kameron Johnson was given only $300 to put up a
defense. That was the amount granted the court-appointed attorney
by Judge Dietz.
</P>
<P>
   Dietz declined to be interviewed, his staff said, because he
remains the sitting judge on the case if prosecutors try it a third
time. Earlier, he told ``60 Minutes'' that it was his fault the
defense had limited resources. ``At the time, we did not realize
the amount of controversy this was going to garner,'' Dietz said.
</P>
<P>
   It was Dietz who agreed to grant Murray a second trial, saying
he believed justice had not been done in the first trial. Instead
of $300, this time around he provided what defense and prosecutors
alike call a generous budget, and highly unusual in a
court-appointed case. Defending her in the second trial and
successful appeal has cost $171,756 so far, enough for three
attorneys, two expert witnesses and an investigator.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the handsome budget, some of the remaining members of
the defense team say disagreements among the lawyers led to some
bad decisions in the second trial.
</P>
<P>
   In all likelihood, if the case goes to trial a third time,
Murray's future will hinge solely on complicated and conflicting
medical theories of the prosecution and the defense. The most
important issue, all agree, is the time the fatal injury to Jayla
occurred.
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Linda Norton, a medical expert in Dallas who normally
testifies for prosecutors, is convinced that LaCresha Murray did
not kill the 2-year-old. She says that in a third trial, she will
present even more convincing evidence, although she declined to
give details. Norton has taken such a strong interest in Murray's
case that she calls the girl's interrogation by the police the
``mental equivalent of a rubber hosing.''
</P>
<P>
   A reading of statements given independently to police, Norton
said, shows clearly that Jayla was very ill when she arrived at the
Murray house the day she died. Jayla was mostly lethargic and
sleeping, vomiting when forced to eat, and sweating profusely,
witnesses said. LaCresha Murray reported that she saw the child
shaking in distress before she was taken to the hospital.
</P>
<P>
   ``It becomes very clear that she was going into shock at the
time she walked into the Murray household,'' Norton said.
``Clearly, this liver was slowly bleeding into the abdominal cavity
during the day.''
</P>
<P>
   Norton's theory for the defense: Someone _ either the toddler's
mother or boyfriend _ inflicted Jayla's injuries before dropping
her off at the Murray home, causing a tear in the liver and
fractures to the ribs. Efforts to revive the child when she was
brought to the hospital emergency room late that day in Murray's
arms compounded the rib fractures and the liver injury as well,
Norton contends.
</P>
<P>
   The injury that state medical experts analyzed from the autopsy
was not the original injury that killed the child, Norton said.
</P>
<P>
   Jayla was malnourished, she said, and had bruises, some of which
were not fresh, and scars.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's completely ridiculous. All the injuries were fresh. All
of them occurred around the time of her lethal injury, the split
liver,'' said Travis County Medical Examiner Roberto Bayardo, who
conducted the autopsy and testified for the prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Why, when the child had 10 visible bruises on her forehead, did
no one notice them all day long? Not possible, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Both Bayardo and Bexar County Medical Examiner Vincent DiMaio of
San Antonio _ also called as an expert _ &UR;  &LR; believe the massive and
fatal injury that split the liver occurred shortly before the
child's death. The only person around Jayla at that time was
Murray. Their theory is that Murray killed Jayla by viciously
stomping her on the chest with her full weight, so hard it split
the liver wide open and blood poured quickly into the abdominal
cavity _ a rapid death, not a slow one.
</P>
<P>
   Back at home again, Murray is still coping with people she calls
``different.''
</P>
<P>
   Until her case is resolved, she's attending an alternative
school for problem children caught fighting or carrying knives or
guns.
</P>
<P>
   All her classmates are boys, but still, it's better than being
incarcerated in the youth facility at Giddings she says.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only difference is people up in Giddings, they use
(weapons) to get where they're at,'' Murray said. ``They shot
somebody or stabbed somebody or they tried to hurt somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
XXXX END OF STORY &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
