<SLUG> BC-BBA-FERNANDEZ-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FERNANDEZ REWRITES DOMINICAN RECORD BOOKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MATT McHALE  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   With all the attention surrounding his run for .400, Toronto
third baseman Tony Fernandez has achieved a number of which he is
even more proud.
</P>
<P>
   His game-winning single on June 20 gave him 2,178 career hits,
the most by any major-league player from the Dominican Republic.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, who turned 37 on Wednesday, passed Julio Franco, a
contemporary and idol during his 15-year career. He is reluctant to
talk about his batting average, which stood at .387 heading into
Friday's game against Tampa Bay. But he is not reluctant to speak
about Franco, now playing in Mexico after spending spring training
with the Devil Rays, or Franco's place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``Julio told me then that it would be amazing if two little guys
like us from San Pedro de Macoris wind up being the ones with the
most hits,'' Fernandez told the Toronto Star. ``To me, Julio is
still the best hitter of all of us. It's a shame he still isn't
playing in the majors... a shame he's going to be second.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, I can't say where this ranks (among his
achievements). Only after I sit down and think about this will I
able to place it.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might mean more for my kids. It probably means a lot to the
people back home in the Dominican Republic. I know many people will
be surprised that, with guys like George Bell, Cesar Cedeno and so
on, they realize Tony Fernandez has more hits than all of them _
including Julio Franco.''
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez's game-winning and record-breaking hit was worth more
than posterity. Blue Jays starter David Wells, who signed a
two-year contract extension before the game, promised $500 to any
player who delivered a game-winning hit.
</P>
<P>
   Recently, Fernandez played in his 2,006th game, which broke a
tie for second place with Cedeno for games played by a Dominican.
Felipe Alou, now the Expos manager, had 2,082.
</P>
<P>
   Fernandez, a .285 lifetime hitter going into this season, is in
his fourth tour with the Blue Jays. He once was considered the
defensive equal of Ozzie Smith at shortstop and when Toronto's
young shortstop Alex Gonzalez went down with a shoulder problem
earlier this year, manager Jim Fregosi was asked if he would move
Fernandez back.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not about to tamper with a .400 hitter,'' he said.
``These things don't come along every day.''
</P>
<P>
   The secret, say most Jays watchers, was Fernandez's move last
September from second base to third. Although he doesn't provide
much pop for a power position, the switch-hitting Fernandez batted
almost .390 the rest of the way and .321 overall because he no
longer had the pressure of charging baserunners trying to break up
the double play.
</P>
<P>
   ``Health is a big thing,'' said Hernandez's former manager, Joe
Torre. ``I've never seen a guy work as hard in the weight room as
Tony. He might be the best- conditioned athlete in baseball.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
