<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0387 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 23:16 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8079 &Cx1f; tta-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-TEN-STEVENSON-ERVING-     07-02 0741
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-STEVENSON-ERVING-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JULIUS ERVING ADMITS HE IS FATHER OF TENNIS STAR
</HEADLINE>
  
 (Eds: CORRECTS from three to four children in fourth graf.)  (rm) 
 By   JAMES C. McKINLEY JR.   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   With each surprising victory at Wimbledon, Alexandra Stevenson,
the 18-year-old rising tennis star, faced another set of questions
_ intensifying curiosity about everything from her style of play to
her experiences as a black woman in a predominantly white sport.
</P>
<P>
   Then this week, as she continued her run through the world's
most prestigious tournament in her first performance as a
professional, Stevenson, the daughter of a single white mother,
began to be asked insistently about an issue &UR;  &LR; that had shadowed her
during her rise through the amateur ranks: Who is your father?
Politely and repeatedly, the young player declined to answer.
</P>
<P>
   But Stevenson did not stop winning _ she will play in the
women's semifinals Saturday _ and the question did not stop being
asked, the interest driven by a newspaper report that claimed to
identify the father. So Friday her father came forward, saying he
was acting to help relieve the stress on his daughter as she
prepared for the biggest match of her life.
</P>
<P>
   Julius Erving, the Hall of Fame basketball player who had been
one of his sport's greatest performers and sturdiest models of
personal rectitude, issued a statement acknowledging that he was
Stevenson's father, and that he had, in secret, provided for her
well being from the day of her birth. Erving, who was married when
Stevenson was born, said he had kept his wife informed all along,
and that his four children were aware that he had another daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand they are being besieged because she won her match
today,'' Erving, in his only public comment, told the Associated
Press. ``Getting this statement out will help.'' He declined a
request to be interviewed for this article.
</P>
<P>
   Stevenson has known who her father was for years, but has only
met him once, according to her mother. And in a brief interview
Friday night, Stevenson said she did not feel cheated because she
had grown up without her father present. She pointed out many of
her friends came from homes where the parents had divorced.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's always been normal to me,'' she said. Stevenson said she
had also learned to live with the secret and with the agreement not
to reveal her father's identity. ``I have been well trained,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   The rather remarkable events Friday were only the latest in what
has been a tumultuous and often exhilarating 10 days for Stevenson.
Having graduated from high school in May, she arrived at Wimbledon
as a relative unknown who had won a berth for unseeded players at a
qualifying tournament. In quick succession, Stevenson won five
straight matches against mostly higher ranked players, becoming the
first qualifier in history to reach the women's semifinals of the
venerable tournament.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Stevenson declined to talk about her father and
declared her mother had served as her only role model.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had both parents wrapped into one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But the debate about her father intensified, and the question
became unavoidable on Wednesday when the Ft. Lauderdale
Sun-Sentinel published a copy of her birth certificate identifying
a Julius Winfield Erving 2nd as the child's father.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Stevenson has become an instant celebrity, and
the London tabloids have given her extensive coverage. Stevenson
has appeared quite comfortable amid the excitement, and her mother,
Samantha, a freelance sports writer whose work has appeared in The
New York Times, has moved easily and aggressively in the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Stevenson has written extensively about her experiences
as a single mother raising a gifted tennis player, and over the
years she had not discouraged speculation that her child's father
was a prominent athlete. She has been working on a book project
about her daughter's life as a promising tennis player.
</P>
<P>
   But Friday, Samantha Stevenson said very little about her
daughter's father. ``I can't comment all,'' she said. ``The mother
maintains her silence.''
</P>
<P>
   In his prepared statement, Erving acknowledged he had had a
relationship with Stevenson's mother in 1980. ``All matters
concerning Alexandra since her birth have been handled privately
through counsel,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Erving told the Associated Press he had met Stevenson only once,
when she 3 years old, but had supported her financially since her
birth. ``She was brought to me at a basketball clinic at a public
school,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Erving, now a vice president of the Orlando Magic basketball
team, initially denied the Sun-Sentinel's story. But reporters
mobbed Stevenson at the tournament, peppering her with questions
about her father.
</P>
<P>
   Samantha Stevenson became pregnant in 1980 while she was living
in Philadelphia, covering, among other things, the 76ers. She moved
to San Diego, where her parents lived, to have the baby.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stevenson recognized her daughter's talent early and
enrolled Alexandra in tennis lessons at the age of 4 at the La
Jolla Beach and Tennis Club. When Alexandra was 9, she was taken in
and coached by Dr. Peter Fischer, the Los Angeles pediatrician and
tennis guru who helped Pete Sampras develop his game as a youth.
Three times a week, her mother drove three hours to Los Angeles for
her daughters lessons.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Under Fischer's tutelage, Stevenson developed a classic style,
reminiscent of Margaret Court, whom she now calls her heroine.
Stevenson is almost a tennis throwback, using a wicked one-handed
backhand, a big serve and lightning volleys in an era when
two-handed backhands and dogged baseline play is the vogue.
</P>
<P>
   Fischer also encouraged her to play in junior tournaments above
her level to better her game, so she did not wrack up the string of
victories that might have made her a household name.
</P>
<P>
   As her game developed, Stevenson received help from other
prominent coaches in California, including Pancho Segura in
Carlsbad and Robert Lansdorp in Pacific Palisades. Fischer dropped
out of her life in 1997, when he was arrested on charges of
molesting children at his medical practice.
</P>
<P>
   Lansdorp, who helped Stevenson perfect her ground strokes, said
rumors that her father was a professional athlete began circulating
years ago in West Coast tennis clubs. Erving's name was sometimes
mentioned, he said, but neither the mother nor daughter would talk
about the subject.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many times, kiddingly, I would say, hey, who's the dad?'' he
recalled. ``But they said its not important.''
</P>
<P>
   Lansdorp said the absence of her father never seemed to bother
Alexandra.``She seems a real well-adjusted kind of girl,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Although Stevenson has never achieved a No. 1 ranking in the
U.S. national junior rankings, she has been a member of the U.S.
national junior team and developmental squad for several years. She
has played in international junior tournaments as a representative
of the U.S. Tennis Association, and in 1996, at age 16, she won the
U.S. Open junior doubles title.
</P>
<P>
   Prior to Wimbledon, Stevenson had played only a handful of
matches on the women's pro tour, and as an amateur won a
minor-league tournament in Michigan last year.
</P>
<P>
   In March, she had received a wild card into the Evert Cup in
California and had lost creditably to Martina Hingis, 6-3, 6-4. In
June in the DFS Classic, a traditional Wimbledon tuneup played on
grass, Stevenson, ranked 114th at the time, upset 12th-seeded
Anne-Gaelle Sidot of France, 6-3, 5-7, 8-6, after surviving a
double match point. She lost in the quarterfinals when Magui Serna
of Spain stopped her run as Stevenson was forced to retire with a
pulled stomach muscle, trailing, 6-1, 1-0.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The admission that he had fathered an illegitimate child was not
in keeping with Erving's public image. Many prominent players in
the NBA have been hit with paternity suits from single mothers in
recent years, and several have acknowledged supporting children
born outside marriage.
</P>
<P>
   But Erving, or ``Dr. J'' as he was known, has always been held
apart by fans, not just for his breathtaking play, but as a model
family man who had deep religious beliefs. He has been married
since 1972 to his wife, Turquoise, and they have raised four
children.
</P>
<P>
   More than his numbers or his midair artistry, he became known as
one of the league's most prominent ambassadors, speaking eloquently
on issues of sportsmanship, race and the game.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2316EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
