<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0389 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 23:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8091 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-KOSOVO-PROTESTS-ART-N     07-02 1055
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-PROTESTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
10,000 DEMONSTRATE AGAINST MILOSEVIC IN YUGOSLAV CITY 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Locator map is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BLAINE HARDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NOVI SAD, Yugoslavia _ Whistling and jeering, about 10,000
people filled the main square of Yugoslavia's second-largest city
Friday night to demonstrate against Slobodan Milosevic and heard a
parade of local opposition politicians threaten that if he did not
resign as president soon, they would throw him out.
</P>
<P>
   It was the first large public gathering in this Danube River
city since NATO bombs knocked out three bridges that were its
economic arteries. The city is the capital of the province of
Voivodina, the richest food-producing region in Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   Like Kosovo, Voivodina was autonomous under Tito, but was
stripped of that autonomy by Milosevic, and now the city is
controlled by his opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd and the politicians had little to say about the bomb
attacks. Instead, as in the bomb-damaged Serbian city of Cacak,
where the first opposition rally since the war took place on
Wednesday, they blamed all their troubles on Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Mixing sarcasm, black humor and threats of violent defiance,
speaker after speaker blamed the Yugoslav leader for a decade of
fomenting lost wars, for ruining the economy of Voivodina, for
forcing their children to leave the country to find work and for
fouling up local efforts to repair the bridges.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we decide to throw him out by force, he will not be there
by morning,'' said Nenad Canak, president of the League of Social
Democrats, a Voivodina-based party that helped to organize the
rally.
</P>
<P>
   With the aroma of fresh popcorn drifting through the main square
on a splendid July night, the mood of the rally was jubilant, as
the crowd celebrated surviving the 11-week war.
</P>
<P>
   The evening, though, also had an edge of rage. The crowd erupted
in jeers as speakers complained that Milosevic's regime was sucking
taxes from this province to subsidize his wars and creating fuel
shortages that are hobbling the ability of farmers to harvest their
crops.
</P>
<P>
   Novi Sad and much of the region have voted against Milosevic and
his ruling Socialist Party for much of this decade. But unlike
Albanians in Kosovo, the opposition has not been violent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did we die of fear or are we still alive?'' Canak shouted as
he started off the demonstration and people in the crowd, young,
middle-aged and old, shouted back that they were very much alive
and furious to be part of Milosevic's Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
   ``My greatest wish is for Voivodina to be a republic, but this
is not the moment for that to happen,'' Canak told the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   No police officers were in sight Friday night in or around Novi
Sad, unlike during the earlier rally in Cacak. Police there turned
away busloads of protesters and carloads of reporters outside of
town. Police here did arrest four men on Thursday for handing out
fliers about Friday night's rally. One was beaten up before they
were all released.
</P>
<P>
   A number of people said they came to the demonstration because
they believe that, in the end, the only way to get rid of Milosevic
is to force him out. They said that street demonstrations will
probably have to turn violent if they are to have any effect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We would like it to be peaceful, but Milosevic rose to power
in blood and he will only go out in blood,'' said Jelena Radovanov,
27, a biologist who said she has been looking for work since she
graduated from college here four years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Radovanov, who came to the rally with her sister, Dobrila, a
doctor, said she should have fled the country years ago, but now
feels that the reputation of people from Yugoslavia is too tainted
for her to emigrate.
</P>
<P>
   ``They look at us like we are wild animals,'' Dobrila said.
</P>
<P>
   Voivodina is one of the most ethnically mixed parts of
Yugoslavia, with Serbs constituting about half of its 2 million
population, but with large numbers of ethnic Hungarians, Croats,
Slovaks and Romanians. Intermarriage of Serbs with other groups is
common. The Radovanov sisters are half Serbian, half Hungarian.
</P>
<P>
   Asked if she blames the Americans for bombing her city, Jelena
Radovanov said, ``Not even a tiny bit. I am sorry for the bridges.
I cried when they went down. But if that was the price we had to
pay to stop the killing in Kosovo, then I am willing to pay it.''
</P>
<P>
   Her sister interrupted to say, ``We are not all bad in this
country. The world shouldn't hate us so.''
</P>
<P>
   The substance of the demonstration was the problems the city is
having in trying to fix the bridges before winter. Novi Sad, which
is divided from some of its suburbs by the Danube, now has to haul
people back and forth across the river on barges pushed by
tugboats.
</P>
<P>
   Vienna, Austria, has agreed to give Novi Sad a temporary bridge
and to pay $10 million to erect it, Canak told the crowd. But he
said that the Yugoslav government is insisting that the Austrian
money be funneled through Belgrade, the Yugoslav capital, where
Canak said he fears it would be stolen.
</P>
<P>
   He also said that the Yugoslav government has denied visas to
six Viennese engineers who want to come to Novi Sad to start
planning construction of the bridge.
</P>
<P>
   The fight over the bridges in Novi Sad gets at the central
question of how _ or if _ the West should get involved in aiding
Milosevic's Yugoslavia after the war.
</P>
<P>
   The United States and many European countries have said that,
until Milosevic is removed from power, they will give only food,
medicine and perhaps help in restoring electricity.
</P>
<P>
   But opposition leaders argue that these limits will backfire,
punishing Milosevic's victims and goading Serbs into rallying
around their government. Some opposition leaders have been trying
to persuade European countries to funnel aid through cities, such
as Novi Sad, where the opposition is strong. They say that
carefully targeted help can increase popular support for getting
rid of Milosevic.
</P>
<P>
   Interference by Belgrade in the construction of a bridge for
Novi Sad suggests that even if Western countries want to help
individual cities in Yugoslavia, it will not be easy or quick to do
so.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
