</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LIGHTNING-AIRPORTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LIGHTNING HITS CONTROL CENTER AND GROUNDS MANY PLANES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.H., Mass., Conn., N.Y., R.I., Maine, Vt.)  (mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Air traffic across the northeastern United States
was snarled for hours Friday night, delaying tens of thousands of
travelers on the eve of a holiday weekend, after lightning hit New
England's main air traffic control center, in Nashua, N.H.
</P>
<P>
   Many airports were shut down almost entirely for about three
hours. Planes bound to Europe from Kennedy Airport in New York were
among those delayed.
</P>
<P>
   The Federal Aviation Administration said it appeared that its
Boston Air Route Traffic Control Center, which handles
high-altitude, long-distance traffic, sustained a ``direct
lightning strike'' at 3:37 p.m. and did not return to normal
operations for five hours. Delays still persisted because planes
were out of position.
</P>
<P>
   Fraser Jones, a spokesman for the agency, said that the center
continued operation for a few minutes using a computer system that
provides less detailed data to controllers, which would ordinarily
allow it to keep running for hours, with a lower capacity to handle
traffic.
</P>
<P>
   But the mainframe computer began reporting error messages to
technicians, because various devices attached to it were not
running properly, and the mainframe had to be shut down and
restarted. This entails a longer recovery because data on flights
in progress must be loaded into the computer again.
</P>
<P>
   The computer in Nashua also supplies data to other air traffic
offices that handle lower-altitude traffic, so those, too, were
disrupted; controllers in the Boston area had to write out some
data that is usually printed by a computer.
</P>
<P>
   At 4:22 p.m., the FAA ordered all planes in the United States
bound for the Boston area to stay on the ground, although those in
flight were allowed to continue. Planes in the air over the Midwest
were delayed so they could be spread out and bring the flow into
New England to a level that the Boston center could handle.
</P>
<P>
   Departures from the New York area for airspace controlled by the
Boston center were stopped for a few minutes, and then allowed to
resume, but with a longer interval between each plane.
</P>
<P>
   Even after the control system was restored, Logan Airport in
Boston had no space on the ground and had to continue to bar
arrivals until some planes already there could take off, the FAA
said.
</P>
<P>
   Airports affected by the lightning strike, in addition to Logan,
included Green Airport in Providence, R.I.; Bradley International,
north of Hartford, Conn.; and airports in Manchester, N.H.;
Bridgeport, Conn.; Portland and Bangor, Maine; Burlington, Vt.; and
Albany, Syracuse and Plattsburgh, N.Y. In addition to the storm
that hit Nashua, thunderstorms between Washington and New York
disrupted hundreds of flights.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA could not immediately say how many planes were delayed
by the lightning strike. But it hit at the beginning of the holiday
weekend, leaving many passengers sweltering on planes that were
completely full.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
