<HEADER>
A8095 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-AIRPORTS-TECH-PICKETS     07-02 0727
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORTS-TECH-PICKETS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TECHNICIANS SAY FAA CAUSES BIG DELAYS IN AIR TRAFFIC
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Hundreds of technicians who maintain the nation's
air traffic control computers picketed at 53 airports Friday,
handing leaflets to holiday travelers saying the Federal Aviation
Administration had caused big delays by mishandling its
modernization program, not hiring enough technicians and not
consulting with them on the new equipment.
</P>
<P>
   The leaflets listed nine incidents since January, including two
in New York City in May, in which thousands of passengers were
delayed because of the failure of air traffic computers or related
equipment. The leaflets hinted that safety was at stake, but the
FAA denied this.
</P>
<P>
   The technicians' union, the Professional Airways System
Specialists, is negotiating for a new contract in which pay,
staffing levels and training are issues. The technicians' last
five-year contract with the agency expired in February 1997. There
are 7,600 unionized technicians at the agency but, as federal
employees, they are barred from striking.
</P>
<P>
   Under new personnel powers given to the FAA by Congress, the
agency now has more latitude in setting pay scales. It concluded a
new contract with its air traffic controllers earlier this year,
but is still in negotiations with the technicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``The average traveler has a right to know why they are so often
delayed or rerouted,'' said Thomas Brantley, a national vice
president of the union. ``I don't think the FAA is held to task
very often.''
</P>
<P>
   Agency spokesman William Shumann said that 90 percent of air
traffic delays were caused by weather and that in the last five
years only 2 percent to 3 percent were because of equipment
failure. But Brantley said that equipment breakdowns lasted longer
than they used to, a factor that represented a decline in the
margin of safety.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way things used to work, if something went down and you
were running on backup, you'd have somebody trying to fix it,'' he
said. ``Now, they will allow it to go for a few days. If it
happened today, they'd wait until after the holiday weekend.''
</P>
<P>
   Brantley compared the situation to driving a car for a long time
on a temporary spare tire.
</P>
<P>
   The FAA said safety was not at stake. ``I think we have proven
time and again that we will take delays, we will slow the system
down, to maintain safety,'' Shumann said.
</P>
<P>
   The agency's associate administrator for air traffic services,
Steve Brown, said, ``We are disappointed that PASS is attempting to
unnecessarily alarm America's airline passengers on our
Independence Day holiday instead of joining us in a good-faith
effort to resolve our differences in a reasonable and responsible
manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The technicians have complained for years that management has
allowed their ranks to dwindle, leaving some positions vacant and
contracting out some maintenance work to the companies that sell
computer hardware and programs.
</P>
<P>
   The agency acknowledged Friday that staffing had been down to 65
percent of the target level, but said it was now back up, to 72
percent. The staffing level itself is negotiable, Shumann said.
</P>
<P>
   Brantley said technicians were often called in for so many extra
hours that they had more overtime than they wanted.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's got to a point where people go home and they don't want
to answer the phone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Henry Brown, a union official who represents technicians in the
New York area, said, ``I could use another 50 people; I have 235.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It's absolutely nonsensical at this point,'' Brown added.
</P>
<P>
   Technicians are paid an average of $50,000 a year, before
overtime. Many have worked for the FAA for decades and are familiar
with computer and mechanical systems that are no longer in use
elsewhere. But as the agency has brought in new equipment, it has
often signed maintenance contracts with the equipment vendors. And
at many air traffic control offices it leaves the technician's slot
unstaffed on the midnight shift.
</P>
<P>
   The technicians also complain that some new equipment was
developed without enough thought to how malfunctions would be
detected and how it would be maintained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-07-02-99 2344EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
