<DOCNO> NYT19990702.0392 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-07-02 23:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A8097 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-SOF-REINALDA-LBPT     07-02 1625
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOF-REINALDA-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REINALDA FOLLOWS LIFE PATH TO HALL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JASON THORNBURY  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   No need to remind Barbara Reinalda of the quirky turns life can
take. She knows how whims can become momentous decisions, how
pitstops can become final destinations.
</P>
<P>
   In retrospect, a seemingly nonchalant decision 23 years ago
defined the road Reinalda traveled her adult life.
</P>
<P>
   And along the way, that road became the signpost for all
softball players who would follow.
</P>
<P>
   As an Amateur Softball Association Major Fast Pitch hurler,
Reinalda steamrolled through opponents. The only breaks put on
Reinalda were on her uniform, playing for the Raybestos Brakettes
based in Stratford, Conn., home of the car breaks company.
</P>
<P>
   She kept steamrolling all the way to the National Softball Hall
of Fame and Museum in Oklahoma City, Okla., where she will be
enshrined with four others today at the 19th induction ceremonies.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was one of the greatest players of all time, no question
about it,'' said Hall of Fame services manager Bill Plummer. ``The
thing about Barbara, she was a team player in the ultimate sense of
the word. She's not the type of player hungry for publicity.
Obviously, she did quite a job. She played in 10 Olympic Festivals.
And she was also a very good hitter. She hit .290, which is very
good for women's fast pitch.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinalda, who grew up in Lakewood, never had some grand plan for
softball. When she enrolled at Cerritos College after a stellar
career at Valley Christian High in the mid-1970s, she was as
unsuspecting as a bench warmer given her first start. She didn't
know softball could take her around the world or make her the
subject of adoring fans.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just going to play a couple of years at the JC level and
then go on and work,'' Reinalda said.
</P>
<P>
   (subhead) Making news
</P>
<P>
   A newspaper article changed that. A Raybestos salesman read a
story spotlighting a standout freshman pitcher at Cerritos and
relayed his discovery to company headquarters, where Coach Ralph
Raymond needed to restock club.
</P>
<P>
   A new women's professional softball league ravaged the
Brakettes' roster, taking all but two players. Among the
considerable holes to fill was the team's ace hurler Joan Joyce,
the lone softball inductee in the International Women's Sports Hall
of Fame.
</P>
<P>
   The team invited Reinalda, but she wasn't too sure at first. She
grew up a sun-bathing, beach-walking, care-free California girl.
Connecticut? It had only one thing in common with Lakewood:
softball.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, that was enough. She played for Raybestos each
summer following college, which included a transfer to Cal Poly
Pomona, where she enjoyed two All-American years that eventually
landed her in the school's hall of fame with a 0.31 ERA over 412
innings and .340 batting average (still a school record).
</P>
<P>
   By 1981 a job opened in the Raybestos advertising department and
Reinalda knew her future was in Connecticut.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game took on a whole new aspect,'' said Reinalda, 42, now
an assistant softball coach at Yale. ``You were representing
Raybestos and you had to carry yourself accordingly. They flew us
out, gave us a job and we played softball for them. It was neat how
the fans related to the team. They take to the players and make
them feel at home. The community embraces it and it makes you feel
like a family. I had done enough schooling and I said if I don't
try it I'll never know. I knew I could always move back home.''
</P>
<P>
   She never did move back. She spent 19 season with Raybestos and
rolled up numbers that would make Nolan Ryan proud. She ended her
career on a 77-game winning streak and as the winningest pitcher in
team history at 441-31, breaking Joyce's team record of 429 wins.
She hurled 19 perfect games, 31 no-hitters, 76 one-hitters and 312
shutouts.
</P>
<P>
   She was unstoppable, but not because of her speed. She didn't
overpower hitters, rather she picked her spots, hit the corners.
And if a batter did make contact, well, that was fine because she
had her team behind her.
</P>
<P>
   Her personal accomplishments genuinely don't impress her. The
Hall of Fame ranks slightly higher, but still her favorite subject
is her teams' accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   She'd rather talk about the 10 national championships, Pam Am
Games and ISF World Championships gold medals. Forget the Most
Valuable Player award she earned in her first season at the
national championship tournament. Or the 14-0 record, .038 ERA and
.145 opponent batting average in her final season incidental
byproducts to team success, according to Reinalda.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember my first no-hitter,'' said Reinalda, who
retired in 1994. ``Those are things I didn't keep track of. The
team winning was more important. I left (keeping track of
highlights) to my mom. Some people are big on those things, but I'm
not. That's what mothers are for.''
</P>
<P>
   And Anna Mae Reinalda was up to the task. Barbara's mother can
recite her daughter's statistics as quickly, and with the same
glee, as a schoolchild reciting the ABCs.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. and Mrs. Reinalda, now retired and living in Ontario, raised
four kids in Lakewood, Barbara the youngest. All played sports, but
Barbara came of age when girls' sports were just beginning to
blossom. And she played them then, just like does now.
</P>
<P>
   ``She shows no reaction,'' Anna Mae said. ``She said, `Well, I'm
gonna be inducted this year,' as if it was no big thing at all.
Around here we're making a big thing out of it. She's always been
that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Inside she has the enthusiasm, but never shows it. When she
was 9 or 10 we didn't know she'd be an exceptional pitcher, but we
knew she'd always be a top player no matter what sport. She was
just a real competitive person. She gets it from her father.''
</P>
<P>
   She also got excellent coaching from her father.
</P>
<P>
   As a youngster in Bobby Sox, Barbara spied a girl on the mound
and decided she wanted to do it, too. So, her father, Gerrit,
practiced with her nearly every day in the backyard.
</P>
<P>
   Gerrit emphasized control and location. Barbara would master her
control then increase speed. Then further improve her control
followed by another increase in speed.
</P>
<P>
   The technique gave her an arm few could match. By the time she
reached high school, she was untouchable.
</P>
<P>
   (subhead) Prep honors
</P>
<P>
   She was the 3-A Girls Player of the Year in the 1974-1975
season, excelling in both softball and basketball. Cal-Hi Sports
named her the top female athlete in the state for the 1974-75
season. She was also named by Cal-Hi as the state Small Schools
Player of the Year three years in a row (1972-75). In softball, she
was the state Player of the Year in 1974 and 1975. In basketball,
she earned 3-A Player of the Year honors in 1975 and CIF Division
III Player of the Year honors from Cal-Hi in 1975. She was also
honored as the top junior in girls basketball in 1974 by Cal-Hi.
</P>
<P>
   Athleticism wasn't the only constant for Reinalda. Humility was
also present from the beginning.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was not into stats, never was,'' said Valley Christian
athletic director Eleanor Dykstra, who coached Reinalda's high
school softball team and recalled a game in which her ace pitcher
struck out 20 of 21 batters.
</P>
<P>
   ``She was the ultimate team player,'' Dykstra continued. ``She
had a great respect for teammates. She wasn't surrounded by great
players. She was always an encourager to her teammates and she
realized she needed a team behind her. Kids liked to play for
her.''
</P>
<P>
   Too bad the feeling wasn't always mutual.
</P>
<P>
   One of the unintended consequences of softball becoming an
Olympic sport was the chasm that developed between a player's
individual and team goals. They no longer had the same end: to win.
</P>
<P>
   Olympic tryouts were extended to those who made the
all-tournament team at the national championship tournament. It
didn't take long before making the all-tournament team was more
important than winning the title.
</P>
<P>
   Reinalda wanted no part of it. Elevating the individual above
the team was as foreign a concept to her as not caring about first
place.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I played everybody had the same outlook,'' Reinalda said.
``For three months in the summer, during the season, we were a
family. It was emphasized that it was a team sport. Individualism
is one of the reasons I decided to retire when I did.
</P>
<P>
   ``The last couple years when they started talking about
Olympics, the whole attitude of the team changed. It started not to
be fun anymore. We got to the tournament and some kids didn't care
what place we finished, they just wanted to make the all-tournament
team. Well, that's not the way I was raised. I couldn't deal with
it. It wasn't fun anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The grossest unintended consequence, though, resulted from her
low-key persona, according to Plummer, who said said Reinalda's
substance-over-style approach may have cost her points in some
circles. That probably speaks more to the current sports culture
than anything else.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes because she wasn't flamboyant people didn't think
she was as good as she was,'' Plummer said. ``But you go back and
look at her stats and you'll say, `wow.' Some didn't realize how
good she was because she just did her job and didn't seek
publicity. She, without question, was one of most humble athletes
I've met in my 35 years here. She was a team player in every sense
of word and her numbers speak for itself.''
</P>
<P>
   Reinalda, who never married, cares about perception about as
much as she cared about keeping her uniform clean. But her career
will be validated when she is officially enshrined with the game's
best, not that she ever looked for validation.
</P>
<P>
   She was just having fun.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
