</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-ORIOLES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YANKEES NIP ORIOLES, 2-1 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ When Joe Torre knows he's going to replace a pitcher,
he walks slowly to the mound, signaling to the bullpen before he
crosses the basepath, giving the New York Yankee pitcher no
opportunity to talk him out of his decision. But when Torre is
wavering, when he's not sure what he's going to do, he will jog to
the mound.
</P>
<P>
   Torre moved in this manner in the sixth inning Friday night,
when David Cone's energy waned in the pivotal point of the game
against Baltimore. Torre asked questions and looked into Cone's
tired eyes for answers. The decision Torre made proved crucial, as
the Yankees edged the Orioles, 2-1, before 37,518 at Yankee
Stadium. It was New York's 11th victory in its last 13 games.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, the Orioles managed to delay their descent into
oblivion by winning 11 of 13 games, but they are into a free fall
once more: After nine straight losses, they held another team
meeting before Friday night's game, and word from some members of
the Baltimore organization is that owner Peter Angelos is
considering changes. With the bullpen in disarray, the Orioles'
pitching coach, Bruce Kison, may be in jeopardy, but manager Ray
Miller has indicated to others that he will put his job on the line
to protect the jobs of his coaches.
</P>
<P>
   If the Orioles keep losing _ at 32-46 they are 14 games under
.500 _ Miller may not have a job to put on the line for much
longer.
</P>
<P>
   They fell behind, 2-0, in the third inning Friday night after
run-scoring singles by Bernie Williams and Tino Martinez, but the
Orioles were at least taking pieces out of Cone's stamina, forcing
him to throw 27 pitches in the third inning, another 33 over the
next two innings.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Bordick, Baltimore's pesky shortstop, forced Cone to throw
19 pitches in his first three at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   As usual, though, Cone finagled his way out of trouble,
uncannily. The Orioles had three at-bats with runners in scoring
position in the second and could not score; they had two more in
the third, two in the fourth. Going into Friday night's game,
batters had just 10 hits in 79 at-bats (.127) with runners in
scoring position against Cone, and in only one game this year had
the right-hander allowed more than one hit with runners in scoring
position.
</P>
<P>
   But his pitch count was mounting, Cone was tiring and with
nobody out in the sixth inning, Cal Ripken's bloop single allowed
Jeff Conine to score, Ripken advancing to second when Williams'
throw went homeward.
</P>
<P>
   With the score 2-1, Ripken took third on a grounder, and with
one out, the Yankees' infield moved in, attempting to cut off the
run. Charles Johnson had struck out in his first two at-bats, but
this time he hit a sharp bouncer up the middle _ and with a flash
of his glove, Cone grabbed the ball, held Ripken at third and threw
to first for the second out.
</P>
<P>
   Ramiro Mendoza was warming up in the bullpen. Cone's pitch count
approached 120, and against the left-handed hitting Brady Anderson,
Cone worked carefully. Anderson walked, and Bordick was due to bat.
Torre stepped out of the dugout, and jogged to the mound; he wanted
to hear from Cone before deciding whether to call on Mendoza.
</P>
<P>
   Cone looked away on Torre's first question. There was no doubt,
he was tired. Torre asked another question, and Cone looked Torre
in the eyes and nodded, yes, he had enough to get Bordick. Torre
turned and jogged back to the dugout.
</P>
<P>
   Cone knew Bordick would be his last hitter. He threw a slider
for strike one, then another slider that Bordick fouled off. No
balls and two strikes. Bordick had to be wary of the slider. Cone
began his motion homeward, dropped down to throw sidearm _ he likes
to throw sliders from this angle _ and fired a high fastball.
Bordick swung and missed, ending the threat.
</P>
<P>
   It was Baltimore's best bid, for Mendoza came on in the seventh,
Mike Stanton relieved in the eighth and Mariano Rivera set the
Orioles down in order in the ninth for his 21st save.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
