</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-RHODEN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: METS SEND MIXED MESSAGES 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By WILLIAM C. RHODEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There was talk from the New York Mets that this
series with Atlanta would be a barometer, a measuring stick for how
far the team had come in the last month. If the game was a stick,
Atlanta used it to thrash the Mets back to reality Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta led by 10-0 after four innings and won by 16-0. The talk
about Greg Maddux losing his stuff is myth. Maddux pitched six
innings and allowed just two hits and two walks.
</P>
<P>
   Still, based on the last couple of miserable months, eternally
optimistic Mets fans felt _ feel _ their team is on equal footing
with Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   But what was supposed to have been a grand first chapter Friday
night in the powerful new Mets wound up being another page in the
madcap history of an often bizarre franchise: Matt Franco was
forced to pitch, Roger Cedeno was forced to play second, and the
pitcher Rick Reed finished the game playing the outfield.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got to be prepared for the worst,'' manager Bobby
Valentine said. ``And that was the worst.''
</P>
<P>
   This game was a flashback to where the Mets were one month ago,
mired in one of their worst slumps of the 1990s. There were calls
for Valentine to resign; three of his coaches were fired. Finally
Valentine, in a startling strategic ploy, said at a news conference
on June 6 that perhaps he should be dismissed. ``I believe within
the next 55 games if we're not better, I shouldn't be the
manager,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   That was 20 games ago. Now the Mets are in second place, in
fire-breathing distance of first-place Atlanta, despite Friday
night's loss that leaves them four games back. Valentine, looking
back on his self-imposed death sentence, said: ``I just thought
that I was stating the inevitable. I felt that if the team had a
mind and a conscience that it would either put up or shut up for
me.''
</P>
<P>
   Is this love for the manager or a sense that the Mets have an
opportunity this season to finally catch and pass Atlanta? The
National League East door was supposedly opened by baseball's
decision to enforce a narrower strike zone, thereby robbing Maddux
and Tom Glavine of strikes called on pitches off the outside corner
of the plate. Maddux has been hit hard this season: The four-time
Cy Young award winner with a career 2.75 earned run average going
into the season took a 3.87 ERA to the mound Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just believe some of those guys are entering an age and time
of their life where they are going to have to change a few
things,'' Montreal manager Felipe Alou said.
</P>
<P>
   Maddux has adjusted, all right. He shut out the Mets last
Sunday, 1-0, and carried a no-hitter into the fifth inning Friday
night before finishing his six innings by allowing two hits.
</P>
<P>
   The difference between Atlanta, the NL team of the 1990s, and
the amorphous, aspiring Mets is confidence and consistency. The
Mets have been pointing toward the Atlanta series for days, while
Atlanta has focused on its opponent at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``We might be thinking, `Oh, it's a big series. We got to beat
them,''' Rickey Henderson of the Mets said before the game. ``But
Atlanta's just going out there to play the game. That's the way we
have to approach it.''
</P>
<P>
   For Henderson, the steepest mountain the Mets have to climb,
especially the young players, is learning how not to panic when
things go bad. For players like Henderson, who has been around for
19 years, slumps are merely the prelude to something great.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't care what we do to Atlanta,'' Henderson said.
``They're not going to panic. They've been there. They've won, over
and over again. When you've done something as much as they have,
your attitude, even when you lose, is: `If it doesn't work this
time, it's going to work next time. So why panic?'''
</P>
<P>
   Who are these Mets? The team that surged at the beginning of a
season, or the team that spiraled and was filled with dissension
just a month ago? The team that was routed Friday night? Or a team
of young talent coalescing into a unit, sometimes despite rocky
relationships with the manager? Is this current surge one more peak
in a number of peaks and valleys?
</P>
<P>
   The Mets have won 88 games in each of the last two seasons and
haven't made the playoffs. This is a playoff-caliber team. So wait.
Wait and see. If the Mets make the playoffs, stay with Valentine;
if they don't, make the tough decision and let go.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that we have half a season left to play,'' Valentine
said before the game. ``But we sure in heck want to beat Atlanta.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, it will take more than wanting it to beat Atlanta, a
team that for all the talk about fading appeared to be three levels
beyond the Mets. If ever there was a time to send Atlanta a signal,
it would be now. If Friday night is any indication, the Mets are
sending mixed messages.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
