<HEADER>
A8106 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS03-COX     07-02 0411
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BRAVES-METS03-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Braves shame Mets at Shea
 &HT;    By Thomas Stinson
 &HT;    c.1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If the New York Mets actually intend to make something
happen in the NL East, they must know something the Braves don't.
</P>
<P>
   Chipper Jones hit a pair of two-run homers while Ryan Klesko
continued his most torrid period of the season with two doubles and
another homer as the Braves embarrassed the Mets 16-0 to open a
weekend series at Shea Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   ``You never know,'' manager Bobby Cox said. ``Baseball's
crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Atlanta's division lead grew to four games and the same Mets who
had won eight of their last 11 games played No. 12 like an
abandoned youth team. Their bullpen empty, Matt Franco, the Mets'
heralded pinch-hitter, came in to pitch the final out while pitcher
Rick Reed ended the night in right field.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't work. Gerald Williams' hit a three-run homer off Franco,
the last of the Braves' five pitchers. The 16-run margin tied the
biggest ever in a shutout game by an Atlanta team.
</P>
<P>
   Greg Maddux (8-5) pitched six shutout innings, most of them long
after the Mets had submitted. Eddie Perez also homered in a game
that was completely devoid of drama from the third inning on.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, it's a win,'' Maddux said. ``Obviously, we want to win
the series. But it's easier to lose a game like this than it is 2-1
or something.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They gave us one of these the first game at our place,''
second baseman Bret Boone said. ``Just one of those weird games.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory was the Braves' third straight over the Mets after
dropping a 10-2 decision in Atlanta last Friday. More important,
Maddux followed Tom Glavine with a consecutive victory for the
third time in the last four times through the rotation. Through the
season's first 13 trips through the rotation, the No. 1 and 2
starters won consecutive games only once.
</P>
<P>
   Every Braves starting position had either scored a run or driven
one in by the fourth. Klesko, in the midst of an 8-for-17 road
trip, now has 11 RBIs in seven games. Jones' seasonal total rose to
a team-high 16 as the third baseman ended a 21-game homerless
streak with the eighth two-HR game of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's nice to have a break-out game. I haven't had one for a
while,'' Jone said. ``To have it come in the first game in the
biggest series you can have in July, it was a good feeling.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
