<HEADER>
A8107 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a &Cx13;  &Cx11;  BC-NY-SONOFSAM-SCENE-NYT     07-02 0895
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SONOFSAM-SCENE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FILM DRAWS THOSE TOUCHED BY SON OF SAM AND A SUMMER THEY CAN'T
FORGET 
</HEADLINE>
  (editors: also see EDIT-SONOFSAM) 
 (bl)  
 By KIT R. ROANE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William and Diane Perez escaped the heat in their
Brooklyn home Friday afternoon for a trip to the past.
</P>
<P>
   Their vehicle was a movie, but as they snuggled into their seats
at the nearby Fortway Cinemas in Bay Ridge, it was clear that they
had come to experience something much greater.
</P>
<P>
   They were there to relive 1977, the most memorable year of their
lives, to recall the joy of a Yankee World Series championship and
the discomfort of a heat wave, and to taste again the fear that
gripped the city as it was stalked by the killer known as the Son
of Sam. That terror struck close to home for Mrs. Perez, who was a
high school classmate of one victim.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came because this was a time we'd never forget, a time that
was really terrifying and full of activity, one that affected all
of our lives,'' explained Perez, 42.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was the big blackout and it was too hot to move, and we
all remember the looters,'' he said. ``It was also a time when you
could be sitting in a car on lovers' lane and that would be your
last kiss.''
</P>
<P>
   The Perezes were among thousands of New Yorkers who showed up
Friday for the opening of director Spike Lee's film about that
time, appropriately titled ``Summer of Sam.''
</P>
<P>
   The film has already made headlines in recent weeks as relatives
of the victims _ as well as the killer, David Berkowitz _ have
protested what they say is needless exploitation of the killings,
in which Berkowitz sought out and shot young lovers in cars and
women walking dark streets.
</P>
<P>
   Lee has said that his film is about much more than the murders,
exploring a time that he has called an ``insane'' episode in New
York City's history.
</P>
<P>
   The film, which runs 2 hours and 20 minutes, follows the
changing lives of a group of young New Yorkers who are brought
together and pulled apart by volatile forces: race, shifting
attitudes toward sex, the disco craze, the advent of punk rock and
seemingly random violence.
</P>
<P>
   This may have seemed like ancient history to the giggling
teen-agers who sat at the front of the theater Friday to get the
full impact of the pulsing soundtrack and the visual violence that
peppers the movie. But most in the audience were older, people who
remembered the madness of the serial killings and the other events
of that summer.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Valentino and his wife, Bernadette, took two of their
three young boys to the theater to show what life was like back
when they were teen-agers. Outside the theater, Valentino recalled
that he was on a Ferris wheel in Coney Island on July 13, 1977,
when the blackout hit, and that he nearly cried when Elvis Presley
died.
</P>
<P>
   ``He died on Aug. 16, four days after Berkowitz was captured,
and it was the only thing that ever pulled Son of Sam out of the
headlines,'' Valentino recalled. ``All of it seems just like
yesterday, even though it's been more than 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Petrillo, 46, called that summer the most defining season
in his life. ``You were scared to do anything that you were used to
doing,'' he said. ``Going to the park? Forget about it. Lovers'
lane? Forget about it. Everyone was too scared to even go
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   Petrillo and Mrs. Perez each knew one of Berkowitz's last two
victims, 20-year-olds who were shot on the night of July 31 as they
sat in a parked car on a quiet street near Dyker Beach Park in the
Bath Beach section of Brooklyn. The young woman, Stacy Moskowitz,
died of her wounds several days later, while her date, Robert
Violante, lost an eye.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were especially aware because the killings were taking
place around here and Stacy went to my high school,'' said Ms.
Perez, 42.
</P>
<P>
   Petrillo said that he still sees Violante every six or eight
months. ``He works at the post office,'' he said, adding, ``I bet
he doesn't want to see this.''
</P>
<P>
   Berkowitz, now 46, was sentenced to more than 300 years in
prison for killing six people and wounding seven over a period of
13 months. He has said the killings were committed on the orders of
a black Labrador retriever owned by a neighbor named Sam. Now
imprisoned in the Sullivan Correctional Facility in the Catskill
Mountains, the former postal worker says he has converted to
Christianity.
</P>
<P>
   Like so many of the characters in the movie, Petrillo and Perez
said they, too, had hung out with their friends in 1977 trying to
figure out who in their neighborhood might be the killer, taking
mental notes of those who seemed less sociable or strange.
</P>
<P>
   That awareness and continued fear of the lurking stranger is
perhaps Berkowitz's most lasting effect on them. Now when they park
near the shore for a jog or a walk, they may recognize the site of
a murder, and if they see a stranger there, they say there is still
a split-second when they wonder if he, too, might be a killer.
</P>
<P>
   Life just seems more dangerous now, even though crime is down,
they said. Petrillo said he worries about his 17-year-old daughter.
</P>
<P>
   ``You've got no control over what happens these days, so I worry
about her,'' he said. ``And, you know, it doesn't have to be a
serial killer anymore; someone could just push her in front of a
train. Stuff happens all the time.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
